<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, March 10.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AIDS (Beijing) _ Song Pengfei, 17 years old, is one of a
small but growing number of Chinese infected with the virus that
causes AIDS in a country that is emotionally, financially and
medically largely unprepared to deal with them. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT13,25) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BOOK (Mexico City) _ A new children's book in Spanish and
English is being published by a small press in El Paso _ a
profusely illustrated ``History of Colors,'' which tells an ancient
Mexican Indian myth of how colors came into the world. The
publisher received a grant from the National Endowment for the
Arts. Open the book and on the jacket is a picture of the author:
Subcommandate Insurgente Marcos, leader of the left-wing Zapatista
rebellion in Mexico. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT22) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-LAWYER (New Orleans) _ Over the last five years, Wendell
Gauthier has organized the largest ever group of American trial
lawyers and led them in a sustained assault against the tobacco
industry for the damage caused by nicotine addiction. Though he
claims to be neither the smartest nor the richest of the trial
lawyers who have taken on the tobacco industry, he is the architect
and chairman of a growing legal enterprise that is mounting a
similar assault on the gun industry. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT14,24) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SUN-FORECAST (Undated) _ Analyzing X-ray images of transient
S-shaped patterns on the Sun, scientists think they have found a
reliable way to forecast powerful solar eruptions that can cause
disruptive magnetic storms in the Earth's atmosphere, knock out
electrical systems and communications and disable orbiting
spacecraft. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-GOTTLIEB (Washington) _ Dr. Sidney Gottlieb, has died. He
who ran the CIA's programs for mind-control, brainwashing, LSD
experiments, germ warfare and assassination by poison in the Cold
War _ and who then repented and spent the last years of his life
running leper colonies in India and hospices for AIDS patients in
rural Virginia. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-COMMUTE (Alma, Colo.) _ Traditionally, Westerners have
viewed mass transit as something vaguely synonymous with socialism.
But here in the Colorado Rockies, surging tourism, employment,
population and real estate prices are forging transportation
strategies that look positively European. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT16,17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-DEFENSE _ In an institution that runs on comity and
tradition, Sen. John W. Warner has mastered the art of fitting in.
With his impeccably tailored suits, silver-gray hair and
associations with Elizabeth Taylor and Barbara Walters, the
gentleman from Virginia looks, at first glance, like the senator
from central casting. But Warner's back-slapping bonhomie has not
always gotten him the respect that some colleagues say he really
wants. As he assumes a leadership role as chairman of the Armed
Services Committee, the Republican is working to overcome a
question that still lingers among some of his peers: Is John Warner
really up to the task? By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
