<P>
   RJR-NABISCO-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Since its fabled leveraged
buyout in 1989, RJR Nabisco has labored under a heavy debt load.
But with the announcement Tuesday that RJR Nabisco Holdings would
sell its international tobacco business, use the proceeds to reduce
corporate debt and split its domestic tobacco business from its
food operations, the outlook for shareholders brightened
considerably. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   RJR-NABISCO-TERMS (Undated) _ Examining the terms of the
breakup. By Edward Wyatt. &UR; (BU) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RJR-NABISCO-LEGAL (Undated) _ Legal implications of the breakup:
Will tobacco lawyers try to block it? By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   RJR-NABISCO-ICAHN (Undated) _ The role played by investor Carl
Icahn. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   NBC-AD-COLUMN _ Becoming the first broadcast network to own a
portion of a home shopping channel, NBC announced Tuesday that it
will make a significant investment in the cable network Value
Vision and link it with the NBC network, the cable channels CNBC
and MSNBC, and the Web site MSNBC.com. The move speaks to NBC's
strategy to move away from the old network economic model, which
has always generated revenue only through advertising. By Bill
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRAVEL (Undated) _ In software, Microsoft is the
gorilla whose every thundering step shakes the industry. But in the
on-line travel business, it is just another money-losing upstart.
And so at the same time that Microsoft is wrestling the Justice
Department in a landmark antitrust suit, it is also asking the
federal regulators to file an antitrust action against the nation's
airlines.
</P>
