   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARTICHOKE (Davenport, Calif.) _ This is the rough-hewn far edge
of America that has drawn painters and moviemakers and tourists.
But it is also, as it turns out, the domain of the artichoke, which
flourishes in the mild mist here _ particularly along the stretch
just north of Santa Cruz _ as it does nowhere else. By Amanda
Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ARTICHOKE-COOKING (San Francisco) _ It can seem like a nasty
customer, tightly closed and unyielding, more than forbidding
enough to frighten off a cook or two. But those who know the
artichoke know just how to slip past its defenses. That's
especially true in San Francisco, where artichokes are as familiar
in restaurant kitchens as potatoes. The trick, the city's chefs
say, is to keep it simple and don't work too hard. By Amanda
Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT7,8) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ARTICHOKE-WINE (Undated) _ Why artichokes fight with wine.
</P>
<P>
   ESCOLAR-EATING-WELL (New York) _ Lately some New York
restaurants have been offering a fish of unparalleled richness
that, miraculously, is hardly fattening at all. It's called
escolar, and it would be a dream come true except for one problem:
For a significant number of people, the flesh of this fish acts
like a laxative. So restaurateurs have found themselves in a
predicament _go with it anyway, even if a few customers suffer, or
give up on a food that other customers crave. By Marian Burros.
</P>
