<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS RIP DEMOCRATS OVER EDUCATION BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The political sniping over an education bill turned
sharper Tuesday as five congressional Republicans _ all former
governors _ accused Democrats of using the issue in a ``cynical''
attempt to score political points.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called education flexibility bill would give states the
power to waive federal rules on certain education programs so that
schools could channel the money where they saw fit.
</P>
<P>
   All 50 governors support the bill, and a dozen states, including
Kansas, have the flexibility under a trial program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a no-brainer as far as I'm concerned,'' said Sen.
George Voinovich, an Ohio Republican and former governor whose
state was among the first to receive the waiver. ``Why should this
be tied up in partisan politics? Let's get on with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Voinovich were Sens. Kit Bond and John Ashcroft of
Missouri, Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island and Rep. Michael Castle
of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Democrats see the politically popular ``ed-flex'' bill
as a chance to make good on last year's promise to hire 100,000 new
teachers. Congress approved a $1 billion down payment on the
program last year. Democrats want to attach an $11.4 billion
amendment to ed-flex that would pay for the teachers over the next
six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed-flex is a good idea...but flexibility and accountability
mean little if we don't also give communities the support they need
to implement school reform strategies that work,'' Sen. Edward
Kennedy, a Massachusetts Democrat, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A procedural vote expected Wednesday could determine whether the
Senate would be allowed to vote on the Democratic amendment. And
that may determine what happens to the ed-flex bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, who is running for re-election next year, led the five
Republicans on Tuesday in decrying the time that schools and
teachers were forced to spend on federal paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every minute spent on forms is a minute not spent on students,
and these are people who love students,'' Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, who has emphasized education as both governor and senator,
said the depth of Washington's intrusion into education policy was
like ``the nose of the federal camel under the education tent.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Democratic effort to alter the ed-flex bill
was designed to deny Republicans a political victory after the
impeachment trial of President Clinton, Bond said yes, and the
others appeared to agree.
</P>
<P>
   A top aide to House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri
denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd argue that the Democrats made this a top priority during
Clinton's entire term in office, but it's only recently that the
Republicans have gotten some religion on this issue,'' Laura
Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy aide James Manley said the Republicans were ``desperate
to get out from under the cloud caused by the impeachment process
and are trying to find legislation they can move through the Senate
and demonstrate they are moving on an agenda that will impact the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, national Republicans held a town meeting on
education outside Philadelphia to demonstrate their support for an
issue that polls show resonates with voters in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Both Chafee and Castle said the bill's appeal was clear by the
fact that every governor _ Republican, Democrat and Independent _
supported it.
</P>
<P>
   They said the other education issues that Democrats wanted to
talk about, such as teachers, class size and technology, should be
dealt with when the Senate took up reauthorization of the more
expansive Elementary and Secondary Education Act, presumably later
this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
