<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-TESTS-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA PONDERS FUTURE AFTER RULING BARRING USE OF SAT TO DETERMINE
ELIGIBILITY  
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE WITH LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now in his senior year at St. Patrick's High School in
Elizabeth, N.J., Jamal Jackson has a 2.4 grade-point average in the
classroom to go with his 11 points and eight assists a game on the
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   He has received inquiries from Division I schools like St.
Peter's and Fairfield, but in two attempts at the Scholastic
Aptitude Test, he has failed to make the NCAA minimum score of 820
required for an athletic scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Now he, as well as hundreds of high school athletes across the
country, may not have to. On Monday, a federal judge in
Philadelphia struck down the NCAA's minimum test score requirement,
or Proposition 16, saying that it discriminated against
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling removed from the NCAA's control the issue of college
athletic eligibility, and for now placed it with the individual
schools. It left college administrators and the NCAA in limbo
Tuesday, with many officials acknowledging that in the absence of
guidelines, confusion would reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does present somewhat of a chaotic environment,'' said the
NCAA president, Cedric Dempsey. ``It leaves a lot of unanswered
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jackson and other students, the window of opportunity may be
brief. The NCAA will ask Judge Ronald I. Buckwalter Wednesday for a
stay of his decision, saying the chaos among its member schools
would be counterproductive. In the mean time, it will prepare an
appeal. Elsa Kircher Cole, the organization's general counsel, said
she expected a response from the judge ``within a day or two.''
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials said they have been studying eligibility
standards since last summer and are prepared to move quickly in
establishing a new standard. Charles Wethington, the University of
Kentucky president and chairman of the NCAA executive committee,
said that coming up with an acceptable standard has been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   He said the NCAA has not strayed from its goal of having initial
eligibility standards in an effort to improve graduation rates and
insure that student athletes are prepared for college work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are greatly concerned at this moment with the effect this
ruling will have on academic preparedness of prospective student
athletes,'' Wethington said.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when NCAA officials conceded they had more questions
than answers, they also announced that the NCAA would pay $54.5
million to about 2,000 Division I coaches who had sued over the
restricted earnings rule, which had capped their salaries at
$16,000 for a calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   It is the settlement of a $75 million judgment against the NCAA
in a case challenging its decision to limit the earnings of
entry-level coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Buckwalter's ruling on one of college sports' most
enduring challenges _ how to improve graduation rates without
excluding economically disadvantaged students _ that left coaches,
administrators and college presidents uncertain of who is eligible
for scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Without Proposition 16, there are no guidelines by which to
decide if incoming freshmen are academically eligible.
</P>
<P>
   It poses immediate problems in the NCAA basketball tournament,
which begins on Thursday. The NCAA estimates that 500 to 1,000
athletes have been affected by the existing test score minimum
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Until a stay is granted, the NCAA said Tuesday, athletes sitting
out their freshman year because they failed to meet the minimum
requirements are free to play _ including the Temple basketball
player Alexander Wesby, who was one of the four plaintiffs in a
class action suit in Philadelphia. He won't play in the tournament,
said the Temple sports media director, Brian Kirschner.
</P>
<P>
   Wethington said he wouldn't approve an ineligible player if the
situation arises at his school. ``I think this situation is too
fluid, too undecided and there's too much at risk,'' Wethington
said, emphasizing that he was speaking only for himself. ``I think
it would be sending the absolute wrong signal.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The ruling touched on an issue that resonates among coaches and
athletes. If it is upheld, the ruling could restore a lost year of
eligibility to athletes like Rasheed Brokenborough, the Temple
senior guard who sat out his freshman year because of the SAT
cutoff and ran up $15,000 in debt because he could not qualify for
a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in coaching has been affected by the NCAA test
rules,'' said Lute Olson, the Arizona coach. ``There are a number
of kids we would have recruited had they not had test scores
standing in their way. This particular kid pops into my mind _ he
is from southern California and he's playing in the pros now. He
did not have high enough test scores in the initial period that we
needed them to make the decision. We went with the kid with the
test score. We would have opted for the southern California kid.
Later, he got the test score at the end of the year. His first
choice was us, but we couldn't wait and take the chance on him
getting the score.''
</P>
<P>
   New York high school coaches, athletic directors and school
administrators applauded the judge's ruling. Wade Williams, for 10
years the basketball coach at Bronx Regional, an alternative high
school for students with academic problems, remembered the players
who didn't meet the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them were intimidated by the SAT because they hadn't
had academic success,'' said Williams, who has placed at least 40
athletes on scholarships at junior colleges or Division III
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams, who is black, also worried that the ruling might
have a damaging effect on those it aimed to help: black students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned that kids will think they don't have to do
anything,'' Williams said. ``It also exposes kids to unscrupulous
coaches who will accept them for their talent, then cast them
aside.''
</P>
<P>
   That situation, with embarrassing admissions by college students
that they were not being educated or even had trouble reading, was
what prompted the NCAA to institute minimum test scores in the
first place back in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   For St. Patrick's Jackson, a change in the requirements for
athletic eligibility would bring an opportunity to be rewarded for
the hard work he has done in the classroom. He is the second oldest
of five children and would be the first in his family to attend
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the judge's rule stands because I'd get a lot more
offers,'' Jackson said Tuesday by telephone as his team prepared
for the state sectional tournament. ``Right now, schools are scared
to take me because of my SAT scores. They're afraid they may have
to park me on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   His coach, Kevin Boyle, said Jackson has steadily raised his
grade-point average over his four years. ``He came in not as a
great student,'' said Boyle. ``But he stayed on the straight and
narrow, worked hard and we made sure he didn't slip through the
cracks. He's really tried to improve his SAT scores, but he doesn't
test well on big tests. This is a kid that deserves a break.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
