<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ATWOOD-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN ATWOOD, AVIATION EXECUTIVE, DIES AT 94
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Pa., Texas, Ky., Ohio)  (nk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Leland Atwood, an engineer who rose through the executive
ranks at North American Aviation as it built the P-51 Mustang, the
most powerful fighter plane of World War II; the F-100 Super Sabre,
the first supersonic fighter, and the Apollo capsule that took men
to the moon, died on March 5. He was 94 and lived in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, who was known as Lee, retired in 1970 as chairman of the
North American Rockwell Corp., a company formed three years earlier
by the merger of North American Aviation Inc. of Los Angeles and
the Rockwell-Standard Corp., an auto parts maker in Pittsburgh. The
company became Rockwell International in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Don H. Davis, the chief executive of Rockwell International,
said Atwood's contributions ``helped the United States to attain
aerospace superiority.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood was assistant general manager of North American Aviation
in 1940 when he persuaded the British government to pay for
development of a new plane instead of modifying the Curtiss P-40.
Pilots flying the new plane, the P-51 Mustang, were responsible for
almost half of the enemy aircraft downed in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Luther Smith of Villanova, Pa., one of the Tuskegee Airmen, a
unit of black fighter pilots, flew 50 of his 133 World War II
combat missions in a P-51. He said Tuesday that the Mustang ``could
outmaneuver all of the German fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The P-51 was so powerful, with its Rolls-Royce engines, and so
maneuverable, that we would give Germans 10 seconds to parachute
out once we got behind them,'' he added. ``They knew, and we knew,
that we had them and we would have our gun cameras on, and as soon
as we got a picture of them bailing out we would shoot down the
plane and let the pilot live.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood also played a key role in designing the B-25 Mitchell, a
medium-range bomber, 16 of which were used by Gen. Jimmy Doolittle
in the raid over Tokyo in 1942, an attack that had little military
value but helped raise American morale.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, Atwood disclosed that the F-100, which his company
built, had become the first production jet fighter to operate at
supersonic speeds in level flight. He also helped North American
Aviation win the contract to build the X-15 rocket plane, which
Capt. Pete Knight flew at more than 4,500 miles an hour in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood was born in 1904 in Walton, Ky. He graduated from
Hardin-Simmons University in 1926 and two years later earned a
master's degree in civil engineering at the University of Texas. He
then went to work as a junior airplane engineer for the Army Air
Corps at Wright Field in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, he was hired at Douglas Aircraft in Santa Monica,
Calif., and he moved to North American Aviation in Los Angeles as
chief engineer and vice president. He was promoted to assistant
general manager in 1938, to first vice president in 1941, to
president in 1948, chief executive in 1960 and chairman in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, when the company merged with
Rockwell-Standard, Atwood was named chief executive, a post he held
until he retired in 1970. In 1996, Boeing acquired the aerospace
operations of Rockwell International.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood is survived by his wife, Patricia, Rockwell International
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For many years after World War II, North American Aviation was
the biggest military contractor, relying on Washington for
virtually all of its revenue. Atwood was called to Washington
several times for hearings by congressmen about how well the
company spent taxpayer money, as well as its relationship with
Robert G. Baker, the Senate Democratic secretary whose outside
business dealings were the subject of a 1964 congressional inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, North American Aviation abruptly reduced by half its
contract with a vending machine company to make room for another
company, U-Serv, in which Baker was a major shareholder. The deal
was valued at $2.5 million, the equivalent of $13.6 million today.
Atwood told the Senate Rules Committee in 1964 that he was unaware
of Baker's role or that his company's lobbyist was also a major
U-Serv shareholder. Ten days later, Atwood announced that he had
dismissed the lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Atwood was again called on the carpet after a fire
killed three Apollo astronauts during a pre-flight test of the
space capsule. Atwood said that in designing the capsule no one had
considered the possibility of a fire on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The government's own inquiry found shoddy work that was not
caught by inspectors of North American Aviation, including a socket
wrench left inside the Apollo capsule. The moon project was not
only a huge political issue but also an economic giant that
accounted for almost 1 percent of the gross national product at its
peak.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood told a House committee that ``overconfidence'' was behind
some of the problems, which he vowed to correct without delaying
the national goal to put a man on the moon before the end of the
decade. He installed new managers on the project and made other
changes. On July 20, 1969, Neil A. Armstrong put his boot into
lunar dust and later that year the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration gave Atwood its Public Service Award.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
