<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Texas) 
ACCOUNTING IS QUESTIONED IN LAWSUIT AGAINST iVILLAGE 
 (nk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just days before the planned initial public stock
offering of iVillage Inc., a New York Internet service for women, a
former chief financial officer of the company has filed court
documents accusing iVillage of ``inappropriate'' accounting
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were made in connection with a lawsuit filed in
January by a former employee, Todd L. Kenner. Kenner contends that
iVillage reneged on a promise to give him stock options, a benefit
that could prove valuable if the offering, expected next Monday, is
successful.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Tuesday that it could not directly respond to
the allegations since it is restricted in its public statements
because of the pending offering. But it did say that it stood by
its financial statements, which have been audited by
PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting allegations were made in a sworn declaration
filed in federal court in Nashville, Tenn., last Friday by Joanne
O'Rourke Hindman. She wrote that she joined iVillage in September
1997 as chief financial officer and almost immediately raised
questions about the company's accounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the company was recognizing revenues prematurely
(indeed, in some instances even before letters of intent were
signed),'' the declaration said. In general, companies must wait
until they are assured of receiving revenues before claiming them
in financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hindman wrote that she told Candice Carpenter, the company's
chief executive, that iVillage should ``clean up our act'' with
regard to accounting for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Eight weeks after being hired, Ms. Hindman wrote, she was
demoted from chief financial officer and assigned to run the
company's Better Health subsidiary. She was dismissed two months
later, she wrote. Her declaration asserts that she was denied stock
options that were promised her when she was hired.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration was filed in an unusual legal maneuver. The case
is at an early stage, with arguments pending over whether it should
remain in Tennessee, where Kenner lived before joining iVillage, or
be moved to New York. So evidence on the facts would not normally
be entered yet. But lawyers for Kenner applied to the court for
permission to file declarations by Ms. Hindman and by Steven D.
Carter, another executive who says he was let go by iVillage and
denied promised stock options.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver had the effect of making public the allegations of
Ms. Hindman before the public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hindman declined to comment Tuesday, referring calls to her
lawyer, R. Paul Yetter in Houston. Yetter, who is also representing
Kenner, did not return a call.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers say that the offering is likely to proceed as
expected and that the company will rely on the reputation of
PricewaterhouseCoopers as its defense.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agreed that this filing, in itself, was unlikely to
derail the offering. After all, they said, Ms. Carpenter has long
had a reputation as a mercurial manager, and there has been far
more turnover at iVillage than at typical Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know that the women running the show over there are
fairly aggressive and can rub people the wrong way,'' said Mark S.
Basham, a new-issue analyst for Standard &AMP; Poor's. ``Investors who
like the company's go-for-broke style will still like the company.
Those who don't like that way of doing business didn't like it
before and won't change their mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
