<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE REPUBLICANS CALL FOR BIGGER TAX CREDIT FOR
LOW-INCOME WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Taking up one of the favorite causes of advocates
for the poor, the Republicans who control the state Senate called
Tuesday for an expanded tax credit for more than a million
low-income workers, most of them with children.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was a first for the Senate Republicans, and it is
sure to make their overall tax cut package more palatable to a
skeptical Democratic majority in the Assembly as the two houses
negotiate the 1999-2000 state budget. It also greatly increases the
chances that the increased tax credit, which has been approved in
the past by the Assembly, will become law.
</P>
<P>
   As he announced the plan, the Senate majority leader, Joseph L.
Bruno, also warned that with just three weeks left before the start
of a new fiscal year, Senate and Assembly leaders remain billions
of dollars apart in their projections of how much money the state
has to spend.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to a gap of ``a couple of billion'' between the
Senate estimate and the Assembly's higher figure, later adding,
``that's conservative,'' though he and other lawmakers said the
exact difference was unclear. Aides to the Assembly speaker,
Sheldon Silver, confirmed that the two sides were wide apart.
</P>
<P>
   Agreement on how much money is available is a crucial precursor
to serious budget negotiations between the two houses. This year,
there is added pressure on them to pass a budget on time for the
first time since 1984 because a law enacted in December that gave
legislators a pay raise also requires that their salaries be
withheld as long as the budget is overdue.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gov. George Pataki proposed a 1.8 percent rise in
state spending, to $72.66 billion, despite a surplus that is
expected to exceed $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republicans, led by Bruno, had called for tax cuts
worth $800 million a year, and Tuesday they increased that figure
to $1.1 billion. But the Assembly Democrats are leery of deep tax
cuts that will inhibit their ability to restore spending cuts that
the governor has proposed in education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Democrats released the first concrete part of
their own budget plan, calling for $289 million more for higher
education than Pataki had proposed. Most of that would simply be
rejecting cuts that the governor is seeking in tuition aid for poor
students and other programs, but about $16 million would go toward
hiring 300 more professors in the State University and City
University systems.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office reserved judgment on the proposals from
the Legislature. ``We're always willing to look at ideas that
follow the governor's lead in cutting taxes,'' said Joseph Conway,
a spokesman for the governor's budget office. Of the Assembly plan,
he said, ``We can't comment because we haven't seen any details on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Senate Republicans' tax cut proposals have
mostly benefited businesses. But this year, the centerpieces of
their package are tax deductions for college tuition, and tax-free
accounts for people to save to buy their first homes, ideas with
broad appeal to middle-class voters.
</P>
<P>
   Today's proposal would expand the state's earned income tax
credit by half. The state credit, modeled on a federal credit, was
established in 1994, and it benefits childless workers who earn
less than $10,000 a year, and families with children and incomes up
to $30,000 a year. New York is one of just nine states with such a
credit.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.1 million wage earners in New York qualify for the
credit, most of them parents. And most are in New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
