A4346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KUBRICK-NYT &LR;      03-10 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KUBRICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE EDGY LEGACY OF STANLEY KUBRICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The adjectives that cluster around Stanley Kubrick and his work
_ cool, distant, reclusive, savage, brilliant _ are words that
measure discomfort. Moviegoers love nothing more than certainty,
but Kubrick, who died Sunday at age 70, rarely gave them that
consolation. Hollywood, which also loves certainty and is deeply
distrustful of artistic independence, found Kubrick an
unquantifiable sum, a man driven by perfectionism and the ideal of
artistic control in an art form where collaboration, not to say
compromise, is the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paths of Glory,'' ``Lolita,'' ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``2001: A
Space Odyssey,'' ``A Clockwork Orange,'' ``The Shining,'' ``Full
Metal Jacket'' _ these are movies governed by the passion of
Kubrick's unflinching eye and by his implacable visual
intelligence. That they are also sardonic and discomfiting goes
without saying. ``Dr. Strangelove,'' which appeared in 1964, is an
unforgettable send-up of the Cold War, but it also embodies an
ironic view of America that would characterize the counterculture
of the late 1960s at its best. Yet by the time that counterculture
reached its peak of dissent, 1968, Kubrick had released ``2001: A
Space Odyssey,'' a film that transcends irony completely.
</P>
<P>
   What Kubrick's choice of projects reveals is a keen literacy _
he drew, after all, from Anthony Burgess and Vladimir Nabokov _ and
a taste for the extremes of logic, the conclusions our culture's
unexamined premises lead us to. That is the point of Jack D.
Ripper, the base commander in ``Dr. Strangelove'' who is obsessed
with the purity of his bodily fluids, and of Dr. Strangelove
himself, played memorably by Peter Sellers, a one-man embodiment of
the arms race. That is the point, as well, of Humbert Humbert, who
is equally besotted with the adolescent lure of 1950s America and
with his pubescent Lolita. The visions that get at difficult truths
are not usually the ones that soothe us, and those were Kubrick's
visions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
