<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-BUCKS-NYT &LR;      03-10 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-BUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING HURT AS KNICKS FALL TO BUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was the same opponent, the same unsettling scene.
There was Patrick Ewing, the New York Knicks' center leaping to tip
off the game against the Milwaukee Bucks. Then he came up limping
and wincing, and he left the court in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Just 29 seconds into the Knicks' 87-86 loss to the Bucks Tuesday
night at Madison Square Garden, Ewing walked off the court with a
sore left Achilles' tendon. A magnetic resonance imaging
examination showed no tendon disruption, according to the team
physician, Dr. Norman Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was listed as day-to-day with tendinitis, a far better
prognosis than the one he was handed the last time he left the
court and went to the hospital. On Dec. 20, 1997, Milwaukee's
Andrew Lang put a hard foul on Ewing that sent him crashing to the
floor at the Bradley Center. A day later, Ewing had surgery to
repair torn ligaments and a dislocated bone in his shooting hand.
He missed the last 56 games of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks reached the second round of the playoffs last season
without Ewing before being eliminated by the Indiana Pacers.
Tuesday night, they came undone against the Bucks. Latrell Sprewell
was left exposed in a defensive mental lapse. Sucked in by a
pick-and-roll, he left 3-point artist Dell Curry alone in the right
corner of the court. Curry shot a perfect arching 3-pointer with
3.4 seconds left to give the Bucks a comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's chance at redemption, a 25-footer at the buzzer,
banged off the rim. The Knicks, who had played with an awakened
sense of urgency in Ewing's absence, were left crestfallen and
wondering how they let go of a four-point lead with 54 seconds to
play.
</P>
<P>
   All of the energy Larry Johnson had poured out to score a
team-high 19 points and grab seven rebounds to counter Robinson's
27 points.
</P>
<P>
   All of the right things that Sprewell accomplished off the bench
in scoring 17. All of the good turned bad in the time it took Curry
to release a smooth 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left Dell and it was totally my fault,'' Sprewell said.
``Knowing how good of a shooter he is, I should have stayed on him.
You're reacting to what's going on. It was my fault.'' The blame
had to be shared, though.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston disappeared during the game under a 4-for-16
shooting night. And in the last 54 seconds of the game, mistakes
and misses put the Knicks (10-8) in position to lose only their
second game at home this season.
</P>
<P>
   After getting a defensive stop, the ball ended up in Chris
Childs' hands. Trying to dribble among three defenders, he lost the
ball, turned and had to foul Terrell Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks' point guard hit two free throws to cut the Knicks'
lead to two points. A miss by Johnson with 17 seconds left opened
the door for the Bucks to send the Knicks to another loss at the
buzzer. It was their third in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't finish games right now,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy
said. ``Other teams are making and we're missing. Without Patrick,
we need guys to step up and be efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing missed Monday's practice and Tuesday's shoot-around
because of the soreness he has felt since the Cleveland game nine
days ago. ``I felt it pull and was concerned,'' he said, ``so I
took myself out of the game. I hope to return soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks led by 78-71 after a 3-pointer by Childs with just
over 7 minutes left in the game. But the Bucks were not ready to
buckle just yet. In a game of catch, the Bucks (11-5) kept pace
with the Knicks and then tied them at 82-82 when Robinson uncorked
a 3-pointer in front of a late-arriving Sprewell with two minutes
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Childs hit two free throws with 1 minute 24 seconds left to give
the Knicks back the lead, 84-82. That effort was topped when
Sprewell popped up for an 18-foot jumper over Ray Allen to put the
Knicks ahead, 86-82, with 54 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, in the second year of his four-year, $68 million
contract, had been remarkably healthy until last season. He has
played with tendinitis in both knees for years, but at 36, he has
shown some signs of wear.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was working himself back into shape after losing
precious workout time due to his leadership during the pro
basketball lockout, Ewing has had a couple of nagging injuries. He
had a sprained right knee in the preseason, and then injured his
Achilles' tendon against Cleveland last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby, Sprewell and Ewing's insurance man, Chris Dudley,
were pressed into heavy minutes last night. Dudley, who was signed
to a 4-year, $28 million deal before the season as a safety net for
Ewing, can rebound and defend the post but is an offensive
liability.
</P>
<P>
   Camby can play center, but can be tentative around the basket
and is not an assertive force on the defensive boards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
