<SLUG> BC-BK-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOODLES' HAS HIT REBOUNDING STRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To fans and foes, he's freshman forward JaRon
Rush. To UCLA coaches and teammates, he's Noodles _ a nickname
given him by guard Baron Davis to describe Rush's dancing technique
and his limber physique.
</P>
<P>
   Sleek and slender, Rush uses his frame to slither through the
lane and establish rebounding position against bigger, stronger
opponents in the low post. He is UCLA's top rebounder (7.1 per
game) and has six double-figure rebounding games. No one else has
more than three.
</P>
<P>
   Rush credits quickness and positioning for his success: he was
taught years ago that most errant shots carom long, so he creates
space for himself opposite the shooter's side of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Davis credits instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like Dennis Rodman,'' Davis said. ``He has a knack for
knowing where the ball is. He's a baby Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush played center in high school but never expected this
success, especially in his first season. He figured to grab two or
three rebounds per game and help the big men, Dan Gadzuric and
Jerome Moiso. His approach changed when he returned from Christmas
break a few days late because of homesickness, and guard Earl
Watson, his closest friend, was waiting with a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Watson had seen DePaul freshman Quentin Richardson corral at
least 10 rebounds in several December games, and he dared Rush to
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do what he's doing,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   He almost did, grabbing 32 rebounds in the next three games.
Suddenly, Noodles was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what he is,'' Davis said. ``He's a noodle.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad seed: The No. 5-seeded Bruins must overcome Detroit and
their own tournament history Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Since the NCAA field expanded to 64 teams in 1985, the Bruins
have been a No. 1 or 2 seed three times (1992, 1995, 1997) and
always advanced to the regional finals.
</P>
<P>
   However, of the eight times they have been lower than a No.2
seed, they've survived the first weekend only twice: in 1990, when
they upset Kansas, and last year, when they surprised Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have lost in the first round three times in the 1990s
_ twice as a No. 4 seed (Penn State, Princeton) and once as a No.5
seed (Tulsa).
</P>
<P>
   Over the wall: Watson endured a mid-February stretch in which he
averaged 8.8 points, made 11 of 31 shots and committed 17 turnovers
in four games. The trainers offered some advice: Take a load off _
and in the last three games, Watson has scored 57 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hit the wall in the Bay Area,'' he said of the Feb.
11-13 road trip. ``The trainers told me to take a day off and have
less contact work when I practice, and that's helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, everything's easier. It's just coming to me. Since I got
my health back, I'm more patient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
