<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS EDGE JAGR BY ONE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Credit Coach Robbie Ftorek for the success of the
Devils this season, and credit his decision to form a line of Jason
Arnott centering for the two young wings from the Czech Republic,
Petr Sykora and Patrik Elias.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora has particularly established himself as a top player for
the Devils. After drifting between the minor leagues and the Devils
for the last three seasons, the 22-year-old right wing is anchoring
the Devils' attack, leading the team in scoring with 55 points.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora and Arnott had a goal and an assist each Tuesday night in
leading the Devils to a 3-2 triumph over the Penguins, whose two
goals were scored by Jaromir Jagr. Elias also had an assist, giving
the line 44 points in their last 11 games for the Devils, who
improved to 36-21-8 overall and 22-8-2 away from New Jersey, the
best road record in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora has been the most consistent member of the line. His
points Tuesday night marked the 18th time that he had multiple
points in a game, leading the team in that category. This was also
the sixth consecutive game in which he registered at least a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really starting to blossom,'' Ftorek said earlier this
week about Sykora, who has 23 goals and 32 assists and leads the
Devils in both categories. ``He's played well offensively and
defensively, and he has played physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek's last remark merits more attention because Sykora had
problems withstanding physical play in his first two seasons.
Although he has been targeted by some teams this season, he has
absorbed some crunching hits without serious harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people try to hit me,'' Sykora said, ``but for me the
best way to take revenge is get points against them. I was very
happy tonight because we played against their best line.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant the line with Jagr, who is the league's leading scorer.
Jagr could have had one or two more goals in the third period were
it not for Martin Brodeur, who made 21 saves to earn his 30th
victory (30-18-8).
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur became only the sixth goaltender in the history of the
league to record 30 or more victories in at least four consecutive
seasons. Brodeur accomplished the feat in his ninth consecutive
start and 14th in the last 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered to be with those big names,'' Brodeur said,
referring to goaltenders such as Terry Sawchuk and Ken Dryden.
``I'm happy to get it. I didn't know about it until this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur's only blemishes Tuesday night were Jagr's 30th and 31st
goals, marking the eighth consecutive season he has scored at last
30 goals. His first goal came from the low slot after a pass from
behind the goal by Robert Lang, 10 minutes 13 seconds into the
game. His second came with 2:59 left in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the Devils scored all their goals, all in the late
stages of the first period. Brendan Morrison scored his 10th of the
season with 4:07 left in the period and Sykora got his 23rd with a
blast from the outer perimeter of the left circle 33 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott extended the lead to 3-1 with his 20th goal with 31.1
seconds left in the session, and Brodeur took it from there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
