</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NASSAU-TAX-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE COMPTROLLER URGES COUNTY TO OVERHAUL PROPERTY TAXES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ For the first time, New York's state comptroller
has called for the complete overhaul of Nassau County's archaic
property tax system, which the federal government says
discriminates against black and Hispanic homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear the system is not fair, and all of Nassau County's
residents are paying the price,'' the state Comptroller, H. Carl
McCall, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, a Democrat, who has been critical of the assessment
system since 1994, said he had repeatedly urged the
Republican-controlled government of Nassau County to update the
system. But after reading a Justice Department report that said
black and Hispanic homeowners were assessed at higher rates than
white homeowners, he said, he decided that a completely new system
was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it discriminatory,'' he said of Nassau's property
tax, ``but inequities within the system are costing the county
hundreds of millions of dollars a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nassau's property tax system has generated a large number of
lawsuits from taxpayers who have successfully argued that their
property was overassessed. And to pay claims in these judgments,
the financially strapped county has had to issue more debt in what
has become a never ending downward spiral, said McCall.
</P>
<P>
   That debt now totals $818 million, fully 45 percent of the
county's total outstanding debt of $1.8 billion, according to a
recent state review of Nassau's finances by the state comptroller.
While nearly 85 percent of the total debt is due to judgments for
overassessed commercial properties, the judgments for homeowners
add at least $100 million a year to the debt.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has been required by state law to issue regular reports
on Nassau County's finances since 1994, after the county issued
debt to end a 1992 general fund deficit of $65 million. With the
county again experiencing fiscal difficulties _ a projected deficit
of $150 million for 1998 and at least $100 million for 1999 _
McCall has urged a review of its assessment practices, which are
based on 1938 construction costs and 1964 land values.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Vieser, a spokesman for Nassau County Executive Thomas S.
Gulotta, said the county executive had no immediate comment on
calls for the system's reform. But he said Gulotta was now working
on a plan aimed at reducing the debt and meeting other concerns
raised earlier by McCall.
</P>
<P>
   He said the county executive would be announcing the details of
the plan soon, perhaps as early as next week. Gulotta, who has held
the line on taxes to stay in office, has not proposed new taxes
since 1994.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gulotta also declined to comment on a ruling on Monday by a
state judge rejecting a move by the county to dismiss a suit by six
Nassau property owners challenging the county's tax assessment
system as racially discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Fredrich, the lawyer who handled the case for the
county, said the county hadn't decided yet whether to appeal or go
to trial, but added that it would rely on past court rulings that
upheld the county assessment system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several years ago, there were challenges that claimed that the
county assessed at different rates in different areas, creating
inequities, but the county proved the differences were
insignificant and that all areas were assessed under the same
methodology,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's decision added weight to the Justice Department
charges. U.S. Attorney Zachary W. Carter sent a letter to Gulotta
last week stating that a government investigation ``revealed that
owners of residential property in predominantly minority areas
unfairly pay millions of dollars more in county property taxes than
they would pay if property were assessed on a nondiscriminatory
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the government would delay filing a suit if the
county made an effort to settle the matter through negotiation.
Gulotta, in a letter to Carter, rejected the government's view,
and, like Ms. Fredrich, insisted that the county's tax assessment
system was fair and that its constitutionality had been upheld in
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Federal lawyers noted, however, that all past court rulings were
not in favor of the county. For example, 10 years ago, a state
Supreme Court justice, Leo McGinity, found that the assessment
system was irrational, inequitable and illegal, and he ordered the
county to reassess. While McGinity's ruling was overturned in 1994,
the case never addressed the question of racial or ethnic
inequities.
</P>
<P>
   McGinity's decision also encouraged a study of the assessment
process by the Nassau Citizens Budget Committee. Phoebe Goodman,
executive director of the private panel, said it would cost between
$30 million and $40 million for the county to reassess. She said
that under state law, part of the cost would be absorbed by the
state.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled Tuesday that the study determined that close to
half of the county's residential property owners would see an
overall tax decrease, while a quarter of all owners would see an
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goodman said the committee concluded that the most equitable
way to assess property was at full market value and recommended
that reassessments be made often and on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said last week's ruling and the action taken by the
Justice Department against the county added credence to what he has
been telling county leaders for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the convergence of these two events will bring
about a complete overhaul of this unfair assessment process,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
