u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-EXPOS-BOS     03-10 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
PAVANO NO LONGER FEELS LIKE MARKED MAN
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-EXPOS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ It happens so often now that Carl Pavano
minds only when it's a family member who introduces him as the man
who gave up Mark McGwire's 70th home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not mom or dad,'' Pavano said with a laugh here after
facing his former team, the Red Sox, in Montreal's 6-5, 10-inning
exhibition win Tuesday at City of Palms Park. ``But it's been done.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come up to me and say, `Oh, so you're the guy who gave
up the home run to McGwire.' Maybe I should just tattoo it on my
forehead. No name. Just the number 70.''
</P>
<P>
   The words are delivered without rancor and seasoned with humor.
Maybe it's because he understands that history permits no do-overs,
but Pavano has come to terms with a moment that at first gripped
him with shame.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano, in his only relief appearance of the 1998 season,
delivered the fastball that McGwire launched into legend last Sept.
27 in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought it was the end of the world,'' he said.
``I flew home after the game ashamed of it.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months earlier, he had done a TV interview in which
he said he never would want to be the pitcher watching the ball
going over the fence. ``And that's exactly what happened,'' he
said. ``I'd turn on the TV, and there I was, watching it go over.''
</P>
<P>
   But once he was safely back in Southington, Conn., Pavano
stepped back and developed a different take on the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time went on,'' he said, ``I realized this was not
something that was going to hinder my career. It wasn't something
that was going to help it, but it wasn't going to hurt it, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of history, part of the game. Every year, something
has happened to me. In '97, I was traded for Pedro Martinez. In
'98, the 70th home run. This year, I don't know what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As a native New Englander, he knows how a single play affected
Bill Buckner. This, he said, wasn't Mookie Wilson's ground ball
dribbling between Buckner's legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``For Buckner, that kind of ruined his
career. Hopefully, I have a lot of years left.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no reason to believe otherwise. This winter, Pavano
bought a house in Palm Beach Gardens, close to the Expos' training
facility in Jupiter, worked out religiously, and has avoided the
kind of arm ailments that traditionally plague him during camp.
After a debut season in which he went 6-9 with a 4.21 ERA for the
Expos, Pavano could come out of camp as Montreal's No. 2 starter,
behind 14-game winner Dustin Hermanson.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching against the Red Sox Tuesday could not compare to the
first time he took the mound in Fenway Park last July, when the Sox
rocked him for six runs on eight hits and drove him from the mound
in the fifth inning of a 15-0 loss. Pavano gave up a long home run
to Mike Stanley in his three innings of work, but he was satisfied
with his outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just spring training,'' he said. ``You just go out and
do what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavano said he never had trouble accepting being traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that was a no-brainer,'' he said. ``You're going to
trade a guy with no major league experience for a guy who won the
Cy Young Award.''
</P>
<P>
   And he harbors no ill feelings toward the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't thank the organization enough,'' he said. ``They gave
me all the opportunities in the world. I was 20 years old and I was
in Double A, 21 and in Triple A. A lot of my success I owe to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was an adjustment. New manager, new pitching coach,
new teammates, and old friends now on the other side of the
Canadian border. The transition took time. It helped, he said, to
read the good things Martinez said about him even after he was lit
up by the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to hear those things from a fellow competitor,''
he said. ``He's a first-class guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos share their training complex with the Cardinals, but
the clubhouses are so far apart that Pavano has yet to encounter
McGwire. He's thought about asking McGwire to sign a few things for
him, especially a T-shirt they're selling in the stadium souvenir
shop on which both players are featured.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has sent word through the Expos' clubhouse man that
he'll sign whatever Pavano asks him to sign.
</P>
<P>
   But a word to fans: Don't ask Pavano to sign a photo of McGwire.
A picture of the two of them together, OK. But he says it would be
as ludicrous for him to sign a photo of McGwire as it would for the
home run king to sign a photo of the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're ever introduced,'' he said, ``I wouldn't be
embarrassed. I'd say hi.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavano laughed. ``I don't think he'd go, `Oh, so you're Carl
Pavano.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than exchanging pleasantries, Pavano said he is looking
forward to standing on the mound when McGwire steps into the
batter's box. The last time, Expos manager Felipe Alou had told his
pitchers to challenge Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wasn't going to mess with fate,'' Pavano said.
``There were 52,000 people yelling and screaming. It was a big
carnival. Every time a pitcher threw a ball, there were boos.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will happen the next time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it all the time,'' he said. ``I visualize it all
the time. Yesterday, I went to a game and watched him hit, and I
was visualizing how I was going to get him out the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably throw him sliders and changeups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
