<HEADLINE>
KARL UNABLE TO BURY BITTERNESS WITH WEALTH, POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ He talks endlessly about being liberated. Then,
George Karl wants badly to show you why he feels this way most
days.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with a 10-minute drive along the city's lakefront.
Karl has traveled the half-scenic, half-industrial route to the
Milwaukee Bucks practice facility in his red Ford Expedition a
hundred times already.
</P>
<P>
   However, you get the impression that every trip reinforces his
appreciation for a new quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get in your boat and sail to Chicago or Detroit,''
says Karl, pointing toward Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   These are fine times for Karl. The winningest coach in Sonics
franchise history is in his first season as coach of the Bucks.
That life is good is most noticeable when Karl steps into his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Karl's coaching existence wallowed in disarray.
But the only mess present on this day are papers scattered about
his wooden desk _ on which sits the same Sonics-logo-bearing name
plate he used in Seattle _ and moving boxes misplaced throughout
the room.
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee, Karl says he finally has peace of mind. That goes
well with a four-year, $20 million contract, a young team with
playoff hopes, and bosses that respect his desire for personnel
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   There are no more futile arguments with Sonics president Wally
Walker. No more worries about contract status. No more feeling of
disrespect. Everything is basketball, and in Karl, the Bucks
completely trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, I've coached more in 15 games than I've coached in 50 in
Seattle. I'm coaching like I'm in the playoffs every night. It's
uplifting. It's invigorating,'' Karl said. ``I actually talk to my
owner (Sen. Herb Kohl) often. It's tedious but I like that. There's
a togetherness here.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what I take out of Seattle is a tradition of excellence
that we built. Now it's like, can we re-identify that in another
place? Can we have some tradition and a championship? It gets you a
little juiced.''
</P>
<P>
   Juice turns to bittersweet Wednesday night when Karl and his
Bucks face his former team for the first time. While Karl says he
is content, a large part of him still wishes the Seattle franchise
could have gratified him more.
</P>
<P>
   But Karl said that became increasingly impossible as his
relationship with Walker rapidly deteriorated the past two seasons.
Still bitter about the split, Karl remains dumbfounded 10 months
after the Sonics let his contract expire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally totally discontinued the communication,'' Karl said.
``He said it's because I talked too much. I say it's because he's
incompetent. You could say (his reason for firing me) was an attack
of character and you could say it was laughable because the league
was laughing about it. There were very few things negative about
Seattle outside of Wally. I believe in doing the right things and I
don't think he does. He's a politician. He's a trickster. And
that's opposite of how I handle my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Karl, at 47, hasn't changed one bit.
</P>
<P>
   He still is the same fiery coach who kept Seattle's ear bent
with his candidness. And Seattle, it seems, is never far away; his
wife and two children still live in their Eastside home.
</P>
<P>
   The team picture hanging on the wall in his office is not of the
Bucks, but the 1992-93 Sonics. ``The best team I ever had,'' Karl
said. He even owns a brick from Safeco Field with his name and
``Respect the game'' inscribed on it.
</P>
<P>
   Karl doesn't own a home in Milwaukee. He lives in a hotel suite
three blocks from the Bradley Center where the Bucks play.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Karl's coaching enthusiasm has been sparked by the
opportunity to turn Milwaukee around. After eight losing seasons,
Karl has his team positioned to earn a playoff berth for the first
time since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between the team being new and the city being new, it's
refreshed George,'' said Bucks assistant coach Terry Stotts, who
was Karl's top assistant in Seattle. ``There's always pressure in
coaching. The challenges here are obviously different than in
Seattle. But you see a bounce in his step. The freshness carries
over in a lot of aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Sonics arrive, they will immediately sense Karl's
influence on the Bucks. His picture graces the team's media guide,
magnet calendars and billboards around the city. He demands that
his players run around the court, trapping and pressing on defense.
He has imparted the same winning attitude in Milwaukee that he did
upon arriving in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great fit because when you see him, he's not straight
across the board,'' Bucks guard Ray Allen said. ``He doesn't have
to conform. He does things his way. I think that's important. He's
come in here and he's made it our program, our franchise. He allows
us to do it together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's also the type of person who will humble you. He's like,
`So what, you're talented? You still have to work hard.' And that's
been good. You need that to win.''
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee, Karl doesn't have the superstar point guard that
he had in Gary Payton, or veteran leadership up and down the
roster. Karl is getting used to players with a much lower threshold
for pain, and he's had to rid the team of a few bad habits.
</P>
<P>
   There are internal conflicts. Free-agent-to-be point guard
Terrell Brandon won't commit to the team. Forward Tyrone Hill wants
to be traded if Brandon goes. Karl is already resigned to the fact
it will take a couple of years to mold the Bucks into a consistent
winner.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Karl is getting the most out of his players,
just as he did with the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's intense,'' Bucks forward Glenn Robinson said. ``He likes
to win, and he knows how to get his players fired up and get us
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Two nights ago, the Bucks trailed the Chicago Bulls by 15 points
in the first half. Milwaukee trailed the entire game until the
fourth quarter. Karl detonated, trimmed his rotation to seven
players and called upon his ``attitude team.'' The Bucks turned up
the heat defensively, stifled the Bulls down the stretch and won
the game, 81-76.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very successful because of my energy every day, my passion
every day,'' Karl said. ``There's daily leadership and direction
here. It's harder now, but it's a good challenge. In Seattle, we
were on cruise control.''
</P>
<P>
   That was on the court. Off the court is where Karl often
experienced bumpy rides.
</P>
<P>
   Everything isn't smooth in Milwaukee, but it's close enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are days I'm scared,'' Karl said. ``The strangest thing
about it is I don't know my team like I knew my team in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Karl believes coaching against his former players
will be fun. He's kept one eye on the Sonics' transition while
going through his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know their personality. I know when to double-team. I know
who to put on Gary if it's a fourth-quarter game,'' Karl said. ``We
present some problems to them. We've got some (players) who give us
an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no, I'm not happy when they (the Sonics) lose. I wish the
players could win and Wally lose. But I don't think that can
happen. The game itself is going to be 90-percent positive. Seeing
Wally sitting over there ... the game should be fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of memories in Seattle. I love it here and I'm
enjoying the change. But Seattle will always be in my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
