<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE DEFIES PANTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-BRUINS-PANTHERS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By NANCY L. MARRAPESE 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coach had started to get a little anxious about his top
goaltender. Byron Dafoe at times had shown a tendency to wander a
little too far, to take a few too many chances, to put himself in
danger during games.
</P>
<P>
   So several days ago, Pat Burns took Dafoe aside, telling him to
wait that extra second, to make the opposing players come to him
instead of the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of that powwow at practice and partly because of
some flat-out remarkable saves, Dafoe earned his 14th career
shutout and seventh of the season Tuesday night in a 2-0 win over
the Florida Panthers at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Bruins into sole possession of the eighth
and final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference, 2 points ahead of
the Rangers and 3 ahead of the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a tendency at times, especially when we as a team are
struggling, to try to do too much,'' said Dafoe. ``I force the
shooter, I dive out at pucks that I shouldn't. Pat talked to me
about that last week a little bit. He told me I'm quick enough to
just sit back and wait for them to make the first move.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe had 19 saves for win No. 22. The game-saver came with
Boston clinging to a 1-0 lead in the third period. At 9:14, with
Florida at the tail end of a power play, Ray Whitney fired a shot
from the right circle that Dafoe kicked out with his right pad.
Defenseman Robert Svehla swooped in for the rebound and tried a
shot from the slot. Dafoe dived across the crease from right to
left and threw out his stick in time to block Svehla's shot that
was earmarked for a spot inside the left post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a rebound I kicked out, and all I could do really
was fall back and put my stick on the ice,'' said Dafoe. ``He had
the whole net and obviously he was pressured and he just shot it on
the ice and it hit my stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Ray Bourque gave the Bruins the only goal they would
need at 9:45 of the second period, scoring on the power play. Jason
Allison drew the penalty _ a holding call on defenseman Paul Laus _
and assisted on the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Khristich, who had a pair of assists, set up Bourque by
skating the puck into the far left circle and pulling up along the
boards. He caught Bourque coming down the slot and fired a quick
pass over. It was Bourque's seventh goal of the season, one of his
five shots in the period. It was the 150th power-play goal of
Bourque's 20-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after killing off a two-man disadvantage for 31 seconds
midway through the third, the Bruins got an insurance goal.
</P>
<P>
   Khristich took a shot from the slot that caromed off the right
pad of goalie Sean Burke and over to Allison at the left post.
Allison tried to get his stick on the puck but it ricocheted off
his right skate and into the net at 11:38.
</P>
<P>
   Only two Boston skaters _ Landon Wilson (who left with what was
reported as a mild concussion at 3:05 of the second) and Ken
Belanger (who had just 3:32 of ice time) _ did not land a shot on
Burke (39 saves).
</P>
<P>
   It was a dominant performance by the Bruins and another
star-making performance by Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe a lot of that to the guys in front of me,'' the goalie
said. ``I'm thankful to Pat Burns for giving me the opportunity and
I'm thankful for the guys in front of me who play a system that is
great for goaltenders.''
</P>
<P>
   They can't savor this one for long. The Bruins face the Rangers
and Sabres in back-to-back road games Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play .500 from now until the end of the year, it will
give us about 83 points or so,'' said Burns. ``That won't be
enough. We're going to have to play more than just .500 hockey.
It's going to be tough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
