<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UW-MACCULLOCH-SPI     03-10 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UW-MACCULLOCH-SPI </SLUG>
  
 OFF THE COURT, MacCULLOCH SHOOTS FOR THRILLS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On the basketball court, Todd MacCulloch goes with the
percentages. His repertoire consists of layups, put-backs and
tip-ins along with occasional bank shots and jump hooks. All, of
course, are taken within five feet of the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   It is fundamental and effective, but boring. It will be on
display again Friday night when the Huskies play Miami of Ohio in a
Midwest Region first-round NCAA tournament game at the New Orleans
Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   Matching his game, MacCulloch plays without much expression,
plodding about, seemingly indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   You can picture Donald Watts or Thalo Green with lampshades on
their heads in New Orleans this week, sampling the night life and
cutting loose.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch? Someone who won't even take a 10-footer getting
crazy? Well, here's a news flash. To those who know him, MacCulloch
is a risk-taking, thrill-seeking wild man.
</P>
<P>
   How many of his teammates have launched themselves from the top
of the West Edmonton Mall on a bungee cord? How many have
parachuted over the Manitoba prairie after hanging onto the strut
for dear life before being coaxed to let go? And who else has the
courage to jump off a cliff into a lake in British Columbia,
jeopardizing his future for a little fun in the present?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not on a death wish or anything, but I made up a list,''
he said. ``I don't have too many things left on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   He always wanted to parasail over the Mediterranean, so he paid
$30 to do that in Nice.
</P>
<P>
   That was as conservative as his buzz cut. The other stuff was
outrageous. His best friend, Jeff Krahn, watched MacCulloch climb
some rocks near Invermere, B.C., last summer. It was a serene spot
until 7 feet and 280 pounds hit the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a pretty good splash going,'' Krahn said. ``I was
looking at him, thinking: `NBA career.' And there he is standing on
the top of a rock somewhere about to jump. `Is this something he
should be doing?' The rest of us are going nowhere so it really
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Krahn also parachuted with MacCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't jump the way the rest of us did,'' Krahn said,
alluding to MacCulloch's size. ``He had to hang behind the blade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Superman hanging on the strut,'' MacCulloch said.
``I let go and a couple of seconds later, the chute fully opened. I
thought, `Well, I'm alive.' It was pure peacefulness. The prairie
looked like perfect squares on a quilt.''
</P>
<P>
   The bungee jump at the Edmonton Mall was just as exhilarating.
MacCulloch paid $60 to be thrown down toward a wave pool with his
choice of music from Canadian rockers Our Lady Piece wailing in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm so tall, there were some beams, and I had to watch
my head,'' he said. ``They told me to jump out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial jump was fun, but after that you got jerked
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Picturing MacCulloch doing any of the above is difficult given
his basketball personality. But when you talk about MacCulloch,
there are misperceptions and contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   NBA scouts love his size and touch. Everyone talks about his
great hands, which he partially developed by juggling as a
youngster. His fifth-grade teacher, Mr. Matas, was a master juggler
who taught his students during the noon hour.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch went on to win a provincial ``joggling'' contest, a
competition combining running around cones in a gym while juggling.
The skills that he learned from juggling might turn him into a
millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd's name consistently comes up in the top 30 names,'' said
Billy McKinney, Sonics executive vice president of basketball
operations.
</P>
<P>
   But then you'll hear something about his lack of passion.
``Barring injury, he could have a 12-year career if he wants it,''
said Jay Hillock, Vancouver Grizzlies director of scouting. ``He's
got the foreign mentality of seeing it (basketball) more as
recreational.''
</P>
<P>
   As a youth, it was. MacCulloch wants a pro career now. Coach Bob
Bender said the unseen passion is evident to him.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch remains laid-back only when he's elsewhere, when a
fishing rod is in his hands instead of a basketball. Growing up in
Saskatchewan and Manitoba, MacCulloch loves the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   When he gets uptight, MacCulloch imagines being at Red Deer Lake
on a summer day, water skiing at dawn, returning to a
bacon-and-eggs breakfast. His mom and aunt would pick blueberries
and whip up pancakes for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch has a watercolor painting that shows him paddling his
canoe by the boathouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see anyone,'' he said. ``There's no running water,
no electricity, just a bed, kitchen, couch, coffee table and
cupboard space. In tough times, I picture myself there.''
</P>
<P>
   If the passion is ever missing, compassion is not. MacCulloch
wants to help people. His major is an unusual one for an athlete _
speech and hearing science. If the NBA does not work out, he could
become a speech pathologist, helping others communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a very, very sensitive youngster,'' said Lois
MacCulloch, Todd's mom. ``He shows great concern for other people's
welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   It extends to animals. MacCulloch releases the fish that he
catches. Growing up, he was close to his dog, a Yorkshire Terrier
named Chainsaw.
</P>
<P>
   On one winter night in Edmonton when the temperature dropped to
40 below, MacCulloch took his dog for a walk. Chainsaw went up to a
metal light standard and licked it. His tongue got stuck to the
frozen pole.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch blew on the pole. He rubbed his mitts together. He
did everything he could to warm it up and loosen the grip. Finally,
Chainsaw was freed, but MacCulloch was shaken, returning home in
tears.
</P>
<P>
   Now he will laugh about the incident, saying Chainsaw ``didn't
have taste buds for awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   The jokes will continue, but the college career is about to end
for MacCulloch. Nothing will change, however. His size 19s are
where they should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``His value system is where it needs to be,'' his mom said.
``He's managed to keep his feet firmly on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
