<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-WOLVES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARNETT SLAMS HOME POINT: SONICS REELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ They used to strut. They used to swagger. The
Sonics used to never lose more than three games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But after Tuesday night's 85-84 loss to the Minnesota
Timberwolves, it has become clear the Sonics are a team losing more
than games.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, they have lost their edge.
</P>
<P>
   Once a dominant force in the Western Conference, the Sonics
suddenly look no better than average. If four straight losses,
including two straight to the Timberwolves, doesn't indicate an
unthinkable dropoff, the standings do.
</P>
<P>
   Once 6-0, the Sonics fell to 9-8 and are off to their worst
start since the 1990-91 season. The last time they dropped four
straight regular-season games was the 1991-92 season.
</P>
<P>
   The team that ruled the Pacific Division with four titles in the
past five years is suddenly in fourth place. Even worse, they are
eighth in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday marked the second time in four games the Sonics lost
on the final possession. They know the questions well, and it is
getting tougher and tougher for the Sonics to find the right
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think things are that dire,'' Sonics coach Paul
Westphal said. ``But obviously we need to put wins together.''
</P>
<P>
   Astounding to all, the Paul Westphal era is stuck in
mediorcrity. The good news is there are 33 games remaining for the
Sonics to snap back to form. The bad news is the timing of their
skid.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight they're in Milwaukee for a game against former coach
George Karl and his 11-6 Bucks. However, proving something to Karl
is the least of the Sonics' worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has mentioned George,'' Sonics guard Hersey Hawkins
said. ``The reporters bring up George more than we do. We're
concerned about getting out of this skid. Four (losses) in a row is
unheard of. It's getting tough for the coaching staff and the guys
who've been here. You're used to winning and all of a sudden you're
9-8. You kind of wonder what the heck is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The team is plagued by the same ills that were evident from Day
One. The offense is out of sync, and forward Vin Baker is nowhere
near the player he was a year ago. For the second straight game,
Baker took just six shots.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with six points, again crippling the Sonics with
virtually no inside presence. Baker has been bothered by
inneffective play all season and didn't bother to talk to reporters
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vin's not doing what he's supposed to be doing,'' reserve Dale
Ellis said. ``Once he comes to play basketball, we'll be a better
team. We're better than this. Once we get a few guys playing up to
their potential on a consistent basis, we'll win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite shooting 41 percent from the field, the Sonics still had
a chance to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 81-75 with 2:27 to play, Ellis hit back-to-back
3-pointers to tie the score. Hawkins eventually sank a wide-open
3-pointer to put the Sonics ahead 84-83 with 27.6 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Minnesota quickly went back in front and stayed there.
Stephon Marbury handled the ball at the top of the key with Gary
Payton guarding him. But the Wolves' Kevin Garnett screened off
Payton, which caused Baker to switch out and defend Marbury, who
blew right to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury's layup fell off, but Garnett followed with a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Payton had a chance to score the game-winner on the final
possession. But the Timberwolves double-teamed Payton, forcing him
to make a pass to Billy Owens that was muffed out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got what we wanted,'' Westphal said. ``We wanted to get
Gary in the post and let him operate. ... From what I saw, it
looked like they hammered Billy and Gary.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton finished with 10 assists and 10 points. But he was just 4
of 16 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a good job of executing and playing together to get
back in the ballgame,'' said Detlef Schrempf, who led the team with
18 points off the bench. ``But we seem to find a way to lose. I
can't remember being 9-8. I don't think I've been that since
Indiana.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
