<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGRY M'S EYE DODGERS PITCHING FEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ The Mariners have what the Los Angeles Dodgers
need. The Dodgers have what the Mariners need.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone had this to say
about the Mariners as he watched his team in Florida Tuesday:
``That's an organization I think we'd be compatible with.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most teams, the Mariners badly need a starting pitcher. The
Dodgers are one of the few teams that have a starter to give.
Further, the Dodgers' farm system was stripped of many top
prospects in trades for veterans last summer. The Mariners'
minor-league pitching is the organization's biggest source of
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has targeted Los Angeles as one of several teams in
Florida with pitching to give, and has contacted the Dodgers. The
Houston Astros and New York Mets are other clubs with a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers seem to be in the strongest position to deal,
with a starting corps of Kevin Brown, Chan Ho Park, Ismael Valdes,
Carlos Perez, Darren Dreifort and Dave Mlicki. Malone said he's
content to wait until later this spring before making a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got six starters, so maybe we could help our bullpen by
keeping all six, or try to build up the farm system (with a
trade),'' he said. ``It's early in spring, but we'll keep a couple
of these guys for a while and let it work itself out.''
</P>
<P>
   With pitching at such a premium around baseball, Malone isn't
sure he wants to give up that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know with pitchers, because so many of them seem to
go down or get hurt,'' he said. ``The worst-case scenario is that
we trade someone and someone else gets hurt. Then we'd be down to
four and looking around ourselves. I don't want to get in that
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners tried to acquire a starting pitcher during the
winter, but could not afford a top free agent and had no luck in
trades. After Jeff Fassero and Jamie Moyer, the projected rotation
falls off sharply, with talented but unproven Ken Cloude in the
third spot and an assortment of prospects and veterans competing
for the other two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners vice president of baseball operations Woody Woodward
said he remains committed to holding onto the team's young pitching
unless he gets a young, big league pitcher in return. He said he's
contacted every team about pitching but didn't sound optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you're in the market to take on some high-salary player
that may be a risk, it's a tough market to find somebody,''
Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   One eminently available starter is Kansas City's Kevin Appier,
who fits that description. The former All-Star has impressed
several clubs this spring, but he is coming off an injury and makes
$5 million, well out of Seattle's range.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR A LEFTY: Manager Lou Piniella has not been
overwhelmed by any of the left-handed relief candidates in camp,
including Mike Bertotti, Huck Flener, Damaso Marte and Greg
McCarthy, and it seems more and more likely that a left-handed
starting hopeful will have to break camp in relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good chance that (John) Halama or (Butch) Henry will
end up in the bullpen,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry had success as a reliever with the Boston Red Sox in 1997,
but Halama has not relieved at all since Class A ball in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Halama, acquired from Houston in the Randy Johnson deal, will
pitch three or four innings in his start tomorrow against Colorado
in Tucson. Piniella said he wasn't sure he would make that trip,
but decided to go because he didn't want to miss Halama's start.
</P>
<P>
   GAME NOTES: Moyer worked three strong innings in Tuesday's 6-2
win over the San Francisco Giants. The left-hander struck out four
and allowed one run, throwing all of his pitches. He will build to
four innings his next start and five the next. ... Ken Griffey Jr.
went 2-for-3 with a double and his second homer, which cleared the
right-field bullpen. ... Raul Ibanez has hits in his last five
at-bats, and Piniella said he's swinging the bat as well as anyone
in camp. Ibanez credits hitting coach Jesse Barfield with helping
him stay back when he hits. ``It's the first time I've had a
foundation in my whole life,'' said Ibanez, who is out of options
and is bidding for a spot as a reserve outfielder/catcher/first
baseman. ``When I went south, I didn't really have anything to go
back to. He's helped me make tremendous strides.'' ... Second
baseman David Bell continued to impress in the field, turning three
double plays and ranging far to his left to rob Bill Mueller of a
hit in the fifth. ... For the second day in a row, Bobby Ayala
threw a shutout inning, this time striking out the side despite
allowing two hits. ``Everything's going great so far,'' Ayala said.
``I'm happy and satisfied and it's great to be getting the ball.''
... Piniella expects to make five or six cuts after this morning's
``B'' game against San Diego. Cloude starts Wednesday's ``A'' game
against Milwaukee, with Henry to follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
