<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN A FORGOTTEN SEASON, BULLS ARE BETTER THAN NETS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The New Jersey Nets, now known around the National
Basketball Association for being unable to back up their boastful
words, entered the season bragging about how they scared the World
Champion Chicago Bulls in the first round of last season's
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being swept like a pile of dust in three games, they
talked of gaining poise and confidence from the series. Coach John
Calipari mentioned repeatedly that the Nets scored more points
against the Bulls than anyone, and unbelievably, Chris Gatling said
the stretch of games taught the team how to win.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both clubs are mere shadows of themselves now, the
Bulls because Michael Jordan retired and Scottie Pippen and Dennis
Rodman joined other teams. And the Nets because their combination
of shaky coaching and shoddy play has proved powerless.
</P>
<P>
   But despite being built to lose in order to get a high draft
pick and expensive free agents at season's end, the Bulls somehow
are still superior to the certifiably hapless Nets. With Toni Kukoc
and the aged Ron Harper acting as Jordan and Pippen, Chicago played
steamroller to New Jersey's aluminum can, blowing out their guests
by 103-87 at the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc owned the second half, scoring 18 of his game-high 28
points after intermission, and Harper owned the first, scoring 20
of his 25, as the Bulls, who average a league-low 80 points a game,
reached 100 points for the first time this year. Chicago, also the
worst shooting team in the league, made 45.7 percent of its shots
against the Nets' soft defense.
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams led the Nets (3-14) with 23 points and 12
rebounds, while Keith Van Horn added 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, who improved to 5-13, grabbed a 5-point lead at
halftime and increased it to double digits midway through the
fourth quarter. Kukoc opened the lead almost singlehandedly,
hitting long jumpers or driving to draw fouls. He made 13 of 20
shots from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   While the Nets have been much maligned for their woeful
shooting, it was their defense that did them in in the first half.
Allowing Harper to experience a Jordanesque half, they surrendered
20 points to the 35-year-old guard. Somehow able to blow by and
shoot over Kerry Kittles, Scott Burrell and Kendall Gill, Harper
made 9 of 10 shots before the break. He scored 15 in the first
quarter, when the Bulls shot 58 percent to build a 29-28 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Harper wasn't the only Bull to play above his head at the
expense of the Nets. Randy Brown, the unheralded point guard who
was a reserve during Chicago's golden years, scored 12, 4 above his
average, in the first half and picked Doug Overton of his dribble
at half court on one play.
</P>
<P>
   With defense at a minimum, the Nets competed by shooting 44
percent over the first two quarters, a low percentage for most but
blazing for New Jersey. Williams, who has of late been roasted by
legitimate centers, took delight in his matchup with Dickey
Simpkins, scoring 10 points and grabbing 6 rebounds before
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   In displaying his power during one second-quarter sequence,
Williams grabbed two offensive rebounds and made a putback to give
the Nets a 38-32 lead, their biggest of the game. But with Harper
sinking jump shots, the Bulls began chipping away at the lead and
went ahead by 45-44 when he hit a 12-footer with 3 minutes 33
seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Simpkins became active, scoring on a tip-in and
fastbreak slam off a nice feed from Kukoc that gave the Bulls a
52-47 lead. Kukoc was one of the few Bulls who could not find the
range in the first half, but he made up for it by drawing fouls.
Shooting 1 of 6 from the field, but 8 of 12 from the line, he
scored 10 first-half points to help Chicago take a 54-49 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The halftime score was surprising because, with the Nets and the
Bulls at the tail of the league rankings in field-goal percentage,
the game was billed as the battle of the bricklayers. The Nets,
shooting 39 percent on the season, entered with a 1/100th of a
percent point advantage over the last place Bulls (.389).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
