<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENDER KEEPING COOL DESPITE MARCH HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He is not a ``hot'' coach at this particular moment,
though that could change.
</P>
<P>
   If University of Washington coach Bob Bender gets his Huskies on
another NCAA tournament run this coming weekend in New Orleans, you
never know.
</P>
<P>
   This is the season for hot coaches, every bit as much as it is
the season for Dick Vitale, Digger Phelps and office pools.
</P>
<P>
   Bender knows all about this topic. Last year, thanks to the
Huskies' Sweet 16 appearance, Bender's name was hotter than a bowl
of French Quarter gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   From Virginia to Texas, Bender was the next great savior of
college hoops, or something like that. But after a week or two of
flirtation, Bender decided _ after one bike ride through the Lake
Washington Arboretum _ that he liked it in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching intrigue is all part of March's madness, not that
Bender gets terribly caught up in this game within the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a hot coach. I've been a cold coach. But I think I'm
best described as lukewarm. I'm just lukewarm,'' Bender said, then
flew off to the Big Easy with his team.
</P>
<P>
   Humor is a good quality in basketball coaches, especially those
whose programs demand not only an appearance in the NCAA tourney,
but that you actually go and do something.
</P>
<P>
   Bender may not have that kind of pressure on him, yet. His two
wins and Sweet 16 run last year gives him a nice cushion.
</P>
<P>
   He is really just getting rolling at Washington, where it should
take only a few more seasons of losing recruits to Stanford and
Arizona before Bender has to worry whether he made a mistake by not
taking advantage of his hot status last year.
</P>
<P>
   You can string together all sorts of 18- or 20-win seasons. You
can win your conference championship. You can even have a hand in
developing NBA stars.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains, right or wrong: What you do in March is
ultimately what makes or breaks your reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is why Bender, a former Duke player and former
assistant to Blue Devils coach Mike Krzyzewski, has called upon his
Duke mentor several times the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got off the phone with him a few minutes ago,'' Bender
said.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of proportion and history and where things fit in helps
during these crazy days of March, even if Coach K is working toward
``coaching god'' status with his 32-1 Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rollie Massimino wins a national championship at Villanova. He
coaches what many say is the perfect game (in 'Nova's 66-64 upset
of Georgetown in the 1985 championship game). But he can't get back
to that and expectations grew and, suddenly, some people start to
question you,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   That is Bender's best example of the trouble March brings.
</P>
<P>
   It is a common affliction, which is why Jim Boeheim at Syracuse
has spent years fighting the demons that say his NCAA
``shortcomings'' have blotted his reputation _ even if it was
Derrick Coleman's missed free throws that killed Syracuse during
the 1987 championship game, not Keith Smart's last-second shot for
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Knight, the coach Bender played for during the Hoosiers'
1976 NCAA championship season, has a tough first-round game against
George Washington this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Will Knight win and dampen criticism that his time is past at
Indiana, where first-round busts have made some of the Hoosier
faithful impatient?
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about coach Knight, he isn't worried about the
match-up. He's only worried about Indiana,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   It also is why Jim Calhoun of Connecticut, the No. 1 seed in the
West, heads into his eighth NCAA tournament in the '90s still
looking for UConn's first Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, Bender's Huskies were just one Richard Hamilton
buzzer-beater away from being part of Calhoun's NCAA nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make it to the Final Four, I won't be any better of a
coach, and if we don't, I won't be any worse,'' Calhoun said last
week when the touchy subject was broached.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all around the country, Calhoun's bretheren in the
Division I coaching fraternity know that Calhoun is whistling
Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   It does matter. What happens in these next two weeks carries
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Does Jim Harrick, gone in semidisgrace from UCLA and now at
Rhode Island, again prove himself a NCAA stalwart by upsetting
UNC-Charlotte in the first round?
</P>
<P>
   Does Mike Jarvis, in his first season at St. John's, further
embellish his credentials by leading the Red Storm to the Sweet 16
or beyond?
</P>
<P>
   Does ex-Texas coach Tom Penders, now at George Washington, have
his next moment of glory, upsetting Knight and the Hoosiers?
</P>
<P>
   Does Paul Hewitt at little Siena become the next candidate for
Pittsburgh, exactly 10 years after former Siena coach Mike Deane
got hot in the 1989 NCAA tournament, when the Saints upset
Stanford?
</P>
<P>
   March brings answers. March also raises questions. This is why a
well-schooled coach like Bender said he inspected the tournament
brackets. He had to check up on his fraternity mates, guys like
Delaware's Mike Brey, New Mexico State's Lou Henson, former Oregon
coach Jerry Green, and Rick Barnes, who went from Rhode Island to
take the job Bender bowed out of at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's part of our game. It's part of our business,
especially if you have somewhat of a relationship,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the guys Bender was most interested in was Gonzaga's Dan
Monson, whose Bulldogs are the No. 10 seed in Seattle, going up
against No. 7 Minnesota Thursday at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of hot coaches, there is talk that Monson could have
his name in the hopper for coaching jobs in bigger conferences,
especially if Gonzaga (of the West Coast Conference) can get hot
and knock off the Gophers.
</P>
<P>
   Bender, a close friend of Monson, said that so far the two have
not addressed the hot-coach issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Dan) did ask about travel parties. He's just getting killed
for requests for tickets and hotels,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   But those are the minor hassles and anxieties of March. For
coaches _ be they hot, cold or even lukewarm _ there is a lot more
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
