</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
VOSKUHL HAS TO WATCH STEP
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-UCONN-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By JOE BURRIS 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ In a couple of weeks the NCAA Tournament will be
complete, and Jake Voskuhl can find a comfortable place to recline
and stay off his left foot for as long as it takes to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the University of Connecticut junior center is like
an automobile trekking along a desolate stretch of road, miles away
from the desired destination, with the ``check engine'' light on.
</P>
<P>
   He must take things slowly, do as much maintenance as possible
and pray for the best until he reaches the end. And Voskuhl plans
to do just that, knowing that this UConn team has arguably the best
chance of any of making it to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I ice three times a day,'' said Voskuhl Tuesday,
minutes after UConn's first practice since arriving in Denver
Monday night for Thursday's West Regional first-round game against
Texas-San Antonio. Battling a recurring stress reaction in his
foot, he played a total of 30 minutes in the Huskies' final two Big
East tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ice when I wake up, before practice and after practice,''
said Voskuhl. ``I also have two bone stimulators that I use, one
for 20 minutes, twice a day. The other one I keep on for 8-10 hours
a day. Whenever I'm not doing anything I just wrap it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl said he expects to play and be effective during the
Tournament, and whether he's correct might determine how far the
Huskies go. His presence is invaluable: Though he averages just 5.9
points a game, Voskuhl is second in rebounding, is one of the
team's best defenders, and he forces opponents to respect UConn's
interior.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl missed both Syracuse games because of his foot injury;
the latter contest was the Huskies' season finale. Yet he came back
in the Big East tournament and played steadily. Meanwhile, his foot
_ which once bothered him so much in high school he required a
wheelchair to get around until it healed _ has been progressing
steadily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good, really good,'' he said. ``Coach (Jim Calhoun) has
been with me 100 percent through this. There are certain drills in
practice I don't do. I think it's important up here for me to
practice, because I have to start getting my wind back.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun Tuesday limited Voskuhl to one hour of the
1-hour-40-minute practice session. ``We'll push him a little more
in practice but pull him out, hopefully, at the appropriate times
so he won't have three days of straight practices,'' said Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun expects Voskuhl to play about 20 minutes a game. The
center played 21 minutes in the Huskies' first-round game against
Seton Hall in the Big East tournament. He has not played 25 minutes
of a game since Feb. 13 at Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I try to do is make sure he doesn't have pain, as opposed
to, `When you have pain you tell me,' said Calhoun. ``On the MRI
that was done 12 days ago, he actually had healing going on, which
is unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he really gets it sore, he can't play, because the pain
is too much and he's limping. When he gets sore, he makes the coach
look bad because he's limping and people say, `That (expletive),
he's worse than we thought he was; he's playing that kid.' But
structurally we see nothing but improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl said he will play through as much pain as he can stand
during the NCAA Tournament. He said there are signs that tell him
he is in for a struggle, adding sometimes he can't run as fast or
jump as high. ``But it's almost healed up, so I'm just working on
it every single day,'' he said. ``All the things humanly possible
that can be done, we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely Calhoun had Voskuhl in mind when he decided to come to
Denver Monday night to get his players acclimated to the high
altitude. He said the team will spend the days leading up to the
game working on sprinting and added he will rotate more players in
than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said the same approach worked in 1995, when UConn played
in the first round in Salt Lake City, beating Tennessee-Chattanooga
in the first round and Cincinnati in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those games, we made a conscious effort to try to get
people in early, so in the last 10 to 12 minutes we had people in
who were fresher,'' said Calhoun. ``We took it as a factor to deal
with. Is it a major factor? Well, when you're talking about 19, 20
year olds, probably not. But if it it causes one of your real good
players to not be able to play 28 minutes, but 22 minutes, then
it's a factor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
