<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
A BOSTON HOME BOY RETURNS
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-TYLER-MIAMI-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MARK BLAUDSCHUN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Elton Tyler never knew for sure. Some days seemed so
normal. His mother, Eleanor, would be home, along with other family
members. Brothers. Sisters. Aunts. Uncles. Grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``As many as 12 of us,'' Tyler was saying Tuesday with a smile
as he and his University of Miami teammates prepared for their NCAA
first-round East Regional game against Lafayette Friday night at
the FleetCenter. ``All living in a three-bedroom apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days Eleanor would be there when Tyler came home. Some days
she wouldn't. Elton's father, Elton Elmore, was just as elusive,
moving in and out of his son's life.
</P>
<P>
   Some days Elton would come home. Some days he wouldn't; he might
hang out at a friend's house, depending on his mood.
</P>
<P>
   Usually he would be playing ball, listening and watching as the
street stories of Roxbury unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   All of it seemed normal, because that's all he knew. There was
support, although it may have been loosely structured. Sometimes
there was too much, too many opinions on how he should do things.
</P>
<P>
   When that happened, Elton took off. Not for long. He always came
back, catching up with the family business and the doings of his
older brother Kareem and his younger sister Nichelle.
</P>
<P>
   What Elton Tyler wanted to do was play basketball. Oh, not at
first. At first he just wanted to chill with his buddies. But
across the street at Marcella Park in Roxbury, Tyler would watch
the pickup basketball games that took place every night during the
summer. He saw an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``A way out,'' said Tyler on a March day, sitting 1,500 miles
away in Florida, where the temperature was 50 degrees warmer than
in Roxbury and in an atmosphere that has given him so much
stability the past two years. ``Going to college was going to be a
big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   As a seventh grader, Elton Tyler was 5 feet 10 inches. Two years
later he was 6-5. Eleanor Tyler encouraged her son to use the
opportunity. So did his coach at West Roxbury, Thom McNair. So did
Leo Papile, whose Boston Amateur Basketball Club AAU teams were
stocked with kids like Elton Tyler looking for alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Tyler was a senior, he was more than just another
kid who would do some trash-talking at Malcolm X Park, where the
big-city pickup games were played.
</P>
<P>
   He was a prospect, recruited by schools nationwide. It didn't
matter, though. Tyler's first step was going to be a small one. He
was going to Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Mention BC and Tyler's face clouds up. ``I can't talk about
that,'' he says, at first, not explaining whether he means
``can't'' or ``won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame him? Recruited by former Boston College coach Jim
O'Brien, Tyler was part of a recruiting class (along with BABC
teammate Jonathan DePina) that was going to make the Eagles a Top
20 program.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler felt secure because he was a qualifier, someone who had
met the NCAA's minimum academic standards. He was set.
</P>
<P>
   And then he was told he wasn't. The BC admissions office swatted
away his application, deeming him unworthy, not qualified, whatever
description you want. The bottom line was that Tyler was not headed
to BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `What am I going to do now?' '' said Tyler,
who has had no glitches academically or athletically in two years
at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly he was a free agent, not sure of anything anymore. His
father, whom Elton says he was not close to, had died a year
earlier. Life at home was chaotic, especially since the recruiting
window again had been opened on a 6-9, 215-pound prospect.
</P>
<P>
   UConn called. So did George Washington and Michigan. And then
came Leonard Hamilton and Miami, who offered not only an
opportunity to stay in the Big East, but to do it in a program that
was building a foundation and in a place where you could walk
around in a T-shirt and shorts in mid- January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my visit on Martin Luther King Day,'' said Tyler,
``Once I got here, it was all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler went to Miami with no great expectations. Nor did anyone
expect too much from him.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, he has been the primary backup to Big East
Co-Player of the Year Tim James. ``What I do,'' said Tyler, ``is
bring energy into the game. The tempo picks up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton thinks Tyler can do more. ``He's got to be a more of a
tiger,'' Hamilton said. ``He hasn't come close to reaching his
potential, which is to be a very, very good ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton knows that coming back to Boston in a tournament format
can be a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was two years ago,'' Hamilton said with a sigh when asked
about the recruitment process. ``He's at the University of Miami
now. He's happy and all that stuff is behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler said he is eager to come home, but not overwhelmed. He had
his stage fright last season when he scored just 2 points in 16
minutes in Miami's first and only visit to BC's Conte Forum. He
wasn't much more productive in two games against the Eagles this
season, but the Hurricanes won both nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   As the competition gets tougher with each round, the Hurricanes
will need more than minutes from Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to coming back to Boston,'' he said. ``I'm
not sure how many of my family and friends will be there, but it's
going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler says it will be more like a business trip than a
homecoming. He won't head back to Roxbury for any quick visits.
``The focus is going to be on basketball,'' he said. ``I can come
back and visit my friends after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   As for BC and what might have been, Tyler only shrugged. ``It's
time to move on,'' he said. ``What happened, happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
