<SLUG> BC-LA-SALARIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS PRODUCE, EARN MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Employees and their bosses each received good
economic news on Tuesday with the release of reports that showed
workers produced more -- and made more money doing it.
</P>
<P>
   American workers' productivity grew at a 4.6 percent annual rate
during the final three months of 1998, the most in six years, the
U.S. Department of Labor reported. For all of 1998, productivity
gains totaled 2.2 percent, a big improvement over the 1.2 percent
gain in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last year also saw inflation-adjusted hourly wages and benefits
jump 2.6 percent, the largest gain in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   And a salary report by a New York-based human resources
consulting firm concluded that California salaries are among the
nation's highest.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity gains are especially important because they
determine a country's standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you are producing more, you can pay higher salaries
without raising prices and shooting your profits right in the
foot,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los Angeles County
Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   While salaries are on the rise, growth in unit-labor costs, a
key indicator of underlying inflation pressures, slowed. Those
costs rose 1.9 percent last year compared with 2.3 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees are now reaping the benefits of the surging
economy,'' said economist Mark Zandi of Regional Financial
Associates in West Chester, Pa. ``Both continued productivity gains
and the exceedingly tight labor market are allowing employees to
garner a bigger share of the increasing economic pie.''
</P>
<P>
   A big piece can be had in California, where there is no
tarnishing the gilding of the Golden State, concluded the wage
comparison survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Paychecks in major California locales -- like Los Angeles,
Ventura and Orange counties -- are among the highest in the U.S.,
said the 1999 Geographic Salary Differentials Report compiled by
William M. Mercer Inc., the human resources consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer's methodology is as straight-forward as the result is
predictable. The company takes a salary for a middle-management or
technical position that averages $50,000 nationally and figures out
what employers would have to pony up to fill that job in various
cities and communities.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list this year is San Jose, where the job would
command $60,200, or 20 percent above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, it would be $58,150, or 16 percent above the
average; in Los Angeles, it would be $56,900, or 14 percent above
the average; and in Ventura County, it would be $53,150, or
approximately 6.3 percent more than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, a place like Brownsville, Texas, is Nowheresville
salary-wise. The same job in that city on the Texas Gulf Coast
would pay $41,750, or 17 percent below the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, since it's Texas, that money would probably go
farther.
</P>
<P>
   And mid-America is middle of the road in wage-earning potential.
Companies would have to pay someone $50,300 a year in Wayne, Ind.,
and Louisville, Ky., to perform that $50,000 job.
</P>
<P>
   The survey does not address where the employer would get the
most work for his or her bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser said California's high salaries reflect a continued strong
economy in the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of ... high intellect jobs, everything from
technology through the entertainment industry to management
consulting,'' he said. ``And even some in international trade. We
know that the longshoremen get paid very well.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
