<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TOURNEY HAS HAD NEW ENGLAND ACCENT
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-RYAN-NCAATOURNAMENT-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By BOB RYAN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   New England may not be known as a mecca of college basketball,
but we can say this much: when the NCAA Tournament began in 1939,
we were there.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was, anyway. Yup, Brown, that trendy school of the late
'90s. The first New England team to participate in the NCAA
Tournament was a 16-4 Brown team coached by George E. Allen and
captained by George Truman. They were paired against Villanova, and
they fell by a 42-30 score.
</P>
<P>
   There has been only one national champion from these parts, the
1947 Holy Cross team, which knocked off Navy, CCNY, and Oklahoma to
win the title in Madison Square Garden. Most people associate that
team with Bob Cousy, but the fact is that The Cooz was an auxiliary
part of the puzzle. His great college days lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen New England schools have taken part in the most famous
of all NCAA-sponsored events. Connecticut has been the most
frequent competitor, this current trip to the tournament being the
Huskies' 21st. But the most successful team, aside from those early
Holy Cross clubs, has been Providence, which numbers Final Four
appearances in 1973 and 1987 among its 13 trips to what we now
refer to as the ``Big Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the New England participation in the NCAA
Tournament:
</P>
<P>
   One and out
</P>
<P>
   Springfield: 1940
</P>
<P>
   One trip to The Show, and whom do you get? The eventual champion
Indiana Hoosiers, who, according to the Springfield Student,
``overwhelmed'' the ``courageous Maroon basketeers'' by a 48-24
score at the legendary Butler University Field House, the site some
13 years later of the Milan (i.e. ``Hoosiers'') triumph. Were they
nervous? Well, they shoot 13 percent (8 for 63!), Rip Redding leads
Springfield with 8, as the Maroons cannot compete in any category _
save one. ``Mid-western observers marveled at the fact that the
Springfield players taped their own ankles,'' reports the Student.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts: 1945
</P>
<P>
   For some utterly inexplicable reason (other than the fact that
it was war time and in terms of athletics absolutely anything could
happen) a 10-6 Tufts five is invited to play in a tournament that
includes Kentucky, Utah, and Bob Kurland-led Oklahoma A&AMP;M. NYU
defeats the Jumbos, 59-44, and a Globe correspondent observes that
``perhaps because they did not respect the opposition too much the
Violets were careless and sloppy.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard: 1946
</P>
<P>
   With a 20-1 record, the Crimson seem to belong in the august
company of defending champion Oklahoma A&AMP;M, NYU, and North
Carolina. The Globe's Jack Barry notes in his preview that ``should
Wyndol Gray be `on' in his one-hand shooting and intricate passing,
the Crimson quintet will be a pushover for no one.'' The game is
scheduled in Madison Square Garden for 8 p.m., we are told, in
order that ``Harvard can catch the 11 o'clock plane.'' (Hey, there
might have been a Greek class to monitor). Alas, Gray, fellow
future Celtic Saul Mariaschin, and the rest of Floyd Stahl's team
flame out against Ohio State, losing, 46-38. ``Harvard literally
froze cold,'' writes Barry. ``Harvard exhibited its worst
basketball of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like so many of those Penn-Princeton weekends to come,
eh?
</P>
<P>
   Williams: 1955
</P>
<P>
   Brainiest bunch ever to play in the tournament? The only way
they weren't is if someone could produce five Dean's List guys, and
then they'd need to include a Phi Beta Kappa, such as Tom Moro. At
17-1 in the regular season, Moro, Ron Wilson, Bob Buse, and Wally
Jensen can play a little, too. The student ticket allotment for the
game in Madison Square Garden is sold out in 20 minutes. The end
result is respectable, but predictable: Canisius 73, Williams 60.
</P>
<P>
   A taste or two
</P>
<P>
   Brown: 1939, '86
</P>
<P>
   Brown earns an inaugural invitation, losing by a 42-30 score to
Villanova in Philadelphia. Writes Associated Press, ``After loafing
throughout most of the battle, the Rhode Island boys hit a hot
streak and scored eight futile points in the closing minutes.'' . .
. Forty-seven years later, Brown returns as Ivy League champs and
draws second-seeded Syracuse. Oops. Syracuse 101, Brown 52 . . .
The Bruins shoot 8 for 32 in the first half with 15 turnovers and
'Cuse has one 27-2 run.
</P>
<P>
   Yale: 1949, '57, '62
</P>
<P>
   Eli drop close one (71-67) to Illinois in '49 and not-so-close
one (70-54) to eventual champ North Carolina in '57 . . . Has great
shot at powerful Wake Forest in '62, missing chance to win in
regulation when David Schumacher misses a free throw at :02. Wake
(Lenny Chappell, 25) wins, 92-82, and rolls into Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Fairfield: 1986, '87, '97
</P>
<P>
   Bombed by Illinois (75-51) in '86 and Indiana (92-58) a year
later after entering tourney as a 15-16 Cinderella conference
tourney winner . . . With guard Greg Francis nailing eight threes,
Stags frighten North Carolina in '97 and almost thwart Dean Smith's
record-tying 846th victory. ``They were like mosquitoes,'' marvels
Antwan Jamison.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University: 1959, '83, '88, '90, '97
</P>
<P>
   1959: Inspired by fiery captain (and future UMass mentor) Jack
Leaman, the Terriers of Matt Zunic surprise UConn and Navy to earn
shot at Jerry West and West Virginia. Crowd noise from back home at
Sargent Gym is piped into arena in Charlotte for Navy game.
Hook-shooting Bob Cummings, a 24-year-old service vet, torments
Mountaineers with 22, but BU gets into foul trouble and is finally
undone by West (33), who runs off 14 straight WVU points in one
stretch. Down 2 with 10 seconds left, BU can't get rebound of
missed West Virginia free throw . . . 1983: Rick Pitino's boys lose
first-rounder to La Salle when injury to Gary Plummer forces Pitino
into such things as a four-guard offense . . . 1988: Hang in pretty
well against Duke (85-69). ``I thought we did a helluva job,'' says
coach Mike Jarvis . . . Blown away by pressing UConn (76-52) two
years later . . . In 1997, sustain what coach Dennis Wolff calls a
``total breakdown'' in 81-52 loss to Tulsa . . . Star Tunji Awojobi
held to 7.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern: 1981, '82, '84, '85, '86, '87, '91
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd be battling Northwestern for last place in the Big
10,'' sneers Al McGuire before NU, with backcourt stars Pete Harris
and Perry Moss, stops Fresno State, 55-53. Utah, with Danny Vranes
(27) and Tom Chambers (21) too big and athletic in 94-69 loss . . .
1982: Eric Jefferson's two free throws push Huskies over St. Joe's,
setting up epic battle with Villanova. Dave Leitao's put-back hangs
on rim and won't drop at end of first OT. Jefferson's tip gets NU
into a third OT. Villanova prevails, 75-71. ``People think we
rolled off a cow truck,'' says coach Jim Calhoun, ``But I want
everyone to know this is Northeastern University of Boston, Mass. _
a damned good team.'' Broadcaster Ted Sarandis is scraped off
Nassau County Coliseum ceiling two days later . . . 1984: Dispatch
LIU, 90-87, before playing in one of weirdest NCAA games ever.
Huskies shoot 74 percent, hardly turn it over and get 31 (15 of 17)
from freshman Reggie Lewis _ and lose. Rolando Lamb hits one while
falling down at the buzzer to give Virginia Commonwealth a 70-69
triumph . . . 1985: Lewis makes only 2 of first 11 shots as
Illinois prevails, 76-57 . . . Next year Reggie has 35, but
Oklahoma has three over 20. ``We can best them,'' says Calhoun, but
final is 80-74, Sooners . . . 1987: Calhoun is off to UConn, but
Karl Fogel has team in tourney against Purdue. A 104-95 Boilermaker
win deteriorates into ugly mess and Messrs. Keady and Fogel have
still not shaken hands . . . 1991: North Carolina blasts NU,
101-66. Dean Smith had just watched No. 15 seed Richmond beat
Syracuse and said, ``That's my meeting.'' Says NU's Leroy Hodge,
``It was unbelievable how fast they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Making statements
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth: 1941, '42, '43, '44, '56, '58, '59
</P>
<P>
   It's the early '40s, and Dartmouth rules. Ozzie Cowles and his
boys from Hanover take two-day train ride to New Orleans before
victories over Penn State and Kentucky (``there was no comparison
between the two clubs as they played tonight'' _ AP) propel Indians
(pre-P.C. days) into championship game against Stanford. George
Munroe, Jim Olsen, and Marvin Akers meet their match against
Stanford, which wins crown, 53-38, without even bothering to employ
star Jim Pollard, who, while recovering from illness, could have
played . . . After first-round loss in '43, Dartmouth roars back in
'44, blowing by Catholic U (63-38) and outlasting Ohio State
(60-53) before meeting Utah in the finals. A Dick McGuire hoop gets
Dartmouth into OT, but Utah's Herb Wilkinson scores at the buzzer
to give the Utes their only NCAA crown . . . 1958: After advancing
to second round two years earlier, Doggie Julian takes what he says
is ``my best team'' into battle, beating UConn and Manhattan before
running afoul of Temple and its great Guy Rodgers-Pickles Kennedy
backcourt, 69-50 . . . (Roughhouse) Rudy LaRusso leads Big Green
back a year later, but Jerry West and West Virginia are too much,
82-68.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross: 1947, '48, '50, '53, '56, '77, '80, '93
</P>
<P>
   1947: We knew the Crusaders were good, but this good? Yup. With
players such as George Kaftan, Frank Oftring, Joe Mullaney, Dermie
O'Connell, Andy Laska, Ken Haggerty, Bob Curran, and, of course,
freshman whiz Bob Cousy, Holy Cross turns out to be the best team
in the land. First to fall is Navy. Then CCNY goes down, 60-45.
That leaves Oklahoma, and with tourney MVP Kaftan in charge, the
Sooners fall, 58-47. It is an astonishing achievement for a little
Catholic school. According to the Globe, ``the only semblance of a
home court is the confines of a red barn atop Pachachoag Hill.''
Says our own Barry, ``It will be a long time before another
combination so smooth, so balanced, and so adaptable is seen again
in Madison Square Garden.'' A crowd of 10,000 greeted the train in
22-degree weather at Worcester's Union Station. 1948: No repeat.
Kentucky, with Alex Groza, Ralph Beard, &AMP; Co., wins, 60-53 . . .
There is another one-round KO in '50 . . . Bob Pettit (29) leads
LSU past Crusaders in '53, and Temple wins by a 74-72 score against
a Tom Heinsohn team in '56 . . . 1977: Without ailing (ankle)
Ronnie Perry, HC hangs very tough against Michigan, but Wolverines
take it, 92-81, despite stout efforts of Mike Vicens (23) and Chris
Potter (20) . . . Final two NCAA appearances in '80 (Iona, 84-78)
and '93 (Arkansas, 94-64) are one-and-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island: 1961, '66, '78, '88, '93, '97, '98
</P>
<P>
   1961: Tourney debut spoiled by St. Bonaventure duo of Fred
Crawford (34) and Tom Stith (29) in 86-76 setback . . . 1966: Lefty
Driesell's Davidson squad, led by Mike Maloy and Fred Hetzel, is
much too much for overmatched Rams, 95-65 . . . 1978: Painful loss
to eventual finalist Duke. Rhody there all the way, and even leads
by 3 with 43 seconds left. Mike Gminski hits huge jumper and Irv
Chatman misses a key layup for Rams. Two free throws by Gminski win
it, 63-62 . . . 1988: Tom Penders inherits a Brendan Malone squad
and gets it past Missouri (Tom Garrick, 29) and haughty Syracuse in
touted A-10/Big East showdown as Garrick has 28 more and rugged
Kenny Green owns paint with 23. Says Penders, ``This is the biggest
thing ever to happen to this program.''. . . Dream ended when Duke
runs out to 18-5 lead. Bill King (now Sixer GM) defense holds
Garrick (30 ppg in entire postseason) to 14 in 74-72 Duke win . . .
1993: Rams squashed in Round 2 by Carolina, 112-67 . . . Four years
later Purdue wins first-round game in OT (83-76) . . . 1998: Jim
Harrick plays '98 Penders role, inheriting a veteran team from Al
Skinner and taking it on tourney joyride. Murray State goes down
first, as six Rams hit double figures. The reward is a meeting with
No. 1 seed Kansas, but the Jayhawks have no clue what to do with
guards Cuttino Mobley and Tyson Wheeler, who combine for 47 (8
threes). Rams control final four minutes of 80-75 conquest. Next to
go is lovable Valparaiso, which cannot offset Rhody's great
balance. What follows is the Ending From Hell. Leading by 6 (71-65)
with 59 seconds to go against Stanford, the Rams come undone less
than a minute from the Final Four. Stanford's Arthur Lee first
makes a great leaning three and then a coast-to-coast 3-point play
(he has 13 points in final 2:06), there is a steal and there is a
zig-when-should-have-zagged Wheeler bad pass turnover. Just an
amazing, mondo bizarro finale. ``We experienced a 180-degree change
of emotion in the final minute,'' says Stanford's Mike Masden.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College: 1958, '67, '68, '75, '81, '82, '83, '85, '94,
'96, '97
</P>
<P>
   Tourney intro short and sweet in '58: Maryland 86, BC 63. Eagles
can't get it done with a 6-3, 6-5, 6-4 front line . . . Cousy
returns nine years later with some bigger lads. Eagles stop
stalling UConn in opener (14-13 at half), 48-42, then beat St.
John's, 64-62 as Billy Evans makes game-saving steal and Eagles
sink final 21 free throws. BC grabs quick 12-3 lead on North
Carolina, but Bobby Lewis (31) leads comeback, as Tar Heels give
Dean Smith his first Final Four berth, 96-80. Thirty-two years
later, this 23-3 squad ranks as BC's best team ever . . . Bill
Butler sticks 'em for 34 and Bob Lanier owns the paint as
undefeated St. Bonaventure wins Kingston (R.I.) Relays a year
later, 102-93 . . . Eagles return under Bob Zuffelato in '75,
defeating Furman and losing to Kansas State when Chuckie Williams
erupts for 32, including 24 in second half . . . Tom Davis
establishes his tourney credentials in '81 as BC beats Ball State,
93-90 and Wake Forest, 67-64 (John Bagley, 35). But ride ends in
messy 42-41 loss to a St. Joseph's team that had just shocked
top-ranked DePaul . . .
</P>
<P>
   Not much expected from 19-9 team in '82, but Eagles first stop
San Francisco and then take care of DePaul themselves, 82-75.
``We've found our style,'' says Dr. Tom. A win over Kansas State
(69-65) gets BC to Final Eight for second time. Team gets lift when
athletic director Bill Flynn leads fog-frustrated delegation that
includes a roaring band into Reunion Arena early in second half.
But Houston handles Eagle press and sub Reid Gettys buries 10
straight free throws in stretch. Even Michael Adams dribbling
through Akeem Olajuwon's legs isn't enough to get BC to the Final
Four . . . Gary Williams is in charge a year later as BC beats
Princeton (14 passes before first shot), 51-42. Trailing by 1 just
23 seconds into second half, BC watches Ralph Sampson head to bench
with fourth foul. A lift? Sure, for UVa. BC goes six minutes-plus
without a field goal, and Virginia wins, 95-92, with Rick Carlisle
making all his foul shots in the end. ``We relaxed too much when
Ralph went out,'' laments forward Jay Murphy . . . 1985: Williams's
final BC tourney team beats Texas Tech on Adams's buzzer-beater
(55-53), and then stuns Duke with a 1-3-1 zone and equal backcourt
speed. Next up: a coulda/shoulda/woulda loss of the worst kind.
Tied with Memphis State, and in possession of the ball, Roger
McCready turns it over and Andre (Little General) Turner, wins it
with foul line jumper at :01. Says an ultra-emotional Williams,
``What hurts is how hard these guys worked . . . I wouldn't mind if
the season went until June with these guys . . .''
</P>
<P>
   1994: Jim O'Brien brings senior-oriented team back to tourney,
and the Curley Gang responds with wins over Washington State, North
Carolina, and Indiana, meaning that Obie beats Dean and Bob
back-to-back. Oh, yeah, North Carolina is a No. 1. Probably should
mention that. BC put five starters in double figures against Heels.
Dean Smith whines that freshman Danya Abrams is a bully. Boo-hoo.
Against Indiana the guards shoot 17 for 30. In third trip to Final
Eight, BC again stopped, this time by Florida and guard Craig
Brown, who nails three straight threes in clutch to give Gators a
74-66 trip to Final Four . . . 1996: Eagles whip Indiana again, but
are trashed by hot-shooting Georgia Tech (Stephon Marbury, six
threes, 29 points and 9 assists . . . 1997: BC beats Valparaiso and
dangerous Bryce Drew, 79-66, but O'Brien era closes out with 81-77
OT loss to A-10 champs St. Joseph's, which fires up awesome 43
threes and connects on 14. ``Single most bizarre stat sheet I've
ever seen after a game,'' O'Brien says.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts: 1962, '992, '93, '94, '95, '96, '97, '98
</P>
<P>
   1962: ``We're a year ahead of schedule,'' says Matt Zunic, who
has relocated from Comm Ave. to Amherst since last heard from. But
State U shoots 17 for 68 and succumbs to NYU, 70-50 . . . 1992:
It's a new hoop world now, in every way, and UMass is in it to
stay. John Calipari's squad toys with Fordham (85-58) and then wins
landmark 77-71 OT struggle with Syracuse. Harper Williams clinches
it with a three, only his second of the season. Coach Cal had asked
for ``bankers with basketballs on their heads'' to show up for the
'Cuse game, and he got them. Run ends in mild controversy when
87-77 Kentucky victory is marked by ridiculous technical called on
Coach Cal by noted showboat ref Lenny Wirtz when Minutemen were
down 2 (70-68) with 5:47 left . . . There was no spark at all in
'93. UMass squeaks by Penn before losing untidy game to Virginia.
``We've done this about 16 times,'' says an exasperated Coach Cal.
``Put ourselves in a hole.''. . . More distress a year later when
lackluster opening win over Southwest Texas (78-60, but not that
big a rout, really) is followed by 95-87 loss to Joe Smith and
Maryland, a team the Minutemen had already beaten in Baltimore.
``They wanted it more than we did,'' says the mentor . . . 1995:
UMass makes first trip to the Final Eight. It starts with
tooth-pull win over St. Peter's (UMass needs 13-0 run in second
half to pull away), and continues with easier victories over
Stanford (75-53) and Tulsa (76-51, as playmaker Edgar Padilla
sprains his ankle). Final Four is beckoning, but Bryant (Big
Country) Reeves is too much of an obstacle. He gets 24 points and
10 rebounds. Marcus Camby gets 6 and 4. Big Country goes to the
Final Four. Camby goes home and decides he isn't quite ready for
the NBA . . .
</P>
<P>
   1996: With a chastened Camby a Player of the Year sort, UMass
makes its greatest run. After rolling over feisty Central Florida,
UMass beats ever-improving Stanford with three perfectly-executed
plays in final three possessions. Arkansas is no sweat at all, as
UMass starts off with 13-0 how-do-you-do. One game away from the
Final Four, the Minutemen put together a masterpiece, flattening
Georgetown and Allen Iverson (6 for 21) as Camby has 22 and Carmelo
Travieso tosses in 20. UMass can't match that effort in national
semis against Kentucky, but team makes nice run after falling
behind by 15 and get it to 3 with 4:51 left. Kentucky wins national
title, 81-74, but winning coach Pitino (UMass '75) is proud of his
alma mater. ``Ninety-nine percent of the teams in the country would
have gone under with the pressure we applied,'' he marvels . . .
The NCAA later strips UMass of its honor because Camby is found to
have consorted with agents, but the games were played and the
memory will never fade . . . UMass returns to the tournament in
both '97 and '98, but exits quickly with a pair of flat efforts
against Louisville and Saint Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut: 1951, '54, '56, '57, '58, '59, '60, '63, '64, '65,
'67, '76, '79, '90, '91, '92, '94, '95, '96, '98
</P>
<P>
   As tyrannical rulers of the old Yankee Conference for more than
a decade and a half, UConn could count on an NCAA automatic bid
most every year. But UConn's first eight trips to the tournament
produce just one W, a 1956 triumph over Manhattan . . . 1964: A
breakthrough! The Huskies first beat Temple, and then they upset
Bill Bradley and Princeton, 52-50 (with Dom Perno sealing things by
swishing two free throws), earning a shot at Duke, led by Jeff
Mullins and Art Heyman. Crash. Duke hits poor UConn with a 62-point
first half, Mullins goes for 30 and the Blue Devils win, 101-54 . .
. After more first-round losses to St. Joe's ('65), BC ('67,) and
Syracuse ('79), UConn returns to The Dance in a whole new guise
under Jim Calhoun in '90. Armed with a No. 1 seed, the Huskies
smash both BU and California (which turns it over under the
relentless Husky press nine of its first 11 possessions), before
heading to the Meadowlands to play Clemson. Losing by a point with
one second left, the Huskies get a miracle accomplished when former
high school quarterback Scott Burrell throws a full-court pass to
6-5 guard Tate George, whose right baseline turnaround beats the
Tigers, 71-70. Ah, but live by the sword, etc. Two days later it is
UConn with the lead against Duke and a second left. But Christian
Laettner takes an inbounds give-and-go feed from roommate Brian
Davis and hits a double-clutch jumper to deprive Calhoun and his
kids a trip to the Final Four in Denver. Calhoun will always see
George making a steal of a Bobby Hurley pass with that 1-point
lead, but being unable to stay inbounds at midcourt and thus giving
the ball back to Duke. It is the beginning of tournament
frustration for Calhoun . . . 1991: Huskies earn a second tourney
shot at Duke after dispatching LSU and Xavier, but this time Duke
needs no late heroics. Blue Devils lead, 44-27, en route to an
81-67 triumph. ``We let a good Duke team get the jump on us,'' says
Calhoun . . . After one tourney win in '92, UConn returns in '94
with reasonable hopes and a No. 1 seed. They beat Rider and George
Washington to get to the East Regional, and, despite a sluggish
effort, they are primed to beat Florida when All-American Donyell
Marshall steps to the line with 3.4 seconds left and the score
tied. He clanks 'em both, and UConn loses in OT. ``He's done too
much for UConn to be concerned with a couple of missed free
throws,'' says Calhoun . . .
</P>
<P>
   A year later Calhoun comes back with another wagon, and his team
rolls right to the Western finals against UCLA after taking care of
Tennessee-Chattanooga, Cincinnati, and Maryland while averaging 98
points a game. But the Huskies get engaged in one shootout too
many, trying to outrun the one team in the land that can't be
beaten in a running game. Despite 36 points by Ray Allen, the
Huskies lose, 102-96, as Tyus Edney goes for 27 and Toby Bailey for
26. ``We ran into a team that had more answers than we did,'' says
Calhoun, who to this day regrets not trying to slow down the tempo
(well, he should, anyway) . . . 1996: By this time merely winning
two tourney games isn't good enough, and so there is disappointment
all around when, following triumphs over Colgate and Eastern
Michigan, the Huskies lose to Mississippi State, 60-55. The Huskies
were forced to play with defensive standout Ricky Moore (ankle),
and Mississippi State's predictably unchecked Darryl Wilson goes
for 27 . . . 1998: More frustration for the Huskies, as another
good Calhoun team can't catch a break. This time UConn survives 43
from Elijah Allen to beat Fairleigh-Dickinson and then stops
Indiana before being forced to play North Carolina in, of all
places, Greensboro. UConn is only down one (59-58) with 5:37 left
when star forward Richard Hamilton is forced out with a deep thigh
bruise . . .
</P>
<P>
   Providence: 1964, '65, '66, '72, '73, '74, '77, '78, '87, '89,
'90, '94, '97, '98
</P>
<P>
   After winning the still-prestigious NIT in 1961 and 1963, Joe
Mullaney brings Providence into the NCAA Tournament for the first
time in 1964, losing to Villanova, 77-66. He comes back with a
stronger crew in '65, because this time he has Jimmy Walker. The
Friars beat West Virginia in the first round, setting up a showdown
with No. 3-ranked St. Joe's. Combined, the teams were 49-2, and so
it is no surprise when 40 minutes aren't enough to settle matters.
PC survives, 81-73, and is only a perfunctory rout of Princeton
away from a trip to the Final Four in Portland. Oh, really? Coach
Mullaney is worried, even if no one else is. ``Bill Bradley hasn't
really had a great game in the tournament yet,'' he says. ``I hope
he doesn't have it against us.'' Good call, coach. Bradley has 41
points (14 for 20 from the floor and 13 for 13 from the line), to
go with 10 rebounds and 9 assists. Princeton 109, Providence 69.
Ouch . . . St. Joe's knocks PC out in Round 1 again in '66, and so
then it is a seven-year wait to get back into the tourney. It is
all worth it, for this is the great Marvin-Ernie team. With Marvin
Barnes and Ernie DeGregorio giving PC the greatest 1-2
inside-outside punch in New England history, Providence rolls over
St. Joe's and Maryland. It doesn't even matter that Ernie D has big
foul trouble against the Terrapins. Kevin Stacom simply takes over
the show. The Memphis State game in the national semis leads to the
greatest PC what-if? ever; namely, what if Marvin doesn't hurt his
knee in the first half while PC is kicking the Tigers' butt? But he
does, and despite Ernie D's brilliance, it is Memphis State
advancing to play UCLA by a 98-85 score (Hah! Bill Walton drops 44
on their heads). Be it known that this is the greatest New England
team of them all . . .
</P>
<P>
   PC returns behind Marvin and Stacom in '74, beating Penn, but
loses to eventual champ David Thompson and NC State, 92-78 . . .
The Friars lose first-round games to Kansas State and Michigan
State (there was this guy named Magic) the next two times . . . By
1987 Pitino is here and a long dry spell is ending, not that anyone
is expecting great tourney results from a No. 6 seed. But with
Delray Brooks, Billy Donovan, and Pop Lewis raining threes on
everyone, PC gets by Alabama-Birmingham (Donovan, 35), Austin Peay
(after trailing by 10 with 5:52 left), and then Alabama (14-22 on
threes) to get a game with powerful Georgetown. Pitino changes up,
attacking the Hoyas from the inside, and it works. PC wins, 88-73,
to earn Final Four berth No. 2. But the spell is broken by Big East
foe Syracuse, which beats Providence for the third time as PC
shoots 36 percent and Donovan goes 3 for 12 . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Friars lose close first-round games in '89 (Virginia), '90
(Ohio State) and '94 (Alabama), but there is a big shock in store
for everyone in '97. This is a strange team that isn't supposed to
like each other or the coach very much, but for some reason it
comes together in the tournament. Operating from a 10th seed, Pete
Gillen's Friars knock off Marquette by 22 as Austin Croshere goes
for 39 and then astonishes the entire basketball world by stopping
Duke, 98-87. No one can figure it out. ``Duke is Duke,'' says
Gillen. ``They're on TV more than `Leave It To Beaver' reruns.'' PC
continues with a 71-65 win over UT-Chattanooga. ``The starters
dislike me,'' jokes Gillen, ``and the four guys on the bench hate
me. Then they change roles.'' One game away from what have been the
most improbable Final Four appearance in anyone's memory, PC takes
Arizona into overtime before losing, 96-92. PC's Corey Wright can't
nail the last shot in regulation, and everyone wonders what would
have happened if Croshere hadn't been in foul trouble or if referee
Dick (Froggy) Paparo hadn't gone off the deep end and called three
second-half techs on PC. Arizona goes on to win the national title.
``It would have been a hell of a story,'' shrugs Gillen, who heads
off to Virginia.
</P>
</TEXT>
