<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETH-ORTON-MUSIC-$ADV     03-10 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETH-ORTON-MUSIC-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FOLKIE PLUGGED IN TO THE CURRENTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Anthony DeCurtis is the author of ``Rocking My Life Away: Writing
About Music and Other Matters.''  
 By ANTHONY DECURTIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the music industry slices itself into ever thinner market
fragments, the language of music critics is dutifully following
along. Performers are extolled or denounced for crossing boundaries
invisible to the eye (or ear): divisions that often have little to
do with how people actually create music.
</P>
<P>
   The English singer-songwriter Beth Orton, for example, has on
several occasions collaborated with the Chemical Brothers, whose
block-rocking electronic beats made a big impact a couple of years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   She has also worked with William Orbit, who is now best known as
the co-producer of Madonna's techno-flavored album ``Ray of
Light.'' For those reasons, Ms. Orton has been widely praised for
bridging the vastly disparate worlds of folk traditionalism and
electronic innovation.
</P>
<P>
   But in her spellbinding 1997 album, ``Trailer Park,'' Ms. Orton
was hardly seeking to be a boundary-shattering revolutionary.
Rather, she was simply using whatever materials came to hand to
enhance the atmosphere of her songs.
</P>
<P>
   At 28 and living in London, she had many styles and sounds to
choose from. But for any listener unfamiliar with the trends of the
moment, ``Trailer Park'' sounded gloriously as if it could have
been made at any point in the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of Ms. Orton's equally transporting new album,
``Central Reservation'' (Deconstruction/Arista, CD, ARCD-9038).
Once again, the songs wander a misty terrain of romantic yearning,
of loves lost and sought. Fewer electronic touches surface this
time: a steady hip-hop beat undergirds ``Stars All Seem to Weep,''
which is also colored by an eerie keyboard figure and what she
describes as ``abstract sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   A percolating remixed version of the title track, produced by
Ben Watt of Everything But the Girl, closes the album. Beyond that,
however, subtle string parts adorn many songs, and guest musicians
like the New Orleans pianist Dr. John and the American folk singer
Terry Callier, a cult figure from the 1960s whose career Ms. Orton
has helped revive, ground the album in a long musical history.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Orton's distinctively husky voice and her acoustic guitar
are always at the center of her music. The rough grain of that
voice and how Ms. Orton uses it are precisely what attracted the
likes of the Chemical Brothers and Orbit to her. Ms. Orton may be
drawn to traditional musical virtues; she has a lovely, if dark,
sense of melody and her songs, though ranging only from slow to
midtempo, typically rise from well-defined verses into elegant
choruses.
</P>
<P>
   But as a singer she does everything she can to escape those
structures. Like Rickie Lee Jones, one of her idols, she slurs
words, stretches syllables, slides one phrase into another, sings
over line breaks and circles the beat, often lingering sensuously
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   At those times she is using her voice like an instrument, like
pure sound. At other times she sings with a detachment that is both
cerebral and erotic, as if she were a voyeur occupying some
langorous space at one step removed from the song itself. That
combination of distance and desire, of dreaminess and
impersonality, perfectly mirrors the characteristics of
contemporary electronic music and makes Ms. Orton one of the few
singers who can move gracefully in that world.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Ms. Orton often calls on her skills as a stylist
to rescue lyrics that fail to meet the expectations created by her
eloquent music. In ``Stolen Car,'' a song about a lover's
deception, she flirts with meaning but settles for cleverness in
lines like ``Why should I know better by now/ When I'm old enough
not to?''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Ms. Orton burdens cliches, which have a time-honored
place in popular music, with too much emotional weight. ``Why must
people always want what they can't have?'' she wonders in ``Blood
Red River.'' On ``Pass in Time,'' she concludes, ``You might as
well smile/ Because tomorrow you just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Orton's lyrics may not find their way into poetry
anthologies, they are only one part of the textured sonic landscape
she is creating, a quality she shares with sound-shaping electronic
musicians. She may be mining a folk tradition, but she is not
writing the message songs for which the 1960s version of that
movement is known.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in her career, Ms. Orton is far more noteworthy
for the sound, rather than the sense, of her songs. That sound is
so evocative that it conveys an intelligence and allure all its
own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
