<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4381 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEVE-REICH-MUSIC-$AD     03-10 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVE-REICH-MUSIC-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING STEVE REICH FOR THE DANCE FLOOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Adam Shatz is a New York journalist who writes about the arts.  
 By ADAM SHATZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Marcel Duchamp to Robert Rauschenberg, artists have created
new work out of found objects, the humble products of mass culture.
In recent years, however, DJs in the club scene have reversed the
process by recycling high art for popular ends. Thanks to such
appropriation (or, as some think, sacrilege), liturgical chant and
Italian opera, Herbie Hancock and John Coltrane have all found a
second home in dance music, where rhythm trumps everything.
</P>
<P>
   On the new album ``Reich Remixed,'' American, British and
Japanese DJs pay tribute to the American minimalist composer Steve
Reich, at the invitation of his label, Nonesuch (CD, 79552-2).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the DJs, notably DJ Spooky (aka Paul Miller) were versed
in his music; others just saw it as an archive of cool sounds.
Either way, their attraction to Reich's work is anything but
arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   Drumming phases and sampling _ the central components of
contemporary dance music _ have formed an integral part of his
style since the mid-1960s. Reich's 1965 electronic piece ``It's
Gonna Rain,'' in which a street preacher's voice was transformed
into a reverberating band of sound, is a particular favorite of
remixers.
</P>
<P>
   And though Reich became a convert to acoustic instruments in the
70s, he shares a place alongside Karlheinz Stockhausen, Brian Eno
and Miles Davis in contemporary electronica's pantheon of
distinguished forerunners. Bands like Tortoise have flirted with
Reichian phasing, while Orb used his ``Electronic Counterpoint'' as
a setting for their 1991 song ``Fluffy Little Clouds.''
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd (even a little masochistic) that Reich has
licensed a group of DJs to reassemble his life's work according to
their whims. In fact, it's a shrewd endorsement, coming less than
two years after the release of Reich's 10-CD career retrospective.
</P>
<P>
   The album not only flatters Reich; it may provide him free
advertising in the club scene, where he's unknown beyond the sound
booth. Even so, there's no reason to doubt his enthusiasm for the
project. Reich has long aspired to reconcile the refinements of
concert hall music with the pleasures of pop, building his pieces
on the repetition of infectious rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Reich Remixed,'' the composer adapts well and even
gloriously at times to his new environment. And a new environment
it is: ``Reich Remixed'' is a dance record, albeit an unusually
cerebral one. Reconfigured by Jonathan More and Matt Black of the
English duo Coldcut, the wordless, vibratoless vocals and
percussive waves in Reich's ``Music for 18 Musicians'' retain their
lush aura. And yet the overall effect is different.
</P>
<P>
   Reich, who studied drumming in Ghana and Bali, uses polyrhythms
and timbral inflections in order to generate patterns that repay
the attentive listener with small, fragile epiphanies. Coldcut's
version, by contrast, emphasizes drama over process. Ultimately,
the subtler qualities of Reich's art _ the details that might get
lost on the dance floor _ tend to resist remixing.
</P>
<P>
   The best tracks on the album dare to deconstruct Reich's work.
In ``Megamix,'' Tranquility Bass (aka Mike Kandel) weaves together
nine Reich pieces into a slow, ethereal montage that could well
serve as a primer on Reich's music.
</P>
<P>
   At the other, minimalist, extreme, the DJ Nobukazo Takemura
demonstrates the power of concision by obsessively repeating a
simple, plaintive vocal figure from Reich's 1995 work ``Proverb.''
It's a maddeningly static yet enjoyably bleak work that suggests
Morton Feldman more than it does Reich.
</P>
<P>
   It is the techno composer Ken Ishii, however, who makes the most
interesting case for remixing Reich's music. Ishii has intriguingly
reworked ``Come Out,'' a 1966 electronic tape work that Reich
originally presented at a Town Hall benefit for the retrial of six
young men arrested for murder during the Harlem riots of 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The voice in ``Come Out'' belongs to one of those men, Daniel
Hamm, who survived a beating by the police. Hamm says, ``I had to
... let some of the bruise blood come out to show them.'' Composed
just a year after ``It's Gonna Rain,'' ``Come Out'' produced a
comparable distortion of Hamm's speech _ an effect that may have
undercut the work's value as agitprop.
</P>
<P>
   In his ominous remix, Ishii restores clarity to Hamm's
testimony. By laying bare the catalyst for ``Come Out,'' Ishii
reminds us that Reich's timeliness as a composer is not merely
musical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
