<HEADER>
A4384 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETTY'S-VACATION-THEA     03-10 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTY'S-VACATION-THEATER-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A TABLOID COMEDY, THE SERIAL KILLER IS SENSITIVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 Bob Morris contributes to The New York Times Magazine and National
Public Radio.  
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a recent Sunday, as the subscriber audience at
Playwrights Horizons filed into the venerable 140-seat house on
Theater Row, Christopher Durang poked his head out from behind a
door for a moment and then retreated. ``Looking at them,'' he said
of the mostly older crowd known to be armed with opinions as sharp
as their umbrella tips, ``we could be in for some trouble today.''
</P>
<P>
   The acerbic Durang's latest play, ``Betty's Summer Vacation,''
directed by Nicholas Martin and opening Sunday night, was in its
second week of previews. The author had already seen audiences love
and hate his sendup of tabloid culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``With comedy,'' said Durang, who watches from the lighting
booth, then flees to the basement to avoid direct interaction,
``it's hard not to pay attention to the audience.'' Especially when
a dozen members of it walk out at some intermissions.
</P>
<P>
   Well, he's been through it before. After all, his first hit
play, ``Sister Mary Ignatius Explains It All for You,'' offended
its share of Roma Catholics. Now, the cherubic Durang is poised to
draw attention to himself with the only comedy in town that has
more bile and murder than ``Electra.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This play is like a roller coaster,'' Durang said. ``People
who like it sit back and enjoy the strange ride; the ones who don't
feel they're being abused.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the laughter during the first act, the audience was
ready for the ride. Sure, they were watching characters inspired by
Jeffrey Dahmer and Lorena Bobbitt, as well as a sex-maniac surfer,
a flasher and one overbearing mother mixing it up in a Jersey Shore
summer share that would make the Hamptons seem tame.
</P>
<P>
   And sure, there was a laugh track coming from the ceiling,
torrents of obscenities and venomous tabloid dialogue. But at
intermission, only a few people departed. Not bad for a mostly
older, matinee crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby, conversation was brisk. ``It's interesting when
tragedy becomes comedy and a serial killer is attractive because
he's so sensitive,'' said Walter Krumholtz, a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The characters remind me of your family,'' said his date,
Lauren Ezersky.
</P>
<P>
   The action grew more intense in Act II and, by the time the play
was over, some offended people were storming out. ``It's a
sophomoric idea to suggest that the world is a trash-TV talk
show,'' said one man.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement, Durang worried about his second act and his
audience. ``I'm not a confrontational person,'' he said. ``It's not
my intention to offend anybody.'' Especially a devout Catholic aunt
whom he had to warn about the play, even though it has no nudity
and no (prolonged) religious attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in her 70s, and gets upset easily,'' Durang said. ``I
mean, she told me she had to stop watching `Touched By an Angel' on
TV because it was too sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a couch in his tweedy jacket and checked shirt,
Durang squirmed and sighed. It was almost as if his latest Swiftian
nightmare, which he had originally intended as a lighthearted
memory play about summers at the beach, was upsetting
(italics)him.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just starting it when I got distracted by the Menendez
trial on Court TV,'' said Durang, who lives in Bucks County, Pa.
``I watched the whole thing. Then I got hooked on the Bobbitt
trial. One of the dangers of being a writer is that you have a lot
of free time on your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The same thing could be said, of course, about serial killers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
