<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4396 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTHUR-MITCHELL-DANCE     03-10 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTHUR-MITCHELL-DANCE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL A MOVER AND SHAKER WITH HARLEM ON HIS MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)  
 (af)  
 Valerie Gladstone is a contributing editor to Dance magazine.  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From his office window, Arthur Mitchell, artistic
director of Dance Theater of Harlem, was looking out on an
undistinguished block of West 152nd Street near Amsterdam Avenue,
not far from where he spent his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, next to an overgrown lot, are a couple of
abandoned buildings. ``We'll be putting dorms in there soon so our
out-of-town students won't have to stay with local families,'' he
said, standing up behind his desk for a better view. ``They're
being made landmarks. Look at the details.'' The bright winter sun
cast stark shadows on the elaborate cornices.
</P>
<P>
   It is a landmark year for Mitchell. In the coming months, he
will be celebrating his 50th year in dance, the 30th anniversary of
Dance Theater and his 65th birthday. Dressed in a black silk shirt,
black jacket and black slacks, he makes as striking an impression
now as he did as a principal dancer with the New York City Ballet
in the 1950s and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   On his bookcase are photographs of himself with Balanchine,
another with Jacqueline Kennedy at the White House and a more
recent shot with President Clinton in 1993, when Mitchell won the
Kennedy Center Honors. He seemed self-conscious about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone told me you were supposed to display these kinds of
things,'' he said, then changed the subject by joking about the
imposing 19th-century pulpit he installed on the far side of his
office. ``My mother always said I'd make a good preacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Many artists strive to escape from their beginnings; instead, at
35, Mitchell returned to his. He had always known his experience
would rarely be repeated by others _ receiving a full scholarship
at the School of American Ballet and, at 21, becoming the first
black man to be a permanent member of a major ballet company.
</P>
<P>
   But the murder of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. in 1968
made that knowledge intolerable to him. ``I could no longer wait
for others to change things,'' he said. Abruptly, he made a
remarkable move for a dancer at the height of his powers and
resigned from the New York City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Peabody, who served on Dance Theater's board for many
years, called it ``an extraordinarily courageous thing to do.'' It
turned out to be historically significant as well.
</P>
<P>
   When he founded Dance Theater in 1969 with Karel Shook, his
mentor and ballet teacher (Shook died in 1985), few schools offered
ballet classes to blacks and even fewer ballet companies had black
members. ``It's hard to imagine now,'' he said, ``that most people
then thought we were totally unsuited to ballet.'' His school and
troupe soon proved otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Johnson, a principal dancer with the company from its
inception until 1997, recalled: ``We went to small towns where
they'd never seen blacks before. We had an enormous impact on many
narrow-minded people. Not just whites. Some of our people felt: Why
do ballet? It's only the white man's art. Our repertory showed that
many classics were applicable to blacks. That's why Mitchell
commissioned a Creole `Giselle' and an African `Firebird' for us to
dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company's repertory of more than 112 works includes
ballets by Balanchine and contemporary choreographers like Geoffrey
Holder, Dwight Rhoden, Alonzo King and a South African, Vincent
Mantsoe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But despite Dance Theater's breakthroughs, no other
predominantly black ballet company has yet been established, and
black dancers still find acceptance in ballet hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, racism is worse now,'' Mitchell said. ``It's caused
by the increased migration of people from around the world into our
country, for with it comes increased competition for jobs and
places in schools. It makes some Americans see anyone different
from themselves as a threat.'' But he doesn't let the situation
depress him. ``I have a large ego,'' he said. ``I've always figured
there isn't anything I can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no one expected his enterprise to last. Even today,
rumors spread every year that financial problems will close it
down. ``Yes, of course, we always need money,'' Mitchell said.
``Who in dance doesn't? But we finished last year in the black.''
</P>
<P>
   To insure continuity at Dance Theater, Mitchell and his board of
directors have just appointed James S. Keeler Jr., the former
president and chief executive of the Arthur Ashe Foundation, as the
company's executive director. ``Although I'm not planning to
retire,'' Mitchell said, ``I realize I must get my house in order
administratively.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To keep Dance Theater going, Mitchell has often had to make
difficult decisions. A few years ago, he determined that it was too
expensive to have regular seasons at City Center and at Lincoln
Center. Dance Theater now performs more often at Aaron Davis Hall
in Harlem and the Brooklyn Academy of Music. Only the company's
30th anniversary prompted him to plan a three-week season at the
City Center in September and October.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere the company's visibility is up. In the last two
years, it performed in Monte Carlo and at the Festival of Two
Worlds in Spoleto, Italy. And in February it made its first tour of
historically black American colleges while students from the
company school were performing in Hong Kong for the Chinese New
Year. Dance Theater is probably now better known outside Manhattan,
except in Harlem, where it is a cultural mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this isn't surprising. From the beginning, Mitchell's
primary purpose was to give minority children a complete education
in music, dance, theater and art. Today his school enrolls 1,000
students a year, ages 3 through 17, and offers dance and exercise
classes to adults. It also spreads its influence to other cities
with outreach programs.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of youngsters have learned about dance, costumes,
lights and scenery from company members. At the end of each
session, Dance Theater gives a performance at a local theater.
``Audiences for the last two or three generations have grown up on
television,'' Mitchell said. ``If you don't go into the community
and teach them about theater, they're never going to have any
interest in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dance Theater's monthly open houses are all about theater and
the arts. On a recent wintery Sunday afternoon, families and
children streamed through the company's doors at 152nd Street for a
program of music and dance. The big upstairs studio quickly filled
to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Coles, the widow of the legendary tap dancer Charles
(Honi) Coles, began the proceedings by offering to teach the
shim-sham to all comers. Before long, several couples were giddily
gyrating to the music. In the wings, Mitchell, smiling, danced to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   After the demonstration, he came out and proudly told everyone:
``I used to be a hoofer. Did gigs with Eartha Kitt when City Ballet
wasn't performing. Pearl Bailey taught me how to work a house.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusually rich program continued with young violinists, an
opera singer, ballet dancers and a gospel chorus all entertaining
the crowd. At the close, Mitchell announced an open house that is
to take place Sunday at 3 p.m. at the Dance Theater headquarters to
celebrate the forthcoming anniversaries. People rose to their feet
to applaud and then made their way to an adjoining studio for juice
and homemade desserts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year,'' he said later, ``someone tells me that we should
move downtown, that we'd get more attention and more money. What
they don't understand is that Harlem is our heart _ and that to
most of the world Harlem is a magical word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
