<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DLUGOSZEWSKI-DANCE-$A     03-10 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DLUGOSZEWSKI-DANCE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING UP CHOREOGRAPHY AS A PATH OUT OF MOURNING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich.)   (af)  
 Christopher Reardon's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was
about the choreographer Susan Marshall.  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not often that someone starts making dances
after turning 60. Lucia Dlugoszewski, who makes her choreographic
debut on March 23 at Playhouse 91, is not a total neophyte, though.
A seasoned composer and musician, she carried on a creative
partnership, and marriage, with the choreographer Erick Hawkins for
more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   When Hawkins died at 85 in 1994, Ms. Dlugoszewski briefly lost
interest in making music. ``I was sick with mourning,'' she said in
a recent interview. '`I wanted to die with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now that she's working again, she wears her black the way
older women in Europe do: as an expression of grief, not a nod to
downtown fashion. But that and a caginess about her age (61, she
said, though her alma mater puts it at 73) are her only traits that
could be called old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   Born and reared in Detroit, she first caused a stir in New York
in the early 1950s by inventing new instruments, and new ways of
playing old ones, and often sharing the stage with her husband's
troupe, the Erick Hawkins Dance Company. On the piano, she likes to
play the strings with mallets, picks and bows.
</P>
<P>
   Her compositions are equally unorthodox: frenzied at times, but
also strangely lyrical. The critic Virgil Thomson once
characterized her idiom as ``far out music of great delicacy,
originality and beauty of sound.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hawkins died, Ms. Dlugoszewski set about staging three
pieces outlined in a notebook he kept at his deathbed. Mikhail
Baryshnikov's White Oak Dance Project performed the first of these
posthumous works, ``Journey of a Poet,'' to mixed reviews at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music in 1997. The Hawkins company will present
the two others during its one-week run at Playhouse 91, which wraps
up the 92d Street Y's monthlong Harkness Dance Project.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of a static repertory, the troupe's board also began urging
Ms. Dlugoszewski, who succeeded her husband as artistic director,
to make her own dances. After all, she had taken over Hawkins'
course in dance composition some 15 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And there were other skilled choreographers, like Susan Marshall
and Boris Eifman, who had never danced professionally. What sold
her on the idea was the chance to work with Pascal Benichou, a
former Joffrey Ballet dancer who took her course two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I'm choreographing,'' she said. ``Pascal got me
out of my mourning.'' Her first dance, ``Taking Time to Be
Vulnerable,'' is a 50-minute solo for Benichou. With his long
auburn hair and earthy sensuality, he looks as if he had stepped
out of a Pre-Raphaelite painting. Like the rest of the program, it
will be danced to live musical accompaniment by Ms. Dlugoszewski.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe her dances, she drifts into reveries about
D.H. Lawrence, Pablo Neruda and Basho, whose haikus she regards as
the pinnacle of verbal expression. Or she discourses on esthetics,
with frequent references to the philosopher F.S.C. Northrop, who
championed ``direct experience'' over ``naive realism.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, these mystical digressions shed some light on her
work, which concerns itself less with how a dance looks than with
what its audience feels. ``I've always been very interested in
poetry, but it's (italics)about(end italics) something instead of
it is something,'' she said. ``Only music gives you direct
emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, dance intrigues her. Her second effort, a set of duets
for 10 dancers called ``Radical Ardent,'' pairs Benichou with
Katherine Duke, who joined the troupe in 1986. As the couple
rehearsed a veritable decathlon of amorous lifts last month, Ms.
Dlugoszewski reiterated her artistic creed: ``Direct experience is
a hard thing to achieve. Emotion interferes. Intellect interferes.
But as the haiku poets found, you can disable the intellect with a
clash of opposites.'' Ever straddling the romantic and modernist
camps, she added, ``I want you to see beauty where you never
thought you'd see it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 0128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROMANCE-FILM-2TAKES-$     03-10 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMANCE-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARING THE INTRICACIES OF DESIRE AND SHAME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Leslie Camhi's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the Iranian film ``The Apple.''  
 By LESLIE CAMHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROTTERDAM, the Netherlands _ If you can't dazzle them, shock
them!'' the adolescent heroine of Catherine Breillat's 1989 film
``36 Fillette'' declares, with a glance at her own daring
decollete.
</P>
<P>
   Could that be the French director's motto? Ms. Breillat, who is
50, is no stranger to scandal. From her first novel, written when
she was 17, to her most recent film, ``Romance,'' her candid
dissections of human sexuality have ignited debate at home and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make moral films,'' the director says. ``But mine is a
rather ambiguous, Dostoyevskian morality. I believe that human
beings are forever torn between their worst and best impulses. And
nothing represents that better than sex _ what is most trivial,
most obscene, most debased and most beautiful in human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Romance'' enjoyed a noisy premiere last month at the
International Film Festival here alongside a retrospective of Ms.
Breillat's six previous films. (``Romance'' is being shown as part
of the series ``Rendez-Vous with French Cinema Today'' at the
Walter Reade Theater on Friday and next Sunday and has just been
acquired by Trimark Pictures for an American release.)
</P>
<P>
   Filmed with almost glacial control, in the manner of a moral
fable, it centers on Marie (Caroline Ducey), a primary school
teacher whose boyfriend (Sagamore Stevenin), a fashion model,
refuses to have sex with her. Setting off in search of adventure,
Marie finds herself in bed with Paolo (Rocco Siffridi), a Latin
lover, and literally tied up with her headmaster, Robert (Francois
Berleand), in a sadomasochistic relationship that proves to be the
most tender of the three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romance'' alternates florid bedroom philosophizing with
explicit (and at times violent) sexual scenes. The casting of
Siffridi, a star of European pornograhic films, caused a stir; his
presence on the set was revealed to the other actors only after
they'd signed their contracts and was disturbing to some.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the real shock of ``Romance'' is its weirdly hybrid nature;
it's both a serious exploration of female masochism and a farce
about contemporary sexual relations. With an outrageous final scene
of childbirth that brilliantly overturns the conventions of both
romantic films and pornography, it's a scandal that challenges one
to think.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely source of so much commotion is the mother of three,
whose mild appearance belies her ferocious intelligence and
self-assurance. She grew up in the French provinces, ``in a deadly
little town,'' she said in Rotterdam, ``conventional and
narrow-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the age of 11, I was already developed, with a woman's
figure, and so my parents locked me up. But I read Lautreamont,
Sade, the most violent things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Breillat escaped by enrolling in the Paris university
system's College of Oriental Languages. She used her first year as
a student to write ``L'Homme Facil'' (``The Easy Man''), a novel
published in May 1968 and immediately banned as licentious for its
frank tone and language.
</P>
<P>
   Her first film, ``Une Vraie Jeune Fille'' (``A True Young Girl''
1976) _ an adaptation of her third novel ``Le Soupirail'' (``The
Sigh'') _ is shot from the perspective of a brooding adolescent who
takes refuge in wild and vaguely surreal erotic fantasies.
Hilariously abject and audacious, it's a portrait of the artist as
a sexually obsessed young solipsist, whose preoccupation with her
own bodily fluids mingles with her first, hesitant creative
impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Denied distribution in France, where for many years it was
considered a shameful film, but acclaimed in Rotterdam, ``Une Vraie
Jeune Fille'' may finally be released in France, 23 years after it
was made.
</P>
<P>
   As a director, Ms. Breillat specializes in explorations of the
psychological terrain of feminine shame and desire. ``Tapage
Nocturne''(``Night Noises'' 1979), a dark film about a married
woman consumed by adultery, was criticized for its sexual boldness.
</P>
<P>
   In the more buoyant ``36 Fillette,'' which was shown at the New
York Film Festival in 1989, a sullen 14-year-old girl on holiday
with her family considers losing her virginity to a jaded older
man. ``Parfait Amour'' (``Perfect Love''), a 1996 film based on a
crime story, details the destructive passion that erupts between a
37-year-old woman and a 28-year-old man. Its analysis of the need
and despair that underpin romantic love is radically unsentimental
and stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sale Comme un Ange'' (``Filthy as an Angel''), a 1991 police
thriller in the style of Ms. Breillat's mentor, Maurice Pialat,
tells the story of a worn-out detective (Claude Brasseur), who
falls in love with his partner's wife (Lio). Her seduction is
filmed in one long take in which the woman's face fleetingly
records shame, fear, longing and rapture.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The contradictions of that moment interest me intensely,'' Ms.
Breillat remarks. ``Because the closer you get to an actress in
that state of physical rapture, the more she offers herself to you,
the more distant she becomes, the more she escapes you. And it's
something you can only film _ the simultaneous desires, for example
of a woman who says no, and thinks it, and yet says yes at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Breillat, filmmaking is a passionate act. ``It happens
under the eye of the camera,'' she explains, ``that the actors are
transfigured, like people in love. Because the camera is a way of
loving people. The way you look at them transforms them totally.
That's why directors sign their films, even though they're not the
ones holding the camera, or saying the words. But their vision
transforms things so totally that the film belongs to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Breillat is a leader in the growing ranks of French women
who are directing films. Unifrance, an agency that promotes French
cinema, lists 39 women whose films have been released commercially
over the last two years including Claire Denis (``Nenette et
Boni''), Daniele Dubroux (``Diary of a Seducer'') and Anne Fontaine
(``Dry Cleaning'').
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have contributed to the wealth of opportunity
for female directors in France. One is a government-sponsored
system in which a percentage of profits from all films are
reinvested in projects chosen according to merit. Another is the
willingness of public television to co-finance risky material.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Boidin, the director of cinema at Arte, the
French-German cultural television channel that co-produced both
``Perfect Love'' and ``Romance,'' finds little in the latter film
that shocks him. ``Every day, television news programs project
images of greater violence against women,'' he says. ``What's
extraordinary about `Romance' is that it lets a woman's desire
speak. So-called sexual films are almost always presented from a
man's perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond ``Romance,'' this year's ``Rendez-Vous'' series at the
Walter Reade Theater includes four films directed by women,
including Tonie Marshall's ``Venus Beaute (Institut),'' a
bittersweet comedy of manners about customers and attendants in a
Parisian beauty salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a radicality to Catherine's work,'' Ms. Marshall said
from Paris in a telephone interview, ``which links her to the
preceding generation of directors _ people like Marguerite Duras
and Agnes Varda, who really opened doors for women. She frightens
people at times. She's always bothered people a bit. But she's
extremely stubborn, and she follows her own path.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, that path involves a marked and rather
unfashionable indifference to social concerns. It's an attitude
that distinguishes Ms. Breillat's work from the miserabiliste
strain in contemporary French filmmaking exemplified by Bruno
Dumont's ``Life of Jesus,'' Phillippe Grandrieux's ``Sombre'' (in
the ``Rendez-Vous'' series) and Gaspard Noe's ``I Stand Alone,''
opening this week at the Film Forum. But her films do share
something of their dark tone and preoccupation with violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a citizen, I pay attention to social problems, but as a
filmmaker, they don't interest me,'' Ms. Breillat says.
``Metaphysics, sentiment and passion are more important to me than
the kind of jobs people do.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds: ``I don't make films in order to present a realistic
vision of society, but rather to track down the truths we are not
supposed to see. It's not realism that interests me, but reality,
truth, which is very incorporeal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 0129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4408 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBARA-MORGAN-PHOTOG     03-10 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBARA-MORGAN-PHOTOGS-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSFIXING MOTION AND EMOTION IN A SHUTTER'S BLINK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photography does some things poorly and others too well. For a
long time it could not stop motion, and then, when it could, the
results were too good to believe: people were uncomfortable with
Eadweard Muybridge's pictures of galloping horses because no one
had ever seen a horse look exactly like that.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually viewers grew accustomed to seeing what was invisible
to the eye and counted it as a kind of miracle. Conventions created
by the camera were accepted: blur signified speed, and a
stroboscopic series of figures in a single frame indicated motion,
although if the eye takes in blur and such tiny increments of
motion, it does not register them.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties of stopping movement and making it credible
meant that cameras had trouble portraying dance for quite some
time. Early in this century, dancers were sometimes held up by
cables to last through a long exposure.
</P>
<P>
   When Edward Steichen photographed Isadora and Therese Duncan on
the Acropolis in 1921, they were standing still in dance poses,
sometimes with the wind blowing their garments. Even now, when the
camera can catch the least flicker of a foot, it is still difficult
to convey a sense of a fluid and unfolding event in such a
minuscule scrap of time. But splendid approximations have been
made.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Morgan showed the way in the 1930s. At the James
Danziger Gallery, in Manhattan, a retrospective exhibition of 47 of
her photographs presents some of her landmark images of Martha
Graham and other dancers from the late 1930s to the early 40s. In
good retrospective fashion, the show, which runs through March 27,
includes numerous photomontages and light drawings, genres that
Morgan experimented with seriously at an earlier date than most
American photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a painter and printmaker and recognized with shows in
California museums, Morgan (1900-1992) married a photographer and
learned to photograph but said she had no desire to make it her
profession. After moving to New York in 1930, and having a second
child in 1935, she turned to photography because she thought it
would take less time away from her children. She also considered it
the only medium that could capture the 20th-century metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1935 that she saw Martha Graham dance for the first
time and began to photograph her and members of her company. Morgan
had seen an exhibition commemorating Isadora Duncan and been
stunned to realize how little remained of the great dancer's art.
</P>
<P>
   She soon began to document modern dance, in part to give form to
her admiration for pioneer dancers who, though they had little to
live on during the Depression, continued to create art that
affirmed life and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was the perfect subject for Morgan and Morgan the perfect
photographer for the task. They began a close professional
relationship that sometimes entailed working together for an entire
day in the studio and darkroom to get one flawless print.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan would watch rehearsals and performances until the pivotal
instants were locked in her memory, then photograph in her studio
or at the theater. (She never took pictures during a performance,
however, because that would have meant the loss of control over her
dramatic lighting system.)
</P>
<P>
   Graham brought many new movements to the dance repertory, and
Morgan had a knack for finding the moment when motion and emotion
most keenly intensified each other. Look at Erick Hawkins' taut
leap in Graham's ``Penitente,'' a rope in his hand flying out to
the side; or Merce Cunningham jumping with legs tucked up and palms
outstretched in ``Totem Ancestor.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cunningham danced with Graham for six years.) Morgan also used
moments of stillness or completed movement that were meaningful in
Graham's choreography: look at Graham with her knees spread and her
hands, clasped, uplifted in a tortured piece of fabric in
``Lamentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan also took full advantage of Graham's remarkable costumes
to suggest the vector of movement before, during and after the
split second that her camera halted it. In the well-known image
``Letter to the World (Kick),'' Graham's voluminous skirt
momentarily arcs back toward her head as her foot, invisible
beneath the fabric, kicks up behind her; the skirt must have
subsided as soon as the shutter clicked.
</P>
<P>
   In other photographs, a swirling garment billowing out to the
side traces the previous instant and hints at what's to come. Dance
photography (and other photography that stops movement) magnifies
the sense of interrupted time that the camera cannot help but
produce, the awareness that something happened the instant before
the lens opened and the instant after it closed.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan did not ignore Graham's personal beauty and remarkable
dancer's body. In a tight close-up from ``Ekstasis,'' Graham, seen
from collarbone to ankle in a tight tube dress, with light
caressing the long curve of her right side, becomes a sinuous
column emblematic of the female form, life and the potential for
movement.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Improved photographic capacity and Barbara Morgan's talent and
devotion gave history a larger and finer record of an era called
the golden age of American modern dance than we have of dancers
like Duncan or Ruth St. Denis. One writer has suggested that
thousands of Americans first got an inkling of the look of modern
dance, which was not widely seen outside major metropolitan centers
in the 1930s, when a show of Morgan's photographs traveled to more
than 150 universities and other exhibition spaces beginning in
1938.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition that opened at the Museum of Modern Art in 1945
was shown at the first United Nations conference and toured Latin
America under State Department sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, dance photography has changed and acquired a
virtuosity and elasticity beyond what it formerly had, but Morgan's
expressiveness and ability to imply a trajectory of motion in just
one tiny, stopped moment has continued to influence important
photographers of the dance like Martha Swope and Lois Greenfield.
</P>
<P>
   The multiple, contrasting, chaotic rhythms of the modern city
and modern life also attracted Morgan. Photomontage, with its
superimposition of incidents or forms from different realms, looked
like the one medium capable of containing the simultaneity and
diversity of contemporary experience.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938 she wrote: ``Photomontage originates in this multiple
kind of life we are living. We are elated by the spectacle. Life
roars indifferently on. We are saddened by the spectacle. Life
roars indifferently on. The chief function of montage is that of
mirroring this complex life.'' She also used montage to mirror the
complexity of dance, superimposing related moments of a ballet,
sometimes with figures in different scales.
</P>
<P>
   European and Soviet artists had made montage an important part
of their repertory in the 20s and 30s, but America was initially
hostile to the idea (and even in Europe very few women touched it).
Here the doctrine of straight, unmanipulated photography and a
virtual worship of the documentary approach in the 1930s put other
forms of photography in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who was familiar with European art and a good friend of
Laszlo Moholy-Nagy, who had written about montage and continued to
use it when he came to America from Europe, was one of the earliest
Americans to work with this form regularly. Her most hopeful
montage, ``Spring on Madison Square'' (1938), is a now classic
image of people trudging through snow while above them looms a huge
silhouette of Erick Hawkins striding boldly, confidently, with the
white shape of an enormous tulip looping across his form.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Morgan's photomontages refer to social concerns.
``Hearst Over the People,'' a laughing, distorted face of William
Randolph Hearst with octopus tentacles hovering over a crowd,
comments on the power of the media in a manner entirely relevant
today.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples are not quite so clear. ``City Street'' (1937), a
view of the Empire State Building, symbol of money and power,
leaning in two directions and juxtaposed with an aerial view of
pedestrians in fedoras buying pretzels, was said by Morgan to be an
image of ``desperate souls marching across the street in utter
despair, searching, not knowing what was their future.''
</P>
<P>
   But these desperate souls look like nothing so much as
pedestrians in fedoras buying pretzels. Perhaps it was clearer at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   The label of ``Brainwashed'' doesn't say so, but this unfocused
image of a woman's face with a huge black hole where one eye should
be and an odd series of lights streaming across her face was
inspired, according to Morgan, by a school teacher who was
distressed by the effect of television violence on students and who
told Morgan, ``Our children are being brainwashed!'' This was in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan would earn a mention in American photographic history for
her early dedication to photomontage at a time when this country
was leery of European art and single-minded about what kind of
photography it would tolerate. But her major contribution was to
have preserved, in elegant form, the pioneering works of American
modern dance: one art turning another into a feast for the eyes
while offering a plum to history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
