<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4422 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-CONVENTION-LADN     03-10 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CONVENTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD APPLIES BRAKES TO PRODUCTION COSTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS -- Hollywood has temporarily halted its financial
insanity, the industry's top spokesman proclaimed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie industry may have begun taming that fiscal Godzilla
slouching around movie budgets for so long,'' said Jack Valenti,
chairman of the Motion Picture Association in his state of the
industry keynote address at the ShoWest convention in Las Vegas.
``The industry is trying to apply more disciplined habits in one of
its periodic fits of cost control.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti's comments came as part of his report that Hollywood's
seven major studios saw average production costs dip 1.3 &UR;  &LR; percent
last year to $52.7 &UR;  &LR; million per movie, following a stunning
34 &UR;  &LR; percent jump for 1997 films. Of course, 1997 included the
$200 &UR;  &LR; million spent on ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti acknowledged the decline was ``small, small, small,''
but it is also the first concrete evidence to back up studios'
claims that they have actually been holding a line on expenses and
putting the brakes on excessive spending.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti noted that although ``Titanic'' had goosed 1997's cost
significantly, that impact had been more than canceled out by
several megabudget projects last year such as ``Armageddon'' and
``Godzilla.'' The decline in ``negative'' costs  &UR; -- &LR;  industry
jargon for the money needed to complete a movie  &UR; -- &LR;  was the first
since 1991. The cost of prints and advertising shot up 13 &UR;  &LR; percent
to $25.3 &UR;  &LR; million per film, which Valenti blamed on soaring ad
rates for top-rated TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing we can do about it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day convention, sponsored by the National Association
of Theater Owners, also saw release of the final 1998 domestic box
office statistics which came in slightly higher than earlier
projections, with a 9.2 &UR;  &LR; percent gain to $6.95 &UR;  &LR; billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fiscal arithmetic is not founded in illusion,'' Valenti
said. ``With inflation about 1.6 &UR;  &LR; percent, this huge gain in box
office is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Admissions for 1998 rose 6.7 &UR;  &LR; percent to 1.48 &UR;  &LR; billion, the
highest level in four decades. ``We are clearly outpacing the
growth of the population,'' said William Kartozian, president of
the theater owners association.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti and Kartozian also shrugged off the 1999 slump at the
box office, which trails last year's comparable period by
8 &UR;  &LR; percent, mainly due to the success of ``Titanic.'' ``Wait until
May,'' Kartozian said, referring to the opening of ``Episode One:
Phantom Menace.'' ``We'll catch up very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti also said the increase in box office was particularly
impressive given the competition from such areas as satellite TV,
the Internet and DVD. ``Not only did families want to get out of
the house to be entertained,'' he added, ``they also wanted an epic
viewing experience.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Valenti was not entirely upbeat, warning of the
dangers of copyright theft, particularly in Asia where he recalled
seeing vendors hawking pirated video copies of ``Titanic'' outside
theaters showing the film. ``Consider the potential for looting the
Internet of digital movies where the thousandth copy is as pure as
the original,'' he said. ``Unless we find suitable technological
armor, we will soon be standing in the ruins of a once great
enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Kartozian acknowledged that the success of megaplex theaters,
which have become key drivers in the last year's addition of more
than 2,300 screens nationwide, has created a significant problem
for older theaters in nearby areas. ``Evolution is not always
pretty,'' he said. ``The ugliest part is the obsolescence of
multiplexes that are sometimes only 5-8 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the new screens being built in the United States
are in megaplex theaters which offer at least 16 screens with
stadium seating and massive concession stands.
</P>
<P>
   Two surveys released Tuesday showed that the movie business
remains heavily dependent on frequent moviegoers. The theater
owners group reported that customers who visit a theater at least
one a month comprise 28 &UR;  &LR; percent of the population and account for
83 &UR;  &LR; percent of all admissions.
</P>
<P>
   A separate survey by ACNielsen EDI found that 49 &UR;  &LR; percent of
Americans between the ages of 16 and 24 average at least one visit
to the movies per month, well above other age groups. That compares
with 22 &UR;  &LR; percent of those in the 25-34 range, 16 &UR;  &LR; percent of those
35-44 and 15 &UR;  &LR; percent of those 45-54.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 0136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
