<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE TALK GATHERS STEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ There's nothing like the NBA trade winds to
blow an issue out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   With the league's swap-meet deadline scheduled for Thursday, the
proposed deal involving the Los Angeles Lakers and the Charlotte
Hornets continues to gather steam.
</P>
<P>
   As has been reported for the last few weeks, the Lakers would
ship guard Eddie Jones and center-forward Elden Campbell to
Charlotte in exchange for hotshot small forward Glen Rice, power
forward J.R. Reid and guard B.J. Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I do is deal with me,'' Jones said before Tuesday's game
with the Clippers at the Sports Arena. ``It'll work out no matter
how it comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   But recent breezes indicate the Lakers are considering a trade
with Milwaukee that would bring free-agent point guard Terrell
Brandon in exchange for Campbell. That would give the
playoff-contending Bucks a low-post presence, but require the
addition of a floor leader to replace Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   According to a league source, Lakers owner Jerry Buss isn't wild
about dealing Jones, but would love the opportunity to jettison
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Deadlines for Clippers: News of a trading deadline hasn't
escaped the Clippers, who continue to field inquiries from teams
eager to steal something from a team that lost its first 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Another approaching deadline arrives Saturday, the last day
teams can offer contract extensions to current players. The roster
of Clippers in the last year of their contracts includes Lamond
Murray, Lorenzen Wright, Rodney Rogers and Eric Piatkowski.
</P>
<P>
   According to a team source, the Clippers aren't expected to make
any contract-extension offers until after July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Playing not to lose: Maintaining a winning streak in the NBA is
no cinch, and it's an even bigger chore when the next opponent is
absolutely starving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a tough game for us,'' Lakers point guard Derek
Harper said of playing the winless Clippers. ``You have to guard
against playing to your opponent's level. It's important for us to
take it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   But does the threat of eclipsing the league record for
season-opening losses (17 by Miami in 1988) add pressure to the
Clippers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Clipper forward Maurice Taylor said. ``I really
don't think it's a factor. There's a lot of basketball left to
play. If you worry about losing streaks and that sort of thing,
you're too busy thinking about the wrong stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   `Kandi' update: According to Clippers rookie center Michael
Olowokandi, his visit to the injured list (left ankle) is expected
to end tonight at the Forum. The 7-footer from Pacific injured the
ankle the last time the Clippers played at the Forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 0138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0045 </DOCNO>
