<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-NUGGETS-H     03-10 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-NUGGETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Scottie Pippen blocked a shot, batted the ball upcourt, chased it
down, reached for one of Calvin Murphy's cookies and passed to
Michael Dickerson for an open-court layup.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rockets' 84-75 win over the Nuggets at Compaq Center on
Tuesday should have been that easy. Fill the highlight tapes, erase
the memory of the Trail Blazers _ and have a tasty snack.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. Had Pippen kept in step with the Rockets' night, the
play would have been spectacular (not that it wasn't), but the
cookie would have slipped from his hand and the Nuggets' Danny
Fortson would have been there to grab it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets shot well, ran their offense as expertly as they
have in weeks, played outstanding defense and did almost everything
they could hope to do to win easily. Instead, they won ugly.
</P>
<P>
   And though Pippen did actually wait until the ensuing dead ball
to (unsuccessfully) raid Murphy's cache, he had offered a clue as
to how easily he would later take over, knowing he could if needed.
</P>
<P>
   With the Rockets inexplicably unable to put away the game as
late as midway through the fourth quarter, Pippen scored 10 of his
17 points in a span of three minutes, each on a more remarkable
play to finally let the Rockets surge safely past the Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and didn't take care of business early,'' Pippen
said. ``We should have played a lot better. We should have allowed
our bench a chance to come out and have some fun. We got outworked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity was there, and I was able to make some shots
down the stretch. I felt like I had to be more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich: ``Scottie was great. He
made big play after big play, defensively and offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets needed someone to take over, despite pushing the
Nuggets into the worst shooting night ever in the building. While
the Nuggets could make just 23 of 77 shots (29.9 percent, the
third-worst night in franchise history), the Rockets shot well,
passed well and ran their break well. They also got the ball inside
routinely, outscoring the Nuggets 52-26 in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   But because they were careless with the ball, committing 20
turnovers, and routed on the boards, they were unable to put the
Nuggets away. Fortson, the Nuggets' burly 6-7 center, had 21
rebounds, 11 on the offensive glass.
</P>
<P>
   With Fortson immovable inside, the Nuggets scored 19
second-chance points, a number held down only because he was able
to make just four of 12 field goal attempts and seven of 13 free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles (Barkley) made me play harder,'' said Fortson, who
drew a technical for looking to retaliate after a hard Barkley
foul. ``He was creating a monster, and he didn't know it. I still
respect him, and he's one of my favorite players. Those type of
guys you can't listen to, or you'll go crazy. You just have to go
out and play hard. Charles was trying to get me to go over the
edge, and I knew it. It was a smart, veteran move.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who grabbed 13 rebounds but never could control
Fortson, would not comment after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebounding is `rrrrrrr,''' Tomjanovich said. ``It's `my man is
not getting it this time. I'm going to put my butt on him, and he
is not getting it this time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Failing that for much of the night, the Rockets found themselves
in an odd sort of toe-to-toe battle. They had seen an 11-point lead
turn into a three-point deficit, and they lost all of a five-point
lead in the third quarter, falling into a three-point hole.
</P>
<P>
   But almost as if shifting into another gear that had been
dormant all along, the Rockets turned up their defensive intensity,
took care of the boards and began to roll. The Rockets took off on
a 12-0 run, all on layups, dunks or free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen set up Hakeem Olajuwon for a layup, Cuttino Mobley drove
for a dunk, and Pippen had his block and pass to Dickerson. By the
time Brent Price cut down the lane to convert a pass from Olajuwon
into a layup, the Rockets had rebuilt their 11-point lead, 65-54,
two minutes into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They could not, however, make that lead hold up. The Rockets'
penchant for coming up with every sort of turnover _ they had seven
in the first seven minutes of the fourth quarter _ would not allow
them to expand their lead.
</P>
<P>
   It did not even matter that the Rockets were shooting well _
they were 7-of-9 in the first 10 minutes of the fourth quarter _ or
that the Nuggets were shooting horribly. The Rockets' turnovers
limited their chances. And Fortson continued to dominate on the
offensive boards to keep the Nuggets within range.
</P>
<P>
   But then Pippen took over. He drove for a layup before taking a
pass from Barkley for a 3. The next drive was even better, with
Pippen cutting across the lane and past the basket before flipping
a shot in. And finally, he took off on a fast break, then after
drawing hard contact from Nick Van Exel, flipped the ball under the
Denver guard's arm and somehow in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got fouled and just tried to get it up to the basket,'' said
Pippen, who seemed to enjoy the moment far more at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the sort of game _ like the cookie Murphy
successfully guarded _ that was difficult to find satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' Price said. ``Scottie made the big plays we
needed to secure the victory. We won ugly, but it's a win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
