<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4433 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      03-10 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Basketball is a non-contact sport in which the
imagination provides the only restriction on movement.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the way it is supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   But the game has gotten physical, very physical. Especially at
the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That is a significant change for the Longhorns, who in recent
years had been known for their guard play _ little guys who played
as if there was a ``No Trespassing'' sign posted at the 3-point
line.
</P>
<P>
   Remember BMW? Lance Blanks, Travis Mays and Joey Wright? They
led Texas to the Midwest Regional final in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Well, now it is the Big Three. Chris Mihm, Nnadubem ``Gabe''
Muoneke and Kris Clack hope to do as well, or better.
</P>
<P>
   Big because they are bigger than most and are responsible for
Texas turning around a dismal start to claim the Big 12 Conference
regular-season title and a No. 7 seed in the NCAA Tournament's East
Regional, where it will face Purdue on Friday at the Fleet Center
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The trio enters games expecting to win the matchup down low.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Chris Mihm is the best center in the nation,'' said
Muoneke, a junior power forward who leads the Longhorns in scoring.
``I sat and thought about it the other day, and it's hard to say
about a sophomore, but I think Chris is mature enough to hear it. I
don't think there is a true center out there that's better than he
is. That gives us an advantage right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we always have an advantage at the `3' spot _ Clack is too
big and too athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   That description of the versatile Clack _ who leads the team in
3-pointers and is second in steals and third in points, rebounds
and assists _ is one that Big 12 coaches use in describing the
difficulty in matching up with all three players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick one _ they are all bigger and stronger than anyone we can
put on him,'' Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton said. ``And I'm
pretty sure almost every team in the country will say that. They're
big, strong and can shoot outside _ all three of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Difficult matchups up front are why Texas coach Rick Barnes
believes a grind-it-out style of play suits his team best.
</P>
<P>
   That get-it-low philosophy is why the trio accounted for 61
percent of the field goals attempted by the Longhorns during the
regular season. They are 1-2-3 on the team in scoring, rebounding
and blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're supposed to carry a big part of the load _ our
teammates expect us to do that every night,'' Clack said.
</P>
<P>
   They lead in nearly every category and, of course, are 1-2-3 in
foul shots attempted as teams resort to all sorts of tactics to
contain them.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual to see:
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke working his way to the basket with an opponent's knee
poking the back of his thigh with every movement and the foe's
forearm lodged in that ever-so-uncomfortable spot in the small of
his back. The collisions come at rhythmic intervals, like football
players attacking a blocking sled.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm, low post position already established, with a defender
draped all over him, an elbow against Mihm's biceps and a hand on
his hip, and a 5-11 pest fronting Mihm with an elbow poised near
the solar plexus.
</P>
<P>
   Clack in his usual spot on the baseline, trying to get to the
other side of the floor where he can get free for his favored
fadeaway jumper from the corner but being denied by a defender
engaging in an extended hand-to-hand tussle with a few body blows
mixed in.
</P>
<P>
   One would think activity like that would lead to complaints from
Texas' frontcourt stars, but that is the kind of game they long
for.
</P>
<P>
   That also is the type of game they expect in the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get away with a lot of stuff too,'' said Muoneke. ``For the
most part over a 40-minute period, that plays more to our liking.
Chris can take a lot of contact and score anyway, and so can Clack.
When (a defender) gets physical with Clack, especially a guard,
it's no match whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down to a physical game and the referees aren't
calling the contact, I think it works to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas does pack a solid punch across the board. Teams like
Purdue need not be warned of what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Texas shooting guard DeJuan ``Chico'' Vazquez tips the scale at
about the same weight as the heaviest player on Purdue's roster,
6-8, 230-pound Brian Cardinal. The Boilermakers run a three-guard
offense, with Cardinal as a forward. Their center is 6-7, 215-pound
Greg McQuay.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Three outweigh the Boilermakers' heftiest three starters
by a combined 102 pounds. That is an average of 34 pounds a man.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder what the Longhorns' game plan will be?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think going into games, Gabe and I feel like we can
dominate,'' Mihm said. ``It's just a matter of if we come to play
together and play as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that our frontcourt has gotten some respect this
year. The turnaround has helped us start to get some team
recognition as well as some individual recognition. It's something
to be proud of, but we don't really pay that much attention to it,
because if we don't play well it's going to be, `What a
disappointment the Big Three are.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
