<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4434 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-10 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE Rockets told us not to read too much into the 40-point loss at
Portland two days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It was deceivingly one-sided, they said. Don't worry. Don't
punch the panic button. And certainly don't go postal, or even
Mailman, about the ugly possibilities on the Rockets' horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But don't snuggle up to a warm fire and embrace Tuesday's
nine-point victory against lowly Denver, either.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice, timely and at times entertaining tale that
certainly had a happy ending _ Rockets win 84-75.
</P>
<P>
   But it might have been scripted as much by William Faulkner as
Rudy Tomjanovich. It was so much a flowing story, yet awkward, so
much a classic Rockets exhibition and yet difficult to get through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started out doing what we wanted. We were running the
ball,'' Cuttino Mobley said. ``But then, I don't know if it was
because we were tired, but we weren't doing it. I guess it's hard
to expect to have everything together at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   One moment you understood what this Rockets story could be all
about _ ah, yes, this is how it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dickerson, he of the young legs and soft shot, bolts in
front of the pack for a layup on the fast break. On the next
possession, Mobley, he of the sly smile and clever game, slides
between bodies and lays in another fast-break bucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we were trying to establish,'' Dickerson said.
``Get out and run. Establish something.''
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon, on the way to 20 points, shook like a dream.
Scottie Pippen, seemingly on the way to finding his place in this
Rockets story with 10 points in a span of three fourth-quarter
minutes, sealed the win the way champions do.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the Rockets' defense held the poor Nuggets to
29.9-percent shooting and left them dangling there, exposed and
helpless, like participles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that 29-percent,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I don't remember
having a stat like that. When you look at the defense, that's good.
That's the foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet the next moment, the story fell flat. The Rockets'
effort made you cry as much as it made you laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets hadn't won a road game all year _ they are 0-10 now
if you're keeping track _ yet took a couple of brief leads on the
Rockets and made a game of it into the fourth quarter despite the
horrendous shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio McDyess flew spectacularly through the air, while Danny
Fortson threw elbows with Charles Barkley and wound up with a
pointed 15 points and 21 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was as confusing in victory as the Trail Blazers loss was
confusing in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the Rockets still were not sure if they wanted to
be Showtime or Slowtime, sometimes impressively moving up the
floor, sometimes content to pitch it into Olajuwon or Barkley and
simply watch what happened.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many signs that this story is unfolding exactly
the way Tomjanovich would like to write it. Pippen on the run,
finally knifing through the lane. Mobley earning his place at the
point, while Bryce Drew sat and Matt Maloney watched.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the early review of this one should be that
Cuttino is beginning to cut it at the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's coming,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We made big plays.
We rebounded. I see Mobley doing a good job (at point guard).
Scottie made big play after big play defensively and offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there also were signs that the story remains an unsolved
mystery, as if the Rockets still are not sure what they want to be
and are not always comfortable with where they are on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Those 20 turnovers are a sure sign of indecisiveness. The
Rockets' 19-7 deficit on offensive rebounds can only partially be
blamed on the brick-throwing Nuggets getting more shots. The flat
feet while watching Olajuwon and Barkley work the post was like a
bad novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got outworked tonight,'' Pippen said. ``They had more
energy than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   They did. But the Rockets won. It was a good win and a
much-needed win, but how much should be read into it?
</P>
<P>
   Not much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it all over the league: Teams that have been together
for years are getting out of what they do,'' Tomjanovich said.
``But I like what I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't read too much into it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
