<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' TEMPERS FLARE IN PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Some of the struggling Los Angeles Kings'
frustration boiled over during Tuesday morning's skate, when goalie
Jamie Storr and winger Donald Audette exchanged a couple of
harmless punches before being separated by teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred when Storr objected to a high shot by
Audette as the Kings were practicing at the Forum for Tuesday
night's game against the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of frustration out there, but nothing
happened,'' Audette said.
</P>
<P>
   Storr added, ``It's no big deal. It's part of hockey. Over the
course of a season, you're going to have confrontations and
controversies. It doesn't mean you don't like each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Larry Robinson said he had his back turned during
the brief incident. Asked his reaction, Robinson said, ``At least
it shows they're a little bit (ticked) off, which they should be.
Those things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fond memories: Robinson returned Monday from Canada, where he
attended the funeral of his mother, Isobel, who died last week at
78.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long couple of days,'' Robinson said. ``I'm hanging
in there. I'm trying to get my hockey mode back. I can't say I've
been thinking too much about hockey the last few days. But life
goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a native of Ontario, added, ``We grew up on a farm. My
dad didn't have a lot of time to take us places. It was mom who
took us to the rink, who fed us and took care of us when we were
sick, because dad didn't have time.''
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne scratched: Defenseman Steve Duchesne, who has struggled
all season, was a healthy scratch for the 4-2 victory over Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen and hear, over the last two or three
games, he's still not willing to pay the price to make a play,''
Robinson said. ``We can't afford to wait. We've got to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson gave no guarantee Duchesne would return to the lineup
Saturday against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Murray struggling: Winger Glen Murray scored 15 goals in his
first 37 games this season, putting him on pace for 33 goals in an
82-game season. But a knee injury on Jan. 2 sidelined him for seven
weeks, and since returning to the lineup on Feb. 19, Murray was
without a goal in eight games entering Tuesday night's meeting with
the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I thought I'd come back in and play the way I was
playing (before the injury),'' said Murray, who admitted he's had a
difficult time adjusting to the brace he now wears on his right
knee. ``Obviously, it's not true. I feel like I'm still one step
behind every play. Maybe I'm thinking too much. I've got to keep
everything simple and do my own job, not everyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   Puck-less plans: Two weeks ago in Detroit, Robinson skated his
players for 40 minutes without pucks, and threatened that for the
rest of the season he would repeat the grueling practice regimen
one minute for every minute he is dissatisfied with the team's
effort in games.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson - who missed key home losses Thursday and Saturday to
Nashville and Calgary while attending his mother's funeral in
Canada - said Tuesday he intends to stand by that threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys aren't paying the price,'' Robinson said when asked to
evaluate the Nashville and Calgary losses. ``You can have all the
game plans you want. I look at (Eastern Conference leader) Ottawa.
I don't think there's a huge difference from their personnel to
ours. But everyone from (Alexei) Yashin on down goes hard and pays
the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Winger Vladimir Tsyplakov may return from his knee
injury Saturday against Vancouver, and winger Steve McKenna may
return next week from the abdominal injury that has sidelined him
for most of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
