</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTSTOPS BATTLE FOR BACKUP JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ One might think the shortstops in camp would see
Gary DiSarcina's injury as an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   If DiSarcina, out since Feb. 21 with a broken bone in his left
forearm, can't make it back by opening day, one of these guys will
be the Anaheim Angels' shortstop on April 6 against the Cleveland
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not necessarily true for the season. DiSarcina will
be back eventually, whether it's by opening day or a week into the
season, so Jeff Huson and Luis Rivera are simply fighting for a
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys in my situation come to camp having to do everything they
can to begin with,'' Huson said. ``There's no margin for error.
Even if Gary didn't get hurt, there's still no margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's a battle every day; it's a battle every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Huson and Rivera have been around a while; Huson, 34, has played
professionally since 1986. Rivera, 35, has played professionally
since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize it's easy for starters to come to camp,''
Huson said. ``It's hard for part-time players. If I don't perform
for six weeks (during spring training), I'm done.''
</P>
<P>
   Huson and Rivera have split the starts at shortstop in the
Angels' first five Cactus League games, Huson starting three of the
five. Huson is 2 for 9 and has not made an error. Rivera is 2 for 5
with one error.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've got to show them is that I can play defense at
shortstop,'' Huson said.
</P>
<P>
   Angels have arms to spare: A Randy Johnson-Roger Clemens duel in
late September would have been something.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, however, barely missed out on signing Johnson, and
the Texas Rangers came within a whisker of trading for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   So, we'll have to settle for Chuck Finley vs. John Burkett, or
Ken Hill vs. Rick Helling with the AL West up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case in the division known for the Mo Vaughns, Juan
Gonzalezes and Ken Griffeys, not the Steve Sparkses or Mark Clarks.
</P>
<P>
   While the Angels won't hesitate to admit their strength is a
lineup that has Vaughn, Darin Erstad, Tim Salmon and Jim Edmonds
among others, they aren't whining about lacking quality arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have choices,'' said new Angels pitching coach Dick Pole.
``We're not in a situation where we have to make a pitching staff
up. We've got guys competing for spots ... We've got people who
will compete, and when you've got people who compete like that, you
have a good chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Pole was speaking about the likes of Finley and Tim Belcher. At
ages 36 and 37, respectively, both are past their prime. But both
are known for keeping their team close and eating up innings over
the course of a season.
</P>
<P>
   Health is always an issue. And when it comes to the Angels, the
most important health question involves Hill's surgically repaired
right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   He missed 2 1/2 months last year after having arthroscopic
surgery to remove bone chips, and wasn't at full strength when he
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Hill's the key,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``If
Ken Hill's arm is healthy, he will give us 200 innings, 200 quality
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why I don't worry about the bullpen. If the starters give
us what we anticipate they'll give us, the bullpen sets itself up.
They don't get overworked and stay in their roles.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case last year, when the starters completed only
three games. It took a toll on the bullpen late in the season.
Shigetoshi Hasegawa pitched 97 1/3 innings last year, the most by a
reliever in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have Sparks penciled in as their No. 4 starter, with
Omar Olivares, Jarrod Washburn and Jason Dickson competing for the
fifth spot. Closer Troy Percival anchors the bullpen; Rich DeLucia
joins Hasegawa as the primary set-up men. Mike Holtz will be the
situational lefty.
</P>
<P>
   Pole has his work cut out for him getting to know his pitchers,
but he has former pitching coach Marcel Lachemann, now the
organization's roving pitching instructor, helping with the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher said he likes what he sees in the Angels' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the old baseball adage says you never have enough
pitching,'' Belcher said. ``But I feel our pitching is as good, if
not better, than anybody in our division. It's equal to Texas, and
I think we have the edge in experience. They have (closer John)
Wetteland; we have Percival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle's got quality starters, but no Cy Young candidates.
Over the course of 162 games, I'll take our chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 0206EST &QL; 
