<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creative film funding
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Action. Lights. Camera. Oil filter.
</P>
<P>
   Austin filmmaker Steve Mims is auctioning off his 1980 Honda
Civic on the Internet to help pay for the low budget film he's
about to introduce at the South by Southwest Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should know that the air conditioner blows cold,'' said
Steve, who also owns a 10-year-old Honda.
</P>
<P>
   Steve is borrowing $20,000 to pay for the final print of his
film, ``The Perfect Specimen.'' To help repay the loan, he's
selling the older car, which is not a perfect specimen.
</P>
<P>
   Steve says State Farm Insurance has declared the '80 Civic
totalled twice, after two different wrecks. Something tells me
Steve isn't going to get quite $20,000 for this car, unless
somebody like Michael Dell has a weak moment.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if Steve could get Sandra Bullock to sit on the hood it
would jack up the bidding war. ``We could just auction off the warm
spot,'' Steve said. But that's not likely to happen because Steve
doesn't know Sandra Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   The car has a crinkled left front fender. ``If you see this car
in a movie, it's the one that's going to go off the cliff,'' Steve
said. Still, the Civic runs well.
</P>
<P>
   Steve says he will drive the car to the winning bidder. ``I have
sworn I'll deliver this anywhere in North America,'' said Steve,
39. Let's hope he doesn't have to rent a tow truck to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Specimen,'' Steve's first feature, will have its
world premiere Sunday at South by Southwest at the Paramount
Theater. The movie is getting a fancier unveiling than the car.
Steve will show off the Honda at 1:30 p.m. today at a press
conference at Putt-Putt Golf &AMP; Games at 6700 Burnet Road.
</P>
<P>
   You can get in on the auction _ it starts Thursday at noon _ by
calling up ebay.com, Steve said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far as we know, nobody has ever done this,'' Steve added.
And I'll bet that includes Cecil B. De Mille.
</P>
<P>
   I drove the car. My big problem with it is that it doesn't have
an outside rearview mirror. ``But it used to,'' Steve said. Now
there's a selliing point.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Steve's new movie is a romantic comedy about two
young people whose desires are interrupted by technology.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they try to drive this heap to a cheap motel and
the engine bursts into flames en route? That's not the plot, Steve
says.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Steve doesn't expect to get the $20,000 he needs from
the auction. Steve and his friends have a pool going on what the
actual bid will be. The guesses on the high bid range from $400 to
$2,200.
</P>
<P>
   The car fits the movie, however. ``The Perfect Specimen,''
filmed at various locations around town, including the Continental
Club, was an extremely low- budget venture, Steve says. For
example, a tuxedo company loaned him the tuxes for the prom scene
that he filmed at the Texas School for the Deaf.
</P>
<P>
   I drove the 19-year-old Civic to Howdy Honda in South Austin to
see what I could get for it. Hey, a sharp talker like me might be
able to settle this deal before we have to go to all the trouble to
auction the car, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``And you said the name of the film is ``The Perfect Specimen?''
said used car sales manager Steven Walker, laughing a lot as he
looked the car over.
</P>
<P>
   ``In real money to a dealer, this car is probably a $700-$800
car,'' he said. ``But a dealer wouldn't even keep this car. They'd
sell it to a second-chance dealer on South Congress. What would
happen is they'd put '$1,995' on the windshield, then they'd take
$200 down and charge him $25 a week until it blew up.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, in the case of this car, might not be too long.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
