<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4734 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-TAKE     03-10 1865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: There was a lot in the news last year about a commercial
videotape version of a home movie of President Kennedy's
assassination. Supposedly it was to be made available to the
public. Where can I get a copy?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're referring to ``Image of an Assassination: A New Look
at the Zapruder Film,'' a 45-minute, digitally enhanced version of
an 8-mm home movie Abraham Zapruder made Nov. 22, 1963, when
Kennedy's motorcade passed the Texas School Book Depository and
Dealey Plaza in Dallas. If you can't find it at a video store, one
option is to try Blockbuster Entertainment, 1-800-800-6767. A
representative can tell you which Blockbuster location near you has
it. We were told that it can be ordered for purchase at any
Blockbuster store by referring to film 634853.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is in charge of the American Red Cross, now that
Elizabeth Dole has resigned as president?
</P>
<P>
   A: Steve Bullock, chief executive officer of the organization's
Greater Cleveland (Ohio) Chapter, has been serving as acting
president since Dole announced her resignation Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that the eradication of polio is expected by next
year. I always understood that Rotary Clubs were involved in this
worldwide effort, but that wasn't mentioned. Can you explain the
Rotary's role?
</P>
<P>
   A: Much of the impetus and money that has gone into quashing
polio did indeed come from Evanston, Ill.-based Rotary
International. Polio vaccines developed in the United States in the
1950s and early '60s virtually rid the United States and Western
Europe of the disease by the 1970s. But only 5 percent of all Third
World children were immunized by then, and polio continued to cut
down millions. In the 1980s, a coalition of international agencies
launched a plan to finally make the vaccines available to all
children.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Rotary International came into the picture. In
1988, as the plan to destroy polio came together, Rotary raised
$400 million to help it along. The Rotary money _ which bought
vaccines to immunize more than a billion children _ has been a
handy stick that Rotary has used to keep squabbling at a minimum
among agencies, governments and experts as they struggle toward the
goal. So Rotary indeed did play a role, and a crucial one, to bring
an end to the deadly virus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Deviled eggs are a favorite treat at family gatherings. Where
does the ``devil'' part come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: In cookery, to ``devil'' a food item means simply to prepare
it with hot or savory seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to singer Tommy Edwards of ``It's All in
the Game'' fame? A brief part of the song is in the current movie,
``October Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   A: The rhythm and blues singer, pianist and songwriter died in
October 1969 at age 47. ``It's All in the Game'' was his biggest
hit, peaking at No. 1 in October 1958 and staying on the charts for
22 weeks. Edwards recorded more than a dozen songs, but only three
others made the Top 20 list: ``Please Mr. Sun,'' ``Love Is All We
Need'' and ``I Really Don't Want to Know.'' The 1958 version of
``It's All in the Game'' was a rerecording by Edwards of his own
1951 hit, a feat that started a rush of rerecordings by various
artists.
</P>
<P>
   And here's a bet-you-didn't-know tidbit: The melody to ``Game''
was written in 1912 by Charles Dawes, who later would become
President Calvin Coolidge's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do the digits in the three sequences of a Social
Security number represent?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first three digits indicate the state shown in the
mailing address on the original application. The lowest Social
Security numbers were assigned to the New England states, and the
numbers grew progressively higher in the South and West. However,
in recent years this geographical relationship has been disrupted
somewhat by the need to allocate numbers out of sequence as state
populations changed.
</P>
<P>
   The middle two digits have no special significance, but serve to
break the numbers into blocks of convenient size. The last four
digits represent a straight numerical progression of assigned
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recent voter unrest in Africa brings to mind the Mau Mau
rebel violence of the 1950s. What present-day country or countries
constitute where the Mau Mau were then?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Mau Mau African nationalist movement originated among the
Kikuyu people of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported on TV that a 1943 penny was worth half a
million dollars. Can you provide any information about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: That item generated considerable interest from people who
have pennies from this era. But the American Numismatic Association
says the most ever paid for a 1943 penny was $86,500, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the story, however, as reported initially by the AP: Zane
Mangum, owner of Mangum's Automotive near McCall, Idaho, had a 1943
copper penny, known among collectors as a ``wheatie.'' It was a
rare coin _ only about 40 were created, because copper was too
valuable in wartime for such use _ that Mangum had had for about 14
years. Mangum said he had been told by collectors that the last
time one of these pennies was sold, in 1981, it went for $10,000.
Estimates that he received recently said the penny could fetch more
than $100,000, and possibly $500,000, if sold at auction, he told
the AP.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Mangum, last August he apparently mixed the
rare coin with his regular change and spent it. He said he wanted
his story published in hopes of ending the sick feeling he gets
when he thinks about the penny.
</P>
<P>
   The television report in Atlanta said magnets won't attract the
copper pennies, as they will the steel pennies minted that same
year. But a coin expert has warned that some 1943 steel pennies
were coated with copper. The best advice to people people who think
their 1943 penny is rare to take it to a coin dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After Jordan's King Hussein died, I saw a report referring to
him as a Hashimite. What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: A Hashimite (also spelled Hashemite) is a member of any Arab
dynasty in the Middle East founded by Husein ibn-Ali or his
descendants. The line traces to the prophet Muhammad, a member of
the house of Hashim, a subdivision of the Quraysh tribe. The most
revered line of Hashimites passed through Hasan, son of the
prophet's daughter Fatimah, and her husband, Ali. The modern
Hashimite dynasty was founded by Faisal and Abdul Allah, the sons
of Husayn ibn Ali, emir of Mecca, who became kings of Iraq and
Jordan, respectively. The official name of Jordan, by the way, is
Al-Mamlakah Al-Urdiniyah Al-Hashimiyah (Hashemite Kingdom of
Jordan).
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the movie ``L.A. Confidential,'' someone uses the
expression ``Q.T.,'' in the sense of ``hush, hush,'' as in when you
tell somebody something ``on the QT.'' Where does this come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: The initials stand for ``quiet,'' according to the Facts on
File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins. An early recorded use
was in a British ballad, circa 1870, containing this line:
``Whatever I tell you is on the Q.T.'' The expression gained more
popularity in 1891 when it appeared in a minstrel show
number,``Ta-ra-ra-boom-de-ay.'' According to accounts of the time,
London ``went stark mad'' over the refrain:
</P>
<P>
   A sweet Tuxedo girl you see,/ Queen of swell society,/
</P>
<P>
   Fond of fun as fun can be/ When it's on the strict Q.T./
</P>
<P>
   I'm not too young, I'm not too old,/ Not too timid, not too
bold, /
</P>
<P>
   Just the kind of sport I'm told _/ Ta-ra-ra-boom-de-ay . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I obtain a copy of the congressional ``Pig Book
Summary,'' which lists costly government spending projects that
benefit few people?
</P>
<P>
   A: Those with Internet capability can read it at
http://www.cagw.org, the home page of Washington-based Citizens
Against Government Waste. Or call 1-800-BE-ANGRY (1-800-232-6479)
to order it for $5. Those who join CAGW for $25 get it free, along
with quarterly newsletters and other mailings, a spokeswoman said.
Information: Citizens Against Government Waste, 1301 Connecticut
Ave. N.W., Washington, DC 20036.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My brother-in-law told me that Ghana is offering dual
citizenship for blacks living in the United States. Do you have any
information?
</P>
<P>
   A: A representative of the Ghanaian Embassy in Washington said
there has been discussion on the matter of dual citizenship for
both Ghanaians wanting U.S. citizenship and U.S. citizens of any
race wanting Ghanaian citizenship, but nothing has been
implemented. She declined to speculate on a timetable or on the
outlook for a decision.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. State Department, the government of Ghana
at present recognizes dual nationality only for minors younger than
21. A dual national who enters Ghana with a Ghanaian passport is
treated as a Ghanaian citizen only, the State Department adds. If a
dual national Ghanaian-American enters Ghana on a Ghanaian passport
and is later arrested for any reason while there, the U.S. Embassy
normally is not notified of the arrest by Ghanaian authorities. As
a result, consular assistance for dual U.S.-Ghanaian citizens may
be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Embassy of Ghana, 202-686-4520.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On a recent ``Jeopardy,'' one of the answers was that tons of
chicken feet are sent to China. What do the Chinese do with chicken
feet?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are cooked and eaten or used in recipes for such things
as chicken foot soup. You sometimes can find items like braised
chicken feet at Chinese restaurants in the United States, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I received in change a 1999 quarter with the image of George
Washington on one side and a man on a horse, under the word
Delaware, on the other. Will all the states have such coins?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, eventually. Delaware is the first of the U.S. Mint's
``50 States Quarters Program,'' which will recognize all the states
over a 10-year period. Distribution of the Delaware coin began in
January. A series of five quarter-dollars with new reverses will be
issued each year through 2008, in the sequence that the states
entered the union. To date, designs have been selected for the
first five state quarters: Delaware, Pennsylvania, New Jersey,
Georgia and Connecticut. The reverse side of the Delaware quarter
depicts Caesar Rodney on horseback en route to Philadelphia to cast
the tie-breaking vote in the Delaware delegation in favor of
independence in 1776. Information is available online at the U.S.
Mint's site: http://www.usmint.gov
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about Tubby Smith, the basketball coach at the
University of Kentucky. Is that his real name? Also, his son, who
played basketball for the University of Georgia Bulldogs, is called
G.G. Where does that come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: The real first name of both father and son is Orlando. The
son's full name is Orlando Guffrie Gibson Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
