<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4735 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-TAKE     03-10 1929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS11-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDITORS: THIS IS PART TWO OF A TWO PART FILE)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I haven't seen anything in print lately about actress
Katharine Hepburn. Can you update those of us who are longtime
fans?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hepburn, who will be 92 in May, keeps a low profile, having
moved permanently from her Manhattan townhouse to a mansion in Old
Saybrook, Conn. Her father, a Connecticut doctor, built the mansion
in the early part of the century. While Hepburn generally stays out
of public view, she does pop back into the news occasionally. In
October, for instance, the New York Post published an account of a
dinner visit with Hepburn by longtime friend and neighbor Max
Showalter. In it, Showalter, an actor and artist, said she was in
``wonderful condition'' and showed no signs of the acute stomach
flu that landed her in a hospital earlier last year.
</P>
<P>
   That same item included a comment by Ellsworth Grant, who lives
near Hepburn and who was married to her late sister, Marianne.
Grant said Hepburn walks a little and talks a little, but her
memory is pretty much gone. In an interview with the Boston Herald
the day after Hepburn's 91st birthday, her brother, Robert, said
she spent the birthday quietly. ``She doesn't like old age. She
doesn't particularly approve of old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of Frank Wills, the security guard who
discovered the Watergate break-in during the Nixon administration?
I had heard he was unemployed and couldn't get a job.
</P>
<P>
   A: Wills was last known to be living in virtual obscurity in
South Carolina, having become almost a footnote in history since
his date with destiny at Washington's Watergate complex. It was on
June 17, 1972, when he noticed suspicious tape on a doorway of the
Democratic Party offices. He eventually called the District of
Columbia police, setting in motion a momentous chain of events that
included political burglary, conspiracy, obstruction of justice,
illegal use of the FBI and CIA, and illegal campaign contributions.
And brought down the presidency of Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wills was the focus of media attention for a time, his
moment in the sun didn't last long. Comedian-activist Dick Gregory
put him to work for a while, and during the 1980s he drifted from
one security job to another. By 1990 he had returned to South
Carolina to take care of his invalid mother, living off her Social
Security and odd jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, on the 25th anniversary of the Watergate break-in,
Wills was interviewed by several newspapers. He admitted that he
had grown bitter and lashed out at political leaders and civil
rights groups that, he said, didn't help him during his
post-Watergate troubles. ``The people of the cause . . . not one of
them came to say: `Can we do anything to help you?'''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recent articles have mentioned a pay boost for active duty
and retired military personnel. Is this retroactive to Jan. 1 of
this year, or does it begin Jan. 1, 2000?
</P>
<P>
   A: The pay raises and sweetened pensions contained in the
measure, called the Soldiers', Sailors', Airmens' and Marines' BIll
of Rights, would take effect Jan. 1, 2000. The Senate
overwhelmingly approved the bill Feb. 24. It authorizes a 4.8
percent raise next year, allots bonuses of up to 10.3 percent, and
provides for slightly better pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several weeks ago, a woman sailing solo in an
around-the-world race had to abandon her capsized boat in the South
Pacific. A competitor saved her. What was the end of the story?
</P>
<P>
   A: At last report, famed French sailor Isabelle Autissier was
still aboard the boat of Giovanni Soldini, the Italian sailor who
rescued her. The incident occured Feb. 15 when Autissier, competing
in the Around Alone sailboat race, was capsized by a huge wave.
</P>
<P>
   Autissier, the leader of the competition's third leg as it left
New Zealand and headed around Cape Horn, was saved thanks to a
revolutionary transmitter known as an Emergency Positioning Radio
Beacon. After her 60-foot vessel rolled onto its topside, remaining
afloat by virtue of an air pocket inside the hull, Autissier was so
confident that her emergency message would be heard that she
collected her lifesaving gear and went to sleep. Soldini, 200 miles
away when her beacon sounded, spent a day and a night to get to
her.
</P>
<P>
   Even that isn't the end of the story. Nine days after he rescued
Autissier, Soldini was diverted again to assist race leader Marc
Thiercelin, whose vessel was flooded when its broken mast punched a
hole in the deck. The 27,000-mile race, held every four years,
began in September in Charleston, S.C., and is expected to end in
late May.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall an article saying the Red Cross was investigating a
method of numbing a small area of a blood donor's arm with a patch.
Is that available yet? If they promise to get me numb, I'll promise
to give blood.
</P>
<P>
   A: The subject came up last year when Elizabeth Dole, then
president of the American Red Cross, was visiting Atlanta. Among
the projects talked about was a bandage called a ``numby'' that
would be applied to the spot on the donor's arm where the needle
was inserted to collect blood. The bandage would transfer just
enough anesthetic to the needle-stick area to numb it and allow for
a painless collection procedure. The numby is still in the research
phase, with implementation several years down the road, according
to the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that washing your hands with ordinary soap
doesn't get rid of bacteria. What about the new alcohol-based,
waterless hand sanitizers?
</P>
<P>
   A: Handwashing with soap is intended to remove bacteria from
skin surfaces by the action of the water, and not necessarily kill
them. The key is to wash thoroughly in water as hot as the hands
can stand comfortably, said Elizabeth Andrews, a professor and food
safety specialist at the University of Georgia Extension Service.
Rub hands together with lather for at least 20 seconds and dry with
a new paper towel. If necessary, use a brush for nails.
</P>
<P>
   Hand sanitizers can provide an extra measure of protection,
Andrews said, but they aren't necessary if proper hand-washing
techniques are followed. They work best on clean hands, anyway, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A has responded to several questions about Air Force One.
My question: Is there also a Marine One?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. If the president is, for example, aboard a Marine Corps
helicopter flying between the White House grounds and Andrews Air
Force Base in Maryland, it goes by that designation. If it's a Navy
or Army craft, it would be Navy One or Army One. And by definition,
Air Force One has to be an Air Force aircraft and not, say, a
commercial airliner.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently read that Lee Iacocca was going to market electric
bicycles. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The E-Bike is being manufactured by Los Angeles-based EV
Global Motors. Iacocca, former chairman of Chrysler Corp.,
describes his Light Electric Vehicles as ``an all-new breed,'' the
first of their kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The E-Bike has a sealed battery unit and electric hub motor,
with a thumb throttle allowing the rider to control its speed. It
operates in three modes: power only, letting the hub motor do all
the work; rider power, in which the motor is disengaged and the
rider pedals just like on a traditional bicycle; and combination,
which allows the battery power to supplement the rider's effort,
such as on hills or to maintain cruising speed.
</P>
<P>
   The bike will be available in three versions, standard
(manufacturer's suggested retail price, $995), ``comfort'' ($1,145)
and ``touring'' ($1,295). Top speed is said to be 15 mph; cruising
range is 20 miles. A spokeswoman for EV Global Motors told Q&AMP;A that
the bikes will be available for sale in April. They will be sold
through automobile dealers, but they haven't yet been finalized.
Information: on the Internet, http://www.evglobal.com, or toll-free
at 1-800-871-4545.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Robert Shaw, after his death, won a Grammy for the best
choral performance of the year. Can you list his other Grammys?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maestro Shaw won 16 in all, said Meredith Harris, Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra spokeswoman. Before joining the ASO, he had won
these four: 1961, Bach, B-Minor Mass; 1964, Britten, ``Ceremony of
Carols''; 1965, Stravinsky, ``Symphony of Psalms'' and Poulenc,
``Gloria''; and 1967, Handel, ``Messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ASO, these were the winners (some recordings received
two Grammys): 1986, Berlioz, ``Requiem'' (classical album and
choral performance); 1986, Faure, Suite from ``Pelleas and
Melisandre'' (orchestral); 1988, Hindemith, ``When Lilacs Last in
the Dooryard Bloom'd'' (choral); 1989, Verdi, ``Requiem,''/Opera
Choruses (classical album, choral performance); 1989, Rorem,
``String Symphony/Sunday Morning/Eagles'' (orchestral); 1990,
Britten, ``War Requiem'' (choral); 1991, Walton, ``Belshazzar's
Feast'' and Bernstein's ``Chichester Psalms'' and ``Missa brevis''
(choral); 1998, Adams, ``Harmonium'' and Rachmaninov, ``The Bells''
(choral); 1999, Barber, ``Prayers of Kierkegaard,'' Vaughan
Williams, ``Dona Nobis Pacem,'' and Bartok, ``Cantata Profana''
(choral performance and classical album).
</P>
<P>
   Q: The NCAA Final Four basketball championship tournament will
be played in Indianapolis in 2000. How can I apply for tickets?
Also, can you list other Final Four sites after that?
</P>
<P>
   A: For information about tickets to the 2000 tournament, wait
until after March 30 and then call the NCAA's headquarters in
Overland Park, Kan., at 913-339-1906, to request an application.
Or, toward the end of March, check the NCAA's Web site,
http://www.ncaachampionships.com, and register there to have an
application sent to you. Other Final Four cities have been selected
through 2007: 2001, Minneapolis; 2002, Atlanta; 2003, New Orleans;
2004, San Antonio; 2005, St. Louis; 2006, Indianapolis again; and
2007, Atlanta again. This year's finals are being played in St.
Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A travel publication says Israel and the Occupied Territories
are on the State Department's advisory list for American travelers.
Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The latest State Department advisory, dated Feb. 17, says
this: Although they have not been targeted for attack, U.S.
citizens have been injured or killed in past terrorist actions in
Israel, Jerusalem, the West Bank, and Gaza. The most recent attacks
have been in highly frequented shopping and pedestrian areas, and
on public buses. The U.S. Embassy and Consulate General have warned
their employees and American citizens to exercise caution when
utilizing public transportation, and when in the vicinity of bus
stops and other crowded areas. Travelers should remain aware of
their immediate surroundings, and should not touch any suspicious
object.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations by Palestinians and Israelis have led to
confrontations and clashes with the police and military, with some
turning deadly. Stone throwing and other violence in the West Bank
and Gaza can occur without warning and can escalate quickly.
Hebron, in particular, presents a significant risk of confrontation
and should be avoided. In view of the continued potential of
violence, the State Department advises all American citizens to
exercise extreme caution when trveling to these areas.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department posts information online at
http://travel.state.gov/travelwarnings.html, or you can call
202-647-5225.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
