 &HT;    Good Stuff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One good pepper
</P>
<P>
   Foodies who read the New York Times or magazines such as Gourmet
and Saveur have heard of Piquilla Peppers, the sweet, slightly
piquant beak-shaped peppers from the Spanish Pyrenees. Given that
trendy chefs are so eager to feature them, it's surprising to learn
that the fire-roasted pimientos are a canned product. They're
available at Dorothy Lane Market stores ($8.99 for an 8-ounce jar).
Stuff them, saute them or serve them as is as an appetizer, maybe
with a few slices of Spanish Manchego cheese and a chunk of bread.
</P>
<P>
   One good question
</P>
<P>
   Can food be flambeed in a nonstick pan? The answer is no, not
using conventional nonstick pans. Many manufacturers of nonstick
pans use plastic-based coatings that could burn off if subjected to
a direct flame as lighting brandy or a sauce . That's why cookware
directions warn against placing such pans under the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Artichokes rebound from early freeze
</P>
<P>
   Remember that December freeze that nipped produce production in
California? Well, artichokes were literally nipped in the bud, but
such farm catastrophes are temporary.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, winter-kissed _ frosted _ artichokes were all that
were available, but the plants shook off the chill and artichokes
are back in the supermarket this month. The harvest is good, if not
great, and supplies should last through May.
</P>
<P>
   For more recipes, log onto our online partner, Active Dayton, at
www.activedayton.com
</P>
<P>
   Story filed by The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
