<HEADER>
A4739 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PANKO11-COX     03-10 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PANKO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panko adds punch with its crunch
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As ethnic ingredients go mainstream in American
supermarkets, cooks no longer have to seek out small specialty
markets for basic supplies. Ingredients ranging from Thai coconut
milk to Japanese soba noodles are readily available in
``international'' sections of the superstores.
</P>
<P>
   Even panko.
</P>
<P>
   What's panko? Well, any '90s chef worth his toque can tell you
about panko.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing more than Japanese bread crumbs _ and the secret to
a crisp, crunchy exterior on fried foods.
</P>
<P>
   While Japanese chefs traditionally use panko to bread foods such
as pork cutlets ( tonkatsu ), imaginative Americans have extended
the use to the list of all the recipes where crumbs are used, from
baked fish and pan-fried crab cakes to familiar casseroles.
</P>
<P>
   What's different about panko is visible when you pick up a bag.
These are untoasted and coarse, more accurately described as bread
flakes than bread crumbs. The result, quite simply, is more crunch.
</P>
<P>
   In ethnic markets such as Koyama Shoten, 5256 N. Dixie Drive,
Harrison Twp., panko is sold in an 8.8-ounce bag labeled ``bread
flakes'' for $1.79. The Dynasty brand panko is available in
3.5-ounce boxes for about $1.60 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us don't deep-fry food, but the coarse crumbs come in
handy as a topping for baked fish or in pan-fried fillets.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is a variation of one of my family favorites for
cooking walleye.
</P>
<P>
   CRISPY WALLEYE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 to 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   dash of cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1 cup panko
</P>
<P>
   peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pounds thick fish fillets such as walleye
</P>
<P>
   In a shallow plate such as a pie tin, beat the eggs with a fork.
Add salt, pepper and cayenne, then mix.
</P>
<P>
   Place the panko crumbs on waxed paper or foil and spread out.
</P>
<P>
   Pour oil in a large skillet to a depth of inch and heat over
medium high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Using tongs, turn the fish in the beaten eggs. Let excess drip
off, then roll in the crumbs and place in the hot skillet. Cook
until brown on both sides, turning only once. Fillets inch thick
will be done in 5 minutes. Drain on paper towels and serve on a
warm platter.
</P>
<P>
   Fish fillets at least inch thick are best.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
