<HEADER>
A4746 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-KENSETH11-COX     03-10 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-KENSETH11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Busch's Kenseth rising fa
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most drivers get pretty irritated when NASCAR starts
tinkering with their cars.
</P>
<P>
   But Busch series driver Matt Kenseth probably would like NASCAR
to get down to some serious changes _ like installing a
compact-disc player in his yellow-and-black No. 17 Chevy Monte
Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, who turned 27 Tuesday, is an avid music fan. But it's
not that same longtime love affair between NASCAR drivers and honky
tonk. No, Kenseth likes his music to sound like his race car _ loud
and fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy a lot of types of music,'' Kenseth said. ``Metallica
is probably my favorite band, but I like a lot of the new
alternative stuff, too. I like a lot of the new stuff that's come
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth is one of several drivers on the Busch circuit who are
changing NASCAR's dial from country. And he's one of the young ones
that probably will lead Winston Cup racing into the next century,
along with multi-generation drivers Dale Earnhardt Jr., Glenn Allen
Jr. and Adam Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth enters Saturday's Yellow Freight 300 Busch race at
Atlanta Motor Speedway as one of the circuit's hottest drivers.
Dating back to July's DieHard 250 at Milwaukee, Kenseth has 14
top-10 finishes in the past 18 races, including 11 top fives and
one victory.
</P>
<P>
   Until he finished 30th in last week's Sam's Town 300 at Las
Vegas, Kenseth had four top-five finishes in a row. He was running
in the middle of the pack in that race, which was dominated by
Winston Cup regulars, until he lost a lug nut on a wheel and was
called back to the pits. Kenseth trails Randy LaJoie by 55 points
in the Busch standings.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth made the jump to the Busch Series in April 1997 after
being hired by longtime friend Robbie Reiser, a native of Allenton,
Wis., who raced against Kenseth on numerous occasions. Reiser spent
a few seasons driving in the Busch Series, but by 1996 he had
switched to ownership. When Reiser's driver was injured early in
the '97 Busch season, Kenseth was the first driver he called.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to race Late Model cars together in Wisconsin,''
Reiser said. ``In 1993, I won four championships, and Matt was
second or third in all of them. When I went to the Busch Series, I
was the driver and trying to do everything else _ ownership, crew
chief, everything. When I decided to move over to only the
ownership side, I chose Matt because he's good and he's young.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth competed in 21 Busch Series races for Reiser during the
'97 season, grabbing two third-place finishes. During his first
full season on the Busch circuit in '98, Kenseth captured his first
victory at Dover Downs International Speedway in Delaware in only
the second race. Kenseth also had the most top fives and 10s in the
Busch Series last year, finishing only 48 points behind close
friend and series winner Earnhardt Jr. in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   That was a long way from his obscure beginning in racing. When
Kenseth was 13, his father bought a stock car. His father drove it
for three years while Kenseth maintained and repaired it. Three
years later, his father turned over the driving duties.
</P>
<P>
   In just his third race in 1988, Kenseth, then only a junior in
high school, won his first feature event. Two weeks later, he got
another victory. By age 19, Kenseth had moved up to the
ultra-competitive Wisconsin Late Model division, battling the likes
of Dick Trickle, Ted Musgrave and Rich Bickle, all of whom are
racing in the Winston Cup Series this season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Kenseth became the youngest driver to win a feature
event in the ARTGO racing series, winning at LaCrosse Fairgrounds
in Wisconsin. That record had been held by Winston Cup star Mark
Martin. Kenseth still owns the record of 12 feature wins in the
Late Model division at Madison International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth and Reiser plan on jumping to the Winston Cup circuit
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the direction everybody would like to go in,'' Reiser
said. ``We'd like to go to Winston Cup and keep this team
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
