<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-MODELS11-COX     03-10 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-MODELS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where do old models go? Back to work
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dayle Haddon blames the coyote.
</P>
<P>
   The story goes like this: Aging former model lives in Paris,
making movies. Husband dies. Seeking a change of scenery and the
means to raise her daughter, she moves to California, where she
learns her European acting means squat.
</P>
<P>
   Too old for modeling (so they said), she takes a job as a
receptionist in a tiny ad agency, making coffee and answering
phones. While going over reports, she discovers that the coyote _
the coyote _ in one photo shoot is making more than she earns in a
month.
</P>
<P>
   That's it, she decides. Grabs Rolodex. Visits cosmetics
companies. Tries to point out the potential of the aging Baby
Boomer market. Doors slam. Keeps trying.
</P>
<P>
   Starts a modeling agency for older models, including herself.
Gets picked by Clairol as a spokesperson. Then Estee Lauder. Then
L'Oreal.
</P>
<P>
   Then she writes a book.
</P>
<P>
   Ageless Beauty: A Woman's Guide to Lifelong Beauty and
Well-Being.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told when I was 38 that my life was over,'' Haddon says.
</P>
<P>
   She's 50 now. Recently, Vogue magazine reunited the top models
of the 1970s for a photo shoot by Annie Leibovitz. Lauren Hutton
was there, Isabella Rossellini, Iman, Christie Brinkley. . . and
Haddon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we all looked more beautiful than in our heyday,''
Haddon says.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do they airbrush your photos, or do you ask them not to?
</P>
<P>
   A. I can't do much about it, but I ask them. I don't like to
airbrush too much.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you think about plastic surgery?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think that's an individual choice. I don't think there's
anything wrong with it. It's like makeup or a great dress _ if you
don't feel great about who you are . . . At this stage, you've got
to develop your inner life.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you had plastic surgery?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. I don't know if I would do it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your morning routine?
</P>
<P>
   A. The moment I wake up, I like to stretch. Then I meditate. I
shower, drink coffee and read the paper. I like to watch the sun.
Then I have a mini-trampoline _ $49.95 _ and I turn on music and I
jump. Or I take a very early morning walk. It helps you in
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How much time does all of this take?
</P>
<P>
   A. As much time as I can. I'm always late (laughs). I like to
have a half-hour that's mine. And I organize my outfit the night
before.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about makeup?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm very big into cleaning and moisturizing. And I make sure
to put sunblock on my hands, too. (She suggests Neutrogena's
Sensitive Skin SPF 17.)
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are some of the mistakes older women make, beauty-wise?
</P>
<P>
   A. Some think the older you get, the more makeup you put on. And
applying blush in stripes. We don't blush in stripes! And hair
coloring _ going too dark. That kabuki look, jet black.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you color your hair?
</P>
<P>
   A. I definitely color, yeah. My hair was almost blue-black. You
can't keep that up. (She uses Clairol for her roots between visits
to the salon.)
</P>
<P>
   Q. Any exercise advice?
</P>
<P>
   A. Exercise! I use (resistance bands) while washing dishes, I do
squats while vacuuming. I do side bends while brushing my teeth.
When I'm with friends, we take a walk instead of getting a big ol'
danish.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about people a generation older than 50, in their 70s
and 80s?
</P>
<P>
   A. Go walking. Do mini-weights. I keep weights by the TV and use
them while I watch.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What happens to all the other models who get old?
</P>
<P>
   A. They get sent to a farm far away (laughs). They kind of
disappear into the sunset. They either marry, or marry very well,
or get into other parts of the beauty business or do other things.
I call myself a dinosaur in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Q. During the Vogue photo shoot, was everyone checking each
other out, thinking, ``Look at what's happened to her!''
</P>
<P>
   A. No! I think women are more beautiful when they're older.
There's more freedom. A merging of who they are and what they look
like. How you've lived shows up after a certain age in your face.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does your face say?
</P>
<P>
   A. That's up to others to say. Behind it, I feel great.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
