<HEADER>
A4750 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRUISES11-COX     03-10 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to pick the cruise that's right for you
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I have cruised on a lot of ships.
</P>
<P>
   I've taken enormous mega-ships and small vessels _ the humongous
Carnival Destiny and the cozy little OceanBreeze.
</P>
<P>
   I've sailed on clipper ships (Windjammer's Polynesia _ renamed
the Polynausea on my voyage) and glided along on European river
boats (KD Cruises' Austria).
</P>
<P>
   I've taken legendary, and expensive, ships and those less
storied, and less expensive _ the Queen Elizabeth 2 and Carnival's
Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   I've been on family ships such as the Disney Magic and those
that tend to attract sophisticated adults like Windstar's Wind
Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mention this to impress you, but to tell you firsthand
that there are huge differences between cruise lines and ships.
</P>
<P>
   Your choice will determine whether you have a wonderful or
disappointing cruise vacation.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen a lot of contented cruisers and many unhappy, and even
irate, passengers.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen seniors trapped on ships filled with late-night, and
loud, young partiers, and I've seen a pair of 20-something
honeymooners marooned on a ship filled with retirees.
</P>
<P>
   I've run across first-time cruisers with movie visions of brass
portholes and polished teak stuck on new mega-ships that have all
the shipboard atmosphere of a Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   And I've seen passengers hoping for the neon and glitz of new
ships stranded on old vessels with as much glamour as a freighter.
</P>
<P>
   Which ship is for you? With more than 24 cruise lines and more
than 120 ships serving North America, the choices are overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   But never fear.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in fact, easy to choose the right ship. We will help
guide you to the right ship. Read on.
</P>
<P>
   Want a dream boat? ask lots of questions
</P>
<P>
   How do you choose a ship?
</P>
<P>
   There are expensive ships and ships known for good value; ships
legendary for their cuisine and others known for their
Broadway-caliber entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips for choosing your dream boat.
</P>
<P>
   Write down your priorities for a great cruise _ gourmet food,
entertainment, luxury, low cost, mostly adults, mostly families,
etc. And most important _ what ports do you want to see? Want a
no-smoking cruise? You'll want to consider Carnival's new Paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Go to a bookstore and buy a guidebook, preferably one that has
non-biased reviews of cruise lines and ships. One good bet is
Frommer's '99 Caribbean Cruises and Ports of Call (Macmillan Co.;
$19.95). Some people hesitate to spend the money on a guidebook,
but it could save them from landing on the wrong ship. Cabins,
public areas, service and food are rated for each ship.
</P>
<P>
   Visit a cruise-only travel agency. Cruises are all they do and
they should be able to guide you to the perfect ship.
</P>
<P>
   Tell the agent exactly what you are looking for. Agents get
frustrated when people come in and want to take a cruise but have
no idea what they want. And don't expect to take the QE2 for
bargain-basement prices.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a lot of questions and take home brochures. What is a
certain ship known for? Food? Entertainment? Maybe your top
priority is good value and you don't need a fancy room or a spa. On
the other hand, if it's your 50th anniversary (and the kids are
buying), you might want a luxury cruise. If you're 25 and looking
for late-night fun, don't be shy about saying it. Do you want a
casual ship or an elegant atmosphere that warrants bringing along a
tuxedo?
</P>
<P>
   Find out the age of the ship. Some people love the old ships
that have teak decks and brass portholes. Cruises on the older
ships are usually cheaper. Other people like the new, modern ships,
which look more like floating hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the brochures carefully. They offer a lot of clues. Are
there families in the photos or retirees? Look at the public areas,
decks and rooms. There shouldn't be many surprises when you board
the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Ask friends about their favorite ships. But listen closely.
Things they like may not be important to you.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never been on a cruise, try a weekend cruise to the
Bahamas to test the waters. If you don't like it, you won't have
invested that much time and money in it. A cruise isn't for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Think creatively. How about a riverboat on the Mississippi
River? Or a cruise around Hawaii?
</P>
<P>
   You can rest easy in the right cabin
</P>
<P>
   There can be huge differences between cabins even on the same
ship. Here are some tips to make sure you get the right one.
</P>
<P>
   Look closely at the photos of cabins in the cruise line
brochures. What do the rooms in each category look like? Would you
be happy on that narrow, single bed? Does it look like you could
stand in the middle of the cabin and touch both walls with
outstretched arms? Would that bother you? It might not if you plan
only to sleep there.
</P>
<P>
   If a double bed is important, ask for it. Or else, you and your
mate will be spending your cruise sleeping in twin beds like Desi
and Lucy.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your travel agent a lot of questions. Does the room in your
price range have double beds or singles or bunks? Is your outside
cabin facing a deck so that you have to keep your drapes closed for
privacy? Are the windows partially obstructed by lifeboats? Is
there a tub or just a shower? Is there a minibar? (This might be
important if you have children or need to keep medicines cold).
</P>
<P>
   Ask for a cabin located midship. There's less movement and less
chance of seasickness.
</P>
<P>
   Inexpensive lower decks also have much less movement than top
deck suites.
</P>
<P>
   Is it an outside or inside cabin? In other words, does the cabin
have a window? A windowless room can seem like a cell, especially
if there's bad weather and you end up spending lots of time in your
room. One of the joys of traveling by ship is watching the scenery
and going to sleep with reflections of moonlight on the water. A
few ships, such as the Clipper Cruise Line ships, have all outside
cabins. But on most ships you have to pay more for a window. The
price difference usually is not that much.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about upgrades. Are you a repeat customer? Is it an
anniversary or honeymoon? Your agent may be able to get you an
upgrade, especially if the ship isn't full.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be smooth sailing if you shop for deals
</P>
<P>
   There are several ways to get inexpensive fares and cabin
upgrades without paying extra. These aren't sure-fire methods, but
you might as well give them a try.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the best way to save money is to travel with friends and
family. The magic number to qualify for a ``group rate'' is usually
eight cabins, and the savings and upgrades are substantial. Have
that family reunion at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Tell your cruise-only travel agent if you are on a honeymoon,
celebrating a big anniversary or if you have traveled with the
cruise line before. Cruise lines often give cabin upgrades to
honeymooners and loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise lines usually offer big savings on reservations made more
than six months in advance. But buy trip cancellation insurance in
case your plans change or someone gets sick.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting until the last minute to make reservations is a good way
to get better cabins at lower prices. Of course, you're risking not
getting on the ship at all if it is sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your travel agent about ``low season'' for cruises in
certain parts of the world. Make travel plans when rates are lower.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about ``repositioning cruises.'' That's when ships are moved
from one part of the world to another, such as from the Caribbean
to Europe or from the Caribbean to Alaska. These cruises often are
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Think about exotic locales. Mediterranean cruises are
exceptional deals especially when you consider how much it would
cost to fly to the cities you would visit by ship. And often, the
cruise lines' charter overseas flights are far better than fares
you could get on your own.
</P>
<P>
   How to pack for a cruise
</P>
<P>
   Now's the time to be your most glamorous self. How often do you
get to wear an ankle-length gown or tux? Don't worry about packing
light, but keep in mind that most shipboard closets are small.
</P>
<P>
   Pack a couple of things for warmth, even on Caribbean cruises.
Public areas often are cold and the decks can get nippy at night.
In Alaska, you can always identify cruise ship passengers huddled
in their thin windbreakers. That's what the cruise lines tell them
to pack and they are all freezing in Alaska's cool summer
temperatures. When going to Alaska, pack a fleece jacket to wear
under a windbreaker. This also applies to European cruises,
especially in the spring and fall.
</P>
<P>
   Comfortable rubber-soled shoes, hats with wide brims, suntan
lotion, sunglasses, mosquito repellent, Band-Aids.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your travel agent if there's a costume party or talent
contest. This may sound a little dopey, but once you're on the ship
you'll wish you had brought that Madonna-esque leather bra so you
could impress your new friends with your own version of Like a
Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Blackerby writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
