A4751 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROMANTIC-EUROPE11-COX     03-10 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMANTIC-EUROPE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Europe's two most romantic cities
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I'm going to tell you my picks for the
two most romantic cities in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But before I do that, allow me to give those of you
contemplating a honeymoon a few pieces of advice:
</P>
<P>
   First, stay put! In one place in Europe, that is. Don't go
driving all over the continent in an effort to see everything.
You'll just get tired and cranky.
</P>
<P>
   Stay in one city, and it will become ``your'' city, the one that
will be foremost in your photo album.
</P>
<P>
   Second: Go in spring or fall, even winter, but not summer.
Europe is too crowded, hot and expensive in summer, and this tends
to make people tired and cranky.
</P>
<P>
   And, I thought of a third point: Don't worry about spending
money. Budget enough for the trip so that you're not fretting about
every franc you're spending on taxis and food. The wedding trip is
not the time to worry about money _ there's plenty of time for that
later in the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   And my No. 1 personal favorite city for romance?
</P>
<P>
   Venice.
</P>
<P>
   When the moon hits your eye like a big pizza pie, especially on
a gondola ride along the 1,000-year-old city's many canals,
serenaded by a gondolier _now, that's amore. You'll both be sighing
as you glide under the Bridge of Sighs.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also be awed by the 11th-century Basilica with its
Moorish domes and the magnificent Ducal Palace with the frescoed
ceilings decorated with solid gold.
</P>
<P>
   You can sip cappuccino in St. Mark's Square while admiring the
Byzantine buildings with graceful arches that still frame the
square Napoleon called ``the most beautiful salon in the world.''
This is the city that inspired Lord Byron and Robert and Mrs.
Browning.
</P>
<P>
   There's great shopping _ you new husbands can buy that Venetian
cameo that has a remarkable resemblance to your beloved.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay? If you've saved a bundle for this trip, you
should go straight to the Hotel Gritti Palace. Kings and queens,
prime ministers and presidents have slept in the ultra-luxurious,
antique-filled rooms of the hotel, a 16th-century palace
overlooking the Grand Canal. It's expensive _ rates start at about
$557. For reservations, call (800) 325-3589. Ask about package
rates and specials.
</P>
<P>
   The Albergo San Marco is in a medieval building only 100 feet
from St. Mark's Square and next to a quiet canal. Rooms start at
about $150 a night and have modern baths, phones and CNN. The rooms
vary quite a bit so ask to see the room before you pay.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the Albergo Cavalletto &AMP; Doge Orseolo, which opened
in 1308 and is one of the oldest hotels in Italy. It's also only
100 feet from St. Mark's Square and faces a gondola dock. Double
rooms start at about $200. For reservations at both hotels, call
(800) 528-1234. Ask about specials.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that Paris is romantic. But I'll go ahead
and say it.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling along the Seine, hand-in-hand, and spending most of an
evening in an outdoor cafe is the best entertainment in town.
There's also the Louvre, Notre Dame, the Musee d'Orsey, and, of
course, the Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   You can stay at the Hotel d'Albe (call 011-331-46-34-09-70), a
medieval building that was once home to a princess. Rates start at
about $125 for two. It's in an excellent location in St. Michel on
the Left Bank just a block from the Seine. It has modern rooms and
baths, and is on a pedestrian street with lots of inexpensive
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The Marronniers Hotel (011-331-43-25-30-60) is about $140 (not
including breakfast), and is an atmospheric inn on Rue Jacob, a
cobblestone street on the Left Bank. If the room isn't important,
you might consider the St. Michel Hotel (011-33-1-43-26-98-70) on a
narrow cobblestone street a half-block from the Seine. The location
is excellent, but rooms have a faded '70s decor. Those with shower
and toilet are only $68 for two (in April). A room with bath and
toilet down the hall is about $45.
</P>
<P>
   Other romantic places in Europe: any of the Greek isles;
Florence, Italy; Cologne, Germany; Stockholm, Sweden; and any
smalltown in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, any place is great if you're in love.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Blackerby writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
