r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGH-TEA11-COX     03-10 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TEA11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tea partyers take sips of life in `Gilded Age'
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Mark Twain dubbed it ``The Gilded Age.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decades after the Civil War, industrial prosperity left
some Americans with too much money and a nagging sense of
inferiority.
</P>
<P>
   So they made Grand Tours of Europe, crinolined culture-vultures
on a raid. They built huge mansions in Newport, the Hamptons and
Palm Beach and called them ``cottages.''
</P>
<P>
   And they had tea parties.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, about 75 people about to bid farewell to the 20th
century paid homage to this 19th-century custom at the Flagler
Museum's first Gilded Age Tea.
</P>
<P>
   They nibbled cucumber sandwiches _ no crust on the bread, of
course. They chatted in reverent murmurs under the high ceiling of
the old dining hall. They showed the good breeding not to request
Sweet 'n' Low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretentious?'' said Joyce Schiller, a curator at Reynolda
House, the R.J. Reynolds mansion in Winston-Salem, N.C. ``I suppose
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Schiller prepared the party-goers with ``Reading Gilded
Leaves,'' a lecture on the manners and meaning of 19th-century tea
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was also a delightful ritual,'' she said, ``a gentility
we want to hold onto in this fast-food, fast-paced life.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Branyan of Lake Park, Fla. arrived at the tea in a white
lace dress she's held onto since 1905, when her mother made it for
her eighth-grade graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel elegant,'' she said, peering from under a
wide hat adorned with white roses, ``like I want to stand
straighter and act properly and be a lady. A lot of women don't
want to be ladies these days.''
</P>
<P>
   One striking difference between the Flagler Museum's recreation
and a real Gilded Age tea lay in the gender disparity.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, men and women took tea together.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Herbert Mueller of West Palm Beach was one of only
three or four men present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It beats happy hour,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hayes writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
