<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, March 10, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PARENT-TEACHER-STAB (Richmond, Calif.) _ A discussion over a
girl's classroom progress took a vicious turn when the child's
father, without warning, allegedly stabbed his daughter's
fourth-grade teacher in front of several horrified students,
including the suspect's daughter, and left the 43-year-old teacher
in serious condition with a stab wound to her right side. By RAY
DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-COSTS (San Francisco) _ Three years, three upgrades,
$250,000 and numerous glitches later, Michael King says he's almost
got his small business' Year 2000 problems licked. ``If you don't
have the money to address this problem, and you haven't started
working on it by now, for a lot of companies it may be too late,''
he said. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-FUTURE (San Francisco) _ Twin investor uprisings _ one an
open battle, the other an underground movement _ could affect the
financial future of Wired Digital, a pioneering Web company. By
MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROBOT-SURGERY (San Antonio) _ Before heading into surgery, Dr.
Morris Franklin grabs a black microphone set. It's not for music.
Rather, it's used to communicate with the Hermes surgical
assistant, a robot that performs surgical functions through voice
commands. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   HERBAL-TREATMENTS (San Antonio) _ With demand for herbal and
natural health products exploding, health officials say pharmacists
must help bridge the gap between conventional and alternative
medicines. Once found mainly in specialty health food stores,
alternative products now line the shelves of mainstream drug stores
and groceries. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-MATTERS (San Francisco) _ Q: I've been married four years.
For some reason I don't want sex. Everything was fine until I went
on the pill about one month before we got married. I noticed an
immediate lack of desire but hoped that it was due to the stress of
planning our wedding. But it never got better. A: Your situation
requires some detective work to sort out the possible cause(s) of
your decreased sexual desire. The areas to consider are: your
hormonal levels, your general health and your relationship. By
LOUANNE COLE WESTON, Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   TAUSCHER-DIVORCE (Martinez, Calif.) _ Rep. Ellen Tauscher,
D-Calif., has petitioned for divorce from her husband. Huge amounts
of money _ their assets are about $36 million, with a net worth of
nearly $18 million after subtracting debts _ are at stake,
according to the divorce case records. Stock in Bill Tauscher's
computer company makes up more than half of the assets. By ERIC
BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SKI-FOOD (Albany, N.Y.) _ Few outdoor activities offer easier
opportunities for intimacy than cross-country skiing or
snowshoeing. But if you haven't packed properly for this outing,
you will rue the day. Plenty of water and high-energy snacks are
absolutely essential for a memorable Nordic adventure. By DOUG
BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-DiMAGGIO-MEMORIAL (San Francisco) _ San Francisco
supervisors have begun batting around ideas about what to name
after the late Joe DiMaggio, and, for the most part, they want to
avoid a ``street'' fight that would soil his name. By GREGORY
LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ A good character witness _ in this
case a politician _ can make or break a court case. It helped
Donald Boyle, a lobbyist who was charged _ and acquitted _ of
drunken driving. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
