<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER HOTLIST: ARCHAEOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stone Pages _ www.stonepages.com/dmeozzi/HomEng.html
</P>
<P>
   Stonehenge is just the beginning. England and much of Europe is
dotted with stone monuments, the real purpose of which remain a
mystery today. Learn about the megaliths and the efforts being made
to understand their creation. Shown is the Drombeg stone circle in
County Cork, Ireland. The main stone is aligned with the winter
solitial sunset, with good but not precise alignment, the site
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Collapse: Why Do Civilizations Fall? _
www.learner.org/exhibits/collapse/
</P>
<P>
   Civilizations are like gravity _ what goes up eventually comes
tumbling down. This online exhibit looks at four different ancient
civilization and explores why they eventually fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeological Sites _
lrs.ed.uiuc.edu/students/b-sklar/sites.html
</P>
<P>
   Africa is considered the cradle of homo sapiens, our species.
This simple but fascinating site looks at some of the most
important archaeological sites in that continent in a search for
the roots of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeology on the Net _ www.serve.com/archaeology/
</P>
<P>
   Because the Internet began under the aegis of science, there's
naturally plenty to find about archaeology on the Web. This
exhaustive site tracks archaeology online, sorted both
geographically and by topic.
</P>
<P>
   Pyramids: The Inside Story _ www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/pyramid/
</P>
<P>
   This site, a companion to an episode of PBS' Nova, includes a
Quicktime tour of a pyramid. You can also learn about the work of a
team of archaeologists uncovering a bakery that was built to feed
pyramid workers.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeology Magazine _ www.he.net/archaeol/
</P>
<P>
   Archaeology Magazine's online edition includes feature stories
that will interest both the layman and the professional. Recent
pieces include a story about a mummy found in a South American
pyramid and a dive by Australian archaeologists to an 18th-century
sunken ship.
</P>
<P>
   World Wide Ancient Egypt _ www.geocities.com/amenhotep/wwae/
</P>
<P>
   Ancient Egypt has fascinated both professional and amateur
archaeologists for centuries. Come here for links all over the Web
to sites devoted to ancient Egyptology.
</P>
<P>
   The Chauvet Cave _
www.culture.fr/culture/arcnat/chauvet/en/gvpda-d.htm
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the government of France announced an astonishing find
_ a cave filled with remarkable Stone Age paintings that apparently
had been untouched for thousands of years. Read about the find and
see photographs of the artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Stonehenge _ www.intel.com/cpc/explore/stonehenge/
</P>
<P>
   First, download the Viscape browser plug-in software for Windows
95/98, then use it to explore an accurately rendered 3-D model of
the enigmatic Stonehenge.
</P>
<P>
   Repatriation and Reburial Information _
www.uiowa.edu/anthro/reburial/repat.htm
</P>
<P>
   The idea that people would be digging up the artifacts and bones
belonging to ancient people is not always a popular one. This site
explores the issues involving indigenous peoples' efforts to have
their ancestors bones returned to the earth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
