<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, March 11, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Being snowbound has its
advantages. I have, for instance, recently learned everything I
could ever want to know about Stonewall Jackson and Grand Funk
Railroad. Everything and more. How many times have you longed for
some time to sit down, relax and converse with your spouse? During
the recent inclemencies, Jim and I have had the opportunity to do
just that. Be careful what you pray for. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ In the 1970s, my wife, Ruth, and I were
standing on the veranda of a wonderful old hotel at Cooperstown,
N.Y. Joe DiMaggio was across the veranda, chatting with friends.
``I'm going to say hello to him,'' Ruth said. I wouldn't have
dared. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Deregulation of public education: Is that
what we're talking about with these school vouchers? If so, hold
the phone. I happen to have an opinion about public education. My
opinion is that no other institution has contributed more to
democracy in America. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin filmmaker Steve Mims is
auctioning off his 1980 Honda Civic on the Internet to help pay for
the low budget film he's about to introduce at the South by
Southwest Film Festival. ``People should know that the air
conditioner blows cold,'' said Steve, who also owns a 10-year-old
Honda. Steve is borrowing $20,000 to pay for the final print of his
film, ``The Perfect Specimen.'' To help repay the loan, he's
selling the older car, which is not a perfect specimen. Steve says
State Farm Insurance has declared the '80 Civic totalled twice,
after two different wrecks. Something tells me Steve isn't going to
get quite $20,000 for this car. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's get this
straight: The day President Clinton apologized to the nation but
not to Monica Lewinsky, the poor thing felt dirty and used. Monica,
who considered herself the president's ``sexual soulmate,'' is
sorry for what happened. Oh, and by the way, she didn't intend to
cause the president public embarrassment. She was fully prepared to
lie in the Paula Jones investigation. That would be ``like putting
on a team jersey.'' Really? To play offense, defense or both? I
gleaned these meager details from the pre- and post-hype of Barbara
Walters' tour through the sewers of Monica's mind last week on
20/20. (Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
