recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BISCUITS _ Want to impress guests? Cheap and fast, a homemade
biscuit elevates any meal from breakfast to dinner. So you've never
made biscuits from scratch before. Don't tell your grandmother, but
forget that messy technique of cutting in the butter or shortening
into the flour. Not necessary. The easy secret to this melt- in-
your mouth favorite is cream. Pour and stir. Then prop your feet up
and listen to your favorite CD while they bake. Same technique
works for Irish soda bread or scones. (Crider, Austin
American-Statesman). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   IRISHSTEW _ Guiness Irish Stew takes to a Crockpot. (Austin
American-Statesman). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-PANKO _ The Japanese panko adds punch to fried foods with
its crunch. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GOODSTUFF _ Food briefs. (Heller, Dayton Daily News). WITH
PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TEA _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ How to serve tea in the style of
the gilded age, a Flagler Museum presentation. (Hayes, West Palm
Beach) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-FANS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Some people can't figure
out what they'll be doing next week, much less in two months. Not
Joseph Helmsorig. For the past year, May 21 has been a sacred date.
That's when the new Star Wars movie, Episode I: The Phantom Menace,
debuts in theaters. And the day before, the 29-year-old emergency
medical technician from Sunrise, Fla. will don a homemade costume
and transform himself into Boba Fett, an obscure character who had
all of six lines of dialogue in the three previous films. Then
he'll trudge down to the local theater _ in his $1,100 get-up _ and
camp out overnight so he can party with hundreds of others who have
waited since 1983 for a fresh Star Wars movie. And after seeing
Phantom the first time, he plans to go to as many showings as he
can get into that day. Yes, Helmsorig is truly devoted. ``My
fascination with Star Wars knows no boundaries,'' he says, almost
solemnly. He has plenty of company in his galaxy of adoration. If
Internet traffic is any indication, an untold legion is lurking in
a parallel universe waiting for the big day. (Houck, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-WEBSITES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Thousands of
unofficial fan Web sites are up and running, in anticipation of
Episode I: The Phantom Menace. We list a few of the main sites that
will help even the biggest Star Wars novice catch up to diehard
fans. (Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CNN-HUNTERGAULT _ Charlayne Hunter-Gault is about to become
CNN's point person in Africa as the South Africa bureau chief. The
former civil rights activist who integrated the University of
Georgia was hired by CNN away from PBS's MacNeil NewsHour. Talking
to her about TV coverage of Africa, CNN, her roots to Georgia.
(Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-COLUMN _ Main video review. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-NEW _ New releases: ``What Dreams May Come'' (C-); ``Butch
Camp'' (D-); ``Frank and Ollie'' (B). (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT _ Spotlight on Annabella Sciorra (``What Dreams
May Come''). (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-RENTALS _ Top rentals, top sales. Upcoming: next Tuesday _
``The Waterboy,'' ``Living Out Loud,'' ``Bulworth,'' ``One True
Thing,'' ``Flamenco,'' ``Polish Wedding.'' Plus The Video
Collector. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
