 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Games play into PC choices 
By Omar L. Gallaga  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Intel Corp. and AMD Inc. made a big to-do last
week when they introduced faster, more powerful processors _ the
Pentium III and K6-3.
</P>
<P>
   And for what? To run Microsoft Word or complex personal finance
programs? For many, the most important reason of all is that these
processors will help you dominate death matches in ``Quake II.''
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like a trivial thing, basing the purchase of a new
computer or upgrade on a single game, but as it has always been in
the history of computers, games are a primary motivator for
computer evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Games, in short, are a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, it's often been the simplistic _ games such as
``Tetris'' and ``Solitaire'' glued millions to desktops. But
increasingly, it's violent first-person shooters such as ``Quake
II,'' ``Unreal'' and ``Half-Life'' that are upping the ante on how
much computing power is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   To fully take advantage of a game such as ``Unreal'', you need a
fast processor, plenty of memory, a big enough hard drive to hold
the software, a 3D sound card that lets you hear the position of
your enemies and a speedy Internet connection to battle online.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all together, and you have a very powerful computer
system that, like the oversized, cartoonish weapons in ``Unreal,''
amount to computational overkill. In few other applications except
games do you need that kind of power. Who needs a $150 graphics
accelerator card to write a letter in Microsoft Word or to do a
Yahoo! search in Netscape Communicator?
</P>
<P>
   The computer demands of games are so great, in fact, that
magazines and Web sites that review computer systems regularly use
games such as ``Quake II'' ``Turok the Dinosaur Hunter'' and
``Descent: Freespace'' to benchmark systems _ the true test of a
computer's power is how many frames per second it can display a
3D-rendered character's head being blown off by a plasma cannon.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of people who planned to purchase a new computer for
the home in the next 12 months, 57 percent of respondents said they
would buy games for that computer.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that many people are using $1,500-$2,000 computer
systems as little more than game consoles is a bit confusing given
that a Sony PlayStation, which often offers better control in a
wide variety of games, sells for $129. And a coming generation of
consoles including Sega's Dreamcast and Sony's next PlayStation are
to offer processing, sound and graphics that will surpass PC
capabilities for less than $300.
</P>
<P>
   But high-end, resource-hogging games continue to be popular,
especially among early adopters and PC experts. The reason is that
PC games are playable over the Internet (Dreamcast will ship with a
modem, but so far console games have not made effective use of the
Net), they can be added to with downloaded patches and upgrades,
and they usually have rich graphics and sound.
</P>
<P>
   Gamers also like the demands these games place on their systems
_ nothing speaks more highly of a gamer's dedication than having
the fastest computer with the best graphic capabilities on which to
play.
</P>
<P>
   What console systems and PC games have shared is the ability to
create a demand for hardware based on a few popular titles. Sony
has had Lara Croft and the Tomb Raider Series, ``Resident Evil''
and ``Final Fantasy VII.'' Nintendo had ``Mario 64,'' ``Goldeneye:
007'' and ``The Legend of Zelda: Orinca in Time.'' And the PC has
had breakthrough games such as ``Quake,'' ``Unreal'' and ``Grim
Fandago.''
</P>
<P>
   While those console games have moved entire systems, the demands
of games for PCs have provoked gamers into buying powerful graphics
cards, better sound systems and faster processors.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon is not new _ Origin System's ``Wing Commander''
games in the early '90s enticed gamers into purchasing Sound
Blaster-compatible sound cards to hear the digital soundtrack and
speech incorporated into the game.
</P>
<P>
   But more than ever, computer games are becoming the primary
motivator for the introduction of faster, more powerful computer
systems. Until the Internet evolves as more people get higher
bandwidth connections in the home, the dimly lit, spectacularly
detailed walls and skies of ``Unreal'' and ``Half-Life'' will be
where computer users get the most out of their machines.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-08-99 1029EST &QL;
</P>
