 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
With cable modem, the thrill returns 
By Bill Husted  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Those of you who know me, either from reading this
column or from having breakfast with me at the Waffle House,
understand _ despite the fact that I've messed around with gadgets
for my entire adult life _ I am not a bold man when it comes to
adopting new technology.
</P>
<P>
   I've never, for instance, stuck a deposit in an ATM, because I'm
sure it'll get lost somehow. I use a bald-headed man named Marvin,
not a computer, to figure my taxes. And my checkbook stays
unbalanced just fine without Quicken. My computer is slow and
clunky compared to what most people have and want. I'm happy with
old tech that is dependable and has proven its worth.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you ought to listen when something new catches my
eye. If I like it, you probably wil, too.
</P>
<P>
   Do yourself a favor. As soon as they're available in your
neighborhood _ and if you have the money to spare _ get a cable
modem and use it to connect to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I did a week ago. It made a big difference, but
maybe not in the ways you'd expect. In fact, what I expected and
what I got were two different things.
</P>
<P>
   I'll tell you what I mean. I saw a cable modem as simply a way
to get Web pages to load faster and something that would let me
download new files quickly. Both those things turned out to be true
(I downloaded a new 15-megabyte copy of Netscape Navigator in the
time it took me to eat five cookies), and Web pages are fast now,
faster even than when I use the expensive T1 high-speed data line
at work.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, things that weren't practical before, like
downloading a new program just to see what it is like; looking at
video that appears as clear and stable as a TV signal (although
still in a tiny box on my screen); and listening to audio that is
of an almost high-fidelity quality, become possible.
</P>
<P>
   But something more important happened, too. I began treating the
Web the way I used to, way back in the beginning when it was new. I
was surfing again.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing used to be a big deal to a lot of us. We'd go to one Web
page, click on an interesting link, follow it, and then follow
another one. A person could literally go from beekeeping to Peru in
just a few minutes. A lot of what we found wasn't immediately
practical, but it was almost like getting a liberal arts education:
Some of the things I learned became important later on.
</P>
<P>
   It was very much like picking up a book out of boredom,
something you would have never read, and discovering something
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Then two things happened. The Web got useful _ something that I,
you too probably, use at work to find out boring stuff like the
gross national product of Mexico. So, instead of surfing, I'd head
right to the spot where the information was held. The second thing
that happened was that Web pages got big and complicated _ full of
video and sound _ and that meant they took forever to load at
analog modem speeds. So I hesitated before pressing a link just for
fun. Sometimes it took a couple of minutes for the page to build.
</P>
<P>
   Think of owning a cable modem as being data-rich. You have
enough bandwidth to squander some, to use it just for fun. And,
truthfully, with my old dial-up connection the Web wasn't much fun.
There were times when I could go to the kitchen to fix a sandwich
while I waited for a page to build.
</P>
<P>
   But now, thanks to my cable modem, I'm surfing again. And it's
just as much fun as it used to be. Get yourself a cable modem. The
surf is up.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
