 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
A site for headache sufferers 
By Mark Clothier  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Headache sufferers now have their own home on the Web,
http://www.headaches.org.
</P>
<P>
   It costs $20 to join the organization that sponsors the site,
the National Headache Foundation, based in Chicago. The membership
fee includes a headache relief video. The site also offers lots of
free information. A comprehensive guide to headaches lists
different types of headaches, such as tension, migraine, cluster
and hormone. The site offers tips on how to choose a headache
doctor and what to expect on your first visit to that doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was started in 1970 as a nonprofit organization
focused on three goals: to offer information to headache sufferers,
their families and the physicians who treat them; to promote
headache research into potential causes and possible treatments;
and to teach the public that headaches are serious disorders and
that sufferers need understanding and continuity of care.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in the organization includes a quarterly newsletter,
brochures about headache prevention, a list of physician members,
discounts on books, brochures and audio and video tapes, toll-free
access to the NHF office, breaking news developments, and
information about support groups near your home.
</P>
<P>
   NBA PLAYER LAUNCHES AMBITIOUS WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   Sports teams have had their own Web sites since the Internet
became popular. Now individual players are taking the cue.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio Spurs second-year power forward Tim Duncan has
launched http://www.slamduncan.com, known as The Official Tim
Duncan Website.
</P>
<P>
   The site lists a biography, stats and highlights. The bio
includes such must-have information as Duncan's shoe size (16),
what tattoos he wears, his favorite actor and what cars he drives
(a Yukon Denali and a Porsche).
</P>
<P>
   The Courtside page gives you the chance to e-mail Duncan, sign
his guest book, read about his charitable contributions and look at
the Spurs' 1999 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   For the true Duncan fan, the stats page lists Duncan's numbers
in the NBA as well as in his four seasons at Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the site will offer a public fan mail section
complete with Duncan's responses to e-mail and regular chat
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is apparently a movie and music lover. Ultimately, the
site will give visitors the chance to read his reviews of CDs and
movies.
</P>
<P>
   HERE'S HOW TO TREAT A CELL PHONE WITH RESPECT
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watched ``The X-Files'' last Sunday remembers Fox
Mulder waking up over and over to a series of annoying things, one
of which was a leaky water bed that shorted out his cell phone,
which was on the water-soaked rug. Mulder could have avoided a
shorted-out phone had he paid attention to the rules of cell phone
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at AirTouch, one of several cellular phone sellers on
the market, recently put out a list of cell phone tips, one which
was to keep your cell phone dry.
</P>
<P>
   Other tips include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Read your owner's manual.
</P>
<P>
   _ Treat a cell phone like other electronic devices and keep it
and all parts and accessories away from children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't keep your phone in hot areas. High temperatures can
shorten the life of electronic devices, damage batteries, and warp
or melt some plastics.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the same time, don't store your cell phone in cold areas.
As the phone warms, moisture forming inside can damage the circuit
boards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never try to open your cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't keep your cell phone in dusty, dirty areas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try not to drop, knock or shake your cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't use harsh chemicals or solvents to clean your phone. Use
a soft, cloth, lightly dampened with a soap-and-water solution.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider getting your phone an annual service check-up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
