<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4807 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-     03-10 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CENTERPIECE-CHIP09-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Intel's Pentium III more evolutionary than revolutionary 
By Bill Husted 
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ PCs with the new Pentium III chip from Intel are on
shelves now. These new machines are the fastest yet, reasonably
priced and _ based on early reports _ relatively bug-free.
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy one.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? If the chip is a good one, and it is, and if the price
is right, and it is, why not rush to the store and take one home?
</P>
<P>
   You'll be able to answer that question for yourself by the end
of this article.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to know about the Pentium III is the internal
workings of the chip _ its architecture _ isn't all that different
from the Pentium II. In fact, if you have a Pentium II machine, the
new chip is so similar to the old one, odds are good you can simply
remove the old chip and plug in a new Pentium III with no problems
at all. But don't do that, either.
</P>
<P>
   Keep reading.
</P>
<P>
   The real changes in this newest Pentium from Intel are in what
is called its instruction set. The instruction set is really more
like a computer program than a part of the chip. It consists of
computer code that instructs the chip on how to compute. Without
the instructions, it would be an expensive and useless piece of
silicon about the size of a matchbook.
</P>
<P>
   The new instruction set will eventually allow Pentium III chips
to handle video much better (since computer games are loaded with
video, games will run much faster). The instructions _ called
Katmai New Instructions _ also let the chip do a better job with
speech recognition, a technology rapidly becoming practical and
useful.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the first reason why there's no need to rush to the
store today: Only software specially written to take advantage of
the new instruction set will get a speed boost. Your old programs
won't profit from this instruction set.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only a few games take advantage of KNI (including
``Wargasm'' and ``Descent III''). As time goes on, that will
change. Video cards will be created that recognize the new
instructions, and Windows 2000 will have built-in support for KNI.
(Microsoft has said it will create a patch _ a tiny program
designed to improve an existing one _ that will let Windows 98 take
advantage of KNI.) Since Windows itself is a heavy user of graphics
and sound, the combination of the patch and the new chip should
make your PC run faster.
</P>
<P>
   MARK OF THE BEAST?
</P>
<P>
   When the Pentium III's specifications were first announced,
there was panic and protest among many computer enthusiasts.
Messages zipped through cyberspace as word got out that the new
chip has a built-in electronic serial number. Intel says the
purpose of the serial number _ which will identify the computer to
other computers on the Internet _ was to increase security. After
all, passwords and user names can be faked. But Intel said _ when
combined with the built-in serial number _ there would be less
chance of someone faking an electronic transaction or e-mail. But
for some computer folks, that serial number was the mark of the
beast. There was worry that the serial number would make it
impossible to have any privacy on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's reaction was to create a small program that can be
downloaded from Intel's Web site (http://
</P>
<P>
   www.intel.com) that gives users control over the serial number.
Those who fear the number can invade their privacy can turn off the
serial number, and those who buy into Intel's argument that the
serial number actually protects privacy and security can leave it
turned on.
</P>
<P>
   BUY TODAY, LOSE OUT TOMORROW
</P>
<P>
   You've already learned most of the speed is yet to come, as
software programs take advantage of the new instruction set.
Depending on what figures you see and whom you believe, the new
machine should run about 5 percent to 8 percent faster (not enough
of a change for most people to notice) with programs that do not
take advantage of the new instruction set.
</P>
<P>
   Software companies will gear up to support the KNI instructions.
But at least as important is the fact Intel has said it expects to
offer Pentium III chips by the end of the year with speeds as fast
as 1 gigahertz (a little more than twice as fast as the
450-megahertz speed of the current PIII chips).
</P>
<P>
   So, if you buy a Pentium III today, you may find yourself with a
high-tech antique.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you decide the faster Pentium IIIs aren't important,
waiting makes sense. New chips and king-of-the-hill computers
command a premium price. Prices for slower Pentium IIIs will take a
nose dive as 1-gigahertz class machines are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   If you'll settle for a Pentium II, take note of Intel's
announcement last week that it will drop the price for that chip by
15 percent to 20 percent. That doesn't mean Pentium II PCs will
make the same percentage drop, since there's more to a computer
than a single chip, but it adds momentum to price drops already
taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it is true with automobiles, prices vary widely. But
some of the new Pentium IIIs sell for $2,000 or a bit more at the
bottom end of the price range. That's a good introductory price.
And, some people (especially those who have graphics-intensive
tasks to perform at work and who are lucky enough to use programs
that do or soon will take advantage of the new instruction set)
will pay it gladly.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of us, the introduction of the Pentium III marks a
time when watching and waiting makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   FACTS ABOUT THE INTEL PENTIUM III
</P>
<P>
   _ A set of internal instructions will eventually make it a
better chip for games and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ A controversial built-in serial number makes transactions on
the Net more secure _ or invades your privacy (depending on whom
you believe).
</P>
<P>
   _ Initially, it will come in two speeds: 450 megahertz and 500
megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   _ Later versions (out by the end of the year) will be twice as
fast.
</P>
<P>
   _ Features in the chip should make new technologies such as
voice recognition work faster and better.
</P>
<P>
   _ Since the basic design of the chip has not changed from the
Pentium II, it can be used as a direct replacement in most Pentium
II machines.
</P>
<P>
   _ It is backward-compatible: All the programs that are running
on your current PC should work just fine on a new Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-08-99 1029EST &QL;
</P>
