<SLUG> BC-HERBAL-TREATMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHARMACISTS URGED TO BONE UP ON HERBAL PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE FOY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ With demand for herbal and natural health products
exploding, health officials say pharmacists must help bridge the
gap between conventional and alternative medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Once found mainly in specialty health food stores, alternative
products such as ginseng, kava kava, melatonin and shark cartilage
now line the shelves of mainstream drug stores and groceries.
</P>
<P>
   But the proliferation of the thousands of alternative treatments
has come with a price: consumer confusion over what works and what
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   That is where pharmacists come in, said Dr. Mary Hardy of Los
Angeles who is a specialist in integrative medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists have the opportunity to help consumers through the
maze of alternative therapies on the market, Hardy said Monday
before a panel of the American Pharmaceutical Association, which
held its annual meeting in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we don't yet have the confidence of the public
so that patients identify their pharmacists or physicians as a
major source of herbal information,'' Hardy said. ``And I think it
behooves us to get our knowledge base up, get our education up and
get the word out so that our patients feel comfortable approaching
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that 30 percent of Americans are using herbal
products on a regular basis, Hardy said. About half of them are
also using prescription or over-the-counter drugs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The herbs are drugs. They have drug-like effects,'' Hardy
said. ``We can expect that our patients are going to be
experiencing potential drug-herb interactions or maybe making
substitutions where it's not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a need for pharmacists who can help consumers make
educated choices regarding which alternative medicines to take and
whether such therapies might conflict with other medicines, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bombarded by false claims and misleading advertising about
natural therapies, many consumers are left scratching their heads,
said Amanda McQuade-Crawford, a California herbalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, the public is baffled,'' she said. ``There is so much
misinformation out there about herbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternative products _ including vitamins and nutrients, amino
acids and botanical supplements _ are considered dietary
supplements. That means they aren't being regulated as drugs by the
Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that many alternative therapies act as drugs,
yet are allowed to skirt critical quality controls. They also
aren't subjected to the rigorous clinical tests pharmaceuticals
must go through before hitting the market.
</P>
<P>
   A sharply worded editorial last year in the New England Journal
of Medicine detailed the many pitfalls of alternative medicine. The
journal warned of ``irrational approaches to medical practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the medical establishment isn't shunning natural products
completely.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal of the American Medical Association has published
several articles on herbs, finding in some cases that herbs could
provide better treatments than conventional care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
