r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBOT-SURGERY-HNS &LR;      03-10 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBOT-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY PLAYS A BIGGER ROLE IN THE SURGICAL WARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE FOY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Before Dr. Morris Franklin could stride into the
dimly-lighted operating room, his nurse shouted out a reminder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget your microphone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin grabbed for a black microphone headset. Once in the
operating room, he plugged it into a nearby machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microphone connected,'' a computerized woman's voice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hermes, VCR record,'' the doctor commanded, glancing up at two
large video monitors displaying the patient's inner abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recording,'' the voice confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hermes, pressure: Down, down, down,'' Franklin said, watching
as the patient's bloated belly automatically flattened from the
decreasing gas pressure being pumped into his system.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may seem straight out of a ``Star Trek'' episode,
this scene is becoming a familiar one in operating rooms. Where it
was once common for a patient to spend hours under the knife, the
doctor of today may use voice-activated commands to shorten
surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   New technologies such as the Hermes control system Franklin uses
at the Southeast Baptist Hospital in San Antonio are a driving part
of the operating room revolution. State-of-the-art medical machines
and tiny, more precise tools can enhance a surgeon's skills, as
well as cut down on the pain and recovery time a patient often
faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another step toward having the operating room
fully automated _ or as fully automated as we can get,'' Franklin
said excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   Although some doctors are reluctant to embrace the idea of a
high-tech operating room where machines and robots follow a
surgeon's commands, Franklin welcomes it. He foresees a day when
robotic technology will be widely used in operating rooms to enable
a doctor to perform surgery using virtual reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could sit here at my desk and put my hands into a pair of
gloves that send signals to the robot in the operating room. Every
time I moved, the robot would move,'' Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consider this: when you get down to the fine stuff, every
doctor has a hand tremor. We've all just learned to control it,''
he said. ``Robots don't have tremors. That means you can do finer
and more delicate surgery that is more accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Such technology is available, but not widely used, today. The
surgeon can sit at a console and use instruments similar to
conventional surgical tools to control robotic arms in the
operating room.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular afternoon, Franklin performed a minimally
invasive, laparoscopic surgery on a 46-year-old man. The patient's
abdomen was inflated with carbon dioxide gas to allow a team of
doctors to insert microscopic tools _ including a small video
camera and light source _ through five small incisions.
</P>
<P>
   The patient was undergoing surgery to correct a condition called
Barrett's esophagus, marked by reflux of acid matter into the
throat. The condition can lead to esophageal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   To correct the condition, Franklin had to tack the patient's
stomach to his esophagus and then suture both to the diaphragm to
create a valve.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the procedure, Franklin kept his eyes on two large
television monitors stationed above the patient's head. A pioneer
in laparoscopic surgery, Franklin has had lots of practice
manipulating the long, thin instruments inserted through tiny
valves.
</P>
<P>
   But he was getting used to the newest member of his staff _ the
Hermes system, manufactured by Computer Motion Inc. of Santa
Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital bought Hermes two weeks ago for about $40,000.
Franklin and another doctor have programmed their voices into the
system so that it will recognize their commands.
</P>
<P>
   Hermes actually takes over other equipment during surgery. It
can control the gas pressure, light source, digital printer and
video-cassette recorder, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Before, nurses often had to constantly monitor each individual
piece of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would literally have to be there to do all these things _
we were the doctor's hands,'' said Toni Halcomb, a nurse
administrator at the San Antonio hospital. ``With this, the nurse
doesn't have to be available for the surgeon the entire time and we
can be doing other things.''
</P>
<P>
   But some nurses say they are nervous that more technology means
less need for their skills in the operating room. Halcomb downplays
such concerns, saying nurses will continue playing a vital role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you have all this equipment, you have to have someone
to talk to the patient, to soothe them,'' she said. ``I sure
wouldn't want a robot to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearing the end of the surgery, a mischievous grin spread across
Franklin's face. He called upon Hermes again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hermes, controls,'' he said, bringing up a control panel on
the television monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compliment,'' he ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're such a great surgeon,'' the computerized voice said,
eliciting giggles from the operating room staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``See what a great system this is?'' Franklin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
