A4881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-10 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PERFECT CHARACTER WITNESS: A POLITICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A lawyer I once knew displayed a sign on his desk
that got right to the point: ``Reasonable doubt for a reasonable
fee.''
</P>
<P>
   But reasonable people can, and often do, disagree about what
constitutes reasonableness. Just ask anybody involved in the case
of Donald J. Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   He's 57 and one of roughly 2,200 registered lobbyists in New
York's capital city. He's a respected member of a
$50-million-a-year Albany industry.
</P>
<P>
   The police pulled Boyle over last April in suburban Colonie. It
was a bit after 8 p.m. He'd just spoken to a group at the Colonie
Elks Club. The cops said he was going too slow and that his BWM was
weaving. They took Boyle back to headquarters and administered a
breath test. Boyle's breath registered a .25 blood alcohol content.
The legal limit for driving while intoxicated is .10. Deeply
disapproving, the cops charged him.
</P>
<P>
   There's a little irony worth mentioning here. Boyle lobbies for
driving schools. One of them is called the New York Safety Program.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Boyle wasn't permitted to drive home. Instead, he
called a friend to pick him up. Boyle then hired a lawyer. Plea
bargaining began. Since Boyle had copped a plea three years earlier
to another drunken driving beef, the district attorney's office
would accept a plea only to what he was charged with and not to
lesser offense.
</P>
<P>
   This set the stage for a three-day jury trial last month in
Colonie Town Court.
</P>
<P>
   Two witnesses testified on Boyle's behalf. One was an official
of the group that Boyle had addressed. He said that Boyle had
downed only one drink and seemed fine. The friend who'd picked up
Boyle and driven him home that night also testified that Boyle had
appeared perfectly sober. That friend, one juror told me, was an
impressive witness. He was Mike Hoblock, the former Colonie town
councilman, former Albany County executive, former assemblyman and
state senator. He's currently chairman of the New York State Racing
and Wagering Board and one of the most popular and highly respected
local politicians in the Albany metro area.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle and Hoblock have known each other for decades. Boyle
kicked in $250 to Hoblock's last campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The jury retired and acquitted Boyle in just a half hour. The
prosecutor is still slapping his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle's lawyer had argued that the single drink Boyle had
consumed at the Elks Club had produced a false blood alcohol
reading _ that residual alcohol in his client's mouth and throat
had thrown off the measuring device. A juror I spoke to said that
the defense also had raised the possibility that the device that
had measured Boyle's blood alcohol content had been thrown off by
radio waves. The jury had been impressed by that _ and by those
witnesses, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not all the jurors. One had served as an alternate,
standing by in case another juror died or became unable for
whatever reason to participate in deliberations. At the end of
testimony, but before deliberations, she went home. When I told her
that Boyle had been acquitted, she was aghast. She wouldn't have
voted that way.
</P>
<P>
   Neither she nor the other jurors knew of Boyle's previous
conviction. He didn't testify, so the defense had no clean way to
bring it up. Hoblock, by the way, told me that he hadn't known
either.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line? None of the jurors had heard any personal history
of drinking and driving. They simply ended up with reasonable
doubts about the accuracy of that breath test _ especially after
hearing from those convincing witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's some advice: Don't drive drunk. It really annoys the
cops. But if they ever stop you and charge you with it, you know
whom to call for a ride home. Somebody credible enough to attract
57,421 votes the last time he ran for office.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
