<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE FIGHTING WORDS FROM HOLYFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evander Holyfield is supremely confident of three
things this morning as he's riding down Central Park West heading
toward the Church Street Gym near Wall Street, where a crowd of
several hundred photographers and expectant journalists from around
the world are impatiently waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, he will walk into Madison Square Garden, with
more than 20,000 people screaming for blood and a 6-foot-5-inch,
245-pound man waiting to make it flow. Many, including that massive
opponent 20 feet away, will be there in the strong belief that this
is the end for the Humble Warrior, the last big fight for the best
heavyweight of his time.
</P>
<P>
   As the street scenes of midtown Manhattan pass by, Holyfield
looks out the window of his limousine and considers what he is
about to face before he speaks of it. At 36, an age at which most
prizefighters have reached the status of pensioner or punching bag,
the heavyweight champion of much of the world is about to embark on
the biggest challenge of his career still certain of three things:
his God, himself, and the fact that a man named Lennox Lewis is
coming to Madison Square Garden Saturday to do him harm.
</P>
<P>
   God will be there to protect Holyfield, Holyfield will be there
to protect himself, and Lewis will be there to defend his third of
the heavyweight title while hoping to snatch away the 66.7 percent
Holyfield controls. In the opinion of the World Boxing
Association-International Boxing Federation titleholder, the latter
fact is as welcome as the other two because he sees them as a
winning equation for possibly the last big fight of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta understand what makes a fight difficult,'' Holyfield
said. ``Vaughn Bean (whom Holyfield defeated in a desultory
performance in his last outing) came to survive. Lennox is coming
to win. A guy trying to win leaves himself open to be hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Bean was trying to do was prove he belonged in the same
ring with me. I'm a winner. I'll do everything necessary to win,
but if your opponent says, `I don't think I can win so I just want
to survive,' he covers up and the fight goes the distance and
causes you problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis won't do that. He's trying to prove he can win. I
know Lennox is coming to win, so I know it's gonna be a good fight
and a short night.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has been uncharacteristically bold about offering this
opinion, making pronouncements about a third-round knockout that
caught even his trainer, Don Turner, off-guard. When Holyfield
originally said he would dismantle Lewis so quickly, a surprised
journalist asked if he had heard correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not predicting,'' Holyfield said. ``I'm telling you.''
</P>
<P>
   Three is a number he has stuck with, and nothing changed as he
rode through the streets of Manhattan Tuesday because those words
were based not on anything lacking in Lewis but in a supreme belief
in himself and the God he is sure has brought him to this moment
only for victory, just as He twice did when Holyfield fought the
seemingly unbeatable Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying he's less than what he is,'' Holyfield said of
Lewis, an Olympic and two-time world champion. ``I'm not saying
he's a bum. I'm not saying he's not a hard puncher. But even if
he's as good as he says he is, what does it mean? I'm still going
to knock him out in three rounds because this is not about Lennox
Lewis. That's how confident I am in my ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes me able to say and do these things is my
relationship with God. It's at its best right now and so I'll be at
my best. I want to be the very best I can be. If I am, I don't have
anything to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying these things and then going to sleep. I'm
working hard. I'm preparing to be the very best I can be. If I'm at
my best, I know what the outcome will be, so I'm holding to the
truth. The truth is the fact, and the fact is I'm going to knock
him out in three rounds. My confidence is great. It don't have
nothing to do with Lennox Lewis in no form or fashion. Lennox just
happens to be the opponent I'm going to knock out in the third
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not asking anybody to believe that or write that. I'm just
telling you. You can write it now or write it later.''
</P>
<P>
   What is most shocking is that Holyfield never before has
belittled an opponent or made any predictions except to say that he
would win.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the opponent was Dwight Muhammad Qawi or Buster Douglas
or Riddick Bowe or George Foreman or Michael Moorer or Mike Tyson,
it was the same. Holyfield was always secure in that knowledge. But
it was not until he found himself facing an opponent who has
accused him of being a hypocrite for professing his faith so loudly
while at the same time fathering three children out of wedlock that
has he chosen to be specific about his dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has not passed up any opportunity to speak out on the
apparent contradictions between what Holyfield has said about God
and how he has treated one of the Ten Commandments, pointing out
that anyone can make a mistake but when you repeat it twice in one
year, as Holyfield did in 1998, it isn't a mistake. It's a habit.
</P>
<P>
   Those words surely stung, but Holyfield has insisted they are
not what has inspired him. Rather, he said, ``I was worse than what
he's saying about me. But my past is my past. It gives me
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it is strength enough to knock Lewis unconscious in
nine minutes because ``Lennox poses a threat to a lot of people but
not to me,'' said Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   To Holyfield, he is something less than a threat but also
something more. He is an opportunity to cement Holyfield's standing
in boxing and to shore up his standing with God on the same night.
</P>
<P>
   It is an odd way of looking at an opponent capable of knocking
you out with one right hand while trying to do it with the movement
of his lips as well, but that is how Holyfield sees the world _
through a looking glass all his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he said about me gave me an opportunity to explain to the
world what a hypocrite really is,'' Holyfield said. ``A hypocrite
quits when he falls. Everybody always knew my relationship with
God. My strength comes from the Lord regardless of my mistakes.
I've made a lot of them but He's always got me through. He's always
given me another opportunity to redeem myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you fall short doesn't mean you don't get up and
continue on. That's why I'm a three-time heavyweight champion. I
fell short. I came back. I didn't make excuses. I don't make
excuses for other things that happened in my life, either. I was
born out of wedlock and I had kids out of wedlock. I made mistakes,
but they are still my kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox saying what he did about me gave me the opportunity to
look at myself and to inspire people not to give up just because
they made a mistake. God forgives your mistakes. He tells you it's
not how you start but how you finish. So a hypocrite isn't somebody
who makes mistakes. A hypocrite is somebody who pretends to be
something he's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox has proclaimed he wants to be the undisputed
heavyweight champion. After this fight Saturday he'll have the
opportunity to see if he's a hypocrite. Does he want to be champion
bad enough to come back after he gets hisself knocked out?''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield stretched after he said that, his tightly muscled body
relaxing as the car approached the gym and a sea of cameras
encircled it. Instructions were given that it go around the block
to let the champion slip in through a side door, but Holyfield
rejected the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go right in the front,'' he said. ``Let them all see
we're coming.''
</P>
<P>
   A smile crossed his face as he slipped into the crowd with one
last thought for Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going to hurt him,'' Holyfield said. ``Then we'll
see who's a hypocrite.''
</P>
<P>
   And who isn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
