<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-KENT-BOS &LR;      03-10 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-KENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR KENT, REAL MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTY PANTAGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   March Madness?
</P>
<P>
   How about driving home through fog so thick that a relatively
simple 4-hour trip to Miami of Ohio turned into an overnight crawl
along a deserted highway outside of Oxford, Ohio, with a friend
hanging out the car window shining a flashlight to find the white
line on the side of the road?
</P>
<P>
   March Madness?
</P>
<P>
   How about traveling to Ypsilanti, Mich., on a last-minute whim,
only to take a wrong turn somewhere near Toledo and arrive at
Eastern Michigan's Bowen Field House to watch the last 30 seconds
of a 1-point loss?
</P>
<P>
   March Madness?
</P>
<P>
   How about cutting down the nets at Ohio State's old St. John's
Arena _ off rims tucked away in a storage area long after a
20-point defeat to a perennial Big Ten power?
</P>
<P>
   No, we didn't lack March Madness at Kent State in the early
1980s; the problem always seemed to be that these acts of temporary
insanity during college basketball season took place in December,
January, and February.
</P>
<P>
   Come March, the Golden Flashes quickly were eliminated from the
fledgling Mid-American Conference tournament, and we had turned our
attention to ridiculing the antics of a Ted Stepien-owned Cavaliers
team and anticipating another hopeless summer of Indians baseball.
</P>
<P>
   How times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers teeter on competitiveness, the Indians have been
in two of the past four World Series, and Kent _ minus the State _
is playing in its first NCAA basketball tournament, facing Temple
at the Fleet Center on Friday afternoon in a first-round East
Regional game.
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost 30 years, but mention that you attended the
21,000-student university in northeastern Ohio and undoubtedly the
response is tied to May 4, 1970, when four students were killed and
nine others wounded by National Guard gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young wrote a song about Kent State
that became an anthem for the '60s protest movement. But the
university could just as easily be remembered for producing Gene
Michael, Thurman Munson, Jack Lambert, Michael Keaton, and Arsenio
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   As for basketball history? Well, that's another story _ unless
you consider 1951 graduate and longtime Lakers assistant coach Bill
Bertka an NBA legend. The MAC has a tradition of producing
NBA-caliber players _ Nate Thurmond, George Gervin, Ron Harper, and
Dan Majerle, among others. But Kent State's fortunes usually
revolved around 5-foot-10-inch point guards and 6-7 centers who
were passed over by the Michigans and Ohio States. But that didn't
stop us. I was a freshman at Kent State in 1979, more interested in
Trent Grooms's chase to become the MAC's all-time leading rebounder
than ongoing protests on campus over the site of a gym annex.
</P>
<P>
   In our minds, Duke's Cameron Crazies had nothing on us. Heck,
their teams played for national championships. Off we'd go, cutting
Wednesday classes to follow around a sub-.500 team, either on
assignment for the Daily Kent Stater or for the sheer joy of the
game (and who could pass up a trip to Corapolis, Pa., for a
nonconference game against Robert Morris?).
</P>
<P>
   After I departed Kent, the Flashes did enjoy a modicum of
success under coach Jim McDonald, posting a couple of 20-victory
seasons that gained NIT berths. But the NCAA is virgin territory.
</P>
<P>
   Third-year coach Gary Waters's team has won a school-record 23
games this season _ matching the total number of victories my
freshman and sophomore years. The Flashes still rely on undersized
players, but they play that patient style that causes upsets this
time of the year. (Just ask Miami of Ohio All-America forward Wally
Szczerbiak, who was shut down by Kent in the MAC tournament title
game.)
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to think we were ahead of our time in Kent, preparing
some 20 years for this day that all college teams strive to reach.
After all, I never thought I'd see the Indians in the World Series.
So Kent in the Big Dance? Stranger things have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Madness begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1322EST &QL; 
