<HEADER>
A4943 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-CHARITY-MEMORABIL     03-10 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CHARITY-MEMORABILIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collectors: Payne price was `inflated'
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Olympic memorabilia collectors and dealers worldwide
marvel at the price Billy Payne fetched for his Atlanta mementos,
which have been valued at $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot imagine what's in the collection of Mr. Payne that
can be so expensive,'' said Bernhard Winter, an auctioneer from
Dusseldorf, Germany, who specializes in Olympic items.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, who was president and chief executive officer of the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games, received $975,000 for his
memorabilia from the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation and
credit for a noncash contribution of $528,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Olympics chief said he could not remember all the
items in his collection but did cite the commemorative torch he
carried in Greece, an engraved brick from Centennial Olympic Park,
signed posters, ``tons of photographs'' and gifts he received for
making speeches.
</P>
<P>
   GAAF President Ralph Jernigan Jr. said he could not identify the
items and that he had never seen an itemized appraisal. He said he
thinks one exists but would not make it public. Jernigan earlier
said the collection is contained in about a dozen boxes. The
material is destined for an Olympics museum proposed for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid O'Neil, a Colorado Springs, Colo., auctioneer and
authority on Olympic material, acknowledged that she appraised
Payne's collection but declined to say what it contained or how
much it appraised for.
</P>
<P>
   So what could add up to $1.5 million in those boxes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been at this a long time, and I haven't got that kind of
money (invested in a collection),'' said Don Bigsby, president of
the Olympic Collectors Club, based in Schenectady, N.Y. He has
hundreds of valuable items, including a winner's medal from almost
every Games.
</P>
<P>
   Collector Alan Polsky of Los Angeles said, ``This stuff must be
rare and one-of-a-kind.'' And fellow collector Jon Becker said the
amount paid by the GAAF ``seems to be an inflated price.''
</P>
<P>
   Winter, the German auctioneer, said that if Payne's torch is no
different in design from the 13,000 others produced, then it is not
worth more than the typical price of $1,500 paid by collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a special thing if it's the only one,'' Winter said.
Polsky said some collectors would pay a premium of perhaps $500 for
an item because Payne received it personally. But ``I don't think
it would make it priceless because it came from the local former
head of the Olympic committee,'' Polsky said. ``It's not (Olympic
founder Baron Pierre) de Coubertin's torch.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, a personal award given by a foreign country to Los
Angeles Olympics chief Peter Ueberroth was purchased recently for
$150.
</P>
<P>
   Payne says he is offended that anyone would question the
appraised value of his collection or the transaction with the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a private and confidential transaction,'' he said.
``There was no attempt to hide anything on this issue. The people
who brought the Games to Atlanta are not dishonorable
people.''Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Melissa Turner contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
