<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKW-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US HOPING TO REGAIN ITS GOLDEN FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPOO, Finland _ If this hockey team were a movie, it would be
``Starting Over.'' If it were a song, it would be ``Yesterday's
Gone.'' If it were a carbon copy of the 1998 Olympic squad, it . .
. well, it isn't _ and that's exactly the point the coach is trying
to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of something old, something new, something
borrowed and something blue,'' said Ben Smith with a chuckle.
``This is really the first time we've actually played together.''
</P>
<P>
   And Smith said that after the first game of the Women's World
Championship of ice hockey, which got under way here Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 women on the US roster for these world championships are
a mix of 11 Olympic veterans (captain Cammi Granato and assistant
captain Karyn Bye among them), experienced former national team
members (including Erin Whitten and Stephanie O'Sullivan, two of
the last pre-Olympic roster cuts) and rookies still in high school
(including Minnesotans Krissy Wendell, 17, and Natalie Darwitz, at
15 the youngest player ever named to the national team.) For a
number of reasons _ perhaps all of them inevitable _ blending them
into a well-oiled unit in only two weeks has been more difficult
than Smith had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to get 20 people on the same page even though some
people are coming from different books is taxing for the student
and the teacher,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute arrival here Monday of key defensemen Angela
Ruggiero and Tara Mounsey perhaps best illustrates the difference
between this year and last. Instead of spending five months
training, touring, living, and bonding with their national
teammates, as they did leading up to the 1998 Olympic gold medal,
the Harvard freshman and Brown sophomore played weekend games for
their college teams and then endured an overnight flight from
Boston to join the other 18 members of their new team, racing from
the Helsinki aiport to the Hotel Rivoli with just 30 minutes to
spare before the bus left for the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually without sleep for over 24 hours (``Some guy was
snoring behind us,'' said Ruggiero), the two barely had time to put
on their skates before each got an assist in the 10-2 win against
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like a haphazard way to assemble a team, it's not
because the US views this tournament as trivial. Far from it:
despite beating perennial foe Canada for the Olympic gold medal 13
months ago, the US has yet to defeat them in four tries at the
world championship and wants nothing more than to knock them off
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada's the reigning world champion,'' said Ruggiero after a
good night's sleep. ``It would be really nice to take that away
from them.''
</P>
<P>
   But after putting their lives on hold to attain their Olympic
dream, many of the 20 American players from Nagano have moved on.
Sandra Whyte, Gretchen Ulion, Colleen Coyne, Vicki Movsessian, and
Lisa Brown-Miller have retired; six players (including both Olympic
goalies, Sarah Tueting and Sara DeCosta) are back in college after
taking as much as two years off to train for the Olympics, with
only defensemen Mounsey and Ruggiero feeling prepared to miss
school and/or the first round of the ECAC women's tournament in
favor of Finland.
</P>
<P>
   ``With scheduling the tournament at this time of year, we knew
it was going to be a problem,'' said Smith, who had only 14 players
available when camp got under way at Lake Placid two weeks ago.
``We didn't want to haul people out of school to play (exhibitions)
in January because we knew we were going to have to haul people out
for this thing. It can cause quite a bit of consternation and we
don't want to disrupt the collegiate ranks because we're so
indebted to the product they're producing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mounsey looks on the bright side, if realistically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully you can take 20 good athletes and they'll perform,''
said the Concord, N.H., native who turns 21 on Friday. ``Obviously,
this won't be as good a team as the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the Olympics. Another problem, this one more insidious and
therefore potentially more threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had a little trouble getting back into the mode
that previous teams were used to playing in,'' said Smith,
referring to a 6-1 drubbing by the Canadians in an exhibition in
Brampton, Ontario, before the teams left last week for Finland. ``I
think some people thought just getting back and stepping onto the
ice was all it was going to take.''
</P>
<P>
   This tournament, all now agree, is the first phase of gently
shutting the door on 1998 while beginning to crack open the door to
2002. ``The Olympics have come and gone, and people have accepted
that,'' said Mounsey. Agreed Katie King, a forward out of Salem,
N.H.: ``It's been kind of fun to get on with things.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Canada wants to start over, too, for reasons that are
colored silver. New coach Daniele Sauvageau, an assistant at Nagano
who took over the team when Shannon Miller's contract was not
renewed, has brought a dozen Olympians, including Danielle Goyette
and Hayley Wickenheiser, to Finland on a team that may boast more
speed, more strength and more depth than it did a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment,'' said Sauvageau on Monday after her team's
10-0 rout of Switzerland, ``we are not talking anymore about the
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not until the hoped-for rematch in Sunday's final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
