<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-CHARITY-PAYNE-COX     03-10 1880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CHARITY-PAYNE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reality short of Olympic promise
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A little-known public charity founded by Billy Payne
more than a decade ago is shouldering a huge responsibility _
carrying on Atlanta's Olympic legacy. But the Georgia Amateur
Athletics Foundation is a long way from fulfilling its mission.
</P>
<P>
   Although the nonprofit foundation's stated tax-exempt purpose is
to support amateur sports, in the 2 1/2 years since the Games
ended, it has given grants of $10,000 each to two youth golf
programs. At the same time, the foundation spent nearly $1 million
to buy the personal memorabilia of its chairman _ Payne _
presumably for an Olympic museum the foundation intends to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletic legacy for the Games has basically been nil, and
that has really been unfortunate,'' said Dennis Berkholtz, a former
Olympian and president of the national team handball federation,
which relocated to Atlanta after the Games in hopes of benefitting
from that legacy.
</P>
<P>
   A foundation-sponsored community development program that would
pump $1 million provided by the U.S. Olympic Committee into Olympic
sports programs for local youth has not begun.
</P>
<P>
   And the GAAF's vision for an Olympic museum has yet to come into
focus, although it has assembled a vast collection of memorabilia
and archived documents that remain behind closed doors at the
Atlanta History Center. A temporary exhibition was opened to the
public in 1997, but there are no plans for additional showings.
</P>
<P>
   Far from shining light on Atlanta's Olympic experience, the
foundation at present is vigorously trying to shelter itself from
an ongoing Olympic bidding scandal.
</P>
<P>
   No evidence has emerged to link Atlanta's bid campaign to
bribery allegations that have debased the Salt Lake City 2002
Olympics bid effort. But the foundation has been in the news for
refusing to open its bid records to the public even as an
International Olympic Committee investigation widened to include
all recent bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   Payne contends that GAAF has ``an admirable record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has hosted sporting events and given grants for a multiple
number of years,'' he said. ``The process was interrupted when the
bid was accepted. Now that everybody has got a second wind, we are
going to pick it back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Salt Lake scandal erupted last fall, the GAAF
kept a low and private profile.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, created by real estate attorney Payne in 1987,
is the brainchild of the people who brought the Olympics to town.
Its board of directors still includes the Atlanta Nine, private
citizens who circled the globe extending Southern hospitality to
the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The stated purpose was to establish amateur athletic
competitions in Georgia, but the foundation's primary role was as a
vehicle for public contributions to lobby for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation took in about $12 million in cash, value-in-kind
contributions and licensed merchandise sales.
</P>
<P>
   During the three years of the bid campaign, GAAF co-hosted
international swim meets, volleyball tournaments and road races. It
launched the Olympic Day in the Schools program to build awareness
of the Games and to demonstrate to the USOC and the IOC that
Atlanta _ heretofore known for pro sports _ supported amateur
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primarily, everything GAAF did was related to the bid,'' said
foundation president Ralph Jernigan Jr.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta won the Games in 1990, Payne formed the Atlanta
Committee for the Olympic Games and appointed his foundation
colleagues as officers and board members of the new organizing
committee. The foundation turned over much of the money it had left
in the bank to ACOG _ in the form of a $1.3 million loan _ to
launch operations.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six years, the foundation's primary beneficiaries
were ACOG and Payne, who remained its chairman while also president
and chief executive of ACOG. The foundation's tax returns indicate
several substantial grants to the organizing committee. Some were
cash advances that came back to GAAF after the Games. Others were
transfers of cash from GAAF's Children's Olympic ticket fund that
provided seats to competitions for kids with special needs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the foundation loaned Payne $500,000 at a 6 percent
annual interest rate. Payne had quit his job when he launched his
bid effort and had secured a personal loan from a private source to
cover his expenses. The foundation's loan allowed Payne to pay off
the debt.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation did make grants to a number of organizations,
including the Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs, the Atlanta Project, a Techwood
Outreach basketball program and the Martin Luther King Jr. Center.
Jernigan acknowledged: ``We were not out publicizing the fact we
had a foundation trying to help youth sports. We were just
responding if somebody came to us.'' But in the months before the
Games, the foundation's board began to visualize its future,
Jernigan said. ``We began to realize if there was going to be any
ongoing legacy after the Games, GAAF was going to be the
organization to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Years before, Payne pledged to leave an amateur sports legacy
for inner-city youth. Originally, ACOG had projected a substantial
financial surplus, a portion of which would go to build soccer
fields and handball courts. But the budget tightened as the Games
drew near and organizers said after closing the books that the well
was dry. The USOC stepped in by announcing that it would contribute
$1 million to launch an Olympic sports program for local kids. The
GAAF would be its local partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think GAAF is the right partner, especially being the
legacy organization for the Olympic Games,'' said Maureen Stone,
the USOC program manager in Atlanta. ``The commitment is there from
the leadership to make this a successful program and resources are
there in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   While that program will encourage coaches, volunteers and
children to get more involved with Olympic sports such as team
handball, judo, canoeing and kayaking, it has not gotten out of the
starting blocks. Stalled by legal wrangling over liability issues
for two years, the committee is waiting for the foundation to sign
off on the paperwork, a USOC official said. When the Community
Olympic Development Program is launched this year, it will pale in
comparison to the one birthed after the 1984 Olympics in Los
Angeles, the last previous U.S. city to host the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Amateur Athletics Foundation, a model for GAAF, was created
in 1985 and funded with $90 million in surplus revenues in Los
Angeles. The foundation has granted more than $57 million to help
build an aquatics center, teach 100,000 children how to swim,
introduce thousands more to sports such as cycling and beach
volleyball and turn out more than 600 certified coaches through its
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   With its relative lack of funds or support from any governmental
entity, the GAAF could never hope to foster a similar sports
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an Atlanta resident, I would selfishly have liked to see a
strong amateur sports movement and to have used the Olympics as a
springboard to do that,'' said Atlanta resident Dwight Bell, a USOC
board member. ``But clearly there has to be a commitment by some
organization to go after it and support it and coordinate it and be
a lighning rod for that activity.''
</P>
<P>
   GAAF was supposed to be that lightning rod. But it has yet to
generate any electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, the foundation had no staff. In January 1998,
it hired a part-time executive director, Linda Stephenson, a former
ACOG employee. Many of its directors and officers have been busy
closing down operations at ACOG. ``Most of us have been at this
eight or nine years,'' Jernigan explained. ``We had to take a
breather.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's number is not listed in the phone book, and it
operates temporarily out of a cubicle in sparse space still leased
in the near-empty Inforum by ACOG. When the board gets together,
it's usually in a member's living room or conference room at the
member's business office.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has $4.5 million in assets _ $3 million in cash
returned by ACOG at the end of the Games and Payne's memorabilia,
which it values at $1.5 million. It still is not actively seeking
contributions or soliciting grant applications from sports
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Games, GAAF has given away no money, save the $10,000
golf program grants last fall to the East Lake Community Foundation
for its Junior Academy and the Friends of John A. White Park for
First Tee for inner-city kids.
</P>
<P>
   Both programs were connected to Payne or his board members.
Payne chaired the recent PGA Tour Championship at East Lake Golf
Club. His college friend, Jimmy Gabrielson, heads the First Tee
program. Two GAAF board members sit on the John A. White Park
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me and a lot of people that their objective is get
the museum built, and that's a legacy, but that's not a legacy for
kids and sports,'' lamented Berkholtz.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is a priority for GAAF and its executive director.
Stephenson has spent countless hours working on the Olympic
collection with the History Center. She helped put together the
center's ``Let the Memories Begin'' exhibition while still on
ACOG's payroll in 1997. Last year, she launched an ``oral history''
program seeking athletes, officials, volunteers and the public to
put their Olympic memories on videotape. Along with History Center
curator Don Mooney, she developed an Olympic display at the
Teaching Museum South, a special learning center for Fulton County
school children.
</P>
<P>
   A feasibility study for a permanent museum suggests making ``The
Olympic Experience'' a major downtown destination. But, in the
midst of the Salt Lake scandal, officials believe now is hardly the
time to launch a fund-raising campaign for about $30 million to
build the facility.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Stephenson is producing a commemorative brochure on
the Games. ``When people come to Atlanta and they want to know
about the Olympics, it's difficult for them to see something,'' she
said. Payne defended the foundation's emphasis on preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``GAAF has spent thousands of hours beginning the process of
looking into the memorabilia and records,'' he said. ``We have
spent thousands of hours on the museum feasibility study. Those are
fundamental and appropriate undertakings and ones that we are proud
of.'' The largest financial undertaking since the Games is GAAF's
$975,000 purchase of Payne's Olympic memorabilia collection in
1997. That purchase allowed Payne to pay off his loan to the
foundation and still receive about $370,000 in cash. The foundation
considers Payne's memorabilia an essential part of any museum
collection. But while the sports activists don't begrudge the
foundation their drive for an Olympic museum, many agree with
Atlantan Steve Kearney, president of USA Badminton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've already got a beautiful (Centennial Olympic) park, and
I'm glad we've got it. But what is that going to do for the
sports?'' he said. ``I'd also like to have a gym I could play in
and teach kids in. The athletes are the legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
