<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4970 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-10 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LIMITS OF LIABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Sex and adultery can wreak havoc in a workplace, but the
consequences often depend more on who the people are and where they
are than the affair itself. Double standards still rule the day.
Power, wealth and, yes, gender, still make a difference. So does
the type of workplace. Certain behaviors may be ignored by one
company and severely punished by another.
</P>
<P>
   Few employers actually ban consensual relationships. Some try to
discourage sexual relations between employees, particularly when
managers and subordinates are involved, because of the negative
impact those relationships may have on productivity and company
morale.
</P>
<P>
   In February, I wrote a Valentine's Day column on romance in the
workplace, and the increase in dating among co-workers. What I did
not touch on, as explained in the following letter, was the
extramarital affair, or dating among married employees, and its
ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your February article on love in the workplace hit very hard,
not for what it covered, but for what it did not cover. What do you
do when adultery has struck? It's a fairly typical situation:
</P>
<P>
   --Married man in his 40s, put through bachelor's and master's in
science by professional wife.
</P>
<P>
   --Small company with fabulous potential.
</P>
<P>
   --Attractive girl in her 20s who works for him. She gets hot; He
gets hot. They fall in love and/or are infatuated.
</P>
<P>
   --The wife observes ``chemistry'' between them. They claim
friendship and temptation, but deny sexual relationship. Co-workers
have been suspicious for some time.
</P>
<P>
   --Girlfriend is removed from his team. They continue the
relationship for a year and a half, denying all. He resigns from
his team.
</P>
<P>
   --He confesses, after wife finds proof. Marriage deteriorates.
Wife insists on separation if he can't be faithful. He asserts he
is not capable of being faithful.
</P>
<P>
   --Separation planned. He's taking an apartment, the cost of
which is going to put severe financial burden on a budget strained
to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   As the wife, I can cope with the essential tragedy of my loss of
a marriage partner, but I have a larger question: To what extent
could the company be held liable for the alienation of a husband
when the executive ranks were aware of the adulterous affair and
did nothing about it?
</P>
<P>
   Adultery, for all its commonplaceness, is still illegal, is it
not? If companies are held liable for damages due to tolerating
behavior that results in harassment, sexual or otherwise, does it
logically follow that they could be found culpable in situations in
which they tolerate behavior that causes a woman to lose her future
stake in a partnership that provided her and her child with
material security?
</P>
<P>
   What are a wife's options? Should she make a formal complaint to
the company and demand the (girlfriend) be let go? Should she
divorce him, and sue for his options?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Name Withheld Upon Request &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Tragically, this letter demonstrates how devastating these
relationships can be to families.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several high-profile divorce cases that have
raised questions about a wife's role in a marriage and have focused
on her options during divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Lorna Wendt, then the wife of GE Capital
chief executive Gary Wendt, sued for half of the $100 million she
estimated he was worth. She wanted more than the house they had
shared before the break-up of their 32-year marriage. Lorna Wendt
wanted Gary's unvested stock options. She also wanted a share of
his retirement benefits, even though they would not be available to
either of them for several years.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, she prevailed. Instead, of the $8 million her
husband had offered, she received $22 million. Additionally, a
Connecticut judge ruled that any stock options awarded to Gary
Wendt during the marriage were ``marital property'' and, therefore,
had to be shared with Lorna.
</P>
<P>
   The other question is more difficult to answer. I could not find
anyone who knew of a case in which an employer had been found
liable for an adulterous relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Can the wronged spouse demand the firing of an adulterous
employee? ``It is not the wife's place to demand that the woman be
transferred or fired,'' said Chicago employment lawyer Laurel
Bellows, former chairperson of the American Bar Association
Commission on Women. ``She is not the supervisor of the workplace.
She is an affected party between two adulterers. In legal language,
she does not have the standing to complain about the atmosphere in
the workplace because she is not an employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what if this was the 10th adulterous relationship fostered
by a workplace where loose sex and orgies were common,'' she
continued. ``Even then, the wife or spouse might not have a cause
of action, but the employees would.''
</P>
<P>
   About the illegality of adultery, Bellows asked, ``Who is to say
a consensual relationship is wrong legally? Morally, we would all
probably agree with this letter writer. But few states now have
Alienation of Affection Acts or statutes that make adultery
illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she noted, ``This woman has raised cutting
edged legal issues. We read her letter and we laugh at first, then
we cry. She would like to use the law to turn the workplace in the
opposite direction, but that is too much of a stretch since most
people now feel that employers have no place in their personal
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments, story ideas? Contact Diane Lewis at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
