<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-INVESTING-2TAK     03-10 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-INVESTING-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RISE OF E-WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Tony Pelletier, a retired engineer who trades stocks through
his on-line brokerage account, is considering buying something his
son typically avoids: Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand technology stocks because of my profession, and
I'd been planning to get more into them,'' says the 65-year-old
Hyannis, Mass. resident, who trades several times a week.
</P>
<P>
   For Pelletier's 37-year-old son, Bruce, the siren call of
electronic investing has a different timbre. Although he trades on
line for a living, investing his own $500,000 in up to 50 stocks
each day and cashing out before the market closes, he generally
shuns Internet issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grind out small profits and sometimes have a windfall,'' he
says. ``But it's hard to track the short-term direction on Internet
stocks, so I generally don't buy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite different approaches, the Pelletiers are at the fore of
the biggest revolution in investing since the rise of mutual funds.
Spurred by Internet mania, a bull market in stocks, and the speed,
economy, and ease of Web-based trading, on-line investing has gone
mainstream. Barely a fringe culture three years ago, it now
accounts for roughly one-third of stock trades by individual
investors, and is challenging traditional Wall Street brokerages as
well as the buy-and-hold principle that has ruled investing for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more people buy and sell stocks electronically _
often with the click of a mouse from home computers _ investing has
become much more of a do-it-yourself affair. In the process, power
has shifted to small investors, and the barriers separating
professional stock pickers and amateurs have eroded.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers are increasingly worried about the harm that
neophyte Web-based investors may do to themselves. While
on-line-only brokerages come under the purview of the Securities
and Exchange Commission, the investment industry's regulator, such
sites have made officials and observers nervous about the
consequences of high volume trading.
</P>
<P>
   With Web-based trading, investors are taking matters once left
to brokers into their own hands. As a result, ``people are having
to spend a lot more time on decision-making and choosing,'' says
professor Erik Brynjolfsson of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's Sloan School of Management. ``There's an element of
self-discipline that becomes more important. Some of the old rules
aren't going to be very useful in this new culture.''
</P>
<P>
   On-line investors are not just day traders, who make bungee jump
transactions dozens of times a day in rapid-fire succession. Nor
are they only thirtysomethings dabbling in America's hottest hobby.
Increasingly, they are also the affluent and the elderly, for whom
money management is now a self-service affair from the home
computer as much as an occasional trip to the financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the number of on-line brokerage accounts more than
doubled to 7.3 million, with $420 billion in assets, according to
Piper Jaffray Inc., a Minneapolis investment firm. Around 27
percent of all retail trading by individuals in stocks and mutual
fund shares was done on line in 1998, says Piper Jaffray. For
stocks only, the firm says, on-line brokerages accounted for a
whopping 37 percent of all retail trading.
</P>
<P>
   The growth is not just in new accounts. Investors using one of
the nation's 100 or so on-line brokerages trade an average of 20
times a year, four times more often than regular investors,
according to Gomez Advisers Inc., a Concord, Mass., consulting firm
on the Web-based brokerage industry.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of on-line trading is clear. At anywhere from $5 to
$29.95 a trade, electronic transactions cost a fraction of the $300
and more charged by full-service brokers. Offering research,
charts, fancy analytical tools, and live price quotes,
cyber-brokerages blur the boundary between the trading room of a
Wall Street money giant and a kitchen in Kansas with a computer and
a modem.
</P>
<P>
   As such, on-line investing reflects the growing populist tone of
the US investment industry, where the rise of discount brokerages,
mutual funds, and 401(k) pension plans have all shifted power to
the individual investor.
</P>
<P>
   But while emblematic of an increasingly consumer-driven,
computerized world, on-line investing and its perils in fact recall
shady aspects of Wall Street earlier this century.
</P>
<P>
   Often full of bogus tips and false hype, the Internet's
thousands of investment chat rooms and message boards sometimes
echo the market manipulators and bucket shops of the 1920s, when
shady dealers would solicit money from investors, talk down a
stock's price, and then pocket the difference.
</P>
<P>
   There are other, more modern perils.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the crush of investors racing on line has
caused overloaded systems to crash, most seriously at E-Trade, a
popular online-only brokerage, and most recently at Charles Schwab
&AMP; Co., the industry leader. Such outages have caused investors,
whose profits depend upon instant trade execution, to lose
thousands of dollars. Some investors, their confidence shaken, have
even filed lawsuits against electronic brokers.
</P>
<P>
   For those who make profits, fast and furious electronic trading
can produce bigger capital gains taxes, since there are more
transactions to tax.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperactive trading also creates more activity in
already-volatile markets and has spawned a shorter-term investing
horizon. That in turn has created a new class of investors who
increasingly forsake stocks with good long-term prospects in favor
of popular, flavor-of-the-month issues _ a major shift in investing
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   As state officials shut down renegade day-trading shops and the
nation's top securities regulator calls for increased scrutiny of
on-line brokerages, some industry players wonder just how safe
investing's brave new world is.
</P>
<P>
   ``With on-line brokerages, the cost of investing is the lowest
in history,'' said professor Jeremy Siegel of the University of
Pennsylvania's Wharton Business School. ``But the risk is not.''
</P>
<P>
   That point is not lost on Bruce Pelletier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely an art,'' says the Hyannis resident, who
worked as a carpenter and resort manager before becoming a
full-time self-avowed day trader three years ago. Bruce invests
side-by-side with his father out of a ``trading room'' the elder
Pelletier built on the third floor of his Cape Cod-style house.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father, who trades only through his $1 million
account at Fidelity Investments' on-line brokerage, Bruce has
gradually moved his business from Fidelity to an obscure Web-only
brokerage, whose name he won't mention for fear of creating a
systems-crushing flood of new business. With all the trading he was
doing, Bruce says, Fidelity's system of routing orders to
specialists and market makers, rather than executing trades
automatically, was costing him time and, hence, profits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
