<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-TUITION-ART-     03-10 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-TUITION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE OFFERS UNIQUE WAY TO SAVE FOR EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. JAFFE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A new Massachusetts program allows for tax-deferred
college savings, and provides the kind of flexibility most previous
tuition-savings programs lack. The U. Fund is the state's version
of a so-called ``529 Plan,'' and its creation makes Massachusetts
the first state with both major forms of state-sponsored savings
program, one that involves guaranteed tuition savings (the
previously established U. Plan) and the newer form of investment
account.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the Roth IRA of college savings plans,'' says
Brian Grodman of the Grodman Financial Group in Manchester, N.H.
New Hampshire last year became the first state in the country to
offer a 529 Plan, opening the Unique College Investing Plan, which
is very similar to the U. Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offers tax-deferred growth, with flexibility that was not
previously available. Anybody with children or grandchildren is
going to have to look at this as an option, because you can build
your college savings around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the basics on how the U. Fund works:
</P>
<P>
   Parents or grandparents open a U. Fund account in the name of a
child, who becomes the beneficiary of the account. The money grows
with all state and federal taxes deferred until the child reaches
college age. There already is a proposal from the governor's office
that would make the program state-tax exempt.
</P>
<P>
   When the child reaches college age, the money is withdrawn to
pay for tuition, room, board, books and/or required equipment and
supplies. The money, at this time, is taxed at the child's tax
rate, typically much lower than that of the parent.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the U. Plan, in which investments essentially buy
tuition credits at participating colleges throughout the state, the
U. Fund has no borders. The child can attend any college, anywhere,
and be a beneficiary of the money.
</P>
<P>
   The money is invested into funds managed by Fidelity
Investments. One of the rules allowing 529 Plans is that the people
establishing the account are not allowed to have discretion over
how the money is invested; you do not get to pick the funds, nor
decide what percentage goes into each fund in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the Massachusetts plan _ like the one offered by New
Hampshire _ the money is invested in one of eight portfolios of
funds, starting out with a mix of 88 percent stocks/12 percent
bonds when the child is young, and becoming steadily more
conservative until it reaches an allocation of 20 percent stocks/40
percent bonds/40 percent short-term bonds and cash when the child
hits college age.
</P>
<P>
   The money is placed in up to 16 different Fidelity funds, from
equity choices such as Blue Chip Growth, Overseas, Spartan Market
Index, and Equity-Income II, to fixed-income selections including
Government Income, Investment Grade Bond, and Short-Term Bond.
</P>
<P>
   (Each state develops its own plan for how the money should be
invested. Most of the 16 states with 529 Plans in operation invest
more conservatively than either the Massachusetts or New Hampshire
plans and/or do not adjust the portfolio for the age of the
beneficiary.)
</P>
<P>
   Both the Massachusetts and New Hampshire plans have neither
residency requirements nor borders. Plans can be established by
residents of any state. (Out-of-state residents could face
different state tax implications, depending on tax laws where they
live.)
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the U. Fund allows the money to be moved from one
beneficiary to the next. Say the oldest child in a family decides
not to go to college or graduates with a balance left in the U.
Fund account. The money can be transferred without penalty into the
account of which a younger child is the beneficiary, or even into
one in which the parent saves money to go back to school.
</P>
<P>
   If you withdraw the money early, for a use other than qualified
college expenses, the earnings are taxed at the
parent/grandparent's rate, plus a 10 percent penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, the structure of 529 Plans in general has some positive
estate/gift aspects. Normally, a parent can give a child only
$10,000 per year without hitting the limit and triggering gift
taxes or dipping into certain estate tax benefits. With the U.
Fund, however, a parent or grandparent can give the child up to
$50,000 in a single year (maximum of $100,000 per couple).
Essentially, this works like an advance on the $10,000-per-year
rule; you can make the maximum gift now, but give no more for five
years. Still, that puts the money to work upfront, and eases
certain estate-tax provisions.
</P>
<P>
   There are costs associated with the program. Aside from the
regular management fees of the mutual funds involved, there is a
0.3 percent annual management cost. And there is a $30
set-up/annual fee, which is waived if the participant makes
automatic monthly investments of $50, or once the account reaches
$25,000 in value.
</P>
<P>
   With the average fund in the program having an expense ratio of
0.7 percent _ more for the stock funds, less for the bond funds
involved _ the average expense ratio on the investment will be
roughly 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For information and application forms on the U. Fund, call
800-544-2776.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no income limits and the contribution limit is five
years at the highest-priced institution in the state,'' says Peter
Mazareas, executive director of the Massachusetts Educational
Financing Authority, which is running the program for the state.
Currently, that means the maximum contribution is pegged at
$158,750 (although giving that much in one lump sum could have
estate/gift tax consequences). ``This is really a program that
everyone can participate in and benefit from.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazareas says he believes the new program will not put the
existing U. Plan out of business. That program allows investors to
set aside current dollars to pay for college tuition at a list of
participating institutions. If, for example, a parent puts in
enough money to pay for 10 percent of a UMass education at today's
prices, he will be guaranteed of having that percentage of tuition
covered when his child reaches college age, regardless of what
happens with tuition inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for this type of plan has been, however, that the
guaranteed rates of return have been low, compared with stock
market returns. That, plus a limited enrollment period (the U. Plan
accepts new participants in May only, compared with the 529 Plan,
which is open year-round), have curtailed interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some people who want the guarantee, the safety
of knowing that they have purchased tuition and that the education
is paid for no matter what happens to prices,'' Mazareas says.
``But for everyone who felt the U. Plan was too conservative, the
U. Fund provides a new option. Hopefully, we've now got something
for everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
