<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-UNEASE-BOS &LR;      03-10 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-UNEASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASY PEACE IN BOSNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Packed with commuters, the city
tram chugs down the center of ``Sniper Alley,'' a road once so
dangerous that few dared attempt the trip except in an armored
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But while the shooting and looting have virtually stopped in
Bosnia since the end of the war in 1995, the peace is an uneasy
one. The presence of NATO Stabilization Force (SFOR) peacekeeping
troops gives Bosnia the unsettled feel of a country patrolled by an
occupying army, and many here believe fighting would break out
quickly if the troops pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Northern Ireland,'' said Stef Whelan, an Irish
observer with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, as
he monitored the streets of Omarska, in the north. ``The guns
aren't being fired. But that doesn't mean they can't be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   More than three years after the Dayton accord ending the 1992-95
war, Bosnia is still tense, with the previously warring factions of
Serbs, Croats, and Muslims still living wary, separate lives.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnian Serbs are furious with an international decision last
week to put the town of Brcko under three-way rule by Serbs,
Croats, and Muslims. The town is of critical strategic importance
to the Serbs because it sits on the narrow connection between the
two wings of Republika Srpska, a Serb-run part of Bosnia. The rest
of Bosnia is largely Croat-Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Dayton agreement, Brcko has been officially neutral,
but effectively controlled by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament of Republika Srpska voted late Sunday to boycott
participation in national Bosnian affairs with their Croat and
Muslim counterparts. They also voted to condemn last week's firing
of its hard-line nationalist president, Nikola Poplasen, by
international peace coordinator Carlos Westendorp.
</P>
<P>
   Poplasen insisted Tuesday he would not step down, but
Westendorp, who has sweeping powers as peace coordinator, said the
decision was final.
</P>
<P>
   The votes have strained relations between Republika Srpska and
the international community, and raised questions about the Serbs'
commitment to the Dayton agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bosnia remains on edge. The 30,000 troops _ including
6,900 US soldiers _ have been able to keep the locals from killing
each other en masse. But few refugees have returned to their homes
in Bosnia _ some because they are afraid to return to a town
largely populated by another ethnic group, and some because they
fear their homes have been booby-trapped by departing soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Houses throughout Bosnia remain burned and empty since the war.
Between one and two million land mines are still scattered
throughout the region, making much of the land off-limits for
housing or farming.
</P>
<P>
   Also, critically needed economic reform has not come about, said
Colin Soloway, a political analyst with the International Crisis
Group in Sarajevo. There is virtually no private banking system in
Bosnia, and wage-earners and business owners must put their money
into state-run accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Since the accounts are controlled by party bosses on all three
sides, the system, a vestige of the socialist era, makes it
personally risky for people to speak out against politicians,
international observers say, further holding up change.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of publicly accused war criminals are still at large, and
locals are disinclined to help the International Criminal Tribunal
for the former Yugoslavia find them, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Local Serbs ``consider them heroes,'' said Lee Snell, a human
rights investigator in Prijedor, northern Bosnia. Those whose
family members were killed or tortured during the war also may keep
quiet, since ``they'd rather take care of it themselves. They'd
rather kill them themselves,'' Snell said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Dayton agreement, the Stabilization Force is not
allowed to arrest accused war criminals unless the soldiers come
across them in their ``daily duties,'' said Lieutenant Commander
Glenn Chamberlain, an SFOR spokesman. ``We're not policemen,'' he
said. ``We can't do investigations, going door-to-door.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing tension in Bosnia is made even more troublesome
because of the crisis in neighboring Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians
and Serbs are fighting for control of the Serb-governed, but mainly
Albanian-occupied, province.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs in Bosnia are sensitive about the fate of Kosovo, which
many Serbs consider a kind of sacred, historical homeland. Bosnian
Serbs, who are mainly Orthodox Christian, see the mainly Muslim
Albanians as being just an extension of the Bosnian Muslims, said
Radisar Mashic, head of the single radio station in Foca, southern
Bosnia, and a prominent local Serb leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the war increases in Kosovo, stability here would not
exist,'' Mashic warned. ``Dayton would be in danger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
