<HEADLINE>
FOLK-ROCK SERVICES HELP CHURCH REACH YOUNG ADULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the very beginning it is clear this is not your typical
Sunday morning service at College Avenue United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning and welcome to the church of rock,'' the Rev.
Edward Deyton says in greeting his small congregation in
Somerville, Mass. The congregation responds in unison: ``And
roll.''
</P>
<P>
   The 45-minute service in a small alcove on the church's second
floor has more the flavor of a coffeehouse folk concert than a
Christian worship experience _ just a few songs and a brief, lively
discussion of the challenges a church faces when it tries to do
things differently.
</P>
<P>
   There is no praying and no preaching. Just Deyton and his six
band members, singing and playing guitar, drums and keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's church for people who aren't interested in what they
normally associate with church,'' said Liz Strausbaugh, 27, who
sings and somtimes plays the flute and violin at the service.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists might scoff, but the Sunday morning folk-rock
services have helped College Avenue make inroads to a population
that many mainstream Christian churches are having a hard time
attracting _ adults in their 20s and 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Experimenting with worship service _ usually by making it less
formal or introducing more contemporary music _ is one strategy
many churches are trying to draw younger members. Without young
blood, aging congregations say they face a perilous future.
</P>
<P>
   College Avenue was a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   Like many mainline Protestant churches, its membership had been
declining since the early 1960s, as younger generations grew
suspicious and disenchanted with institutional religion.
</P>
<P>
   When Deyton arrived at College Avenue about 6 1/2 years ago, he
found only one person under 40 who regularly attended the church.
Most members were in their 60s or older. Today, the church has
about 40 active young adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that if we didn't do something we were going to
die,'' said Deyton.
</P>
<P>
   The church also looked at the demographics of the surrounding
neighborhood and found that the majority of residents were single
people in their 20s, 30s, and 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation also benefits from a favorable location near
the MBTA station, which draws heavy commuter foot traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to do something that would send the message to the
community that we were going to do some serious work in terms of
welcoming young adults,'' said Deyton, who has led United Methodist
churches in Lowell, Mass. and Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the idea of the folk-rock service was born. ``We
wanted to have, in a sense, a church that's not like church,''
Deyton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a generation that is incredibly skeptical
of institutions,'' said Chance Hunter, 25, who is the church's
director of young adults ministry and a student at Boston
University School of Theology.
</P>
<P>
   Deyton strives to create a laid-back atmosphere at the service.
He writes many of the songs, or chooses folk songs with a spiritual
theme. Instead of a sermon, he presents a theme, then invites a
short discussion, and those at the service have a short discussion
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of College Avenue's congregation, which has about 350
members, still attends the more traditional Sunday morning service.
But the folk-rock service has brought in people who otherwise would
not set foot inside a church, Deyton said.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Leary, 30, grew up in a Methodist family. When she first
moved to Somerville several years ago she started looking around
for a church. She liked College Avenue because it had people her
age and it was actively involved in social issues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying to start repairing the deep divisions within the Greek
Orthodox Church in America, leaders of the church, including
bishops, have adopted a resolution encouraging greater solidarity
and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We oppose the spirit of all negativism, destructive criticism
and division,'' stated the resolution adopted last week in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, which was released by the Greek Orthodox
Archdiocese of New York, was signed by the metropolitans, the
bishops of the church's large dioceses who called this year for the
resignation of the church's embattled national leader, Archbishop
Spyridon.
</P>
<P>
   Spyridon has come under criticism for what detractors say is an
authoritarian and unyielding management style.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
