<HEADLINE>
ADDING INSULT TO OLD WOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You dine out at a local restaurant and worry whether the tip you
leave is too small or too large. Will the size of your gratuity
confirm the waiter's image of you as a cheapskate doctor or as a
yuppie spendthrift?
</P>
<P>
   You go to work and wonder whether your new patient averted her
eyes when you shook hands. Did she recognize you? Did you imagine
it, or did she recoil?
</P>
<P>
   You move to a new neighborhood and want to make friends, but you
are more guarded now, more wary of strangers. Will they ask, offer
an opinion, or avoid the subject altogether?
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy changes you. Loss diminishes you. But there is no
vocabulary for what happens to you when your life becomes a public
spectacle, when your deepest scars are laid bare for public
dissection.
</P>
<P>
   It has been two years since Matthew Eappen suffered fatal head
trauma, two years since his parents, Deborah and Sunil Eappen,
spent four long days and nights at his bedside in the intensive
care unit before he succumbed to his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a year since a Middlesex Superior Court
jury convicted, and a judge confirmed, that it was Louise Woodward
who violently shook 8-month-old Matthew Eappen and slammed his head
against a hard surface. It has been months since the Massachusetts
Supreme Judicial Court affirmed that conviction and sent Matthew
Eappen's British au pair back to England and allowed her to reclaim
her life.
</P>
<P>
   All that time, all those judicial proceedings, all of Louise
Woodward's appeals exhausted and yet, incredibly, it is still
Deborah and Sunil Eappen who remain on trial.
</P>
<P>
   To what end were the airwaves crackling and the presses rolling
this week with new theories about Matthew Eappen's violent death?
To what end was a platform provided to doctors whose hands never
touched his swollen eyes or cradled his fractured skull?
</P>
<P>
   To what end did those doctors proffer their wild speculations
that he was strangled, not shaken, that his injuries might have
been inflicted days, not hours, before an ambulance sped him away
from home for the final time?
</P>
<P>
   There has been little peace for the Eappens since, but is there
to be no peace for their son, ever?
</P>
<P>
   On the television screen, a man with a pointer and a white coat
jabs at an X-ray of their son's brain. Is his to be an autopsy
without end? Is the baby Debbie carried, the boy Sonny cherished,
public property now? Is anyone with a medical credential and a pet
theory invited to take a scalpel to his corpse?
</P>
<P>
   On the airwaves and in the press this week, the medical experts
are offering hypotheses about CAT scans, opinions about tissue
slides and brain injuries. The defense lawyers are ranting about
``new evidence'' and ``reasonable doubt'' and ``a new trial.'' The
celebrity TV interviewer is intoning solemnly about the search for
truth and ``a miscarriage of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is talking about a mother and father who have lived for
two years as the public's shadow suspects _ those fancy Newton
physicians who left their children with a teenage baby sitter to
indulge their careers. In some eyes, they can never really be
exonerated, no matter what the X-rays show.
</P>
<P>
   All along, they've heard the whispers but they pushed forward.
They had lives still to live, two other children to rear, friends
and family to support them. He began to think it might be getting a
little better. She had days when it was possible to feel normal for
hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   But that was last week, when the possibility of resuming a
private life seemed tantalizingly real.
</P>
<P>
   This week, it is deja vu, all over again:
</P>
<P>
   You walk into a room and all conversation stops. Are you
imagining it or is the atmosphere suddenly tense, awkward?
</P>
<P>
   You get in line at the supermarket and the woman in the aisle
beside you peers over the top of her National Enquirer. Don't I
know you?
</P>
<P>
   You take your son on a run down the sledding hill, longing to
feel nothing but the wind in your face and the weight of his body
snuggled beside you. Instead, you feel the eyes of the other
parents and you wonder: What are they thinking? Do they think we're
going too fast?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
