<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING TRAINING FOR SHARPENING SKILLS, PENCILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; have a new cause: spring training for the professions.
Specifically, for my profession.
</P>
<P>
   As year succeeds to year, it's hard not to cast an envious eye
southward at baseball's Boys of Spring. Luxuriating under the palm
trees, gently tossing the pill in the tropical breeze so as not to
distend any sinews or ligaments; wife and children safely tucked
away in Kalamazoo; chucking rookies' cleats into the swimming pool;
dogging your way through a series of meaningless games, PowerAde in
one hand, Marlboro Light in the other . . . That's the life for me!
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, why not for us? We white-collar drones work too. Why
can't we start fresh each spring, sharpen our skills, and ramp up
slowly to the demands of another trying year of bilking the public
(real estate brokers, auto dealers, Microsoft employees), lying
about sex (politicians, psychiatrists), or piping quotes (Globe
columnists)?
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be great to drop tools in February, head down to
Fort Myers, check into the La Quinta, and reacquaint ourselves with
the basics of our profession? Accountants could do left-brain
exercises, like trying to imagine themselves as vegetables. Doctors
could tune up their penmanship, and maybe crack open some anatomy
texts while languishing poolside. Perhaps refresh their memories as
to where the vertebrae end and the spinal discs begin.
</P>
<P>
   Take someone like Ken Starr. He's been working so hard now, five
years straight, righting the world's wrongs. Don't you think he
needs a couple of weeks in, say, Tempe, Ariz., just to relax, maybe
hang out with other prosecutors, bone up on civil procedure? I
could see Bill Clinton down in Fort Lauderdale, escaping the
missus, finally getting the time to read that fat biography of
Warren Harding, another ``misunderstood'' president. Isn't spring
break coming up? An ideal opportunity for Clinton to mix with the
country's future leaders . . .
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it would work in my profession. The Globe team would
hole up in a motel near Jacksonville, with the other newspapers
encamped elsewhere in the Sunshine State: the Herald at Kissimmee,
the Times at some classy joint like the Fontainebleau in Miami
Beach. Every couple of days we'd invite them over for a scrimmage,
mostly playing the kids just up from the Standard Times and the
Eagle-Tribune. Sure, New York might start Anthony Lewis and William
Safire, and we'd counter with Marty Nolan and Ellen Goodman. But
there would be an understanding that the vets would exit in the
second or third inning and give the rooks a chance to play.
</P>
<P>
   When not scrimmaging, we'd be honing our skills. Dave Barry and
Carl Hiaasen could come over from The Miami Herald and share a few
laughs. Maybe we could bring in some reporters from The Wall Street
Journal to tell us how they keep all those complicated business
facts straight. I'd have The Washington Post people drop by to
explain those double bylines they're so fond of. Two reporters
doing the work of one? I'm sure it's more complicated than that.
</P>
<P>
   But the real goal is to learn. We'd let staff aces like Dan
Shaughnessy and Will McDonough watch the younger scribes and then
offer advice: ``Not bad, kid,'' I'd hear Willie growling. ``But
your stuff could use more leaked depositions.'' Shaughnessy could
teach them how to work in allusions to long-forgotten rock groups,
like Toto. And I'd be happy to help the columnists of tomorrow
answer the kind of tough questions I often hear from fans: ``So,
what do you do the other three days of the week, Mr. Beam?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, spring training wouldn't be all work. It would be
important to eat right and get plenty of sleep in preparation for
the difficult months ahead. And I suppose one might be cajoled into
lifting a jar after a long day in the sunshine, improving one's
skills. Afterward we would all return to Boston, tanned, fit, and
ready to handle anything the world wants to throw at us.
</P>
<P>
   I'll slide this idea into the suggestion box and tell you what
happens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
