<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4992 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-REICHL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     03-10 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-REICHL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... so much power.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I always thought that a critic needed a great palate, stamina,
and good metabolism,'' she said. ``A friend once said, `What you
really need is to be endlessly social.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And she is. ``That part of it I really like.''
</P>
<P>
   Before reviewing took over her life and abolished the nightly
dinner hour, she and her then-husband, Doug (she has since
remarried), were part of a group house in Berkeley. The place, as
she describes it in her book, was always filled with friends, most
of them hippies willing to go along with a housemate's latest
ecological phase.
</P>
<P>
   When she became a reviewer, said Reichl, she had to move the
party out of her home. ``I just transferred it to restaurants. Now
I'll transfer it back. What really makes me happy is to have people
around the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, she and her husband bought a house in the country and
now she has a Wolf range. ``The house has a really good kitchen.
There are wonderful days when I cook and write. I bake or make a
big stew. My big pleasure is just cooking, and now I'll get to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Conde Nast approached Reichl, she had no idea what went on
at Gourmet, or if, in fact, there was any talent on board. The
pages lack vitality and many think its subscribers are mostly
octogenarians.
</P>
<P>
   Reichl shows off her new allegiance. ``It's the most loyal
readership of any magazine ever. I want to keep them,'' she says _
and add others.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast publisher Si Newhouse called Reichl when the
appointment was made public. ``Will you go over and knead the
staff?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   So she called a meeting. ``I love meetings.'' When she was food
editor of the Los Angeles Times, the staff met all the time. ``We
wrote captions together,'' she said, ``and headlines. You can do a
lot in a 10-minute meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Would this happen at Gourmet? ``There I was. These people were
worried about their careers. I was fully prepared to talk to
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   What she found, she said, was a roomful of willing people, ``an
amazing resource, a staff that was eager and full of ideas.' As it
turned out, they were attending their first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Reichl says she plans to bring new writers to the pages of
Gourmet. Her own issues won't begin until September and she has
already contacted a few friends. An early phone call went to
humorist Calvin Trillin.
</P>
<P>
   Did he want to travel somewhere and write for her, she asked.
</P>
<P>
   No, he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, Bud. Isn't there somewhere you want to go?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay,'' he answered. ``To the pimento festival in Spain. I've
always longed to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just what she wanted to hear. ``I want travel to be like
that. We have the expertise to add the other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   To her amazement, she learned that the staff traveled as a group
once a year to an exotic location and that every editor got to
attend cooking school wherever in the world she wanted. ``Does the
magazine reflect this?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   And the testers. ``It's a dream job. I want to take that kitchen
and give it a personality.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be eight kitchens in the new Gourmet offices at 4
Times Square, which will house all the Conde Nast publications. The
magazines will move in gradually over the course of next summer.
Gourmet's editor in chief will have a private office. It was to
have a sofa and coffee table, and a private bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed to use a toilet that's just mine,'' says the
populist reviewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the designer to take out the sofa and put in a big
table and six chairs. I want meetings every morning. That way we'll
get a magazine that has its look. I want to be able to open the
magazine and say `This is Gourmet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   By then, someone else will own the wigs, though not her
successor, William Grimes, a reporter in the Times's Dining
section. Reichl says she had visions of throwing a party and
tossing out the wigs like bouquets. ``Whoever caught the most would
get the job.''
</P>
<P>
   She checks her watch. The staff at Gourmet is waiting for her.
On the way over, she'll call her office at the Times for messages
and it's unclear whether she'll do this from the back of a taxicab
or right on the street. She grabs the ubiquitious black bag carried
by every well-dressed New York woman, straightens out the jacket of
her expensive black suit, and dashes away.
</P>
<P>
   For today a platinum blonde with arched eyebrows, sunglasses,
and big scarlet lips, she looks like Tracey Ullman doing the Upper
East Side. There are so many women who fit the description, it's
scary.
</P>
<P>
   Even after sharing a meal, it's not easy to tell what Reichl
really looks like.
</P>
<P>
   (It wasn't very good.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4993 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-INVESTING-2ND &LR;      03-10 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-INVESTING-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... hence, profits.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike his father, who trades mostly large-cap stocks like Dell,
Home Depot, and Staples, Bruce buys and sells ``just about anything
that moves'' _ except, curiously, Internet issues. Day in, day out,
he tracks tiny shifts in the flow of orders for hundreds of stocks,
and then buys or sells seconds ahead of the curve.
</P>
<P>
   For all the detail and precision of his work, it is a foggy
experience.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to his father, who can rattle off his worst bets
(Informix, Compaq, and AMD are among them), and who knows the
companies he buys, the younger Pelletier struggles to list his hits
and misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a blur _ you don't actually remember the particular
wins and losses,'' says Bruce, who has two children but has not
used his trading profits to set up long-term investments, like
college education funds. ``Sometimes, I can't even remember what a
particular company does,'' he says. All he knows, he adds, is that
he makes around $1,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his son, Tony Pelletier buys puts and calls _ fancy
options to buy and sell stocks at a later date for locked-in
prices. He also uses ``stop-loss'' orders to automatically sell
issues that fall more than 7 percent. Since he started trading on
line eight months ago, his strategy has helped him earn a 15
percent return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had the guts to do an E-Bay yet,'' he says,
referring to the high-flying on-line auction house, ``but I'll
probably try it through options.''
</P>
<P>
   To Michael Gazala, a senior analyst at Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass., Tony Pelletier reflects one of on-line
investing's more interesting trends: the growing willingness of
older, wealthy investors not reared on computers to trade via the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forrester, 10 percent of all affluent households,
or those with at least $1 million to invest, traded with an
on-line-only brokerage last year, double 1997's level. And nearly
half of affluent households did some form of on-line trading in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston-based Fidelity, the nation's largest mutual fund firm,
on-line accounts grew 19 percent last year to 2 million. Fidelity
now accounts for nearly 10 percent of all on-line brokerage trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just play money and it's not just the young,'' Gazala
says. ``It's also serious people with serious money. And it's
definitely more than a fad.''
</P>
<P>
   That has old-line money managers quaking in their wingtips.
While full-service Wall Street giants like Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the
nation's largest brokerage, are inching toward offering on-line
investing services, the old guard has been shocked by the power of
much smaller, Web-only firms like Waterhouse and Ameritrade to
transfer the broker's expertise to the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   As on-line brokerages rush to modernize their computer systems
and consider offering advice and planning services, their
established counterparts are rethinking the way they do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely the demise of the traditional stock broker
and his traditional role,'' says Julio Gomez, head of the
Concord-based consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence for that shift abounds.
</P>
<P>
   At Brown &AMP; Co., a small discount brokerage in downtown Boston,
business has flowered since company chief executive George Brown
launched Web-based investing services last March. Brown, who calls
on-line investing ``a socially acceptable form of gambling,''
expects firm revenues to rise 20 percent this year, the same as in
1998. His client base, now at 80,000 active trading customers, will
probably grow 10 percent, as demand for on-line accounts soars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole new generation of people out there who want to
do things for themselves,'' says Brown, whose $5 fee for trading
5,000 shares is among the lowest in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But he admits that on-line trading has changed the calculus of
risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have money to lose,'' the no-nonsense Brown says
flatly, ``you shouldn't be in this business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
