<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKILLED-FOREIGNERS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGH-TECH SOS IS HEEDED FROM AFAR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes two visa/foreign worker text tables.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Di Zhao and Anisha Mahajan are software programmers at
two Greater Boston companies. They earn annual salaries of between
$50,000 and $70,000 each, comparable to the pay of their American
colleagues. Neither is an American citizen, and neither is
considered an immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, both are classified as ``temporary workers,'' part of
the growing influx of foreigners with prized technical skills
recruited by US companies. Zhao arrived from China and Mahajan from
India last year under a temporary visa program for skilled
professionals. Known as H-1B, for the section of federal
immigration law, the visa allows foreigners with highly specialized
knowledge to work up to six years in the United States, provided
their employers can demonstrate an inability to find American
workers to do the same jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The tight US job market has touched off an international
scramble among high-tech employers for skilled professionals. Both
Zhao's and Mahajan's employers are among hundreds of US companies
that insist they have difficulty finding critical talent on US
shores. Employers have flocked to the H-1B program, in the process
fanning controversy over whether the high-priced, highly-skilled
foreigners are displacing American workers.
</P>
<P>
   Several labor and engineering groups, including the AFL-CIO,
claim that high-tech firms exaggerate the worker shortage problem
and that employers hire foreigners merely to save on wages.
``Importing'' foreign professionals, they argue, undermines the
American work force.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhao and Mahajan don't see it that way, pointing out how
they are taking jobs at prevailing wages that Americans have either
turned down or simply were not qualified for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see what I do as saving (American) jobs,'' said Zhao, a
25-year-old programmer at Primeon Inc. of Burlington, which helps
businesses solve their year 2000 computer problems. ``I am here
helping to prevent possible disasters at these companies.''
Similarly, Mahajan, who works for Westford-based Intersoft
Technologies Inc. developing telecommunications software, sees her
programming job as helping the US economy.
</P>
<P>
   The scramble for foreign talent has been so intense that the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, after using up its yearly
allotment of 65,000 H-1B visas in just 7 1/2 months last year,
stopped issuing them for 4 1/2 months.
</P>
<P>
   In response, big employers like Microsoft Corp., Texas
Instruments Inc. and Sun Microsystems Inc. asked Congress to change
the law. After much debate, H-1B visa laws were modified last fall
to boost the allotment of such visas to 115,000 for this year and
another 115,000 for next year.
</P>
<P>
   But now, there are indications that the higher maximum will be
used up well before Sept. 30, the end of the fiscal year. As of
Jan. 31, more than 70,000 H-1B visas have been approved, prompting
the Information Technology Association of America to predict the
new, higher quota could be exhausted by this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, we were stunned when the cap on H-1B visas was
reached in May and now we are equally concerned that the cap may be
reached by midyear,'' said Dyann DelVeccchio, an immigration
attorney at Palmer &AMP; Dodge in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Her clients include Parametric Technology Corp. of Waltham,
which hired 125 foreign hardware engineers and software programmers
in the past 12 months under H-1B.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric, which was formed by Russian emigres, has a high
concentration of Russian engineers and programmers like Dmitri
Fomin, who works in the engineering software company's core
geometry group.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 70 percent of the people I work with are Russian.
Russia, India and China have so many bright programmers and
mathematicans,'' said Fomin, who taught mathematics in Russia at
his alma mater, St. Petersburg State University. He joined
Parametric two years ago on an H-1B visa to work on new versions of
the company's flagship software for computer-aided engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Any limitation on H-1B visas worries Fred Wang, cofounder and
chief technology officer of Primeon, where Zhao has been working as
a programmer since October.
</P>
<P>
   The company is uniquely linked to China through the H-1B
program. Twenty-four (five women and 19 men) of its 70 employees
are from China, many of them from Tsinghua University in Bejing,
considered the MIT of China. Wang still hopes to add up to 10 more
programmers from China.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first people Wang recruited 18 months ago was Robert
Ying, a well-regarded professor of computer graphics at Tsinghua
who is now Primeon's chief software architect. Since Ying and Wang
keep in touch via the Internet with a close knit circle of friends
and graduates from Tsinghua and four other universities in China,
finding software engineers was not too difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to find US citizens for a service-oriented
business. The best and smartest engineers all find employment
developing computer networking products or want to work on the
latest frontiers of technology,'' said Wang, who left China in 1986
to earn a doctorate in computer science at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst. ``We work with mainframes, where the
software is sometimes very old, where we have to know more than 20
different application development languages.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Lixia Zheng and her husband Dongchen Wang, both Tsinghua
classmates with Fred Wang, knowing some of those arcane software
development languages helped them land jobs at Primeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the challenges of learning a new computer language and
figuring out problems,'' said Zheng, 39, who earned a master's
degree in computer science from the University of Oklahoma and
worked in Germany before coming to Primeon on an H-1B visa.
</P>
<P>
   Her younger colleague, Zhao, however, acknowledges an itch for
more interesting work. ``There are many brilliant people here, but
some of the programming work is a little boring,'' he said of
Primeon. ``I want to create something and I think they (Primeon)
will give me the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Under H-1B regulations, employers can bring in temporary foreign
professionals for up to six years at prevailing US wages set by the
Department of Labor. However, employers must show they are not
replacing US workers with H-1B visa holders and that the foreign
workers have the education and skills to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   To allay concerns about foreign workers taking jobs from
Americans, the new H-1B laws require employers to pay $500 for each
visa. The funds _ estimated to reach $250 million in three years _
are for federal job training programs for American workers and
college scholarships for low-income students in engineering,
computer science, math and science.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
