<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-THINGS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... drying out.)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Brush the tops of the chicken
thighs with the oil. Put the chicken in the oven and bake for 20
minutes. Turn the thighs and bake another 25 minutes or until
chicken is tender. Baste with the drippings 3 or 4 times while
cooking. Remove the chicken from the pan and pour the liquid into a
small pot. Boil until the liquid is somewhat reduced. Arrange the
thighs on a platter, pour the sauce over them, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CHIUCHOW GARDEN'S CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Ken Hom's ``Fragrant Harbor Taste'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, 1989). The cubed chicken is moist and extremely
flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds chicken thighs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rice wine or rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarsely ground black and Szechuan peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, minced
</P>
<P>
   Remove the skin from the thighs, and bone by cutting on one side
of the bone with a sharp knife and scraping off the meat on the
other. You should have about 1 1/2 to 2 pounds of meat after
boning. Cut the meat into bite-size 1-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the soy sauce, rice wine, salt, sugar, and cornstarch,
and mix in the chicken pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a wok until it is quite hot. Add the chicken
mixture and stir-fry over high heat for about 5 minutes. Add the
peppercorns and continue to cook for 2 more minutes or until the
chicken is completely cooked. Place the chicken on a platter,
sprinkle with the scallions, and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
TURKEY RABBIT
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to Marcella Hazan, whose recipe for stewed rabbit
in ``The Classic Italian Cookbook'' (Knopf, 1978) inspired this
dish. The turkey cooks down to savory shreds, and the sauce is
perfect over cheesy mashed potatoes or rice.
</P>
<P>
   3 to 3 1/2 pounds turkey thighs, skinned and trimmed of excess
fat
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely diced celery
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons rosemary
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, 6 to 8 twists of mill
</P>
<P>
   1 bouillon cube
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tomato paste plus 1/2 teaspoon sugar, or 2 to 3
tablespoons ketchup
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the thighs in cold running water and pat thoroughly dry
with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Choose a deep, covered skillet large enough to contain the
thighs in a single layer. Put in the oil, celery, garlic, and
turkey, and cook over low heat for 2 hours, until the meat is very
tender. Turn the meat once or twice but keep the cover on.
</P>
<P>
   After cooking for 2 hours, the meat throws off a great deal of
liquid. Uncover the pan, turn up the heat to medium, and cook,
turning the meat from time to time. When the liquid has evaporated,
add the wine, rosemary, salt, and pepper. Simmer, uncovered, until
the wine has evaporated. Dissolve the bouillon cube and
tomato-paste mixture or ketchup in 2/3 cup warm water, pour it over
the turkey, and cook gently for another 8 to 10 minutes, turning
and basting the turkey 2 or 3 times. Serve immediately or reheat
gently before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN WITH 40 CLOVES OF GARLIC
</P>
<P>
   An old favorite that anticipated the current craze for roasted
garlic, from ``The New James Beard'' (Knopf, 1981).
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   8 whole chicken legs, cut into drumsticks and thighs, excess fat
removed
</P>
<P>
   4 ribs celery, cut into long strips
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh tarragon, or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry vermouth or white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   40 garlic cloves, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   Put the oil in a shallow dish, add the chicken pieces, and turn
them to coat evenly with the oil. Cover the bottom of a heavy
6-quart casserole with a mixture of the celery and onion, add the
parsley and tarragon, and lay the chicken pieces on top. Pour the
vermouth over them, sprinkle with the salt, pepper, and a dash or
two of nutmeg, and tuck the garlic cloves around the chicken
pieces. Cover the top of the casserole tightly with aluminum foil
and then the lid (this creates an airtight seal so the steam does
not escape). Bake in a 375-degree oven for 1 1/2 hours, without
removing the cover.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the chicken, pan juices, and whole garlic cloves with thin
slices of heated French bread or hot toast. The garlic should be
squeezed from the root end of its papery husk onto the bread or
toast, spread like butter, and eaten with the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
OREGANO CHICKEN BAKED WITH POTATOES AND TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   (POLLO IN FORNO)
</P>
<P>
   An immensely satisfying dish from Giuliano Bugialli's ``Classic
Techniques of Italian Cooking'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1982).
</P>
<P>
   3 to 3 1/2 pounds small chicken thighs and drumsticks
</P>
<P>
   1 pound potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh tomatoes, ripe but not overripe
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   Clean and wash the chicken carefully. Peel the potatoes and cut
them into thick slices. Put the slices in a bowl of cold water
until needed.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze the lemon and reserve the juice. Cut the tomatoes
horizontally into slices less than 1/2 inch thick. Remove the
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil a 13-by-8 3/4-inch Pyrex baking dish. Preheat the
oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Layer the potatoes over the bottom of the dish. Sprinkle the
potato slices with salt and pepper, then pour the lemon juice over
them. Make a layer of chicken pieces over the potatoes. Put a
tomato slice over each piece of chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Finely chop the garlic. Pour the oil into a small bowl, then add
the garlic, red pepper flakes, oregano, and salt to taste. Mix well
with a wooden spoon. Pour the sauce over the tomato layer in the
baking dish. Place the dish in the oven and bake for 50 minutes to
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the oven, let stand for 2 minutes, then serve
directly from the dish.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
