</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKILLED-FOREIGNERS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... and science.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bringing in a foreign professional can cost an employer as much
as $20,000 per person. That includes immigration attorney fees,
H-1B application costs, air fare and living arrangements until the
worker is settled in, said Rajan Zambre, founder of InterSoft. His
firm specializes in finding software workers from India and placing
them at Massachusetts-based telecommunications companies and at his
own company, which also does software projects.
</P>
<P>
   India, with its abundance of technical talent, has been by far
the biggest source of professional workers under the H-1B program.
Nearly half of all H-1B visas approved last year were from India.
</P>
<P>
   ``In India, young computer software engineers can earn $1,000
per month at companies like Texas Instruments, but their growth
path is limited compared to coming here and working on the latest
technologies and earning more than $50,000 a year,'' said Zambre,
who recruited Anisha Mahajan and her husband Prithviraj Banerjee
</P>
<P>
   Having spent 14 years at Digital Equipment Corp. followed by a
year at Stratus Computer Corp. before starting his own company,
Zambre has hired more than 60 programmers from India on H-1B visas
in the last two years, and expects to recruit more than 70
programmers from India this year. Last week Zambre said he made
offers to programmers in China, Hong Kong and Korea, although 80
percent of his recruits are from India.
</P>
<P>
   Zambre's search usually begins with computer science graduates
from the Indian Institutes of Technology in Kanpur and Madras. Most
have worked for Indian companies or US firms doing business in
India, such as Hewlett-Packard Co. and Texas Instruments Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as many as 30 percent _ more than 500 graduates of
the Indian Institutes of Technology went to the United States to
pursue either jobs or graduate degrees, according to published
reports. In recent years, the emigration has been so great that the
Indian government has raised concerns about a national brain drain.
</P>
<P>
   For Zambre, bringing a young Indian programmer to Massachusetts
means providing the works. He houses them temporarily at one of two
homes he rents in Acton and Lowell. He also supplies food and
provides them with an automobile during the transition. He helps
them get their Massachusetts driver's licenses and has an English
tutor on call to help them understand American accents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't treat them well, there are 10 other companies that
will offer them jobs,'' said Zambre.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian programmers often stick together, dining at Indian
restaurants and sometimes socializing at a Hindu temple in Ashland.
Zambre also encourages them to continue their education at Boston
area colleges and universities, paying 75 percent of their tuition.
</P>
<P>
   He expects most of his young hires to return to India in three
to six years to take care of their parents and younger siblings,
although several recent arrivals say they want to stay in the
United States for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Zambre even offers his recruits cultural survival tips, such
advice to avoid ironing shirts in the kitchen while they are
cooking curry.
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 60 Indians he has brought in on H-1B visas,
Zambre claims only two were sent back because they did not work
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two presented skills in certain areas but when they
began working here, it was clear they could not demonstrate
competency,'' he added, noting he paid for their return to India.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
