<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-THIGHS-2TAKES-BO     03-10 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-THIGHS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THIGHS HAVE IT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DEBORAH P. JACOBS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the world can be divided between the night owls and the early
risers, those who rush to the phone when it rings and those who
screen every call via answering machine, those who read the last
page of a novel first and those who won't even look at the jacket
copy for fear of spoiling the ending, surely there is a line
between those who like their poultry lean and white and those who
lust after the juicy dark meat.
</P>
<P>
   These two tastes are so distinct that it's sometimes hard to
believe they come from the same bird: the delicate breast meat that
depends almost wholly on a sauce or seasonings for character, and
the ripe, slightly gamy flavor of the thigh. Though one usually
associates the White Meat Only school with children, a surprising
number of otherwise reasonable adults also turn up their noses at
the nether parts of a chicken or turkey.
</P>
<P>
   This preference is surprising when you consider the differing
levels of labor involved in preparation. Without constant
surveillance by the chef, a chicken breast can quickly cross the
line from moist to inedibly woody, while the thighs only improve
with longer cooking.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, thighs lend themselves to a greater range of cooking
styles, yielding equally delicious results with slow braising,
high-temperature roasting, and stir-frying. They provide a huge
chunk of protein at a low price, and if skinned and trimmed of
excess fat, they can meet the standards of those concerned about
fat and calories. The thigh also presents a compact, easy-to-handle
package, much quicker to prepare than a whole chicken, for example,
and simpler to convert into leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   In the following recipes, which require a minimum of effort and
ingredients, the thighs form the succulent center of an enticing
whole. A mouthwatering Indian dish, a magically easy French confit,
an Italian stew with wine and rosemary _ they all prove that the
thighs have it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
TURKEY CONFIT
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from a Sunset magazine recipe from the mid-1970s. The
succulent meat goes beautifully with potatoes and a nutty green
such as broccoli or kale.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cracked bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 pounds whole turkey thighs (unskinned)
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Combine the salt, bay leaves, rosemary, and thyme. Rub the
mixture all over the meat. Place the meat in a heavy plastic bag or
a glass or stainless steel container. Cover and refrigerate for 12
to 24 hours (for lightest salt flavor, let it chill the minimum
time).
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly rinse the meat under cold running water, rubbing
lightly to extract as much salt as possible. Drain the meat, then
pat dry. (At this stage, the meat can be covered and chilled for
another day. Just rinse and dry again before cooking.)
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy 12-inch frying pan or 5- to 6-quart kettle (choose
one with a tight-fitting lid) over medium-low heat, arrange the
thighs so they are as flat as possible. Cover and cook slowly until
the meat is very tender when pierced and is richly browned, about 2
1/2 hours. Turn occasionally to equalize the cooking. As the fat
cooks out of the meat and the meat begins to brown, you will hear
it sizzling. From this point, check the meat frequently and turn
more often for even browning.
</P>
<P>
   Lift the meat from the pan, drain briefly, and remove and
discard the skin. Arrange on a large serving platter and keep warm.
Pour off the fat in a pan and discard. Add the garlic to the pan.
Cook, stirring, over medium heat until the garlic is soft. Add the
water to the pan and bring to a boil; stir to free any browned
particles. Blend in the parsley and serve this sauce spooned onto
the meat, or from a small bowl to add to individual portions.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 7 or 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN WITH SUMAC
</P>
<P>
   This recipe from Mary Laird Hamady's ``Lebanese Mountain
Cookery'' (David R. Godine, 1987) is exquisite in its simplicity
and combination of flavors. The pita bread soaks up the juices from
the chicken, and the ground sumac imparts a deep tang that
contrasts nicely with the rich meat. Sumac can be found in health
food stores and Middle Eastern groceries.
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 rounds pita bread
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups onions, slivered in thin crescents
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons ground sumac
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 pounds chicken thighs, excess fat removed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup or more olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 425 or 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Open up the pita rounds so they are 1 layer thick. Tear them
into large bite-size pieces. Line the bottom of a 10-by-14-inch
baking pan with the bread. Spread the onions over the bread. Salt
and pepper the onions and bread liberally. Sprinkle 2 tablespoons
of sumac over it all.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chicken pieces, skin side up, on top of the bread.
Drizzle the olive oil over the chicken, then sprinkle generously
with 2 to 3 tablespoons of sumac. Add the salt and pepper to taste.
Bake for about 1 hour. Check every 15 minutes as it bakes; if the
skin begins to get too dark, cover the baking dish loosely with
foil. Cooking time will depend on the size of the thighs and the
oven temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
SPICY BAKED CHICKEN &QC; 
(MASALEDAR MURGHI)
</P>
<P>
   A wonderfully easy and flavorful dish from Madhur Jaffrey's
``Indian Cooking'' (Barron's, 1983). Adjust the amount of cayenne
to suit your taste. One teaspoon will be enough for most people.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 1/2 teaspoons cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 teaspoons freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 to 3 teaspoons salt or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 garlic cloves, peeled and mashed to a pulp
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 pounds chicken thighs, skinned and trimmed of excess fat
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cumin, paprika, cayenne, turmeric, black pepper,
salt, garlic, and lemon juice in a bowl. Mix well. Rub this mixture
over the thighs, pushing the paste inside any flaps and openings
that you find. Spread the thighs in a shallow baking pan and set
aside in a cool place for 3 hours. (Longer will not hurt. Just
cover the chicken with plastic wrap to prevent it from drying out.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
