<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-REICHL-2TAKES-AR     03-10 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-REICHL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HER TABLE IS READY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ruth Reichl slips into a corner seat, eluding yet
another commanding maitre d' with one of her trademark disguises.
The restaurant critic for The New York Times has just dropped her
son off at school and is on her way to meetings at Gourmet
magazine, where she will take over as editor in chief at the end of
April. In the afternoon, she'll pick up her son, then end the day
in a restaurant. Tomorrow or the next day she'll file one of her
last reviews for the Times.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of this double life, which she finds exhausting,
she'll travel to several cities on a book tour for ``Tender at the
Bone'' (Broadway Books), her memoir that was just released in
paperback. Tomorrow night, Reichl will read from the book _ in
disguise, of course _ at the Brookline Booksmith.
</P>
<P>
   Reichl (pronounced RYE-shul), 51, surprised colleagues in
January with the announcement that she would leave the Times after
5 1/2 years to revamp sleepy Gourmet magazine. Considered one of
the most influential voices in the food world, Reichl writes
reviews that are read as much for lively cultural commentary as for
her dissection of restaurant pretentions. She admits she hardly
glanced at Gourmet when it came across her desk. ``I had to go back
and read old issues,'' she says of the Conde Nast publication,
which has a subscription of 760,000 and newsstand sales of 130,000.
</P>
<P>
   While some restaurateurs find Reichl too critical (this goes
with the territory), others say that she elevated the art of
reviewing with stylish writing and refreshing frankness. Amusing
reports on what happened during her visits invariably include
snippets of overheard conversation _ some of it absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Her most celebrated review occurred early: After poor treatment
(in disguise) at Le Cirque, a temple of cuisine, Reichl returned
looking like herself. ``The King of Spain is waiting at the bar,''
owner Sirio Maccioni told her, ``but your table is ready.'' In the
star-rating system of restaurant reviews, this discrepancy cost Le
Cirque one precious star.
</P>
<P>
   A staff who caters only to the rich will pay a price. ``My
particular bent is that restaurants aren't for the 1 percent who
can afford them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend calls it my misguided populism.''
</P>
<P>
   That populism was honed in Ann Arbor, where she attended the
University of Michigan, and polished in Berkeley, Calif., where she
worked in a restaurant for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Reichl stumbled into reviewing 20 years ago, long before the
nation's interest in food peaked. She worked at New West magazine,
which later became California magazine. After handing in her first
review, an editor told her, ``You were born to do this,'' she
recalls in ``Tender at the Bone.'' From there, she moved to the Los
Angeles Times, where she began as critic and eventually became the
food editor, too.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she arrived in New York in 1993, ``restaurants had
become the icon of the '90s,'' she said. Now, she adds, ``they're
part of the natural conversation because the culture demanded it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her job, in a way, was to entertain. ``Reviews are an odd
combination of service journalism and fantasy journalism,'' she
said. In the same way that readers examine reviews of plays and
films they might never see, they also read about food they'll never
eat. ``People get to have little visits to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't even mind know-it-alls _ the people who study
restaurants and then make sure everyone knows their views. ``It's
much more fun dealing with an educated public,'' she said, ``than
dealing with a stupid public.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reichl began using disguises as a way to remain anonymous in a
city where critics' photographs hang in restaurant kitchens. She
owns many wigs and pairs of glasses, which she combines for a
variety of looks, from sleek to heavy, chic to frumpy. ``They took
on a life of their own,'' she said. ``I was late this morning,''
she said, holding out plain hands. ``I usually do nails.''
</P>
<P>
   It would seem cumbersome to eat when tucked into a costume, but
the critic has made much about the disguises, talking about them on
radio interviews when her book was first published. Yet one diner
who has eaten with Reichl several times contends he has never seen
her in disguise. Reichl says she goes out in disguise about half
the time: ``There's a limit to how long you can stand to be done up
all day. Every restaurant I go to I try to do both to see what kind
of a difference there is. Usually if I go out to a restaurant in
disguise at lunch, I don't (do so at) dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   She also distances herself from the restaurant owners. She
eliminates any difficult conversations with them after her visits
by not talking to anyone at the restaurant. She hired an assistant
to call for details about hours and to book reservations because
New York restaurants-of-the-moment fill early. ``It can take hours
on the phone because they keep you on hold.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no problem filling the table. Her eaters include
``starving artists, friends whose children have already left home,
and childless friends who are always thrilled to have a free
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   When she first began at the Times, she thought it was a plum
assignment. She was dutiful about reporting to work in the Dining
section. ``The first three years I went in all day every day. `This
is such a princess job,' I told myself, `it really behooves you to
show up.' '' She would work until 5 p.m., go home for an hour or so
to see her son, and then go out again. Now she picks him up from
school every day. ``But we don't have family dinners.''
</P>
<P>
   The job, she said, is ``very high pressure. You think, what's so
high pressure about it? But people read these things with such
intensity. You have so much power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
