<SLUG> BC-SEX-MATTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIABETES, OTHER FACTORS MAY TAME SEX DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LOUANNE COLE WESTON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: I've been married four years. For some reason I don't
want sex.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was fine until I went on the pill about one month
before we got married. I noticed an immediate lack of desire but
hoped that it was due to the stress of planning our wedding. But it
never got better.
</P>
<P>
   Even though my husband could (and still can) arouse me to
climax, it has been more work than pleasure. I noticed a
lubrication problem as well, so after six months I quit taking the
pill. I hoped that things would eventually return to normal, but
they haven't.
</P>
<P>
   It's now taking a toll on our marriage since we have sex less
and less frequently. My husband's become closed off emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   Can the pill cause hormone fluctuations that don't easily
correct themselves? I've tested negatively for thyroid dysfunction.
I've heard that the pill can cause low testosterone levels in women
which, in turn, can cause decreased sex drive. My doctor says she's
never tested any women for low testosterone levels. She was
supposed to get back to me but has not.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, this isn't getting any better. The less we have
sex, the more closed off my husband is, the less I want sex. It's
extremely frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Your situation requires some detective work to sort out
the possible cause(s) of your decreased sexual desire. The areas to
consider are: your hormonal levels, your general health and your
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   If you have not already had a thorough physical exam, do so. It
may uncover a condition that would be antagonistic to your sexual
drive. For example, some women experience sexual difficulty with
the onset or full occurrence of diabetes. Decreased lubrication can
be a symptom.
</P>
<P>
   Your physician's reluctance to assess your testosterone level is
unfortunate, but common. This hesitance is based on several
concerns. Physicians are very concerned about masculinization when
it comes to women and testosterone. Rather than carefully monitor
female patients, many physicians choose to avoid the area all
together. Some are not well informed about the normal range of
adult female testosterone levels (20 to 90 nanograms per deciliter
of blood) and unnecessarily worry if a woman's blood level goes to
30.
</P>
<P>
   Though many people acknowledge the connection between sexual
drive and testosterone levels for women, there are those who would
prefer to view female sexual arousal problems as strictly a mental
problem. It's unfortunate that our culture has so rapidly embraced
physiological approaches to enhance male sexual functioning (Viagra
for instance), but drags its feet when it comes to research and
patient access to solutions for females with low sexual drive.
</P>
<P>
   Also unfortunately, the birth control pill formulas that cause
the fewest side effects (such as headaches, irritability, weight
gain) also tend to suppress libido. The good news for you is that
usually when birth control pills are discontinued, women's hormonal
levels tend to resume the pre-pill taking levels in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   That's where we have to take a look at your relationship. When
something physically undermines a person's libido (which the birth
control pill may have done to you), people sometimes also make
mental adjustments in their sexuality to accommodate the physical
change. They may perceive themselves differently.
</P>
<P>
   You may have sown some seeds of sexual disharmony in your
relationship while on the birth control pill that persisted even
after you stopped taking it. Your husband may also have contributed
in some ways to the sexual shutdown that sprang up between you. In
other words, a collection of factors may have influenced you
somewhat simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Get your physical exam, re-ask your physician (or another one)
about a blood test for your testosterone, and consider couples
counseling with your husband before your relationship grows any
further apart. Even in just four years, couples can settle into a
familiarity that is undermining to their mutual sexual enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
   Explore this before you form any long-lasting conclusions about
your relationship.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Weston is a board-certified sex therapist and licensed marriage
and relationship counselor with offices in San Francisco and
Sacramento. Send questions to: Sex Matters, San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
