<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, March 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Belgrade) _ Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy, meets
Solbodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, on the ethnic-Albanian
province of Kosovo. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REPUBS (Washington) _ Henry Kissinger, the former
secretary of state, and Jeane J. Kirkpatrick, the former U.N.
ambassador, help House Republicans start to build a fire against
sending troops to Kosovo. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SALVADOR (San Salvador) _ President Clinton gives a
speech to the El Salvador legislature and leaders of peace effort.
By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUERRILLAS (San Salvador) _ The scene as former
guerrillas listen to Clinton, the leader of their former
imperialist enemy. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-PROTEST (Jerusalem) _ More trouble for Yasser Arafat
as Palestinian security forces kill two teen-agers protesting a
death sentence. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-POLITICS (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Elizabeth Dole announces the
formation of an exploratory committee for a run at the Republican
presidential nomination. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-EDUC (Washington) _ The Senate is to takes a test vote
on the 100,000-new-teachers proposal. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SOCSEC (Washington) _ Republicans discuss an
alternative plan on Social Security. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-SNOW (Washington) _ The new mayor had campaigned on the
promise of improving municipal services here. So last night's giant
snow removal provided a test of that promise. How well did he do?
Pretty well, it seems. Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FBI-INFORMANT (Boston) _ It began in 1995 as a simple
racketeering indictment. Now, however, the case has exploded into
what many call one of the most embarrassing messes for the FBI in
years. And it has called into question a practice at the very heart
of the bureau's operations _ its use of ``confidential informants''
to fight organized crime. The case centers on accusations that
Boston FBI agents protected James Bulger and Stephan Flemmi while
they committed assorted crimes for decades because the two also
provided valuable information about their Italian mobster rivals.
By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DROUGHT (Houston) _ Texas is in a worse position than it
was last year at this time and there is fear that if there is
another drought things will be considerably worse. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-PRIZE (Undated) _ The world's largest monetary prize,
the Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion, will be awarded to
Ian G. Barbour, a physicist and theologian who has spent nearly
four decades working to foster a dialogue between science and
religion. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-STABBING-NEIGHBORHOOD (New York) _ On the mood in Prospect
Heights, a changing neighborhood in Brooklyn where people are
trying to understand the death of a young woman from Kansas, Amy
Watkins, who was knifed in the back in a robbery as she walked to
her apartment. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS (Washington) _ A battle over the nation's
scarcest medical resource, human organs, has moved from Washington
to the states, where a number of legislatures have begun passing
laws that would bar donated hearts, lungs, kidneys, livers and
pancreases from being shipped beyond their borders to sick people
elsewhere in the country. The laws are intended to thwart a new
regulation, put forth by the Clinton administration last spring,
that would force the widespread sharing of donated organs. By
Sheryl Gay Stolberg. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUBBLE-GYROS (Washington) _ Gyroscopes on the Hubble space
telescope are failing more quickly than expected. Rather than one
mission next year, NASA plans to fly a team in October to replace
the gyroscopes, then complete the repairs in 2001. By Warren Leary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Nakanojomachi, Japan) _ Confidence about an economic
recovery is growing in Japan, but the majority view continues to be
that this is just a temporary respite and that the nation still has
not steered a course toward self-sustaining growth. Even so, there
is relief that some progress can be seen. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly economics column: Japan's
monetary policy and what it means to the rest of the world. By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER-NISSAN (Frankfurt, Germany) _ DaimlerChrysler has
abruptly broken off negotiations to acquire a controlling stake in
Nissan Motor, Japan's huge but deeply troubled car manufacturer.
The decision came after face-to-face negotiations in Tokyo between
the chairmen of both companies. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-ASSESS (Tokyo) _ It is back to square one for Nissan,
which is burdened with known debts of more than $20 billion,
declining sales and a cost structure that is high even by Japanese
standards. A news analysis by Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-BANKS (Rome) _ Developments in the unexpected and hostile
bid by Banque Nationale de Paris for two of its biggest French
rivals, Societe Generale and Paribas, which just last month had
agreed to merge. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-BANKS-IMPACT (Undated) _ What a merger of the three
banks, which together have more than $1 trillion in assets, would
mean for global competition. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP (Undated) _ Developments in the RJR Nabisco
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RJR-NABISCO-JAPAN (Tokyo) _ Japan Tobacco's purchase of RJR's
international tobacco business, at a price significantly above what
had been expected, has left some wondering whether the company had
learned any lessons from Japan's last spending spree. By Stephanie
Strom.
</P>
<P>
   DUPONT-STOCK (Undated) _ DuPont plans to issue a tracking stock
for its life-sciences unit to separate the unit from its
more-cyclical businesses. It also says it expects to announce an
alliance in pharmaceuticals by the end of this year. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI-TELECOM (Rome) _ Telecom Italia's board meets to
consider a response to the Olivetti takeover bid. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Brasilia) _ The new chief of Brazil's central bank
meets with foreign journalists. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 11
points and the Nasdaq index was little changed. Elsewhere, prices
rose 2.5 percent in Tokyo and 2.1 percent in Hong Kong. They fell
1.3 percent in Frankfurt, 0.2 percent in London. Prices were up 1.9
percent in Brazil and 1.4 percent in Mexico. On the American debt
market, the long bond was down 11/32 point, with the yield at 5.55
percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
