<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Herbs, spices turn familiar to fantastic
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The discovery and use of herbs and spices by ancient people took
the preparation of food for the purpose of survival to an art form
and a pillar of civilized life. Discovering what tastes certain
dried leaves, seeds or powdered roots imparted to foods was a
process that apparently took place simultaneously all over the
planet and, if nothing else, illustrates mankind's natural urge to
simply add a little spice to life.
</P>
<P>
   There is such a wealth of knowledge about herbs and spices that
one could make a lifetime study of these fascinating plants. And
for eons, people have done just that. In ancient times in many
societies, knowledge of herbs and their uses both in medicine and
in cooking set a person apart as a wise and valued member of the
group. Today, these people are on the Internet. There are many
hundreds of excellent sites where individuals, herb societies and
educational institutions share their collected knowledge for you to
explore.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us cook with the same spices we've used for years. But
by simply discovering a new herb or spice to season an everyday
dish, you can turn the familiar into the exciting. And rather than
spending a lifetime doing it, all this is just a click or two away.
</P>
<P>
   For the novice, the first thing to do is find a good herb chart
_ and there are many. Find one you like and bookmark it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Perhaps the all-round best is
http://www.spiceguide.com/encyclopedia
</P>
<P>
   /encyclopediamain.html, which is nothing less than an
encyclopedia of herbs and spices loaded with information, put forth
in an interesting and understandable format. There are good color
pictures plus recipes and fascinating facts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check out http://www.humorscope.com
</P>
<P>
   /herbs/herbs.html. It has an herb and spice index, recipes, tips
on growing your own, history, geography and more. Here, for
instance, you will find that caraway has been cultivated for at
least 5,000 years. Hungarian herdsmen used the seeds to flavor
their goulash, Germans flavored pork with it and the Swedish put
the seeds in bread. There are growing instructions and a recipe for
caraway yogurt biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Another good site for a chart is
http://foodlines.com/foodgallery
</P>
<P>
   /culinaryessentials/spiceupyourlife
</P>
<P>
   .html. There is also a short but excellent course on the
difference between seasonings and flavorings, often confused
because both are usually used in the final steps of a dish.
</P>
<P>
   Flavoring changes the taste of the dish by adding a new flavor,
while seasoning brings out the flavor that is already there. You
can cook for a lifetime and never learn this kind of thing outside
of a cooking school.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You also will not want to miss the essential information
offered at http://aries27.uwaterloo.ca/(tilde)dmg/faqs
</P>
<P>
   /spices/spices.html, ``Flavoring the World _ Frequently Asked
Questions About Spices.'' First, learn the difference between herbs
and spices. Herbs come from the leafy part of the plant and spices
can be seeds, bark or other parts of plants _ even the same plant
an herb comes from. (Raise your hand if you didn't know.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Another good chart that includes dishes that the herb or spice
goes with is at http://CNN.com/HEALTH/indepth.food
</P>
<P>
   /herbs/chart.html.
</P>
<P>
   After you have digested all that and are ready to try it out in
the kitchen, check these sites for recipes:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.recipe-a-day.com/herbs
</P>
<P>
   .html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.citipage.com/wjac/hk8.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.geocities.com/Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   /Set/6265/Nats.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.wholeherb.com/index
</P>
<P>
   a.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.charlotte.com/observer
</P>
<P>
   /food/recipes/recs0507.htm.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Green Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 7 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This sauce is delicious served over steaming-hot vegetables or
pasta. It can be made a day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (8 ounces) sour cream
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup (1 ounce) grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon each fresh, finely chopped basil, parsley, mint,
chives, tarragon, oregano and lemon thyme
</P>
<P>
   Combine sour cream, butter, nutmeg and cayenne pepper in a
saucepan and simmer for 3 to 5 minutes. Beat the cheese and basil,
parsley, mint, chives, tarragon, oregano and lemon thyme into
sauce. Reheat to melt cheese and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 42 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 90), 1 gram carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 41 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Roast Pork Loin Stuffed With Dried Apricots,
</P>
<P>
   Shallots and Sage
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings Preparation time: 45 minutes Cooking time: 2
hours
</P>
<P>
   The musky flavor of fresh sage offsets the sweetness of the
fruit, yielding a melange that perfectly accents the pork. This is
an elegant main course that also is great at room temperature,
perhaps for a picnic.
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons canola oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried apricots, cut in 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   4 green onions, cut in 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   2 cups orange juice, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups coarse dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, lightly beaten, or 1/2 cup egg substitute
</P>
<P>
   4- to 5-pound boneless pork loin, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet over medium-high heat, heat 2 tablespoons canola
oil. Stir in apricots, shallots, green onions, raisins and sage.
Cook for about 2 minutes, or until the sage is fragrant. Stir in
the brandy and simmer for 1 minute. Stir in 1 cup orange juice,
bring to a boil, lower heat to medium and reduce liquid by
one-third. Remove from heat and stir in bread crumbs. Let cool.
Stir in eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the pork loin in half lengthwise, leaving one side attached.
Fold open and cut out a trough about 1 inch deep and 2 inches wide
in center of each half. Fill the troughs with the bread crumb
mixture. Fold the two halves together and tie with kitchen string.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 2 tablespoons oil in a large ovenproof
skillet or roasting or baking pan over high heat. Add the pork loin
and brown on all sides. Pour in remaining 1 cup orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to oven and cook for 10 minutes. Reduce heat to 350
degrees. Basting every 20 minutes, cook for 1 1/2 hours. Remove
from oven and let stand for 10 minutes. Cut in 1-inch slices and
serve with the pan juices. _ From ``The Herbal Palate Cookbook'' by
Maggie Oster and Sal Gilbertie (Storey Publishing, 1996)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with eggs): 421 calories, 36 grams protein, 13
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 27), 40 grams carbohydrates,
132 milligrams cholesterol, 114 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
