<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soup recipe pops in from Gatlinburg
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Phil Panuska didn't have to wait long for a popcorn
soup recipe he requested for his wife, Tamara. She had enjoyed the
soup at a restaurant in Gatlinburg, Tenn., he said, and he had been
unsuccessful tracking down the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, the manager of the Magnolia Tea Room at
Eight Gables Inn in Gatlinburg, where Tamara had the soup, came
through with the recipe. Cindy Black said it's a favorite there,
too, and it's often on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon parsley flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (15 1/4 ounces each) whole kernel corn, drained
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Popped popcorn for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter in a large saucepan over medium heat. Saute onion
and parsley flakes in butter until onion is tender, about 8
minutes. Sprinkle flour over mixture and stir (mixture will be
lumpy). Gradually add half-and-half, stirring until you have a
smooth, creamy mixture. Add drained corn. Cook until slightly
thickened and soup is hot, about 5 minutes more. Add salt and
pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, pour soup into bowls and garnish with popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 502 calories, 10 grams protein, 40 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 72), 30 grams carbohydrates, 120
milligrams cholesterol, 251 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Penny Wahl seeks a recipe for a chocolate cake made with
Kahlua. ``It is the best cake you've ever tasted, but I can't find
a recipe anywhere,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I am looking for a recipe for creamed codfish. My
grandmother used salted cod that came in a wood box. She soaked the
fish overnight to remove the salt, creamed it and served over
mashed potatoes. Good stuff!,'' says J. Palermo of Marietta (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
