<HEADER>
A5106 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PFEIFFER-DEEP-END-LAD     03-10 1627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PFEIFFER-DEEP-END-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEEP END' GRIPPED PFEIFFER THAN NO OTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By   BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Michelle Pfeiffer bought the movie rights to
Jacquelyn Mitchard's novel ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' before it
became Oprah's Book Club's first phenomenal best seller. Before
millions were shocked and moved by its tale of a family's struggle
to cope after a child goes missing. Before it was even published.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like a good idea at the time, and it probably was. But
even when she first read the pre-publication draft, the
actress-producer had a good inkling of how tough making and
starring in the movie version was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't put it down, and then I had to put it down, if you
know what I mean,'' says the 40-year-old Pfeiffer, known almost as
well for the acting challenges she takes on (``Married to the
Mob,'' ``The Age of Innocence,'' ``Love Field,'' ``The Fabulous
Baker Boys'') as for her classic movie-star beauty.
</P>
<P>
   We do know what she means. ``Ocean's'' protagonist, Beth
Cappadora, loses Ben, the second of her three little children, in a
crowded hotel lobby. For nine agonizing years, she and her husband,
Pat (Treat Williams in the movie), their oldest son Vincent (played
as a teen-ager by ``General Hospital's'' Jonathan Jackson) and
their daughter, Kerry (Alexa Vega), struggle to keep the remnants
of their family functional.
</P>
<P>
   When Ben re-enters their lives, he's a 12-year-old (Ryan
Merriman of the TV series ``The Pretender'') who now goes by the
name Sam and has no recollection of the Cappadoras. This triggers a
whole new set of heartbreaks.
</P>
<P>
   Playing Beth was a harrowing assignment, especially for an
actress with two small children of her own. But doing justice to
Beth's complex story and character _ the novel ran 447 pages _ in a
movie that runs less than two hours was an even more formidable
task.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book was so full, we couldn't possibly get all of it in,''
Pfeiffer explains. ``We had many, many different versions of the
script. Vincent got into a lot more trouble in the book. Beth and
Pat behaved even worse, did all kinds of bad stuff to each other,
had affairs and everything. It was all wonderful and it was rich;
that's what I loved about the book, it painted such a truly, truly
realistic view of how people are.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, the hard thing, when you go to make a movie, is to bring
as many of those colors as you can to it. At the same time, you
can't possibly give all the background information or all the
nuances. So, sometimes, audiences don't understand what motivates
the characters, and they end up just not liking them. It was a very
delicate balance to find.''
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that it's a very different thing from her book,
Mitchard says she likes the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have known that parts were missing if I hadn't
written it,'' she explains. ``There's, like, a cast of thousands in
the book, and that would've been impossible in a film. It's a much
more linear form; it doesn't go back and forth and around the way
that a book can do. There just wasn't enough space.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, essentially, the story's emotional content survives in
the movie,'' adds the author, a mother of five who wrote her first
novel after her husband of 13 years succumbed to cancer. ``It makes
you ask questions about what makes up people's bonds with each
other in the way that you should ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, those unfamiliar with the book may wonder why
Candy, the Chicago detective in charge of the missing boy's case,
announces to Beth for no apparent reason that she's a lesbian. This
is significant in the novel, where Candy is a more significant
character (and is also a white woman; Whoopi Goldberg plays her in
the film).
</P>
<P>
   Readers, on the other hand, are going to wonder what became of
Vincent's psychiatrist, a major presence on the page who does not
even appear on screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't like psychiatrist stuff in movies,'' says
screenwriter and former film critic Stephen Schiff. ``In general,
shrinks in movies are about telling, not showing. Good movies are
about showing.''
</P>
<P>
   While decisions such as this were certainly discussed with
director Ulu Grosbard, Pfeiffer and her producing partner Kate
Guinzburg, Schiff explains that he felt no pressure to increase the
star's film presence at the expense of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a famous story about one actor: If you're ever in a
conflict with them, you're supposed to say `Don't you realize this
is your scene?''' Schiff jokes. ``Michelle is not that in any way,
shape or form. When you talk to her about a scene her character is
not in, she brings the same precision and insight. She gets movies,
she gets details, she understands story; and she does it from a
completely unactorish point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer gives an example of how, when it came time to shoot the
kind of extravagant scene that actors crave, it had to be
sacrificed for the sake of the overall show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really fine-tuning all the way, first in the writing of
the script and then, as we were shooting, discovering things,''
Pfeiffer says. ``For instance, in the novel, she gets really drunk
in the hotel and throws up all over the place. That was in the
script, but when it came time to do it, we thought it might not be
a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, in that situation, it's not anything I would do,
though I guess some people would. But if you don't know the
character, you would think she had a drinking problem. She didn't,
but we weren't able to give you enough about Beth in the beginning
for you to know that, so it was best just to leave it out. I would
never want to diminish a character just because she unnerved people
_ I think that's a good thing. But you had to let go of things that
you felt would confuse the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer also had to let go of a replacement ending she felt
would improve on the one Grosbard originally shot. That delayed the
film's release from last fall to this Friday, but it did not play
any better. The movie is coming out with Grosbard's ending.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this episode, the director describes working with the
star-producer in glowing terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a certain amount of confidence and trust between
us,'' says Grosbard, an acclaimed Broadway director (``The Subject
Was Roses'') who's made such distinctive films as ``Straight Time''
and ``True Confessions.'' ``On the second day of shooting, Michelle
had to tape this demanding, emotional television appeal. She just
walked in, sat down and was right there. She was so full, out of
nowhere, and that's very difficult to do. There were no other
actors for her to build with, she was on her own.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer admits that the material had a special resonance for
her. She and her husband, television producer David E. Kelley, have
a 6-year-old adopted daughter, Claudia Rose (their other child,
John, is 4). And the point of the story, which gradually emerges in
both book and film, is that emotional connections can be as strong
as blood ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our situation is a lot different than the one in this movie,''
she explains. ``But before I ever even became a parent, I'd read
stories about things like this happening, and so much of the time
the resolution was not geared toward what was in the best interest
of the child. I think it has to be about the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always complicated, and there are always extenuating
circumstances,'' she continues. ``This is a movie about people
redefining themselves individually, in relationship to each other
and as family. And I think it's different for everyone. I don't
think our traditional sense of family always applies to people.
It's not always biological or genetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Producing, however, is not a family affair. Pfeiffer's Via Rosa
Productions had a hand in her blockbuster hit ``Dangerous Minds,''
and the not-so-successful ``One Fine Day'' and ``A Thousand
Acres,'' before taking on ``Deep End.'' Although Kelley has had
remarkable success on television with ``Ally McBeal,'' ``The
Practice,'' ``Chicago Hope,'' ``Picket Fences'' and ``L.A. Law,''
Pfeiffer notes that her husband is ``way too smart'' to give her
advice she doesn't ask for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really spend our time talking about work much,'' she
continues. ``There are so many things to focus on about the family
and the kids that we just never get there. I mean, I never know
what he's doing half the time. Probably, if I read the trades, I
would learn a lot about my husband!''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer is learning more and more about filmmaking with each
new movie that she produces. Not all of it is great. There was no
doubt that Oprah Winfrey would have liked to produce the movie
version of her first book club selection. Pfeiffer addresses
whatever friction that might have caused gingerly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never talked to her personally, and anything I ever heard
about Oprah was always kind of third-hand,'' Pfeiffer says. ``I
know that she expressed a lot of interest, and she did a lot for
the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer adds that an appearance on ``Oprah'' was discussed, but
the actress's busy work schedule _ she plays Titania in a film
version of Shakespeare's ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' coming out
in May, and is shooting the marital comedy ``The Story of Us'' with
Bruce Willis _ did not permit it.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever distress, professional or emotional, that making
``Deep End of the Ocean'' caused, Pfeiffer says it was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some weeks when things were a little more difficult
and trying,'' she says of the demanding adaptation and performing
processes. ``But because the process was pretty much an enjoyable
one, I really went home feeling purged in a way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
