<P>
   EMERGING-ARCHITECTS (Undated) _ Eight architectural firms were
selected this year as ``emerging voices'' of 1999 by the
Architectural League of New York, a nonprofit organization that has
sponsored public programs in architecture since 1881. But rising
stars need more than a winning way with a T-square _ or a
state-of-the-art CAD program _ to make a name for themselves. The
simplest projects require a fanatical commitment and Job-like
patience. This year's winners offer a telling glimpse of the state
of architecture _ a mirror of how it is being built today and a
window onto the world of the next century. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   FALLINGWATER (Bear Run, Pa.) _ Fallingwater, Frank Lloyd
Wright's 1936 masterpiece, acknowledged by architects to be the
most significant American building, appears to be falling down.
When this weekend house slung over a waterfall opened here last
week for its annual season of public tours, visitors were treated
to the sight of a bathtub-sized hole in the middle of the living
room floor. The house, a series of intersecting concrete trays,
has, in fact, been sagging; one corner, hanging over the falls, is
more than seven inches lower than it should be. The problem, which
threatened to bring Fallingwater crashing into the rocks below, has
led to a top-to-bottom analysis of the building's structure. By
Fred Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   PIPHER-PROFILE (Lincoln, Neb.) _ Mary Pipher, the psychologist
whose book about adolescent girls, ``Reviving Ophelia,'' was a
phenomenal best seller, was walking on the prairie near her home at
sunset, showing off the quiet beauty of winter in Nebraska. She
walks here with her women's writers' group on weekends, she says,
and it is where she likes to celebrate New Year's Day. She walked
on the prairie a lot during the 11 months her mother lay dying in a
hospital in Kansas five years ago. This is the landscape,
undramatic and Midwestern, that has shaped her life and thinking,
and landscape is the metaphor she uses to explore aging in her new
book, ``Another Country: The Emotional Terrain of Our Elders,''
which will be published next week. As in ``Reviving Ophelia'' which
is as much a social critique as it is a psychological treatise, Dr.
Pipher, 51, views aging through the lens of the anthropologist she
set out to be in college. A profile of the writer by Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   NY-OLD-SIGNS (New York) _ You can't miss it. At the corner of
Greene and West Houston Streets, a new billboard for G-Shock
watches partially obscures an early 20th-century sign for the
United Thread Company. A giant wristwatch, splayed across both
advertising panels, appears to be attached to the building by
trompe l'oeil nails. But is the old sign really old? Or is it new,
too? Such questions crop up often these days, as New York's
construction boom alternately exposes and covers old signs:
advertisements for carriage rentals and patent medicines painted on
brick walls previously hidden by buildings. They appear suddenly,
flashes of the past, when a building is razed. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   HOPPEN-DESIGN (Undated) _ Lionized in Britain but largely
unknown here, Kelly Hoppen has seen the future, and it is beige,
accented with sorbet-sweet shots of aubergine, blackberry and
lilac. The future is also sculptured with concealed, expensively
calibrated light. By Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SEX-MUSEUM (New York) _ When was the last time you loved a
building and it loved you back? This month, the Museum of Sex, or
Mosex, begins sweeping the floor of its new temporary home at 233
Fifth Avenue (27th Street), beneath the shadow of the Empire State
Building, in anticipation of renovations that will deliver a new
facade, 12,000 square feet of exhibition galleries and offices, a
retail shop and a cafe by the end of the year. Mosex _ at the other
end of the block from Le Trapeze, a towels-only night club _ is an
adult museum, the first in the United States to be devoted to ``sex
and culture everywhere,'' said Alison Maddex, 32, its director.
``It's going to be the Smithsonian of sex,'' she added. By William
L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
