<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5114 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIRED-FUTURE-HNS &LR;      03-10 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRED-FUTURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRED DIGITAL FACES RESTIVE INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Twin investor uprisings _ one an open battle,
the other an underground movement _ could affect the financial
future of Wired Digital, a pioneering San Francisco Web company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the aftershocks of Tuesday's resignation by a key
board member of the giant Lycos Web site may hamper that company's
acquisition of Wired Digital, which has itself been the subject of
a reported revolt by investors.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, David Wetherell, chief executive officer of the
Andover, Mass.-based Internet marketing company CMGI Inc., resigned
from the board of Lycos Inc., which is in the final stages of
acquiring Wired Digital. CMGI is Lycos' largest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell contends that Lycos' pending acquisition by Barry
Diller's USA Networks Inc. would inadequately compensate current
Lycos investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``After further consideration, it is my opinion that the terms
of the USA/Lycos transaction are inadequate for Lycos
shareholders,'' Wetherell said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   According to observers, the Lycos/USA Networks spat could
further complicate the pending Lycos-Wired Digital deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could very well be a ripple effect,'' said James
Preissler, an Internet analyst with PaineWebber in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Lycos management will surely be focused on (the USA
Network acquisition) and could easily get distracted from the Wired
Digital deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will come down to how management will be able to handle two
big projects like this,'' added Dalton Chandler, analyst with
Needham &AMP; Co. in New York. ``I mean, how many big projects can
Lycos executives devote themselves to?''
</P>
<P>
   Key to navigating these two controversies, Preissler said, will
be the ability of shareholders and others to ``play nice'' during
these acquisitions. And nice is not a game some want to play.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports first published last month in Boston
newspapers, shareholders at Wired Digital have hired attorneys,
with the possible intention of launching lawsuits that could block
the Lycos-Wired Digital deal. Lycos and Wired Digital officials
maintain the deal is solid, however.
</P>
<P>
   Wired Digital shareholders, including founders Louis Rosetto and
Jane Metcalf, are reportedly miffed over how Lycos shares will be
apportioned among various classes of Wired Digital stockholders.
Rosetto and Metcalf could not be reached for comment on these
reports.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports and documents filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, original Wired Digital investors holding A
class shares are subject to restrictions that give later B and C
class investors a larger stake of the incoming Lycos stock.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, according to SEC filings and reports, Wired Digital
chief executive Beth Vanderslice and other top executives were
issued hefty stock options that might dilute share worth for other
stockholders, including Wired Digital employees lured and retained
by the promise of stock options.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's created some very interesting morale dynamics around
here,'' said one longtime Wired Digital employee, one of six
interviewed, all of whom asked not to have their names published.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew de Vries, a Wired Digital spokesman, said it was
full-steam ahead for the Lycos-Wired Digital deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies remain fully committed to completing this
deal,'' de Vries said. ``According to Bob Davis (the Lycos chief
executive), he's absolutely committed to completing this deal.''
</P>
<P>
   De Vries said talk of a torpedoed merger was ``weak
speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good deal for Lycos,'' de Vries said, and Wired
Digital ``is a key part of the Lycos network.''
</P>
<P>
   Wired Digital is the on-line remnant of the Wired Ventures
empire, which was carved up when the print magazine Wired was sold
to Conde Nast a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Lycos announced it was going to acquire the Wired
Digital properties, which include the bombastic Suck.Com Web site
and the heavily advertised HotBot search engine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
