<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BEAUTY-0311-CO     03-10 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BEAUTY-0311-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THERE SHE IS: THE NEW MISS ISRAEL IS MEMBER OF ARAB MINORITY
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ She wears the sequins, sash and gleaming smile of
beauty queens the world over, but no one should take the new Miss
Israel at face value.
</P>
<P>
   Crowned Tuesday night, 21-year-old Rana Raslan is the first Arab
ever to win the Miss Israel pageant. A Muslim, she will represent
the Jewish state in the Miss World contest late this year.
</P>
<P>
   She is one of nearly a million Arab Israelis -- distinct from
the neighboring Palestinians in that they are Israeli citizens and
within the recognized borders of Israel, rather than the disputed,
occupied areas. Though facing high rates of poverty and
unemployment, the Arab Israelis have slowly increased in numbers
and acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Raslan's photo, with her crown set atop her long, dark curls,
was on the front of Israel's major dailies Wednesday and she seemed
to scramble the region's religious and ethnic lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I belong to Israel. I'm Israeli Arab,'' the exhausted beauty
queen told the Cox News Service in a telephone interview from a
party in her home in Haifa Wednesday. ``We must, the Jewish and the
Arabs, live like brothers. We must show all the world we can live
together.''
</P>
<P>
   A legal secretary, who speaks Arabic, Hebrew and English, Raslan
wants to eventually become a teacher. But, Wednesday was filled
with photo sessions, interviews and comparisons to her predecessor,
a Jewish Israeli who won the Miss World title last November.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits here note that beauty pageants pale in importance in a
land of periodic war and terrorism. But, Raslan's victory was
seized upon by politicians and commentators from Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, who called the choice a ``a clear expression of
equality,'' to a pageant judge who called it a peace gesture to the
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   Most acknowledge that Raslan was, if nothing else, a sign of
Israel's increasingly multi-cultural make up -- a Jewish Ethiopian
Israeli also made history Tuesday by taking second place -- as well
a small triumph for the sizeable Arab minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a creeping recognition. It is very limited and still
not the norm, and not rooted in Israeli political culture,'' said
Majid Al-Haj, an Arab Israeli who heads Haifa University's Center
for Multi-Culturalism.
</P>
<P>
   He said Israeli Arabs are seeking integration into Israeli
society more than ever and could change Israel's identity as the
Zionist, Jewish state. Jews, in turn, he said are slowly starting
to recognize Arab rights.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-sixth of the six million Israelis living here are
Arabs, either Muslims or Christians. Unlike the 2.5 million
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, the families of Arab
Israelis did not flee or get forced out of Israel when neighboring
Arab nations attacked in 1948. Some Israeli Arabs prefer to call
themselves Palestinians or ``Arab citizens of Israel'' rather than
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish and Arab neighborhoods in Israel are segregated, and
Israeli Arabs complain that they receive only a fraction of the
services of Jewish sectors.
</P>
<P>
   But, they have generally the same legal rights, including the
right to vote and hold public office. An Arab Israeli recently
became the first Arab appointed to a nine-month term on the Israeli
supreme court(CQ lower case).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
