<HEADLINE>
BIG NAME HUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By BARBARA MATUSOW  
 FROM: Washingtonian  
 &HT;    They'll try almost anything. Like the time Barbara Walters found
out that William Ginsburg, then Monica Lewinsky's lawyer, couldn't
get bran flakes for lunch at the Cosmos Club. Walters quickly
hopped a plane from New York with his favored food. Katie Couric
once sent skater Tonya Harding's lawyer a cake frosted with the
words WE REFUSE TO STOP SUCKING UP.
 &HT;    As TV talk shows and newsmagazines proliferate, the pursuit of
``gets,'' as high-profile interviewees are known in the business,
is reaching such a fever pitch that some anchors and reporters
wonder what kind of business they are in.
 &HT;    ``We all collectively find it repulsive,'' says ``20/20's''
Connie Chung. ``It's made reporting so much harder because we are
spending half our time booking instead of reporting.''
 &HT;    ``It's something I'm not comfortable with,'' ``60 Minutes''' Ed
Bradley confesses. ``But it's unavoidable.''
 &HT;    The competition isn't likely to cool down. If anything, it
promises to get worse. ``20/20'' has expanded to four nights a
week. ``Dateline NBC'' now puts on five shows a week, while ``60
Minutes'' has expanded to a second hour. Add to that the three
24-hour all-news networks _ MSNBC, Fox and CNN _ and consider that
CNN alone books 12,000 interviews a year. Stir in ``Hard Copy,''
``Inside Edition,'' Oprah, Jay Leno, David Letterman, Charlie Rose,
Leeza, Roseanne and Don Imus, and you have a recipe for insanity.
 &HT;    ``I was away from television for almost 2-1/2 years,'' Chung
says, ``and when I came back, I found the competition much worse.
Before, the arena was pretty much limited to big-name 'gets.' Now
it's spread to the kind of stories you find on the back pages of a
newspaper.
 &HT;    ``Just about any story we think about doing, whether we've read
it in a newspaper, heard it on the radio or come upon it through
word of mouth _ by the time you get there, every other network,
cable station and talk show is already racing to the scene.''
 &HT;    When the trophy is big enough, even the biggest names in
television are forced to hold their noses and pursue hookers,
felons, even convicted murderers. But most of the day-to-day work
in the guest-getting sweepstakes is done by segment producers, or
bookers, as they are known. Most are women, and they are pretty
intense, waging warlike campaigns to land the really elusive
guests.
 &HT;    Carol Ross Joynt, who used to be a booker for Larry King, spent
more than a year helping nail down Al Pacino, who was No. 1 on
King's wish list. ``I sent flowers on his birthday,'' Joynt says.
``I would send flowers on the announcement of a new movie. I made
friends with his assistant. I wrote intelligent-sounding but
fawning letters. When he appeared in a play in New York, I got
Larry good seats down front and made arrangements to go backstage
afterward. Finally, after a long telephone call that Larry placed
to Al, he agreed to come on.''
 &HT;    One producer tells about the scene outside the courtroom in Los
Angeles the day the O.J. Simpson verdict was announced. Every TV
and print outlet in the country was trying to get reaction from
Nicole Simpson's sisters and mother, who were being escorted
through the jammed hallway to a waiting elevator.
 &HT;    Suddenly a booker from ABC reared back and hurled his cell phone
50 feet across the top of the crowd, screaming ``Denise.''
Amazingly, Denise Brown caught the phone. Later, the booker, who
was working for Diane Sawyer, called his number on the cell phone,
reached Brown and got the interview for Sawyer.
 &HT;    Mostly, success is a matter of patience, persistence and charm.
``Does their manner help? Absolutely,'' says Susan Carpenter
McMillan, who fields interview requests for presidential accuser
Paula Jones. ``Larry King's people are wonderful. John Gibson's
people are wonderful. High pressure does not play nearly as well.
When they tell me, 'We have the highest ratings' or 'We'll get
Paula's story out there the way she wants to get it out,' I find
that insulting.''
 &HT;    ``These young bookers have learned to say things like 'It will
make my career' or 'I'll get a big raise,''' says Linda Tripp's
friend Lucianne Goldberg, who was in demand as a stand-in for Tripp
when the Lewinsky scandal broke. ``How can you turn them down?''
 &HT;    The Lewinsky scandal focused a lot of attention on Washington
``gets.'' Tops on everyone's list was Lewinsky. Once it was
announced that she was giving the first interview to Walters, the
scramble did not stop as producers fought tooth and nail for the
right to the second interview with her.
 &HT;    Tripp, Ken Starr, Vernon Jordan and other players in the Clinton
drama also have been the subjects of heavy wooing. ``I have talked
to Linda Tripp half a dozen times at least,'' Mike Wallace says.
``I never promised to make her America's sweetheart, but I did tell
her, 'Look, if you decide you're going to do it, everybody is going
to ask you the same questions, Linda. You and I had a good
chemistry (when they had dinner at L'Auberge Chez Francois.) There
were five of us there. We all sat around and shot the breeze. We
had a drink, then another drink, and if you do that, it naturally
establishes a chemistry.''
 &HT;    At ABC, over the years, the brass have been trying, mostly
without success, to level the playing field between Sawyer and
Walters, but Walters continues to rack up the big ones _ Ted
Kennedy after Chappaquiddick, Michael J. Fox on his Parkinson's
disease, Colin Powell, Christopher Reeve, Elizabeth Taylor, John
Hinckley's parents, Muhammad Ali, Margaret Thatcher, Vaclav Havel
and every American president since Richard Nixon.
 &HT;    The Walters treatment includes everything from flowers, fruit
and charming notes to tea and cookies at her Fifth Avenue apartment
in New York. Her biggest selling points are her empathetic manner
and the big audiences she delivers. But she is also famously
aggressive in pursuit of her quarry.
 &HT;    During the 1992 presidential campaign, her colleague Donaldson
had lined up back-to-back interviews with Bill Clinton, George Bush
and Ross Perot on the same program. At the last minute, Perot
backed out. He had been contacted by Walters, who reminded him of
an earlier promise to give her the first interview.
 &HT;    Another time, Sawyer was getting ready to tape an interview with
Katharine Hepburn. Suddenly, Hepburn took a call from Walters, who
told her to hold everything: She would be right over to do the
interview herself.
 &HT;    Sawyer has been no slouch in getting guests. She did the first
interviews with Tonya Harding, Michael Jackson and Lisa Marie
Presley, Marla Maples, caning victim Michael Fay, O.J. detective
Mark Fuhrman, newly outed Ellen DeGeneres and the family of Nicole
Brown Simpson, whom she interviewed three times.
 &HT;    Sawyer's presence has done wonders for the guest roster since
she began cohosting ``Good Morning America.'' Still, she finds it
hard to compete with Walters' Rolodex. Yet when Sawyer's contract
came up in 1994, and the other networks were offering her the moon,
she chose to stay at ABC. A big factor in her decision, it was
said, was the creation of a central booking unit meant to keep
ABC's magazine shows from competing with one another.
 &HT;    ``What I couldn't stand was that I was making phone calls on
stories (for ``PrimeTime Live''), ``Day One'' was making phone
calls on stories, ``20/20'' was making phone calls _ it was crazy,
taking all our time doing this,'' Sawyer told an interviewer.
 &HT;    She has a point. One person who kept a log of calls _ the
public-relations executive hired by the parents of child beauty
JonBenet Ramsey _ was overwhelmed, not just by the number of calls
but by the number of different people from the same network who
contacted him.
 &HT;    According to Chung, who wrote a paper on the business of
``gets'' while she was a fellow at Harvard, the executive got 23
calls from ABC News staffers in one month. He also reported getting
18 calls from CBS News, 20 from NBC News _ not counting CNBC and
MSNBC _ 22 from CNN and ``Larry King Live,'' nine from Fox, plus
assorted pleas from ``Inside Edition,'' ``Hard Copy,'' Don Imus and
others.
 &HT;    The new booking unit at ABC was supposed to eliminate in-house
competition, making sure that both Sawyer and Walters got their
share of trophy guests. In fact, insiders say, the unit never
really worked. It couldn't function without Walters' cooperation,
and she refused to play ball.
 &HT;    After Westin assumed the helm of ABC News, he too fell under
Sawyer's spell. ``David positively lights up when she walks in the
room,'' a corporate source says. ``When Diane sets her sights on
dazzling someone, rarely if ever do I see a man, a powerful man,
fail to succumb. They just flop right over.''
 &HT;    Westin came up with a new solution to the Walters/Sawyer
competition: He merged ``PrimeTime Live,'' Sawyer's showcase, with
Walters' ``20/20.'' At the same time, he personally intervened on
Sawyer's behalf to get a hotly pursued interview with Kenneth
Starr. Westin committed to doing a full hour with him _ -something
``20/20's'' chief rival, ``60 Minutes,'' virtually never does.
 &HT;    Starr also wanted the interview to take place right after he
finished testifying before the House Judiciary Committee in
November. Westin offered Starr the Wednesday before Thanksgiving, a
night he said had a large viewing audience, and he pledged to
promote the interview.
 &HT;    Starr's appearance drew an audience of nearly 15 million people,
but the interview did not go as his people hoped, even though he
spent four hours taping with Sawyer. Starr's friends complain that
Sawyer was overly adversarial, that her questions were too long,
that his answers were cut down to snippets.
 &HT;    Journalists who watched the interview probably saw nothing amiss
in the way Sawyer conducted the interview. But other players may
have drawn some cautionary lessons from Starr's appearance.
``People are becoming more sophisticated about live vs. taped,''
says Gail Evans, who oversees the booking operation at CNN. ``You
hear them say, 'I'm only going to do live interviews, where I'm
sure of the way my answers will be used.'''
 &HT;    The reaction to Sawyer's piece on Starr illustrates the line
anchors and reporters have to walk if they want to bag the biggest
game. Those who have a reputation for being too prosecutorial often
lose out.
 &HT;    ``Does it hamstring me? I'm sure that it does,'' says tough guy
Wallace. ``It gets frustrating when I hear people have said, 'Oh,
good Lord, you're going to be interviewed by whom?' In one way,
it's flattering, I suppose. On the other hand, it's a myth.
Everybody asks the same questions. They just ask them in different
ways.''
 &HT;    If interviewers are perceived as going too easy, they risk
taking a shellacking in the press. That's what happened to Ed
Bradley after his ``60 Minutes'' interview with Kathleen Willey,
the woman who claimed to have been groped by President Clinton.
During the interview, Bradley gently led her through her story,
never asking her whether she had pursued a book deal (she had) or
if she remained friendly with Clinton after the alleged incident
(she did). Bradley was even criticized by friends of Willey's, who
complained that if he had been tougher, she wouldn't have been open
to so much White House-inspired criticism in the press afterward.
 &HT;    These days, professional handlers keep score for their clients,
and woe unto the journalist or talk-show host who says something
perceived as unfriendly. At one point, Walters was making headway
with her request to interview Paula Jones. But she lost the chance
after a panelist on Walters' syndicated show made an unflattering
remark about McMillan, Jones' spokeswoman.
 &HT;    ``One of the things I believe in strongly,'' McMillan says:
``You really pay back your friends and punish your enemies. It will
be a cold day in hell before Paula does any of the late-night
shows. After all the cruel things they said about her, comparing
her nose to a penis, they can just forget it!''
 &HT;    The one thing nobody on either side of the transaction wants to
talk about is the deals that are made. In exchange for getting the
first interview, broadcasters routinely allow celebrities and other
public figures to dictate the terms of their appearance. ``The
length of the segment is open to discussion, the areas of
questioning can be limited, as well as which of the personalities
or reporters will actually do the interview,'' says Random House
publicist Stuart Applebaum. ``But most of all the timing is
important.''
 &HT;    Timing was a big issue with Lewinsky, who was not paid for her
interview with Walters but had an understanding with ``20/20'' that
the interview would coincide with the release of her book. She also
retained the rights to the proceeds from any sales of the Walters
interview to foreign broadcasters. While that feature of her
agreement with Walters was a little unusual, the promotional
interview, in which celebrities tout their latest movie, book or TV
appearance, has become so standard that even the critics have
stopped bemoaning the naked commercialism of the transactions.
 &HT;    Occasionally, questions are raised about deals that go beyond
mere commercialism. Tom Rosenstiel reported in Esquire that one of
the figures in the 1989 Menendez brothers' murder trial told ABC
the story had to have a positive tone and demanded script approval.
ABC capitulated on both counts, according to Rosenstiel.
 &HT;    On one point, the established outlets are firm: They don't pay
for interviews. However, foreign broadcasters do: Britain's Channel
4 is paying Lewinsky an estimated $640,000 for its interview.
Domestic syndicated shows such as ``Inside Edition,'' ``Hard Copy''
and ``Roseanne'' also pay. Such shows are said to have showered
hundreds of thousands of dollars on friends, employees and
relatives of Michael Jackson's for information about him when he
was being accused of pedophilia.
 &HT;    Money occasionally rears its head at the Fox network as well.
Although Fox has denied paying Earl Spencer, Princess Diana's
brother, for its exclusive interview with him, he reportedly got
$600,000 for home movies and still photos of his sister.
 &HT;    About the only thing the networks and shows such as ``Oprah''
will pay for are airfare, meals and hotel rooms. And in hotly
competitive situations, the subjects may receive small ``tokens of
esteem.'' ''You get flowers, candy,'' Lucianne Goldberg says.
``Nothing you wouldn't get from a nice first date.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Washingtonian  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Barbara Matusow is senior editor at Washingtonian and the
author of ``The Evening Stars,'' a book about TV news anchors.) &LR;
