<HEADER>
A5149 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-SANCTIONS-PEOPLE     03-10 2316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SANCTIONS-PEOPLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUST THE IRAQI PEOPLE BE PUNISHED FOR SADDAM'S EVIL? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MATTHEW ROTHSCHILD  
 FROM: The Progressive  
 &HT;    You probably have heard of Scott Ritter, the UNSCOM weapons
inspector _ and former U.S. Marine _ who resigned his post last
August to protest what he saw as the failure of the United States
to act more forcefully against Saddam Hussein's weapons of mass
destruction.
 &HT;    But you may not have heard of Denis Halliday, who resigned his
post as head of the United Nations' Oil for Food Program in Iraq
just weeks later to protest the humanitarian costs of the U.N.
sanctions.
 &HT;    ``Four thousand to 5,000 children are dying unnecessarily every
month due to the impact of sanctions,'' he said. ``We are in the
process of destroying an entire society. It is as simple and
terrifying as that. It is illegal and immoral.''
 &HT;    Halliday, an Irishman, worked for the United Nations for 34
years. A specialist in Third World development issues, he was
stationed in Iran, Malaysia and Indonesia, as well as at U.N.
headquarters in New York. On Sept. 1, 1997, he was appointed U.N.
Humanitarian Coordinator in Iraq; he resigned 13 months later.
 -0- 
 &HT;    MATTHEW ROTHSCHILD: Why did you decide to resign from the United
Nations?
 &HT;    DENIS HALLIDAY: I found myself in the very uncomfortable
position of representing the United Nations, which in Iraq has two
faces. One is the face of sanctions, which are killing thousands of
Iraqis every month and sustaining malnutrition at the rate of 30
percent for children alone. At the same time, I was trying to run a
humanitarian assistance program, and I found these two functions
incompatible. I don't believe the Security Council has the right to
punish the people of Iraq simply because it is unhappy with the
president of the country.
 &HT;    Q: You have said that the sanctions policy is a breach of
international law. How?
 &HT;    A: It's a complete breach of the Convention of the Rights of the
Child, for example. It's a breach of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights. It undermines the very charter of the United Nations.
The preamble of the charter is being clobbered by these U.N.
sanctions: the right of individuals to have a life, liberty,
opportunities to live, work and so on. It's very fundamental stuff.
 &HT;    Q: What is the magnitude of the suffering in Iraq? According to
one U.N. study, 500,000 Iraqi children had died as the result of
sanctions.
 &HT;    A: I believe the 500,000 is a UNICEF figure. It's probably
closer now to 600,000 and that's over the period of 1990-1998. If
you include adults, it's well over 1 million Iraqi people.
 &HT;    Q: What caused these deaths? What is the chain of fatality?
 &HT;    A: It originated with the horrendous and comprehensive damage
done by the missiles and bombing of the coalition forces during the
Persian Gulf War period, which was of greater extent than any of us
understand. They set about demolishing the civilian infrastructure
of this country, including water supplies, sewage supply systems,
electric power systems, production systems, educational facilities,
places of work.
 &HT;    It's hard to visualize, perhaps, but the infrastructure that
supports a good standard of living has been demolished. So that's
the starting point. And now you have the sanctions for seven or
eight years, and the damage that was done, combined with the lack
of money, or spare parts, upkeep for maintenance in the
agricultural sector. This combined has got us in the situation
where we have poor nutritional intake, very poor health services,
lack of drugs and medicines, and a disastrous water/sewage
situation whereby waterborne diseases like typhus are killing
thousands of Iraqis, particularly children.
 &HT;    Q: Were you an eyewitness to this hardship?
 &HT;    A: Yes, almost every evening driving back from the office I
would have to drive through raw sewage, which was often on the
streets of Baghdad. I would come up against 3- or 4-year-old
children begging for money at the traffic lights. And, of course, I
visited the poor parts of the country outside Baghdad, and I
visited the children's hospital.
 &HT;    Q: What was the hospital like?
 &HT;    A: The conditions are quite appalling. When I was there, there
was raw sewage in the basement of the hospital. The doctors do not
have drugs to deal with the problems they face. I was looking at
young children with leukemia; of four children I got to know, two
died within six weeks. That's a very common situation. Doctors are
making very horrible decisions as to who dies, who lives.
 &HT;    Q: What reaction do you get when you go around and speak about
the calamity of sanctions?
 &HT;    A: When regular, ordinary people understand some of the impact
and realize that Iraqi people are just like you and me, with all
the expectations we have for our children, it hits home that we are
rather callously sitting back and allowing people like ourselves to
be killed. But having demonized Saddam Hussein, policy makers in
Washington have demonized the Iraqi people. And they are just
regular people, with families, and gardens, and dogs, and houses
and all of that stuff. They have the same expectations we have _ to
live a life.
 &HT;    Q: What was your reaction to the massive U.S. and British
bombing campaign against Iraq in December?
 &HT;    A: I must say, I'm appalled that we are resorting to the
brutalization of an innocent people. I find this is incredible.
Apart from that, I really am concerned that nobody thinks through
the consequences of these sorts of actions. There is a bankruptcy
of ideas on how to deal with Iraq, and bombing is the fall-back
position.
 &HT;    It is a totally counterproductive effort. It enhances Saddam
Hussein's image. It outrages the Arab community. It reinforces the
general sense that Washington doesn't understand the Arab world.
 &HT;    Q: Aren't you concerned about the danger of Saddam Hussein
acquiring weapons of mass destruction?
 &HT;    A: I think no matter what approach is taken, there's going to be
a risk factor here, unfortunately. But I believe that if we are
going to move forward, we have to separate economic sanctions _
which only hurt the people, not the leadership _ from the issue of
the rearming of Iraq. Separate those two things and deal with them
separately.
 &HT;    Q: And how do you ensure that Iraq doesn't cheat?
 &HT;    A: You need an elaborate system of control on the manufacture
and purchases of military items. The Iraqis will have to understand
that there would be a need to monitor military rebuilding well
after sanctions have gone. I think that would have to be one of the
arrangements.
 &HT;    Q: By your own estimation, what is the extent of Saddam
Hussein's weapons of mass destruction?
 &HT;    A: I would guess, and this is purely speculation, that it's
extremely modest. I think people overestimate his capacity. The
military is very depleted; the equipment is very old. I think the
capacity is largely diminished and greatly exaggerated. That's not
to say it couldn't be rebuilt. Of course it could. But as of today,
I think it's of no great importance whatsoever _ and certainly
outgunned by the neighborhood American equipment throughout the
gulf countries.
 &HT;    Q: Some people who are harshly critical of Saddam Hussein and
who take a bellicose stand say that the Oil for Food program wasn't
working and that Saddam Hussein was siphoning off the revenues of
the oil sales to feed the military, to feed himself, feather his
nest. What's the truth to that?
 &HT;    A: Well, there's absolutely no truth, whatsoever. Every penny
from oil sales goes into the hands of the United Nations, into a
U.N. bank account, and is released by the United Nations directly
to the contractors _ American, Russian, French, Chinese, whatever
they may be _ who provide the foodstuffs, medical equipment,
medical supplies. There's no possibility of funds being siphoned
off whatsoever.
 &HT;    Q: And what about the extent of the oil revenues? Was there
enough to meet the humanitarian needs?
 &HT;    A: No, absolutely not. It fell short on two counts: On the
day-to-day, current cash-flow needs it fell short in that the funds
available did not provide a balanced diet. We have been providing,
under the Security Council Resolution, a totally inadequate food
basket for the Iraqi people.
 &HT;    Q: How far short was it falling?
 &HT;    A: In terms of calories it was short, but it was more seriously
short in terms of proteins, basically animal proteins. And that was
only the immediate, day-to-day requirement. What is required to
deal with malnutrition of the kind we find in Iraq is a
multisectoral approach. That means putting real money _ and I'm
talking billions of dollars _ into the health-care situation, into
the potable water and sewage situation, into electric power
production, into domestic agricultural production, into education.
All of that money is simply not available.
 &HT;    Q: After the Iraqi experience, what's your view of economic
sanctions as a tool? And why were they legitimate against the
apartheid regime of South Africa but not Saddam Hussein's Iraq?
 &HT;    A: You've picked out the only possible example of economic
sanctions having worked worldwide. I think there was a severe
penalty for the people of South Africa, but I believe they went
along with this proposed program. This was part of their approach _
the ANC (African National Congress) approach _ to resolving the
problem of apartheid and the government at the time. That is not
the case in Iraq. These are innocent people who were not consulted.
They are bearing the brunt of sanctions in a much greater degree
than ever in South Africa, and we've seen the death and
malnutrition that has resulted. It's not putting pressure on the
Iraqi leadership, and it's certainly not producing the results that
the Security Council had hoped for.
 &HT;    Q: Right now the U.S. government is again trying to find and
fund some forces in Iraq that will overthrow Hussein. Do you think
that is credible?
 &HT;    A: Well, I think it makes no sense whatsoever and frankly, I
believe there are about 70 to 80 different Iraqi opposition groups
outside the country. Within the country, I think very few are even
in a position to contemplate any sort of change in government
systems. I don't understand the viability of this program.
 &HT;    Q: There are those in conservative circles in the United States
who say that the only real answer is for the United States to send
in the ground troops, march to Baghdad, overthrow Saddam Hussein
and occupy the country.
 &HT;    A: That's a total nonstarter. The American people would never
accept that kind of exposure to its troops. The Iraqis would fight
back, and the loss of life would be horrific. It would be another
Vietnam.
 &HT;    Q: But the argument is, basically, ``This guy is Hitler. You
can't appease Hitler. You've got to take Hitler out.'' To what
extent is the Hitler metaphor useful?
 &HT;    A: National Socialism grew up because of the Versailles Treaty
and the harshness of the conditions we placed on Germany after
World War I. The conditions that are being placed on Iraq are
rather comparable, and we're getting the same kind of results. And
that's very dangerous. If Saddam Hussein is gone tomorrow, the
system can continue: The party is there, the military is there, his
people are still there. There's not necessarily going to be a
dramatic change. And because of sanctions, we are building a new
generation of Iraqi leaders who are mad, who are introverted _ more
of the Taliban model.
 &HT;    Q: So what's your solution?
 &HT;    A: I think we'd be much wiser to focus on the reality of Iraq
today, work with what we've got and get the country back on its
feet. When the country is back on its feet, you may see change from
within, that's the only change that is likely to last. Clearly,
sanctions have strengthened the leadership. They've increased the
dependence of the average person on the central government. There
is a naive sense that out of this sanctions situation a miracle of
democracy will emerge. That, of course, is completely nonsensical.
I think there is almost nobody left in the country who has time to
think about governance. They're concerned with survival, putting
food on the table, getting their kids educated and keeping
themselves, their children and their families alive. It's naive to
think that positive change will come out of the present sanctions
regime.
 &HT;    Q: So your policy would be to lift sanctions right away?
 &HT;    A: Lift economic sanctions right away, but retain a series of
devices to control arms manufacture and arms purchases.
 &HT;    Q: What should people do who are concerned about the plight of
the Iraqi people?
 &HT;    A: Well, we already have 43 members of Congress who signed a
letter to President Clinton, making a suggestion of separating the
arms issue from the economic sanctions issue. That's the beginning.
And there are others in Congress who are ready to think and listen
and learn about the impact on the Iraqi people. Therefore it's up
to the American voters to express their views through their
electoral machinery.
 &HT;     c.1999 The Progressive  
