<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-COMPLAINTS (Washington) _ Consumers and lawmakers
pounce on the airline industry with complaints ranging from being
stuck on runways for hours to inconsistent carry-on-baggage
policies. Lawmakers warn that if the airlines don't reform,
Congress will impose new rules. Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore
unveils the administration's version of a ``passenger bill of
rights.'' By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-2000 (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Elizabeth Hanford Dole, taking a
first step toward a possible run for the Republican presidential
nomination, says she is forming a presidential exploratory
committee. The former head of the American Red Cross says it is
time that the nation's leaders restore the voters faith in
government. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-POLLS (Undated) _ A survey shows that Texas Gov. George W.
Bush has a commanding lead, 32 percent to 14 percent, over
Elizabeth Dole. But the survey also shows that abortion remains a
key issue for many Republicans. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   NEA-BOOK (San Antonio) _ The National Endowment for the Arts
withdraws funding for a bilingual children's book published by a
small El Paso company after learning that the author is
Subcommander Marcos, head of the Zapatista guerrillas of southern
Mexico. The chairman of the endowment yanked funding for fear some
of the money might find its way to the rebels. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Three major bills that would
limit access to abortion are expected to win approval from a state
Senate panel in a marathon session with 136 witnesses signed up to
testify. A bill that requires parents be notified before their
underage daughters receive abortions, backed strongly by Gov.
George W. Bush, is given greatest chances of winning approval from
both chambers. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-HUBBLE (Houston) _ NASA plans to announce that it will
mount an unscheduled shuttle mission to the Hubble telescope later
this year to replace six gyroscopes, a crucial part of the
mechanism that points to star targets designated by ground-based
astronomers. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRIP (San Salvador, El Salvador) _ President Clinton
pledges justice and fairness for Central Americans living in the
United States, but declares that illegal immigration is eroding
``the control of our borders. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOX-GARDEN (New York) _ For the first time in many years,
Madison Square Garden will be the home to a major heavyweight
championship fight this Saturday night when Evander Holyfield takes
on Lennox Lewis. The Garden, a place that is virtually synonymous
with boxing, was the host to some of the greatest fights in boxing
history, including the legendary Ali-Frazier fight in 1971. By W.H.
STICKNEY.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-SOUTH (Indianapolis) _ Among the No. 1 seeds in this
year's NCAA basketball field, Duke is the overwhelming favorite.
And both Michigan State and Connecticut have been annual attendees
at the NCAA's Big Dance for the past few years. But for Auburn,
which hasn't even been invited to the tournament since 1988, this
business of being a No. 1 seed is pretty rare. By JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA-WEST (Denver) _ The NCAA Tournament opens its annual
run Thursday with 16 games at four regional sites, and most
observers will be watching the West Regional. By BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ For many of the Houston Rockets, March
Madness has been more than just a slogan. With players such as
Bryce Drew, Michael Dickerson, Cuttino Mobley dotting the roster,
the Rockets have their own special memories of the NCAA Tournament.
By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-PROP16 (Undated) _ When a federal judge earlier this week
threw out the NCAA's initial-eligibility standards, it threw the
organization and its members into a chaotic situation that
overturns all of the existing rules. We talk to Texas officials
about what this could mean for the future of recruiting at state
schools. By DAVID BARRON.
</P>
