A5190 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-10 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRONICLE </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLORADO'S PICKING ON SAN FRANCISCO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A friend from Colorado spilled the beans to  &UR; Steve Sherman &LR; :
They're making fun of us. A new ad campaign for the Colorado
lottery, based on the slogan ``Stranger things than you winning
Lotto,'' uses a San Francisco example of a ``stranger thing'':
</P>
<P>
   In this city, the ad says, voters had a referendum on whether a
San Francisco Police Department officer could carry his dummy
around with him on the job. ``Our reputation precedes us,'' says
Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   A slightly embarrassed-sounding Colorado lottery official
confirmed the ad to Personals, adding that prior permission had
been obtained from  &UR; Bob Geary &LR; , the dummy-toting cop portrayed by
an actor in the ad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE METROPOLITAN MATTERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Leafing through his 1999 Amtrak Travel Planner,  &UR; George &LR; 
 &UR; Beckwith &LR;  was struck by the picture on page 76, captioned ``New
York's famous skyline at dusk.'' The Bay Bridge is in the
foreground, stretching westward toward a skyline that includes
silhouettes of Sutro Tower, the Transamerica pyramid and the BofA
building.
</P>
<P>
   - Despite the protests of neighbors,  &UR; King Taufa'ahua Tupou &LR; 
 &UR; IV &LR;  of Tonga has received a permit to add four new bedrooms to a
6,000-square foot-house he owns in Hillsborough. The king uses the
house for twice-yearly visits. In between, it serves as the
official residence for Tongan Consul-General  &UR; Emeline Uheina &LR; 
 &UR; Tuita &LR; , who explained the location and expansion:
</P>
<P>
   The Tongan government doesn't ``have anything in New York,'' she
said, we don't have anything in Washington. We chose San Francisco
because it is more central for the U.S. Tongan community. ... I
have a large family, we can't all fit in the house right now.''
</P>
<P>
   - San Francisco has the lowest rate of diet pill use in the
country, says the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   - The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art's exhibit of works by
 &UR; Alexander Calder &LR;  was the sixth most well-attended art show in the
country last year, seen by an average of 3,300 people a day, says
the Economist. The most popular show in the country was the
 &UR; Vincent Van Gogh &LR;  show at the National Gallery in Washington, seen
by 5,400 a day. - Corporate wife  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR;  will be addressing
the American Society of Newspaper Editors, convening in San
Francisco on April 13 through 15, on her field of expertise:
``Married to the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to hear them one time in England. They had Billy
Preston, who used to work with me. That's why I went there. The
music, they had it so loud that when I came out, I literally scared
myself to death because I couldn't hear. I thought I was losing my
hearing. ... I'm already blind. I can't be no Helen Keller.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Ray Charles &LR;  on hearing the Rolling Stones, in the
Minneapolis-St. Paul Star Tribune.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
