A5207 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENT-TEACHER-STAB-H     03-10 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENT-TEACHER-STAB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER STABBED IN FRONT OF STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Calif. _ The father of a fourth-grade student stabbed
and seriously wounded his daughter's teacher in an apparent
disagreement over the girl's progress, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The stabbing occurred Tuesday in front of several students,
including the suspect's daughter. The 43-year-old teacher was
hospitalized in serious condition with a stab wound to her right
side.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Gonzalez had been waiting several minutes in the back of
his 9-year-old daughter's classroom at J.O. Ford Elementary School
when the teacher, Nancy Peer, dismissed the students shortly before
3 p.m., Richmond police Sgt. Allwyn Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   As students filed out of the classroom, Gonzalez, 30, began
discussing his daughter's classroom performance with Peer, the
children later told the police. As Peer turned away, he stabbed her
once in the right side with a kitchen knife, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a relatively calm conversation, a brief exchange of
words,'' Brown said. ``Nothing that would indicate he intended to
do her harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving his daughter behind, Gonzalez fled the school
immediately, the police said. He was arrested without incident a
short time later outside his home in neighboring San Pablo. He was
booked into Contra Costa County Jail in Martinez on one charge of
assault with a deadly weapon.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators rushed to the classroom, where they found
Peer sitting in a chair, clutching her side, school secretary Ada
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Peer, in her third year of teaching at the school, was taken by
ambulance to a nearby and then airlifted to the John Muir Medical
Center in Walnut Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who were at the school at the time of the stabbing
gathered outside the administration office to comfort distraught
students, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were crying, they were sad,'' Martin said. ``She's a very
well-liked teacher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1624EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BIBLE-ART-3TAKES-     03-10 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BIBLE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD FRIEND, THE FAMILY BIBLE, IS DRESSED UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 Ari L. Goldman teaches journalism at Columbia University. His book
``Being Jewish'' is to be published by Simon &AMP; Schuster in the
fall.  
 By ARI L. GOLDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The family Bible holds a special place in the American home and
imagination. In many families, it is an heirloom, passed from
generation to generation. Whatever the edition (it's usually the
King James) and whatever the language (it's usually English), the
family Bible is considered the authentic Bible, the very word of
God.
</P>
<P>
   The current owners might not even believe that, but they imagine
that once, long ago, someone in the family did.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes an ancestor's thoughts about Scripture are scrawled in
the book's margins. Perhaps some of the pages are worn or dogeared,
maybe at a place an ancestor turned to for solace or encouragement.
And often at the back of the Bible is a family genealogy, where the
names, births and deaths of relatives are recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everything that the old family Bible provided can now
be found in Bible CD-ROM boxed sets. The Bible software on the
market is distinctly Christian and includes both the Old Testament
and the New Testament. It should be noted that in some of the
supporting material in a CD-ROM called the Complete Multimedia
Bible, there are a few not-too-subtle put-downs of Judaism and
Islam.(There are numerous CD-ROMs of sacred text aimed at the
Jewish and Muslim markets, but they are not included in the
following reviews.)
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Bibles may not become treasured heirlooms, but truth
be told, they can run circuits around the old family Bible. Instead
of one version, the electronic Bibles provide a variety of classic
and modern translations, in English as well as Greek, Latin,
French, Spanish and Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   The reader can divide the computer screen into segments and view
the various translations side by side. Bible commentaries, maps and
dictionaries are instantly accessible to help decipher and
explicate the text.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't want to do the reading yourself, the Multimedia
Bible will read the text for you, in the sonorous tones of James
Earl Jones. Other electronic Bibles provide video scenes of sacred
places in the Holy Land, like the Garden of Gethsemane and the
Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
   Yet others offer classic religious works of art, like
Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel and Leonardo's ``Last Supper.''
Others include such inspirational music as Gregorian chant and
Haydn.
</P>
<P>
   Giving new meaning to the term family Bible, the new electronic
sets also include collections of lavishly illustrated children's
stories, like Noah's Ark and the Good Samaritan, and a host of
religious games, including one called Name That Hymn.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling sad or lonely? Need inspiration or advice? No need to
thumb through pages. The electronic Bibles will suggest verses to
turn to in times of need. One recommended verse is Psalms 34:4: ``I
sought the Lord, and he heard me, and delivered me from all my
fears.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bible software even gives the user an opportunity to write
commentary, keyed to particular chapters and verses. These can be
saved with the King James Version and labeled _ as ``Joe's Bible
Commentary,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing, of course, is the feel of a hefty leather-bound
or clothbound book in your hand, a book with a musty smell and a
sense of family history. Computer software can never compete on
that level, but the new family Bibles might inspire some people to
take the old book off the shelf for a new look.
</P>
<P>
   The NIV Study Bible Complete Library  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Zondervan Publishing House; $129.95; Windows 3.1 and later.)
</P>
<P>
   This is the electronic Bible for the serious student. It has
extraordinary versatility and scope for those who want to prepare
sermons, academic papers and Bible study sessions. The CD-ROM
contains four English versions of the Old Testament and the New
Testament: the New International Version (NIV), the King James, the
New American Standard and the Revised Standard Version; there is
also a version in Greek. Supporting the basic text are a dozen
dictionaries, encyclopedias and concordances.
</P>
<P>
   The user can view up to nine screens at once, but four seemed
just enough for me. I put one Bible translation on each of my four
screens and went exploring. I could easily turn to any chapter and
verse and see how the versions differed. (The Old Testament was, of
course, originally written in Hebrew and the New Testament in
Greek, so all English versions are mere translations.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Word searches were a snap but had to be narrowed to be
meaningful. For example, words like Moses, Jesus, forgive,
sacrifice and pray brought up hundreds of citations each. Words
like gorilla and banana brought none. There were quite a few
``frogs,'' but only one when I matched the search with ``pray,'' as
when Pharaoh prays to rid his kingdom of the plague of frogs
(Exodus 8:8). I had to come up with a more modest word. I tried
``meek.''
</P>
<P>
   The King James was the champion of meek, with 16 references, the
most famous from the Sermon on the Mount: ``Blessed are the meek,
for they shall inherit the earth'' (Matthew 5:5). The others had
far fewer references to the word meek. The New American Standard
Bible rendered the verse from Matthew as ``blessed are the
gentle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bible software allows the user to install the Greek font,
but since I do not read Greek, I did not try that. A Hebrew font is
not available, but a useful Hebrew transliteration is.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM also has an excellent Bible atlas with full-color
maps of things like the journeys of the apostles. It also contains
dazzling photographs of the Holy Land. The images on the screen are
sometimes small, but scrolling in all directions provides the user
with some beautiful panoramas.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features of this program was the 200-page user's
guide. It helped me with installation and then guided me on my
searches.
</P>
<P>
   There was one area in which the user's guide was of little help,
and that leads me to my only criticism of the NIV Study Bible: when
it came to the Inspirational Reading, the software promised Bible
verses for almost anything that ails you: sickness, confusion,
impatience, temptation, fear.
</P>
<P>
   But the program delivers only chapter-and-verse references,
rather than the verses themselves. The user (perhaps already under
stress) has to search alone.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you are confused, check out Isaiah 42:16. ``I
will lead the blind by a road they do not know, by paths they have
not known I will guide them.'' I just looked it up in the family
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Zondervan New International Version Bible  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Zondervan/Compton's; $49.95; Windows 3.1 and later.)
</P>
<P>
   This collection has two CD-ROMs and an unusual touch: a
hardcover book. The CD-ROMs hold the best-selling classics _ one
includes the King James Version (1611) and the other the New
International Version (1978) _ while the hardcover book is the
reissue of a 1925 inspirational volume, ``Streams in the Desert,''
by L.B. Cowman.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the Cowman book, I could have used a user's guide for
the CD-ROMs. Installation instructions are limited to two scant
pages inside the jewel-box CD cover. There is an online user's
guide, but no printed version.
</P>
<P>
   The two CD-ROMs contain much more than different versions of the
Bible. The King James CD is called The Complete Multimedia Bible
and has graphics, video, music and maps. What most distinguishes it
is the voice of James Earl Jones, who reads selections like the
Sermon on the Mount and the Ten Commandments. When you hear the
commandments from a voice like that, you listen.
</P>
<P>
   The search capabilities were slower than those on other Bible
CD-ROMs and less useful. Rather than searching for specific words
in the Bible, users can also search the CD-ROM by subject. As a
result, you can search a broad category without confidence that you
will catch the reference you want.
</P>
<P>
   The inspirational readings did not disappoint; they gave not
only the citations but the verses themselves. But I began to detect
a certain fundamentalist interpretation. Under ``abortion,'' for
example, the reading was from Deuteronomy 30:19: ``I have set
before you life and death ... therefore choose life, that both thou
and thy seed may live.''
</P>
<P>
   In the videos, you can see devout pilgrims at the Via Dolorosa,
the ``way of sorrow'' that Jesus followed to his crucifixion, or at
the Stone of Unction, where Jesus' body was laid out to be
anointed. The story of the suffering, death and resurrection of
Jesus is told with reverence. But my suspicions about a
fundamentalist approach were confirmed when I saw in the videos
that Jewish and Muslim beliefs were presented as superstition.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, an unnamed narrator walks jauntily through a
Jewish cemetery and almost sneers as he says that Jews believe that
the dead will rise from their graves. Perhaps the most offensive
clip is one that discusses the mosque on the Temple Mount in
Jerusalem. The narrator suggests that Muslims now offer camel rides
there, which is not true. The video clip gratuitiously shows a man
in an Arab headdress helping a tourist off a camel and then giving
the camel two kisses on the lips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The second CD in this set, called Compton's Interactive Bible,
contains beautiful examples of religious art and music. At the
beginning of Genesis, for example, you can click to hear a
selection from Haydn's ``Creation.'' At the beginning of Matthew,
the ``Hallelujah, Amen'' by Handel. ``Jesu, Joy of Man's
Desiring,'' by Bach, opens another chapter. As for art, there are
details of each of the prophets from the Sistine Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem I found with this CD-ROM was that it was very
slow. Moving from one image to another took inordinately long. I
waited several minutes for a word search. If you have the time (or
a more powerful computer than I have), this CD-ROM would be worth
exploring. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family Bible Collection, Deluxe Edition  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Encore Software; $49.99; Windows 3.1 or higher.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three CD-ROMs in this box contain a variety of programs. On
one disk, there are 10 Bible versions that can be searched and
studied with the help of 17 Bible study resources, like
dictionaries, commentaries, concordances and maps. I found the
searches lightning fast and precise, but the graphics were not as
clear and inviting as several of the other search programs I
sampled.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguished this set was not the Bible study tools as
much as what is in it for families. One disk has 24 Bible stories
that introduce children to the characters and tales from Scripture
through words, song and animation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stories are ``Moses in a Basket,'' ``Jesus on the
Mount'' and ``The Cross and the Resurrection.'' These are geared to
preschoolers and children in the early grades who are just
beginning to read. I found the illustrations vivid and appealing,
but the music grated on my nerves after a story or two.
</P>
<P>
   Another program has a wealth of Bible games. The CD-ROMs
developers seem to be arguing that if children are going to play
video games, they might as well play ones based on the Bible.
Players are gently guided through the games by the Archangel
Michael, who helps them select the appropriate level and lets them
choose from Old and New Testament challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the ever popular Name That Hymn. Was that ``A
Mighty Fortress,'' ``God Is Good'' or ``Holy, Holy, Holy''? The
Archangel Michael rewards you with praise if you get it right.
</P>
<P>
   The set also includes a program that reviews the history of
Jerusalem from a Christian perspective and a program of 1,000
clip-art images for use in church publications and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   You can, of course, find better graphics and sound on other
computer games, but given the difficultly of getting young people
interested in the Bible, the Family Bible Collection can be
considered a noble effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bible Study Companion  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Expert Software; $14.99; Windows 95 and 98.)
</P>
<P>
   Bible Explorer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Expert Software; $14.99; Windows 3.1 and 95.)
</P>
<P>
   The Bible Study Companion has many of the Bible versions and
Bible commentaries that other CD-ROMs offer, but it has superior
graphics, layout and clarity. Reading through ancient texts, even
inspirational ones, can be tedious, but the presentation on this
CD-ROM was among the best.
</P>
<P>
   The makers did not try to put too much on the page by crowding
it with small print, and they kept extraneous art off the screen.
What the user gets is swift searches and clear text.
</P>
<P>
   The CD also offers Scripture in languages not found on other
software, including Latin, Spanish, French, German and Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   And while all the CD-ROM's offered users an opportunity to add
their own Bible comments, The Bible Study Companion was the only
one that always kept a screen open for this purpose _ a definite
plus for the compulsive note taker.
</P>
<P>
   Bible Explorer uses the King James Version as its text. In some
ways, it seemed like the poor man's version of the Complete
Multimedia Bible, one of the two CD-ROMs in the Zondervan set.
While that set featured the voice of James Earl Jones, Bible
Explorer has an unnamed actor reading passages.
</P>
<P>
   The video clips depicting the life of Jesus have the quality of
a mediocre made-for-television movie. One of the best features of
Bible Explorer is the biblical time line, which stretches from
creation through the New Testament books. Moving between two posts
of a scroll, the time line is inventively designed and links the
stories to Bible verses, photographs, videos, historical dates and
narration.
</P>
<P>
   For the money, you cannot beat these Expert Software versions.
They do not have everything that the more expensive Bible CD-ROMs
offer, but not everyone needs all the extras. After all, we got
along for centuries without nine viewing windows in the family
Bible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
