<HEADLINE>
MCDONALD'S PLANS 20 RESTAURANTS IN BOSNIA  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent newspaper in
London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
  
 By MARCUS TANNER  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McDonald's said it plans to open 20 restaurants in Bosnia, in
another sign that the divided country's fragile peace is continuing
to take hold and that a kind of normality is returning to the
former Balkan killing fields.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Bosnian government said representatives of
the U.S. fast-food giant held talks with Prime Minister Edhem
Bicakcic and other ministers to finalize its plans.
</P>
<P>
   It said the American group planned to open at least three
restaurants in the capital, Sarajevo, though it did not say when
this would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a local population of roughly two million people in
the federation, thousands of foreigners live and work there for
numerous international organizations overseeing the Bosnian peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Post-war Bosnia consists of two entities, a Muslim-Croat
federation and a Serbian republic, but it is not clear whether
McDonald's may also be planning to open restaurants in the Serbs'
territory.
</P>
<P>
   If McDonald's does establish a presence in Bosnia it would be
seen as a boost for the country's Western-sponsored efforts to
rebuild its economy following the devastating 1992-1995 war.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only a few foreign investors have come to the country,
notably German car maker Volkswagen which last August started a
joint venture with conglomerate United Industry Sarajevo (UNIS) to
produce Skoda Felicia cars.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors have been reluctant to enter Bosnia, partly due
to the slow pace of reform to establish a properly functioning
market economy with legislation protecting their investments. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 250-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
