<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEYLAND-HONGKONG-ASAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG FLIRTS WITH MICKEY MOUSE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi News Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renownd for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
STANDS IN 875 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,200 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By PETER McGILL  
 c.1999 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Martin Lee, head of Hong Kong's Democratic Party, is
normally a thorn in the flesh to the new Chinese rulers of the
former British colony.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even this opposition curmudgeon admits to have fallen for
Disney's magic spell, saying, ``All the political parties support
this. Who could say no to Donald Duck?''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not Sir Donald Tsang, the bow-tied financial secretary
of Hong Kong, who chose to announce in his budget speech last week
that Hong Kong is holding serious negotiations with the Walt Disney
Company to host the first Disney theme park in Asia outside of
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   For the Hong Kong economy, it is no laughing matter. Tsang
called last year's 5.1 percent fall in Hong Kong's gross domestic
product ``the worst economic setback our generation has ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Disney project is just one of several bold attempts unveiled
by Tsang to rekindle growth and stem a hemorrhage of business and
investment to Singapore, including a Hong Kong $13 billion (205
billion yen or $1.7 billion) ``cyberport'' project to help Hong
Kong develop into a global information services hub.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney theme park is intended to revive the flagging tourism
industry, which accounts for about 4 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
   Since the July 1997 handover to China, there has been a sharp
decline in foreign visitors, particularly Japanese, who were by far
the biggest spenders.
</P>
<P>
   The park would be built on Lantau Island, site of the Hong Kong
$155.3 billion (2.45 trillion yen) new Hong Kong International
Airport that opened last year and is already connected to Kowloon
by the world's longest road/rail suspension bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Hong Kong brings a Disneyland theme park to town, it would
generate about Hong Kong $20 billion (316 billion yen) in
construction spending, 3 million additional tourists and about
95,000 low-skill jobs,'' according to Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of talks had already rallied the stock market in Hong
Kong, with prices rising 7.5 percent since last week.
</P>
<P>
   This represents a backhanded tribute to the astonishing success
of Tokyo Disneyland, which in the past 16 years has excited the
envy and admiration not just of other cities and countries, but
even of the Walt Disney Company itself.
</P>
<P>
   From April 1, 1997, to March 31, 1998, Tokyo Disneyland drew
16,686,000 visitors, making it the most popular theme park in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney World in Orlando, Florida, trailed second; third was
the original Disneyland in Anaheim, Calif.; and fourth was
Disneyland Paris (the new name for Euro Disneyland), 32 kilometers
(20 miles) east of the French capital.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike all the rest, Tokyo Disneyland is entirely owned by a
local company, Oriental Land, which only pays royalties to Walt
Disney _ 10 percent of all admission fees and 5 percent of revenue
from restaurants and shops in the theme park.
</P>
<P>
   For its 1997 financial year ending last March 31, Oriental Land
had revenue of 175.5 billion yen and net income of 14.3 billion
yen.
</P>
<P>
   The share price of Oriental Land has fallen steeply from 8,850
yen when it was first listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange in
December 1997, but its closing price on Friday, 5,950 yen, was
still higher than that of Honda Motor, 4,690 yen, and it has a
higher price-to-earnings ratio than the export giant.
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes being made in Japan did not pass unnoticed at
Disney headquarters. Since Walt Disney's death in 1966, the company
had entered what seemed like a terminal decline. Corporate vultures
were circling and there was talk of Disney being broken up and sold
off.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, the 50th anniversary of Donald Duck, a boardroom
revolution brought in Michael Eisner as chairman and Frank Wells as
president, and the company stopped croaking and began to fly,
becoming one of Wall Street's darlings and hottest stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking they had learned their lesson from Tokyo Disneyland,
the company decided to sink a large sum of its own money in the new
Disneyland outside Paris, to have hotels built inside the park and
to control its management.
</P>
<P>
   The French government had to add expensive sweeteners to lure
Disney away from Spain, such as building a rail extension and a
highway interchange, and reducing its amusement taxes on the theme
park's receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this time the Disney magic failed to work. Euro Disney had
to be rescued from losses by creditor banks and a Saudi Arabian
prince, and Disney had to accept a moratorium on royalty payments
and management fees from Euro Disney, of which it owns 39 percent.
Unlike Oriental Land, the share price of Euro Disney has collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the euphoria in Hong Kong about
hosting a Disneyland will be justified. Tsang has warned that
``much hard negotiating lies ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney's first choice for a second Asian theme park was
Queensland, Australia, but the company backed out in October after
the Queensland government balked at the amount of subsidies, tax
breaks and land concessions that Disney was demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Queensland Premier Peter Beattie commented that ``only Goofy
would have picked up such a deal.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 875. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Oriental Land is phlegmatic about the challenge from a rival
Disney theme park in Asia. For the business year ending last March
31, it says 96.9 percent of visitors to Tokyo Disneyland were
Japanese, and mostly from the Kanto region (Tokyo and the
neighboring prefectures of Chiba, Saitama, Ibaraki and Kanagawa).
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the Japan National Tourist Organization from April
1, 1998, to March 31, 1999, of visitors to Japan from Hong Kong,
mainland China, Taiwan and the Republic of Korea (South Korea)
found that Tokyo Disneyland was most popular with those from Hong
Kong (visited by 40 percent) and Taiwan (26 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Visitors from China showed little interest (only 9 percent went
there) and those from South Koreans were even more indifferent (3.6
percent). For Americans and Europeans, Tokyo Disneyland did not
even make the top 10 places visited in Japan, said a JNTO
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In the year 2000, Oriental Land plans to open a commercial
complex, including cinemas, restaurants, shops and a ``Disney
Ambassador'' hotel, on a 12-hectare site adjacent to Tokyo
Disneyland. This development will cost about 65 billion yen.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, it plans to open another theme park on 71.4 hectares of
reclaimed land, called ``Tokyo DisneySea.'' This will charge
separate admission to Tokyo Disneyland, and is costing another 338
billion yen to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies want to emulate the stellar success of Tokyo
Disneyland, and the greatest risk now to Oriental Land is from
domestic competition.
</P>
<P>
   Flanking Tokyo Disneyland on either side are two other Tokyo Bay
theme parks under construction, both conveniently near stations on
the Keiyo Line: the 350-billion-yen Lotte World Tokyo on a
19.2-hectare site in Tokyo's Edogawa Ward, and the 20-billion-yen
Legoland near Makuhari in Chiba Prefecture, a project of Denmark's
Lego Group.
</P>
<P>
   In Osaka, the 170-billion-yen Universal Studios Japan theme park
is also due to open in 2001. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this article from the Asahi News Service, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
