<HEADER>
A5232 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIETNAMESEDISHES-2ndT     03-10 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAMESEDISHES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: fish sauce. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a mortar, pound the chile and sugar to a paste. Stir in the
lime pulp and pound gently to make a coarse sauce. Stir in the lime
juice and fish sauce. Allow to sit at least 10 minutes before
serving. The sauce will keep in the refrigerator for up to 5 days.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 144 calories, 4 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 56 milligrams cholesterol,
235 milligrams sodium, 27 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Simple Art of Vietnamese Cooking''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BEEF MEDALLIONS WITH WATER SPINACH (THIT BO XAO RAU MUONG)
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 to 5 cups cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced, and 4 cloves garlic, very thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plus 2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried chile flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound beef tenderloin, cut crosswise into slices 1/4-inch
thick
</P>
<P>
   1 pound water spinach, tough lower stems removed, see Glossary
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons bottled fish sauce (nuoc mam)
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the rice and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix the minced garlic with the sugar. Stir in
the soy sauce, sesame oil, 1/2 teaspoon of the black pepper, 2
teaspoons of the oil, and the chile flakes. Add the beef slices and
coat well. Set aside to marinate at room temperature for 2 hours,
or cover and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   In large skillet, combine 1 tablespoon of remaining oil and
sliced garlic. Cook slowly over low heat until the garlic softens
and becomes golden, about 4 minutes. Increase the heat to high and
add the water spinach. With chopsticks, stir the spinach to wilt.
Add 2 tablespoons water, the fish sauce and remaining 1/4 teaspoon
black pepper. Cook, stirring, until most of the liquid evaporates,
about 1 minute. Put water spinach on a warm platter and cover with
foil.
</P>
<P>
   Put skillet back on fire, and over high heat add the remaining 1
tablespoon oil. When it's almost smoking, add half of the beef
slices in an even layer and cook about 1 1/2 minutes per side for
medium-rare. Remove to a plate. Repeat with remaining beef. To
serve, arrange beef over water spinach. Serve with the rice.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with rice: 299 calories, 19
grams fat, 8 grams carbohydrates, 26 grams protein, 67 milligrams
cholesterol, 592 milligrams sodium, 56 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Simple Art of Vietnamese Cooking''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN WINGS IN CARAMEL SAUCE AND GINGER (CANH GA KHO GUNG)
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   Pickled bean sprouts, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   Caramel sauce, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds chicken wings
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely shredded fresh gingerroot
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Prepare pickled bean sprouts and caramel sauce. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut each chicken wing into 3 pieces; the main wing joint, the
second joint and the wing tip. Reserve wing tips for soups or
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In 3-quart saucepan, add chicken wing pieces and shredded ginger
to the cooled caramel sauce. Stir to combine. Set over high heat
and bring mixture to a rapid boil. Cover the pan, reduce heat to
low and simmer, stirring occasionally, for 30 to 40 minutes, or
until chicken is very tender. Skim off any excess fat.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer chicken wings and sauce to a serving dish. Sprinkle
with black pepper, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, spoon some of the sauce over rice and serve with
pickled bean sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Pickled bean sprouts (dua gia):
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh bean sprouts
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch scallions, cut into 2-inch-long sections
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Combine bean sprouts and scallions in large nonreactive bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Combine salt, vinegar and 4 cups water in small saucepan. Bring
to a boil. Cool until warm to the touch. Pour brine over bean
sprout mixture. Marinate for at least 1 hour, or until ready to
serve. Drain before serving.
</P>
<P>
   (Pickled bean sprouts are best served the same day they are
made. They won't stand longer marinating, as they will become
soggy.)
</P>
<P>
   Caramel sauce (nuoc duong thang):
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 shallots, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cook sugar in small, heavy saucepan over low heat, swirling pan
constantly, until brown. It will smoke slightly. Immediately remove
pan from heat and stir fish sauce into caramel, being careful to
guard against splattering (the mixture will bubble vigorously).
</P>
<P>
   Return mixture to low heat and gently boil, swirling the pan
occasionally, until sugar is completely dissolved, about 3 minutes.
Add shallots and ground pepper to taste; stir to combine.
</P>
<P>
   Cool this sauce thoroughly before using. If cold food is added
to a caramel sauce that is hot, the sugar will harden instantly and
you'll end up with a dish of candy chips.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with caramel sauce and pickled
bean sprouts: 236 calories, 11 grams fat, 16 grams carbohydrates,
18 grams protein, 46 milligrams cholesterol, 468 milligrams sodium,
43 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Foods of Vietnam'' by Nicole Routhier (Stewart, Tabori &AMP;
Chang, $40)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Glossary:
</P>
<P>
   Chiles: The Vietnamese use an assortment of chiles, but the most
common is the tiny (but combustible) ``bird'' chile also used
extensively in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Chile sauce: Not the namby-pamby stuff Americans call chili
sauce, the Asian condiment is a thick paste of ground chiles with
vinegar and garlic. Each brand has its own version of heat. Widely
available in Asian markets, the most popular brands are sold in
plastic squeeze bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Fish sauce: The cornerstone of Vietnamese cooking, the sauce is
made by fermenting anchovies.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger: As in most of Asia, ginger is an important seasoning
agent.
</P>
<P>
   Green papaya: The Vietnamese prefer the green variety of this
fruit. Look for papayas that are green, firm and unblemished.
</P>
<P>
   Noodles: Noodles appear in the national dish, ``pho,'' as well
as in combinations with curries and stir-fries.
</P>
<P>
   Oyster sauce: An ingredient that was introduced by the Chinese
and is used in stir-fries as an enriching agent.
</P>
<P>
   Rice: Buy aromatic jasmine rice. If you can't find it,
substitute basmati rice.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp chips: Another ingredient borrowed from the Chinese.
These dried chips are sold in bags and should be deep-fried. Do not
buy colored shrimp chips.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar cane: Buy fresh sugar cane (in Vietnamese or Hispanic
markets) if it is
</P>
<P>
   quite moist and heavy with juice. Canned sugar cane, packed in
juice, is a fine alternative in most dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Water spinach: This water-growing vine does not require the
extensive cleaning of our domestic version. The stems are long and
the leaves are shaped like arrows. The stems are tough, the leaves
tender. Break off the bottoms of the stems, pull off the leaves
with some of the tender stems and chop the tougher parts of the
stems.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
