<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5234 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-KIDS-INTERNET-ART     03-10 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KIDS-INTERNET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFER PLAYGROUNDS ARE AIMED AT KIDS (AND PAYING PARENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago, Alan Rothenberg was a frustrated parent. He was
tired of buying educational CD-ROMs at $45 a pop, only to have his
daughters become bored and abandon them after a couple hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the World Wide Web had plenty of sites with children's
games, but he wasn't impressed with their educational content and
he was reluctant to let his young daughters roam on the Internet,
where they might end up in a seedy corner. Like many parents, he
thought: ``If only there were an Internet just for them.''
</P>
<P>
   So he made one. This month his company, JuniorNet
(www.juniornet.com), begins what it says will be the first safe
online service just for preteen-agers. After purchasing JuniorNet
software and using it to log on, members can access only approved
links, trade messages only with approved friends and post only
approved postings.
</P>
<P>
   Several other companies, some still in embryonic stages, plan to
follow with similar pay services in the coming months. They are
jumping on what has become a marketing bandwagon aimed at signing
up parents made wary by scary news reports about the Internet _ or
by what they have seen with their own eyes.
</P>
<P>
   These services, which are becoming known as ``subscription-based
virtual private environments for children,'' say they are like
roped-off portions of the Internet, where youngsters can get their
feet wet with the ways of the Web without swimming into dangerous
waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a safe playground that's being monitored by people you
trust,'' said Parry Aftab, the author of ``A Parents' Guide to the
Internet'' (SC Press, 1997). ``This is where it's going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did for the longest time was say `you can't go here
and you can't go here' instead of saying `These are the places you
can go,''' Ms. Aftab continued. ``We were taking the slipper away
from the puppy and not giving them anything else to play with.''
</P>
<P>
   One attempt by lawmakers to keep out the ``bad stuff,'' the 1998
Child On-Line Protection Act, has been delayed by court challenges
every step of the way, said Stephen Valerie. He is the founder of
Kids On-line America (www.kola.net), a service for students,
teachers and parents that hopes to be up and running by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time and time again, the courts are not going to enforce any
kind of censorship,'' he said. ``Again the private sector is the
one that's going to have to come to the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his small San Francisco-based company is banking on it.
In a survey released in June 1998 by Jupiter Communications in New
York, 53 percent of parents said they would be willing to pay for
an online service for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg said almost 4,000 parents signed up to the test an
early version of his JuniorNet, for which a CD-ROM provides access
to the service and allows subscribers to download stories,
activities and games to their hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   The content comes from such sources as the publications Ranger
Rick and Highlights for Children. ( Rothenberg says he looked at
the magazines that littered his children's room for inspiration.)
</P>
<P>
   The JuniorNet service has no links to other Web sites, but it
does aim to be an Internet community with e-mail and bulletin
boards. Messages to and from people not on the parents' approval
list will be automatically bounced, and messages for bulletin
boards will be screened by JuniorNet employees before they are
posted.
</P>
<P>
   One selling point pushed by some subscription services is that
they will provide safety not only from cesspools of pornography and
lurking predators, but from a constant barrage of Internet ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole strategy to use kids to get money out of their
parents' pockets,'' said Gerry Bishop, editor of Ranger Rick
magazine. He called his publication and JuniorNet ``refuges from
that assault,'' since neither accepts outside advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Established companies are starting to pay more attention to
their younger consumers. America Online, which has always had a
roped-off area of the Internet pool, has revamped its Kids Only
section. Disney's Blast Online (www.disney.go.com) has memberships
for children, complete with parental controls for e-mail and chat
groups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   To try to jump ahead of the competition, the newest services are
asserting that their security measures are even more strict. KOLA
says it plans to keep its community upstanding through
``registration validation.'' Members join through schools,
community organizations (like the Boy Scouts) or partner
corporations that can verify that a 12-year-old girl really is a
12-year-old girl, not really a 40-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   Another service, Safe-Site, which is not yet available, plans to
be so exclusive that it cannot even be accessed through a regular
computer. For $100-150, parents can buy the Electronic Learning
Aids sold by Safe-Site parent company Oregon Scientific. These toy
laptops directly dial up www.safe-site.net, where children can
compare game scores and trade greeting cards. A Safe-Site modem
($50) and Internet Service Provider ($15 a month) are also
required.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a safe harbor type of thing,'' said Jean Armour Polly,
whose Net-Mom Web site (www.netmom.com) has links to 100
``mother-approved'' sites. The whole industry is making a move
toward accentuating the positive, she said, not just screening out
the negative. To that end, software filters, which were first
developed to search for ``bad words'' and block access to sites
containing them, now often work from a list of approved sites.
</P>
<P>
   But site addresses have a way of changing overnight, Ms. Polly
pointed out, so any services that link outside their own system
leave a potential door ajar to something creepy from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never hear me saying we are the 100 percent safe
solution,'' said Valerie, whose KOLA service will have outside
links.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, even services like JuniorNet that promise to
provide their young clients with endless new material can offer
only a shadow of the wonders of the Web, said Barry Fagin, a
founder of Families Against Internet Censorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also a lot of really great stuff on the net that
children's online networks would never capture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to parents to decide whether these services, some of
which use filters themselves, are better than such leading
filtering software as SurfWatch and Cyber Patrol. A truly enclosed
environment might be more prohibitive than the strictest filter,
Fagin said.
</P>
<P>
   Enclosed communities are good for busy parents who might not
have time to scrutinize their children's computer use, he said, but
``there is no substitute for parental involvement and it would be a
mistake to become too complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   For three years, Marney Morris, an interactive software
designer, has worked on creating such a closed environment for an
educational service called SprocketWorks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we said, you know what? That's not the spirit of the
Web,'' Ms. Morris said. ``And we got feedback from parents, too,
who said, `We don't want our kids restrained.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, anyone can visit the Web site, www.sprocketworks.com,
where youngsters can use e-mail and do such things s follow stocks
in selected companies (such as The Gap) on the mock Sprock Market.
The site also encourages parents to order a series of educational
CD-ROMs from the Palo Alto-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Seema Williams, an industry analyst with Forrester Research,
predicts that scholastic networks that help teachers pull the
Internet into the classroom will soon make it into the home market
as well. Good educational content, she said, is what will sell
parents on the idea of plunking down $10, $20 or $30 a month for a
subscription service.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the real challenge for these guys right now: Are they
able to offer enough of extra value that is not available free on
line?'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
