<HEADER>
A5236 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIETNAMESEDISHES-2700     03-10 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAMESEDISHES-2700-(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAMESE CUISINE EXTRACTS A WORLD OF FLAVOR AND TEXTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vietnam's food is a happy result of bad times.
</P>
<P>
   This swath of land between China and India has long been coveted
by outside forces. In earliest times, it was the Mongols from China
who came over the bordering mountains to exert their will. Later,
in this century, the French came colonizing, bringing Catholicism
and their system of government. In between, this verdant land was
visited by Portuguese traders and Japanese occupiers.
</P>
<P>
   This historic uproar has resulted in a cuisine that incorporates
elements from all those nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Mongols brought a love of beef, evident in the country's
national dish, ``pho.'' Pho is a broth of noodles and beef stock
garnished with any of various pieces of beef described at great
length on menus. The Vietnamese don't distinguish foods for various
meals, and pho is a popular breakfast item. The Chinese-Vietnamese
populations also brought ingredients such as hoisin sauce and
oyster sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The French were another big influence, bringing their fine bread
(used today to make submarine sandwiches garnished with chopped
pepper and cilantro). The French also introduced their intensely
roasted coffee. The Vietnamese added sweetened condensed milk to
make their own version of cafe au lait.
</P>
<P>
   But through it all, the Vietnamese have put their own stamp on
the food. It's lighter than the food of neighbors _ and the
interplay of cooked ingredients served with raw ingredients, smooth
ingredients punched up with crunchy ingredients, is the hallmark of
this delicate fare.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a cuisine of technique, but rather one of texture
and taste.
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP ON SUGAR CANE (CHAO TOM)
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 to 6 appetizer servings
</P>
<P>
   Nuoc cham dipping sauce, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   1 pound medium shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   1-inch piece rock sugar
</P>
<P>
   1-ounce piece fresh white pork fat
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch or potato starch
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large white of scallion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   12-inch-long piece sugar cane, cut crosswise into 4 (3-inch)
pieces, then split lengthwise in half and in half again, or 1 can
sugar cane in syrup, pieces split, see Note
</P>
<P>
   Boston lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   Mint sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Cucumber slices
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you can find it in good condition, use fresh sugar
cane, but the canned sticks packed in syrup are also excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the nuoc cham dipping sauce and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Spread shrimp out in an even layer on a baking sheet and freeze
until very firm, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In mortar, pound rock sugar to a coarse powder. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan of boiling water over high heat, cook the
pork fat until translucent, about 2 minutes. Drain and cut into
tiny dice.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the shrimp from the freezer and with a large, sharp knife
chop them fine. Add the pork fat and continue chopping until a
coarse paste forms, leaving some small pieces of shrimp. Put the
mixture in a bowl and stir in the pounded sugar, baking powder,
cornstarch, pepper, salt, and white of scallion until well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   With oiled hands, take about 3 tablespoons of the shrimp mixture
and wrap it evenly around a piece of sugar cane, leaving about 1/2
inch exposed on both ends. Repeat with the remaining shrimp and
sugar cane. You should have about 10 shrimp sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Oil a steamer basket and place the shrimp sticks evenly apart on
it. In a large saucepan, bring 1 inch of water to a boil over high
heat. Put in the basket, cover, and steam the shrimp sticks until
almost cooked through, about 3 minutes. Preheat the broiler or
grill.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the steamer basket from the pan and, if broiling, put the
shrimp sticks on a baking sheet. Broil about 5 inches from the
heat, turning often, until deep brown on all sides, about 3
minutes. Or grill the shrimp sticks over a hot fire, turning often.
Serve hot. To eat, remove the shrimp from the cane, wrap it in
lettuce with sprigs of mint and slices of cucumber, and dip it in
the nuoc cham. Chew on the sugar cane if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Nuoc cham dipping sauce (nuoc mam cham):
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 small fresh red chiles, minced, or 1 to 2 teaspoons dried
pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white vinegar, heated
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup bottled fish sauce (nuoc mam)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 small carrot, finely shredded, rinsed and squeezed dry
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   If using dried chile flakes, soak them in the vinegar in a
medium bowl for about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the bowl with the chiles, add the bottled fish sauce, lime
juice, carrot, garlic and sugar. Stir in 1 1/2 cups warm water
until the sugar is dissolved. Serve at room temperature. Store in a
jar in the refrigerator for up to 3 days.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving, including dipping sauce: 222
calories, 6 grams fat, 28 grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 98
milligrams cholesterol, 1,723 milligrams sodium, 24 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Simple Art of Vietnamese Cooking'' by Binh Duong and Marcia
Kiesel (Prentice Hall, $30)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GREEN PAPAYA SALAD (GOI DU DU)
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   Sour lime sauce, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds green papaya, split, seeded, peeled, and cut into
long, thin strips, see Glossary
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound lean shoulder or loin of pork
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound medium shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped peanuts
</P>
<P>
   Chile sauce, see Glossary
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the sour lime sauce and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl of ice water, soak the papaya to crisp it, about
10 minutes. Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan of boiling water, simmer the pork over
medium heat until cooked through, about 15 minutes. Drain and let
cool slightly. Cut into long, thin strips.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan of boiling water, cook the shrimp over high
heat for about a minute. Drain, cool and cut in half lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   Put the papaya in a very large bowl. Add the pork, shrimp and
sour lime sauce and toss. Put the salad on a large platter and
sprinkle with the cilantro and peanuts. Pass the chile sauce
separately at the table.
</P>
<P>
   This salad is especially good with shrimp chips (see Glossary).
</P>
<P>
   Sour lime sauce (nuoc mam chanh):
</P>
<P>
   1 small red chile, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 large lime, peeled and sectioned, any juice squeezed and
reserved
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
