<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5239 &Cx1f; tth-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-CONGRESS-SPI &LR;      03-10 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CONGRESS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS, COMPANIES WARY OF Y2K LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Executives at Alstom Esca, a midsized Bellevue
software company, think they're ready for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which makes energy management programs for
electrical utilities, has tweaked and tested its product. Managers
even plan to dispatch an employee to New Zealand on New Year's Eve
so they can watch the software's reaction to 2000 from a country
close to the international date line and then phone back any alerts
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company's president, Alain Steven, says he is confident his
software won't be afflicted by the millennium bug. But Steven has
another worry: lawsuits that could somehow ensnare his company if
anything goes wrong in the complex world of utilities for which he
makes a small part.
</P>
<P>
   Now, egged on by the concerns of businesses ranging from the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce to tiny Puget Sound software companies,
Congress is debating three measures that would restrict lawsuits
arising from damage caused by computers that fail to recognize the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of Y2K liability reform is being promoted by Sen.
Slade Gorton, R-Wash., as well as numerous other lawmakers who
argue that fear of lawsuits is diverting resources from fixing the
problem. The supporters cite a variety of studies warning of a
potential explosion of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Software companies and software users should concentrate all
of their attention on solving the Y2K problem, and not be
distracted by litigation,'' said Gorton, who has tried
unsuccessfully to rein in other types of product liability
lawsuits. ``The goal is to see to it that we solve the problem, not
enrich lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation is hotly opposed by trial lawyers, consumer
groups and the Clinton administration, who worry that businesses
and individuals will lose legal recourse to which they are
entitled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real mistake to talk about restricting rights before we
even know what the problem is,'' said Mike Misner, a Gig Harbor
attorney who counsels companies and lawyers on Y2K liability
issues. ``When Congress starts limiting people's access to courts
or damages, it usually creates a bigger problem than the one they
tried to fix.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is this: Many computer programs use only two digits
to identify a calendar year, making the assumption that all dates
are during the 20th century. The fear is that, left as is, those
programs will mistake 2000 for 1900, and will fail.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Senate Commerce Committee, more than 40
lawsuits arising from the Y2K bug have already been filed. In one
highly publicized case, a group of doctors sued a Florida software
company that wanted to charge them to replace medical office
software that would crash in 2000. The company, Medical Manager
Corp., settled the case by providing the doctors with a free
upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   One expert told a congressional panel last year that ``Y2K has
the potential to become the most litigious event in the history of
civilization,'' and cited a Lloyds of London report estimating that
dealing with the year 2000 _ changing software as well as defending
lawsuits _ will cost $1 trillion in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the litigation resulting from Y2K-related failures is
anything like experts are predicting ... the courthouses will be at
standing room only and Y2K litigation will last for years into the
next millennium,'' said Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, chairman of
the Senate Special Committee on the Year 2000 Technology Problem.
</P>
<P>
   The measures moving through Congress would not prohibit
lawsuits, but would attempt to restrict them by imposing a 90-day
cooling off period in which consumers must notify businesses of a
Y2K problem and allow them an opportunity to fix it. The bills also
limit punitive damages and class-action lawsuits and encourage the
use of arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   One of the measures is co-sponsored by Rep. Jennifer Dunn,
R-Wash. The measures are generally supported by Republicans and
opposed by Democrats, but one is co-sponsored by Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that we need to be certain that Y2K problems are
not going to result in any economic hardship for a responsible
company that is working to solve the problem,'' said Sen. John
Kerry, D-Mass, whose state is home to numerous technology
companies. ``But at the same time, we don't want to ... wind up
protecting the negligent company that has failed to meet the
appropriate standard for fixing a negligent product.''
</P>
<P>
   The measures were proposed by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the
National Association of Manufacturers and the National Federation
of Independent Business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main concern of the business community is that they don't
get forced to divert resources from fixing the problem to a flood
of lawsuits,'' said Jim Wootton, director of the Institute for
Legal Reform at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has expressed concern about the
proposals. Assistant Attorney General Eleanor Acheson, testifying
about one proposal, said, ``Our preliminary analysis indicates this
bill would be by far the most sweeping litigation reform measure
ever enacted.'' She called some of the provisions ``extremely
unfair,'' and said others might encourage businesses to slow their
Y2K readiness programs.
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers argue that it is unfair to restrict the lawsuits
for a problem that they call ``the most expensive negligence in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Misner, the Gig Harbor attorney, said that he anticipates both
businesses and individuals might have reason to file suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone is on a ventilator, and it fails, and that failure
can be traced to a Y2K complication, that patient or patient's
family probably won't be pleased if someone says you can't sue or
your damages are limited,'' Misner pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, already a defendant in one year 2000 lawsuit over the
Foxpro database program, is staying out of the congressional fray.
The company says it is focusing its efforts on debugging its
software, rather than steeling for litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers have been very clear to us that Y2K is the No. 1
issue they're facing, and if it's the No. 1 customer issue, we're
going to have the resources and tools for them,'' said Microsoft
Y2K Product Manager Don Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said 93 percent of the 2,000 programs tested by Microsoft
to date are largely free of the Y2K bug. ``We don't expect to get
sued.''
</P>
<P>
   But other companies, particularly those with fewer legal
resources, are worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``All major companies are concerned about surviving and making
sure they come out OK,'' said Joyce Shui, vice president for legal
affairs at Data Dimensions, a Bellevue consulting firm that advises
Fortune 500 companies on Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at companies are so desperately interested in staying
in business _ they've got a very powerful incentive (to prevent a
problem.) They don't need the threat of litigation,'' Shui added.
</P>
<P>
   Steven, the Alstom Esca executive, warned that the issue could
have widespread negative impact in the Puget Sound, with its
concentration of small software companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of companies can be caught up in the Y2K liability
issue and put out of business, even if they don't have anything to
do with the problem,'' Steven says. ``For a company our size,
dealing with one case is very expensive. If we end up stuck in the
middle of 10 different cases, we're out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should he worry if his product works? Steven says that if
anything goes wrong in the complex and interconnected world of
electricity transmission, lawyers searching for defendants will
target his company even if his software functions correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about getting caught in the net, because a power
plant is going to trip somewhere that has nothing to do with us,''
he said. ``Imagine a couple of power plants go off line as a result
of the Y2K bug. Industrial consumers may declare that because they
lost power for a day, they're going to cast a net as wide as
possible and go after all the companies involved. That's the kind
of abuse that I see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
