<HEADLINE>
DOING A LITTLE POLITICAL TIRE-KICKING IN AUSTIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon, in the Austin Convention Center, auto
dealers were showing off their wares. For the bargain price of $5,
would-be car buyers could peruse a dazzling array of vehicles
produced by a dazzling array of carmakers.
</P>
<P>
   There were sport utility vehicles; there were coupes and sedans
of every size and shape. There was the ever-popular Corvette and
the eye-catching new Chevy Impala.
</P>
<P>
   Car shoppers' heaven.
</P>
<P>
   And just a short stroll down the hall, in Ballroom A, the
national media were kicking the tires on the
soon-to-be-ready-for-the-showroom presidential campaign of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was Bush's official announcement that he was
forming an exploratory committee to raise money and measure support
for a possible White House run in next year's Republican primaries.
Calling Sunday's event a ``news'' conference was a stretch, of
course; it occurred five days after Bush tipped off Texas reporters
that he would take the first major step toward a formal campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The governor had promised the home-state new media that they
would be the first to know. That he made good on his pledge should
have surprised no one; he has made a habit of keeping his promises.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every plank of Bush's 1994 platform became state law
during his first term as governor _ and there is no reason to doubt
that he will steer most of his 1998 campaign promises through the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has vowed to postpone any active campaigning for the
presidency until the legislative session concludes at the end of
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person who does in office what I say I will do,'' Bush
said. ``Last year, I told the people of Texas I did not know
whether I would seek the presidency, and they should factor that in
when they went to vote. I also told them I would be here this
spring ... fighting for a bold agenda of tax cuts and education,
welfare and criminal justice reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Legislature adjourns, Bush said, he and wife Laura
``intend to begin traveling to meet with people, to listen to
people and to explore on our own the prospect of a campaign for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize his determination to do his job as governor first,
Bush declined to answer reporters' questions seeking his positions
on national and international issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I leave the state and move around the country, I'll be
talking about all these issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters also wanted to know how George W. Bush the governor
would distinguish himself from George Bush the former president,
who happens to be the governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the newshounds were thinking about the car show, where
passers-by gawked at the highly touted 2000 Impala and wondered
what was new and exciting about this car that carries the name of a
Chevy that symbolized a proud but long-gone era in automotive
history.
</P>
<P>
   Bush didn't offer a detailed comparison of father and son, but
he predicted that ``over the course of time, people will be able to
distinguish differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush added that his father is a man of ``enormous integrity and
decency, and he handled his most important job of all as good as
anybody can do it _ and that is being a dad.''
</P>
<P>
   One obvious distinction between would-be President Bush and
used-to-be President Bush is the makeup of the governor's campaign
team.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-member exploratory committee that Bush introduced Sunday
included longtime Republican mainstays such as former Secretary of
State George Shultz and ex-national chairman Haley Barbour as well
as emerging GOP stars such as Reps. Henry Bonilla of Texas, J.C.
Watts of Oklahoma and Jennifer Dunn of Washington _ but no central
figures from the Bush White House.
</P>
<P>
   Other distinctions will become evident, as Bush promised, over
the course of time.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that car buyers will like that new Impala. I'm
certain that voters will like this new Bush.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
