u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     03-10 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
G3: BLUE AND WHITE AND DIFFERENT ALL OVER, EXCEPT THE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The official name of Apple's most powerful and most stylish
Macintosh is the Power Macintosh G3. Apple Computer, which has been
creative in so many other ways recently and whose current motto is
``Think Different,'' apparently was thinking undifferent that day
and merely recycled the name from an earlier, uglier model also
known as the Power Macintosh G3.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Apple's loyal customers quickly dubbed the new
machine the G3 Blue and White, in an attempt to distinguish this
innovative new desktop machine from its boring, beige and boxy G3
predecessor, which has been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   The new G3 is a gorgeous computer, at least to my eye, far more
interesting than its smaller and cuter but more annoying little
sibling, the iMac. It is unmistakable with its pillow-like curves,
love handles and unconventional color scheme _ translucent blue and
white plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Picasso, one of several deceased celebrities and rebels
whom Apple has enlisted to sell its new line of computers, would
have approved of the bold design, the ads suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Or would he? The master had an eye for imperfection as well as
perfection, and the new G3 has its share of flaws. These
shortcomings are not serious enough to dissuade loyal Macintosh
users from coveting the G3, but they may be annoying enough to keep
undecided customers from joining, or rejoining, the Macintosh
family.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the popular iMac, which comes in five different fruit
colors (blueberry and grape are by far the most popular, retailers
report), the new G3 comes in blueberry only. But the G3 processor
itself comes in three versions: mild, or 300 megahertz; spicy, or
350 MHz, and hot, 400 MHz.
</P>
<P>
   The mildest version costs $1,599, not including monitor, and the
spiciest costs $2,999, although by adding options and necessities
you can easily spend more than $5,000 for a fancy system.
</P>
<P>
   While those current offerings hold their own, and sometimes
surpass, rival systems based on the Intel Corp.'s Pentium II line,
the recent arrival of Pentium III systems highlights Apple's
challenge to match Windows-based machines on price and performance.
A new crop of faster Pentium IIIs is coming before June.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with earlier Macintoshes, however, the new G3 computers
are much faster, thanks in part to a faster internal data bus and
more special, high-speed memory called backside cache.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which makes Apple's Power PC G3 chips, recently
disclosed details of the successor G4 chip, which, like Intel's
Pentium III, has a new set of instructions designed to accelerate
the performance of multimedia applications like 3D graphics, video
and audio. Apple has not publicly discussed plans to add the G4 to
its product line, but Motorola said it would be shipping the chips
in volume before summer. Beyond power, features are the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The new G3s come with an array of connection ports for attaching
peripherals. These consist of two high-speed Firewire ports, two
Universal Serial Bus (USB) ports, one Apple Desktop Bus (ADB) port
and a fast Ethernet port for linking the computer to a network.
</P>
<P>
   Firewire is a new connection method, developed by Apple, to
transfer data at high speeds (up to 400 megabits per second)
between the computer and a variety of peripheral devices that need
higher-speed connections to the PC _ digital video and still
cameras, storage devices and so on. Only about 100 Firewire
devices, mostly video cameras, are available today.
</P>
<P>
   Firewire is good. USB is good. The problem arises from Apple's
decision to drop connectors for older SCSI and serial
peripherals.(Apple had the good sense to retain one ADB port for
attaching older keyboards and mice, which is a profound relief
since the new G3 also uses the horrible round mouse and skeletal
keyboard that Apple first foisted on iMac buyers.)
</P>
<P>
   And echoing its unfortunate decision with the iMac, Apple has
not included a floppy drive with the new G3. Apple contends that
the floppy diskette is a thing of the past and that users ought to
be able to choose from a variety of newer alternative portable
storage devices.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that means the customer has to pay at least $100 or
$200 extra for an Iomega Zip drive, an Imation Superdisk drive or
some other variant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Apple contends that SCSI is old-fashioned, too, but
what about customers who have invested lots of money in SCSI
devices? They can pay $50 or more for a SCSI expansion card to put
into one of the precious expansion slots, Apple says. There have
been some compatibility problems with early SCSI cards.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a serial port can be addressed by converting one of
the two standard Universal Serial Bus (USB) ports to a serial port,
again at added cost. Attaching an older, non-USB printer to the G3
requires yet another adapter, at yet another cost.
</P>
<P>
   These are annoyances, as is Apple's decision to cover up the
headphone jack and volume control on the front of the new G3s
built-in CD-ROM drive. An Apple spokeswoman said it was not a
design flaw. ``The customer is expected to connect the headphones
from the rear of the computer,'' she said. Well, of course. They
were just thinking different.
</P>
<P>
   Such decisions do not make the Power Macintosh G3 easier to use,
and that is the main problem. Ease of use is one of the traditional
strengths of the Macintosh line. If Apple is to gain market share
from Windows machines, it has to be the champion for ease of use,
not just brightly colored plastic.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the new G3 has scored a huge advance with its
innovative drop-down side, which makes it refreshingly easy to gain
access to the computer's internal slots and components. Anyone who
has struggled to open the case of a computer will appreciate the
simplicity and elegance of Apple's drop-down design, which lays out
the main circuit board flat on the table. Brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   And Apple has taken the right step by including an ATI Rage 128
graphics card with 16 megabytes of video RAM, which means the
computer is an excellent game machine. I've been using the spicy,
350-MHz G3 to play the Mac version of ``Myth II: Soulblighter,''
which is a delightful strategy game for anyone who enjoys attacking
demons with an army of homicidal dwarves, warlocks, archers and
swordsmen (www.bungie.com).
</P>
<P>
   The Mac was about equal to the Micron Millennia Max, a 500-MHz
Pentium III machine that came with a formidable 3D graphics system
of its own, a testament to the power of the G3 and its graphics
subsystem. The only drawback was trying to navigate through the
game using the Mac's miserable mouse and keyboard, whose dinky
arrow keys were basically unusable, especially in the heat of
battle.
</P>
<P>
   The best news of all, however, is that Apple this week cut
prices of its Powerbook G3 laptop computers by hundreds of dollars,
bringing the base price below $2,000 for the first time. These
stylish portables, which have 14.1-inch screens, can do double duty
as desktop computers by attaching a normal keyboard, a normal mouse
and a normal monitor through its normal, albeit old-fashioned,
connection ports.
</P>
<P>
   They are not svelte, but they are impressive, and now they are a
better bargain than ever. Until the end of April, Apple will toss
in an extra 64 megabytes of RAM or a copy of the Connectix Corp.'s
Virtual PC software, with Windows 98, at no extra charge. Virtual
PC allows a Mac to run both Mac OS and Windows programs.
</P>
<P>
   The price cuts, which are as much as $800 on some models, signal
that Apple is getting ready to introduce a new generation of
portable computers. These new portables will round out Apple's
revamped product line, especially at the lower range of the price
scale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
