<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIPHER-PROFILE-ART-90     03-10 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPHER-PROFILE-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURING FOREIGN TERRITORY: OLD AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ Mary Pipher, the psychologist whose book about
adolescent girls, ``Reviving Ophelia,'' was a phenomenal best
seller, was walking on the prairie near her home at sunset, showing
off the quiet beauty of winter in Nebraska. She walks here with her
writers' group for women on weekends, she said, and it is where
they like to celebrate New Year's Day. She walked on the prairie a
lot during the 11 months her mother lay dying in a hospital in
Kansas in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   This is the landscape, undramatic and Midwestern, that has
shaped her life and thinking, and landscape is the metaphor she
uses to explore aging in her new book, ``Another Country: The
Emotional Terrain of Our Elders,'' which will be published on March
15 by Riverhead. As in ``Reviving Ophelia'' (Putnam, 1994) which is
as much social critique as psychological treatise, Dr. Pipher, 51,
views aging through the lens of the anthropologist she set out to
be in college. In ``Another Country,'' she observes that to grow
old for many people in today's fragmented, age-phobic,
age-segregated America is to inhabit a foreign country, isolated,
disconnected and misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xenophobia means fear of people from another country,'' she
writes. ``In America we are xenophobic toward our old people.'' She
says she hopes her book can be a guide to that other country and
offer ways for the generations to reconnect. ``The more we love and
respect our elders,'' she writes, ``the more we teach our children
to love and respect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pipher (the name is pronounced PYE-fer) said she has always
loved older people, and her book started out as a way to get
reacquainted with her five aunts, Grace, Henrietta, Margaret, Agnes
and Betty, who are all in their 80s. ``I thought, I'll go and hang
out with my aunts and interview them,'' Dr. Pipher said. ``They're
all wonderful and quirky.''
</P>
<P>
   But she eventually expanded her focus to include the stories of
many other Midwesterners, men and women who have been shaped by the
Depression, World War II and the hardships of rural life. She
describes them as the last generation to have come of age in a
communal culture, and writes that what also defines them, and
causes conflict with their baby boomer children, is that they are
pre-therapy and pre-irony.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pipher says she deliberately chose not to write a book about
90-year-old marathon runners and tennis players and other
age-defying men and women held up as exemplars of ``successful''
aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to explore the experiences of ordinary people.'' she
said. ``And many ordinary people are heroic.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordinary people she interviewed for her book ``know about
loss, ill health and diminishment,'' she writes, adding that ``they
cope with experiences that would take down a younger person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The two things I love most to do are walk and read,'' Dr.
Pipher said. ``I can't imagine not being able to walk and read.
Many older people lose all the things I love.'' The loss is made
doubly difficult, Dr. Pipher writes, in a culture that worships
autonomy and independence. Older people are made to feel ashamed
for needing help. ``They want to be kind and strong,'' she writes,
``and, in America, they learn that to do so means they should ask
little of others and not bother young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pipher knows something about loss and diminishment herself.
One of her retinas became detached two years ago and, at home
during a record blizzard, she was unable to get to a doctor. She
lost the vision in her right eye. ``It started me thinking about my
own aging, how to prepare for it,'' she said. ``I wanted to see how
old people cope.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the morning after the sunset walk on the prairie, and she
was talking in one of her favorite indoor places, the Mill, a
friendly, bustling coffeehouse in downtown Lincoln where the tables
are shared by college students, musicians, mothers, children and
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pipher is wearing beige jeans, a blue cotton turtleneck,
Birkenstocks with socks and no makeup. Her curly graying blond hair
is still damp from her morning swim at the University of Nebraska
at Lincoln. She warmly greets several people she knows, but her
presence does not draw any particular attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reviving Ophelia,'' which described how adolescent girls lose
their identities in a culture obsessed with looks, was on the New
York Times paperback best-seller list for 154 weeks. Dr. Pipher
draws sellout crowds wherever she speaks, has been invited to the
White House by Hillary Rodham Clinton and was anointed ``a guru
from Nebraska'' by Newsweek. But in Lincoln, where she arrived in
the early 1970s to go to graduate school in psychology and never
left, she is still just Mary.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband Jim, 49, who is a psychologist and a jazz
and bluegrass musician, have lived a dozen years in a modest stone
house full of books, guitars and family photos in an old
neighborhood south of downtown. They drive a nine-year-old Honda.
They have had the same friends for decades. The couple have two
children, a son and a daughter, in their early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a really strange, paradoxical way, the reason I've ended up
being a popular writer is that I'm very ordinary,'' Dr. Pipher
said. ``I've had the same sort of experiences most middle-class,
middle-aged people have. I've taken my kids to Yellowstone and gone
to a lot of potluck dinners with friends, and so on.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   One Midwesterner who inspired ``Another Country'' was certainly
not ordinary, and that was Dr. Pipher's mother, Avis Bray, who
managed to raise seven children and work a grueling schedule as a
small-town doctor in Nebraska and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd get up in the morning,'' Dr. Pipher said, ``drive 20
miles to a hospital, do her rounds, work at her own clinic, maybe
do house calls in the evening, and the phone would ring at night,
and she'd go sit by some older farmer while he died.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Bray did not draw on her experience with illness and
death when it came to confronting her own decline, from diabetes
and its complications. ``She was in fairly strong denial about her
illness, and her death,'' Dr. Pipher said. ``I don't want to be
critical about my mother, but she wasn't a good role model in terms
of that. She was a wonderful role model in other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pipher, the oldest daughter, writes of driving on weekends
to visit her mother in the hospital three hours away, and of trying
to handle her medical care, while at the same time juggling her
responsibilities as a mother of two teen-agers, a writer and a
psychotherapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That year, no matter where I was, I felt guilty,'' she says in
the book. ``If I was with my mother, I wasn't caring for my own
kids or my clients. If I wasn't working, I was ignoring my family.
When I was with my children, I thought of my mother alone in a
faraway hospital. I got depressed and crabby.''
</P>
<P>
   It was her mother, Dr. Pipher said, who without knowing it set
her on the path toward becoming a writer back when she was a young
girl. ``I'd ride with her, and she'd tell me stories about her
childhood, about her patients,'' Dr. Pipher recalled. ``That's
where I started getting really interested in stories. She was a
really good storyteller.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were early impediments to Dr. Pipher's translating her
fascination with stories into writing. When she confided to her
father, Frank Bray, that she dreamed of becoming a writer, he
discouraged her, she said, explaining that writers don't make any
money.
</P>
<P>
   Encouragement did not come at school, either. She was about 12
when she wrote a sonnet about the seasons, which her teacher marked
``trite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up on writing,'' she said. ``I just gave up. I thought,
I don't have any talent, and my dad says even if I were talented, I
couldn't make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   She got her undergraduate degree in anthropology at the
University of California at Berkeley. But in 1969, the year she
graduated, jobs and graduate school financial aid were scarce. So
when Nebraska offered her a five-year fellowship in psychology, she
took it. She met her husband the first day of graduate school in
Lincoln. Psychology turned out to be the right choice for
professional reasons, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just a therapist to the bone,'' Dr. Pipher said. ``I'm
fascinated by people, I love to listen to people's stories, and,
modestly speaking, I'm very good at problem solving.''
</P>
<P>
   Through her 20s and into her early 30s, she was busy seeing
patients as a therapist, teaching at the university and raising her
children. But when her younger child entered fourth grade,
something happened. ``I decided, `I want to write,' '' Dr. Pipher
recalled. `` `I will do it even if nobody ever sees a word I
write.'''
</P>
<P>
   She took a writing class at the university. Her teacher was an
ex-football coach from Texas named Charles Stubblefield. ``After my
first story, he said, `You know, you can be a writer if you want.'
'' She started writing every morning _ book reviews, fiction,
essays, commentary for National Public Radio. Her first short story
was published by The Cottonwood Review at the University of Kansas
and won a prize. In the 1980s, she published her first book,
``Hunger Pains,'' about women and their obsession with thinness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reviving Ophelia'' was rejected by 13 publishers before
landing on the desk of a New York publisher, Jane Isay. ``I read
this proposal for `Reviving Ophelia' from an unknown agent, and I
thought, `I have to publish this,''' said Ms. Isay, who is now the
editor in chief of Harcourt Brace.
</P>
<P>
   In a following book, ``The Shelter of Each Other: Rebuilding Our
Families'' (1996), she observed that families are under siege in a
culture that's driven by technology, money and the media.
</P>
<P>
   The women in Dr. Pipher's writers' group continue to read her
work, offering encouragement and inspiration, she said. They are
all around the same age, she said, and lately they have been
talking about what it will be like when they are old. ``We plan to
be together,'' she said, suggesting that down the line the group
might even set up house together.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she has visited the other country she said she is less
afraid of growing old, in part because of some of the people she
has met. She writes that she learned about the importance of
remaining engaged in the world from Jane Jarvis, still a jazz
musician at 81, and from Sally Gordon, who at 89 holds two jobs in
the Nebraska state government and volunteers at a senior center.
She says she learned about acceptance from an 86-year-old woman
named Alma, who for 66 years not only cared for her profoundly
retarded daughter but embraced the burden.
</P>
<P>
   To love our elders, she said, we have to know them. ``Take your
children to visit their grandparents,'' she said. ``Send them to
spend the summer with an elderly aunt.'' She encourages people to
just sit with their aging parents. ``So many times people send
flowers to their mothers,'' she said. ``Their mothers really don't
want flowers. They want them.''
</P>
<P>
   And she says the younger generation has much to offer. ``I
really do believe that our generation also has a lot to teach about
coping, including the idea that you talk things over, and you tell
the truth, and you say what needs to be said,'' Dr. Pipher said.
``After all, our generation in many families taught our parents to
hug and say `I love you.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
