<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5273 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ARCHITECTURE-ART-     03-10 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ARCHITECTURE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTLES, AND PLANETARIUMS, IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No engineering degree is needed to appreciate how useful a
computer would be in designing an 87-foot steel sphere capable of
holding 585 people at once, apparently floating on air in the
center of a giant glass cube, neither suspended from its top pole
nor supported at its bottom.
</P>
<P>
   However, the architects of the new Hayden Planetarium, which is
to open at the American Museum of Natural History in Manhattan
early next year, are (italics)really(end italics) marveling at
their ability to design something that is three-sixteenths of an
inch tall.
</P>
<P>
   That is the height of the lozenge-shaped acoustical cutouts _
5,599,663 of them _ that will perforate the skin of the planetarium
sphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never have attempted that by hand,'' said Todd H.
Schliemann of the Polshek Partnership, the New York architectural
firm that designed the planetarium and the surrounding Frederick
Phineas and Sandra Priest Rose Center for Earth and Space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five and a half million perforations you don't attempt by
hand,'' Schliemann said.
</P>
<P>
   In ways big and small, computer-aided design _ CAD for short _
is changing the built environment. Any doubt about that was
dispelled in 1997 when the world first glimpsed the undulating,
titanium-clad surfaces of the Guggenheim Museum designed by Frank
O. Gehry in Bilbao, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was engineered with Catia, by Dassault Systemes
(www.dsweb.com), a software program that was also used to design
the Boeing 777.
</P>
<P>
   By making possible engineering feats that would have been
impractical in the past, computers are ratcheting up the wow factor
in architecture, that feeling of utter astonishment in those who
behold buildings whose forms defy orthogonal convention and _ it
sometimes seems _ even gravity itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wow factor _ not in the sense of gimmickry but in the
power of the reality of the world around us _ is a most exciting
thing,'' said Ellen V. Futter, president of the American Museum of
Natural History. ``It's the beginning of people wanting to learn
and understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing that sphere seeming to float, with nothing holding it
up at the south pole, will have that effect. The average person's
reaction will be, `I want to get in there.' And the good news is,
you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Invited by Ms. Futter to let his mind run free, James Stewart
Polshek, of the Polshek Partnership, happened on the sphere idea in
early 1995 while looking at a cross section of the old Hayden
Planetarium. Completed in 1935 and well loved for generations, the
building was distinguished by a copper dome 75 feet in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Polshek placed the point of a compass on the center point of the
dome in the drawing and twirled the instrument around until it
formed a full circle. Epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I then began to get nervous because I wondered how in the
world would we ever be able to represent this to a client,''
Polshek recalled. ``The CAD system allowed us to develop multiple
views, inside the box, outside the box and from a variety of
angles. And I knew we had something.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology informed every step in the design. Besides the
startlingly realistic renderings that were used to convince the
client, impress donors and pacify neighbors, there were skeletal
outlines known as wire-frame views, animated vignettes of changing
sunlight patterns, studies predicting temperature and lighting
levels, and structural drawings refined enough to send via e-mail
directly to the fabricator of the sphere panels in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sphere appears to float, it actually rises from a
tripod of steel legs. They support a circular truss on which the
upper hemisphere rests and from which the lower hemisphere is
suspended.
</P>
<P>
   In the upper hemisphere will be the 432-seat Space Theater,
where a Zeiss star projector and a Zeiss video projector will cast
images of the night sky on a dome overhead. In the lower half will
be the Big Bang Theater, where up to 150 viewers will stand on a
circular platform to see the first moments of the formation of the
universe on a curved screen below them.
</P>
<P>
   The theaters are reached by a 320-foot spiral ramp that wraps
around one and a half times, constantly changing in height and
radius.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly simple, the ramp was actually as much of an
engineering challenge as the sphere because none of its dimensions
are constant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of a seashell,'' said James A. Schmidt, an architect who
is the museum's executive director for the Rose Center project.
``In nature, it's beautiful. But when you go to build it, you'd
never be able to figure it out. In theory you could _ physics
hasn't changed. But in practice, you couldn't do it without the
strength of computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than beginning with a laborious calculation of the
coordinates for each point in this intricate structure, the
architects created a virtual model of the spiral form and let the
computer figure out the X, Y and Z.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer is opening up the possibility of more complex
geometries in buildings,'' said V. Guy Maxwell of the Polshek
Partnership. At age 32, he is squarely on one side of the
generational divide between the architects who grew up with pencils
and tracing paper and those who learned through CAD.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell does not even have a Mayline straight-edge rule on his
drafting board, once standard equipment for any architect. Instead,
a visitor to his cubicle finds an animated study running on his
monitor. Intricate, lattice-like shadows are seen gliding silently
over the spherical planetarium surface, as they would in the course
of a day in June.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell speaks of building a ``model'' of a railing that he
needed to study. The model is not made of paper-and-plastic
Foamcore board; it resides in his computer, which runs the software
Microstation, by Bentley Systems (www.bentley.com).
</P>
<P>
   Other widely used programs include Autocad, by Autodesk
(www.autodesk.com), and Archicad, by Graphisoft
(www.graphisoft.com).
</P>
<P>
   Another architect who grew up with CAD is Trent J. Tesch, 28, a
senior designer at the architectural firm of Kohn Pedersen Fox
Associates in New York. ``When you depict form traditionally, it's
in plan, section and elevation,'' he said. ``What CAD allows you to
do is plan the form intuitively, as you think it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the generational divide is Frederick P.
Rose, the New York real estate developer and patron of the Rose
Center, who earned his engineering degree at Yale in 1944 and still
keeps a slide rule at his desk _ ``the last man in captivity to
have one,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much of the Rose Center could have been created
without CAD, he answered firmly, ``We could have designed all of
it.'' Asked how much time it would have taken to do so, he
conceded: ``Ah! Now you've got it. At least three or four times as
long.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the realm of construction, timing is critical _ the cost
and availability of labor and materials can change day by day,
prime development sites cannot be left fallow for long, financing
can dry up in an instant, and tenants can have their own exacting
demands and schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Structural novelty was one of several reasons it took 16 years
and revision upon revision to realize Frank Lloyd Wright's
unorthodox design for the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, which has a
spiraling ramp somewhat akin to that of the Rose Center. CAD has
not necessarily made architects and engineers more imaginative. But
it has made imaginative solutions more feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is the ability to explore alternatives rapidly and
to reach a conclusion on various alternatives that allows you to
make choices,'' said Matthys P. Levy, a principal in Weidlinger
Associates, consulting engineers on the Rose Center. ``The computer
doesn't create the idea, but the computer allows you to make
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   CAD programs have allowed Kohn Pedersen Fox to choose all kinds
of dynamic forms. The Shanghai World Financial Center, for example,
which is to be the tallest building in the world on completion in
2002, will begin as a square block at the base. As it rises, two of
the sides will taper along the lines of intersecting arcs, leaving
a thin slab at the top, 1,509 feet in the air. For good measure,
the upper part of the building is to be penetrated by a
165-foot-high hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the computer,'' said Tomas Hernandez Jr., director of
computer services at the firm, ``most people would seek simpler
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Philip Johnson, who has been designing buildings for more
than half a century, has used CAD in recent years to produce
polymorphous structures like the proposed Cathedral of Hope in
Dallas. The main sanctuary will have 46 different wall planes,
leaning both inward and outward as the building reaches its full
height of 111 feet over the pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all of these shapes and sculptural forms, the computer is
the right vehicle to do this,'' said Alan Ritchie, the partner at
Philip Johnson/Alan Ritchie Architects who is in charge of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, speaking from the older side of the
generational line, Ritchie cautioned, ``We've all got to be very
careful that the tool does not control the master.''
</P>
<P>
   His words were echoed by Polshek, who has just turned 69 and has
been practicing architecture for 35 years. He worries that CAD
encourages architects to be too facile, doing things effortlessly
that once demanded much intellectual discipline and, at the
drafting table, a lot of elbow grease.
</P>
<P>
   ``For architects of my generation, it's a very threatening
tool,'' Polshek said. By the same token, he allowed, ``In a funny
way, it's made me a young designer again because I feel that I can
accomplish things that I thought for a while were getting away from
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Schliemann, of the Polshek firm, grew up in architecture as
computers did. He spent almost a semester at Cornell in 1974
working with a four-inch stack of punch cards to produce a
rudimentary drawing of a simple gable-roofed house. (The
(italics)big(end italics) achievement was to coax the computer into
suppressing the lines on the far side of the house, to make it
appear solid.) His embrace of CAD comes with a few reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A computer doesn't understand gravity,'' Schliemann said. ``In
its bounds there are only X, Y and Z planes. You have to willfully
step away from the seduction of the machine and ask, `Is it telling
me the truth?' I don't doubt that it's calculating truthfully, but
is it the appropriate truth for this time and place?''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the exterior of the Rose Center, CAD was used to
fulfill a mission. ``The main idea was to open the museum to the
public,'' Schliemann said. ``Through the glass wall, you can walk
down the street and look right inside at this spherical artifact.
That entices you.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve a crystalline surface with an overall transparency of
90 percent, the glass panels composing the wall will have no
mullions between them. Rather, they will abut one another, fastened
together at their corners by four-legged stainless steel
``spiders'' attached to struts, which will connect in turn to wall
trusses or hanger rods suspended from the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the computer, we were able to refine things to an
extraordinary degree,'' Schliemann said. CAD-generated renderings
of the wall system are so exquisitely detailed they even show the
faint reflection of the steel spiders on the glass surface.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you the ability to see reality before it exists,''
Schliemann said. ``We can imagine it. The computer
(italics)proved(end italics) it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is an unalloyed benefit. In the past, architects
could count on a structure showing unexpected facets after
completion: a fiery sparkle of windows catching an October sunset,
for example, or a pleasing alignment of columns when seen from a
particular perspective that had not been depicted in the
architectural renderings. Now architects can anticipate all of that
at their desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no surprises, which is too bad,'' Schliemann said.
``I yearn for surprises.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to design a sphere with millions of
perforations, each row different from the next. But how do you
inscribe this complex filigree on the metal panels themselves,
especially when the factory is across the continent?
</P>
<P>
   By e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Because the architects at the Polshek Partnership in New York
used a CAD (computer-aided design) program for the new Rose Center
at the American Museum of Natural History, they were able to send
their drawings electronically to the fabricator, Ceilings Plus of
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At the factory, Polshek's files were converted to a program
based on Autocad software, which could be read by the machinery
that punches out the tiny holes in the aluminum panels, each
one-sixteenth of an inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   The 87-foot sphere, which is to be enclosed in a glass cube,
will be covered by 2,474 panels. The perforations will absorb sound
around the sphere. (Just think of busloads of schoolchildren _
there will be plenty of sound to absorb.) Gary Kawamura of Ceilings
Plus calculated that the design had yielded 5,599,663 perforations.
</P>
<P>
   A computer plotted out the many arrays of perforations that were
needed to insure that the rows lined up evenly on the panels'
irregular surface without creating distracting patterns or
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago, this would have been almost impossible,''
said Albert Kiechle of Ceilings Plus, which was founded in 1932.
The advent of CAD has expanded its business far beyond ceilings and
far beyond Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Architects are e-mailing their Autocad files from Singapore or
China,'' said Nancy Mercolino, the president of Ceilings Plus.
``You can punch out these graphic designs and shapes. It doesn't
matter how they're laid out. What you can draw in Autocad now can
be manufactured at extraordinary rates.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
