<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOPPEN-DESIGN-ART-NYT     03-10 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOPPEN-DESIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: U.K.)  
 TURNING A MINIMALIST EYE ON AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(js) 
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truism No. 1: Divas make pronouncements. Truism No. 2: A diva
hankering to conquer a new continent makes grander pronouncements
than most.
</P>
<P>
   Lionized in Britain but largely unknown here, Kelly Hoppen has
seen the future, and it is beige, accented with sorbet-sweet shots
of aubergine, blackberry and lilac. The future is also sculptured
with concealed, expensively calibrated light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always trying to convince people to spend money on
lighting and buy a sofa later,'' said Ms. Hoppen, 39, whose
recently remodeled home in London has a glass-walled bathroom.
``Rooms only come alive with light, which is something that a lot
of interior designers aren't especially good at. They're just
interested in the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   A designer who is to English residential design what John Pawson
is to the country's architecture scene, Ms. Hoppen creates
interiors that are sleek, minimalist, obsessively finished and
deceptively simple. But unlike the work of the cerebral Pawson,
known here for the Calvin Klein store on Madison Avenue, Ms.
Hoppen's rooms are a bit more populist, warmed by allusions to
Asian culture and humanizing textures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an ethnic look at all, but she gives Oriental design
a crisp contemporary look,'' said Martin Waller, the managing
director of Andrew Martin, a hip British textile company that gave
her its first designer of the year award, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ms. Hoppen's hallmarks is the use of fabric runners,
inspired by obi sashes, flung over tabletops and bed canopies and
deployed as impromptu slipcovers. ``It's easier to throw a runner
over a chair than it is to re-upholster,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Monochromes may dominate Ms. Hoppen's vision of the new
millennium, but the designer is not unaware of their inherent
dullness. Or how to combat it. ``Texture is the new color,'' she
said, with all the gravity of Martha Stewart saying, ``It's a good
thing.'' Which explains why the living room of the Kensington
apartment she shares with her American-born husband, Ed Miller, is
dressed in five types of linen, all shades of beige. And why the
low modernist sofa combines linen upholstery with button-bedecked
cashmere cushions the color of a pencil lead.
</P>
<P>
   The curtains framing the bay windows are linen, too, full-length
and unlined. Says Ms. Hoppen: ``Everything should be sheer, simple,
elegant. Curtains should blow around.''
</P>
<P>
   The comparison between America's diva of homemaking and her
potential English doppelganger is not strained. ``Newspapers and
magazines in England are always calling me the diva of design,''
said Ms. Hoppen, who was born in South Africa. A romantic cataract
of red pre-Raphaelite curls is paired with the determined air of a
self-described ``triple A'' personality. She has already laid a
Martha-like foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hoppen's first book, the Asian-themed ``East Meets West''
(Rizzoli), was published in America last year. This year, Rizzoli
plans to release her book on texture in design, which will be
followed, the designer intends, by a line of paint with carpeting
to match, furniture and rugs.
</P>
<P>
   A popular line of Kelly Hoppen home accessories, priced under
$60, is already on the shelves of Debenhams, an English chain. Ms.
Hoppen compares her work for it to Ms. Stewart's association with
Kmart. A boutique hotel that she designed as ``a hideaway for
plastic surgery patients'' is due to open this year in London, and
she has created a taupe-and-black car interior for Honda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to open shops internationally,'' she said. ``England
first, then the United States, Japan, Germany and France.'' She
paused, blinded not by the glory of her global vision but by the
sheer logic of it. ``What's the point of having ideas if you can't
make them happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Take Ms. Hoppen's apartment, for example, where she and Miller,
``an investment banker, of sorts,'' have lived since 1988. (Each
has been previously married, and they have five children between
them, ages 16 to 31.) Occupying a floor of a Victorian building, it
had been a U-shaped arrangement of four small, dingy apartments. In
just three months, the 2,500-square-foot space was gutted,
remodeled and decorated.
</P>
<P>
   It is not difficult to imagine the reason behind the builders'
speed. ``Every single item is ordered and on site before the work
starts,'' she said. ``There is no margin for excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hoppen's domestic minimalism starts at the front door, which
opens to a limestone-floored entrance hall that broadcasts a
Stanley Kubrick air, at once sinister, sexy and space age. Seven
taupe-lacquered doors stand closed, reflecting an unearthly tide of
light streaming from glassed-in niches in the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Simplicity is key to the Hoppen program. The glass-and-brass
chandelier in the dining room was found in a junk shop and revived
with Porsche car paint. Walls throughout the apartment are
punctuated with support-free shelves that give them the appearance
of floating (under-shelf strip lighting underscores this effect).
In the master bath, Ms. Hoppen removed the legs of a cast-iron tub
and set it up on limed oak blocks.
</P>
<P>
   In the bedroom, curtains are lingerie satin, and the same
shimmering fabric edges the mohair bedspread. Pale pink artificial
pigskin upholsters the headboard, and some of the cushions are
encased in cashmere, others in basket-weave wicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some men say it's very hard core; others call it virginal,''
Ms. Hoppen said, in a tone that implied greater satisfaction with
the former.
</P>
<P>
   What visitors say about the entrance hall doorstops, however,
remains a secret: Ms. Hoppen employs wooden Indian phallic symbols
to hold the lacquered doors open. Martha Stewart, meet Margaret
Mead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
