<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5283 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     03-10 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICKEN SALAD TO CROW ABOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sharon Plankey requested the recipe for the chicken salad served
at the lately departed Bagel Chain restaurant on Hulen Street in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   I love that chicken salad, I have dreams about that chicken
salad, I have devoted prose to that chicken salad. And now it's
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. Here's the history. Thirteen years ago, when Marc
Lopin began his Bagel Chain chain, he used his sister Leslie's
recipes for tuna and chicken salad.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Leslie happens to be married to Yogi Florsheim, who owns
Yogi's Deli farther along Hulen Street. And Yogi's Deli also serves
the chicken salad.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the chicken salad is still available, Leslie and
Yogi were kind enough to give us the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   YOGI'S CHICKEN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12-16
</P>
<P>
   12 chicken breast halves (including skin and bones)
</P>
<P>
   1 onion
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch celery
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches scallions, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons onion salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups light mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Place chicken breasts in stock pot or pots. Chop the onion and
add to the chicken. Halve the celery and roughly chop (one-half
only) and add to the pot or pots. Season with salt and pepper,
cover with water and bring to a boil. After the water has reached a
boil, lower to medium and simmer for 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, slice the scallions (including about 2 inches of the
green part). Finely dice the remaining celery to be about the same
thickness as the scallions.
</P>
<P>
   When the chicken is cooked, remove the pot from the stove and
strain off the liquid. (This stock can be saved and used for
chicken soup or to add to other recipes.) When chicken is cool
enough to handle, remove skin and bones. Chop or shred the chicken,
making sure not to chop or shred too finely. You want texture.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the chicken with remaining ingredients. (You'll be
tempted to add more mayonnaise, but don't. This is plenty, and one
of the things that distinguishes this chicken salad from others.)
Refrigerate until serving. For maximum effect, serve the salad on
Yogi's salt bagels.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving for 16: 221 calories, 11 grams
fat, 3 grams carbohydrates, 26 grams protein, 77 milligrams
cholesterol, 873 milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   On the sweet side: Stephanie Sterie writes, looking for a good
recipe for baklava. Here's one we've run before, a recipe that came
via my mother-in-law from Doris Scott of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   This makes a lovely dessert with a cup of strong tea. And this
is the proper way to make it _ not the lazy man's way often served
in restaurants. Often, the nut mixture is lumped together in one
layer instead of being dispersed throughout the layers.
</P>
<P>
   DORIS SCOTT'S BAKLAVA
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 50 pieces
</P>
<P>
   18 sheets phyllo dough (1-pound box)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds ground nuts (pistachios, pecans, walnuts or a mix
of any or all), fairly powdery (food processor does this well)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon cinnamon, mixed with the ground nuts
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Grease 16-by-11-inch pan. Using 6 sheets of phyllo, place 1 at a
time in pan, brushing butter on each before topping with the next
layer of phyllo. Sprinkle cinnamon/nut mixture on top of the 6
sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Layer 3 more sheets, spreading each with butter. Then add more
nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with 3 more sheets. Top with 6 buttered sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Cut into cross-hatch diagonal strips to form diamond-shaped
pieces before baking.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 1 1/2 hours or until fairly golden. Cool for several
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Syrup:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/4 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Boil syrup until medium consistency. This takes 15 to 20
minutes, and the syrup will still be fairly runny. Pour over cooled
baklava. Let cool before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Tips on handling phyllo: If frozen, dough should be defrosted in
refrigerator. Don't let phyllo get to room temperature, or it will
be too dry to work with. While working, keep dough to be used under
a damp (not soaked) kitchen towel.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per piece: 201 calories, 12 grams fat, 22
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 15 milligrams cholesterol, 89
milligrams sodium, 54 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
