<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-OLD-SIGNS-ART-NYT &LR;      03-10 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OLD-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD AD SIGNS REAPPEAR, YOUNGER ONES VANISH AMID N.Y. CONSTRUCTION
BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You can't miss it. At the corner of Greene and West
Houston Streets, a new billboard for G-Shock watches partially
obscures an early 20th-century sign for the United thread company.
A giant wristwatch, splayed across both advertising panels, appears
to be attached to the building by trompe l'oeil nails. But is the
old sign really old? Or is it new, too?
</P>
<P>
   Such questions crop up often these days, as New York's
construction boom alternately exposes and covers old signs:
advertisements for carriage rentals and patent medicines painted on
brick walls previously hidden by buildings. They appear suddenly,
flashes of the past, when a building is razed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, pedestrians were astonished by a sign that appeared
in the Times Square area at Broadway and 47th Street. Through the
dust of a demolished building, it emerged on the side of the Roxy
delicatessen: J.A. KEAL'S CARRIAGE MANUFACTORY. REPAIRING.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are noticing them more and more,'' said Linda Cooper
Bowen, who wrote an article on the signs in the current issue of
Print magazine. Last year, the New-York Historical Society had a
show of signs photographed by Frank Jump. Ms. Bowen's article
accompanies photos by her husband, Sava Mitrovich, who is preparing
a book, to be called ``The Wall Dog's Art.'' (The itinerant
painters of the signs were called wall dogs.)
</P>
<P>
   Sam Quinones, who painted the G-Shock sign, did not mind
obscuring part of the work of his predecessor. ``There's very
little sentimentality in this business,'' Quinones said. He has
painted over his own work many times, in the same space.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question of saving most of the signs; no landmark
laws apply. ``You can't tell a building owner to save them,'' Ms.
Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   But some forces in the urban economy actually work to preserve
the signs. Buildings erected next to them provide protection from
weathering, producing the eerily fresh look of the 1877 Keal sign.
And since the old paint is lead-based, building owners are
reluctant to sandblast them off.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week, I followed Mitrovich and Ms. Bowen as they
went to photograph another sign. Mitrovich is a city building
inspector who, through his work, discovers signs that can't be seen
from the street.
</P>
<P>
   From a balcony on West 94th Street, he had caught sight of a
sign on the old Hotel Paris to the north, boasting, in red-orange
hues, of the hotel's solarium and cafe. (Many signs that are
invisible from the street were meant to be seen from an elevated
track, Ms. Bowen observed.)
</P>
<P>
   As we left the building, Mitrovich made a confession that
astonished me. ``It's the photographs that are important to me,''
he said. ``I couldn't care less about the signs.''
</P>
<P>
   How we see them seems to depend on our perspective. Unlike her
husband, Ms. Bowen enjoys the faded quality of the signs
themselves. Graphic designers and other ``letterheads'' prize the
signs' block alphabets. For Jump, who is HIV positive, they are a
kind of memento mori. He calls them ``dead signs,'' since the
businesses they advertise are gone. For ad agencies, they are found
objects to be replicated or incorporated, as in the G-Shock sign.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a strange mingling of old and new. When I first
spied the Keal sign, in the wake of seeing the G-Shock ad and
retro-styled signs for Players tobacco and Old Navy, I didn't
believe it _ the paint was so fresh, the letters so realistically
antique. It looked so old I was sure it was brand-new.
</P>
<P>
   Even stranger than how suddenly the signs appear is how fast
they disappear again. Last week, I noticed that the Keal sign was
about to vanish. The wooden frames for the concrete posts of the
Planet Hollywood Hotel are rising to obscure it. An X painted in
bilious green marks the spot for some construction attachment. The
workers I talked to shrugged off any suggestion that it was a shame
to cover the sign. They were as blase as the languid models in the
Banana Republic ads, looming and lounging at once above the old
sign. In days, it will be gone _ again.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Fellini's Roma,'' a famous scene shows subway workers
burrowing into a subterranean chamber filled with ancient wall
paintings. They watch in astonishment as the paintings vanish on
contact with the air. Something similar happens when signs appear,
then disappear, in this far less eternal city.
</P>
<P>
   Some signs have already outlasted one or two generations of
neighboring buildings. In 50 years, given the pace of change in the
city, we may see the Keal sign again. But if we do, in the context
of Gotham future, it will look completely different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
