<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5295 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MUSEE-DU-MONDE-2T     03-10 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MUSEE-DU-MONDE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS ART? THAT CAN MOSTLY DEPEND ON THE CONTEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Context is what people use to make sense of new information. An
unfamiliar word can make sense in a sentence. An unfamiliar place
can have meaning on a map. An isolated event can be significant in
the context of history. Context turns information into knowledge.
It's the difference between a warehouse and a museum.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to art, there are many warehouses of digital
information: image libraries, CD-ROM encyclopedias that
cross-reference everything to everything else. There are cultural
institutions that use famous images to promote their Web sites, but
there are very few digital museums.
</P>
<P>
   Le Plus Beau Musee du Monde (The Most Beautiful Museum in the
World), a CD-ROM published by France Telecom Multimedia, is one of
the best. (It's available in French only; you can view a demo at
www.plusbeaumusee.com.)
</P>
<P>
   In it, there are spectacular works from the most famous art
troves in the world: the Louvre, the Prado, the Guggenheim, the
Museum of Modern Art _ three dozen cultural juggernauts from Taipei
to the Vatican. Le Plus Beau Musee houses the crown jewels of art
history, from the celebrity Old Masters to the marquee idols of
modernism. It's the Western canon's answer to the Hollywood Walk of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also works from China, Southeast Asia, Africa and
pre-Columbian Peru. American Indian art from the Pacific Northwest
and ritual objects from the ancient Near East are stored, cheek by
digital jowl, with medieval manuscripts and Renaissance frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this collection a museum, rather than a digital
warehouse, is the context into which it places these 150 works.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, there is context for each work as a singular
experience. Every piece of art is displayed in high resolution
against a black background. Icons are illuminated by the cursor,
but are otherwise invisible. There are no buttons, no tabs, no
clutter, no distractions. It's a deceptively simple and supremely
elegant interface, with all the hallmarks of good tailoring. The
seams are perfect, and every pocket of information is beautifully
placed.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these pockets contains a different perspective on the
object displayed _ a different context in which to view it. An
hourglass icon generates a time line.
</P>
<P>
   A globe puts the work on a map. Click on the ruler, and a
miniature version of the painting or sculpture appears next to
human figures to create a sense of human scale, which is so often
lost when people view reproductions of art.
</P>
<P>
   Most people think of Dali's ``Persistence of Memory'' is
gigantic because they see it blown up to poster size. But the
painting itself is the size of a paperback. It's important to know
that an artwork is huge _ or tiny _ and Le Plus Beau Musee restores
that context, to great effect. It allows you to take a step back.
</P>
<P>
   It also allows you to step forward. Pass a magnifying lens over
an image, and you can see the texture of canvas or hairline cracks
in 12th-century paint. It's reminiscent of the scene in ``Blade
Runner'' where a photograph is digitally reproduced, systematically
magnified and dissected for its details.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone notices the customers at the front tables of Toulouse
Lautrec's ``Au Moulin Rouge,'' but what about the bald customer in
the back? What about reflections in glass? On a computer screen,
you can get closer to the surface of these paintings than you can
in life because no museum is going to let your nose touch the
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   There are ancient debates about whether it is really possible to
understand a work of art by viewing a representation of it. Those
debates, like theological questions, are not meant to be resolved.
But one certainty does emerge from this CD-ROM: If you're going to
view a reproduction, digital media beats dead trees hands down. And
it's not just because a computer close-up gives you more resolution
than a textbook photograph. It's not a question of resolution. It's
a question of context.
</P>
<P>
   Digital media create a much more intimate context for viewing
art, and the difference is disconcerting. The first time you
magnify the Venus de Milo to see how hair falls across the nape of
her neck, you feel as though you're leering. Because the ability to
stare so intently, for so long, whenever you feel like it implies
ownership, and the Venus de Milo clearly does not belong to you.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By subjecting the work to this kind of intense scrutiny and
manipulation, the digital image creates a sense of possession that
physical copies cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Power shifts to the viewer. You no longer have to move. The
image comes to (italics)you.(end italics) That's probably why Bill
Gates installed big flat screens in his dining room instead of
hanging paintings _ digital objects can be controlled in ways that
physical objects cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings have a physical integrity you must respect. Digital
images have no physical integrity, so anything goes. You can
superimpose them, alter them and shuffle them around. It's a power
trip.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a learning opportunity. In Le Plus Beau Musee du
Monde, digital imagery allows the designers to clarify aspects of
composition and illustrate principles of perspective. Animated
explanations lead the eye toward an understanding of how a painting
works (the great unanswered question of museumgoers who are told
that the painting is great, but never why).
</P>
<P>
   Having provided a context for understanding each work
individually, Le Plus Beau Musee also provides a context for
understanding them in relation to one another. On the main page,
there are eight tours through these works, each organized around a
central theme, like portraits or pictures that illustrate events.
</P>
<P>
   Within these virtual exhibitions, the meaning of each painting
has been slightly altered because it has been put in a particular
order for particular reasons. The art means more because it has
been chosen, because some defining sensibility has established
relationships among these objects.
</P>
<P>
   That's what curators do. In the brick and mortar world, this is
a rare and highly prestigious job. In Le Plus Beau Musee, it's an
open invitation to the viewer. Using the same stunning warehouse of
images, you can compose your own exhibit, complete with annotations
and digital wall text.
</P>
<P>
   The defining sensibility is that of the viewer, and the context
is personal. The most beautiful museum in the world is your own.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the imaginary museum you create in your mind from the
memories of paintings you have traveled to see, your virtual museum
can be readily shared. You can upload it to Le Plus Beau Musee's
Web site. You can also download other people's museums.
</P>
<P>
   What you're downloading is a tiny amount of information _ a text
file containing the annotations and the order of the paintings. But
it is highly potent information because it conjures meaning.
Wandering through someone else's virtual museum, you see the
objects through that person's eyes, and the art makes a different
sort of sense.
</P>
<P>
   You understand it from a different angle, and you also
understand how another mind works, through the prism of a painting.
And you understand how your own mind works, by measuring the
difference. In the context of human intelligence, the meaning of
the work multiplies. It makes a deeper kind of sense.
</P>
<P>
   It's a singular delight, one that is all too lacking on, say, an
Internet search engine, which offers no context at all. A Web
search looks like junk because it's arranged like junk _ piled up,
regardless of quality, in no particular order.
</P>
<P>
   There is lots of information but very little meaning. That's why
people gravitate to virtual communities; human intelligence makes
sense of new information. It culls the gems and makes them sparkle.
It makes manmade images into priceless works of art.
</P>
<P>
   What is the Mona Lisa without her palace and her plexiglass?
</P>
<P>
   Item 8,497 of 26,912. Click here for next 20 items.
</P>
</TEXT>
