<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNO NEWS AND NOTES: LOTS AND LOTS OF MUSIC; RAGE AGAINST THE
MACHINE; FILTERING SITE GETS BLOCKED; 007, EMILY DICKINSON AND THE
N.Y. TIMES; BYTE IS BACK; `WING COMMANDER' COMETH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Great Britain)   (mk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Users of the latest car stereo may opt to bring it inside every
night, but not just to prevent theft. Rather, they may want to hook
the stereo to their PC to load it with music.
</P>
<P>
   The Empeg stereo, which is scheduled to start shipping later
this month, is billed as the first MP3 stereo designed for use in a
car. MP3 is a format that allows songs to be downloaded from the
Internet and stored and played in digital form.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the relatively limited capacity of compact disk
players or changers, the Empeg player could test the musical
endurance of the most determined road tripper. The 2-gigabyte
model, which will sell for $999, can store and play up to 35 hours
of music, and the 6-gigabyte model, which will sell for $1,399, can
play up to 100 hours. That compares with the more modest 32
megabytes of memory (about 60 minutes worth) found on the popular
Rio PMP300 personal music player.
</P>
<P>
   To load the stereo with music, users pull it from the car, plug
it into the PC and load it with songs downloaded from the Internet
or converted from CDs. The stereo also comes with an FM receiver,
but it does not get the AM frequency; the reason is that the
on-board computer interferes with AM reception, said Rob Voisey,
customer service manager for the stereo's maker, Empeg Ltd., based
in Wells, England.
</P>
<P>
   Voisey said the stereo would appeal to high-end audiophiles who
appreciate its versatility _ that it stores so much music, can be
programmed to play the songs in any order and can also be hooked
into home stereo and PC speakers.
</P>
<P>
   PCs Take Brunt of Workplace Anger
</P>
<P>
   If you have hard feelings toward your hard drive, malicious
thoughts about your monitor and consider drop-kicking your
keyboard, take heart: You are not alone. A new survey suggests that
computers are eliciting rage in the workplace, or at least taking
the brunt of it.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, performed by Concord Communications, a network
consulting firm in Marlboro, Mass., found that 83 percent of
corporate network administrators reported ``abusive and violent
behavior'' by employees toward their computers. The administrators
said employees smashed monitors, threw mice, kicked hard drives and
shattered screens.
</P>
<P>
   But the computers themselves are not, as it turns out, the true
target of the anger, according Dr. Wilfred Calmas, a Boston
psychologist hired to interpret the survey results for Concord
Communications. Instead, Calmas said, employees are merely taking
out the frustration they feel toward their bosses and work in
general on their computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just displacing those feelings toward an inanimate
object,'' Calmas said. ``It's a loss of control over feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Should we really let computers off the hook so easily? Maybe if
Calmas spent hours trying to download a file from the Internet
unsuccessfully or lost a document he worked on all day, he might
displace a few out-of-control feelings on the keyboard too.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the Tables
</P>
<P>
   The Web site Filtering Facts (www.filteringfacts.org) advocates
use of software filters in libraries to protect children from
``objectionable'' material. One catch: Last week, the site was
itself temporarily blocked by Surfwatch, one of the leading
filtering programs and one that is recommended by Filtering Facts.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of filtering, who, among other things, contend that
the automated software sometimes inadvertently blocks innocuous
content, jumped on the Surfwatch error. Surfwatch, which produces
daily filtering updates that its customers can download, promptly
unblocked Filtering Facts. Teresa Marcroft, Surfwatch's director of
marketing, said the Web site had been blocked by mistake because it
shared a commercial server with a pornography site.
</P>
<P>
   David Burt, the creator and keeper of the Filtering Facts,
dismissed the incident. ``Those mistakes do sometimes happen,'' he
said. ``The fact it was unblocked so quickly shows how responsive
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3 Is Offered to Literary Set
</P>
<P>
   The use of the controversial MP3 format to download audio files
from the Internet has taken on a literary twist.
</P>
<P>
   Selections from James Bond novels, Emily Dickinson poetry and
daily selections from The New York Times and The Wall Street
Journal are among the works available for download in MP3 format
from a company called Audible Inc. (www.audible.com). Many of the
offerings are free, the first time that copyrighted books not
already in the public domain are legally available for download in
MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the MP3 format is controversial is that the format is
not encrypted, so files can be readily downloaded and traded by Web
users. Music companies, in particular, have expressed distress that
Web users will simply download music for free rather than pay for
it.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the case of Audible.com, the company's founder,
Donald Katz, said the idea was not to promote free and illegal
distribution of copyrighted content, but just the opposite. Katz
said the company hoped to entice people to use books on MP3 format
so they would be willing to buy audio files when an encryption
standard is eventually set.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Katz said his company had the full backing of the book
and magazine publishers to give the content away. ``They really
want to promote the spoken-word category,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Geeks Heave a Sigh of Relief
</P>
<P>
   When the venerable Byte magazine bit the dirt in July last year,
it created a void for the kind of computer users who are happiest
when they are up to their pocket protectors in circuit boards and
cables. For more than 20 years, spanning the PC industry's
transformation from an esoteric hobby to an unavoidable part of
everyday life, Byte was the guide for those who are known
affectionately as computer geeks.
</P>
<P>
   Months after the magazine folded because of lack of advertising,
its dormant World Wide Web site was still getting hundreds of
thousands of clicks a month from bereft bit-heads.
</P>
<P>
   But now Byte is back in business, not in print but on the
Internet at www.byte.com. And so is Jerry Pournelle, Byte's
longtime columnist whose lengthy narrative reports from his home
office, known as Chaos Manor, discussed everything from graphics
card incompatibilities to science fiction to movie reviews. He is
back and, not constrained by paper and printing costs, is writing
even more than before.
</P>
<P>
   Byte.com's first virtual issue includes a detailed technical
analysis of the Pentium III chip, a report on the next-generation
Internet and discussion forums for topics like software utilities
and Web development tools.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER H. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   From Video to the Big Screen
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, ``Wing Commander'' opens in theaters around the
country. If the title sounds familiar, that is because ``Wing
Commander'' came to life as a science-fiction video game. In making
the jump to the big screen, it is going where few video games have
gone before.
</P>
<P>
   Several video games, including Super Mario Brothers and Mortal
Kombat, have spawned movies, but ``Wing Commander'' includes a new
twist. It marks the first time that a video game creator has also
directed the movie based on the game _ and it hints at a further
convergence of animated games and video.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Roberts, who created Wing Commander in 1990 and just put
the finishing touches on the film, used extensive film footage in
the making of his games. Roberts said he expected more video games
to make the leap to the theater, particularly because movie
executives like the idea of funding a movie whose story already had
a fan base.
</P>
</TEXT>
