<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENT-FARMERS-$     03-10 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-FARMERS-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FARMERS, ENVIRONMENTALISTS AT ODDS OVER REGULATION
 &HT;    720&AMP;add. With ENVIRONMENT-GORE, ENVIRONMENT-WEB and
ENVIRONMENT-ADDRESSES. Moving in (w) Washington and (a) national
categories for release Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HICO, Texas _ Dairy farmer Klaas Talsma was a member of
Greenpeace _ until they threatened to sue him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Talsma embodies a growing conflict between farmers, who
depend on the land and water for their living, and groups who are
using every public and private means to protect the environment
from harm.
</P>
<P>
   It's a conflict that promises to heat up even more as the
federal government prepares to step up regulation of livestock
operations and widely used pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   For Talsma, it hit home eight years ago when two days of
unusually heavy rainfall caused his farm's waste-water lagoon to
overflow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way in the world we could have prevented it,'' he
said. It was the kind of flood that happens only four times a
century _ ``an act of God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Talsma and other farmers received letters from a group of
environmental organizations warning of a possible lawsuit over the
pollution caused by the runoff. While the suit never materialized,
Talsma said blaming dairy farmers for a host of water quality
problems is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a scapegoat, and we're the guys,'' he said. But the
truth is that farmers care more about the environment than just
about anyone, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups say their efforts to curb animal waste
pollution do not target all farmers, but only the small percentage
who cause problems. In fact, said Robbin(cq) Marks of the Natural
Resources Defense Council, the issue of animal waste is one that
unites family farmers and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there's a really big difference between factory farms
and family farms,'' she said. ``The largest facilities are causing
major environmental problems'' such as fish kills, drinking water
contamination and toxic emissions into the air, she said, while
``the communities that are feeling the pollution effects are rural
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Marks said last year's vote in Colorado to impose rigorous
restrictions on runoff from hog farms was largely a result of a
combined effort between environmentalists and farm groups.
</P>
<P>
   But some in the farming community resent what they see as an
increasing effort to regulate agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think environmentalists are probably good people, (but) some
of them have gone a little overboard,'' said David Jackson, who has
been a dairy farmer in Waco, Texas, for 15 years. Jackson said his
operation is very environment-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   He spent more than $13,000 last year to build a lagoon to keep
ground water from running off, and he says state inspectors stop by
about every two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to be good neighbors. We go to church here. Our kids go
to school here,'' he said. Not only that, he added, but the well
where his family gets drinking water is no more than 200 yards from
his waste water lagoon, so it wouldn't make sense to allow leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said farmers have been given a bad name by a small group
of big companies that have bought into agricultural businesses and
``tried to run them like they do their corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   Those large animal feeding operations have become a target of
environmental groups that are lobbying the Clinton administration
to place tough regulations on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Vice President Al Gore announced a plan to require
thousands of additional cattle feedlots, poultry farms and large
hog farms to get permits and develop nutrient management plans in
hopes of controlling pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups said the plan didn't go far enough. Some
farm groups, who prefer local control, said it would penalize many
farmers who have never had problems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the issue of pesticides promises to galvanize both
farmers and environmentalists this year. A decision on whether to
ban two classes of widely used pesticides _ organophosphates and
carbamates _ is expected in August as part of a U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency effort to review 9,600 pesticide registrations
over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Newpher, executive director of the Washington office of the
American Farm Bureau Federation, said conflicts between farmers and
environmental groups are not about choosing sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anyone that's in favor of pollution,'' he said.
``But everybody has a different idea of how, whatever the remedy,
it ought to be employed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers say certain government environmental actions border
on the ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Talsma and other farmers have been circulating a Department of
Interior letter sent to a state agency in response to a permit
request from a North Texas cattle farmer. The letter recommended
that the farmer put giant nets across his waste-water lagoons so
that whooping cranes and bald eagles wouldn't get into them.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is absurd, Talsma said, because the birds would likely
get caught in the net and die.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating when people don't use their common
sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson agreed the nets were a bad idea, adding that ducks come
into his lagoon and feed off some of the grain that washes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all look fat and happy to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
