<HEADER>
A5307 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENT-GORE-$ADV     03-10 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-GORE-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE BALANCES APPEAL TO FARMERS, ENVIRONMENTALISTS
 &HT;    With ENVIRONMENT-FARMERS. Moving in (w) Washington and (a)
national categories for release Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore has been talking to farmers
a lot lately _ and offering them a whole bunch of cash.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, Gore has announced millions of dollars
in federal support for agriculture in what many say is an effort to
improve his standing among farmers in preparation for his 2000
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in the farm community that have read his
book, 'Earth in the Balance,' and are very concerned,'' said Dick
Newpher, executive director of the Washington office of the
American Farm Bureau Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants ``to make sure he's regarded for other things besides
his stand on the environment,'' Newpher said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gore announced the government would give $50 million
in direct payments to struggling pork producers and an additional
$80 million to buy diseased pigs to help ease the industry's
oversupply problem.
</P>
<P>
   In December, he announced a $15 million purchase of pork for
government food programs, and on a separate occasion said the
government would spend $20 million on beef to help cattle
producers.
</P>
<P>
   At the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland in January,
Gore pledged that the Clinton administration would demand major
reductions in the world's farm trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts to reach the agriculture community come at a time
when environmental groups and farmers are squaring off over the
possible banning of widely used pesticides and federal regulation
of animal waste disposal from livestock farms.
</P>
<P>
   Both issues have proven that balancing the two sides isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gore pushed for the creation of an advisory panel
that would include representatives from agriculture and
environmental groups in implementing new pesticide regulations. The
idea came after a warning from Reps. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, and
Marion Berry, D-Ark., that rumors about the loss of the pesticides
were causing an uproar in farming communities.
</P>
<P>
   One environmental group quit the panel, complaining that the
administration was bowing to industry pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Cook, president of the Environmental Working Group, said
in a resignation letter that ``over all, pesticide risks have only
gotten worse during the Clinton administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The tension will likely heat up as the Environmental Protection
Agency (EPA) moves toward an August deadline for deciding the
breadth of restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Farm groups and environmental organizations have also expressed
disappointment _ for different reasons _ about a plan from the EPA
and the Agriculture Department to regulate animal waste from
livestock operations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore announced the plan last Tuesday (March 9), saying that
``this comprehensive strategy forges a new partnership with
American agriculture to tackle a major threat to water quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan will require thousands of additional facilities to get
permits and develop nutrient management plans in hopes of
controlling pollution from cattle feed lots, poultry farms and
large hog farms.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups said the plan was a start, but that it
didn't go far enough. They also objected to its timetable, with
most of the more stringent requirements not taking effect until
2002 and in some cases several years after that.
</P>
<P>
   Some farm groups said the plan penalizes many farmers who have
never had any problems, forcing them to deal with more regulations
and burdensome paperwork. Newpher said Gore's quest for the White
House could be hurt if he pushes for more federal regulation of
animal feeding operations and if he supports allowing individuals
to sue states and farmers if they don't comply with new rules. It's
an important issue in many key states including Texas, California
and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make a difficult time for him politically,''
Newpher said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
