<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VANDERBILT-BOOKS-NYT &LR;      03-10 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANDERBILT-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 AT THE BILTMORE ESTATE, KEEPING TRACK OF A RAILROAD BARON'S 23,000
BOOKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the 23,000 books in George Washington Vanderbilt's
collection at the 250-room mansion he built in Asheville, N.C., are
marked with a bookplate he designed featuring an oil lamp and the
Latin inscription ``Quaero Ex Libris Biltmore'': Inquire in the
books of Biltmore.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five years after his death, that is exactly what is being
done _ with remarkable results _ at the Biltmore Estate, the
stunning French chateau that remains the largest private residence
in the United States with 34 bedrooms, 43 bathrooms, 65 fireplaces
and three kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   George Vanderbilt, the youngest child of Cornelius Vanderbilt's
oldest son, William Henry Vanderbilt, did not just build one of the
country's most opulent residences, he also built an astounding
collection of books. Much of it is housed in the estate's
53-foot-wide, 72-foot-long, 27-foot-high walnut-paneled library,
which remains almost exactly as it was when he died suddenly in
March 1914 at 52 after an emergency appendectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time, the collection is being professionally
cataloged and sorted out by a curator after decades of largely
being left alone. What is emerging is a glimpse of a collection
with strengths in art and English literature, one that is
significant both for its rare books and for its portrait of one
remarkable man's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's remarkable is that this library has remained virtually
unknown,'' said Jerry Patterson, author of ``The Vanderbilts,''
(Abrams, 1989) and former head of the rare books department for the
auction house Sotheby's. ``It's a very significant collection, but
I've never heard a single person in the rare-book trade mention the
library. Even the ones who've been to Biltmore talked about the
fabulous antiques and tapestries, but didn't seem to know anything
about the library. It's a 125-year-old private library that until
now has remained virtually inaccessible and unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most interesting to me is that it's a creation of a
single mind,'' Patterson said. ``It's one man's reading library,
which gives it personality and eccentricity, and to find a
collection of this size still intact for this period of time is
very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vanderbilts created one of America's great fortunes,
beginning with Cornelius Vanderbilt's ferry service across New York
harbor and growing into the great railroad fortune of the 19th
century. Cornelius Vanderbilt left most of his $100 million fortune
to William Henry Vanderbilt, who eventually doubled its assets.
</P>
<P>
   George Vanderbilt, youngest of William's eight children, grew up
in the family's 58-room mansion at 640 Fifth Avenue. In a family
defined by commerce and high society, he was a bookish
intellectual. He moved into bachelor quarters, complete with a
handsome library, in the family mansion and devoted himself to
travel, reading and intellectual pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting Asheville in the southern Appalachians, he
decided to build an estate, a Vanderbilt passion, and set about
purchasing 125,000 acres of land and hiring two of the most
influential figures in design, the architect Richard Morris Hunt
and the landscape architect Frederick Law Olmstead.
</P>
<P>
   Work began in 1889; when it was completed in 1895 there were
elaborately sculptured gardens, farms, woodlands and a four-story
stone house with a 780-foot-long front facade in the richly
ornamented style of the French Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   The room that perhaps most showed off its owner's personality
was the library, with its carved walnut bookcases, red damask
drapery and upholstery, black marble fireplace and early
18th-century ceiling painting by the Venetian Giovanni Antonio
Pellegrini. The library holds about 10,000 books, organized by
subject; the rest are in the den, smoking room, hallways and in
storage.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt was described by one contemporary journalist as ``one
of the best-read men of the country,'' and over the years Biltmore
was host to Edith Wharton, Henry James, John Singer Sargent and
other celebrated figures from the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt, who went to private schools in New York and was
tutored at home but never went to college, was no mere dilettante
with lots of time on his hands. He started acquiring books in eight
languages at the age of 11. Eventually he became fluent in French,
German and Italian, and gained a reading knowledge of Latin, Greek,
Hebrew and Sanskrit.
</P>
<P>
   A display case includes a copy of notebooks he kept in which he
recorded all the books he read. The last entry, No. 3,159, was the
third volume of Henry Adams' ``History of the United States,''
which means that between 1875 and 1914 he read an average of 81
books a year.
</P>
<P>
   His collection reflected his diverse interests, but researchers
are only now finding out how significant it is. ``We feel like
we're at the beginning of a great journey here,'' said Hal Keiner,
an archivist and historian hired in April 1997 to study the library
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important book in the collection is ``Sibylline
Leaves: A Collection of Poems,'' an 1817 collection of Samuel
Taylor Coleridge's poems that includes a first edition of ``The
Rime of the Ancient Mariner'' with the author's corrections for
subsequent editions inked in and signed.
</P>
<P>
   There is a rare first edition of John Milton's ``Paradise Lost''
printed in 1667, a 1737 edition of Alexander Pope's ``Essay on Man
in the Four Epistles to a Friend,'' with handwritten notes by the
author, and a rare first edition of Charles Darwin's ``On the
Origin of Species.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection is particularly strong in art and architecture,
including many titles almost impossible to find in the United
States. It is also very strong in French, German, American and
English literature with first editions of works by Melville,
Hawthorne, Dickens, Thackeray and others.
</P>
<P>
   Biltmore which is owned by George Vanderbilt's grandson William
A.V. Cecil, is open to the public and visited by 850,000 people a
year. But the library collection has been private, with books only
occasionally made available to scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The new attention to the library's holdings will almost
certainly lead to more requests from scholars and researchers. Mr.
Keiner said the library did not have the staff, space, security or
resources to become a much more public institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to provide access when we can,'' he said. ``But I'm
not sure we'll ever be set up to operate like a large research
library. We're still not certain how this will work out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
