<SLUG> BC-CIR-BOVINE-NET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEVY OF BOVINE TRIBUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cows and computers go together like, well, milk and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   The Gateway computer company uses the familiar Holstein
black-and-white pattern in its advertisements and packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Nullsoft's Winamp, an MP3 music player for Windows, allows the
user to change the on-screen look of the program by adding
different ``skins,'' one of which is the Moo Amp, a festive cow
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature of the Moo Amp is the Ecowlizer _ a digitized
stereo equalizer display that replaces pulsating LED lights with
tiny cow heads bouncing up and down. And cows also turn up in the
darndest places in the South Park Nintendo game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps cows became so popular because of their ubiquitous and
comforting presence in the American consciousness. Or just maybe it
has something to do with the fact that many highly regarded
computer-science programs are located at universities in the middle
of cow country _ the state universities of Illinois, Wisconsin and
Texas, and Purdue University, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the subliminal influence of Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice cream
(and other fine Vermont dairy favorites that go well with all-night
computing) is having an effect.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the World Wide Web and its fancy graphics went on
line, there was a sense of bovine inspiration on the Internet,
specifically in the form of simple ASCII art. For those who do not
remember computer visuals before GIF's and JPEG's, popular image
formats that are Web standards, users would create rustic graphics
by carefully arranging alphanumeric text characters. Links to
samples of the great works can be found on a Yahoo page that is
devoted to collections of ASCII cow art (at www.yahoo.com, follow
the trail from Arts to Visual Arts, Computer Generated, ASCII ART,
Cows).
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect, cows have also stampeded the World Wide
Web. Moocow.com (www.moocow.com) greets its visitors with a large
winking cow picture and an opportunity to click on one of its
hundreds of Random Cow Links. In addition to many pictures and a
collection of book titles about cows, the site maintains its own
long list of links to cows on the Web _ the Super Moo Web Pages
Index.
</P>
<P>
   Cows on the Web are far from sacred. The Cow Tipping Home Page
(members.xoom.com/toch) lets Web surfers participate in that
infamous rural prank of shoving over sleeping cattle _ albeit in a
much safer, humane and tongue-in-cheek way. The page gives you
several cows to choose from, and with one click, Bossy is upside
down with a startled, indignant ``Moo!''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Web's most popular shareware sites, Tucows.com
(www.tucows.com), naturally features a couple of cows on its home
page. Tucows, which is an acronym for The Ultimate Collection of
Winsock Software, has expanded its collection to include Macintosh
and some Java applications.
</P>
<P>
   A search of the Tucows site will reveal a collection of
cow-related software, just in case you need the Moo Amp skin for
your Winamp player or that handsome cow screen saver. And for
comfortable computing wear, the distinctive Ben &AMP; Jerry's Blue Moo
shirt is available at
store.benjerry.com/benjerry1/bluemootshirt.html.
</P>
</TEXT>
