<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      03-10 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING OLDER USENET POSTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there any way I can find a particular posting from a few
months ago in a Usenet newsgroup? I know the author's name but
cannot recall the exact subject line.
</P>
<P>
   A. For those unfamiliar with Usenet, it is an international
electronic bulletin board where Internet users can post messages
(also referred to as articles) in newsgroups, which are public
discussion areas devoted to specific subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Usenet now has newsgroups available on just about any topic
imaginable. For example, Lynne Russell, a CNN ``Headline News''
anchor, is the subject for a newsgroup of adoring fans commenting
on her every move, at alt.fan.lynne-russell.
</P>
<P>
   With so much material available and thousands of postings from
around the world every day, finding things in Usenet can be
time-consuming. As with many kinds of research, one of the quickest
ways to find information is on the Web. The Deja News site
(www.dejanews.com) will let you search through Usenet articles
using keywords, including the author's name.
</P>
<P>
   If you search for the author's name or e-mail address, Deja News
will show you the articles posted by that person, along with all
the different newsgroups the person has contributed to. The Deja
News archive of postings goes back about two years.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How accurate are the scanners that let you copy documents
into your computer so you can edit them?
</P>
<P>
   A. Software that lets you scan text documents into your computer
is called an optical character recognition (OCR) program. These
programs analyze the images of type on a printed page, and
translates them into text that can be edited with a word-processing
program.
</P>
<P>
   For most home users, a basic scanner and off-the-shelf software
like Caere's Omnipage Pro or Expervision's Type Reader will work
just fine. Most OCR programs can distinguish a variety of fonts and
formats and usually come with proofreading and spell-checking
functions to help catch any errors right away.
</P>
<P>
   Although some software makes claims of up to 99-percent accuracy
in the translation from paper to computer file, the legibility of
the document being scanned affects the results. Any program will
have a much better time with a clean, clear page from a laser
printer than with a blurry photocopy of a fax or a magazine article
with coffee rings all over it.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
