<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCREENWRITER-CONTEST-     03-10 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCREENWRITER-CONTEST-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIR MAY RIDE `LAST TRAIN' TO FAME 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ariz.)  (mk) 
 By SCOTT HADLY   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ They're not young wannabe movie moguls
on Hollywood's up-and-coming hot list, but the writing partners who
took home this year's top prize for screenwriting at the Santa
Barbara Film Festival are generating a buzz all the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't just get out of film school,'' said Jane Ilsa Wells,
who with Ian Ginsburg penned this year's first-place winner in the
festival's annual Peter Stark Screenwriting Competition. ``But with
the win, I really feel things starting to happen for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, a widow and mother of a teen-age daughter, and Ginsburg,
a music teacher, have so far produced five scripts. Their latest
and winning script, ``The Last Train,'' follows the lives of two
brothers shipped out of New York City on the eve of the Great
Depression aboard the last of the so-called orphan trains.
</P>
<P>
   A real part of history, the trains were started in the 19th
century by a minister who wanted to help young orphaned immigrant
children find better lives. The trains were loaded with youngsters
sent to rural homes in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the children ended up in loving families, sometimes
they ended up in near servitude, and Ginsburg and Wells' screenplay
follows both fates. In their script, two teen-age Jewish brothers
sent to rural Texas end up in very different circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg, who is 35 and lives in Phoenix, got the idea after
listening to a survivor of the orphan train tell his story on the
radio. He said it wasn't until he started working with Wells, who
is 40 and lives in Cottonwood, Ariz., that the plot took off. She
recognized the story needed to immediately draw people in, so she
put together an arresting opening sequence.
</P>
<P>
   The script begins with no dialogue. The camera focuses on the
face of a tired, disheveled young mother standing atop a New York
tenement. The pretty young woman's sons sit crying nearby behind a
railing. The woman steps off the ledge of the building. The camera
turns to the face of the older of the two boys who plaintively
cries, ``Mama.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw what we had, I said, `This is hot, let's write
it,''' Ginsburg said. ``There's no doubt about it that it was a
brilliant beginning and we were off from there. We fight sometimes,
but we work very well together. When we get going we can be writing
six to eight hours without stopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Since learning that they won the award, the writing partners
have also attracted an independent film company interested in
another of their scripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how the Hollywood world works _ until you're
validated by a star that champions your work or you win a contest
like this one, you don't get much recognition,'' Ginsburg said.
``Now things are happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-place award earns the writing partners a $5,000 check
and an introduction to a Hollywood agent. The competition drew
entries from more than 100 script-writing hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   The award will be handed out at a ceremony on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Hadly writes for the Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press.
This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
