   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING _ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises filed with theSEC
to sell as much as $800 million of securities. It plans to use the
proceeds for expansion,including working capital, capital
expenditures, debt repayment and possible acquisitions. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES _ The Clinton administration proposed tougher measures
designed to compel U.S. airlines to respond to passengers'
complaints about service. The legislation would double airlines'
maximum liability for a lost bag from the current $1,250, and
double to $800 the minimum penalty for involuntarily ``bumping'' a
passenger. TENTATIVE (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WEBMD _ Lycos and WebMD announc a $52.5 million deal in which
WebMD will be the exclusive heathcare provider over Lycos networks
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PBP-PAXSON _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Paxson Communications
earnings are out _ the first full-year earnings that take into
account PAX-TV. For the year, total revenue rose 52 percent to
$134.2 million, and operating loss was $59.4 million compared with
operating income of $20.4 million one year earlier. The increases
were due to the launch of PAX-TV. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   PAY-SOUTH _ ATLANTA _ Two surveys on wage and employment:
Randstad polled 3,100 workers at 2,500 companies in five southern
states, including Georgia. Retaining workers is employers' biggest
worry. Very large and very small companies paid the highest average
wage. Transportation and communications paid the highest; retail
paid the lowest. Study by pay consulting firm William M. Mercer
says pay in private industry can, and does, vary considerably
depending on where you live. (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GAMING-LOTTERY _ ATLANTA _ Anchor Gaming, moving to enter the
online lottery business, acquires Atlanta-based Powerhouse
Technologies, the nation's second-largest lottery operator, for
$220 million in stock plus assumed debt of $60 million. Shares of
Powerhouse jumped 21.1 percent, or $3.12, to $17.93. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATL-DRUG STUDY _ ATLANTA _ An Emopry University study finds that
drug addicition costs the state nearly $8 billion a year in lost
work productivity, drug treatment and law enforcement concerns.
(Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOUCOM _ ATLANTA _ CEO Bill Dahlberg won't talk about reoports
that Southern Co. held acquisition talks with El Paso Energy , but
says he's certainly like to add natural gas to the company's
electricity holdings. (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELL _ Dell Computer Corp. and Amazon.com, two of the Web's
biggest retailers, from a marketing alliance. It is the first of
what may be more alliances between the companies. (Mahoney, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TSHIRTS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Imprinting T-shirts featuring World
Championship Wrestling characters including arch hero Bill Goldberg
has been a bonanza for Littlefield, Adamns &AMP; Co., a small , Dayton
area traded company whose traded shares and fortunes were thrown
out of the ring a few years ago after losing its lucrative Harley
Davidson license. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, expected
to unveil on Wednesday a package of tax cuts aimed at spurring
research and development work in Texas as well as promoting
business development in some of the state's poorer regions,
particularly the border. Sibley's bill goes before Senate Finance
Committee today, while House Ways and Means Committee is expected
to consider several related research and development bills,
including one by Rep. Sherri Greenburg, D-Austin. However, neither
committee expected to vote bills out today. (Hight, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
