<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, March 11,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CENTAM-CLINTON-0311 _ President Clinton Wednesday continues his
four-day trip to hurricane-devstated areas of Central America, and
is expected to make a ``major'' policy speech to the Salvadoran
legislature. DEVELOPING.
</P>
<P>
   (Lipman, Cox News Service). NOTES _ Palm Beach Post OUT.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BEAUTY-0311 _ JERUSALEM _ For the first time ever, Miss
Israel is an Arab. At the beauty pageant Tuesday night, judges
chose Rana Raslan, a 21-year-old Arab citizen of Israel from the
port city of Haifa. The Arab Christian (EDs: Checking to make sure
she's not Muslim.) will represent the Jewish state at the Miss
World contest, won last year by the previous (Jewish) Miss Israel.
There are almost 1 million Arabs among the six million Israeli
citizens and the win was seen as another in a series of small steps
toward acceptance by the majority. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the International and Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SPYING _ WASHINGTON _ Security at U.S. weapons labs has
been lax for more than a decade, prompting strong warnings from
government investigators since 1988. Yet the Department of Energy
repeatedly failed to enact recommended safeguards against espionage
among foreign visitors at its three labs that develop nuclear
bombs. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-CHARITY-PAYNE _ A little-known public charity founded by
Billy Payne more than a decade ago is shouldering a huge
responsibility _ carrying on Atlanta's Olympic legacy. While it
hoped to become known for supporting youth sports and giving the
city an Olympic museum, the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation
(GAAF) is a long way from fulfilling its mission. (Turner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 70 inches. MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   w/PHOTOS (Linda Stephenson, kids at Olympic display, file photo
of Payne and Andy Young.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-CHARITY-MEMORABILIA _ Olympic memorabilia collectors and
dealers worldwide question the assessed value of $1.5 million for
the mementoes bought by the GAAF from Billy Payne. (Rosen/Turner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Being snowbound has its
advantages. I have, for instance, recently learned everything I
could ever want to know about Stonewall Jackson and Grand Funk
Railroad. Everything and more. How many times have you longed for
some time to sit down, relax and converse with your spouse? During
the recent inclemencies, Jim and I have had the opportunity to do
just that. Be careful what you pray for. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ In the 1970s, my wife, Ruth, and I were
standing on the veranda of a wonderful old hotel at Cooperstown,
N.Y. Joe DiMaggio was across the veranda, chatting with friends.
``I'm going to say hello to him,'' Ruth said. I wouldn't have
dared. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Deregulation of public education: Is that
what we're talking about with these school vouchers? If so, hold
the phone. I happen to have an opinion about public education. My
opinion is that no other institution has contributed more to
democracy in America. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin filmmaker Steve Mims is
auctioning off his 1980 Honda Civic on the Internet to help pay for
the low budget film he's about to introduce at the South by
Southwest Film Festival. ``People should know that the air
conditioner blows cold,'' said Steve, who also owns a 10-year-old
Honda. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's get this
straight: The day President Clinton apologized to the nation but
not to Monica Lewinsky, the poor thing felt dirty and used. Monica,
who considered herself the president's ``sexual soulmate,'' is
sorry for what happened. Oh, and by the way, she didn't intend to
cause the president public embarrassment. (Jefferson, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
