<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, March 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Increasing breezes from the southeast will begin to draw moist
air northward from the Gulf of Mexico Thursday. As the moist air is
forced to ascend up and over a front, scattered heavy showers will
blossom over eastern Texas, southeastern Oklahoma, and the lower
Mississippi Valley. Isolated thunderstorms will also erupt,
especially near the Texas and Louisiana Gulf coasts, where the air
is especially humid. Farther north in the colder air, a period of
sleet or snow will occur in northern Oklahoma and western Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of snow will accompany a jet stream disturbance crossing
the interior Southwest. The snow will be locally heavy in the
mountains of northern Arizona, southeast Utah and western Colorado,
where over six inches of new snow could accumulate by evening. As
the disturbance presses farther east, moderate to heavy snow will
develop later Thursday night over eastern Colorado and northeast
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Generally dry and cool conditions will cover an expansive area
from the Middle West to the Middle Atlantic States. Sinking air
currents associated with high pressure nosing south from Canada
will promote partly to mostly sunny skies across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Ample sunshine will cover the Great Lakes and southern New
England regions Thursday, but a band of moisture pin-wheeling about
a low near Nova Scotia will promote clouds and snow showers over
the mountains of northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, sunshine will be dimmed by high clouds near the
Southeast Coast, while Florida stays mainly sunny and seasonably
warm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: D.C. Snow
</P>
<P>
   The snow drought in Washington, D.C. ended on Tuesday when 8.4
inches of snow were measured at Reagan National Airport. Last
winter, a mere 0.1 inches of snow were recorded, and, until
Tuesday's storm, only 2.9 inches of snow had been measured this
winter. The average winter snowfall in Washington, D.C. is 18
inches. There have been huge swings in snowfall in the 1990s. The
0.1 inches of snow that fell during the winter of 1997-98 tied as
the least snowiest season on record, but the 46 inches of snow that
were measured during the winter of 1995-96 ranked as the snowiest
this century. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1758EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
