<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUCLEAR-SPYING11-COX     03-10 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-SPYING11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEAPONS LABS IGNORED 10 YEARS OF WARNINGS ON SECURITY LAPSES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Security at U.S. weapons labs, now the center of a
major espionage probe, has been lax for more than a decade,
prompting repeated warnings from government investigators that were
unheeded until recently.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of reports, secret briefings and public testimony
going back to 1988, the General Accounting Office (GAO) has told
Congress and top administrative officials that nuclear secrets were
at risk from the thousands of foreigners who visit the
laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, as he fired a scientist
Tuesday suspected of leaking secrets to China from the laboratory
at Los Alamos, N.M., pointed to upgraded counter-intelligence teams
and tighter procedures ordered a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore also tried to allay concerns _ and shift
the blame _ when he told CNN this week that a presidential
directive ``fixed problems that we had inherited, and changed and
vastly improved the security procedures in the national laboratory
system.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a chief investigator of the labs said Wednesday that
``it's very unlikely'' that the new safeguards have corrected more
than a decade of inattention to glaring security problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good first step, although I think it's long overdue,''
said Keith O. Fultz, assistant comptroller at the GAO, the
investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The House Science Committee asked the GAO this week to begin an
assessment of the new security measures at the weapons labs, which
include Los Alamos and the Sandia laboratories in New Mexico and
the Lawrence Livermore laboratory in California.
</P>
<P>
   As late as 1997, the accounting office found serious lapses in
security, which had followed a pattern since the mid-1980s. Among
the disclosures:
</P>
<P>
   _ Six boxes of papers marked ``sensitive materials'' in red
letters were left in an open hallway in 1997 at a Los Alamos
facility to which foreign visitors had access.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also at Los Alamos, foreign visitors as late as 1997 were
allowed to roam unescorted through buildings after work hours, ``to
preserve what one official described as an open 'campus atmosphere'
for researchers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Although procedures called for background checks before
admission of visitors from communist and other potentially
unfriendly nations, the Energy Department in 1988 checked out fewer
than 10 percent of the 500 visitors in this category. FBI checks of
visitors found that some were suspected foreign agents, although
the exact number is a classified secret.
</P>
<P>
   _ The follow-up investigation in 1997 found that more than 1,800
visitors from ``sensitive'' countries such as China, India and
Russia visited the three weapons labs, but most underwent no
background investigations. At Los Alamos and Sandia, less than 5
percent were checked. At Livermore, about 40 percent were checked.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department in both 1988 and in 1997 agreed with
findings by the GAO and has issued plans to tighten security for
the program, which is aimed at encouraging international exchange
by scientists.
</P>
<P>
   In February of last year, President Clinton issued an order to
tighten up controls of the foreign visitor program. The Energy
Department has doubled its budget for countering spying and has
instituted more security checks and the use of polygraphs for lab
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Department spokesman Stu Nagurka said the new policy is that all
visitors from sensitive countries will be cleared by the FBI and
CIA as not being identified with espionage. ``That's our goal,'' he
said. He also said that the weapons labs have a policy that ``no
visitors are allowed within the secured part of the complex''
unescorted.
</P>
<P>
   Fultz said that he could not yet assess whether these measures
would work immediately. ``It will take a while to change the
culture, the procedures and the system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that the Department of Energy, from the late
1980s until very, very recently, has not taken serious enough
actions on this very significant issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``They're working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
