<HEADER>
A5397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMERGING-ARCHITECTS-A     03-10 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMERGING-ARCHITECTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING YOUNG TURKS OFFER ARCHITECTURE FOR A NEW CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., N.Y., Calif., Texas, Pa., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wendell Burnette's first building, a house for himself at the
edge of the Sonoran desert, has graced the covers of numerous
international magazines. The British magazine Architectural Review
proclaimed him ``one to watch in 1998'' and Metropolitan Home
recently named him one of ``21 Rising Stars for the 21st Century.''
A 36-year-old architect from Phoenix, he has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Or has he? The only job his office has right now is a small
remodeling project; he can't remember when he last paid himself,
and he can barely maintain a payroll for his one trusty employee.
``The irony is that there are all these accolades,'' Burnette said
on a cell phone last week as he drove to a potential project site
at 7 a.m., ``and at the same time, I'm wondering where the next
meal is coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Berkeley, Calif., Ralph Nelson and Raveevarn
Choksombatchal, both 37, who were married in 1989, have shared an
architectural practice called Loom for six years. Their combined
curriculum vitae is 12 pages long, but it wasn't until they
received a Progressive Architecture award last year that people
began returning their calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent 10 years becoming an overnight success,'' Nelson
said, adding that teaching stints kept the firm afloat. ``Savings?
What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   Burnette's practice and Loom are among eight architecture firms
selected as ``Emerging Voices'' of 1999 by the Architectural League
of New York, a nonprofit organization that has sponsored public
programs in architecture since 1881. But rising stars need more
than a winning way with a T-square _ or a CAD program _ to make a
name for themselves. The simplest projects require a fanatical
commitment and Job-like patience. For those struggling to
distinguish themselves, ``the will to be independent overrides all
sensible decisions'' about life and gainful employment, Nelson
said, gamely.
</P>
<P>
   The League's winners offer a telling glimpse of the state of
architecture _ a mirror of the built world of today and a window
onto the next century. Drawing inspiration from sources as
unexpected as the extreme shapes assumed by materials distorted by
stress, or as poetic as the play of light in a Cartier-Bresson
photograph, these eight firms, for all their travails, are shaping
the future in ways that are strikingly individual but also
surprisingly in synch.
</P>
<P>
   Just about every significant architect who came of age in the
last two decades, including Steven Holl, Tod Williams and Billie
Tsien, Deborah Berke, and Henry Smith-Miller and Laurie Hawkinson
has been an Emerging Voice.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the year he was selected (1982), Steven Holl, who
comes from Seattle, said: ``Here I was, an architect basically
coming out of the woods to New York. And they chose me. It gave me
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Emerging Voices is incredibly important, and not for crass
reasons of career advancement,'' he continued, ``because it
acknowledges and respects the ideas swirling around in the heads of
young architects.''
</P>
<P>
   An interest in the physical world, with all its warts and
wonders, distinguishes one group of winners. Call them the New
Sensualists: they're less interested in the eye-catching photogenic
image of a building, more in how it feels to the touch, or sounds
beneath the foot.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum are the Philosophers, exploring
ideas that straddle the worlds of theory and practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an intensity of design, a commitment to new
technologies and a passion about detail and materiality in all
their work,'' said Craig Conyk, a New York architect, who served on
the Architectural League's selection committee. ``It's a very
healthy sign for architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   In a multi-generational house the Loom team designed in Bangkok,
for instance, a rosewood and teak staircase rings as resonantly as
a music box, and concrete walls overlap to create openings that
weave sunlight into each room.
</P>
<P>
   For Ada Tolla and Giuseppe Lignano of Lotek in New York, the
future means embracing discarded industrial and consumer products,
turning oil cans into armchairs, detergent bottles into lamps. In a
penthouse, they've made a sun-filled bedroom on the roof out of a
truck body, and they divided a loft into living and working spaces
with a wall made of one sheared side of a 40-foot-long aluminum
shipping container. What makes that space so intriguingly efficient
is the way the sink and refrigerator are embedded in the room
divider, in a manner that recalls Jean Cocteau's anatomical
candelabra in ``Beauty and the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Brian Healy in Boston, who grew up surrounded by
cornfields in Bucks County, Pa., only to watch them give way to
subdivisions and strip malls, that experience of transition left
him with a desire to ``make buildings that tap into a place,'' even
as it changes. Healy, 42, is designing a modern writer's and
artist's studio in the Catskills, with references back to the Arts
and Crafts movement, a powerful design force there in the late 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Burnette, who has a naturalist's love of desert geology, applies
an artist's abstraction to his designs, inspired in part by James
Turrell and Richard Serra.
</P>
<P>
   He based his design for a decorator's studio and showroom in
Scottsdale, Ariz., on two mesquite trees in the courtyard. Instead
of cutting them down, as others had proposed, he wove the trees and
the building together, cutting notches in the masonry walls to
frame the trees and let them grow.
</P>
<P>
   A self-taught architect who went to work at Frank Lloyd Wright's
Taliesin right out of high school, Burnette aims for rich spatial
and textural experiences. Passage through the decorator's studio is
labyrinthine: one climbs past several levels that appear to float
free of the structure and, at one point, are illuminated by a scrim
of Indian onyx so thin that sunlight passing through casts a golden
glow on an oak staircase.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in doing many things with one stroke,'' Burnette
said, comparing his work to Cartier-Bresson's photography, as it
captures and distills a singular moment in space and time.
</P>
<P>
   The tension in the work of Kevin Daly, 41, and Chris Genik, 39,
in Santa Monica, Calif., oscillates between technological invention
and hands-on craft. High-performance technologies get them going,
but so does the chance to work side by side with woodworkers and
metalsmiths. For instance, a house in Canada for Genik's parents
bursts like a crystal from a massive pile of boulders. Ten years on
the job and still fascinated by clients who dream of the
impossible, Daly and Genik are interested in ``finding the
extraordinary in the very familiar.'' They look for inspiration in
the seamless craftsmanship of the physical world _ from a World War
II plywood and glue airplane to a tiny 1,000-year-old reliquary
covered in gold that bears no trace of tool marks.
</P>
<P>
   While an appeal to the senses and to found objects animates the
work of the New Sensualists, the Philosophers, like Asymptote, Evan
Douglis and Michael Bell, are investigating ways of building that
seem radical today but may well become the traditions of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Hani Rashid, 40, and Lise Anne Couture, 39, of Asymptote utilize
the most advanced computer technologies to create a kind of space
that exists simultaneously in the real world _ ``first-reality
architecture,'' Rashid calls it _ and in virtual reality.
</P>
<P>
   From their Asymptote office in New York, in Soho's fanciful
wrought-iron Singer Building (and their home in the loft next
door), Rashid and Ms. Couture are ``set on running all our credit
cards into the ground'' to realize the objective of designing at
the edge of reality through such commissions as a
computer-generated theater of operations at the New York Stock
Exchange, which opened Monday. Recently, they designed a showroom
for a research company in Kyoto, Japan, to showcase new computer
technologies in the hush of a museum-like setting, complete with a
black box theater.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Douglis has been on his own since 1991. He has yet to find
a client entirely tuned into his ideas about the poetry of
architecture. ``Early on, I rejected building at any cost,''
Douglis, 39, said at his office in a warehouse in New York's
Chelsea area. ``It wasn't necessarily my best move.'' Luckily, the
architect, as director of the Columbia University Architecture
Galleries, has been able to commission himself to design
installations. Borrowing from military technology for
quick-assembly bridges, he suggests an alternative to solidity
itself: why not a wall made from weather balloons caged in steel?
</P>
<P>
   Bell, 38, lives and works in Houston, dividing his time between
running his firm (six employees when there's work) and teaching at
Rice University. He hopes to combine his theoretical interests ``in
the sheer brutality of economic forces'' with an active commercial
practice that gets things built. Most recently, he was the curator
of a gallery exhibition in Houston, ``16 Houses: Owning a House in
the City,'' which has turned into a commission from Houston's Fifth
Ward Community Redevelopment Corp. to build his entry in the show.
</P>
<P>
   His is not necessarily a pretty house. At 900 square feet, the
design reminded one local critic of two boomerangs squeezed back to
back. All the walls are made of off-the-rack sliding-glass doors to
make the point that we all lead transparent lives. The house, which
will cost $74,000 or $52,000 with federal vouchers, was chosen
along with others in the exhibition to be built later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a breakthrough I'm excited about,'' said Bell,
who has endured seven clients in seven years who he says
``chickened out'' at the last possible minute. (One client, he
said, lost interest when the architect couldn't squeeze the cost of
a design down to $36 a square foot, from $38.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disappointments of the past, and uncertainty that
the housing project will truly happen (``Everyday, I wait for
someone to say it's dead,'' he said), Bell wants to keep designing
houses. After all, he added, houses are ``how we imagine ourselves
participating in the life of the city and the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
