<HEADER>
A5402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     03-10 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: METHODS TO BOND WOOD TO CONCRETE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Illustration is being sent to NYT photo/graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to attach furring strips or other wood members to a
concrete surface might seem like a difficult, almost impossible
task. There are, however, a number of fasteners available today
that make the job easier. Having the right fastener is only part of
the job. You also need to use the right tools. Ordinary woodworking
tools are too light, and steel drill bits are too soft for concrete
work.
</P>
<P>
   Your tool kit should also include safety gear: goggles,
heavy-duty gloves to shield your hands from flying chips of stone,
and ear protection when using power tools.
</P>
<P>
   The cheapest and simplest method of securing a piece of wood to
concrete is by nailing it in place. Obviously you cannot use
ordinary nails for this, but there are heavy-shank, hardened nails
that will penetrate masonry. There are two types of masonry nails:
cut masonry nails and hardened concrete nails. Choosing one type
over the other is largely a matter of trial-and-error, since
performance varies with each job.
</P>
<P>
   The nails should be long enough to penetrate at least 3/4 inch
into the concrete. Shorter nails won't hold, and longer ones may
not penetrate all the way. Whichever type of nail you use, you'll
need a four-pound hammer to drive them. These nails are difficult
to drive into hard concrete and they tend to work loose over time,
so they should only be used for temporary fastenings.
</P>
<P>
   For a more permanent attachment, it is best to choose a fastener
that is driven into a predrilled hole. These fasteners fit into two
basic categories: nails or screws, and expansion fasteners. Nails
and screws have a slightly larger diameter than the drilled hole
and must be driven in place with either a hammer or a screwdriver.
Expansion fasteners, on the other hand, have a smaller diameter
than the hole and expand to grip the surrounding concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Use a carbide-tipped drill bit to bore the hole. Depending on
the number of holes, their diameter, and the hardness of the
concrete, you may be able to use your 1/4- or 3/8-inch drill for
boring the holes. You can, for example, drill six 1/8-inch holes
with a standard 1/4-inch drill, but if you have to bore that many
1/2-inch holes in hard concrete, it may be better to rent either a
1/2-inch drill or a hammer drill.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer drills look similar to ordinary heavy-duty drills, but
they are fitted with a hammer-action mechanism that converts rotary
motion into percussive blows. They can deliver 500 blows per second
as the drilling progresses. You must use special percussion drill
bits for this operation.
</P>
<P>
   Nails and concrete screws are slightly larger than the hole that
they are inserted in. As they penetrate into the hole, they bite
into the surrounding concrete to hold fast. When attaching a board
to concrete, the length of the nail should be twice that of the
board's thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion fasteners, on the other hand, have an expansion sleeve
_ made of metal or plastic _ that slides into the hole. Within the
sleeve is a screw or bolt that expands the sleeve as it is
tightened. The expanded sleeve wedges against the sides of the hole
to hold fast.
</P>
<P>
   When attaching a board to concrete, select an expansion fastener
that is twice as long as the board's thickness. As the bolt is
tightened, it will extend past the tip of the fastener, so drill
the hole an extra 1/4-inch deep. One advantage that expansion
fasteners have over nails is that they can be tightened if the
board becomes loose.
</P>
<P>
   Professional builders often use air-powered or powder-actuated
tools to drive hardened nails into concrete. The air-powered tools
are hooked up to a compressor. The powder tools, sometimes called
stud guns, use a small charge of explosive powder to drive the nail
in place. These tools can quickly drive a nail through a thick
board into the concrete. In addition to being fast and powerful,
they can be dangerous. The do-it-yourselfer should steer clear of
them unless fully acquainted with all operational procedures and
safety precautions.
</P>
<P>
   You can also use construction adhesive to glue boards to a
concrete wall. The adhesive is available in standard-sized
cartridges that load into a caulking gun. For lightweight boards a
1/4-inch wide bead is sufficient, but for heavier pieces or for
very rough surfaces use more. Surface preparation is important to
insure a good bond. Both surfaces should be clean, dry and free of
loose paint. The boards must be held in place until the adhesive
has time to set. For this reason, many builders prefer to use the
adhesive in conjunction with another type of fastener: the adhesive
acts as a damper to absorb vibrations that may loosen a mechanical
fastener and the fastener holds the boards until the adhesive sets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
