<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5403 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-FOOD-HNS &LR;      03-10 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING SOLACE (AND NUTRITION) IN THE SNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Few outdoor activities offer easier opportunities
for intimacy than cross-country skiing or snowshoeing. Privacy
comes quickly away from groomed trails.
</P>
<P>
   It takes only minutes to get far enough from the frenzied crowds
to feel alone amid snow-draped pines and stark brush. Bird,
squirrel and deer tracks signal that other living souls have been
here recently, the sorts of creatures you are happy to interact
with on a winter afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But if you haven't packed properly for this outing, you will rue
the day. Plenty of water and high-energy snacks are absolutely
essential for a memorable Nordic adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Davis, assistant manager at Eastern Mountain Sports in
Albany, is a cross-country ski enthusiast. Packing the right foods
for a weekend outing, he says, is just as important as including a
map and compass in your backpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to bring food _ it's one of the
essentials,'' Davis says. ``In fact, we tell people it's really not
safe to go cross-country skiing without food. You never know how
long you'll end up being outside, and it's important to keep your
energy level up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sustenance, not elegance, is the goal. Davis and other experts
advise skiers to be sure to include high-energy snacks like trail
mix, or gorp, as well as fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Another cardinal rule is to leave wine and other spirits at
home, no matter how romantic the image of a decanter of zinfandel
as the centerpiece of a winter picnic might be. Because alcohol
dilates the capillaries of the skin, more body heat is lost when it
is consumed. This can lead to chilling, loss of energy and,
possibly, hypothermia.
</P>
<P>
   While water is essential for maintaining hydration, Davis often
carries only one liter and relies on the snow to refill his
container.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis knows he will be on the trail for several hours or
longer, he packs a single-burner stove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to heat up soups that I made the night before,'' he
says. ``Sometimes we bring rice so we can stick it in the soup for
extra starch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can also use the stove to whip up some hot drinks, like
hot cocoa. Some of us get wacky and make hot Tang. It's not very
appetizing, but it's a hot drink.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a Thermos usually works just as well as a camping stove
and weighs less. It is a fine receptacle for soups or hot drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Woods and Gordon Hardy, authors of ``Cross Country Skier's
Trailside Guide,'' advocate carbohydrates and simple sugars over
heavy, high-bulk foods that take hours to process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some foods are so classic for day tours as to be almost de
rigeur: fresh or dried fruit, cheese, bread, and crackers are all
favored,'' they wrote, ``along with some sweet treats like
chocolate (be careful no to overdo chocolate; it's loaded with fat
and can cause stomach cramps when you're exercising).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuts and seeds are great, of course, along with cut-up
vegetables, smoked meats, and peanut butter with jam. Try what you
like: Your menu is limited only by your imagination and willingness
to make lunch a special stop.''
</P>
<P>
   It is quite possible to have it all _ privacy, good nutrition
and elegance _ on a cross-country sojourn.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a relatively easy recipe for trail mix, or gorp, that
will keep you going all day long. Just remember to pack water, too,
and the peace be with you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GORDY'S GORP
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 16)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chocolate or carob bits
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cashews
</P>
<P>
   1 cup salted peanuts (or unsalted Spanish peanuts)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sunflower seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped, dried apricots
</P>
<P>
   2 cups raisins (or currants)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped dried apples
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup flaked coconut, if desired
</P>
<P>
   2 cups oats
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup maple syrup or honey
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, blend oats, oil and maple syrup. Spread on a
cookie sheet and bake in oven at 275, turning occasionally. When
oats are crisp (about 45 minutes), remove, and cool. Mix with
remaining ingredients. This recipe makes enough gorp for 16 skiers,
and it may be reduced proportionally.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: ``Cross Country Skier's Trailside Guide,'' by Craig
Woods and Gordon Hardy
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
