<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-COMPLAINTS-H     03-10 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-COMPLAINTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, LAWMAKERS PUSH FOR AIRLINE PASSENGER BILL OF RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers and consumers unleashed a barrage of
criticism against the airline industry Wednesday with complaints
ranging from being stuck hours on airport runways to getting wrong
or inadequate information about flights.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers warned the airlines that unless they improve their
service, Congress will impose consumer-oriented rules.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time. the Clinton administration proposed its own
``passenger bill of rights'' legislation and announced new
Department of Transportation guidelines requiring airlines to give
consumers more information about flights when they are making
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who introduced the administration plan
with Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, said the so-called
``fair treatment initiative ... empowers passengers with all the
information they need to make good decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, House Transportation Committee Chairman Bud
Shuster, R-Pa., said at a hearing of the committee's aviation
panel, ``The airlines must refocus their efforts on providing
better customer service.'' He added that the number of consumer
complaints made to the Federal Aviation Administration about
airlines rose 26 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster and other lawmakers introduced various passenger-rights
bills last month after airline passengers complained of being
forced to sit on airport runways for up to nine hours after a
January snowstorm in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   A similar horror tale was told Wednesday by Patricia Shank of
Frederick, Md., who said she was confined for nine hours that month
on a London-bound Virgin Atlantic plane that never took off from
Washington's Dulles International Airport. She said that when she
declined to take another plane the next day, the airline refused to
return her luggage, which was flown to London.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Plecas, of Walled Lake, Mich., told of being stuck in
Detroit on a Northwest Airlines plane for eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could almost reach out and touch the terminal,'' Plecas
said. ``The lavatories were overflowing and unusable. There was no
food or water. Passengers who needed to take their medication with
food and water were in a panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Hopp, of Royal Oak, Mich., told of spending the night on
the airport floor in Minneapolis and then, after taking a Northwest
flight to Detroit, being stranded on the plane outside an airport
gate there for almost three hours after it landed.
</P>
<P>
   What really irked her, she said, was that she had offered to
stay in Portland, Ore., where she and her family had spent the
holidays, for a few more days when she heard of the Midwest
snowstorm. But a ticket agent had advised against the delay.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Pearlman of Columbia, Md., said he was stuck on a plane
near a gate in St. Louis for more than two hours in good weather
last Christmas. He later learned the airline didn't have enough
employees to direct the plane to the gate because they were staging
a ``sick-out.'' Pearlman said when he asked airline personnel about
that and other delays, one answer he got was that there were
mechanical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have struck a raw nerve here,'' Shuster said. ``I can't
walk through the halls here without members and constituents
telling me their horror stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration's legislation mirrors many provisions
contained in Shuster's bill and one authored by Sens. John McCain,
R-Ariz., and Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, new Department of Transportation guidelines will
require airlines to tell passengers when they are making a
reservation the name of another carrier that may actually operate a
portion of the flight. Passengers flying on United Express, for
example, are often put on planes operated by a smaller airline.
</P>
<P>
   The administration rules, which will take effect in July, will
also require airlines to tell passengers if they will have to
change planes while making a single flight. In some cases a person
may have a ticket that shows one flight number, but it may include
one or more flights.
</P>
<P>
   Under Shuster's bill, airlines would have to tell passengers why
a flight is delayed or canceled and reimburse passengers if they
are kept waiting on the ground for more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Shuster and McCain-Wyden bills would require airlines,
upon request, to disclose the number of seats on a flight that are
reserved for frequent flyer awards. They would also allow
passengers to use any portion of a ticket without penalty, which
would end airline restrictions on passengers who buy two
inexpensive round-trip tickets and then use one segment of each
ticket. Passengers often find this tactic cheaper than buying one
round-trip ticket that does not require a Saturday night stay.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill, as well as the administration proposal, would
require airlines to hold a reservation for 48 hours at the same
price, giving people time to comparison shop. Consumers are often
told they must book a flight immediately to secure a particular
price.
</P>
<P>
   The administration proposal would also require airlines to
provide food and restroom facilities during flight delays and
provide information about lower-priced fares.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry originally warned that legislation could
result in higher ticket prices, but it has since softened its
criticism. Carol Hallett, president of the Air Transport
Association, which represents the major airlines, said in prepared
testimony for a Senate Commerce Committee hearing Thursday that the
airlines are ``taking steps'' similar to ones outlined in the
Senate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The House Transportation Aviation Subcommittee plans to continue
its hearings next week when it will hear from airline industry
officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
