<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, March 11. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BASEBALL That bright morning sky in the background of your favorite
player's baseball trading card might easily be the dazzling light
of Arizona spring-training sunshine. Once each spring, the players
dutifully march before the hoards still and video photographers on
picture day. It's these photos and video clips that not only grace
the ever-expanding variety of trading cards, but they also are the
ones pulled during the regular season for mugs in newspapers,
highlights on television and lineups on the jumbo video screens of
stadiums across the continent. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will move in
the ``S'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - On my father's Little League teams, even
the best hitters needed to learn how to lay down a sacrifice bunt.
He believed in sacrifice. He'd learned about it as a kid during the
Great Depression, and from the war, and from 45 years working three
shifts in a steel mill. Not long ago, a doctor asked him a series
of tough questions, each thrown at him like a high, hard fastball.
He never backed away from the plate. ``No,'' he said to more
needles and tubes. No to more poking. No to more prodding. Whatever
was to come, he decided to face it on his terms. And he did. By
E.J. MONTINI Story moved in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - It was my first day at the gym. Eager to
start a new habit that would shrink my butt from a couch to a love
seat, I was going to begin exercising. I had just opened my locker
and slapped on the new lock I had bought at Target the day before
when it happened. She walked by me, then headed toward a bench
across the aisle. Standing in front of me was a naked lady, fresh
from the shower. I guess I just couldn't believe it. I had never
really seen a naked lady before, except for one time when I was 5
and my mom let our hippie neighbor, Honey, take me shopping with
her and her 5-year old daughter. By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in
the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
