<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5408 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALISON-LURIE-NYTR &LR;      03-10 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALISON-LURIE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULITZER-WINNING NOVELIST WRITES AND TEACHES HAPPILY EVER AFTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Fla.)   By BEN STEELMAN   Wilmington (N.C.) Morning Star  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Once upon a time, there was a little girl
named Alison who loved fairy tales. &UR;  &LR; As she grew up to be a famous
and successful author, she kept on reading them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the first stories we hear _ historically, they're the
first stories anyone ever heard,'' said Alison Lurie in her small
office, tucked away behind the stacks in Randall Library at the
University of North Carolina at Wilmington. ``The old stories are
still there, behind modern writing. Cinderella, Jack and the
Beanstalk, Humpty Dumpty all show up again and again, in different
guises.''
</P>
<P>
   Lurie teaches folklore and children's literature as Whiton
professor of American literature at Cornell University. She's also
edited the Oxford Book of Modern Fairy Tales for Oxford University
Press, written three collections of fairy tales and published a
witty and critically praised study of children's stories, ``Don't
Tell the Grown-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   But does she use those tales in her novels for adults?
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I don't,'' she said, ``but there are parallels.''
</P>
<P>
   Many critics, for instance, caught the connection between ``The
Frog Prince'' and Lurie's ``Foreign Affairs,'' the novel that won
the Pulitzer Prize in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In that book, Vinnie Miner, a 54-year-old spinster professor,
flies to London for a semester abroad. On the jet, she's seated
next to Chuck Mumpson, a loud, middle-aged Oklahoman in a cowboy
suit, who irritates her considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, their paths keep crossing in England. Chuck
becomes first Vinnie's close friend and then her passionate lover _
the first true love of Vinnie's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turns into something better, at least in her eyes,'' Lurie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hailed by critic Polly Paddock Gossett as ``one of our most
gifted and astute chroniclers of the gender wars,'' Lurie is
spending a semester at the UNCW as a visiting professor, teaching a
graduate fiction workshop.
</P>
<P>
   She's living in a rented house nearby in Wrightsville Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' she said, pausing, ``in a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   In a different way, that is, from Key West, Fla., where she's
lived part-time since 1980 and where she's set two of her nine
novels, ``The Truth About Lorin Jones'' published in 1988 and her
most recent, ``The Last Resort.'' ``It's a very small island
populated by strange people at the end of the Florida Keys,'' she
told a audience in a recent appearance at a local Barnes &AMP; Noble
book store. ``Also, Key West is a place where things can happen.
People come and go and have all sorts of adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Last Resort,'' the two adventurers are Jenny and her
husband, Wilkie, a once-famous naturalist. At Key West, Jenny, who
had been in Wilkie's shadow, blooms, taking a job and meeting new
friends _ in particular, Lee, the stunning manager of a women-only
guest house.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wilkie slips into depression and decides to drown
himself _ only to be frequently (and sometimes comically) foiled by
random events.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Resort is Lurie's first novel in a decade, ``but I've
been busy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, she published a collection of stories of the
supernatural, ``Women and Ghosts,'' edited her Oxford anthology,
published ``Don't Tell the Grown-ups'' and updated her 1981 study
of fashion, ``The Language of Clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Born on Sept. 3, 1926, in Chicago, Lurie grew up knowing she
wanted to be a writer. Her father was executive director of the
Council of Jewish Federations; her mother was an editor with The
Detroit Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie published stories and poems while she was a student at
Radcliffe College. Yet marriage and motherhood kept her preoccupied
until the late '50s, when she began to edit the plays and poems of
her friend V.R. Lang, an actress and writer who died in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Her first novel, ``Love and Friendship,'' appeared in 1962. One
recurring theme has been adultery and extramarital sex, notably in
``The War Between the Tates,'' her most critically praised novel
before ``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Her plots are independent but interlinked. Characters from one
novel reappear in others.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie said she usually starts her books by making verbal
portraits of the main characters. She then works from an outline,
compiled after she knows her characters well, but added ``I move
things around'' as the story develops.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie won't discuss current projects but said, ``If I'm living
in a settled place, I try to write every day.''
</P>
<P>
   She finds time for frequent readings, often with her husband,
the novelist and folklorist Edward Hower, the author of ``Night
Train Blues,'' and ``Queen of the Silver Dollar.'' (An earlier
marriage to a professor ended in divorce in 1985).
 &UR;  &LR; Lurie emphatically denies that her books are autobiographical &UR; . &LR; 
``We're not that adventurous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ben Steelman writes for the Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C.)
 &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
