<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-10 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING THROUGH A RAIN DELAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sunday morning smelled like rain. On the way to Good
Samaritan Hospital I rolled down the windows and sped up, filling
the inside of the car with the air's dank perfume.
</P>
<P>
   From my father's room on the 11th floor I watched a lid of
clouds slide up from the south over the mountains, closing the
valley like a retractable dome.
</P>
<P>
   The city had gone too long with the roof open and the sky blue
and clear all the way to heaven. We needed rain.
</P>
<P>
   When it fell, though, it fell softly and for only a few minutes,
barely enough to wash the roofs of houses I could see south of the
freeway, less than a groundskeeper might spray on a dusty infield
before the start of a game.
</P>
<P>
   We'd have to wait for more. Just as, in the room on the 11th
floor, we waited.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:45 a.m. on Tuesday, Feb. 23, my dad lost the grip on his
throwing hand.
</P>
<P>
   He'd had heart bypass surgery the day before and gotten through
it fine, but as doctors were removing a breathing tube from his
throat he had a stroke. It's affected his right side.
</P>
<P>
   He could no longer hold a drawing pencil, as he had so often. Or
a steering wheel. A hammer. A rosary. A grandson's hand.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pitches he threw were made during Little League
batting practice. He lobbed them in for his weaker hitters, then
added a little mustard, maybe even a curve, for those accustomed to
having their way at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   It all depended on what the young player needed to improve, and
what he needed to feel good about himself.
</P>
<P>
   He started coaching baseball years before I was born, and kept
at it long after his own two sons had passed the age of Little
League eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   At a Cactus League game last year, watching a grandson lean on
an outfield fence near a professional player, he smiled and said,
``There's nothing like being at a ball field.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days before World War II, he was a bow-legged infielder
with bad eyes and just enough speed to beat out a grounder now and
then.
</P>
<P>
   But he never developed the killer instinct, in baseball or in
war.
</P>
<P>
   It just wasn't in him.
</P>
<P>
   He taught batters to keep their eyes on the ball and to swing
hard (in case they hit it.)
</P>
<P>
   He taught fielders to get in front of a ground ball, even it if
scared them.
</P>
<P>
   Especially if it scared them.
</P>
<P>
   There's some pain involved in baseball, and luck, and skill.
They're all mixed in with the pleasure of the sport, the way it is
with any game, with life.
</P>
<P>
   Players on the field were ordered by my father to ``talk it up``
for the pitcher, to supply a constant stream of encouragement no
matter how many runs had been allowed.
</P>
<P>
   He'd taken a lot of hits himself in the past few weeks. My
brother and I, and the rest of his family, kept talking it up, just
as he'd taught us.
</P>
<P>
   On my father's teams, even the best hitters needed to learn how
to lay down a sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   He believed in sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   He'd learned about it as a kid during the Great Depression, and
from the war, and from 45 years working three shifts in a steel
mill.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, as more and more complications set in, a doctor
asked him a series of tough questions, each thrown at him like a
high, hard fastball.
</P>
<P>
   He never backed away from the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said to more needles and tubes. No to more poking. No
to more prodding. Whatever was to come, he decided to face it on
his terms. And he did.
</P>
<P>
   He died Monday morning, only a few hours after the great
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments when we can no longer ignore coincidence or
cliche.
</P>
<P>
   On his last day, I watched again from my father's room as clouds
gathered on the horizon, remembering the old saying he'd repeat in
the dugout when a sudden storm swept in, interrupting our game.
</P>
<P>
   `'That's baseball,'' he'd tell us. ``Sometimes you win.
Sometimes you lose. Sometimes _ it rains.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5413 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-10 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
