A5415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALESTINIAN-PROTEST-N     03-10 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO PROTESTERS KILLED BY PALESTINIAN SECURITY FORCES, WITNESSES SAY
 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Palestinian security forces in the Gaza Strip shot
and killed two teen-agers Wednesday in violent protests that
erupted after a suspected member of the militant group Hamas was
sentenced to death for killing a Palestinian police officer,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   In scenes reminiscent of a seven-year uprising against Israel,
hundreds of demonstrators poured into the streets of the town of
Rafah, threw stones at the police, burned tires and barricaded
streets after a Palestinian security court there pronounced the
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The unrest was a serious test for Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, who faces growing disillusionment among his people over the
performance of the Palestinian Authority and its security forces.
Amid worsening economic conditions and a freeze in peace efforts,
many Palestinians accuse the authority of corruption, abuse of
power and violating the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   The protests began after the security court sentenced Raed
al-Attar, 25, a suspected member of Hamas who served in the
Palestinian security forces, to die by firing squad for the killing
of a police captain last month. Another suspected militant,
Mohammad Abu Shamala, 25, was given a life sentence, and a third,
Osama Abu Taha, 24, was sentenced to 15 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The captain, Rifat Joudah, was shot and killed as he tried to
arrest the three men, who were wanted by Israel and had enlisted in
the Palestinian security forces. Although witnesses gave
conflicting accounts of the shooting during the two-week trial, all
three defendants were found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no justice in Palestine!'' Attar shouted as he was
led from the courtroom by police officers. He cannot appeal his
death sentence, but the execution requires Arafat's final approval.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second death sentence handed down by a Palestinian
court in recent weeks. A Palestinian colonel was executed last
month, shortly after a speedy trial in which a security court
convicted him of rape and inciting the public against the
Palestinian Authority by his actions. Such quick trials have been
condemned by Palestinian and international huan rights groups as
miscarriages of justice.
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing Wednesday, relatives of Attar and other
protesters marched on the home of Joudah's family and on local
police headquarters, throwing rocks and bottles as police officers
confronted them.
</P>
<P>
   The officers opened fire, killing two teen-agers and wounding
several other protesters, witnesses said. The dead youths were
identified as Ala al-Hams, 17, and Hamis Salamah, 19.
</P>
<P>
   The protests flared again during Hams' funeral hours later, as
mourners stoned police headquarters and officers, shouting
``Arafat, pull out your dogs!'' Witnesses said the officers fired
back, wounding two protesters.
</P>
<P>
   In a belated response to the clashes, Maj. Gen. Ghazi Jabali,
the Palestinian police chief, denied that his forces had shot at
demonstrators and asserted that Israeli soldiers had fired the
fatal shots when protesters shot at their outpost near Rafah on the
border between the Gaza Strip and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli military spokesman emphatically denied Jabali's
charges, asserting that there had been no shooting by Israeli
forces in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
