A5422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DROUGHT-725&AMP;ADD     03-10 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DROUGHT-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DROUGHT IS FORECAST, AND TEXANS ARE NERVOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Still reeling from a 1998 drought that devastated the
state's farming and ranching communities, Texas officials are
growing increasingly alarmed about what appears to be a potentially
more serious drought looming this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still time for it to turn around, but we are not
looking good over much of the state,'' said Roland Smith, an
agricultural economist at Texas A&AMP;M University. ``People are really
getting nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusually warm winter and dearth of rainfall, particularly
in the western two-thirds of the state, have severely damaged the
winter wheat crop and stunted the growth of hay and natural grasses
for cattle and other livestock. And during the next two months, a
crucial time for the spring plantings of cotton, corn and other
crops, drier than normal conditions are predicted for most of the
major farming regions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agriculture Department's Climate Prediction Center
lists the Trans-Pecos region in far western Texas and most of the
state's Mexican border areas as abnormally dry, and the long-term
drought severity index shows the Trans-Pecos and parts of the
plains of west-central Texas in a state of moderate drought. If
rainfall projections hold true, officials say, most of West and
South Texas will experience a moderate to extreme drought as early
as next month.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Agriculture Commissioner Susan
Combs are expected to unveil drought-related initiatives on
Thursday morning, including declaring emergencies in 170 of the
state's 254 counties where dry conditions have created a
significant risk of fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the La Nina thing,'' Ms. Combs said. ``We are right today
at the same point in drought index comparisons where we were when
the governor declared a drought emergency in June of 1998. We're
three months ahead of last year, and that's what's giving people
heartburn.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite flooding last fall in towns like Del Rio, Texas is
flirting not only with a second consecutive year of paralyzing
drought, but the third year of drought in the last four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain areas of the state did have some very large amounts of
rain in the fall,'' Smith said. ``But that was rains that came so
fast that a lot of the water ran off and we haven't had much rain
in any of those places since.''
</P>
<P>
   And where rain fell over the winter, ``none of it has penetrated
into the subsoil, which is so necessary to make a reasonable cotton
crop,'' said Carl Anderson, an agricultural economist at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been a particularly windy winter, adding to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody knows, that when the wind blows across the surface of
the land, it actually sucks the moisture out,'' Ms. Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the ground is especially dry going into the spring
rainy season, which should be starting about now. ``We keep hoping
for three inches or so each time one of these fronts moves through,
but they just keep on blowing past, dropping just a half-inch here
and there, and then heading out East,'' Mr. Anderson said. ``If it
stays dry another six weeks or so, we will see some tremendous
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service projections call for below-normal
rainfall in Texas in the coming months. But even if the spring
rains come in normal amounts, they may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials say, copious spring rains might produce an
adequate crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is time for a turn around,'' Anderson said. ``This is
only just now becoming a serious threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas agricultural economists predicted last summer that the
1998 drought would mean a drop of $2.1 billion in the state's farm
and ranch production. In fact, a report released in February by
Texas A&AMP;M found that the drop was $2.4 billion, and that $8 billion
more was lost in farm-dependent businesses, mostly in the smallest,
rural towns.
</P>
<P>
   Most agricultural economists are loath to speculate, but the
Texas Agricultural Extension Service estimated that the 1998
drought persuaded as many as 10 percent of the state's farmers and
ranchers to quit the business. ``People are giving up, they just
can't make it,'' Ms. Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas agriculture is very vulnerable as we move into 1999,''
Smith said. ``Another year like last year, without additional
significant federal help, and we're going to lose a lot of
farmers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A bill is working its way through the Texas Legislature that
would provide $25 million in drought relief, but it is aimed at
those suffering from last year's drought. In October, Congress
passed $5.9 billion in disaster aid to farmers affected by droughts
throughout the country and an estimated $2.4 billion remains to be
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Combs said Texas officials will urge the federal government
to speed up those payments.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's drought hit every corner of the state. For the
moment, at least, this year's drought threat is more localized.
</P>
<P>
   The Trans-Pecos areas have had just 19 percent of the rainfall
this winter that they would have had in a normal year, Ms. Combs
said, and the Edwards Plateau region of west-central Texas has had
just 24 percent. But the rolling plains, north of the Edwards
Plateau, have had 69 percent of normal rainfall, and the high
plains of the Texas Panhandle have had 93 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
