<HEADLINE>
DISNEY MAGIC: IT'S A SMALL WORLD AFTER Y'ALL
</HEADLINE>
 IDEAS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP and ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disney's at it again.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks back, to promote the video release of ``Mulan,''
entertainment's most synergistic company built a replica of the
Great Wall of China in the hamlet of China, Texas. This week, in
the near-China city of Beaumont, the company is hyping the video
reissue of the animated ``101 Dalmatians'' by building a
24-foot-tall Dalmatian-spotted fire hydrant.
</P>
<P>
   Why Beaumont? Because it's the home of the Fire Museum of Texas.
And Disney's not about to stop at a massive fire hydrant. During
the dedication ceremony Tuesday, 101 Texas firefighters performed a
production number to the tune of ``Cruella de Vil.'' The
firefighters formed a 101 figure around the hydrant, and the number
concluded with the hydrant showering them with water and confetti.
They had Dalmatian-patterned umbrellas to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Look, we're not making this up. We swear. But it did inspire us
to make up a whole bunch of other stuff. Just imagine what other
promotions Disney could do in Texas cities:
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame''
</P>
<P>
   City: Paris
</P>
<P>
   Record-breaking structure: An actual-size replica of the
Cathedral of Notre Dame _ built with Legos!
</P>
<P>
   Big production number: One hundred local residents dressed as
gargoyles dance to the tune of ``The Bells of Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Hercules''
</P>
<P>
   City: Athens
</P>
<P>
   Record-breaking structure: The world's largest gyro!
</P>
<P>
   Big production number: Hundreds of toga-clad frat boys from
nearby universities form a Greek chorus, doing shots while belting
out a slightly tipsy rendition of ``Go the Distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Little Mermaid''
</P>
<P>
   City: Sea World, San Antonio
</P>
<P>
   Record-breaking structure: World's largest sand castle!
</P>
<P>
   Big production number: Twenty mariachi bands do a salsa-style
rendition of ``Under the Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``A Bug's Life''
</P>
<P>
   City: Flower Mound
</P>
<P>
   Record-breaking structure: World's largest ant farm!
</P>
<P>
   Big production number: Seventy-five exterminators plant a
rubber-tree orchard while singing ``High Hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Winnie-the-Pooh''
</P>
<P>
   City: The Woodlands
</P>
<P>
   Record-breaking structure: A big ol' buzzin' beehive!
</P>
<P>
   Big production number: One hundred oilmen dressed as Tigger
bounce, trounce and flounce to the tune of ``The wonderful thing
about tiggers/is that tiggers are wonderful things ...''
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Bambi''
</P>
<P>
   City: Deer Park
</P>
<P>
   Record-breaking structure: Experience the world's largest
simulated forest fire!
</P>
<P>
   Big event: Area gamesmen compete for the largest rack in a
pre-dawn deer hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``James and the Giant Peach''
</P>
<P>
   Locale: Parker County, home of the peach festival
</P>
<P>
   Record-breaking structure: Duh, a giant peach, of course!
</P>
<P>
   Big production number: Fifty fruit packers sing and dance to a
medley of Peaches and Herb's greatest hits.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
