r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIGRAINE-RELIEF-TEX     03-10 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIGRAINE-RELIEF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRUGS CAN HELP IN THE FIGHT AGAINST MIGRAINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pain of her migraine headaches is so intense that Fort Worth
artist Kathy Suder once threw herself headfirst into a snowbank in
Colorado, burying her face in the snow to get some relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Headaches sound so minor,'' Suder says. ``Migraines shouldn't
be called headaches. They are more like brain explosions,
completely incapacitating.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has experienced a migraine knows they are unlike
ordinary headaches. In a migraine, severe, often throbbing pain
starts on one side of the head and usually stays there, although it
can shift to the other side the next time a migraine occurs. The
pain may cause nausea, vomiting, chills or sweating, cold hands,
shaking and sensitivity to light and sound. Attacks can last
several minutes or several days; most last four to six hours.
</P>
<P>
   For years, there was little relief for the 26 million Americans
_ 18 million of them women _ who suffer from migraines. But for two
to three years, the mysteries surrounding debilitating migraine
attacks have begun to unravel, and new drugs to prevent and treat
migraines are offering much better pain control.
</P>
<P>
   Maxalt, the most recent drug approved for migraine treatment,
won the nod from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration in June. It
is the newest member of a medications class known as the
``triptan'' drugs, and is closely related to sumatriptan (Imitrex,
which six years ago became the first major drug approved
specifically for migraine), naratriptan and zolmitriptan.
</P>
<P>
   Maxalt is available in several forms, including a new ``orally
disintegrating tablet,'' a small tablet that can be taken easily
without water. It has a faster onset of action than other forms,
with relief in as little as 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for health-care professionals is getting the word
out to migraine sufferers. Although the national Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention report that the prevalence of
migraine in the United States increased nearly 60 percent over the
past decade, many people don't seek treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Migraine sufferers are not treated well at all, even now,''
says Dr. Ninan Mathew, president of the International Headache
Society. ``We have good treatments for acute attacks and for
preventing migraine, but less than 40 percent of patients with
migraines ever get proper diagnosis and treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that until the recent research advances,
there were no effective medications, and many patients feared being
labeled hypochondriacs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myths prevent proper treatment,'' says Mathew, a clinical
professor of neurology at the University of Texas-Houston Health
Science Center. Mathew is medical director of the Houston Headache
Clinic and its satellite, the Dallas Headache Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we have the common myth, `It's all in the head, it's
all psychological,' and that is not true. Stress, depression,
anxiety can produce a migraine, but they are not the cause, only
some of the triggers,'' Mathew said.
</P>
<P>
   Second is the mistaken belief that every headache in the front
of the head is a sinus headache, and that the best treatment is to
take decongestants and antihistamines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the so-called sinus headaches are not that at all.
They're a myth,'' Mathew says. ``If you have recurrent, throbbing
headaches, it's not sinus.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most troubling myths is the belief that migraine is an
``emotional problem'' caused by an inability to deal with the
stress of daily living. It is particularly disturbing because it
may reflect a hidden prejudice against women, who are three times
more likely than men to suffer chronic headaches, the American
Council for Headache Education said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the greater vulnerability of women is due to
biological triggers _ primarily fluctuations in estrogen levels _
not emotional or psychological factors,'' said Dr. Joel Saper, a
physician member of the council.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 percent of migraine sufferers have a family history
of headaches, and recent research indicates that the headaches have
physical causes, according to the National Headache Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is dilation during an attack and inflammatory changes
around the blood vessels of the brain. That's what causes the pain,
but ultimately biochemical changes in the brain itself are what
cause a migraine attack,'' Mathew said. ``The whole thing is caused
by a sequence of events. Something triggers biochemical changes
that cause blood vessels in the brain to dilate, resulting in the
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of possible triggers is extensive: stress, the wrong
diet, lack of sleep, missing a meal. Chocolate, red wine, MSG
flavor enhancer, anything with Nutrasweet, and aged cheese can
provoke a migraine; so can noise, certain odors, bright lights and
watching TV. Migraine sufferers are often affected by cigarette
smoke, too much or too little sleep, menstruation and changes in
altitude and temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment for migraine usually begins with lifestyle changes:
determining individual triggers and removing them; avoiding bright
lights and sudden altitude changes such as those caused by airplane
flights and even fast elevators in tall buildings; and taking
over-the-counter pain relievers. Excedrin has a formulation
recently approved by the Food and Drug Administration specifically
for migraine.
</P>
<P>
   Some headache doctors are also recommending magnesium and
riboflavin (vitamin B-2) and the herbal remedy feverfew, along with
pain relievers.
</P>
<P>
   But Mathew says he saw a man recently who had been taking 200
Excedrin a week for months before he sought a headache specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are taking OTC (over-the-counter) pain medication every
day, it's not good,'' Mathew says. ``People feel nonprescription
drugs are safe, but they have many side effects. The stomach and
liver can suffer, and people who take frequent pain medication can
get into analgesic rebound headaches where they feel better for an
hour or two, then their headache's back and they take medicine
again, and it becomes a vicious cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have not developed a cure for migraine. But for some
patients, there's good news _ attacks sometimes become milder or
even stop on their own, especially in women after menopause.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on migraine headaches, call the National
Headache Foundation toll-free at (800) 843-2256.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
