<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5433 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-COMPETITION-TEX     03-10 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-COMPETITION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH'S OPERA CONTEST FLIRTS WITH THE BIG TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORTH WORTH, Texas _ It's not just a homey little contest
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Marguerite McCammon Vocal Competition of the
Fort Worth Opera Guild will move downtown, beneficiary of a growing
endowment and reputation.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the fans were admitted for free and often barely
outnumbered the staff, jury and competitors in the daylong event at
the Scott Theatre. The volunteer staffers, competitors and members
of the press mingled at a casual potluck supper, trading gossip and
tips, before the evening finals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sophistication and prestige have crept up on the McCammon.
</P>
<P>
   The McCammon has sacrificed the up-close intimacy (but generally
poor acoustics) of the 481-seat Scott Theatre for the grandeur of
Bass Performance Hall in downtown Fort Worth. Audience members will
pay $10, which covers admission to both sessions (still a bargain,
considering that the next Placido Domingo or Cecilia Bartoli might
be onstage). The finals will be held in the late afternoon, to
clear the hall in time for the evening performance of Puccini's
``Tosca.''
</P>
<P>
   Opera buffs can make a day of it downtown, attending the first
session at noon, the finals at 4 p.m. and then Tosca at 7:30 p.m.
Particularly hardy fans can also attend a panel discussion at 10
a.m. in the Grand Salon of Bass Hall, at which jurors will discuss
``Ten Ways to Sabotage Your Audition.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still not quite the operatic equivalent of the Cliburn
competition, with its international audition tour, its two weeks of
performances in Fort Worth, its undisputed spot at the top of the
piano competition world and its prize package valued at $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the McCammon has established a secure niche in the operatic
world _ where, admittedly, auditions are the main source of
advancement. And, although it won't challenge the Cliburn as the
focus of local loyalty and pride, it has two elements that
Cliburn's fans might envy.
</P>
<P>
   First, two recent first-prize winners _ mezzo-soprano Vivica
Genaux and Frank Hernandez _ have gone on to establish good careers
in the operatic world.
</P>
<P>
   Second, for competition groupies who really get emotionally
involved, the McCammon lets audiences choose _ and reward _ a
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a year in which chronic controversy over the dismissal
and rehiring of general director William Walker has engulfed the
Fort Worth Opera, the McCammon has provided a focus for members of
the Opera Guild. Legally independent of the Fort Worth Opera
Association (though supporting the Fort Worth Opera is its main
function), the Opera Guild has stayed outside the fray and kept its
collective mind on the McCammon.
</P>
<P>
   The McCammon was founded in 1969 with a gift of $5,000 from Mary
Ann W. Armstrong of Natchez, Miss., in honor of her niece,
Marguerite McCammon, of Fort Worth, who was then president of the
Opera Guild of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The gift from Armstrong originally financed a scholarship
limited to singers in Texas; the concept eventually expanded to a
national competition for professional singers.
</P>
<P>
   The prize money is up, as well. With an endowment fund now at
$91,000, the McCammon can afford to give the top winner, who is
also offered a role with the Fort Worth Opera, a prize of $5,000.
(It was $3,000 at the most recent competition, in 1997.) Second-
and third-place winners will take $2,000 and $1,500, respectively,
compared with $1,200 and $1,000 at the 1997 contest. The three
nonplacing finalists will each receive $250, and the remaining
semifinalists will each receive $150.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the audience ballot will take home $600 in memory
of past opera President Rick Berg.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-three applicants _ an all-time high _ submitted tapes
this year. The competition was open to singers pursuing a
professional career in opera, ages 21-32 if female and 21-35 if
male. A jury _ including former Vienna State Opera bass-baritone
Reid Bunger of the Southern Methodist University faculty; Fort
Worth Opera associate conductor Jing Ling Tam; and tenor David
Sundquist of the faculty of the University of North Texas _
selected 12 semifinalists and two alternates in February.
</P>
<P>
   As Walker, who frequently hears regional Metropolitan Opera
auditions, points out, this is an unusual group in that men
outnumber women.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Metropolitan Opera auditions these days, about 80 percent
of the competitors are women,'' Walker says. ``And 75 percent of
those are lyric sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   The semifinalists will arrive Thursday and Friday and rehearse
with piano accompanists Alan Buratto of the Fort Worth Opera staff,
and Tara Emerson, staff accompanist at SMU, on Friday. Several live
or grew up close by and will stay with family, but most will stay
in the homes of volunteers, as at the Cliburn.
</P>
<P>
   The main competition jury will include Walker, Boston Lyric
Opera general director Janice Mancini Del Sesto, Portland Opera
general director Robert Bailey and Fort Worth Opera principal
conductor Richard Barrett. In the two sessions, the jurors will
select from a list of four arias submitted by each contestant,
including at least two non-English arias and one aria in English.
</P>
<P>
   The competition also presents the chance for exposure to other
opera companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our judges are unique,'' Walker says. ``Each of these people
can offer a job to any of these singers.''
</P>
<P>
   One only need recall the case of mezzo-soprano Vivica Genaux.
Genaux, then 23, drove from Pittsburgh in wintry March weather to
participate in the 1993 competition. With her extraordinary
flexibility and stamina, she walked away with first prize; Jonathan
Pell, of the Dallas Opera, was on the jury, and he immediately
offered her a contract. Genaux has since moved up to title roles in
major houses and an acclaimed Metropolitan Opera debut.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, picking the winner is easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only takes a couple of bars,'' Barrett says.
</P>
<P>
   But, he cautions, ``Some people are good at competitions, and
can win them, and then get on the stage and can't perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Sesto, a frequent judge at vocal competitions, says she
looks for theatrical as well as vocal talent. Even in a recital
set-up, you can spot that dramatic flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it in the way they deliver the sung word,'' she says.
``Beyond the voice, one of the most powerful means of expression is
the face _ particularly the eyes. I've seen singers who didn't have
to move an inch to be theatrical.''
</P>
<P>
   With its steadily growing endowment, its handsome venue and the
success of recent winners, the McCammon hopes to continue growing
in prestige.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that this year is a jumping-off point to become
even bigger,'' says opera guild President Jan Aziz.
</P>
<P>
   And then, perhaps, the Cliburn won't be the only classical
competition that Fort Worth is famous for. (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
