<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BISCUITS11-COX     03-10 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISCUITS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traditional recipe and variations of biscuits
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Take that meal from b-o-r-i-n-g to BOING! in one
easy trick: Bake a biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap and fast, a homemade biscuit elevates any meal _
breakfast, lunch or dinner _ beyond its normal status.
</P>
<P>
   Like a culinary makeover, this pillow of bread _ light as a
cloud _ will make the most of such simple offerings as a bowl of
soup, grilled or fried chicken, a slice of meatloaf, a link of
Texas sausage or a veggie plate.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never made biscuits from scratch, it's a tad more
effort than a bowl of cereal but nothing like you think. There are
tricks out there that make this bread a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   It helps, of course, if you start with the right ingredients:
especially self-rising flour. Soft, low-protein self-rising flour
such as White Lily makes the best biscuits, but it's not always
easy to find in Texas. Thus, some cooks pick up a bag of this flour
on trips through Southern states or order it from the company
(www.whitelily.com) and keep it in the freezer just for biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   However, Shirley Corriher, that Georgia queen of biscuits and
author of ``Cookwise,'' says if low-protein flour is not available,
you can use 1 cup of national self-rising flour and 1/2 cup instant
flour (such as Wondra) or cake flour, plus 1/2 teaspoon baking
powder. That you can find easily in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, forget all those tips you might have heard from your
grandmother about the messy task of cutting shortening into flour.
Not necessary. Times have changed. Think cream instead of
shortening. Think stirring instead of cutting. Think patting
instead of rolling. Think: Is this all there is to it?
</P>
<P>
   Yep, we're talking only two ingredients here _ self-rising flour
and cream. Maybe 15 minutes of effort. Not that you need to tell
anyone. Just let people be impressed that you seemed to have
mastered that generations-old art of baking that gives Texans a
reason to get up in the morning or makes supper a celebratory
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, master this recipe and you are no longer a one-bread
wonder. You can stir in all sorts of flavorful accents from herbs
to cheeses. And the same technique works for strawberry shortcakes
or scones, which are basically biscuits with a touch of sugar. Yet
other opportunities to shine.
</P>
<P>
   Cream Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   2 cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cream, whipping or half and half
</P>
<P>
   Place self-rising flour in a large bowl. Stir in cream, just
until dough is blended.
</P>
<P>
   Use two large serving spoons to drop dough onto a very lightly
greased cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   For rolled biscuits: Turn dough onto a lightly floured surface,
knead four or five times. Then roll or pat dough out to 1/2-inch
thickness. With a biscuit cutter, cut dough into biscuits.
(Old-time cooks may have used a jelly glass to cut out the
biscuits, but a cutter makes a prettier biscuit with a cleaner
edge.) Reroll any scraps and cut more biscuits. Bake for 10-15
minutes or until lightly browned in an oven preheated to 450
degrees. Makes 8-10 biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   If substituting 2 cups all-purpose flour, add 1/2 teaspoon salt
, 1/2 teaspoon baking soda and 3 teaspoons baking powder.
</P>
<P>
   Note: For shortcake, add a tablespoon of sugar
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   2 cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   2/3 or 3/4 cup milk or buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Place flour in a large bowl. Add shortening and cut in with
pastry cutter or two knives until mixture resembles coarse crumbs.
Add just enough milk for dough to come together and leave sides of
the bowl. Place dough on lightly floured surface. Knead lightly
about 10 times. Pat or roll dough out to 1/2-inch thickness. Cut
with biscuit cutter. Place on an ungreased baking sheet, close
together for soft-sided biscuits, about an inch apart for crisper
edges. Bake in a preheated 450-degree oven for 10-15 minutes, until
golden brown. Makes about 10 biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   If substituting 2 cups all-purpose flour, add 1/2 teaspoon salt
, 1/2 teaspoon baking soda and 3 teaspoons baking powder.
</P>
<P>
   Cream Scones
</P>
<P>
   2 cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup white or brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried currants or raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/4 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon and sugar
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour and sugar in large bowl. Add currants or raisins.
Stir in cream, reserving at least a tablespoon to brush on top of
the scones. Mix just until ingredients are moist. Gather the dough
into a ball and knead it gently against the sides and bottom of the
bowl 5 to 10 times. Transfer to a lightly floured surface and pat
the dough into an 8-inch round about 3/4 inch thick. Cut into 8 or
10 wedges and place at least 1/2-inch apart on a large ungreased
baking sheet. Brush the scone tops with the reserved cream and
sprinkle with cinnamon and sugar. Bake in a preheated 425-degree
oven until tops are golden brown, about 12 to 15 minutes. Makes 8
to 10 scones.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all purpose flour, 1 tablespoon baking powder and 1/2
teaspoon of salt may be substituted for the self-rising flour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``Joy of Cooking''
</P>
<P>
   Biscuit boosters
</P>
<P>
   A tablespoon, or more to taste, of one of these will transform a
batch of plain biscuits:
</P>
<P>
   Sage, above Thyme Rosemary Chives Cracked black pepper Grated
ginger Orange zest Goat cheese Cheddar cheese Sweet potatoes Bacon
bits Peanut butter Sundried tomatoes Chiles Top this
</P>
<P>
   Butter, gravy, jam? Everyone's got a favorite biscuit topper.
The most popular is margarine or butter. Second is jelly, jam or
preserves. Gravy is third; honey, fourth. Lagging far behind is
cheese or breakfast syrups.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought people had switched to bagels exclusively, think
again. In the past five years, sales of big refrigerated canned
biscuits have grown more than 38 percent industrywide.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner is the most popular meal for biscuits nationwide. But in
the South, breakfast is biscuit time, although dinner is fast
catching up.
</P>
<P>
   More biscuits are eaten on Sunday in the United States than any
other day. Saturday is the runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
