</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISHSTEW11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let your Irish stew for hours with a wee bit of Guinness
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austinite Helen Frink says her family loves the
Frugal Gourmet's recipe for Irish Stew, but wondered if it could be
adapted to a slow cooker for convenience.
</P>
<P>
   We sent her request to the test kitchen of the Texas Beef
Council, and director Anne Bried worked out the details in time for
St. Patrick's Day next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Beef Stew with Guinness Stout
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds beef stew meat
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion in 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound carrots, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme, whole
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup beef stock
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Guinness Stout
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   2-3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Brown the meat in the olive oil on both sides on high heat.
Place onions and carrots on bottom of slow cooker. Add meat, bay
leaves, garlic, thyme, rosemary, stock, Guinness and parsley. Cover
and cook in slow cooker on high 4-6 hours or follow guidelines for
low setting.
</P>
<P>
   After removing meat from pot, thicken juices with the 2
tablespoons of flour that have been mixed well with 2 tablespoons
water. Add to pot and cook on high until boiling. Add salt and
pepper to taste. Return meat to pot.
</P>
<P>
   Tips for slow cooking
</P>
<P>
   Any dish that is cooked with moist heat does well in a slow
cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce liquids by half. Another rule of thumb is that 1 cup of
liquid is enough for any recipe. Because liquids don't boil away in
a slow cooker, you'll have more liquid at the end of cooking
instead of less.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce most steps in recipes by adding all the ingredients to
the slow cooker at once.
</P>
<P>
   Add milk, sour cream or other dairy products during the last
hour of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Cook pasta and rice before adding to the cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Dried beans should be boiled 10 minutes before adding to the
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   The flavor of leaf or whole herbs will intensify, so start with
half the recommended amount in a conventional recipe. Add ground
herbs and spices during the last hour of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Most uncooked meat and vegetable combinations will require
cooking at least 8 hours on low.
</P>
<P>
   If a conventional recipe says cook 15 to 30 minutes, slow-cook
on low 4 to 6 hours or on high 1 1/2 to 2 hours. If a conventional
recipe says cook for 35 to 45 minutes, slow-cook on low 6 to 10
hours or on high 3 to 4 hours. If a conventional recipe says cook
for 50 minutes to 3 hours, cook on low 8 to 18 hours or on high 4
to 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Food cooked in a slow cooker is safe. The direct heat from the
pot, lengthy cooking time and the steam created inside the
tightly-sealed container act together to destroy bacteria,
according to the Food and Drug Administration. However, because
these cookers can take several hours to reach a safe
bacteria-killing temperature, meat and poultry must already be
defrosted and must be kept in the refrigerator until it's time to
cook. Otherwise, there may be too much time with the food at
``danger zone'' temperatures where bacteria multiply rapidly. Also,
follow the cooker's directions regarding food chopping and how to
fill the pot. _ Anne Bried, Texas Beef Council test kitchen
director
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
