<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More than two-thirds of CEOs choose Bush as GOP's hope
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ George W. Bush is more than the ``spittin' image of
his dad,'' according to Fortune (March 29). He's the man who could
be president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wildly popular Texas governor, a man with enough of a
past to make him interesting _ and the Republican Party's hope for
the future,'' says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   America's corporate chief executives like the son of the former
president. Fortune said 68 percent of the CEOs contacted in a
special poll chose Bush over any of the other likely GOP
candidates, including Elizabeth Dole (8 percent) and former Vice
President Dan Quayle (3 percent). Pitted against Vice President Al
Gore, the CEOs chose Bush 86 percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Fortune says the state of Texas has made a strong
comeback from its long era of economic distress because of
declining oil prices. The recovery occurred when state leaders
turned their attention from finding oil to making computers.
</P>
<P>
   WHY GREENSPAN IS SERENE
</P>
<P>
   With the bond market pushing up long-term Treasury yields,
there's no need for the Federal Reserve to raise short-term
interest rates, Business Week (March 15) says in a look at the
recent trend in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about the economy and prospects of inflation caused bond
traders to panic, which pushed bond yields to the highest levels in
six months before leveling off recently.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in bond yields takes some of the heat off of Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan to engineer a rate hike at the Fed,
Business Week says. Not only that, Fed insiders believe the economy
will slow anyway, which also will make a rate hike unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW OFFICE WARFARE
</P>
<P>
   We're accustomed by now to sexism in the workplace, where men
have privileges women don't have, and so-called age-ism, where the
discrimination is against older workers. The new generational
warfare, says Forbes (March 22), is between young women and older
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just women fighting women. . . much of the
friction takes place between different generations: the older,
trailblazing women who had to sacrifice family for careers and the
younger, want-it-all-now women,'' says Forbes. In both cases, the
biggest problem is balancing career and family.
</P>
<P>
   FROM SURFING TO INVESTING
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Funds (April) magazine takes readers inside the emerging
world of investing on the Net, or cybertrading.
</P>
<P>
   Some 6.8 million U.S. households were involved in online trading
in 1998, and the number will double to 13.8 million households by
2001, says the magazine, which offers a menu of how-to and
where-to-find articles for the fledgling online trader.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
