<HEADER>
A5458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING11-COX     03-10 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring to offer $800 million in securities, possibly for
expansion, acquisitions
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises, the Atlanta-based Internet
service provider, Wednesday notified the Securities and Exchange
Commission of plans to offer up to $800 million in securities,
which could be used to pay for expansion, including acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Desimone, MindSpring executive vice president and general
counsel, would not elaborate on MindSpring's plans for the
offering. ``We've established it to permit MindSpring to react in a
time-efficient manner to market opportunities as they present
themselves. I can't really tell you what the specifics are,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, industry analysts and Internet watchers believe the
$800 million is being put in reserve for MindSpring's future growth
plans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to serious competition from AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom's
Internet divisions, the eventual mass market deployment of high
speed cable and phone access threaten to make obsolete ISPs that
use conventional telephone lines. Although analysts say that
transition is several years away, MindSpring may be thinking about
ways to retain and perhaps convert its 1 million subscribers to
alternative Internet delivery methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving consolidation in a very fragmented ISP market is what
they should be doing,'' says Jupiter Communications analyst Abhai
Chaki, who feels there are many growth opportunities MindSpring
could take on with $800 million. ``They may not do any of these
things, but there are lots of options open to them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Chaki says that acquiring larger ISPs should be MindSpring's
goal, even though it's an expensive one.
</P>
<P>
   ``MindSpring could also be looking at expanding into broadband,
making investments into offering DSL technology and talking with
BellSouth or other telecos.'' (Both broadband cable connections and
the competing technology from the telephone company, Digital
Subscriber Line, offer high speed connections.)
</P>
<P>
   Then again, MindSpring could be thinking along different lines.
``They could be looking at cable operators and considering giving
them significant up-front commitments in return for carriage
rights. Or they could be buying up smaller cable operators or
create some new company like At Home and partner with smaller cable
operators, who would do the marketing while MindSpring provided the
service,'' Chaki said.
</P>
<P>
   Company founder Charles Brewer is credited by many analysts with
building an executive team that is planning for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job Charles Brewer has done is exceptional,'' said Charles
A. Morris, manager of the T. Rowe Price &AMP; Science Technology Fund.
``He's to be commended.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morris also feels the next 18 months are going to be tough
times for MindSpring, Earthlink and other independent dial-up ISPs.
``We believe as we get into the high selling season in 1999, the
customers are going to be offered Internet service from their PC
manufacturer,'' Morris said. ``They will have a customer
relationship that's going to make it very difficult for consumer
ISPs.''
</P>
<P>
   In its registration filing, which listed no underwriters,
MindSpring said the securities could include common and preferred
stock, depositary shares, debt securities, warrants, subscription
rights, share purchase contracts to purchase common or preferred
shares, and share purchase units.
</P>
<P>
   Besides acquisitions, the company said the proceeds could be
used for additional working capital; capital expenditures; general
purposes; and to fund net losses and repay debt.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Robert Luke and wire services contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
