<HEADER>
A5459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBMD11-COX     03-10 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD links with Lycos for $52.5 million
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD announced a $52.5 million deal Wednesday that
will give it exclusive rights to provide health information on the
Internet network of Lycos Inc.
</P>
<P>
   With the three-year pact, Atlanta-based WebMD took another leap
toward its goal of becoming the Net's first name in health
information. And while the company's first stream of business
revenue came from selling subscriptions and services to doctors,
entre to Lycos means access to millions of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, which has one of the Net's best-used search engines
(http://www.lycos.com), claims nearly 30 million users. USA
Networks reaches about 70 million homes. Lycos users looking for
health data will soon be guided to a joint WebMD-Lycos site. WebMD
will also get advertising and promotions on USA Networks.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, WebMD is paying for the audience
enjoyed on the Net by Lycos and on television by its soon-to-be
corporate parent, USA Networks, said Bob Davis, Lycos president,
who will become a WebMD board member as part of the deal. ``This
whole thing translates into audience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD officials cited a recent survey by Penn, Schoen &AMP; Berland,
which showed that Net users are three times less likely to seek out
a particular health site than to use a search engine like Lycos or
Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos now offers a range of links and stories about health, as
well as many other subjects. WebMD's offering is more consistent
and sweeping, Davis said. ``There are too many places that show you
snapshots of information and not enough that give you something
comprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD's consumer offerings are free. But WebMD _ like Lycos _
sells advertising space on their Web pages. WebMD also sells
various products, many of them through partners. The greater the
number of visitors to the site, the more advertisers can be charged
and the greater profit likely to come from product sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to quarterback the health channel on Lycos,''
said WebMD founder and Chief Executive Jeff Arnold. ``It gives us a
competitive advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold shrugged off the investment of $52.5 million as a modest
expense when compared to the potential market WebMD is attacking.
``This business is not as difficult to project as one might think.
You just look at the markets in healthcare and information products
and the dollars being spent by consumers are enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD _ in business for only about six months _ has announced
plans for a public offering of stock. Like other deals WebMD has
recently forged, the Lycos announcement seems likely to bolster the
value of WebMD's coming offer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
