<SLUG> BC-IOWA-POLLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LEADS FIELD OF LIKELY GOP PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES, POLL
INDICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas holds a commanding
lead among likely participants in next year's key Iowa Republican
presidential caucuses, a new poll finds.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, with 32.7 percent, led former Republican Cabinet official
Elizabeth Hanford Dole, at 14.7 percent, according to the survey by
PSI, a marketing and survey research firm, for four television
stations with Iowa viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing were former Vice President Dan Quayle, 7.3 percent;
former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, 7 percent; and
columnist-commentator Pat Buchanan, 6.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other prospective Republican contenders polled less than 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has a wide base of support among all age groups, both
sexes and Republican political activists,'' said PSI president
Craig Tufty, a former Iowa Republican operative.
</P>
<P>
   Tufty said Dole, who on Wednesday announced formation of a
national committee to explore a presidential campaign in Des
Moines, Iowa, was the only other ``genuine contender'' at this
point in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He said 56 percent of Dole's votes go to Bush as a second choice
and 45 percent of Bush's votes go to Dole as a second choice.
</P>
<P>
   All the other possible contenders ``just fell off the end of the
earth,'' Tufty said.
</P>
<P>
   But the views of likely caucus attendees may give hope to some
of the candidates who are more outspoken about their conservative
views, especially their opposition to abortion, than Bush and Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Seven percent of respondents ranked abortion as the most
important issue, which ran closely behind the four leading issues:
Social Security, 11 percent, followed by taxes, morality and
education, 10 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the PSI poll a year before the Iowa caucuses
found Dole's husband, then-Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, with a
giant lead, at 36 percent, 25 percentage points above the
second-ranked former Vice President Dan Quayle, who did not run in
1996 but is expected in the race for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 Iowa caucuses, Dole ran a lackluster first, with 26
percent, followed by Buchanan with 23 percent and Alexander with 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The caucuses historically have emphasized candidates' ability to
sell themselves directly to voters, often in small meetings, and to
organize on a grassroots, precinct-by-precinct basis.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not been in Iowa in the last two years, and Dole has
made four appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest poll, Bush led among male and female respondents
but more narrowly among women. With women, the race broke down Bush
29.6 percent, Dole 15.9 percent. With men, the split was Bush 35.8
percent, Dole 13.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   PSI made 5,857 random phone calls in Iowa to find the final
sample of 300 Iowans deemed likely to attend the Iowa precinct
meetings next February at the beginning of the presidential
nominating season. The final sample was polled March 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
