A5467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-COLLEGES-EDUC-N     03-10 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-COLLEGES-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD SMALL LIBERAL ARTS COLLEGES ADOPT A MORE PRACTICAL FOCUS TO
SURVIVE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Endowments are up, and so are applications. At the nation's 550
small private liberal arts colleges, times have seemingly never
been better. So why do many educators fear for their future?
</P>
<P>
   In the winter issue of Daedalus, the quarterly journal of the
American Academy of Arts and Sciences, being mailed to subscribers
this week, several scholars warn that these institutions face a
serious quandary in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   One, Eva Brann, a former dean at St. John's College in
Annapolis, Md., goes so far as to call these institutions ``an
endangered species.'' And Paul Neely, a trustee of Williams College
who is publisher of The Chattanooga Times, writes that ``there may
simply be more pure liberal arts colleges than we need.''
</P>
<P>
   About half a dozen small private residential colleges close
their doors every year, and many others survive only by merging
with larger institutions. Furthermore, the number of accepted
students who eventually enroll _ a critical percentage that
educators call ``yield'' _ is as low as 30 percent at even some of
the most admired of these campuses, against well over 90 percent
for the Ivy League institutions.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, educators _ and not just those writing for Daedalus
_ are posing a long-term question for the small liberal arts
colleges: Should they shift their focus from a high-minded,
education-for-its-own-sake approach to a more down-to-earth,
job-oriented curriculum featuring programs in subjects like
computer science, the global marketplace and accounting?
</P>
<P>
   More than a few have already made the shift. ``Pre-professional
programs are a definite trend in our schools,'' said David Warren,
president of the National Association of Independent Colleges and
Universities, which represents most of the nation's small four-year
residential liberal arts colleges.
</P>
<P>
   But others warn that the shift to a heavily pre-professional
curriculum will blur the distinction between the liberal arts
colleges and their less expensive competitors _ publicly supported
colleges and universities _ and thus weaken the private colleges by
drawing students away.
</P>
<P>
   At least two-thirds of the 550 colleges are almost unknown
outside their local communities, while a few _ like Williams,
Swarthmore, Haverford, Kenyon, Amherst and Wellesley _ are among
the best-known names in American education.
</P>
<P>
   Their principal selling point in the educational marketplace is
that their diminutive size _ most have only 1,800 to 2,000 students
_ permits faculty members to devote themselves to being teachers
and mentors; research and publishing are preoccupations mainly at
the big universities.
</P>
<P>
   The claim is only partly valid, since small-college professors,
like those at universities, are well aware that throughout academe,
professional advancement is largely based on research and
publishing and therefore are ignored at one's peril.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, universities argue that good researchers are
usually good teachers, and that students are energized by
association with professors working at the cutting edge of their
disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, universities from Harvard on down assign
small-section discussion leadership to teaching assistants
(graduate students), a practice that the small colleges generally
avoid.
</P>
<P>
   But small classes and one-on-one instruction are expensive _
maybe too expensive. Writing in Daedalus, Michael S. McPherson, the
president of Macalester College in Minnesota, and Morton Owen
Schapiro, a professor of economics at the University of Southern
California, report that the almost explosive growth of public
colleges and universities in recent decades has led to a steady
shrinking of the small private college customer base that is
``willing and able to cover the costs of the enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely, the Williams trustee who contributed to Daedalus, blames
``vocationalism, credentialism or even dollarizing'' on the part of
students for the financial stress.
</P>
<P>
   The small colleges most vulnerable to failure, he writes, are
the handful in the lowest economic tier that ``have not had the
resources to develop an additional, career-oriented curriculum''
that many students and their parents are now demanding.
</P>
<P>
   But paradoxically, Neely writes, most of the several hundred
small mid-level liberal arts colleges that have been able to
provide specialized, career-oriented training have done so at the
expense of low tuition, small classes, close faculty-to-student
relationships, competitive faculty salaries and painstaking campus
maintenance _ characteristics that have traditionally distinguished
these colleges from public ones.
</P>
<P>
   Even the small private colleges with national prominence are in
jeopardy, Neely warns, unless they can present themselves as
alternatives to a culture that chooses ``trends over permanence,
image over substance, money over values, and the market over
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   In agreement with Neely, Richard H. Hersh, president of Hobart
and William Smith Colleges in Geneva, N.Y., warns against
``McUniversities _ learning malls catering to the whims of their
customers,'' and urges his liberal arts colleagues to provide
students with ``a coherent body of knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the dangers faced by the small private liberal arts
colleges, most educators who have studied them conclude that their
special contribution to higher education is inextricably related to
their size.
</P>
<P>
   In a personal essay in Daedalus, Geoffrey Canada, president and
chief executive of the Rheedlen Center for Children and Families,
told how he as an African-American student was transformed in the
1970s by four years at the almost all-white Bowdoin College in
Brunswick, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something about the smallness of Bowdoin that brought
about an intimacy that I will never forget,'' Canada wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``People cared about one another. Students would go out of their
way to help you if you needed it. A student who left school because
of poor academic performance, although a rare occurrence, was felt
to be a real loss,'' he continued. ``The faculty seemed to feel the
same way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
