   DOLE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Profile: Elizabeth Hanford Dole
appears ready to become the country's first serious female
presidential candidate and a serious contender, period. As a
two-time Cabinet secretary, former head of the American Red Cross
and immensely popular campaigner for her husband, she has stirred
enormous interest among Republicans. By Melinda Henneberger. 1,860
words.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-2000 (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Elizabeth Dole announces the
formation of an exploratory committee for a run at the Republican
presidential nomination. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   VA-NY-TRANSIT (Sussex, Va.) _ In this quiet corner of southern
Virginia, the humans are few, the wildlife plentiful. But if the
county is rich in beauty, it has also been poor in resources. For
years, residents dumped their trash into the nearest hole in the
ground. No new schools had been built in 30 years. That was before
Sussex County discovered garbage. Five years ago, it embarked on a
controversial path that many people believed would improve their
struggling economy while jeopardizing their beloved environs:
accepting a private, state-of-the-art landfill that would import
thousands of tons of garbage a day, much of it from New York City.
1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANK-TORRE (Fort Myers, Fla.) _ Developing story on the
announcement that Yankees Manager Joe Torre has prostate cancer. By
Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   FALLINGWATER (Bear Run, Pa.) _ Fallingwater, Frank Lloyd
Wright's 1936 masterpiece, acknowledged by architects to be the
most significant American building, appears to be falling down.
When this weekend house slung over a waterfall opened last week for
its annual season of public tours, visitors were treated to the
sight of a bathtub-sized hole in the middle of the living room
floor. The house, a series of intersecting concrete trays, has, in
fact, been sagging; one corner, hanging over the falls, is more
than seven inches lower than it should be. The problem, which
threatened to bring Fallingwater crashing into the rocks below, has
led to a top-to-bottom analysis of the building's structure. By
Fred Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ By making possible engineering
feats that would have been impracticable in the past, computers are
ratcheting up the wow factor in architecture, that feeling of utter
astonishment in those who behold buildings whose forms defy
orthogonal convention and _ it sometimes seems _ even gravity
itself. By David W. Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
