<SLUG> BC-NY-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK DEMOCRATIC CHAIR HINTS AT DOUBTS ABOUT GORE CANDIDACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY _ The chairwoman of the New York Democratic Committee
suggested Wednesday that Vice President Al Gore may not be the
party's best choice for a presidential candidate next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I have high regard for Vice President Gore, I think we
do need to be mindful that in the past (vice presidents who run for
president) have not produced victories for the Democratic Party,''
Judith Hope said in a public radio interview. ``We simply need to
examine all the talent we've got and make certain we are going with
our very best talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Hiltzik, spokesman for the Democratic Committee, said
the party leadership believes Gore would ``make a fine president.''
He said Hope is, however, uncommitted to Gore or anyone else at
this early date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make certain we are going to go with our very best
talent,'' Hiltzik said. ``It is quite likely that Al Gore will be
the choice of Democrats in New York ... Al Gore has been a great
friend of New Yorkers. We trust our primary voters will make the
right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope was interviewed on the WAMC-FM program ``Capitol
Connection,'' a weekly political program.
</P>
<P>
   In recent times, running the vice president has proven
unsuccessful for Democrats: both Hubert Humphrey, who was Lyndon
Johnson's vice president, and Walter Mondale, who served under
President Jimmy Carter, suffered crushing defeats in their bids for
the presidency. Johnson was the last Democratic vice president to
ascend to the presidency when he succeeded President John F.
Kennedy in 1963. A year later, Johnson was elected over Barry
Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1960, three Republicans who had served as vice president
became president _ although only one of them was elected to the
higher office while serving as vice president: George Bush. Richard
Nixon had served as President Dwight D. Eisenhower's vice
president, but lost the 1960 election to Kennedy. Ford inherited
the presidency when Nixon resigned, but was then defeated by
Carter. Bush went from the vice presidency under Ronald Reagan to
the presidency, only to lose a re-election bid to Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on the program about Gore's Boy Scout image, Hope
responded: ``I do think that American voters like to vote for a
human being that they can identify with on some level. But they
also want someone whose lives are not greatly divergent from the
kind of lives that most others lead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
