<SLUG> BC-TV-DAILY-SHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDY CENTRAL'S `THE DAILY SHOW': MORE ADULT (AS IN ADULTERATED)
NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Program airs Thursday night at 11 p.m. ET on comedy central) 
(bl) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Monica Lewinsky jokes worked. Last week, after Ms.
Lewinsky's astronomically high-rated ABC interview with Barbara
Walters, Jon Stewart reported on ``The Daily Show'': ``Lewinsky
said her liaison with Clinton was `the most amazing experience of
my life,' a description she had only previously given to reading
`Flowers in the Attic,' seeing `Phantom' on stage in Baltimore and
helping special-ed kids pull taffy at high school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Daily Show,'' Comedy Central's three-year-old half-hour
parody of a news broadcast, has always straddled the fence between
adolescent humor and grown-up wit. When Craig Kilborn was host, the
adolescence fit. Now that Jon Stewart has taken over (and
negotiated his name into the show's title), it doesn't. But Stewart
is so personable and so genuinely funny that he gets away with it.
And after two months on the job, he seems to be adjusting to the
mismatch. He's one of the writers now, and maybe the others are
finally getting the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 36, is never better than in self-deprecation mode. This
week, in defense of New Jersey, after a report that the state's
residents name sex only as their 10th-favorite activity, Stewart
said: ``Folks in New Jersey have plenty of sex. I didn't, but I
only lived there until I was 24.'' Beat. ``OK, 30.'' Beat. ``I
still live there.''
</P>
<P>
   And at times his Kilborn-like smirk is convincing. It worked
during a report on the complete cluelessness of IRS employees and
one on health maintenance organizations, which, having never heard
of psoriasis, are recommending only one treatment: shunning. But
then everybody hates the IRS and HMOs. The same is not true of,
say, archaeologists. Stewart recently referred to one who had
appeared on an opening-the-tombs special as ``trusted enough to be
allowed inside the pyramids but discredited enough to be working
for Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart often wears a sheepish look on camera, as if he were
being forced to make fun of people just to fit in with the other
guys at school, but he never seems embarrassed during the show's
four-minute celebrity interview.
</P>
<P>
   He's best when he has another person to play off and even does
well with guests who have little to say, like Ryan Phillippe,
plugging the film ``Cruel Intentions,'' and Jeri Ryan, who plays
Seven of Nine (a character name, not a fax-page notation) on ``Star
Trek: Voyager.'' He and Billy Crystal had such a good time that
Comedy Central turned the interview into a half-hour special
(Thursday night at 10:30). And when Stewart has a distinguished
guest, he gets humor just out of showing the proper respect. When
Ian McKellen appeared, Stewart suggested that if he won the
best-actor Oscar for ``Gods and Monsters'' and felt like saying in
his acceptance speech, ``I want to thank my wife, Jon Stewart,''
that would be just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Even the guests, however, aren't sure this is the right forum
for Stewart. Earlier this week, Jon Voight turned to the host and
said, with clear irony, ``This is such a high-level show.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the humor really is idiotic. For an item about Barbara
Walters, Ms. Walters' photograph is shown with a mustache and horns
drawn in. The writers can turn almost anything, even an item about
cosmetic surgery, into a masturbation joke. In a book title, the
writers change the word ``public'' to ``pubic.'' When that gets a
big laugh, Stewart ad-libs, with appropriate dismay, ``I found the
level of the room.'' That may be a problem; sometimes his opinion
of the material seems at odds with his audience's. But at least he
does great asides.
</P>
<P>
   It's still not clear whether Stewart and ``The Daily Show'' will
turn out to be a beautiful marriage, but he's far from the show's
only asset. Its absolute fearlessness is what comedy is all about.
The writers are not afraid to joke about the most recent of deaths.
Thus, on Monday night Joe DiMaggio was called ``the man NBC tried
to kill two months ago'' (a reference to an unfortunate premature
death announcement), and it was announced that in the case of
Stanley Kubrick's death, HAL the computer was being questioned as a
suspect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
