<SLUG> BC-MONICA-FASHION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANNA LOOK LIKE MONICA?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Monica at the Oscars, Monica authoring books,
Monica back in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And what about that fab lipstick and those great brows Monica
Lewinsky sported on her TV interview with Barbara Walters?
</P>
<P>
   All over town, women have been buzzing about the former White
House intern's new look. Especially the lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, all of her makeup (including foundation) was from Club
Monaco, the trendy Canadian chain of boutiques. According to Club
Monaco's national spokesman Gerald Levac, Lewinsky was wearing
Bronze and Topaz eye shadows priced at $11 each; brow powder and
pencil at $10 each; a sheer, berry-hued lipstick called Glaze at
$13; and Bare lip liner, $10.
</P>
<P>
   That glossy smile created by makeup artist Denise Markey of the
Cloutier styling agency in Los Angeles got so much attention that
Club Monaco salesman Brian Choi, lamented, ``We're having a million
calls about that lipstick. Women, middle-age to teens, want it, but
we're already sold out.'' But he says the Beverly Hills location
should have more in stock by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's hairstyle was created by Richard Keogh, also of
Cloutier, and while it did force us to focus on her face, it got
mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   According to Keogh, Lewinsky wanted something sleek that would
be low-maintenance and nondistracting, so he trimmed her thick,
naturally wavy hair, then straightened it with an iron and sprayed
gel on it to keep it in place.
</P>
<P>
   But he and the other artists weren't happy about those unplanned
shots from the back, or the fact that they weren't allowed to do
any touching up during the all-day filming. ``They never shot over
Walter's shoulder,'' he commented, adding that he'd like to give
Walters a new 'do as well.
</P>
<P>
   For the 70 million or so viewers who were fascinated with the
spiffed-up Lewinsky, that understated suit she was wearing was by
Tahari.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we didn't send it to her. She purchased the suit herself
at Bloomingdale's in Century City and paid $496 for it,'' said
Tahari spokeswoman Christina Juarez. In case you couldn't see the
entire suit, Juarez describes it as a classic indigo blue
reefer-style (long and lean) jacket over a slim pant, with a
lavender knit shell.
</P>
<P>
   So, come Oscar time, Lewinsky could wear another Tahari number.
Or maybe a Ralph Lauren gown, since the designer bought the Club
Monaco retail chain earlier this month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1907EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0331 </DOCNO>
