<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS FOR VANITY AND OBSESSION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Publishers are not yet madly bidding against each
other for the rights to books about making movies, but quite
suddenly, it seems, these and other movie-related books are popping
up in numbers that no longer can be ignored. It's a genre about
vanity and obsession: the conceit of the moviemakers and the
infatuation of those who, to a great degree, get their culture in
the flickering darkness of the picture show.
</P>
<P>
   Movie scripts and the novelization of them have been a minor
publishing accessory for a long time, although they are getting
even more popular, particularly during the Oscar hype. What's new
in the genre's growth are what publishers call ``the making of'' or
the ``companion to'' books about the production of particular
movies.
</P>
<P>
   The two classics of the movie-set genus in controlling and
paranoid Hollywood were separated by 39 years. They are ``Picture''
(Rinehart, 1952) by Lillian Ross, about the making of ``The Red
Badge of Courage,'' and ``The Devil's Candy: `The Bonfire of the
Vanities' Goes to Hollywood'' (Houghton Mifflin, 1991) by Julie
Salamon. In each the writer had unlimited access to the production
and the reporting was rigorous and incisive, ultimately at times to
the dismay of the moviemaker who had been bold enough to open his
set.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been nothing in between or since that could be
called journalism in its most muscular form. Although the ``making
of'' books do provide interesting information for the movie fan or
the techie, they are mostly driven by the moviemaker's ego _
there's no critical analysis _ and are generally puffery, with
little tough reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for instance, in ``Titanic and the Making of James
Cameron'' (Newmarket Press) by Paula Parisi, a reporter and editor
of The Hollywood Reporter, a trade paper, the director is depicted
as a ``tempestuous auteur,'' a sort of combination Napoleon and
Humphrey Bogart. He is regularly described as a hero who does his
job amid confusion ``with the quiet intensity of a tightrope
walker.''
</P>
<P>
   Many times these books are subsidized, one way or another, by
studios. Esther Margolis, the president and publisher of Newmarket
Press, which almost specializes in movie-related books, said that
about half the titles she publishes have a guarantee by the studio
to buy so many copies. These are used for the studio's marketing,
as a way to showcase their movies for overseas distributors and for
home-video producers months before the movie is available. They
have to be approved by the moviemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Yet sometimes these books are best sellers. In the great popular
sweep of the movie ``Titanic,'' the debris in its wake included
``James Cameron's Titanic'' (Harper Entertainment), which sold more
than a million copies. It was a species of the ``making of'' genre,
which is the increasingly popular glossy movie coffee table book
with beautiful photographs from the movie set and some text that
gently discusses, for instance, the research that went into making
the movie authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the first best seller in the genre was Ballantine Books'
1993 paperback ``The Making of Jurassic Park'' by Don Shay and Jody
Duncan. While the printings of most of these books stay within
about 10,000 copies, the genre has produced some big successes.
About 25,000 copies of ``The Men in Black'' (Newmarket Press) were
sold. In the book, the actor Tommy Lee Jones was said to have
``sought and found a deeper side to his character in the
screenplay,'' befitting a talented actor and a Harvard graduate,
and the director, Barry Sonnenfeld, wrote a foreword titled ``The
Aliens Are Us.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 50,000 copies of ``Saving Private Ryan: The Men. The
Mission. The Movie.'' (Newmarket Press) were sold, with about 5,000
bought by the movie studio for marketing. ``What makes them work is
the additional material we get from the scriptwriters and the
directors,'' Ms. Margolis said. Such cooperation is seldom
withheld, since the moviemaker has the final say on the book's
contents. A book, no matter how slight, is one of the great
validators: for a director or screenwriter to be interviewed as
Norman Mailer would be for a book is apparently a heady high.
</P>
<P>
   These books are not simply a matter of regurgitating the movie.
John Silbersack, the publisher of Harper Entertainment, said that
these ``making of'' books ``give a reader an appreciation that film
and television are genuine art forms,'' with their chatter about
production and screenwriting and special effects and with
interviews with directors and actors. Harper Entertainment does
book tie-ins with any studio, but mostly with its sister company,
Fox, a partner in the production of ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   The giant of this relatively small but growing part of book
publishing is Hyperion Books, a division of Disney, which publishes
not only books from Disney movies but also from movies of the
Disney-owned Miramax and Touchstone.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. Miller, the Hyperion publisher, takes the high ground
on what can almost be called vanity press publishing. ``Miramax is
the only movie studio that has a brand name, in a sense, for
intelligent high-quality movies for adults,'' he said. One of the
Hyperion/Miramax Books spun off ``Shakespeare in Love,'' a Miramax
movie, is a small book of Shakespeare love poems, from the plays
and sonnets, with 57,000 copies in print. There are nearly 35,000
copies of the Tom Stoppard and Marc Norman screenplay in print.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperion also benefits _ through Disney _ from the increasing
number of people who are becoming serious fans of animation
artwork. Thus its ``Art of the Lion King'' sold nearly 60,000
copies at $50 a pop, and 20,000 copies of ``Mulan'' at $60 each.
</P>
<P>
   But all of this is but a lead-in to the tidal wave that will hit
book publishing in May when the first of the three Star Wars
prequels, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' will be in
the theaters, and Ballantine Books will have all its literary
satellites: the screenplay, the making of, the novelizations
(Ballantine has sold more that 13 million copies of the first Star
Wars novelizations), the picture books, the guide books, the
children's books. The entire galaxy, with 9-year-old Luke Skywalker
as King Arthur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 1910EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALI-DEMOCRACY-ART-NY     03-10 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALI-DEMOCRACY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY FINDS A WELCOME HOME ON BALI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANUR, Indonesia _ From the taut streets of Jakarta to the tense
villages of East Timor, democracy is making unsteady progress in
this far-flung Asian country. But here on the tropical island of
Bali, democratic-style politics is bursting out with a joyful
clamor.
</P>
<P>
   As Indonesia prepares for elections in June, its first
multiparty vote in four decades, Bali has become a swirl of waving
flags and banners. They hang from houses and shops and billow
behind trucks and motorcycles. On street corners, young people
noisily hawk T-shirts, caps and bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other parts of Indonesia, where excitement about the
election is tinged with fear that it could unleash violent social
unrest, Bali has no reservations. Having escaped the riots that
convulsed Java and other islands, people here are exercising their
new political freedom with cheerful abandon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun,'' Ketut, a 34-year-old auto mechanic in this
small coastal town, said as he manned a roadside stand festooned
with banners for a popular presidential candidate, Megawati
Sukarnoputri. ``We could never do this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Ketut, who like many Indonesians has only one name, is an ardent
supporter of Ms. Megawati. Throughout Bali the vast majority of
campaign paraphernalia champions the soft-spoken opposition leader,
who is the daughter of Indonesia's founding president, Sukarno.
</P>
<P>
   Bali is Megawati country. Her famous father was half Balinese,
and though Ms. Megawati lives in Jakarta, people here regard her as
a native daughter. Political analysts say her party, the Indonesian
Democratic Party, could carry 85 percent of the vote in Bali, which
has three million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Megawati has a simple way, and people will follow her,'' said
Ketut Puja, a wood carver. Outside his shop he has hung a giant
party flag, with its distinctive glowering bull's head on a
blood-red background.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Balinese, Puja still bridles at the mention of
Suharto, the longtime leader of Indonesia, who was forced out last
May in a spasm of riots and economic despair. Puja said the coming
election was a chance to sweep out once and for all the remnants of
the Suharto government.
</P>
<P>
   President B.J. Habibie, the aeronautical engineer who replaced
Suharto, is fighting to keep his job. But while he has tried to
distance himself from his predecessor and close friend _
overturning old policies and approving an investigation of
Suharto's huge wealth _ he has not been able to dispel the
impression that he is a crony of the disgraced former leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody believes Habibie is a legitimate leader,'' Puja said
with a wave of his hand. ``He should go back to flying his
helicopters.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the yearning for change, people here recognize that Ms.
Megawati and other challengers face an arduous struggle. Last week
the government licensed 48 parties to field candidates in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Megawati is one of three candidates with mass political
support. The others are Abdurrahman Wahid, the leader of
Indonesia's largest Muslim organization, and Amien Rais, a Muslim
intellectual who gained prominence by opposing Suharto and recently
formed his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say that despite Habibie's tarnished image,
it would be a mistake to write him off. He can still pull powerful
levers in the electoral process through the governing party,
Golkar. And he has won praise from people here and abroad for his
energetic handling of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is overconfidence among the Megawati supporters,'' said
Umar Juoro, an economic adviser to Habibie. ``The competition will
be very high among the political parties, and the president could
do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's president is chosen by the People's Consultative
Assembly, which has 700 elected and appointed members. For three
decades the assembly was a largely ceremonial body dominated by
Suharto. But now, some analysts predict that none of the
candidates' parties will be able to win a clear majority, which
suggests that Indonesia may be entering an era of coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Megawati's supporters predict that her party will win a
majority because she is a nonsectarian candidate at a time when
many people fear that tensions between religious groups pose a dire
threat to Indonesia's stability.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, fierce clashes between Muslims and Christians
have torn apart the Indonesian island of Ambon, about 1,000 miles
northeast of Bali. As the violence has worsened in recent days,
crowds of Islamic activists have marched in Jakarta, demanding that
the Indonesian Army protect the Muslims in Ambon. Some even called
for a jihad, or holy war, against the Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Megawati is the leader of the only party that represents
pluralism,'' said Laksamana Sukardi, one of her chief advisers.
``It is not a party based on race or religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a distinction matters in Bali, a predominantly Hindu island
in the middle of the world's most populous Muslim country. People
here believe that Bali has escaped social unrest because of its
religious homogeneity. But with the collapse of the national
economy, Muslims are migrating to Bali from nearby islands, and
that has prompted fears that the turmoil could flare up here.
</P>
<P>
   Sukardi said that when the Indonesian Democratic Party held its
convention here in October, attracting more than one million
people, provocateurs from outside Bali mingled in the crowd, trying
to stir trouble. He said the government had planted the
troublemakers to subvert the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the government did not want to see our congress go
smoothly,'' Sukardi said. ``They wanted to disgrace our image.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party has been subverted before. In 1996
pro-Suharto forces engineered the ouster of Ms. Megawati as party
leader, and the police sacked the party's Jakarta headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In Bali, at least, the campaign has been trouble-free so far.
But the Democratic Party is taking no chances. To bolster security
it has constructed roadside stands in almost every village here,
which are staffed by volunteers like Ketut, the mechanic. The
rough-hewn structures have become gathering places for young
people, who escape the tropical sun under the corrugated tin roofs.
</P>
<P>
   As they talk about the future, people agree that no matter who
wins the election, the new leader's top priority must be fixing
Indonesia's devastated economy. Although Bali's tourism industry
has sheltered the island from the full fury of the economic
typhoon, it has suffered as well. After plunging disastrously last
May, hotel occupancy rates here are still below pre-crisis levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem is the economy,'' said Puja, the wood carver,
as he chipped away meticulously on his next creation. ``The
government says things are changing, but the people are still
suffering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
