<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth venture aided by PageNet deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BellSouth reinforced its only national gambit Wednesday,
announcing a deal in which PageNet will market BellSouth's
interactive paging.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in May, Dallas-based PageNet will add BellSouth's pager
to its product list, using the names of both companies to sell the
service. BellSouth will also put some of its own sales staff in
PageNet stores and kiosks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is increasingly facing competition from companies that
are national and even global, and the company does have a strong
presence in Latin America. But BellSouth still reaps the lion's
share of its revenues from its local phone business in the nine
Southeastern states, where it has most of its wireless business as
well. That dependence looks _at least to some analysts _ like a
recipe for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   However, BellSouth's paging unit is based in New Jersey, and it
sells service throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive pager permits users to respond to e-mail and
other messages by typing on the device's keypad. The company's
major competitor in national interactive paging is Skytel.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
