<SLUG> BC-NOVA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nova stock drops after CFO sells all of his shares
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nova Corp.'s stock plunged as much as 21 percent Wednesday after
the company's chief financial officer, James M. Bahin, disclosed
that he sold 251,911 shares _ representing all of his direct
holdings in the credit-card processor _ for nearly $7.5 million
last month.
</P>
<P>
   The stock fell to a 52-week low of $17.87 1/2 before rebounding
to finish at $21.87 1/2, down 87 1/2 cents. Nearly 1.6 million
shares changed hands, or seven times average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   The stock traded as high as $37.87 1/2 last July 16.
</P>
<P>
   Bahin said the sale _ at prices ranging from $29.66 to $29.77 on
Feb. 12 and Feb. 16 _ wasn't related to the company's prospects,
but rather to a desire to diversify his portfolio and for
retirement planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have immediate plans to leave the company,'' said
Bahin, who joined Nova seven years ago from the old Fuqua
Industries. ``But I do have retirement plans that I hope to make
happen in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahin, who turns 55 on Sept. 11, said Nova began a search for
his successor several weeks ago. He said he will remain a director
of the Atlanta-based company, which processes credit-card
transactions for 480,000 merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Bahin said Nova's prospects remain bright.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on target in our operating plan,'' he said. ``Earnings
are on track.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by Edward Grzedzinski, chairman and
chief executive, in a statement late Wednesday, confirming Bahin's
plans to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's fundamental business indicators remain strong,
with an expected 20 percent or better internal growth in the first
quarter,'' Grzedzinski said.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Nova posted fourth-quarter earnings that matched
Wall Street's expectations. Analysts generally expect the company
to earn $1.14 a share this year and $1.73 a share next year,
according to IBES International.
</P>
<P>
   Bahin said that, with the help of financial advisers, he began
diversifying his portfolio three years ago to include other assets,
such as real estate and fixed-income securities.
</P>
<P>
   According to CDA Investnet, Bahin sold a total 627,400 shares
over the past three years for $15,711,560, including the latest
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, generally, it's very important not to be too heavily
weighted in one investment,'' said Bahin, adding that about half of
his net worth still is tied to the company. He is vested in options
entitling him to acquire 380,000 shares, many at $1.18 each. He
also has options to acquire an additional 185,000 shares. But those
options aren't vested yet, Bahin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable where I am right now,'' he said of his
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Bahin, who has homes in Dunwoody and on Lake Hartwell in South
Carolina, said he plans to spend his retirement to ``fish and golf
and spend time with my three grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
