<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUCOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern sees natural gas as an 'advantageous addition'
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern Co. would like to add natural gas to its electricity
holdings, but ``it's not an imperative'' for achieving the
company's financial goals, said A.W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg, chairman,
president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg said natural gas pipelines and storage would be an
``advantageous addition'' as the $300 billion-a-year utility
industry moves toward electricity and natural gas combinations.
But, he added, ``we would not add something at any cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern, the largest U.S. electricity generator, gets a vast
majority of its profits from five regulated utilities in the
Southeast, including Georgia Power Co.
</P>
<P>
   Adding natural gas assets would back up its growing U.S.
wholesale energy marketing arm as Southern expands into unregulated
utility businesses around the country and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg, in an interview, declined to comment on reports that
Southern held talks earlier this year with El Paso Energy Corp.
about acquiring the Houston-based natural gas company valued at
more than $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A swirl of rumors last month about a possible combination of the
companies sent El Paso stock soaring and contributed to Southern's
recent downward trend. Southern's stock, which is down 15 percent
since the first of the year, hit a 52-week low Wednesday before
closing at $24.12 1/2, down 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the two companies reportedly ended without a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg would not discuss ``market rumors'' about El Paso but
said he has met with the company's chairman, William Wise, just
like he has with chief executives of a long list of utility firms.
Other companies include Virginia-based Columbia Energy,
Birmingham-based Sonat, Consolidated Natural Gas of Pittsburgh,
Texas-based Houston Industries, PG&AMP;E of California and Williams
Cos. of Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to everybody,'' he said. ``It's not necessarily about
acquiring their business or acquiring a pipeline, but about trends
in the industry.'' He also said he's talked with companies about
possible ``synergies.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dahlberg downplayed the significance of a natural gas
acqusition, a leading utility industry financial analyst said
acquiring such an operation would be ``very important'' for
Southern if it is to maintain or enhance its standing as a top
wholesale energy marketer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be competitive with Duke Energy and Houston
Industries, (which) have electricity and gas, you've got to have
gas,'' said Barry M. Abramson of PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Southern's access to the commodity through its joint marketing
venture with Vastar Resources, a Houston-based natural gas company,
is not adequate, Abramson said. ``You need to acquire a natural gas
pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Energy, Coastal Corp. of Houston and Sonat have figured
in recent speculation as potential takeover targets in the natural
gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   Abramson said he's maintaining a ``neutral'' rating on Southern
stock because of uncertainty over a potential natural gas deal.
``We want to see what the next move is,'' he said. ``We assume a
major acquisition over the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dahlberg, who briefed Wall Street analysts last week and
heads to London and Scotland for meetings with investors later this
week, said Southern already has plenty on its plate for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to consummate $1.2 billion worth of
announced acquisitions of electric power plants in California and
New York, and is scheduled to start up a $1.4 billion plant in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg also said:
</P>
<P>
   Southern is sticking to wholesale and large industrial customers
and steering clear of mass marketing in its energy marketing
business. An energy management business, which included Federated
Department Stores as a client, ``probably didn't work as well as
many anticipated,'' he said. The company is letting contracts to
manage energy purchases expire and not signing up customers.
</P>
<P>
   He does not anticipate a write-down against earnings for
Southern's holdings in Asia like the company's $200 million
write-down last year to reflect decling value of South American
investments. ``We don't have any underperforming assets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He sees no major push for electric utility deregulation in
Southern's Southeastern service territory because of relatively low
electricity rates. Recent problems with Georgia's natural gas
deregulation may ``give people pause,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
