<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTAM-CLINTON-1stLD-     03-10 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTAM-CLINTON-1stLD-03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PROPOSES EQUAL TREATMENT FOR ALL CENTRAL AMERICAN
IMMIGRANTS
 &HT;    EDS: Corrects quotes in 15th graf and deletes next graf (both
before the optional add)
 &HT;    With optional add begins at 650 words.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY, Guatemala _ President Clinton, addressing
lawmakers assembled in El Salvador from across Central America,
said Wednesday he would seek to make it easier for refugees who
fled political oppression in the region -- regardless of the type
government -- to obtain permanent residency status in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived here later from El Salvador, however, and tried to
heal old wounds by acknowledging the U.S. role in supporting
repressive military regimes in Guatemala during the 1980s and the
first half of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Support for military forces or intelligence units which
engaged in violent or widespread repression was wrong, and the
United States must not repeat that mistake,'' Clinton said at a
roundtable of Guatemalan civic leaders to discuss the nation's
recent peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   The president further urged that the United States be viewed
``in a new way, as a partner, a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statement came two weeks after a Guatemalan truth
commission released a report detailing that U.S. policy was pivotal
to state-sponsored genocide against Mayan peasants during the war,
in which an estimated 200,000 died. A 36-year civil war between the
army and leftist rebels, which ripped Guatemala apart, ended as
recently as 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a reminder of the past U.S. involvement, about a hundred
demonstrators protested Clinton's arrival here from El Salvador.
They carried signs decrying genocide, murder, oil companies and
poor wages.
</P>
<P>
   The president will complete his four-day goodwill mission to
Central America Thursday with a summit of regional presidents here
in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, in an address to the Legislative Assembly of
El Salvador, Clinton said he would support equal treatment for
refugees from the entire region.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has been reviewing the 1997 immigration law
which granted amnesty to some 40,000 Nicaraguan refugees who
arrived prior to 1996 to determine whether it can also apply to
refugees from El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   The law was aimed at refugees from Nicaragua and Cuba who fled
communist regimes. It made it easier for refugees who fled
right-wing dictatorships in El Salvador and Guatemala before
October 1991 to apply for permanent status, but was not as generous
as to those who fled communist regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of those countries have been urging a change in U.S.
policy to allow the refugees to remain. They argue that the money
sent back to the region from those refugees is an important source
of revenue for Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, in response to Hurricane Mitch, Clinton gave
refugees from Nicaragua and Honduras an 18-month amnesty from
deportation to relieve those countries from absorbing the returning
citizens at a time of economic difficulty. He also granted a 60-day
amnesty to Guatemala and Salvadoran refugees. That period ended
Monday, but none are scheduled to be deported this week.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's expiration of a temporary amnesty program, nearly
3,000 illegal immigrants from El Salvador and Guatemala face
deportation. They are seeking parity with Nicaragua and Honduras,
covered by more liberal rules.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the Salvadoran assembly, Clinton pledged to
urge Congress to support equal treatment for all Central American
refugees, as well as through administrative changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do everything I possibly can to overcome that different
treatment, `` Clinton said. ``Our treatment of people from Central
America should reflect what they suffered rather than who caused
the suffering. This is wrong and we should change it''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged Central American leaders to give every child a
chance to go to school; adopt environmental practices to avert the
deforestation which may have caused the mudslides that killed 2,000
people in Nicaragua; and crack down on the transportation of
illegal drugs through the region.
</P>
<P>
   For education, Clinton announced an $8 million grant to enable
countries in Central America to enroll more children in schools and
keep them there.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the region's civil wars have been replaced by
democratically elected governments throughout Central America,
Clinton said ``we have a solemn obligation to deliver democracy''
for today's children.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-03-10-99 1832E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
