</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEA-BOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEA CANCELS FUNDING FOR CHILDREN'S BOOK WRITTEN BY ZAPATISTA
LEADER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ It is a whimsical tale of how the macaw got
its colors, a Mexican story told by a character named Old Antonio
deep in the jungle of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   So engaging are the mythical text and vibrant illustrations of
``The Story of Colors'' that a small El Paso, Texas, publishing
house won a highly competitive grant from the National Endowment
for the Arts to print 15,000 bilingual copies.
</P>
<P>
   But with the books hot off the press, the chairman of the NEA on
Tuesday received some troubling news. The author is Subcomandante
Marcos, the quixotic, witty, literary leader of the Zapatista
guerrilla movement in southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Marcos was hiding behind a pen name. His name appears
on the book's cover, and its jacket features a photograph of Marcos
in his signature black ski mask, with bullets slung around his
chest in the best tradition of Mexico's revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
   Told of this by The New York Times, NEA Chairman William Ivey
promptly canceled the $7,500 grant, leaving El Paso's Cinco Puntos
Press with no money to pay its printer. Wary of Republican attacks
that in past years almost led to the death of the government's arts
funding source, Ivey worried that some taxpayer money might get
back to the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was clearly an inappropriate use of government dollars,''
Ivey said Wednesday from NEA headquarters in Washington, D.C. ``I
was concerned about the final destination of the money.''
</P>
<P>
   How could this have happened after the NEA's yearlong screening
process, ``one of the most rigorous in the arts world,'' according
to spokeswoman Cherie Simon? ``This is unique, one in a million,''
Simon said. ``Nobody can remember anything analogous to this, and
we wouldn't expect it to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which is little comfort to Bobby Byrd, co-publisher at
Cinco Puntos, who accused Ivey of caving in when he received a
phone call from a Times reporter questioning the book.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said that at every step of the lengthy grant application
process he told NEA officials that Marcos had authored the
children's book. He said money from the project was never intended
for the Zapatistas. Marcos meant the tale for the public domain,
Byrd said, including it in a 1994 communique from Mexico's Lacandon
jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ivey made a spineless decision without accumulating all the
facts,'' said Byrd. ``He completely disregarded the panel's work.
The NEA is making decisions based on its fears and not standing up
for the literature that it is supposed to be nurturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though NEA spokeswoman Simon said the content of ``The Story of
Colors'' had nothing to do with the decision not to fund it, the
book is a bit of a departure from mainstream children's literature
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with Marcos lighting his pipe and Old Antonio rolling
a cigarette. Antonio sets out to tell the story of a world of only
black and white, where the ``men and women were sleeping or they
were making love, which is a nice way to become tired and then go
to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the book's somewhat sensuous themes, Mexican
Indian artist Domitila Dominguez includes a picture of a naked
woman in what seems to be a sexual embrace with a male god.
</P>
<P>
   In the story, which is based on a Mayan creation myth, the macaw
at first is almost colorless. Then the gods begin to fight because,
with only black and white, the world is a boring canvass to paint.
</P>
<P>
   So, the story goes, the gods create red, green, brown, blue and
yellow. Then, goes the text, they ``drank some corn liquor and went
to sleep,'' leaving the colors in a box underneath a ceiba tree.
</P>
<P>
   But since the box is not closed tightly, the colors escape and
``start to play happily and make love to each other,'' creating new
hues. Finally the gods take all the colors and, fearing they might
forget the vast array of hues, pour them on the feathers of the
macaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was how the macaw took hold of the colors,'' the book
reads, ``and so it goes strutting about just in case men and women
forget how many colors there are and how many ways of thinking, and
that the world will be happy if all the colors and ways of thinking
have their place.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a jacket note by Amy Ray of the Indigo Girls, a
socially conscious pop duo, the text does not address the
Zapatistas. In her note, Ray calls the ``The Story of Colors'' a
reminder that ``the Zapatista movement is one of dignity that
emanates from the grass roots of the indigenous people of Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 the Zapatistas waged an armed uprising against Mexico
but have since favored less violent tactics in their quest for
social justice. Ironically, Marcos, whose real name is Rafael
Sebastian Guillen Vicente, is the only non-Indian among Zapatista
leaders. He is a former university professor.
</P>
<P>
   Marcos' tale, known as ``La Historia de los Colores,'' in
Spanish, was published in 1997 by a group known as Colectivo
Callejero. Byrd happened upon the story at a book fair in
Guadalajara, Mexico, and last March proposed that the NEA fund its
translation.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal included four other books, for which together with
``The Story of Colors'' he sought a $30,000 grant. When the NEA cut
that amount in half during the final stages of the grant
application process, Byrd scaled back his projects to just two
books, one of them the story by Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   With the grant approved last month, but the NEA money not yet in
hand, ``The Story of Colors'' went to press with an initial run of
5,000 copies. It appears with a seal that says it is funded in part
by the NEA.
</P>
<P>
   Though Byrd is out $7,500 for that book, the publisher and poet
is not altogether worried. He believes the publicity surrounding
the Marcos flap will help sell the controversial book, and is
already predicting that his independent publishing house will have
to print more copies of the 40-page book selling for $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   But for the record, Byrd is angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ivy says this is not a censorship issue,'' said Byrd,
referring to the NEA chairman. ``Well I say it certainly is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
