have satisfied a good many shareholders, who lobbied for that kind
of change for years. But there are signs that more fireworks may be
in store for the separate companies created by RJR's decision. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's other regular features:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Treasury securities fell in price under the
sheer weight of corporate and municipal supply Wednesday, as big
companies including Lucent Technologies and Freddie Mac sold debt
to the public sector. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   DOCKERS-AD-COLUMN _ In a khakis counterattack, Levi Strauss &AMP;
Co. is responding to inroads made by competitors by portraying its
Dockers line of casual pants for men in a far more sensual and
youthful manner. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   (The column is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
