<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE FORMS PRESIDENTIAL EXPLORATORY COMMITTEE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ With a description of what she would offer
the nation ``as a woman,'' Elizabeth Hanford Dole put her
Republican presidential campaign on the same official footing as
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, Bush's chief competition in the early running for the 2000
nomination, announced at a public rally that she is starting an
exploratory committee, which can raise and spend political money
without her declaring that she is definitely a candidate. Bush
launched his committee Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But like Bush, Dole left little doubt that she will run for the
White House, were she served as transportation secretary under
President Bush and as labor secretary under President Reagan.
Supporters at the rally were asked to fill out postcards, paid for
by the committee, that say, ``Yes, Elizabeth, I want to help you in
your run for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveys of Republican voters, 11 months before any primary votes
are cast, show Bush and Dole as the dominant candidates. That
status gives Dole the realistic chance of being the first woman
nominated for the presidency by a major political party.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would I, as a woman, offer our country? I'm not a
politician and frankly I think that's a plus today,'' she said,
triggering loud applause from an overflow crowd at a downtown
convention center. ``But I have spent a lifetime in public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have experience in government and, believe me,
I've had a lot of that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, 62, resigned as president of the American Red Cross in
January to germinate her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Her nonpolitician label aside, Dole mentioned that she has
visited all 99 counties of Iowa, the site of the pivotal
presidential caucuses early next year, on behalf of other
candidates. Her husband, former Sen. Bob Dole, lost the 1996
presidential election to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's campaigned out here at least since 1979,'' national GOP
official Steve Roberts of Des Moines told the crowd. ``We want her
to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of her speech to the 1996 Republican National
Convention on behalf of her husband, Dole roamed her own audience
Wednesday, speaking through a wireless microphone in the style of
TV talk-show hosts. On the stage behind her were photographs from
her career: Dole snow skiing, standing with Reagan, hugging
children, posing with military officers and riding a motorcycle
with comedian Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   ``I place public service over politics, consensus over
confrontation, and I think it's important that you know that,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing her work with the American Red Cross and the
federal government, taking credit for making airline travel and the
national blood supply safer, Dole offered the bare beginnings of
her campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   America needs tax relief, its military defense budget is too low
and a strategic missile defense system is needed to protect against
nuclear weapons from countries such as North Korea, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must return our public schools to greatness'' and renew the
government's campaign against illegal drug use by the young, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said she will supply details on these issues later,
``because we want to do it in a thoughtful way.''
</P>
<P>
   She said voters have become cynical about politics because it is
dominated by ``special interests,'' but was no more specific about
that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Introductory speakers cast Dole as a role model for the country.
Their statements dove-tailed with a videotaped Dole speech being
circulated in some early primary states. Alluding to President
Clinton's sex-and-lies scandal, Dole says in the speech: ``I
believe our people are looking for leaders who will call America to
her better nature. Yes, we've been let down, and by people we
should have been able to look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's campaign committee paid for the 14-minute videotape to
air on TV stations in Iowa and New Hampshire, host of a key primary
in February, starting Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Both states were the location for bitter political battles
between her husband and the Texas governor's father. Both ran for
the 1988 nomination, captured by then-Vice President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   This year's polls have shown Elizabeth Dole and George W. Bush
running virtually even among New Hampshire Republican voters. In
Iowa, a similar independent survey conducted March 4 showed Bush
ahead of Dole, 32.7 percent to 14.7 percent. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A national Gallup poll released Wednesday showed Dole with a
narrow lead, 50 percent to 45 percent, in a one-on-one match with
Democratic Vice President Al Gore. Bush had a 56 percent to 41
percent lead over Gore in a one-on-one race.
</P>
<P>
   The poll said four out of 10 Americans think a man would make a
better president, citing the tradition and their emotional makeup,
and three out of 10 said a woman would be better at the job, noting
their common sense, compassion and the need for a change.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's rally, Dole underscored her role as the lone
woman in the race by walking a few blocks to shake hands at a state
high basketball tournament for girls' teams.
</P>
<P>
   She was to make stops in Arizona and New Hampshire this week
before returning Saturday to her hometown, Salisbury, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
