<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-QUEBEC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEBEC ISSUE BRINGS CANADA BOYCOTT OF PARIS MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Staging a tantrum over what seemed diplomatic small
potatoes, Canada Wednesday boycotted an international meeting in
Paris to protest what it considered an untoward sign of diplomatic
respect given to Quebec separatists by the French government.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of bizarre news conferences, Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy implied that France had insulted Canada and had violated
diplomatic protocol by extending a ``government-to-government''
invitation to Quebec to a ministerial meeting on development and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think France would be happy if Canada organized a
meeting and invited Corsica,'' Axworthy told reporters, referring
to the French island in the Mediterranean where there is separatist
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   The squabble was the latest in a string that started in 1967,
when President Charles de Gaulle stood on the balcony of Montreal's
City Hall and exhorted, ``Vive le Quebec Libre!'' (Long Live Free
Quebec). The rallying cry warmed the hearts of Quebecers _ and put
a chill on France-Canada relations that lasted for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Canada was similarly unamused when France proposed issuing a
stamp honoring de Gaulle's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec is the only Canadian province dominated by
French-speakers, and the Parti Quebecois government of Premier
Lucien Bouchard makes no bones about its desire to cut political
ties with Ottawa and to form a sovereign republic.
</P>
<P>
   France hedges on how actively it supports the separatist
movement. But Paris has pledged to extend diplomatic recognition to
an independent Quebec, this to the huge irritation of Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Canada's show of petulance Wednesday was startling,
mainly because it was so public _ with angry utterances in
Parliament, faxes sent to foreign correspondents covering Canada,
supposedly impromptu news conferences by fuming politicians and a
formal protest to the French government from Canada's embassy in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada is an independent country, and there are international
rules to be followed, and France did not follow those rules,''
thundered Prime Minister Jean Chretien, a French Quebecer but also
an ardent federalist.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec separatist leaders, meanwhile, were laughing at Ottawa's
discomfiture. ``I'm surprised Canada would boycott an international
meeting just because Quebec is present.'' said Quebec's
International Affairs Minister Louise Beaudoin. ``It's very
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   According to diplomatic protocol, invitations to
nation-to-nation meetings should be extended only to national
governments, so France technically may have made a boo-boo. But the
session in Paris was hardly a major session, and bemused French
officials insisted no slight was intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're talking about some super meeting of
sovereign states,'' said Louis de Corail, spokesman for the French
Embassy in Ottawa. ``It was more of an informal get-together, with
artists and so on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
