<SLUG> BC-DELL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amazon.com, Dell link in Web venture
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Hoping to build on the Internet's promise of
shopping convenience and product customization, Dell Computer Corp.
and Amazon.com Inc. unveiled joint Web pages Wednesday to lure each
other's customers to each other's Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The links, located at the check-out pages at each company's Web
sites, go to co-branded pages that contain information about
products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Chief Executive Michael Dell said Wednesday both companies
want to exploit the Web to develop deep relationships with
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dell and Amazon.com will each offer our mutual customers
customized services, competitive price, and easy navigation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies operate two of the most active electronic commerce
sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, which had $728 million in sales last year, is the most
popular electronic commerce site with more than 9 million different
visitors a month, according to Media Metrix Inc., a research
company. Dell has more than $14 million a day in online sales,
which projects to about $5 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement, which Dell described as a ``statement
of direction'' rather than groundbreaking news, means each company
gains initially by exposure to each other's customers.
</P>
<P>
   After the exposure, tailored sales pitches based on customer
interests are likely to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be providing Dell customers with a very focused,
customized content experience,'' said Amazon.com Vice President Ram
Shriram.
</P>
<P>
   For Dell, linking with Seattle-based Amazon.com is part of
long-held strategy of developing the Internet as a sales tool,
while developing partnerships with existing businesses rather than
building one from scratch or buying one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had every opportunity to pursue that and chose not to,''
said Bob Langer, director of Dell.com.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com shares closed at $137.12 1/2, up $7.18 3/4 in Nasdaq
trading Wednesday. Dell's shares were off 75 cents to $43.31 1/4,
also in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   An example of how the companies may work together is that
customers who buy a notebook computer from Dell may receive e-mail
from Amazon.com containing titles of books about mobile computing,
said Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies in Campbell,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   While that doesn't break new ground, it opens the way for
sharing more information that would allow each company to
personalize sales information to each other's customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going into it as if they're in a trial marriage,''
Bajarin said. ``They're saying, 'I'll share a little bit of
information, you share a little bit. If it works out, we'll share a
lot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact him at jmahoney(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
