<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill would give businesses statewide a 5 percent credit on their
state franchise taxes
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Efforts to give Texas business interests a much
wanted tax break for spending on research and development took a
big step forward Wednesday thanks to a legislative proposal that
has the backing of an unusual alliance of border Democrats and
business-oriented Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposal, by Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, would give
businesses statewide a 5 percent credit on their state franchise
taxes to offset spending for research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Two other tax credits, designed to help create jobs and foster
investments in machinery and equipment, would apply in 92 of the
state's 254 counties with above-average unemployment and below
average personal income. Most of those counties are along the
Mexican and Louisiana borders, and none are in Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These incentives will help Texas compete nationally and even
internationally for jobs and investments,'' Sibley said at a press
conference. ``By directing development toward economically
distressed areas of the state, the state as a whole will become
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   If they become law, the tax credits would cost state government
about $100 million in the next two-year budget cycle and about $725
million in the 2006-2007 budget cycle. The credits would expire in
2007.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Smith, a spokesman for Motorola Semiconductor Product Sales
in Austin, said the company had not yet studied Sibley's proposal
in detail but that earlier estimates indicated the company would
save $1 million a year in Texas with the research and development
tax credit _ money, he said, that could be plowed back into more
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed tax credits come not a moment too soon, said Jerry
Marlar, president of Austin-based Sulzer Orthopedics Inc. Sulzer
Orthopedics and a sister company, Sulzer Carbomedics, are working
in a new field of biomedicine in which substances derived from cows
are used to stimulate human tissues, such as the gums or along the
spine, to regenerate.
</P>
<P>
   Sulzer now has researchers in Texas and Colorado but intends to
put them together in one place _ along with a new manufacturing
plant that within five years will employ up to 600 people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do have a lot of competition,'' Marlar told the Senate
Finance Committee during a hearing on Sibley's bill.
``Specifically, I am telling you Colorado is being very
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlar said Colorado officials, including the governor, offered
him a number of tax incentives to locate the new facility in that
state. Texas has done nothing, though local officials are working
with him, Marlar said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Marlar noted, Sibley's legislation would provide him
only a research and development tax break. The other tax breaks
would not apply because Travis County is not among the 92 counties
that would qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Given the insistence of many lawmakers that the state should do
more for its economically lagging areas, Sibley's proposed
legislation may be the biggest tax break business interests can
expect _ but he would appear to have a good chance of winning
passage.
</P>
<P>
   Joining him at the press conference to tout the bill were Sen.
Robert Duncan, R-Lubbock, and two Democratic senators representing
border areas, Eddie Lucio of Brownsville and Eliot Shapleigh of El
Paso. Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus Christi, is a co-sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Also in support is Rep. Rene Oliveira, D-Brownsville, chairman
of the powerful House Ways and Means Committee, who said he had
filed it in the House. Praising Sibley's leadership in drafting a
compromise, Oliveira said,
</P>
<P>
   ``It is nice to see it on a bi-partisan basis. And it's not a
border bill; it's a Texas bill.''
</P>
<P>
   If somebody got left out, it was lawmakers representing poor
areas of otherwise prosperous counties that would be excluded from
the investment and job creation tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, said that ``it won't be easy'' to
support the bill as proposed but that he expected to submit an
amendment that would extend the tax credits to low-income areas.
Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas, a member of the Finance Committee,
raised similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Lavine, an analyst with the Center for Public Policy
Priorities, said he could support the tax breaks as a package
because it would help create job in struggling areas. But he said
the center, which seeks to represent the interests of low-income
Texans, could not support such items as the research and
development tax credit alone.
</P>
<P>
   Hight writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Bruce Hight at bhight(at)statesman.com or
445-3977.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
