<SLUG> BC-TSHIRTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestlers pump up T-shirt printer's trade
 &HT;    By Jim Bohman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Superstar grappler Bill Goldberg and the galaxy
of World Championship Wrestling villains and heros were a bonanza
for Littlefield, Adams &AMP; Co. last year as sales and profits of the
Huber Heights T-shirt imprinter exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Littlefield, Adams watched as its revenues ballooned to $25.9
million in 1998, compared with $2.5 million the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Profits of the publicly traded company (OTC BB: FUNW) jumped to
$2.6 million, or 60 cents per share, versus a net loss of $1.9
million, or 70 cents a share, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Balber, president and chief executive, said the
turnaround dates to April 1998 when the company signed a licensing
agreement with World Championship Wrestling and New World Order,
another wrestling series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our success is due in great part to the popularity of
wrestling,'' said Balber, whose company employs 55 workers at a
T-shirt and garment imprinting plant at 6262 Executive Blvd. ``We
started shipping last May.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping retailers stocked with WCW T-shirts and related apparel
imprinted with photos of Goldberg, the Nitro Girls and the Four
Horsemen has kept Littlefield, Adams busy and prosperous, Balber
said. This year the company bolstered its portfolio by signing a
cross-licensing agreement with Warner Brothers to produce T-shirts
featuring WCW wrestlers with cartoon characters such as Bugs Bunny,
Yosemite Sam and ``Taz,'' the Tasmanian Devil.
</P>
<P>
   The company's WCW contract runs another 2 1/2 years, Balber
said, and he believes the licenses can be extended further.
</P>
<P>
   He said the WCW product wasn't available for licensing until
last year. ``When it came up we jumped all over it. We had to
outbid a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Littlefield Adams licenses include The Simpsons and King
of the Hill cartoon characters and Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   The company went into a tailspin two years ago when a lucrative
Harley-Davidson license expired and was not renewed. Harley decided
to withdraw its logo from mass marketers such as Wal-Mart and
Kmart, Balber explained.
</P>
<P>
   Littlefield, Adams shares were listed on the American Stock
Exchange until the Harley-Davidson license expired. ``We
voluntarily got delisted after we looked at our forecast and saw
that our prognosis was very bad,'' Balber said. ``Now we're trying
to get on the NASDAQ Small Cap list.''
</P>
<P>
   Littlefield, Adams shares closed Wednesday at 4, up 3/4. The 52
week trading range is just over 2 to 6 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Bohman writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
