<HEADER>
A5539 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDDA-GABLER-THEATER-     03-10 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDDA-GABLER-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING MODERN TOUCHSTONES IN A CORSETTED IBSEN CREATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, March 14) 
(bl) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ever since Henrik Ibsen wrote ``Hedda Gabler'' in
1890, the role has tantalized and lured actresses. The tragedy,
about a bored, vengeful wife on the edge of madness, has been
interpreted, with various degrees of Freudian and feminist
shadings, by Eva Le Gallienne, Geraldine Page, Maggie Smith, Glenda
Jackson, Jane Alexander and Dianne Wiest, among others. ``What
Hamlet is to men, Hedda is, in some ways, to women,'' said Annette
Bening, the latest Hedda, who has found the role the most complex
and haunting of her career.
</P>
<P>
   Sipping a fruit drink one recent morning at a table in the Bel
Air Hotel dining room, Ms. Bening, an animated and coolly beautiful
actress, said: ``Hedda is not the romantic heroine that Nora was''
_ the protagonist of Ibsen's ``Doll's House.'' ``But she's as
poignant as Nora. She's richly ambiguous and extremely disturbing.
And she's someone whom people can relate to. Even though it's a
different time, even though we're dressed in corsets onstage, what
interests me is there's so much subtext here. We think, `Is there
really that much difference between then and now?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The production, which begins previews Sunday evening and opens
March 24 for a limited run at the Geffen Playhouse in Westwood, has
an unusual pedigree by Los Angeles standards. Here, where there is
an abundance of actors, writers and directors focused on film and
television, theater can seem a stepchild of the arts, though some
do seek out the challenge of live performance. In this case, those
involved have a long relationship with the stage.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Daniel Sullivan, who has known Ms. Bening for
years, ran the Seattle Repertory Theater for 16 years. He has also
directed the playwright Jon Robin Baitz's work since 1989. Baitz,
who adapted the Ibsen text for the production, is the author of,
among other plays, ``A Fair Country'' and ``The Substance of
Fire,'' both of which Sullivan directed in New York, as he did
Wendy Wasserstein's Broadway plays, ``The Heidi Chronicles,'' ``The
Sisters Rosensweig'' and ``An American Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   How the current production of ``Hedda Gabler'' came together was
in some ways remarkably simple. Gilbert Cates, the producing
director of the 498-seat Geffen Playhouse, asked Ms. Bening about
two years ago if she was interested in starring in a Noel Coward
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bening, who began her career at the American Conservatory
Theater in San Francisco, was unsure. ``I said to her, `What would
you really like to do?''' Cates recalled. ``And she said, `Hedda
Gabler.'''
</P>
<P>
   Once the dates were set, Ms. Bening suggested Sullivan, who
agreed to direct, and he called in his friend Baitz to adapt the
play and make the language of the mainly British translations less
stilted and more contemporary. The cast includes Byron Jennings as
Hedda's husband, George Tesman; Rosemary Murphy as his aunt Julia,
and Paul Guilfoyle as Hedda's confidant, Judge Brack.
</P>
<P>
   The production is the most high-profile yet at the former
Westwood Playhouse. In 1995, the David Geffen Foundation gave $5
million to the graduate school of theater, film and television at
the University of California at Los Angeles for the purchase of the
building. The idea was to create a resident professional theater
company associated with the graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Ms. Bening, Sullivan and Baitz came to the play
with their own agendas _ personal and professional. Ms. Bening had
never seen a production of ``Hedda Gabler'' but was stirred by
Janet McTeer's acclaimed performance as a frenetic, sensual Nora in
the British import of ``A Doll's House'' on Broadway in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Bening is hardly similar to the trapped woman she
portrays onstage, the 40-year-old actress made it plain that
``Hedda Gabler'' tugs at her personally in ways she does not fully
grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bening herself was destined for major stardom in the early
1990s. After a grounding in theater _ her performance in Tina
Howe's ``Coastal Disturbances'' off-Broadway in 1986 won her a Tony
Award nomination when the play moved to Broadway _ she received an
Academy Award nomination for her 1990 role as a sexy con artist in
the movie ``The Grifters.'' This was followed the next year by
``Bugsy'' in which she starred opposite Warren Beatty, whom she
subsequently married. The decision to have children _ the couple
now have three _ forced her to pass on some major film roles of the
early and mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women would say they relate to `Hedda Gabler' _ there's a
part of her in them,'' said Ms. Bening, who was seated with
Sullivan and Bates at the Bel Air and was about to rush off to take
one of her children to a birthday party. ``I think Ibsen was
writing about a deep ambivalence that many women feel about
domesticity. I think about myself and friends of mine _ we have
some of Hedda's qualities and traits.''
</P>
<P>
   While she confessed to a deep nervousness about playing the
part, ``the desire to do it is stronger than the fear I have,'' Ms.
Bening said. ``There's such a rich ambiguity about her, and she's
complicated: sympathetic one moment, extremely disturbing the
next.''
</P>
<P>
   Biographers have noted that the Hedda character was loosely
modeled on a young woman whom Ibsen met at a resort when he was in
his early 60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ibsen had a deeply repressed sexual energy,'' Baitz said.
``There was almost no physicality to his life at that point. He had
a loveless marriage, and this young woman somehow lit him up and
triggered something in him, and they apparently had a chaste
friendship.'' The woman later wrote about the relationship and sold
the articles in a manner reminiscent of the 1990s. ``A typical
20th-century story,'' Baitz said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   The drama itself goes far beyond the issue of domesticity and
female repression. ``Hedda Gabler'' is an enigmatic study of a
possibly pregnant woman _ it is left ambiguous _ who is trapped in
a marriage to a plodding man. As the play unfolds, Hedda glides
toward self-destruction as she schemes and shatters lives. Henry
James once said of her, ``She suffers, she struggles, she is
human.'' But the critic Brooks Atkinson wrote in 1936, ``In cold
fact, she is the most hateful woman in dramatic literature.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
