<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5541 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDDA-GABLER-THEATER-     03-10 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDDA-GABLER-THEATER-2NDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: dramatic literature.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baitz said he was still unsure how to characterize what he did
to the classic. ``I don't know what to call it,'' he said. ``I
worked from a literal translation of the play, and I think I
de-Anglified it and got out of its way. I see other people who do
that same thing and say, `It's a new version by Christopher Hampton
or David Hare.' I don't know what to say. I sort of curated it.''
</P>
<P>
   He took the assignment, he said, partly because he was flattered
by it. ``It seemed to be too good to get so close to something so
exquisitely crafted.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a personal element, too, for the 37-year-old
dramatist. He had spent the last two years working as a
screenwriter on projects that have not seen the light of day. He
was well paid but frustrated. Baitz said he began thinking that he
was turning into Clifford Odets, the archetypal New York playwright
who went to Hollywood in the 1940s and endured misery, albeit a
lucrative one, at poolside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It left me feeling practically worthless as a writer,'' Baitz
said. ``The variables that I could not control just stymied me. I
was left feeling impotent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to complain,'' he added. ``This is not self-pity.
But I think Dan Sullivan asked me to do this to jump-start me out
of a long period of writer's block. It made me go back to work. I
became reacquainted with the exhilaration of writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baitz said that within days of starting the adaptation _ which
he considered at first almost a writing exercise _ he became
mesmerized and obsessed by it. ``I always thought it was a mountain
of a play; it would never occur to me to go near it,'' he said.
``By the end of the first scene, I felt I had been seduced by how
cold and hard and righteous and angry the play was, how modern it
was. It's modern in that it's sphinx-like, it defies easy
cataloguing.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Baitz kept thinking of David Rabe's ``Hurlyburly,''
the bleak drama about a group of male friends in the Hollywood
Hills whose lives are at a dead end. ``Take out the Hollywood
stuff, the two plays work on a very brutal level _ you have the
menace between the sexes,'' Baitz said. ``There's a nice parabola
from Rabe to Ibsen.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Bening, Baitz said he began identifying with the drama.
``It's a play about fear, infectious fear; I felt attuned to
that,'' he said. He said the character of Hedda's husband, who is
infatuated with her, struck close to him. ``His desperate need to
make this person happy _ that seemed like my own personal need,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baitz said he would view the adaptation as a failure if
audiences left the playhouse saying ``Hedda Gabler'' was merely a
theatrical relic with no relevance to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Hedda find her access denied in some ways? Yes,'' Baitz
said. ``Do we live in a world where people find access to a future
denied? Yes. Is she someone in free fall, someone whose sense of
panic starts the second before she wakes up and never ends? Yes. Do
we live in a world of Xanax and Ambien and isolation? Are we less
isolated now just because everybody's lives are cantilevered in a
way they weren't 100 years ago? I don't think we're any less
isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Baitz said it was absurd to depict the play as a feminist work
of art. ``That's an infuriating limitation,'' he said. ``What makes
it riveting is that there's no ideology, no agenda. It makes no
attempt to apologize for despicable behavior. It's a picture of
people being crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, a quiet-spoken, almost diffident man, said the drama,
in contrast to some of Ibsen's other works, is driven by one actor
_ the woman playing Hedda.
</P>
<P>
   ``You not only need a strong actress but a strong persona, and
when Annette called me about the play, I said, `That's a wonderful
idea,''' he said. ``She fits the role. She has the kind of
vividness as a performer that the play needs. And she can very
easily get to that trapped place where you feel that the
personality, the mind and the ambition of the character are much
larger than the circumstances she found herself in.''
</P>
<P>
   The director said it was almost impossible to underplay ``Hedda
Gabler'': ``It's a kind of minefield of emotional excess. You have
to play it with full stops out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Sullivan said, ``Hedda Gabler'' is not about gender
issues or about feminism. Such notions, he said, diminish a drama
as timeless as a Greek tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bening and Baitz agree with Sullivan, and so, apparently,
did Ibsen. ``I have been more of a poet and less of a social
philosopher than people have generally been inclined to believe,''
he said at a testimonial banquet given by the Norwegian Society for
Women's Rights. ``I thank you for your toast but I must decline the
honor of consciously having worked for women's rights. I am not
even sure what women's rights really are. To me, it has been a
question of human rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
