<HEADER>
A5543 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDHOOD-PHOTOGS-$AD     03-10 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDHOOD-PHOTOGS-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNOCENT OR NOT SO? THE SHIFTING VISIONS OF CHILDHOOD  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Conn., N.Y., Texas, Fla.)  (af) 
Sarah Bayliss is an associate editor at Artnews magazine. 
 By SARAH BAYLISS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The exact dates are debated, but many historians agree that the
idea of childhood innocence developed in the 18th century. Before
then, they argue, children were generally viewed as little adults
who would benefit from discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Early artistic images of children generally portrayed certain
types: the Holy Child, lamenting cherubs, cupids awakening passion
in feckless mortals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to the 18th century, the concept of the child was
basically as a small person born into sin, especially if they were
Christian,'' says Anne Higonnet, an art historian and author of
``Pictures of Innocence: The History and Crisis of Ideal
Childhood,'' which documents art-historical and contemporary images
of children. ``What happened in the 18th century was a radical
revision of that view.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Images of young people painted by Joshua Reynolds and Thomas
Gainsborough coincided with Enlightenment-era ideas about childhood
and seemed to validate Jean-Jacques Rousseau's argument that
children were naturally innocent and corrupted by society and that
they should be raised as ``naturally'' as possible.
</P>
<P>
   This ideal shifted again with the invention of photography in
the 19th century. In stark counterpoint to entrenched romantic
ideas, realist photographs by Jacob Riis and Lewis Hine, taken at
the turn of the 20th century and later, presented grim views of
child poverty and labor (images like these, in fact, changed
American juvenile labor laws).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other 19th- and early 20th-century photographs
continued to portray children without connection to a cruel world:
young people in society portraits or dressed as literary
characters, or 19th-century postmortem pictures of beatific
children who looked asleep _ and eternally innocent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Childhood innocence, or the lack of it, still receives a lot of
attention. Children in the 1990s are often overprotected and
treated like hothouse flowers to insulate them from dangerous
situations, according to Kiku Adatto, director of the
interdepartmental Children's Studies at Harvard University.
``People remain children for an awfully long time, as any parent of
a child who returns home at the age of 30 knows,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But specific protections of childhood are also under fire, and
the use of glamorous youths in film and advertising causes
perennial controversy over ethical portrayals of children: most
recently, Calvin Klein discontinued a magazine and billboard
advertising campaign for children's underwear last month following
criticism from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Rosie O'Donnell, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   The legal age of childhood is also under debate, as children who
commit serious crimes are tried as adults in some states. ``The
movement to push back the age of childhood from a judicial point of
view brings us back to the idea that children are not necessarily
innocent,'' says Ms. Higonnet.
</P>
<P>
   Devils or angels, children remain hugely popular subjects for
artists, especially photographers. Though art photographers like
Larry Clark and Nick Waplington track the seamy side of youth in
the 1990s, it is the free-and-easy tradition of child photography
that endures and continues to influence the family albums and
greeting cards of today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four museum shows with photographs of children reflect
historically contradictory views of young people: romantic visions
from the past; more jaundiced views from the 1980s and '90s.
``Future Present: Contemporary Photographs of Children From the
Reader's Digest Collection,'' 73 works by contemporary
photographers on view through Sunday at the Aldrich Museum of
Contemporary Art in Ridgefield, Conn., presents a generally warm
and fuzzy view of young life.
</P>
<P>
   Two continuing New York exhibitions of Victorian-era photographs
featuring pictures of children by British photographers _
``Reflections in a Looking Glass: A Centenary Lewis Carroll
Exhibition'' at the Equitable Gallery and ``Julia Margaret
Cameron's Women'' at the Museum of Modern Art _ offer differing
perspectives on Victorian sentimentality toward young people.
</P>
<P>
   And in April, ``Through the Looking Glass: Visions of
Childhood'' at the Snug Harbor Cultural Center on Staten Island
will mix historical and contemporary images and promises some
disquieting moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Future Present,'' culled from some 250 photographs of children
from the corporate art collection at Reader's Digest, is in keeping
with the company's family-oriented public image, though there are a
few provocative pictures in the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children represent hope,'' says Jill DeVonyar-Zansky,
associate curator of the Reader's Digest corporate art collection.
``That is the essence of a lot of stories in the magazine.'' The
collection is also meant to appeal to baby boomers, Reader's
Digest's newly targeted audience as their traditional readership
ages.
</P>
<P>
   Some well-known, edgy photographers are present here, but with
relatively tame images, not necessarily typical of their work. Tina
Barney is represented with a stagy scene of affluent domesticity,
and Robert Mapplethorpe with a defiantly posed (and fully clothed)
portrait of the daughter of the art dealer Bruno Bishofsberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Odalisque,'' a 1989 image by Sally Mann, portrays the
photographer's self-consciously reclining, semiclad young daughter.
Sebastiao Salgado's 1981 ``Three Communion Girls, Brazil,'' who
pose puttilike in white dresses and wings _ while one girl glares
angrily at the camera _ is quite different from the searing
photographs of manual labor and famine for which Salgado is
famous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a gentler note, Abelardo Morell's 1994 ``Laura and Brady in
the Shadow of our House'' _ a favorite image among Reader's Digest
employees, according to Ms. DeVonyar-Zansky _ conveys a charming
sense of teamwork between photographer and children: a boy and a
girl pose in the dark shadow of a pitched-roof house, an ephemeral
play-home decorated with window shapes drawn on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Groover's 1990 ``Untitled (Holding Baby's Hand)'' is a
soft-focus, sepia-toned print showing infant fingers held in an
adult hand, like a parental version of the Creation scene's spark
of life imparted through the touch of a finger. In Charles Hagen's
1996 ``Anna with Magnifier, Brooklyn, New York,'' a young girl
peers through a large magnifying lens, her teeth a twisted
surrealistic display. (The Surrealists themselves, however, were
not known for photographing children. ``They were a very adult kind
of group,'' Ms. Higonnet says.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, photographs of children from the 19th century often
appear more static because of the long exposure time, but many of
them are compelling. At the Museum of Modern Art, Cameron's
soft-focus images of Pre-Raphaelite Madonnas and children are often
overtly religious portrayals; her portraits of mop-haired girls and
boys refer to classical and literary themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cameron had a vision that she was imposing on the children;
they were going to pose for her in a particular manner and way,''
says Roy Flukinger, senior curator of photography and film at the
Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center at the University of Texas
in Austin, which owns one of the world's largest holdings of
Carroll and Cameron photographs. ``Carroll was just delighted that
kids were kids, basically. He was interested in showing the heart
of the child. He would have a lot of fun. It was a collaborative,
even wonderfully conspiratorial experience: him and the children
against the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron and Carroll were acquaintances who occasionally
photographed the same people, but they didn't like each other's
photographs: Carroll, an Oxford don whose real name was Charles
Dodgson, particularly disliked what he called Cameron's ``large
heads taken out of focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Higonnet argues that early photography made it possible for
the ideal of romantic childhood to seem completely natural. ``In
the 19th century, there was a massive reproduction of images,'' she
says. ``The image of childhood was widespread and intensely
visual.''
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence of the era's ideal of innocent childhood also
emerged from literature: the Grimm fairy tales were translated into
English in 1823 and lost their more macabre details in the process.
``They were stripped of potentially dangerous elements for
children,'' says U.C. Knoepflmacher, author of ``Ventures into
Childland: Victorians, Fairy Tales and Femininity'' (1998).
</P>
<P>
   In these post-Lolita times, observers can't help seeing a
disquieting sensuality in both Carroll's and Cameron's pictures of
children, some of whom were photographed scantily clad. The
Victorians romantically equated children with an untainted purity
of spirit; the less encumbered by clothes, the more angelic and
charming.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's evidently obsessive attention to young Alice Liddell,
the inspiration for ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland,'' has made
many view his images in a prurient light. As Knoepflmacher points
out, however, not only Carroll but other formidable Victorian
literati, including John Ruskin, William Thackeray and George
MacDonald, composed fantasy tales for special female children.
</P>
<P>
   Male Victorian authors were ``far more sentimentally attached to
childhood and children'' than their female counterparts,
Knoepflmacher says, because middle-class Victorian boys were sent
away to boarding schools with strict regulations while girls stayed
at home in more nurturing environments.
</P>
<P>
   From all accounts, Carroll's child-friends, including Alice,
thoroughly enjoyed his company; his willingness to tell stories and
indulge in childish fantasy appealed to them. An 1873 image of
9-year-old Xie (Alexandra) Kitchin in Chinese robes, perched on tea
boxes, or an enchanting picture of young Agnes Hughes reclining in
an elaborate headpiece and robe, suggests young people's delight in
dressing up.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron's children, by contrast, tend to look rather uniform,
with tangled hair, sleepily gazing out at the viewer. Alice,
impudent and coquettish in Carroll's famous portrait of her as
``The Beggar Maid,'' is dour and expressionless in Cameron's
photograph ``Pomona,'' taken when Alice was a young adult.
</P>
<P>
   Many contemporary portrayals of children refer to these
carefully orchestrated depictions, which to modern eyes fuse
eroticism and innocence. Inez van Lamsweerde's 1997 photograph
``Kirsten, Star,'' which will be at Snug Harbor, is part Cameron
child, part JonBenet Ramsey: a close-up image of a young girl's
face, with adult-size eyes, closed and glistening red lips.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mann has drawn on Cameron's imagery, according to Shannah
Ehrhart, who is curating the Snug Harbor show: Cameron's 1864 ``The
Double Star'' reveals two young girls locked in a dreamy embrace _
perhaps asleep _ with lips touching; Ms. Mann reinterpreted this
image in her 1988 ``Kiss Goodnight,'' a blurry image of her
daughters, Virginia and Jessie, similarly posed.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer Anna Gaskell, who once worked as Ms. Mann's
assistant, based a series of photographs on ``Alice's Adventures in
Wonderland''; these large color prints of five girls in starched
pinafores pushing, pulling and tussling with each other give a
distinctly unsettling edge to Carroll's tale. (Ms. Gaskell's images
were at the Museum of Contemporary Art in North Miami, Fla., and
others are now at the Guggenheim through May. 16. She declined to
participate in the Snug Harbor show and an exhibition curated by
Ms. Higonnet last year. Casey Kaplan, her New York dealer, says,
``She doesn't like to be in shows that are specifically about
childhood.'')
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of all these pictures, past and present, may lie in a
nostalgic yearning for simpler times _ before children's schedules
were filled with the play dates and day-care regimens that mimic
the rhythms of 1990s working life.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Adatto, of Harvard, sees in unsupervised children's play the
freedom ``to imagine, to be an agent, to be a master of your
world.'' Today, she says, ``We have one cultural trend that speaks
to the erosions of the ideals of childhood, and another that
upholds the old beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   These exhibitions make one thing clear: In photographs,
childhood usually appears the way adults want it to. Innocence, it
seems, is in the eye of the beholder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
