<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-2000-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE SETS HER EYE ON THE WHITE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  (See related DOLE-POLITICS) 
 (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Reprising her most famous moment in the 1996
presidential campaign, Elizabeth Dole bounded into an audience of
Iowans on Wednesday to announce her presidential exploratory
committee and to present herself both as a nonpolitician and as a
prepared government insider.
</P>
<P>
   More than two years after she made a passionate case at the
Republican Party's national convention for the election of her
husband and the party's nominee, Bob Dole, Mrs. Dole sought to do
the same for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Using no notes in her 25 minutes of remarks, Mrs. Dole did not
fumble one word (even repeating her campaign's Web site address) as
she strolled about with a microphone pinned to her dress as she
methodically reviewed her service in five administrations and as
president of the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Mrs. Dole sought to set herself apart as the only
woman in a field of as many as 10 men. ``Now what would I as a
woman offer our country?'' she asked. ``I'm no politician. And
frankly, I think that's a plus today. But I have spent a lifetime
in public service.''
</P>
<P>
   The event was scrupulously conceived as a counter to Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, who in his exploratory committee announcement in
Austin three days ago surrounded himself with party luminaries.
Although Mrs. Dole places second to Bush in the polls here and
around the country, she thus far cannot compete with his parade of
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she portrayed herself as a woman of the people, and
appeared on a stage at the convention center here after receiving
testimonials from a local farmer, a working mother, a high school
teacher and a 12-year-old black student who praised Mrs. Dole's
message against drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The student, Diandra Rollings, was taken by surprise when Mrs.
Dole pulled her into the audience for the beginning of her talk.
``We like some spontaneity, don't we?'' said the decidedly
unspontaneous Mrs. Dole, who moments later walked directly to a
spot on the floor marked with tape and began her own remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole spoke in vague terms of popular Republican themes such
as improving education, tax relief, pumping more money into the
military and combating the ``evil in American society'' of illegal
drug use. But she stayed clear of specific positions and gave no
clues as to where she might fall on an ideological spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's make this a crusade,'' Mrs. Dole said of her call to end
drug use. ``Remember Nancy Reagan's `just say no?' She made a huge
difference with that program.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably her most substantive comment was about the nation's
missile defenses. ``At a time when the secretary of defense is
saying that North Korea within a year may have nuclear bombs that
could reach the United States,'' she said, ``and we know Iraq is
manufacturing biological weapons, I think we need to do everything
to develop and deploy a strategic missile defense system.
Immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole told the audience that her positions would come soon
enough. ``I want to hear from people _ I want to listen,'' she
said. ``Then we're going to be laying out positions on all of these
issues. But we want to do it in a thoughtful way. Right?''
</P>
<P>
   As has been her practice since leaving the Red Cross nearly six
weeks ago _ and at events throughout most of her career _ Mrs. Dole
refused to take questions from reporters, whom her entourage kept
away from her. It was a striking contrast to Gov. Bush, who
bantered with reporters at his exploratory announcement on Sunday,
even as he said he too needed more time to fashion his positions.
</P>
<P>
   Kayne Robinson, the new state party chairman, commended Mrs.
Dole for her ``different style'' on Wednesday, but said that
Republicans who participate in the first important presidential
caucuses in this state expect give-and-take with the candidates.
``You won't have anyone coming to this state if you run a media
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dole committee unveiled a 14-minute commercial that
will run beginning Wednesday for one week only in Iowa and New
Hampshire, which holds the first primary. Mrs. Dole looks into the
camera and repeats many of the identical lines in her speech
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published Wednesday that was taken for several television
stations found that among likely Republican caucus goers in Iowa,
Bush was supported by nearly 37 percent of the vote, followed by 16
percent for Mrs. Dole. The other candidates all placed in the
single digits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Mrs. Dole's announcement Wednesday had been widely
expected, the exploratory committee allows her to raise money to
finance travel and other campaign-related costs _ and leaves no
doubt of her designs on the White House. Mrs. Dole also has begun
assembling a staff.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign manager is Tom Daffron, a former top aide to Sen.
Fred Thompson of Tennessee, and the top strategist is Kieran
Mahoney, who has worked for two New Yorkers: Gov. George E. Pataki
and former Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole borrowed from the announcement of candidacy on Tuesday
by former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, who in his speech
reminded the audience of how Ronald Reagan asked people if they
were better off now or four years before. Mrs. Dole repeated the
line, and posed another question as well: ``Perhaps the relevant
question now is, Are you better? Are your families stronger? Are
your children safe from drugs?''
</P>
<P>
   But the qualities that make her appealing could turn off other
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's a fine woman,'' Wayne Lilly, a Republican from
Chilton, N.H., said after a recent Christian Coalition event in his
state. ``But I don't believe a woman ought to be in that particular
place of leadership. She would be a good help mate. But the Bible
teaches us that a woman should not have authority over men. It's
nothing but foolishness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
