   SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS (Washington) _ The battle over the
nation's scarcest medical resource, human organs, has moved from
Washington to the states, where a number of legislatures have begun
passing laws that would bar donated hearts, lungs, kidneys, livers
and pancreases from being shipped beyond their borders to sick
people elsewhere in the country. So far, the laws have not had a
large effect on the way organs are distributed. Rather, they are
intended to thwart an effort by the Clinton administration to force
organ recovery networks and transplant centers around the nation to
share their precious organs more liberally. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
