<HEADLINE>
ANN CORIO, RACY STAGE PERFORMER KNOWN AS `QUEEN OF BURLESQUE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ann Corio, the auburn-haired, green-eyed beauty who bumped and
ground her way to fame and fortune as the ``Queen of Burlesque,''
died March 1 in Englewood Hospital in Englewood, N.J. She kept her
age a closely guarded secret, but was thought to be in her 80s.
</P>
<P>
   During her prime, attendance at one of her performances in the
Old Howard Theater in Scollay Square became a rite of passage for
young men in Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   She retired from show business about eight years ago, but had
practiced her earthy ``art'' long enough to present it as a put-on.
In the 1970s, she toured the straw hat circuit as the star of
``This Was Burlesque'' at summer theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphasize comedy,'' she said in an interview in 1976.
``There is not total nudity. The girls are lovely and artistic and
they're terribly, terribly pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   She looked down on recent practitioners of her specialty. ``What
is called burlesque today isn't that at all,'' she said in 1976.
``Those girls aren't artists. They just take clothes off, and they
don't even do that very well. Burlesque is exactly what it says it
is. It's from the Italian word burlare, to satirize, to laugh.
That's what we do, and we are not offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   She was one of 12 children of Italian immigrants who settled in
Hartford, Conn. She was a conventional dancer until the age of 16,
when, she said, she learned she could make more money by shedding
her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of Cliffside Park, N.J., she and her third husband,
Michael P. Iannucci, a former linebacker for the Pittsburgh
Steelers, operated the Playhouse on the Mall in Paramus, N.J, where
they presented legitimate stage shows as well as ``This Was
Burlesque'' for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Beside her husband, she leaves two sisters, Helen LaRue of West
Hartford, Conn., and Lillian Denote of Bristol, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
