<HEADER>
A5555 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAY-SOUTH-COX     03-10 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAY-SOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surveys show big variation in salary
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making a good living in the Southeast might boil down to where
you live, according to two wage surveys released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Database administrators, bookkeepers and receptionists fare best
in Georgia, where the average hourly pay in nonmanufacturing jobs
was highest of five Southeastern states surveyed by Randstad
Staffing Services in its first wage and employment report.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama, on the other hand, had the highest hourly pay for
computer programmers and systems analysts: $28.73 and $25.15,
respectively. The high pay was tied largely to the Huntsville area,
which relies heavily on high-tech and defense work.
</P>
<P>
   Randstad surveyed 2,500 companies in Georgia, Tennessee,
Alabama, South Carolina and Mississippi last fall. It looked at
employers' concerns and pay scales of 45 job categories in
manufacturing and nonmanufacturing firms.
</P>
<P>
   A study by New York compensation consultant William M. Mercer
showed variations in salary for the same job in different cities.
That could pose a problem for worker-strapped companies with
operations throughout the country. The study looked at wages in 200
cities in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A salary averaging $50,000 nationally pays $52,700 in Atlanta,
or 5.4 percent above the national norm, the Mercer study said. The
same job would pay as much as 20 percent higher, or about $60,200,
in San Jose and as low as $41,750 in Brownsville, Texas, 17 percent
less than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta's still a hotbed of employment. It's got a very low
unemployment rate and that's going to affect what a potential
employee may ask for. Employees are in a buyer's market,'' said
Atlanta-based Mercer consultant Eric McMillan.
</P>
<P>
   Through the early 1990s, Atlanta's salaries mirrored the
national average, but started edging up in 1995, McMillan said. Now
Atlanta is almost in the same pay league as Chicago, Boston and
Washington, D.C., which tend to pay more than the national average,
McMillan said. Mercer has been tracking salaries for more than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report points up the complexities that large employers
face in managing salary programs covering operations throughout the
United States,'' said Darrell Cira, another Atlanta-based Mercer
consultant. ``Sensitive compensation issues can arise, for example,
when companies relocate employees from comparatively high to
comparatively low salary areas, and vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Salary variations leveled off at higher pay scales. A job that
averages $80,000 nationally would equate to about $81,599, or 2
percent higher, in Atlanta, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   The two studies are an interesting glimpse of employer concerns
in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly what came back from employers was that offering a
competitive wage is key to keeping employees,'' said Jim Reese,
Randstad's managing director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
