<SLUG> BC-DWI-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL BACKS BILL LOWERING ALCOHOL LIMIT IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After tearful pleas from the parents of four
high school girls who were killed in a drunk-driving crash and
little outside opposition, a Senate committee unanimously endorsed
a bill Wednesday that would lower the legal amount of alcohol
drivers can have in their body.
</P>
<P>
   The measure approved by the Senate Criminal Justice Committee
would lower the legal limit from .10 percent to .08 percent blood
alcohol content.
</P>
<P>
   In his second attempt to pass a bill that would lower the
state's legal definition of ``intoxication,'' Sen. Mario Gallegos,
D-Houston, said he proposed SB 114 because he is ``greatly
concerned with the alcohol-related fatalities in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which has been endorsed by Gov. George W. Bush, Lt.
Gov. Rick Perry, Mothers Against Drunk Driving and numerous state
residents, will now be considered by the full Senate. The House
version of the bill, HB 210 sponsored by Rep. Scott Hochberg,
D-Houston, is waiting to be heard by the Criminal Jurisprudence
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lezlie and Doug McWhorter, parents of 15-year-old Mandi
McWhorter who was killed in December with three other girls by an
alleged intoxicated driver, voiced their support for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe our daughter would be here today if we had a stricter
law,'' said Lezlie McWhorter.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband agreed. ``It's time that we, as a state, make a
difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas in 1997, 1,748 people were killed in alcohol-related
crashes, a 13.9 percent decline from the previous year's 1,991
similar fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the bill said that MADD and the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration distort their data by citing all
``alcohol-related'' deaths, rather than the more narrow term of
``alcohol-caused.'' For a crash to be referred to as
``alcohol-related,'' only a small presence of alcohol needs to be
in the driver's blood system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fraud that's being perpetuated on the public,'' said
Luke Ball, state chapter coordinator of the National Motorists
Association. ``The numbers are manufactured and used to say that
(lowering the blood alcohol content from .10 to .08) will save
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration,
in 1996 5.5 percent of all alcohol-related fatalities involved a
driver with .08 to .09 blood alcohol content or lower, whereas 19.4
percent of the drivers had a percentage of .10 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics of the bill argue that lowering the legal
definition of ``intoxication'' will deter people from drinking
socially among friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only effect of an .08 law is that many social drinkers
will be jailed, fined and suffer costs of up to $15,000 for
behavior that is considered responsible,'' said Rick Berman,
general counsel for the American Beverage Institute.
</P>
<P>
   If the limit is lowered, a 170-pound man would have to stop
drinking after four drinks, while a 120-pound woman would have to
stop after three drinks, according to the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the parents and friends of the four students at Brock High
School, west of Fort Worth, who were killed Dec. 19 said people who
drive after drinking are irresponsible and that state laws should
be tougher on those who choose to break the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man who killed my friends wasn't a student or a minor. He
was an adult who should've known better,'' said Candice Sanders, a
friend of the four girls.
</P>
<P>
   David Lee, the father of 16-year-old Staci Lee who was killed in
the same crash, said if lowering the blood alcohol content to .08
percent will help save even one life, then the change will not be
made in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slapping them (people who drive while intoxicated) on the
wrist isn't going to deter them,'' he said. ``We need to start
saving lives now. This can be used as a stepping stone to make laws
more effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz Osina, the mother of 17-year-old Lacey Osina, echoed Lee's
concerns: ``One life lost is one too many.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
