<HEADER>
A5558 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEEP-END-REVIEW-LADN     03-10 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEP-END-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHALLOW IN TOO MANY WAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Friday, March 12 by NYTimes News Service) 
OUR RATING: 2 STARS 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Heart-rending and yet overwhelmingly tedious,
``The Deep End of the Ocean'' bears a passing resemblance to Robert
Redford's powerful ``Ordinary People'' in that both deal with a
family's traumatic reaction to the loss of a son.
</P>
<P>
   But whereas ``Ordinary People'' demonstrated an understanding
and even empathy for its subjects, ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' is
content to wear its pained emotions on its sleeve. It's all
superficial _ the characters, the plotting, even Elmer Bernstein's
tired score _ giving the film the feel of an overwrought television
movie that has been blown up for the big screen. Here,
unfortunately, you don't have the luxury of commercial breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Pfeiffer stars as Beth Cappadora, a devoted, if
absent-minded, mother of three living in Madison, Wis. When Beth
attends her 15-year high school reunion in Chicago, she takes the
kids so her husband, Pat (Treat Williams), can tend to his
restaurant. Beth arrives in the crowded hotel lobby, hands her baby
girl to a friend and then asks her 5-year-old, Vincent, to watch
3-year-old Ben while she registers for their room. In the blink of
an eye, though, Ben disappears, setting off tensions within the
Cappadora family that reverberate for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Beth becomes distant and irresponsible, preferring to stay in
bed than face any kind of normalcy. Pat (in what little there is of
him) pretends everything is going to be OK. A gay police detective
(Whoopi Goldberg) does her best to help, but once the notoriety of
Ben's disappearance wanes, there's not much she can do. The family
settles into a quiet detente of unspoken guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years pass, and then one day, Ben shows up on the
Cappadoras' door step (they've moved), asking if they need their
lawn mowed. Ben _ now named Sam _ lives just two blocks away with
his devoted ``father'' and has no memories of his previous family.
Beth and Pat are overjoyed, but soon must cope with the realization
that their ties to their son are tenuous at best and not all that
easily renewed.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is adapted from Jacquelyn Mitchard's best-selling
novel, the first book to be featured by Oprah Winfrey on her
popular book club. Little fault can be found with the novel (aside
from perhaps its pat ending), but screenwriter Stephen Schiff has
removed most of its insights and tough truths and replaced them
with generalizations that fail to engage the audience.
</P>
<P>
   There are also glaring gaps. In one scene, the now teen-age
Vincent (Jonathan Jackson, whose charismatic performance is the
best thing about the movie) has long hair; in the next, it's
closely cropped. Goldberg's detective character is incredibly
under-developed. All we know about her comes from her introductory
scene. After that, nothing; although director Ulu Grosbard assumes
a familiarity that hasn't been earned.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer has played this kind of brittle character before and
certainly does a credible job in showing Beth's rocky
transformation. But the only way for this off-putting film to work
would be to really get inside its characters, avoid emotional
shorthand and explore the pain, guilt and betrayals in ways that go
beyond the trite and true. Then ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' would
still be hard to like, but at least it would say something about
the human condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2000EST &QL; 
