<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ENVOY FAILS TO BUDGE MILOSEVIC ON KOSOVO PEACE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-REPUBS) 
(wg) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy,
emerged from daylong negotiations with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic on Wednesday, admitting he had failed to win any change
in the Serbian leader's opposition to the international peace
proposal for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As intense fighting continued in Kosovo, Holbrooke was ensconced
with Milosevic in Belgrade. Holbrooke, who brokered the Dayton
accords that ended the war in Bosnia and who negotiated the
now-tattered cease-fire in Kosovo, was brought in to press
Milosevic toward an agreement before peace talks resume in Paris on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet shortly before midnight, after his second meeting of the day
ended, Holbrooke said that there had been no progress. ``After a
long day of talks, there has been no change in the Yugoslav
position during the day nor in our position,'' he said. ``We
discussed every aspect in Kosovo and in Bosnia and I made clear the
significant concern of our government with the fighting that is
continuing at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to keep in close touch. They were very engaged, very
intense talks,'' he said, adding he would return to the United
States on Thursday to report to Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. Holbrooke declined to speculate what his failure meant
for the next round of talks. ``We are in a very difficult situation
tonight,'' he later told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The main sticking point remains Milosevic's refusal to accept a
NATO-led military force in Kosovo to enforce a political
settlement. Holbrooke had been expected to use his personal
relationship with Milosevic and his forceful style to achieve some
movement. But despite an atmosphere described by one American
official as ``business-like,'' there was no hint that Milosevic was
ready to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic told Tanjur, the Yugoslav news agency, that any
attempt to make the presence of foreign troops in Kosovo a
condition of the political agreement was ``unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had played down the chances of a breakthrough before
the talks began. Western mediators had hoped to have a deal ready
for signing by both parties but now it appears the Serbian and
ethnic Albanian delegations are likely to reassemble only for more
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   There was an underlying sense of urgency, as the consequences of
heavy fighting in southern Kosovo emerged Wednesday. Reporters who
reached the still smoldering village of Ivaja found at least four
dead in the abandoned village, along with dead animals and scorched
farm buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces seized control of the village Tuesday after some
fighting. Much of the village was destroyed and the houses were
burned. Villagers had fled, some to the nearby village of Kotlina,
but aid agencies were still searching for an estimated 400 refugees
hiding somewhere in the wooded mountains above.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke had warned on his arrival in Belgrade Tuesday that
Kosovo was heading for an even greater tragedy and Belgrade was on
a collision course with the West. After the talks he reiterated
that the threat of NATO air strikes still hangs over Milosevic and
that the Yugoslav president was aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   But Holbrooke said the current fighting in Kosovo, while
reprehensible, was part of the process and did not entirely disable
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Holbrooke will depart from Belgrade on Thursday, the
steady stream into Belgrade of foreign officials from the six
members of the Contact Group overseeing the region will continue.
Little change is expected before Monday when the talks begin,
however.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Holbrooke was seen as the key to persuading the Yugoslav
president to accept the deal. He was accompanied by Christopher
Hill, the United States Ambassador to Macedonia. Hill has been
largely responsible for drafting the proposed peace plan that would
grant ethnic Albanians in Kosovo self-rule and the protection of
NATO-led troops for an interim period.
</P>
<P>
   The view in Belgrade is that Milosevic will eventually agree to
an international peacekeeping force in Kosovo but that he is not
yet ready to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Bratislav Grubacic, editor of the independent VIP news service
in Belgrade, said this was not the end of the discussions, but
rather a few steps before the end. ``It will be a transfer of
messages, and seeing what are the limits of the other, what can be
the bargaining chips,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grubacic suggested that a peace agreement is still several weeks
away. Milosevic, meanwhile, was looking for some guarantees from
the West, he said, namely that his position of power not be
attacked, that he not be pursued by the international tribunal's
investigation into war crimes, and that he win some lifting of
trade sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic also has to listen to an extent to the generals of the
Yugoslav Army. Many of them want to continue the war to suppress
the guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army, and are also
violently opposed to the presence of NATO troops on Yugoslav soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
