<SLUG> BC-HARMONISTS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARMONISTS: THE FAB FOUR OF THEIR DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Friday, March 12 by NYTimes News Service) 
OUR RATING: 3 STARS 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The German film ``The Harmonists'' tells a
fascinating story that never fails to fascinate, even though it
could have been told better. Strangely but helpfully, whenever this
naturalistic ``Cabaret'' slips into predictable plotting and
gathering Nazi storm cliches, an odd, amusing little musical number
soon comes along and saves the day.
</P>
<P>
   The film, like the controversial new Broadway production ``Band
in Berlin,'' is based on the true story of the Comedian Harmonists.
A vocal quintet and their pianist, the Harmonists apparently were
the Beatles of Weimar Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Noted for their complex, well, harmonies, the weird noises they
made with their voices and clever nonsense lyrics (asparagus was a
major motif in one song), they enjoyed a series of hit recordings,
sold-out concerts and international tours before Hitler pulled the
plug on the half-Jewish combo in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, directed by Joseph Vilsmaier, follows a typical
rags-to-riches pattern, with the focus on the group's founder,
Harry Frommermann (Ulrich Noethen) and his relationship with driven
basso Robert Biberti (Ben Becker). The men disagree over just about
everything _ and in an unnecessarily contrived subplot, even vie
for the same woman's affections _ except their love for music and
respect for each other's creativity.
</P>
<P>
   As the political situation around them deteriorates, Jewish
Harry and gentile Robert are sorely tested and test each other _ in
one of the film's best scenes, Robert accuses Harry of having a
persecution complex, and his colleague slaps him repeatedly for
trivializing the dire situation; instantly chastened, Robert
accepts the blows without argument.
</P>
<P>
   The whole story revolves around the singers' willful refusal to
believe that Nazi anti-Semitism could be stronger than their own
popularity. And even though the other four Harmonists are, at best,
sketchily presented, the way the awful truth creeps into each
individual's consciousness is nicely delineated.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Cycowski (Heino Ferch), a Pole who went on to become the
oldest working cantor in America, insists that his fiancee convert
to Judaism under what he knows are the most difficult historical
circumstances. Erich A. Collin (Heinrich Schafmeister), all
monocles and cigarette holders and haughty Prussian superiority, is
more bemused than anything when he officially is declared
non-Aryan. Ari Leschnikoff (Max Tidof), a boisterous Bulgarian,
just hopes the band can work long enough for him to bed another
hundred or so groupies. And the pianist Erwin Bootz (Kai Wiesinger)
starts thinking up reasons why his marriage to a Jewish woman no
longer is working.
</P>
<P>
   Performances range from good to, where Noethen and Becker are
concerned, excellent. But it's the long-gone Comedian Harmonists
themselves whose work really stands out. Many of the film's musical
tracks are their old, brilliantly preserved and remastered
recordings, and although the modern actors do marvelously evocative
lip-synching, it's those impossibly weird vocal gymnastics that
truly give the movie its distinctive voice.
</P>
<P>
   There's a marvelous bit when the group-in-training, just
rejected by a clueless promoter and considering breaking up, break
instead into an improvised run-through of Duke Ellington's ``Creole
Love Call,'' each singer mouthing the sound of a different musical
instrument. It's a transcendent moment of creative joy in a smoky
old beer hall; seeing and hearing this, you can forgive the
Harmonists their delusion that art could survive the firestorm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
