<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5566 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-HUNTER-GAULT11-CO     03-10 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-HUNTER-GAULT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At the forefront of integration as a student in the '60s,
longtime journalist Charlayne Hunter-Gault now will chronicle
emerging Africa for CNN
 &HT;    W/BIO-BOX
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charlayne Hunter-Gault traded one South in transition
for another.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Atlanta in the '50s and a pioneer of integration at
the University of Georgia in the early '60s, the award-winning
journalist has spent the past two years based in Johannesburg,
South Africa, reporting on all of Africa for National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Come April 2, she'll move from NPR to CNN, becoming CNN's
Johannesburg bureau chief and the global network's most visible
face in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about anywhere you go in Africa, people are able to see
CNN,'' she says. ``Even in cases where people can't access CNN
because they don't have TVs or they don't have electricity, (CNN's)
stories get told.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter-Gault is back, briefly, in Atlanta to meet with
executives at CNN Center about her future with the network. Sitting
in the office of Eason Jordan, president of CNN International,
she's jet-lagged and fighting off yawns, having just flown in from
Africa. But even jet-lagged, she looks a good 15 years younger than
her 57 years, in her taupe jacket and black slacks and with her
tightly cornrowed hair and large hazel eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't made her main residence in Georgia since 1963 but
still considers it home, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pride in seeing Atlanta grow, but I feel some nostalgia
for the old days when there was a Davison's (now Macy's) and a
Rich's'' downtown, she says, even though when she was a teenager,
those stores' lunch counters were closed to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a black Southerner, you have to be careful when you talk
about gentility, because that conjures up all kinds of images that
aren't always positive. But there was, on the positive side, a
gentility in both blacks and whites that has dissipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, she says, has ``lost some of the charm that it had. I
still sort of cringe when I walk through the airport. I want to
hear a Southern voice. I don't want to hear a Muzak voice, a robot
voice. Its identity as a Southern city has been diluted.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey of Atlanta and the South in some ways parallels the
changes in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Africa has, in some respects, followed the path of the
American South. There are many points at which that story diverges,
but there are many points at which they are similar. That's why
it's captured America's attention: It's something they can relate
to.''
</P>
<P>
   And she sees the cosmopolitan growth of Atlanta mirrored in
cities all over the African continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Africa ... you go into places andyou see the charm of the
traditional being eroded by something you call progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hunter-Gault has known CNN chairman Tom Johnson for
almost 40 years _ he was editor of The Red &AMP; Black at UGA when she
was a journalism student _ it was Jordan, CNN's international
president, who recruited her to jump to the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knock on African coverage is it only brings you the
negative, although I don't think that's always fair,'' says Jordan.
``She does a lot of reporting that takes you behind the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to ratchet up our coverage of Africa,'' Jordan adds.
``We're big believers in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter-Gault will continue to live in Johannesburg with her
mother Althea and her husband Ron Gault, managing director of J.P.
Morgan, an investment firm. But she'll roam the continent for her
reports, coordinating with CNN's bureaus in Nairobi and Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coverage of Africa has usually been about who the bad guys
were,'' she says, ``or the end product of the action of the bad
guys. So you get starvation and massacres, you get Somaila. But I
think we have to look at even those stories in a different way. We
have to do the coverage of the breaking news and we also have an
opportunity, if not an obligation, to report those things that go
on between crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the brief is to cover the continent as holistically as
I can. You'll see more of the people on the ground, the people who
are impacted by the leaders, as well as the people who make the
policy. ''
</P>
<P>
   She won't have much competition on a day-to-day basis from the
broadcast networks' news divisions. ABC, CBS and NBC have no
permanent bureaus in Africa, relying on stringers and
correspondents who fly in and out to cover breaking news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody since the end of the Cold War has been trying to
figure out what is news,'' she says. ``I don't think anybody's been
totally successful. You may not have the grand theme of good guys
vs. bad guys. But if you look to the people to tell the stories,
how people survive, people's aspirations, I think that's where the
new news is.''
</P>
<P>
   _ For more information online, see
http://www.usca.sc.edu/aasc/hunter.htm
</P>
<P>
   Bio-Box
</P>
<P>
   CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Making news: Starts April 2 as CNN International's
Johannesburg bureau chief.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Personal: Married to investment banker Ronald Gault (her
second marriage). Grown children: Susan, Chuma.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: Feb. 27, 1942, in Due West, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Raised: Covington, until sixth grade, then Atlanta. Graduated
from Henry McNeal Turner High School.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Childhood hero: Comic strip reporter Brenda Starr.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  College: Integrated the University of Georgia as its first
female African-American student, 1961. B.A. in journalism, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Career: The New Yorker ``Talk of the Town'' reporter; reporter
and Harlem, N.Y., bureau chief, The New York Times; ``The
MacNeil/Lehrer NewsHour,'' correspondent and substitute anchor;
National Public Radio Africa correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Awards: Peabody Award; several Emmys; Journalist of the Year,
National Association of Black Journalists, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Autobiography: ``In My Place,'' 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
