<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECONOMY-ART-2TA     03-10 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECONOMY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUTIOUSLY, JAPANESE TAKE HEART IN INCREASED ECONOMIC ACTIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also JAPAN-ECONSCENE, DAIMLER-NISSAN, NISSAN-ASSESS,
RJR-NABISCO-JAPAN) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAKANOJOMACHI, Japan _ Bulldozers and tall cranes are popping up
around the country like bamboo shoots after a spring rain, raising
hopes that Japan may finally be close to lifting itself out of
recession.
</P>
<P>
   No other country has ever poured as much money _ more than $830
billion the last 12 months alone _ into economic revival as has
Japan, and much of that money is now sloshing around the country
and creating a noticeable impact. Here in this village in central
Japan, as in much of the country, construction crews are again
busy, small companies are getting loans again and some people are
feeling a tad more confident.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese leaders have traditionally funneled money into
brick-and-mortar projects to stimulate the economy, so the signs of
life these days are interpreted by most experts as just a temporary
comeback, not a self-sustaining recovery. There have been many
false starts the last eight years, but the economy has always sunk
back, this time into the deepest recession since the end of World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   To the pessimists, however, Japan is like a vehicle being towed
along the road by all that deficit spending: They doubt its engine
will start without an overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons for the movement, whatever the concerns for
the future, the passengers throughout Japan seem relieved that at
least the vehicle may be going forward again.
</P>
<P>
   Any progress in Japan would also be a major relief for the rest
of the world, since Japan is the second-largest economy after the
United States and by far the largest in Asia. Optimists believe
that Japan has finally bottomed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the worst time has passed,'' Taichi Sakaiya, minister
of state at the Economic Planning Agency, said in a recent
interview in Tokyo. ``At least, there will be no further
deterioration.''
</P>
<P>
   What is different this time, though, is that the government is
battling the recession on many fronts. It is borrowing more heavily
to finance its spending, and it is cleaning up the banking system
to alleviate the credit shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The next sign of Japan's progress comes on Friday, when the
government releases its report on the gross domestic product for
the last quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Some good news, at least, has been wending its way from the
trenches. Orders for new homes are up. Some companies are
refocusing their businesses, while others are selling off products
that had been piling up in warehouses. Banks, which had slashed
their lending under the burden of hundreds of billions of dollars
in bad debts, are beginning to ease up on credit. Small company
stocks are aggressively rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sakaiya, however, has moderated his view from late last
year, when he said he saw a ``quickening'' in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have growth this year,'' said Sakaiya, the author
of 50 books, including some on the reshaping of Japanese society.
``Otherwise, in the scheme of history Japan will be heading into a
dark age if negative growth continues.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest stimulant has come from the government, which has
been pumping taxpayers' money into the construction of dams and
bridges and setting up lending programs throughout the country. In
a grand giveaway, the government is also passing out nearly $6
billion in shopping coupons, and there are some signs that the
coupons are encouraging consumers to spend more.
</P>
<P>
   Fumio Takahashi, for one, is beaming heartily under his hard
hat. Takahashi, a stocky man in a black suit, runs a small
construction company in Nakanojomachi, and he now has several new
government contracts. Those contracts, in turn, have enabled him to
borrow $400,000 from the bank.
</P>
<P>
   One of his main projects is a 37.5-yard stretch of road that he
is rebuilding and widening, even though the road already provides
an adequately smooth car ride. There is also a project to build a
31-yard river embankment and another to build 81 yards of a new
road to a dam. Other construction companies have been assigned
other segments of the roads and the embankment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were no public works, this company would be gone _
bankrupt,'' Takahashi said as he stood on his dug-up road just a
few steps away from a patch of road that a competitor is repaving.
``This area is very rural, and there are very few factories, so
there are very few jobs. If there is no construction work, we can't
make our living.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is great news for Takahashi and his 20 employees. But
there are doubts about whether Japan really needs all the wider
roads and longer embankments. Takahashi relies on the government
for 85 percent of his business, and critics say the contracts are
simply pork barrel projects created by the dominant Liberal
Democratic Party to reward contributors in the construction
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, perhaps one reason Nakanojomachi is so flush is not just
that it is needy but also that it is the hometown of Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi. Home constituencies of prime ministers have always
received a disproportionate share of construction spending.
</P>
<P>
   Takahashi acknowledges he is in an industry scoffed at
frequently for its inefficiency, but he points out that at least
the town has advanced from farming to construction. In any case, he
knows his company will not last forever, not even to the next
generation. His son has already said that he will not take over the
business and hopes instead to find a salaried job at a big company.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of private economists in Tokyo sound a bit more
positive than they did a few months ago, but then again they could
scarcely have become more negative. Many describe the huge
government stimulus package as having stabilized the economy rather
than revived it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're bouncing along the bottom a little instead of
being in a free fall as we were last year,'' said Peter Morgan, an
economist with HSBC Securities Japan Ltd. ``Things are starting to
stabilize a bit, but it's not a clear soaring upward momentum. It's
like a gigantic Band-Aid being put around the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Few officials and politicians are as bold about their
pronouncements on the economy as Sakaiya, Japan's top economic
official. Ichizo Ohara, a Parliament member and occasional adviser
to Obuchi, the prime minister, argues that Japan needs far more
money flowing around if it is to strengthen the banks and revive
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought the economy had bottomed out, Ohara, a
former top Finance Ministry official, said it had. But then he
reversed himself, reflecting the uncertainty among many experts as
they read the mixed signs.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are still falling, signaling deflation. Corporate profits
for this fiscal year, which ends March 31, are expected to be
dismal _ down nearly 25 percent on average from the previous year.
Just last week, the index of leading economic indicators turned
down, after two months of pointing upward.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese politicians and economists agree that this year will be
critical for the economy, mainly because the leadership is running
out of options. The government is spending so much on the stimulus
that its budget deficit is running near 10 percent of total
economic output and the national debt burden will soon exceed the
size of the $4 trillion economy.
</P>
<P>
   Many municipalities are already broke, and the government's
enormous fund-raising plans have sent shudders through the markets
over the past several months and are threatening its previously
pristine sovereign credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank, also has fewer
tricks left in its bag of policy tools, and bank officials
privately acknowledge that monetary policy will have limited
influence in the near future. Short-term interest rates already are
effectively zero.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly why some prominent advisers, foreign economists
and analysts are searching for solutions in a broad restructuring
of Japan Inc., and a move away from the traditional antidote of
paying for public works projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to create a society in which sound and creative
competition prevails,'' said Hirotaro Higuchi, chairman of the
Economic Strategy Council, a high-level advisory group set up by
Obuchi. ``I think it will come earlier than expected because the
change in perceptions has already started.''
</P>
<P>
   That strategy may hold promise, but it can be very threatening
to construction workers like Toshinobu Ichiba, a 37-year-old
foreman in Nakanojomachi, which has only 18,600 people. Ichiba has
been a cog in the construction industry of this picturesque
mountainous town, which has essentially been built up with
taxpayers' money. That money has paid for many of the roads and the
river banks, as well as a long cement tunnel through the mountains
and a suspension bridge that looks like a smaller version of the
Golden Gate Bridge spanning the entrance to San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun faded on his bridge project near a cliff on a recent
frosty day, Ichiba and his co-workers joked about how they had
nothing to do last spring. Now, Ichiba and his men are building a
bridge _ or rather, half of one. The government has only shelled
out the money for half of the bridge, so that is all they will
build for now. But they profess not to worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there will be work even if our company goes
bankrupt,'' Ichiba said.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely this kind of outlook that has led some analysts
to call for a radical turnaround in the way companies are managed.
The problem, they say, is that people do not feel enough of a sense
of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, however measured, some change is beginning to surface in
the corporate world. A number of Japanese companies are selling
less profitable business lines, as well as assets like buildings,
resort clubs and land. While mass layoffs are still taboo,
companies are edging unproductive workers off the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Some hope that Japan may be able to engineer a ``jobless
recovery,'' in which the economy can improve as companies melt the
fat from their payrolls and reposition their businesses to compete
more effectively. Still, while restructuring may improve Japan's
economy in the long run, the initial result may be the opposite.
The first consequence will be an increase in the number of the
unemployed, now 3 million, and perhaps more of the sense of unease
that usually leads workers here to save rather than spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface, people may be persuaded that the economy may
have hit the bottom, but the speed is slow,'' said Teizo Taya, an
economist at the Daiwa Institute of Research. ``How can you expect
a recovery of consumption when companies are busy restructuring
themselves?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
