<P>
   NTSB-BOEING (Seattle) _ The National Transportation Safety Board
is considering calling for extensive, costly modifications to most
Boeing 737s, the most widely used jetliner. The modifications
center around the planes' rudder control devices, which Boeing has
already extensively changed. But a draft NTSB report says more
equipment changes are needed, according to the Wall Street Journal,
quoting sources familiar with the report.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   LIBRARY-ARCHITECTS (Seattle) _ The chance to design Seattle's
$156 million new Central Library tantalizes world-renowned
architects. Among those attending a Q&AMP;A session Wednesday were
representatives from Moshe Safdie, Cesar Pelli, Architectonica and
several other hot international firms. ``It's an exceptionally
attractive project,'' said Joshua Ramus, a Rotterdam architect
whose firm recently designed the Jussieu university library in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Goldsmith. (Story will move in ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Executives at Alstom Esca, a
midsized Bellevue, Wash., software company, think they're ready for
the year 2000. The company, which makes energy management programs
for electrical utilities, has tweaked and tested its product.
Managers even plan to dispatch an employee to New Zealand on New
Year's Eve so they can watch the software's reaction to 2000 from a
country close to the international date line. The company's
president, Alain Steven, says he is confident his software won't be
afflicted by the millennium bug. But Steven has another worry:
lawsuits that could somehow ensnare his company if anything goes
wrong in the complex world of utilities for which he makes a small
part.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAA (Seattle) _ Stanford's quest for a national title
