<SLUG> BC-OBESITY-GENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTANT GENE IN MOUSE HOLDS PROMISE FOR WEIGHT CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eat all the fat you want and still stay slender?
</P>
<P>
   A mutant mouse can do it, and scientists report they have
tracked down the gene that makes it possible, raising the prospect
of new treatments for human obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. in Cambridge,
Mass. say that mice who harbor the mutant form of the gene they've
cloned don't become overweight even when they eat a high-fat diet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the mutant mice stayed at a healthy weight whether they
ate a spartan diet with only 9 percent fat, or pigged out on a
regimen larded with 42 percent fat. Genetically normal mice gained
plenty of weight on that diet.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Millennium hopes to make a drug with the same effect
as the mutation in the gene called mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   The mutant gene and the protein it makes are ``definitely an
inviting target'' for a drug the company hopes to develop as an
anti-obesity treatment, said Karen Moore, a Millennium researcher
who directed the research.
</P>
<P>
   However, she noted that it's too early to say whether this gene
provides a more promising path toward new weight-control treatments
than several other gene-based avenues the company is pursuing.
Other companies are also in hot pursuit of obesity-gene treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and her colleagues at Millennium describe the gene cloning
in an article in current Nature. In a companion article, scientists
from Stanford University and the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in
Boston report that they, too, have isolated the same gene _ but
show that it has a second, completely different function.
</P>
<P>
   John Duke-Cohan, a researcher in tumor immunology at
Dana-Farber, said that the mahogany gene's protein product, which
he and his collaborators call attractin, helps recruit defensive
molecules in the immune system to fight disease. He said it is
interesting but no longer terribly surprising that one gene and
protein can have very different roles. ``It's turning out now that
many proteins are multifunctional,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium team said that in normal mice with an intact
mahogany gene, consuming a high-fat diet leads to obesity, as one
would expect.
</P>
<P>
   But when the gene is mutant, or altered so that it produces an
abnormal protein, the mouse's mechanism of weight control gets
different signals, and the animal doesn't gain excess weight. How
this happens hasn't yet been determined, said Moore, but the
protein made by the mahogany gene serves as a signal-receiver on
cells that are involved in regulating the animal's weight.
</P>
<P>
   Humans also have the mahogany gene, but no one has found people
who have a mutation in that gene, as some mice do. Moore said it
should be possible to design a drug that would block the mahogany
signal-receiver in humans, mimicking the effect of the mahogany
mutation in mice, which keeps them lean.
</P>
<P>
   The isolation of the mahogany mutant comes five years after
scientists at Rockefeller University discovered a gene that causes
obesity in a certain strain of mice. Since then, universities and
biotech companies have been rapidly discovering other genes
involved in the complicated systems by which animals and humans
regulate weight and energy output.
</P>
<P>
   None of the discoveries has yet led to a novel weight-loss drug
approved for general use, though some are in early clinical trials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
