<HEADER>
A5574 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-CSUNWOM-LADN-(SLA     03-10 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CSUNWOM-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATADORS HAVE BIG-GAME EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Cal State Northridge women's basketball coach
Frozena Jerro wanted to, she could start five players with big-game
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's NCAA Tournament game at Colorado State (at 9 p.m.) will
be the first in school history, but it doesn't mean Northridge will
be intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Amari, Natalia Jonas, Jamilah Jones, Viveca Lof and Neda
Milic have played in high-pressure games with plenty at stake,
ranging from high school state championships (Jones) to junior
college state finals (Amari, Jonas), to club national championships
(Milic).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big difference,'' Milic said. ``It's very exciting.
So much is at stake right now. We're gonna go there and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Advantage, CSUN? The Matadors have plenty to worry about when
facing Colorado State, which features All-American point guard
Becky Hammon (22.6 points, 51 percent from the field).
</P>
<P>
   But one thing the tapes reveal is a height advantage for CSUN.
Expect to see plenty of posting up by Amari, Milic, Lof, Leah Rice
and Keisha Harris. Because of the height disadvantage, Jerro
expects Colorado State to play some zone defense, meaning the
Matadors will have to hit their outside shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be able to take what they give us, especially
from 10 to 12 feet,'' Jerro said. ``We can't afford to shoot in the
low 30s/high 20s (field goal percentage).''
</P>
<P>
   If Monday's practice is any indication, there won't be any
trouble there. In 45 seconds, Amari sank 11 of 12 3-pointers,
Harris hit 13 of 18 baseline jumpers, including 10 in a row in one
stretch, and Lof hit 9 of 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can hit them, no problem,'' said Harris, who never gets 18
shots in a game.
</P>
<P>
   But more important, Jerro said, Northridge must control the
tempo by doing the opposite of what Colorado State does.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me is if we start to turn the ball over, they can
score a bunch in a hurry,'' Jerro said. ``If they do, it will be
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Common opponents: Colorado State beat Weber State by seven
points. Northridge lost to Weber by 11 and won by 13.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State beat Portland State by 12 points. Northridge beat
the Vikings by 10, four and 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   __ On sale now: Tickets are available for the West Regional
March 20 and 22 at the Sports Arena. Three-game ticket packages are
available for $30 in the lower levels and $25 in the upper levels.
Youth packages are $12.
</P>
<P>
   The two semifinals will be March 20 at 7 p.m. and 9 p.m. The
final is March 22 at 9 p.m. The winner advances to the Final Four
in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA or Cal State Northridge win their first two tournament
games, they will play at the Sports Arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
