<HEADLINE>
U.S. CURBS LOW-FLIGHT TRAINING IN ITALY NEAR '98 SKI-LIFT DEATHS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American flight crews working temporarily at the
base in Aviano, Italy, are now prohibited from low-level training
flights like the one that hit a ski-gondola cable 13 months ago,
killing 20 people, the Pentagon said Wednesday in announcing plans
for a safety study in the wake of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Tapes of each training flight are routinely reviewed by
outsiders to make sure rules are followed, a Pentagon spokesman
said, but the military will not discuss other details, like whether
the map used by the pilot last year, which did not show the cable,
has been updated.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen has appointed Adm. Joseph W.
Prueher, the former commander in chief of the Pacific Command, to
review measures taken since the Marine Corps Prowler jet hit the
cable. The review is to take 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot was acquitted by a military jury last Thursday, a day
before Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema of Italy visited the White
House. President Clinton promised the review after international
outrage over the verdict. The Italians are to appoint an officer to
work with Prueher (pronounced PREE-er).
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman, Capt. Michael W. Doubleday of the Navy,
said that since the accident, Italian air traffic controllers have
been briefing crews before each flight, and low-level training
flights by American crews not permanently based in Aviano have been
banned. The Marine squadron involved in the cable accident was on a
six-month tour.
</P>
<P>
   New rules also require crews flying low-level missions ``to
initial that they have read all of the appropriate directives and
appropriate briefing materials,'' Doubleday said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenneth H. Bacon, another Pentagon spokesman, asked on
Friday about the chart the crew was using, which did not show the
lift cables, said, ``I'm not aware that a change has been made yet
in the map, but I really can't talk about that because that's the
subject of a different litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The court-martial disclosed other, deeper problems. For example,
the Marines were relying on an altimeter that may have been
disabled by the way they were flying the plane. Also, pilots fly
low-level missions so seldom that they cannot maintain proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps is planning to announce on Monday whether it
will also court-martial the Marine navigator, Capt. Joseph
Schweitzer, on the homicide and manslaughter charges on which the
pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of Marine Forces in the Atlantic,
under whose authority Ashby was court-martialed, will also announce
how the Corps will proceed with obstruction of justice charges
against both officers.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby testified during his trial, at Camp Lejeune, N.C., that
Schweitzer had made a videotape on an early part of the flight and
that after the emergency landing at Aviano, Ashby had stuck the
tape in a pocket and removed it from the plane. He said he gave the
tape to Schweitzer, but it was not clear from the testimony what
happened to it.
</P>
<P>
   Pace could decide on court-martials for each officer on the
obstruction charge, or could call for a less formal hearing, as
defense lawyers have suggested. Pace conducted such a hearing last
year for the commander of the Marine squadron and three other
officers, eventually relieving the squadron commander of his job
and officially reprimanding the squadron safety officer,
effectively ending his career. To date, these are the only
punishments for the incident.
</P>
<P>
   If Pace decides on a court-martial on the manslaughter and
homicide charges, it would take place before a new jury, but those
jurors would know about the result of the first trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Prowler they were flying has a single set of controls, which
were handled by Ashby, but Schweitzer was in charge of planning the
flight, including a check of maps and flight rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
