<HEADLINE>
YANKEES MANAGER TOREE HAS PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Joe Torre, 59-year-old manager of the world
champion New York Yankees, has been diagnosed with prostate cancer
and has left the team to begin treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The startling announcement was made at City of Palms Park
Wednesday, less than two hours before a split-squad Yankee team was
scheduled to play the Red Sox. In Bradenton, Fla., another squad of
Yankee players got the news as it prepared to play the Pittsburgh
Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   The team believes doctors caught the disease in its early
stages, and owner George Steinbrenner said he expects Torre back in
30 days _ which would be April 9, the day of the Yankees' home
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Torre learned of the diagnosis either Tuesday or early Wednesday
and did not travel with either team. He asked catcher Joe Girardi
to address the squad in Fort Myers and veteran outfielder Paul
O'Neill to tell the players in Bradenton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine,'' Torre said in a prepared statement, ``and I am
looking forward to taking care of this problem and getting back to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, who visited Torre at the manager's spring home in
Tampa and said he was in good spirits, said, ``Joe will handle this
situation with the same determination and courage that he has
always demonstrated. Our prayers are with him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how long he will be away from the
team, what his course of treatment will be, or where he will be
treated.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee players were shocked at the announcement, particularly
outfielder Darryl Strawberry, who Wednesday played his first game
since being diagnosed with colon cancer last October. Strawberry
was 1 for 4 against the Red Sox Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad day for all of us,'' said Strawberry. ``We're
devastated. We're definitely praying for him and his family. I pray
the whole process will go well for him.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a particularly difficult week for the New York
franchise. Hall of Famer Joe DiMaggio died Monday and now the team
is without its beloved manager as it prepares for the upcoming
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe treated me as well as a manager could,'' said Girardi.
``He's the reason I'm here from Day One. And Joe has kept me here.
He's meant a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no announcement regarding Torre's interim
replacement. Yankees hitting coach Chris Chambliss managed the team
that lost to the Red Sox, 6-1, Wednesday while former Yankees
manager Stump Merrill, now a special assistant to general manager
Brian Cashman, managed the other squad in Bradenton. Third base
coach Willie Randolph and pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre also are
expected to be part of a rotation of managers in Torre's absence.
In addition, former Red Sox skipper Don Zimmer, who is recovering
from knee surgery, is Torre's trusted bench coach and could be a
candidate for the interim position.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer is second only to lung cancer among cancer
killers of American men, taking about 40,000 lives annually. Most
prostate cancer happens sporadically; patients have no particular
family history of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   There were an estimated 179,300 new cases of prostate cancer in
the United States last year. More than 75 percent of all cases are
diagnosed in men older than 65. In the past 20 years, the survival
rate for all prostate cases, regardless of stage, has increased
from 67 percent to 93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Torre is the third prominent person in baseball to be diagnosed
with cancer this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta first baseman Andres Galarraga was diagnosed with a
cancerous tumor in his lower back and is undergoing chemotherapy.
He will miss the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Marlins third baseman Mike Lowell, a former Yankees
prospect, was diagnosed last month with testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Marv Levy, the former coach of the Buffalo Bills, underwent
surgery for prostate cancer during the 1995 NFL season and, at 70,
was back coaching within a month.
</P>
<P>
   The Torre family faced another medical crisis in 1996 when Joe's
brother Frank, also a former major leaguer, underwent a successful
heart transplant the night before Joe managed the Yankees in Game 6
of the World Series. Now the Yankee manager faces a battle of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
