<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD NEWS FOR TORRE SENDS YANKEES REELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Darryl Strawberry came off the field, got
himself a cup of water, and sat on the visitor's bench at City of
Palms Park. This was a big day for Straw, his first baseball game
since colon cancer ended his season during last October's American
League Division Series against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters gathered around Strawberry and asked questions about
his gallant bid to return to the majors. Suddenly, in front of the
dugout, a Yankee official said the club had an important statement.
None of the reporters around Strawberry moved. But then a sheet of
paper found its way to the Yankee bench and shocked reporters
started asking Strawberry about manager Joe Torre's bout with
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad day for all of us,'' said Strawberry. ``We're
devastated. We're definitely praying for him and his family. I pray
the whole process will go well for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer is democratic. It strikes rich and poor, large and small,
young and old, black and white. Sometimes it seems to find those
best able to spread the word on early detection. This is an
illogical and emotional theory _ one requiring faith in larger
forces _ but it's all we have when we try to explain how Joe Torre
could be diagnosed with cancer the same day Darryl Strawberry
begins a celebrated comeback from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are the best, fattest team in baseball. They won 125
games last year and Time magazine dubbed them the Greatest Team
Ever. They added future Hall of Famer Roger Clemens to the roster
this spring, which is like sending Cindy Crawford to work at the
Playboy Mansion. But now sorrow stalks the mighty Pinstripers
almost daily. Torre's news came just two days after the death of
Yankee Clipper Joe DiMaggio. Meanwhile, Yankee Hall of Famer
Catfish Hunter fights a battle with the degenerative disease named
after Yankee great Lou Gehrig. And Strawberry reminds himself to
stay out of the sun the day after his chemotherapy treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's legs are still weak. He's scheduled to have
treatments until May. The Yankees already have three left fielders
(Chad Curtis, Ricky Ledee, and Shane Spencer), plus a regular
designated hitter in Chili Davis. They may not need Strawberry, but
team owner George Steinbrenner generously renewed his contract for
$2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry faced Pedro Martinez in the second inning Wednesday,
got a nice ovation from the sellout crowd, then fanned on four
pitches. In the fourth, again against Pedro, Strawberry grounded
sharply to first baseman Bob Hamelin. He hit a bloop single to left
off Kirk Bullinger in the seventh, and hit into a fielder's choice
in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel blessed to be able to play again,'' said Strawberry.
``I'm thankful things have worked out well, but there are no
guarantees that you are going to recover as well as you think you
may. With me, it's not about the comeback. It's about the fight
against cancer. Coming back to play baseball is very easy for me.
Coming back to fight cancer is very difficult. I've got to fight
and I've got to be strong about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly devastating when it happens. How much can you take?
How much can a person take? We should go out and dedicate this
season to Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   While Strawberry spoke, Yankees catcher Joe Girardi sat at the
other end of the dugout. Torre had sought Girardi early Wednesday
in the Yankee clubhouse in Tampa and asked him to address the split
squad in Fort Myers. Then Girardi sat in silence at the front of
the bus for 2 1/2 hours, thinking about how he would break the news
to his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's the reason I'm here from Day One,'' said the catcher.
``Everyone loves Joe because Joe treats you the way you want to be
treated. He came to me and asked me to tell the guys on this trip
because we couldn't all be together.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Yankee squad played in Bradenton Wednesday against the
Pirates. Torre asked outfielder Paul O'Neill to speak to that
group.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's problem was discovered as part of routine physicals
given to all uniformed personnel each spring. Team officials said
he'd been unusually quiet in recent days, and senior advisor Arthur
Richman described Torre as ``lightheaded'' Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by the club, Torre said, ``I feel fine and
I am looking forward to taking care of this problem and getting
back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner said in a statement, ``Joe will handle this
situation with the same determination and courage that he has
always demonstrated. Our prayers are with him.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, the baseball world was gripped by the story of
Torre's brother, Frank Torre, who had a heart transplant prior to
Game 6 of the World Series against the Atlanta Braves. The Yankees
won the Series and the story of the Torre brothers, both former
major leaguers, was made into a television movie.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear who will manage the Yankees while Torre
undergoes treatment. Hitting coach Chris Chambliss managed the
squad at Fort Myers while coach Stump Merrill (a former Yankee
manager) did the chore in Bradenton. Torre's bench coach, former
Red Sox manager Don Zimmer, is recovering from arthroscopic knee
surgery, but could be a candidate to take over in Torre's absence.
Zimmer has been in baseball for more than 50 years and managed the
Red Sox in the memorable one-game playoff against the Yankees in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the world champs are reeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't ask why.'' said Strawberry. ``I don't think anyone
asks why this happened to me. You just have to fight it. It's a
battle. When you face cancer you don't know which way it's going to
go. I'm a survivor at this point, but there's no guarantee it won't
reoccur. So you just take life for today.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to see anyone else have to face this battle. But
every cancer patient and myself, we've got to have hope. Anybody
battling the disease, you want to applaud 'em. Joe's a good person.
He'll be able to help others. Joe's gonna be a real good spokesman
for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Richman, a loyal Yankee employee who has been in baseball for
more than a half century, sat in the dugout and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw Joe this morning,'' said Richman. ``This is
terrible. It just shows you. They talked about how we were going to
have everyone back from last year. And now this happens. You never
know. You just never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2018EST &QL; 
