<HEADLINE>
TWO NEW RELEASES LIVING OUT LOUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use  Friday, March 12  by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES &UR;  &LR; _ Two underappreciated films hit the video racks
next Tuesday _ Warren Beatty's politcal satire ``Bulworth'' and
screenwriter Richard LaGravenese's directing debut, ``Living Out
Loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, some thought that ``Bulworth'' would be an Oscar
contender, but mixed critical reviews and so-so box office put an
end to that. The film did pick up a screenwriting nomination for
Beatty and Jeremy Pikser.
</P>
<P>
   There were fewer ambitions for ``Living Out Loud,'' although
LaGravenese has gotten an Oscar nomination for ``The Fisher King''
and has written a number of other high-profile films, including
``The Horse Whisperer'' and ``The Bridges of Madison County.''
</P>
<P>
   What the two films have in common is that they are both about
getting to the truth in unusual ways.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty plays liberal California Sen. Jay Bulworth, who is in a
tough re-election fight. His life has become a sham. After years of
campaigning, he has repeated the same lines over and over so that
he can't tell the bull from the worthwhile anymore. Compounding
this, he has just lost millions in investments. After making a deal
with a corrupt lobbyist for a lot of life insurance, he puts out a
contract on himself in order to leave his daughter financially
secure.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking he has three days to live, Bulworth suddenly finds
himself liberated. On a campaign stop at an African-American church
in Los Angeles, he suddenly starts blurting out statements such as
that blacks will never have power within the establishment until
they've spent the money to buy it like whites do.
</P>
<P>
   That quickly gets him into hot water with his chief of staff
(Oliver Platt), but it picks him up some support from members of
the black community, including an attractive woman named Nina
(Halle Berry).
</P>
<P>
   A short while later, Bulworth is in Beverly Hills, insulting a
mostly Jewish audience of movie moguls and wondering why they
produce ``mostly crap'' and reasoning that it's the money. ``How
much money do you guys really need?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   What ensues ranges from the preposterous to the outrageous.
Beatty is almost as set as his alter ego on waking people up. But
the film probably came across as too risky for most people. Like
Bulworth's fictional audience, movie audiences weren't sure how to
react. Nevertheless, you rarely see filmmakers take chances like
Beatty did in this film, and it is a compliment to him that he
didn't play it safe. If you didn't see ``Bulworth'' in theaters,
take a chance on one of the most provocative films of 1998. If you
did see it and weren't sure about it, it's worth a second look.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Living Out Loud,'' Holly Hunter plays the newly dumped wife
of a high-powered and wealthy doctor, and Danny DeVito is the
elevator operator in her Manhattan high-rise apartment building.
They are an unlikely romantic couple, and LaGravenese uses
unconventional methods to unfold their story.
</P>
<P>
   Devastated by the divorce after 16 years of marriage, Judith
(Hunter) can't cope with life. ``What am I supposed to do with all
this information?'' she worries as she watches the news. And she is
apt to fantasize about a situation rather than act upon it. It
takes an unexpected moment _ she is kissed outside a club by a man
who thinks she's another woman _ to shake her from her lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   Pat (DeVito) has been thrown out by his wife after 25 years
because of his gambling debts, and his daughter, whom he adored,
has died. He refuses to work for a brother who owns a bar, clinging
to his independence, although all he has never followed through on
his grandiose plans.
</P>
<P>
   Before Judith and Pat can move on with their lives, they have to
find out the truth about who they are. And finding out is the joy
of this film.
</P>
<P>
   DeVito and Hunter turn in marvelous performances in
LaGravenese's cleverly plotted and delightful film. An added bonus
is Queen Latifah, who plays a singer in a nightclub Judith
frequents. She not only lights up the screen but does some classy
torch-song renditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
