<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY THEFT ACCUSED FAILED TO DISCLOSE FULL HOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN AND PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The former deputy treasurer who was charged this month
with stealing $2.4 million from a state fund failed to disclose in
government ethics filings his ownership of two pieces of real
estate, including a shopping mall in Ashland worth more than $7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Foley of Lexington declared last year in divorce
papers that he owned three rental properties, but he listed only
one on the annual financial disclosure statements he has filed with
the state Ethics Commission since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Foley made no reference on the statements to owning, through a
real estate trust, two income-producing properties in Ashland: the
shopping center and a multiunit house, which together generated
more than $200,000 a year in profits for him, according to divorce
papers he filed at Middlesex Probate Court. He did list a rental
property in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators have asked for Ethics Commission records on
Foley. If he is found guilty of failing to report ``material''
information, he could face three years in prison and a fine of up
to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gary L. Meyers, Foley's attorney, declined comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's office has charged Foley and three
others in connection with the theft of a total of $8.9 million from
the state's Unpaid Check Fund. On Tuesday, an investigator from the
office requested all of Foley's statements filed with the Ethics
Commission, as well as those of John F. Trischitta, another former
treasury employee charged in the thefts, and of Amelia Viscomi
Tamburrini, who worked with Foley at the treasury and is his
fiancee. She has not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Heffron, spokesman for Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly,
declined comment on the request.
</P>
<P>
   In divorce documents he filed in 1997 and 1998, Foley said he
owned three pieces of income-producing property, including a house
each in Framingham and Ashland and the shopping mall in Ashland in
the name of VLAR Realty Trust, which listed him as the sole
beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had purchased the mall, which has an assessed value
of $7.7 million, in 1989. In an income statement filed with the
divorce papers, Foley estimated he made a net profit of $315,692 in
1997 from the mall. In a separate document, his wife estimated
Foley's equity interest in the shopping mall at $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Foley also alleged in papers she filed in the divorce that
she believed that Robert Foley had made money from an interest in a
28-unit housing development in Holliston as well as from the sale
of a condominium in Quincy. Foley never made reference to owning
property in Holliston or Quincy in any of his government financial
disclosure statements.
</P>
</TEXT>
