<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE11-COX     03-10 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who can stop Duke?
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ For everyone billing the 1999 NCAA Basketball
Tournament as ``The Duke Invitational'' and labeling the No. 1 Blue
Devils (32-1) as unbeatable, coach Mike Krzyzewski and company have
a short response: UNLV, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Runnin' Rebels entered that tournament 34-0 and as the most
prohibitive favorites to win the national championship since the
end of the UCLA dynasty. The defending national champions had three
future NBA players _ Larry Johnson, Stacey Augmon, and Greg Anthony
_ and an average margin of victory of 27.3 points.
</P>
<P>
   But on March 30, 1991, the seemingly invincible team of Jerry
Tarkanian was upset 79-77 at the Final Four semifinals in
Indianapolis. The giant-killer was Duke, which went on to win the
title.
</P>
<P>
   In March Madness, unlike the NBA playoffs, one bad game and
you're on the way home. Doesn't matter if you're Duke or Florida
A&AMP;M, who plays the Blue Devils in Friday's East Regional at the
Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to pop in a tape of that (1991) Final Four to remind
my teammates that a loss can happen, I will,'' junior Chris
Carrawell said. ``It could happen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the cautionary tales. Here's the reality. Duke is
the most dominating college basketball team since that UNLV team,
and it would take a monumental collapse, a monumental performance
or both to keep the Blue Devils from cutting down the nets in St.
Petersburg on March 29. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Duke made a joke of the ACC's regular-season race, winning its
16 conference games by an average of 24.3 points. Then it ripped
through the ACC Tournament, winning by a record 25 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Since an eight-point win at Georgia Tech, Duke won its past
nine games by an average of 28.5 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only three of 32 victories have been in single digits. Duke
has won 13 games by 30 or more.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina coach Bill Guthridge certainly is convinced. On
Feb. 28, the Blue Devils handed his Tar Heels their worst defeat _
81-61 _ in 177 home games in the Dean E. Smith Center. One week
later, with All-ACC guard Trajan Langdon out with a sprained foot,
Duke again pounded UNC 96-73. It was the third-most-lopsided
championship game in ACC Tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a team that's such an odds-on favorite to win
the national championship,'' Guthridge said. ``They are head and
shoulders above everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   This Duke team is so talented that it is the only ACC squad to
place all five starters on first-, second- or third-team
all-conference squads. And freshman Corey Maggette was the
second-leading vote-getter for ACC rookie of the year. The
foundation for the team that could be the best in Blue Devil
history goes back a year, when Kentucky denied the Blue Devils
(32-4) a Final Four appearance. Trailing by 17 points with under 10
minutes to play, the Wildcats rallied to beat Duke 86-84 in the
South Regional final and went on to win the national championship.
The Blue Devils blew their big lead in that game because they
couldn't handle Kentucky's quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski solved that problem. William Avery took over at point
guard, giving Duke a player to run with the fastest guards in the
game and score. Maggette gave the Blue Devils an even greater
degree of athleticism. Those two changes, combined with the talent
on hand, have made the Duke team of 1999 look more like UNLV of the
early '90s than the talented, but methodical, units of the
Christian Laettner era of 1989-92.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has a more athletic team now that can attack you
offensively at all five positions,'' ESPN's Dick Vitale said. ``It
looks like a very special team.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland has been in the top five just about all season and, by
all accounts, has enough talent to get to the Final Four. The Terps
lost by 18 in both games against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a reflection of their coach,'' Maryland's Gary
Williams said of the Blue Devils. ``Each time they walk on the
court, they try to earn the right to win each game. When you have
that kind of attitude with the talent level they have, it's really
something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemson hung tough at Duke for about 15 minutes on Feb. 20. Down
32-30, the Blue Devils went on a 26-0 run and eventually won 92-65.
``Duke has a way of making you fall apart,'' Clemson coach Larry
Shyatt said. ``They play with a great deal of freedom and
fearlessness. They can put it on you on both ends of the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to run off a string of points without warning is the
thing that scares opponents most about Duke. ``They have a great
deal of confidence and are playing very uninhibited,'' Wake Forest
coach Dave Odom said. ``They don't get down about anything. It's
like they enjoy teams taking fast shots. Over the course of 40
minutes, a fast pace will lend itself to a streak of points.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Duke appeared poised for a letdown. They traveled
to Chicago to play DePaul's young, but talented, team. The Blue
Devils had their biggest rival, North Carolina, coming up on
Saturday. No one would have been surprised had they come out flat.
Instead, Duke had one of its most impressive outings of the season,
placing five players in double figures and mauling the Blue Demons
96-64.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're much scarier up close and personal than any tape could
ever describe,'' said Pat Kennedy, the DePaul coach. ``There's no
one competing on their level right now, including the Connecticuts
and the Michigan States and those folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Are there teams in the tournament that can beat Duke? Of course,
but the Blue Devils would have to have an off shooting night and
the opponent would have to do just about everything right.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cincinnati (26-5), the only team to beat Duke this season,
when it went the length of the court in the final seconds to win
77-75 in the Alaska Shootout. The Bearcats have the athletes but
have struggled of late, losing to UNC-Charlotte in the Conference
USA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   _ The No. 3 seed in the South Regional, St. John's (25-8) took
the Blue Devils to overtime before losing 92-88 in Madison Square
Garden on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   _ The No. 1 seed in the West, UConn (28-2) occupied the No. 1
ranking in those few weeks Duke did not. The Huskies have the
guards to handle Duke's pressure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kentucky (25-8), because the tournament-tough 'Cats will not
be intimidated by anybody.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michigan State (26-5), the No. 1 seed in the Midwest. The
Spartans lost to Duke 67-60 on Dec. 2 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski has not backed away from the praise. He concedes that
his team is playing against its own potential and its place in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the position we're in, most people will tell us how good
we are,'' Krzyzewski said. ``If we listen to that, we're fools. We
can be beaten by anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
