<HEADER>
A5587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-FIGHT11-COX     03-10 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis holds no terror for Holyfield
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The two boxers obliged promoters Wednesday, standing
in their cliched poses for photographers, with obligatory stares
and clenched fists.
</P>
<P>
   The staging wasn't much different from four months ago, when the
heavyweight title unification between Evander Holyfield and Lennox
Lewis was announced. The biggest difference then was that Holyfield
used the photo op as a communication op. He approached Lewis and
said, ``I'm going to put pressure on you from the time the bell
rings. I'm going to jump right on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield laughed when he thought about it now, saying, ``It
shocked him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shock or not, Holyfield's camp has not been shy about divulging
its fight plan for Lewis, who is three years younger (33), 23
pounds heavier (243, pending the weigh-in) and four-and-a-half
inches taller (6 feet 7) with a 6 1/2-inch reach advantage (84).
</P>
<P>
   Pressure. Work inside. Stay clear of Lewis's right hand and
counter his shots to the body and head with hooks and uppercuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be easier than the (Mike) Tyson fights,''
Holyfield trainer Don Turner said. ``(Contender) Lou Savarese said
to me, `Evander wins in five rounds.' I said, `What's the other
four for?'''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has shown little concern about Lewis. When he was
asked about comparisons between Lewis and Riddick Bowe, who beat
Holyfield twice, Holyfield said, ``Lennox doesn't fight like
Riddick Bowe. He's just a big guy. Kind of arrogant. He's what you
call proud. So proud. But I just know I'm gonna crush him. Clear as
day. And I'm not feeling bad about it, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Steward, Lewis' trainer, dismissed the brash
projections, and welcomed the planned attack. ``As far as I'm
concerned, that helps Lennox,'' Steward said. ``Everybody says
they're going to get in close to Lennox, but it's not that easy.
Bowe didn't have the physical strength of Lennox.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward then took a shot at Turner, saying, ``I don't think much
of him. What kind of trainer tells his fighter, `The guy you're
fighting can't fight.' He's riding the coattails of Evander's
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward said he believes Holyfield's attack pledge. The result,
he said, will be determined by how Lewis reacts. Steward said he
wants him to throw stiff jabs, ``the kind of jabs that do some
damage, not that pawing jab that he throws too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' also plans to try to tie up Holyfield often, grabbing by
the arms, shoulders and even neck, trying to use his size
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lennox wants to, he can grab Evander and throw him around
the ring,'' Steward said. ``Evander has no idea how strong this man
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield acknowledged that pressing the attack against Lewis
leaves open the possibility of getting hit by a right hand, but he
said, ``I wouldn't be the person I am if I didn't take chances. I'd
still be in the ghetto.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who has watched six of Lewis' fights on tape, echoed
those remarks. ``To be a great fighter, you have to be a great
gambler. You can't sit back and wait for the guy to do something.
He has to work hard to counterpunch a bigger guy. In close, you can
smother punches and counterpunch. It's hard to do that on the
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield will try to move in and out, similar to his fights
against Buster Douglas and Bowe II. Lewis has not handled
opponents' movement well in the past, Turner said, and poor balance
tends to offset his power. Turner also said that Lewis' perceived
lack of hand speed will make it easy for Holyfield to see the
punches coming, duck inside and counter with quick combinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most big guys, their power is everything,'' Holyfield said.
``When they can't hurt you with that, they're ordinary. Then they
start panicking. They can't handle pressure. Guys try to hit me all
the time. I'm used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he has any concern for Lewis' right hand, Holyfield
said, ``All heavyweights have a right hand. You just don't want to
get hit by it. I've always had the ability to see it coming. It's
not like I'm going to hold my head right there and say, `OK, hit me
with that big right hand.'''
</P>
<P>
   Steward said that people overstate Lewis' reliance on his right
and that he thinks the left hook is his best punch. He said he
wants Lewis to throw left hooks, set up by the jab, but he
conceded, ``Lennox hasn't done that enough in past fights.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield smiled when asked about Steward's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emanuel Steward is not going to take responsibility for Lennox
Lewis losing,'' he said. ``His whole thing will be, `Go out there
and jump on him.' Then when Lewis starts breaking into pieces he'll
say Lewis didn't follow the plan. He's not going to take the blame:
`I'm too good a coach to take the blame.' Lennox is gonna jump on
me, and I'm gonna battle, and as the battle goes on, Lennox will
think, `I cannot go past this.' And then he's going to get hit as
hard as he's ever been hit in his whole entire life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
