<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-MINORITIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT URGED TO HIRE MORE MINORITY LAW CLERKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Supreme Court justices Wednesday acknowledged
the high court's poor record of hiring minorities to be law clerks.
</P>
<P>
   But Justices Clarence Thomas and David H. Souter placed the
blame squarely on law schools and lower court judges for failing to
move qualified applicants up the judicial employment pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The paucity of minorities among the justices' law clerks came to
national attention last March when USA Today conducted a study that
found only 1.8 percent of the most recent 394 clerks were black, 1
percent were Hispanic and 4.5 percent were Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, was arrested and held briefly in
October for protesting _ on the steps of the Supreme Court _ the
justices' lack of minority clerks.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before a House panel, Thomas and Souter said that they
and their colleagues would like to hire more minorities to be
clerks, the recently minted lawyers who help the justices decide
cases, but that the pool of applicants is limited. Justices seek
clerks who graduated near the top of their law school classes and
who have clerked for a federal judge, prerequisites not too many
minority lawyers have satisfied, Thomas and Souter told a House
Appropriations subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a person at the court who would not want to
change that'' low number of minority clerks, Thomas said. ``They
would love to see more minorities at the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Thomas, Souter said, ``There's no one on this Supreme
Court who does not want these numbers to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter and Thomas appeared before the Subcommittee on Commerce,
Justice, State and Judiciary to urge Cngress to appropriate $58.6
million for the high court in fiscal year 2000, which begins Oct.
1. But they were quickly called upon to defend the court's hiring
practices when Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif, a subcommittee member,
told the justices that they and their colleagues have not looked
hard enough for minority clerks.
</P>
<P>
   Souter responded with a defense of the justices' system of
hiring experienced clerks and said he is confident the high court's
employment record will improve soon as law schools continue to make
a strong effort to push their brightest minority students to seek
judicial clerkships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that shoving (by law schools) is going to take
place, and that it's going to show up in our hiring,'' Souter told
the Subcommittee on Commerce, Justice, State and Judiciary. ``We're
going to see the fruit of some pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dixon said that perhaps an ``ol' boy network'' exists on the
court that discourages the hiring of minorities. Dixon added that
justices have chosen their clerks largely from Ivy League law
schools like Harvard and Yale and not from other highly respected
but less known universities with a greater number of minority
students.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Souter and Thomas conceded that the justices' law
clerks generally do come from top-flight schools. But the justices
said they and their colleagues look to the most respected
universities only because they must have confidence that their
clerks will be ready to perform well from their first day on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clerks are not trainees,'' Souter said, noting their
important work in helping craft Supreme Court decisions. ``There is
no break-in period.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said justices ``can't take chances'' that the clerks they
choose will not be up to the intense research, concise writing and
vigorous legal debate that are the hallmarks of assisting a Supreme
Court justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (justices) all live with the fear that we will have a clerk
that doesn't work out,'' Thomas said. ``There is no start-up
period. They have to be up and running.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dixon was not persuaded by the justices' defense, saying
that minority lawyers ``can hit the ground running'' at the Supreme
Court. Dixon urged the justices to ``look to alternative methods''
for choosing law clerks and not simply rely on elite schools and
lower court judges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
