u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAPPEN-DOCTORS-BOS &LR;      03-10 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAPPEN-DOCTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD DEFENSE DOCTOR'S FEE IN DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM AND DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Roiled by conflicting accounts of how much a key expert
was paid by the defense team, the tempest continued Wednesday over
Sunday night's ``60 Minutes'' report, which raised questions about
the cause of eight-month-old Matthew Eappen's death.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another twist in the case, ``60 Minutes'' reporter Mike
Wallace said that Dr. Marvin Nelson told him Wednesday he was paid
a total of $1,000 by the defense team rather than the $300 Nelson
initially acknowledged receiving. Nelson was one of two experts
whom the program relied upon for the theory that the infant had
died from strangulation, rather than from being violently shaken.
</P>
<P>
   But Woodward's defense team disputed the new figure of $1,000,
insisting that Nelson was paid only $700. Nelson did not respond to
requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scores of doctors released a strongly-worded
statement refuting the claims by Dr. Floyd Gilles and Nelson, both
of Children's Hospital in Los Angeles, that the infant had been
strangled up to 48 hours before he died. The letter, sent to CBS
and other media outlets, labeled the theory ``preposterous,'' and
called for both the network and the doctors to apologize to Deborah
and Sunil Eappen, the infant's parents.
</P>
<P>
   The network's reaction was far from contrite, however. Wallace
called the letter ``old hash.''
</P>
<P>
   The continued controversy exposed nerves never far from the
surface since Woodward's frantic 911 call two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997 a jury found Woodward guilty of second-degree
murder, agreeing with prosecutors' claims that she killed Matthew
Eappen by violently shaking him, and slamming his head against a
hard object. Woodward was set free after Judge Hiller B. Zobel
overrode the jury's decision, reducing her conviction to
manslaughter and sentencing her to the 279 days she had already
served.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's ``60 Minutes'' report raised questions even about that
conviction, suggesting that the baby could have died from a
strangulation that took place up to 48 hours before he died, but
which did not have any visible effect until the baby began seizing
under Woodward's care.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Nelson, one of the proponents of the
strangulation theory, had been paid more than originally thought
for his 1997 services to the defense team had Wallace rethinking
the presentation of the doctor on Sunday night's segment.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he now wishes he had mentioned the defense team's
payment to Nelson during the ``60 Minutes'' broadcast, though he
reiterated his belief that the payment did not influence the
doctor's judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I known about it, I would have said something about a paid
consultant,'' said Wallace. ``However, I would have appended to
that the fact that both (Dr. Floyd) Gilles and Nelson disagreed
with the defense team's theory of the reasons for the death.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he learned of the higher sum when he called Nelson
Wednesday. According to Wallace, the doctor told him he was paid
$700 for a two-hour telephone consultation with defense attorney
Barry Scheck three weeks before Woodward's murder trial began in
September 1997. The payment also covered Nelson's examination of CT
scans and other medical records at the request of the defense.
(Though the defense team contacted him as a prospective expert
witness, Nelson did not testify in the trial.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Wallace said, Nelson told him he was paid an
additional $300 from Elaine Whitfield-Sharp, then a member of the
defense team, after Sharp visited him at Children's Hospital in Los
Angeles to discuss the case in February 1998. But Sharp denied
making that additional payment of $300. Defense attorneys Harvey
Silverglate and Andrew Good said they did not make an additional
payment, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no knowledge of that (second) meeting, we have no
knowledge of a $300 payment,'' said Woodward defense lawyer Andrew
Good. ``Barry (Scheck) didn't pay anybody either. I don't think the
$300 happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ``60 Minutes'' report prompted a censorious
letter Wednesday to CBS and other media outlets signed by 77 child
abuse, neuropathology, and forensic specialists from Massachusetts
to California condemning the strangulation claims. Many of the
doctors named in the letter had also signed a 1997 letter attacking
the defense's theory that Eappen had died of old injuries sustained
while he was not in Woodward's care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory that (Matthew Eappen) sustained an injury that
would lead to his death and then appear normal for two days is
preposterous (and) not supported by the medical literature,'' the
letter said. The strangulation theory did not account for the
infant's severe head injuries, either, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of people have very strong feelings about this case
because the family has suffered so much,'' said Dr. Carol Jenny,
professor of pediatrics at Brown University Medical School. ``We
felt it was only fair that we counter what we believe to be
misinformation in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter concluded by calling on CBS, and the doctors, to
apologize to the Eappens. ``Once again the Eappen family has been
revictimized by the media and by Louise Woodward,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson and Gilles refused comment on the letter Wednesday.
``Their view is that everybody is entitled to their opinions,''
said Children's Hospital spokesperson Steve Rutledge. ``As long as
it's an informed opinion based on examining the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace suggested the physicians had not seen enough of the
medical evidence to arrive at their conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not unexpected,'' he said. ``What are they going to
say, `We were wrong, we were wrong'? If someone will assemble a
dozen senior pediatric neuropathologists, get them to sit down with
the medical evidence and let them write a letter, then we'll begin
to pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the new theory will be tested in a
courtoom. ``We want to investigate this as any responsible, ethical
lawyer would, with a view to seeing what the investigation shows,''
said Good. ``Then you decide what to do. What we want to do is get
to the facts. This may lead to the truth. At this point, going back
to court is hypothetical.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-producer Katie Leishman, who originated the story for ``60
Minutes,'' sharply denied a Boston Herald report in which Dr.
Umberto De Girolami, a prosecution witness, asserted that she had
called him the day before the ``60 Minutes'' segment and asked for
a written endorsement of the strangulation theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' she said. ``I never asked Dr. De Girolami to
endorse anything.'' What she was seeking on Saturday, Leishman
said, was permission to use a De Girolami quote on a different
scientific matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
