<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIMLER-NISSAN-NYT &LR;      03-10 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-NISSAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER ABANDONS TALKS ABOUT BUYING CONTROL OF NISSAN
MOTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Japan, England, Switzerland)  (See also NISSAN-ASSESS) 
(DW) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ DaimlerChrysler AG abruptly broke off negotiations
Wednesday to acquire a controlling stake in Nissan Motor, Japan's
huge and deeply troubled auto manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which came after face-to-face negotiations in
Tokyo between the chairmen of the companies, is a big setback for
Nissan's increasingly desperate search for a partner that could
help it dig out from more than $20 billion in debt and six years of
losses.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether DaimlerChrysler's withdrawal signals a
victory for Renault SA, the French automobile manufacturer that is
the only other company still openly interested in buying a
significant stake in Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, most industry executives had considered Renault
the underdog as Nissan carried on parallel negotiations with
Renault and Daimler.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the suddenness and apparent finality of DaimlerChrysler's
decision highlighted the serious risks for any potential partner.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Schrempp, DaimlerChrysler's chairman, has said he wanted
to increase Daimler's revenue from Asia, which is minimal now, to
about 25 percent of its total sales. Yet Wednesday he made it clear
that Nissan was too risky a bet and that he was not simply holding
out for concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to accept that the opportunities that a close
relationship with Nissan offer are not achievable as quickly and
smoothly as initially expected,'' he said in a brief statement.
After what he called ``intensive negotiations'' with Nissan's
president, Yoshikazu Hanawa, Schrempp said the companies had
``finally decided not to pursue a participation.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks said Nissan did not object to giving
up what would have been a controlling stake. Daimler executives
were worried about Nissan's suffocating debt load and what they
judged to be the absence of any real revamping plan. Hanging over
everything else was Japan's recession, which has crippled Nissan's
home market.
</P>
<P>
   For Nissan and for Japan, the stakes are huge. Nissan employs
more than 200,000 people and is one of Japan's biggest companies.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler apparently was close to making a formal offer
when Schrempp flew to Tokyo on Tuesday for talks. Nissan's debt
problems were a big topic. Nissan had, however, prepared a broad
plan to rework its debt in a way that would have reduced Daimler's
exposure, and one person close to the talks said that the debt
problem had not been insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Other executives said that Daimler retained doubts about
Nissan's strategy for a revamping. Because Daimler is still in the
early stages of integrating its operations with those of Chrysler,
which it acquired a few months ago, company executives said they
became worried about the need to divert top managers away from
Chrysler and toward Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have emphasized that the integration of Daimler and
Chrysler has utmost priority in our current business activities,''
Schrempp said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Klein, a spokesman for DaimlerChrysler, said his company
did not want to jump into additional acquisitions simply because
the opportunity had arisen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not just in the megamerger business,'' Klein said.
``Size is one thing, but the other thing is to have profitable
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted calmly to the announcement, and
DaimlerChrysler stock moved little in early trading Wednesday.
Analysts generally were relieved that Schrempp had decided not to
go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nissan has heavy debts,'' said Klaus-Juergen Melzner,
automobile analyst at Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt. ``In addition,
there are risks that you do not find on the balance sheet _ heavy
debts in the retailing system, for instance.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lawson, automobile analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in
London, said Daimler's retreat was welcome. ``It's positive that
the company has not simply plowed straight ahead here with an
acquisition that might have been premature,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's abrupt announcement was a particularly
embarrassing setback for Nissan because it came the same day that
Nissan tried to remove one of the sticking points to a deal. Nissan
and its affiliate, Nissan Diesel, announced that they would
together pay 40 billion yen (about $330 million), to retire most of
the debts of their joint venture in truck marketing, Nissan Diesel
Sales.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion over who was responsible for the debts of Nissan
Diesel Sales had been a point of contention between Nissan and
DaimlerChrysler. Scott Sprinzen, the managing director of auto
ratings at Standard &AMP; Poor's, the credit rating agency, said that
the friction over Nissan Diesel Sales showed why DaimlerChrysler
was wary of investing in Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly see why a company like DaimlerChrysler would be
very cautious in the way they would go about a potential
combination with a company like Nissan, given its various
obligations to affiliates, direct and indirect, visible and not so
visible,'' Sprinzen said.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, Daimler's announcement surprised most of the
automobile executives attending the annual car show. Rumors have
been flying for weeks that Nissan was close to a deal with Daimler,
and the Japanese press has reported on at least one occasion that
they two had reached an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   At Renault, executives greeted Wednesday's news with caution.
Louis Schweizer, Renault's chief executive, said he continued to be
in discussions with Nissan but emphasized that Renault had not yet
made a formal offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clear view of the potential synergies, and we have a
clear view of the difficulties,'' Schweizer said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a rush of recent automobile mergers and rampant
flirtation between many other companies, no other manufacturer is
expressing interest in Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co., which still has a big cash reserve despite its
recent agreement to acquire the auto business of Volvo AB for $6.5
billion, already controls Mazda in Japan. Volkswagen AG of Germany,
which recently bought Rolls-Royce Motor Cars and is on the prowl
for other deals, is more interested in luxury brands like BMW AG of
Bavaria. The other big Japanese companies, Toyota Motor and Honda
Motor, do not want to be dragged down by Nissan's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry executives say Renault may have stronger
incentives than Daimler for teaming with Nissan. In contrast to
Schrempp, Schweizer has not been pushing for full management
control.
</P>
<P>
   Renault, which produces about two million cars a year, badly
needs to expand its geographic range and product offerings. After
losing about 5.5 billion francs, or about $1 billion in 1996,
Renault bounced back with vehicles like its Scenic minivan and
earned 8.8 billion francs last year.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts say Renault needs to be bigger to match the
economies of scale enjoyed by companies like DaimlerChrysler or
even Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   Renault also remains overwhelmingly dependent on the European
market, particularly France, and is largely confined to midprice
and low-price vehicles, where price competition has been fierce.
</P>
<P>
   An alliance with Nissan, Japan's second-largest car company
after Toyota, could catapult Renault into both the Asian and U. S.
markets. Nissan also has a strong business in light trucks and
sport utility vehicles, areas where Renault is weak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
