A5592 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMING-LOTTERY     03-10 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMING-LOTTERY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery operator Powerhouse sold
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Powerhouse Technologies, the nation's second-largest lottery
operator, has reached a $280 million deal to be acquired by Anchor
Gaming of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Powerhouse, which is based near Perimeter Mall, makes software
and other equipment for online lotteries, video lotteries and
parimutuel systems in the U.S., Canada, Australia, South America,
Europe and the Caribbean. It owns and operates Sunland Racetrack
and Casino in New Mexico and also has manufacturing operations in
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us great access to capital,'' Powerhouse Chief
Financial Officer Susan Carstensen said. ``Combined, the company is
in a great position to compete in the gaming industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors liked the deal. Powerhouse shares rose $3.06 1/4 to
$17.87 1/2. Shares of Anchor Gaming closed at $38.37 1/2, up $3.81
1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Gaming said it will pay cash totaling $220 million, or
$19.50 a share. The offer is a 32 percent premium to Powerhouse's
closing price Monday. Anchor also will assume about $60 million of
Powerhouse debt.
</P>
<P>
   Todd D. Jordan, an analyst with Raymond James in New York, said
the deal was significant because it gives Anchor an entry into the
online lottery business and ``stable revenue streams from
businesses within the gaming industry.'' Powerhouse is No. 2 behind
Gtech Holdings Inc., the world's largest lottery operator.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor is a major player in the gaming equipment and service
businesses, which is a $1.5 billion to $2 billion industry. The
company operates and develops gaming machines and casinos.
</P>
<P>
   For the year ended June 30, Anchor earned $68.4 million, or
$5.20 a share, on revenues of $231.9 million. For the year ended
Dec. 31, Powerhouse earned $4.6 million, or 42 cents a diluted
share, on revenues of $201.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical point to make is that Powerhouse has great
technology and has done well in terms of being efficient,'' Jordan
said. ``The issue is that they didn't have the capital to really be
aggressive in bidding on contracts. The larger states were out of
their reach.''
</P>
<P>
   With this deal, however, that changes.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Chief Executive Officer Michael Rumbolz said the new
company plans to bid on 10 state lottery contracts within the next
two years. The company will change its name to Anchor Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Powerhouse has about 1,600 employee, 20 of whom are
based in Atlanta. Anchor has about 1,200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Powerhouse Chairman Richard Burt and Chief Executive Richard
Haddrill will join Anchor's board.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close in July.
</P>
<P>
   Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
