<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MICCICHE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.J. MICCICHE, GLOBE VETERAN, FILLED MANY NEWSROOM ROLES; AT 71 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Salvatore J. Micciche, a ``classic Boston
newspaperman'' who was a longtime reporter and later in-house
newsroom counsel at The Boston Globe, died Wednesday in his home in
Naples, Fla. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Micciche combined a keen sense of news, gleaned from years
as a local reporter on general assignment and in government halls
on Beacon Hill and Washington, with his law degree to give the
Globe an invaluable resource in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   His office was in the newsroom, which made it easy for reporters
and editors, all of whom called him ``Sal,'' to drop by and consult
on breaking stories that needed a legal eye cast over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sal was a most gifted journalist who earned a law degree on
the side,'' said retired Globe editor Thomas Winship. ``His only
trouble was that he couldn't leave the newsroom, where he practiced
both skills in a most valuable way. He had about the best political
antennae in Boston. And Loyalty was his middle name.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Micciche was born in Everett. He graduated from Everett High
School in 1945 and Boston University in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   He began his newspaper career at age 12 as a copy boy at the
Everett News Gazette. He later became that paper's city hall
reporter before joining the writing staff of Stars and Stripes
while serving in the Army during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the service, he reported for the Portsmouth (N.H.)
Herald, then came to the Globe in 1955. From 1956 to 1969 he
covered the Legislature. While at the State House he decided there
was more to learn about the legislative process. He studied nights
at Suffolk Law School, graduated in 1968 and passed the bar the
same year. He was 40.
</P>
<P>
   After a year writing on politics for the editorial pages, Mr.
Micciche was assigned to the Globe's Washington bureau, where he
covered Congress, the Supreme Court, and the White House during the
dramatic days of the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sal had a wonderful career as a reporter and editor,''
Benjamin B. Taylor, publisher of the Globe, said Wednesday, ``but
first and foremost he was a terrific reporter. His coverage of the
Supreme Court and the constitutional issues during Watergate was as
good as anyone's in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Micciche returned to Boston in 1975, serving in a number of
key newsroom positions where his journalistic, administrative, and
legal enterprise made a difference because he was always there, at
the ready with advice and counsel. He retired a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a profile published in the March 1986 issue of Presstime, the
journal of the American Newspaper Publishers Association, wherein
he was dubbed a ``classic Boston newspaperman,'' Mr. Micciche said
he witnessed many changes during his career, the most important
being a change in attitudes about ethics. When he began, he said,
``ethics was simply a word to be applied to others. The story was
the thing and there wasn't too much concern over how you got it. I
think that's pretty much changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, William O. Taylor, retired publisher of the Globe,
eulogized him as ``one of the legendary figures who worked for the
Globe for many years, from Washington Street to Morrissey
Boulevard. His skill as an editor, his warm personality, and
wonderful sense of humor made him a role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Micciche leaves his wife, Theresa (Miraglia); a son,
Charles; two daughters, Marcia and Marlene; and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5596 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TRIP-BOS &LR;      03-10 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ACKNOWLEDGES PAST US ROLE IN GUATEMALA   CIVIL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY _ Acknowledging the US role in Guatemala's civil
war and in repression by military-backed governments, President
Clinton pledged Wednesday that Washington would never again engage
in such behavior toward this Central American nation.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks, which contrasted with routine denials during the
Reagan administration, came before community activists in his last
stop on a four-nation tour of Central America.
</P>
<P>
   In ad-libbed opening comments, the president said US support of
right-wing governments in that Guatemala's 30-year civil war was
``wrong.'' In a report released last month, a UN-sponsored truth
commission blamed most of the 200,000 deaths and disappearances in
that conflict on the US-backed army and on the CIA, deeply involved
in Guatemala since fomenting an overthrow of the constitutional
government in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the United States, it is important that I state clearly
that support for miliitary forces or intelligence units which
engaged in violent and widespread repression of the kind described
in the report was wrong, and the United States must not repeat that
mistake,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must and we will, instead, continue to support the peace
and reconciliation process in Guatemala.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict ended when peace accords were signed in 1996 _ and
Clinton lauded the country for the progress it has made since the
end of the war.
</P>
<P>
   His comments concluded a day in which he promised to help the
region's fledgling democracies, fight for enhanced trade benefits
and restore fairness to immigration US laws for Central Americans.
</P>
<P>
   When asked later whether the president's statement was
tantamount to an apology, National Secirity Adviser Sandy Berger
said, ``I think the words speak for themselves. The president was
saying that some of America's activities during the war and that
period were wrong. . . . The words were pretty clear.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials traveling with Clinton said Washington provided
4,000 pages of information, some of it previously classified, to
the UN truth commission, and spent more than $1 million to help pay
for the group's work. Documents released Wednesday detail ties
between the CIA in equipping and training the Guatemalan security
forces that murdered thousands of civilians in the nation's bloody
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights officials say Clinton has the same responsibility
to unearth and acknowledge deep Cold War secrets as did the Soviet
Union when it disclosed its past. They gave some credit to Clinton
but said such disclosures of US ties to death squads were long
overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reagan administration consistently denied that the
Guatemalan and El Salvadoran armies were behind the death squads,''
said Josh Rubenstein, northeast regional director, Amnesty
International USA. ``Everyone understands today that such a claim
was a deliberate lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the United States provided financial and documentary
support (to the UN commission), but I have no doubt that
considerably more documents in US archives substantiate the degree
of American complicity,'' Rubenstein said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged that Central Americans consider Washington ``a
partner, a friend.'' But in a reminder of the bitter past, 200-300
demonstrators stood outside Guatemala's presidential palace to
denounce US involvement in civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was mostly peaceful but a small group of students
was arrested when they set two American flags on fire. They were
removed before the president arrived in Guatemala from El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to former rightist and leftist combatants in El
Salvador _ now sitting together in the nation's 84-member
legislative assembly _ Clinton sounded the same theme of promise
following conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a region where battlefield ideology has been
transformed into a marketplace of ideas,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted El Salvador's own evolution from 12 years of
bloody civil war by aknowledging the country's own presidential
elections -- the third since the war ended in 1992 -- which were
held on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would've been unthinkable that a United States president
would come to El Salvador after an election given the conflict that
we were involved in,'' said Francisco Flores, the president-elect
who met briefly with Clinton Wednesday and attended the speech.
``Democracy is here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated requests this week from Salvadoran officials
for special migratory status for their citizens in the United
States, Clinton defended US immigration policy.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal immigration, he said, ``punishes hard-working people who
play by the rules and who wait their turn to come to the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   But because past political conflicts had influenced US policy
since the Cold War, Clinton pledged to work to develop more
balanced rules for all Central Americans. Aides said some changes
can be made without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our treatment of people from Central America should reflect
what they suffered rather than who caused the suffering,'' he
added. ``This is wrong and we should change it.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to requests for more free trade with the United
States, the president also said he would push for enhanced trade
benefits with the region to remove tariffs on textiles and apparel
products that are produced in El Salvador and sold in the United
States. US officials also signed a bilateral agreement Wednesday to
promote American exports in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Sorto, an economist with the Foundation for Salvadoran
Economic and Social Development, said both measures were important
for helping the country's economy, which has been hurt by
decreasing international aid and the destruction brought on by
natural disasters such as last fall's Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our exports are in clothing and textiles and sold in
the United States,'' Sorto said. ``This could only lead to a
stronger Salvadoran economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction of Clinton, Juan Duch Martinez, president of
the assembly, said that despite recent economic and political gains
seen in El Salvador, the country remained in the ``midst of
adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also asked the president to impress upon congress that
Salvadorans are leaving the country to escape economic hardship and
the widespread destruction left by the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take your presence here as a gesture from a friend,''
Martinez said to Clinton during the ceremony at the assembly's main
chamber, or Blue Room. ``We trust in your work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
