<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winthrop revived by its Marshall plan
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The sweet ride began last April 2 in Rock Hill,
S.C. Just before his introductory news conference as the new head
basketball coach at Winthrop University, Gregg Marshall addressed
his new players thusly: ``Those of you who don't believe we can get
to the NCAA Tournament next spring, don't follow me into this press
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly,'' point guard Tyson Waterman recalled, ``I thought
he was bananas.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't this Winthrop? Hadn't the Eagles just ended 7-20, their
eighth losing season in a row? In the last 14 years, they never
even finished in the top half of the Big South Conference. Now this
35-year-old, a rookie head coach, was talking about the NCAAs?
</P>
<P>
   ``My first three years here, every loss hurt,'' said Heson
Groves, the senior forward from Powder Springs and Marietta High
who was in constant pain during a 26-54 migraine. ``I was ready to
try anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months after Marshall's ultimatum, this school, once a
women's college, is going bananas. While the sweet ride surely ends
here today, Winthrop is still the sweetest 16th seed in the NCAA
Tournament. The Eagles, 21-7 and the Big South regular-season and
tournament champs, play top-seeded Auburn in the first round of the
NCAA South Region. In Winthrop's first NCAA Tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hasn't hit me,'' Waterman said. ``We haven't had time
to sit down and say, `Wow! We won the Big South, which has never
been done in Winthrop's history.' Hopefully,we can do something now
that's never been done on the national level.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the NCAA field expanded to 64 teams in 1985, a 16th seed
never has beaten a No. 1. That 0-56 futility doesn't faze Marshall.
``We were picked dead last (in a preseason Big South poll),'' he
said. ``We finished first. We're here. This is reality, and we're
going to go out and play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every team that is here has earned the right to be
here. They deserve that respect,'' said Cliff Ellis, who coached
Auburn to its first NCAA since 1988. Despite losing to Kentucky in
the SEC semifinals, the Tigers (27-3) are still a No. 1 seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what'll happen,'' Ellis said. ``I know Winthrop's
going to come out and play , and I'd hope our team will come out
and play with a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight years as an aide to John Kresse at the College of
Charleston and two more at Marshall, Marshall got the Winthrop job
and set about assembling a team. He found 6-foot-6 center Eric
Fisher, a high school teammate of Kevin Garnett of the Minnesota
Timberwolves, in a pickup game on campus. Jeff Meyer, now
Marshall's assistant, first saw 6-foot-9 Eyo ``Bubbles'' Effiong
play in his native Nigeria in 1995; Meyer finally reconnected with
Bubbles last year via e-mail while Effiong was living with an uncle
in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   Waterman had played two years at Winthrop before he was
suspended in 1997 over academics and transferred to Winston-Salem
State. But Waterman pleaded with Marshall to take him back; he was
tutored by the coach's wife all summer to regain his eligibility
and, like Groves, made first-team All-Big South.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance jumped from last year's average of 793 to more than
1,300.
</P>
<P>
   Groves, Winthrop's top scorer (12.3) and rebounder (7.6), had 19
rebounds and Waterman had 25 points in an 86-74 win vs. Radford in
the Big South title game on Feb. 27, Marshall's 36th birthday. So
what if oddsmaker Danny Sheridan has made Winthrop 1 trillion-to-1
to win the NCAAs? So what if Auburn beat Winthrop 80-55 three
seasons ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here to roll over, and I don't think my players
did,'' Marshall said. ``We came here to play as hard as possible.
If they didn't think this game was necessary, they'd give the No. 1
seeds a bye.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
