<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5608 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS     03-10 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWS SEEK TO KEEP DONATED ORGANS IN STATE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wis., La., Okla., S.C., Fla., Texas)  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT18 and NYT19 _ are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The battle over the nation's scarcest medical
resource, human organs, has moved from Washington to the states,
where a number of legislatures have begun passing laws that would
bar donated hearts, lungs, kidneys, livers and pancreases from
being shipped beyond their borders to sick people elsewhere in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the laws have not had a large effect on the way organs
are distributed. Rather, they are intended to thwart an effort by
the Clinton administration to force organ recovery networks and
transplant centers around the nation to share their precious organs
more liberally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They changed the rule, so I introduced legislation,'' Gov.
Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin explained in a telephone interview
Tuesday. ``In this state, we go out and aggressively encourage
people to be donors, with me doing public service announcements. If
I'm going to do that, I want those organs to stay in the state and
take care of the patients that need it in Wisconsin.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other states _ Louisiana, Oklahoma, South Carolina and
Florida _ have adopted laws similar to Wisconsin's. In Arizona,
lawmakers in both houses have approved similar bills, but the bills
contain differences that must be ironed out. Legislation was also
introduced in Texas last week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 61,000 Americans are now waiting for organ
transplants, but only 20,000 or so transplants are performed each
year, and there are huge disparities in waiting times across the
country. Last spring, Donna Shalala, the secretary of Health and
Human Services, announced her intention to even out those waiting
times by giving organs to those who need them most, regardless of
where they live. But the plan, issued in the form of a federal
regulation, engendered such a bitter fight between transplant
doctors, hospitals and patients that Congress delayed its effective
date until Oct. 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debate will come to the fore in Washington on Thursday, when
the Institute of Medicine, an arm of the National Academy of
Sciences, starts its own examination of the organ allocation
system. The review is being conducted at the request of Congress;
the institute has appointed a panel of 16 experts, including
surgeons, ethicists, epidemiologists and a health care economist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We need an objective reviewer,'' said Louise Jacobbi,
executive director of the Louisiana Organ Procurement Agency in
Metairie, La. In 1997, Ms. Jacobbi, aware that the federal
government was about to change its rules, was instrumental in
persuading her state to become the first to adopt a law putting its
own residents first. That law has since become a model for the
other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, we have been rationing organs since the
beginning of transplantation,'' she said. ``We have always had
fewer organs than we have had patients. If we are going to change
the way we practice medicine, it needs to be based on good medical
data.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The institute, which hopes to finish its study by September,
will present its findings to Congress, which may decide to step in
and overhaul the allocation system on its own. But if Congress does
not act, the entire issue could wind up in court, with Wisconsin
and the other states suing the federal government in a state's
rights dispute over which provision _ the Clinton administration's
rule or state law _ takes precedence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Claude Earl Fox, administrator of the Health Resources and
Services administration, which oversees the organ allocation
system, said in an interview that the new regulation supersedes
state law. But in a suit filed in Louisiana last spring, the
Louisiana Attorney General contended the opposite, saying that only
an Act of Congress, and not a bureaucratic regulation, could
override a state law.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That suit is being held in abeyance while the Federal rule is on
hold. But should the Clinton administration's plan go into effect,
Governor Thompson of Wisconsin warned, his state would probably
bring suit as well. ``This rule is unconstitutional,'' the governor
said. ``It pre-empts states' rights.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The current organ donation system is 15 years old; it flows out
of a 1984 law called the Organ Procurement and Transplantation Act,
which gives the Department of Health and Human Services authority
to regulate the national organ distribution system. The law
prohibited the buying and selling of organs and declared them a
national resource. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the system works this way: A private, nonprofit
organization, the United Network for Organ Sharing, contracts with
the health and human services agency to distribute donated organs.
UNOS, as the network is known, has divided the country into 11
regions. Within those regions, there are 63 local organ procurement
organizations, whose job it is to obtain and distribute organs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the current rules, organs are offered first within the
local area, then regionwide, then nationally. But the system is
incredibly Balkanized; Dallas and Fort Worth, for instance, share
an airport and are only 30 miles apart, yet they belong to
different organ procurement organizations and do not share organs.
If there are extra livers or kidneys in Fort Worth, they are
offered to patients in Houston, four hours away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy,'' said Dr. Goran B. Klintmalm, chief of
transplant surgery at Baylor University Medical Center in Dallas.
His solution: Baylor is about to set up a satellite transplant
center in Fort Worth, so that its Dallas patients will be eligible
for organs that otherwise would have gone to Houston. ``We don't
want to duplicate services,'' he said, ``but it's the only way we
can make organs stay in the metroplex.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With hospitals raiding other hospitals' organ pools, the Clinton
administration's rule ordered the organ-sharing network to come up
with a new system that would distribute organs more broadly. The
administration said that if network officials did not change the
system on their own, the Department of Health of Human Services
would change it for them. But the network, which is composed mostly
of representatives from the smaller transplant centers, balked at
the rule, saying its members preferred the current system.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the rule was announced, doctors at some of these
centers, along with officials of the local organ procurement
organizations, began pressing their state legislators to pass laws
that would keep organs within state boundaries. Most of the laws
include provisions stating that states can share organs, so long as
they have reciprocal arrangements with other states. Even so, they
have been criticized as provincial and jingoistic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma has been castigated,'' said Robert Turner, executive
director of the Oklahoma Organ Sharing Network. ``We have been
called narrow-minded, self-centered, not caring for others.
Actually, our law is pretty moderate. It says that we can't bypass
local patients unless we get a payback for the organ.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Douglas Hanto, a transplant surgeon at the University of
Cincinnati Medical Center, warned: ``If this rule goes through, you
will see more and more states passing laws. And it will be a huge
controversy. I don't think that Donna Shalala or Bill Clinton
really understands the degree of opposition to this rule.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, however, say the state laws are misguided.
``We know that, on average, about a third of all organ recipients
go outside their state of residence to get a transplant,'' Dr. Fox
said. ``We have a lot of sharing that is going on across state
lines. States, in my opinion, could be shooting themselves in the
foot by passing language that restricts that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the dispute is an economic turf war between
transplant centers, which are competing for their share of the
lucrative transplant business, in which an operation can cost
$250,000 or more. On one side are large hospitals, which tend to
have long waiting lists and would benefit from the new rule by
receiving additional organs. On the other side are small centers,
which fear Shalala's plan could put them out of business by
stripping them of their supply of organs.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess,'' said Dr. John J. Fung, who directs the
transplant program at the University of Pittsburgh, one of the
largest in the nation, and is a staunch advocate of increased
sharing. ``Everybody is hunkering down and protecting their own
turf. It's only going to get nastier, and the sooner we get it
resolved the sooner the healing process will begin. All we are
doing now is making the wounds bigger and bigger.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
