<SLUG> BC-BBO-TURNER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Off base: Turner may face fine, sensitivity class
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig is reviewing punitive
measures against Atlanta Braves owner Ted Turner for insensitive
comments he made in a speech last month.
</P>
<P>
   While the punishment is not expected to include Turner's
suspension from baseball, he could face a fine and sensitivity
training.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said only that he has talked to Turner and is taking the
matter seriously.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are Turner's remarks Feb. 16 to a National Family
Planning and Reproductive Association gathering. Turner urged that
Pope John Paul II ``get with it _ welcome to the 20th century'' and
suggested that adultery should be stricken from the Ten
Commandments. He also referred to his foot as a ``Polish mine
detector.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who also is vice chairman of Time Warner Inc., has
issued apologies to the Catholic League for Religious and Civil
Rights and to the government of Poland. He is out of the country
and had no comment Wednesday, according to publicist Caroline
Harkleroad.
</P>
<P>
   While the Catholic League accepted Turner's apology, a group
based in Cincinatti calling itself Christ or Chaos did not. Thomas
Droleskey, president of the organization that he says has about 500
members, staged a rally in Cincinatti and sent letters to the
baseball commissioner and various news media suggesting Turner get
the same one-year suspension used twice against Cincinnati Reds
owner Marge Schott.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Schott's slurs drew a one-year suspension, a $25,000
fine and the condition that she attend sensitivity training. In
1996, Schott admitted to keeping Nazi memorabilia in a drawer at
her home. Baseball's executive council issued another one-year
suspension and pressured her into selling controlling interest in
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Schott was incredulous that Turner escaped sanctions.
``I don't understand how Ted Turner can get away with what he
said,'' Schott said. ``I didn't say anything or do anything worse
than what he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
