<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH MIGHT BE A FIRST OPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAINES CITY, Fla. _ Before spring training began, Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson told outfielder Todd Hollandsworth he'd try
to be creative in getting him at-bats. Little did Hollandsworth
realize that could mean playing first base, which he did Wednesday
in an exhibition game against the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he can play all three outfield positions and play them
well,'' Johnson said. ``If Eric's (Karros) knee acts up some time
and I want to put a left-handed bat (in the lineup), maybe I can
put Hollandsworth at first. It gives me options.''
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson loves options. When he managed in Cincinnati, he
used Lenny Harris as a backup at first because it provided another
alternative late in games.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, trying not to get typecast as a fourth outfielder
at the age of 25, said it was the first time he played first base
at any level. He also said he didn't know quite what to make of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they're trying to do,'' Hollandsworth said.
``If they want me to play the one-bag, I'll do it, but I'm much
better used in the outfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth didn't have many chances in the 5{ innings he
spent at first. He caught a pop-up and didn't have any grounders,
though he handled the few throws sent his way. He also didn't
complain about the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job,'' Hollandsworth said. ``If the manager wants me
to put on my glove and go play first, I have no problem with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, the National League Rookie of the Year in 1996,
is healthy after spending the last two seasons battling injuries.
Playing time, though, could be hard to find since the Dodgers
signed free-agent center fielder Devon White in the offseason to
complement Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hollandsworth) did a good job over there,'' Johnson said.
``It's the degree of comfort he gets over there. We'll do it some
more.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Getting in the routine: Todd Hundley expects to feel
exhausted come late Sunday, the usual result of catching for the
first time in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always feel like a fish out of water your first time,''
said Hundley, who was the designated hitter Wednesday against
Kansas City. ``Every spring training, you feel like that the first
two or three times out. Physically, with catching, that's the tough
part. You're tired, your back is aching and your legs hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley is slated to catch his first spring-training game Sunday
against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gaining confidence: Pitching coach Charlie Hough said
right-hander Mel Rojas' confidence is so shot that his hitless
inning of relief Wednesday could go a long way in his attempt to
regain his pre-Mets form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's had a tough year-and-a-half and he's looking for
anything good to happen,'' said Hough, who's been working with
Rojas on mechanics. ``When you're trying to make adjustments, I
think you have to feel good about not giving up a run.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: Minor-leaguers reported to Dodgertown
on Wednesday, and included in the 167 scheduled for camp were
former big-leaguers Eric Anthony, Jim Bullinger and Shawn Boskie. .
. . Outfielder Hiram Bocachica, who bruised his ribs in a Monday
collision with Trenidad Hubbard, is ready to resume playing.
However, Hubbard's bruised right thumb remains swollen and it could
be a few more days before he can play.
</P>
</TEXT>
