<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER-BASEBALL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz, Woods change games
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Braves camp played out like a fantasy
camp for golfer Tiger Woods on Wednesday. Woods, along with fellow
PGA Tour player Lee Janzen, took his friend John Smoltz up on an
offer to drop by for batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, Smoltz played a round of golf with the 1997
Masters champion and Janzen, the '98 U.S. Open champion, at
Isleworth Country Club in Orlando. The result?
</P>
<P>
   ``(Woods) got a 67, not even trying,'' Smoltz said. ``I had a
76, grinding my absolute heart out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad played in the Negro leagues,'' Woods said. ``I always
wanted to be like him. I was a pitcher. I tore my rotator cuff and
there went that idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz met Woods at the opening of the All-Star Cafe in Atlanta.
He was happy to give Woods a chance to live out some childhood
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like he's not allowed to have fun sometimes,''
Smoltz said. ``That comes with the amount of (fame) you receive,
kind of like Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   The way it looked Wednesday, those golfers aren't as skilled in
baseball as some of the Braves are at golf.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Janzen both said they hadn't played baseball since
Little League.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
