<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECONSCENE-2TAKE     03-10 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECONSCENE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: TRACKING JAPAN'S PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., Mass.)  (Eds: See also JAPAN-ECONOMY, DAIMLER-NISSAN, NISSAN-ASSESS,
RJR-NABISCO-JAPAN) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have Japanese officials _ finally _ turned economic policy
around?
</P>
<P>
   After a decade-long stagnation caused in part by inadequate
government measures of the past, there are some promising signs.
Monetary policy, for instance, at least seems to be heading in a
more expansionary direction, putting it in line with a more
stimulative fiscal policy as well. And over the past few weeks, key
bank and finance officials have issued oblique promises to follow
through on these moves.
</P>
<P>
   But even the American economists who follow the Japanese economy
are not sure how much policy has actually changed. And there is the
ominous possibility, expressed by one prominent expert, that even
if the Japanese do everything they now hint at, the economy may
still remain sick.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese economy had been the envy of the world throughout
the 1970s and 1980s, growing faster than other industrialized
economies with only a whiff of inflation. But the crash of its
securities and real estate markets in the late 1980s undermined the
solvency of many big banks, whose loans were tied to real estate.
Bank loans to credit-worthy borrowers shriveled. Last year the
economy sank into recession, shrinking by about 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, deflation has set in. Wholesale prices
have been falling for years and now consumer prices appear to be
falling. By creating the expectation that prices will continue to
fall, deflation gives consumers and companies perverse incentives
to postpone purchases. That can trigger a downward spiral of
falling spending, production, income and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The West has accused the Japanese of tolerating a decade of
stagnation with barely a whimper. But professor Allan Meltzer of
Carnegie Mellon University, who serves, along with Stanford
University professor John Taylor, as an ``honorary adviser'' to the
Bank of Japan, provides a plausible explanation. ``The Japanese saw
no reason to panic for most of the decade, confident that their
vaunted economy would recover in a matter of months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But months turned into years. ``It was not until Korea collapsed
in the fall of 1997,'' Meltzer continued, ``that the Japanese
realized that the problem would not go away. So while the West
thinks the Japanese have been dawdling for 10 years, the Japanese
think they've been wrestling with the problem for only about 15
months.''
</P>
<P>
   And over those 15 months, he says, Tokyo has done ``a surprising
amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Posen of the Institute for International Economics, the
author of a recent book on the Japanese economy, agrees. Japan is
running a huge budget deficit _ 10 percent of national output and
rising. (At its most recent peak in 1983, the U.S. federal deficit
reached 6.1 percent of annual output.) Though Posen would like to
see even larger tax cuts, it can no longer be said that Japanese
fiscal stimulus is lacking.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese have also moved decisively in recent months to
clean up their banks. The government is paying off depositors at
failed banks, nationalizing insolvent banks that the government
decides to keep open, and pumping public money into shaky but
solvent banks in exchange for stock. The three-pronged reform aims
to give insolvent borrowers a fresh start and to build up banks'
capital reserves so that they can resume lending.
</P>
<P>
   But few economists think that fiscal stimulus and bank reform
alone are enough. The outside advisers have called on the Japanese
central bank to pump enough new money into the economy to stop
prices from falling.
</P>
<P>
   Why has Japan delayed? Apart from an ideological fear of doing
anything that hints of inflation, one big reason is that Tokyo
might fear retaliation from the United States. Once the central
bank prints more yen, they will leak into the foreign exchange
market and drive down the value of the yen against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   That will make Japan's goods cheaper to buy in America and
America's goods more expensive to buy in Japan _ worsening an
already huge trade imbalance and possibly igniting protectionist
measures in Congress. Officials also worry that a falling yen will
spread to other currencies in Asia, creating a contagion of
currency depreciations in already fragile financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe the Japanese, driven by the greater needs of their own
economy at the moment, are overcoming their reluctance to offend
Uncle Sam. Eisuke Sakakibara, vice minister of finance and Japan's
most outspoken advocate of a strong yen, has reversed course and
stated that it would be OK if the Japanese currency fell in value.
And the central bank has driven down short-term interest rates
within a few tenths of a percentage point of zero. And, as
predicted, the exchange rate has fallen, so that it now takes about
120 yen to buy a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Bernstein, director of research at Bridgewater
Associates, cautions against overinterpreting these recent straws
in the wind. The central bank's monetary policy may be more
lenient, but the change is not dramatic, he says. And the Bank of
Japan's public pronouncements continue to focus on interest rates,
not flooding the economy with more money.
</P>
<P>
   American economists point out that policy does not need to rely
on driving interest rates lower _ they already are near zero anyway
_ to pump up spending. The central bank can print new yen in order
to buy lots of assets, from commercial paper to foreign exchange.
Eventually, the extra yen should boost consumer spending. A recent
statement by a board member of the Bank of Japan suggests that some
of his colleagues are thinking about targeting inflation rather
than interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krugman, professor of economics at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, has provocatively called on the central
bank to go further, much further. He argues that consumers and
companies will not start spending as long as they believe that
prices will keep falling.
</P>
<P>
   So Krugman has urged the government to ``credibly promise to be
irresponsible.'' That may not be the most diplomatic way to
encourage the ever cautious Japanese. But it does drive home the
point that nothing short of expanding the money supply to build in
the expectation that prices will start rising for the indefinite
future will prod the Japanese into deciding to spend now rather
than later.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take the tantalizing hints out of the finance ministry and
central bank at face value. Fiscal and monetary policies will ease
more and bank reform will proceed. Mission accomplished?
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, say Ronald McKinnon of Stanford and Kenichi Ohno of
Saitama University in Japan. They reject their colleagues'
optimism. Bank reform and monetary and fiscal easing are necessary,
they agree. But these moves are not enough.
</P>
<P>
   They trace Japan's problem to decades of pressure by Washington
to raise the value of the yen in a losing effort to eliminate the
United States trade deficit with Japan. In fact, the yen rose, in
dollar terms, by four percent a year from the 1970s to the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon points out that investors who expect the yen to rise
will accept lower interest payments on bonds denominated in yen
compared with bonds denominated in dollars. It is no accident,
then, that interest rates are generally about 4 percentage points
lower in Japan than in the United States. But since interest rates
have dropped in the United States, they have been pushed down to
near zero in Japan. At that rate, banks cannot make any profit on
loans and the economy cannot, therefore, recover.
</P>
<P>
   The way out of this bind, says McKinnon, is to raise interest
rates in Japan. That requires ``wiping out the expectation that the
yen will rise.'' He proposes that the United States and Japan agree
to stabilize the value of the yen at about 130 to the dollar, the
rate at which a dollar buys about as many hamburgers and computers
in Japan as it does in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation that the yen would continue to rise was not
created solely by Japan, and cannot be solved solely by Japan,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   If McKinnon is correct, then recovery in Japan depends on an
accord that no official in either country appears prepared to
adopt. So a more plausible course, for now, is for the Japanese to
print money galore _ and cross their fingers that the weaker yen
that would be a consequence of such a policy will not trigger
protectionism in the United States or worsen the financial
situation across the rest of Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
