<HEADER>
A5635 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-10 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE SUPERVICTIM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an age that celebrates victimhood, Monica
Lewinsky has earned the title of Supervictim.
</P>
<P>
   First, she is portrayed in book and television, and soon in
mythic song and legend, as having been callously used by the
president of the U.S. She was a 22-year-old intern whose insecure
``sexuality'' was exploited by a predatory boss, who then cast her
aside in a fit of guilty self-protection.
</P>
<P>
   Next to victimize her was a faithless friend, Linda Tripp, who _
unlike 10 other friends to whom she confided the details of her
affair _ tape-recorded her streaming consciousness and turned the
evidence over to the feds.
</P>
<P>
   Then she fell victim to a family lawyer, William Ginsburg, who
went gaga over the seduction of publicity and, she thinks,
represented her poorly before the next victimizer _
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel, who terrorized her into confessing that
she had prepared a false affidavit and made her young life a living
hell for a whole year, because it half-exposed her to _
</P>
<P>
   The victim-hungry meanie media, who treated her throughout her
travail as a chubby, ditzy, spoiled and irresponsible slut.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was Monica's privacy plundered five ways, the way she tells
it through her agents, new lawyers, biographer, interviewers and
hairdresser. Never in the course of human history has one
vulnerable young woman been so shabbily treated by so many
powerful, world-class manipulators.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, do we aficionados of Great Cons clasp her to our
bosoms? Because this uncandid Cunegonde is now so good at what she
does. We who respect disciplined professionalism in the concoction
of images salute this sob-solipsister.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of her masterly self-awareness in this role is her
reaction to questions about Sidney Blumenthal's testimony. He swore
that Bill Clinton told him, before the DNA evidence made denial
implausible, that Monica was a stalker, threatening the innocent
president with blackmail unless he succumbed to her demands.
</P>
<P>
   That version would have made Clinton the victim. That was the
one technique that would have usurped her hard-earned victimhood.
No wonder she responded with fury, revulsion and alacrity; it takes
an avid seeker of Supervictim status to know an impressively
pitiable competitor when one appears.
</P>
<P>
   Give credit where it's due. That woman understands that the
ultimate purpose of victimhood is not sympathy but a caring
identification with a social and generational cohort, not to
mention money and all the happiness it can buy.
</P>
<P>
   She seems confident she can hold fast to her lack of self-esteem
despite her world fame. Monica, one of the few with whom the world
is on a first-name basis, knows that if she can institutionalize
her victimhood, she can underdoggedly attract other underdogs who
buy books and magazines about the celebrated ill used.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the poor souls made to appear as her victimizers?
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr, who tried to get a cover-up conspirator to testify
against high-level lawbreakers, gets clobbered in public opinion
every time Monica pretends to be fearful of going to jail for
mentioning his name.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ginsburg, who conceived the ultimately successful strategy
of appeasing Starr with evidence of Clinton's perjury but not
offending Clinton with evidence of his obstruction of justice, is
reviled for being an ultra-available publicity hound by Monica and
media ``getters'' who pursued him so avidly for their shows.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp, to whom Monica blabbed the most intimate details of
her affair, properly suffers for taping secretly and bears Monica's
abuse for not adopting her talking points to lie under oath.
</P>
<P>
   The meanie media, having made a fortune responding to public
fascination with the case, now lacerate themselves for prurient
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton? The incurable romantic, according to his victim's
report, fearfully envisions a time when she is still vibrantly fair
and he is afflicted with embarrassing urgencies.
</P>
<P>
   You and I, though irritated by a waste of time, are not victims.
Thanks to the fine journalism of Barbara Walters, Monica brought
the nation together to share an experience. That counts for
something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
