<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOPOKER11-COX     03-10 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOPOKER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pulling the plug on video poker
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMMOND, La. _ Orlin ``Shorty'' Rogers' small kingdom off
Interstate 55 is a homage to the financial potential of video
poker.
</P>
<P>
   In a busy strip of fast food shops and gas stations about an
hour from the Mississippi state line, Rogers has a hotel, a
convenience store, a barbecue restaurant, a full-service truck stop
and the Cypress Lounge, a mini-casino that keeps everything else in
business. The windowless room with 50 video poker machines, dark
carpeting and a sign that says ``Be a $500 winner: Royal Flush'' is
open 24 hours a day to truckers, travelers and locals. Without
their wagers, Rogers says, the whole operation would sink.
</P>
<P>
   And sink it will, come June 30. That's when video poker will be
outlawed in Tangipahoa Parish and in more than half the state,
seven years after the Legislature legalized it.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 local-option election allowed parishes to vote on video
poker and riverboat casinos, and while every parish that has
riverboats voted to keep them, 33 of 64 parishes tossed out video
poker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terrible,'' said Rogers. ``I did everything the state
required me to do to be in business, and I went in debt to do it,
and they went and had an election. If I knew they were going to
come and pull the plug, I wouldn't have done this.''
</P>
<P>
   As the deadline draws near, Rogers isn't the only one
complaining. Officials in several parishes and cities are concerned
both for local businesses and for government coffers, which have
benefited from taxes on the machines. At least four parishes,
including Tangipahoa, have passed resolutions asking the
Legislature to authorize a new vote.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bobby Gill of Kentwood, a Tangipahoa Parish town four
miles from the Mississippi line, said his town will suffer from the
loss of poker tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This town gets about $25,000 a month from video poker, and you
can imagine what that means to a town of 2,700 people,'' he said.
``I'd like to see the Legislature allow each municipality to vote
on it again.''
</P>
<P>
   While about half of Louisiana is dealing out video poker, some
Alabama legislators want their state to deal it in. They advocate
putting the machines at the state's four dog tracks to help bolster
a parimutuel industry dragged down by lotteries and casinos in
neighboring states. They say their bill would keep casinos out of
Alabama while raising $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, David Beasley lost his re-election bid for
governor in large part because he challenged video poker, calling
it a ``cancer.'' Poker-friendly political action committees threw
their support to Jim Hodges, who won.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges, who is pushing for a statewide lottery, has since agreed
to a referendum on whether to abolish video poker, and the
Legislature is weighing ways to better regulate the $2.3 billion
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Those calling for a revote on video poker in Louisiana are
arguing that the first vote wasn't fair because the Legislature
barred the gambling industry from pooling its resources to
campaign. The Louisiana Supreme Court ruled that law
unconstitutional two weeks before the 1996 vote _ too late,
gambling proponents say, for the industry to mount a real effort to
keep video poker. The industry filed a lawsuit to overturn the
elections; a trial is scheduled for May.
</P>
<P>
   Political pollster Bernie Pinsonat said he doubts the
Legislature will allow a revote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an election year, and why would you want, as an
incumbent, to create an issue for an opponent?'' he said.
``Gambling is a volatile issue _ there's no telling who would be in
your face in a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature does not convene until later this month.
Meanwhile, truck stops and other poker outlets are closing or
pulling up stakes and relocating to legal parishes. A truck stop in
Kentwood has moved to neighboring St. Helena Parish, Gill said. St.
Helena, which voted to keep video poker, is surrounded by parishes
that voted it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to gamble anyway,'' Gill said. ``They'll just
go to St. Helena now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie Jackson, a home health care nurse who was gambling at the
Cypress Lodge last week, said she'll start going to St. Helena when
the Tangipahoa poker outlets close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate that this will close, but I'll just go to the next
place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
