<SLUG> BC-PAXSON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paxson stock rises even after $137.9 million loss in '98
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Paxson Communications Corp. Wednesday
said it lost $137.9 million in 1998 _ the year it launched the
family friendly PAX TV network.
</P>
<P>
   The loss, which equals $2.29 a share, was a 173 percent drop
from Paxson's profit of $188.4 million, or $3.50 a share, in 1997.
The loss surpassed Wall Street's estimate of a $2.13 a share loss,
according to Zacks research service.
</P>
<P>
   The network loss would have been greater if not for a $51.6
million pre-tax gain on the sale of television station assets
during the year.
</P>
<P>
   But traders brushed off the higher-than-expected loss, pushing
the stock (AMEX: PAX) up 19 cents to $8.31 in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury at this date and time is still out,'' said broadcast
analyst Leland Westerfield of PaineWebber in New York. ``The PAX
network has seen robust improvement in ratings off of a relatively
small base. The goal is to increase the reach of the network across
the nation and to attract national and local advertisers to the
network.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxson Chief Executive Officer Jeff Sagansky said, ``PAX TV's
coveted 18- to 49-year-old demographic has grown 52 percent from
the network's launch through the first week of February.''
</P>
<P>
   The rating for weekday prime time, measured by Nielsen Media
Research, was 0.6 the first week after the Aug. 31 launch of PAX TV
and rose to a 1 rating by the first week of the February sweeps,
Sagansky said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts will get a better feel for network advertisers'
interest in PAX TV in May, when the networks present their fall
lineup in New York to potential advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings, revenue and advertiser support has improved each month
since the PAX network's debut, Sagansky said. Advertising revenue
was $134.2 million for the year, 52 percent higher than $88.4
million the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Company expenses increased 144 percent to $269.7 million from
$110.4 million in 1997. Sales and administrative expenses were the
bulk of the increase, rising to $135.5 million from $44.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sagansky also said the company has taken steps to minimize
holdings that aren't at the core of the PAX TV business, including
selling a Bridgeport, Conn., TV station for $21 million and
Paxson's interest in the Travel Channel for $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   Paxson's loss for the quarter ended Dec. 31 was $76.4 million,
compared with a profit of $174 million in the fourth quarter of
1997, which included a $185.1 million after-tax gain on the sale of
discontinued operations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
