<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SENATE PANEL PASSES ABORTION BILL PACKAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Legislation giving parents more say when minors
seek abortions and imposing a three-day waiting period on all women
requesting the procedure won narrow approval from a Senate
committee Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A two-hour debate brought those affected on both sides to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one night since Feb. 20 has passed that there has not been
a nightmare or 2:30 a.m. scream from my daughter,'' said Veronica
Moore of Houston, speaking in favor of parental involvement bills
in the wake of her 15-year-old's recent abortion without her
consent.
</P>
<P>
   But a University of Texas student, who said she was raped and
impregnated by a co-worker last fall, suspects the abortion bill
package is designed to place roadblocks in the paths of all women
seeking abortions. She took special aim at an ``informed consent''
bill that would impose a 72-hour waiting period.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use crafty representation as an emotional scare tactic and
to assume I am not educated enough is both evil and patronizing on
the part of the state,'' said Katie Hatziavramidis, 20.
</P>
<P>
   The three bills, backed by anti-abortion activists, passed the
Senate Human Services Committee in a 3-2 vote and now head to the
full Senate. Gov. George W. Bush has said he supports parental
notification and consent bills.
</P>
<P>
   SB 30, by Sen. Florence Shapiro, R-Plano, requires that parents
be notified before daughters 17 and under can get abortions. It is
widely considered to have the best chance of becoming law. A
similar bill two years ago reportedly had ample votes to win but
was killed on a technicality.
</P>
<P>
   SB 27, by Sen. Jane Nelson, R-Flower Mound, is similar but
tougher, requiring written consent of parents. Another Nelson
proposal, Senate Bill 65, mandates ``informed consent'' for all
women seeking abortions and requires a waiting period unless an
immediate abortion is medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   While supporters of parental involvement bills say 73 percent of
Texans polled favor the proposed changes, opponents point out that
75 percent of minor girls nationally voluntarily inform their
parents already. Those who don't, they argue, fear harm.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing sides _ each represented by lawyers, clergy and those
directly affected _ also argued whether parental involvement
protects or imperils the health and safety of teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   Without help from their parents, young girls can bleed to death
from post-abortion complications, suffer emotional harm, early
breast cancer or fertility problems, the bills' supporters said.
Opponents warned of such dangers as illegal abortions, pointing to
high death rates in neighboring Mexico, suicide risks and harm
inflicted by parents who are abusive or incestuous.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's testimony visibly shook up the indignant Houston
mother and UT student. Both left the witness stand tearful and
trembling. They were embraced and comforted by respective forces
fighting against abortion access or for abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Moore told reporters how she tried to stop her daughter when the
confronted teen-ager admitted she was en route to an abortion
clinic with her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the doctor and asked, could it be stopped? They
refused me any information,'' the mother said. ``They told me I
could not be in there with her. It was her body.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said her daughter has since been shattered by the
experience, breaking down when she sees mothers with babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's real delicate,'' the mother said. ``This abortion was
not her idea. It was his idea, because she has never believed in
anything dying.''
</P>
<P>
   UT student Hatziavramis was indignant as she implored the Senate
panel to consider what her fate would have been if Nelson's
``informed consent'' law was in effect.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that her disabled mother had worked around a tight
schedule of doctor's visits, pain medications and child care
arrangements to take her daughter to an abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had there been a 72-hour or even 24-hour waiting period, I
would not have had access to this procedure because my mother was
the only person who supported me,'' she told the senators. ``That
is exactly what the legislation is intended to prevent _ safe and
effective access to abortion. This bill is about biased
information, not informed consent.''
</P>
<P>
   The parental involvement bills allow what Nelson calls the
``safety valve'' of a judicial bypass in which a court can waive
the requirement that a parent be notified.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. David Berenson, D-Beaumont, said he plans to offer an
amendment when the bills reach the Senate floor that would allow
others, such as counselors, doctors or social workers, to waive any
requirement notifying parents.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson and fellow Democrat Mario Gallegos of Galena Park voted
against all three bills. They were outnumbered by Republican Sens.
John Carona of Dallas and Chris Harris of Arlington, joined by
Democratic Sen. Judith Zaffirini, the committee chair who declares
herself ``pro-life.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaffirini said when she polled the 31 senators last January, 21
favored parental notification and 17 were for parental consent.
While it takes a simple majority to pass a bill, it takes 21 votes
to bring a bill to the floor for debate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
