<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REACHES CONSENSUS ON `ED FLEX' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans may, in the end, get their way in the
current education debate. They may even head into the 2000 election
cycle with education solidly on their platform, thanks in part to
legislation pending in both the Senate and the House.
</P>
<P>
   But by Wednesday it was clear: They won't win without having
fought a bitter fight.
</P>
<P>
   After five days of intense wrangling, the Senate finally reached
a deal on how to proceed with the bill known as ``Ed Flex,'' which
would give states greater flexibility in how they spend federal
education money. The program, already being tested in 12 states,
has support in both parties, as well as the backing of 50 governors
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Wednesday, on the eve of a final vote, it still faced a
formidable opponent in Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who has
maneuvered to force a debate on the topic for a week, confounding
his Republican opponents as he demanded additional initiatives he
said were ``very, very important'' to the state of education.
</P>
<P>
   The chief stumbling block has been an amendment co-sponsored by
Kennedy and Senator Patty Murray of Washington, which would force
the authorization of federal funding of 100,000 new elementary
school teachers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say the initiative is crucial to shrinking massive
classes in overcrowded schools, and Republicans say they back the
ultimate goal. But the GOP is reluctant to confront the issue now _
and potentially cede important political ground to Democrats _
saying they had hoped to address the question later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is all meant, personally, to get someone to make
a vote against a program that could be used in a 30-second
television spot,'' said Senator George Voinovich, a Republican from
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans questioned Democratic motives, and some
accused the Democratic leaders of not wanting to give a political
success to Republicans so soon after impeachment _ at the expense
of students nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask whether the Democrats really want to give
states autonomy,'' said Joe Karpinski, a spokesman for the Senate
Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee, which sent the
bill to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fired back. Accusing Republicans of being the ones to
cause the delay, Kennedy took to the Senate floor Wednesday
afternoon, using the debate to attack Republicans for refusing to
``meet our seven-year commitment to reduce class size.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While Republicans continue to block action on critical
education issues for the sixth day in a row, communities struggle
to make decisions about their school budgets,'' Kennedy said.
``They need and expect our help.''
</P>
<P>
   In the House _ where the majority cannot be waylayed so easily
by the stubborness of a few voices _ advocates of the Ed-Flex bill
faced a far easier battle, thanks largely to the rules governing
the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Senate, where it took a deal to determine the number
of amendments that will be considered, the House rules limited the
number of amendments and set a five-hour time limit on debate.
Wednesday, after two amendments were defeated, the bill was poised
to head to a final vote, which is scheduled to take place in the
House Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Diskey, director of communications for the House Education
and Workforce Committee, said the House leadership ``wants this
thing finished,'' and criticized Democrats for loading up the bill
with amendments that diminish the overall effectiveness of the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about greater accountability, which means nothing
more than adding more paperwork into a bill that's supposed to
eliminate paperwork,'' Diskey said. ``Ed-Flex is a bill designed to
set up a system of waivers of reform. Every mention you hear of
accountability is to load back into the system more reporting
criteria. We are very concerned about accountability, but we feel
the governors can handle that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
