<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK RUNS ROAD TO RECOVERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Seeking instant gratification left Phillip Clark
homeless and addicted to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He found one of his biggest aids to rehabilitation in the
grueling training for a marathon. A week after graduating from his
recovery program, Clark will participate in the L.A. Marathon on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely helping him work toward goals,'' said Carl
Williams, assistant athletic director at the Union Rescue Mission
in Los Angeles, where Clark enrolled last year. ``Losing weight,
that took a long period of time. Training, like anything else, it
takes time and this helps him realize you need to keep going to
reach your goals. Things don't just happen overnight and you can't
give up on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most definitely he'll finish. He's got that never-quit
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark familiarized himself with long-term commitments when he
began training six months ago and shed more than 60 pounds from his
once 300-pound frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get myself back together,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the mission a year ago. Prior to his year and half on
the streets, Clark, 37, served time in a Nevada prison. He grew up
in a foster home in Cincinnati and became involved with drugs after
moving to California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came and gave myself to the Lord,'' Clark said of his
decision to turn his life around.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I decided to run, it was my way to clear my mind and keep
me focused on my goal. I like to run because it eases my mind. I
talk to the Lord when I run and it helps me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark has been clean for more than 10 months. He said he was
drug-free for a three-year period before but vows this time is for
good. He serves in the mission's maintenance department and hopes
to enter the facility's apprenticeship program that would put him
on track for a job in the plumbing or electrical field.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the mission's employees noticed Clark's running and
started working out with him. The idea of running a marathon came
up when Williams, a marathon veteran, mentioned he was
participating in the L.A. Marathon. He encouraged Clark to join
him.
</P>
<P>
   All involved realize the significance of the race is about more
than the course's 26.2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another accomplishment for him,'' said maintenance
supervisor Noah Harrison, who also trains with Clark. ``He needs
something like that. This is one of the monuments in his life that
he can look back on and say, `I did this.' It's an accomplishment
that substantiates he does have the tools to make it off the
streets and do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the gumption to do it. That's what I see in him now.
He won't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the program's other members are also participating in
the marathon, but Williams said Clark is by far the most dedicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most consistent person here,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's daily workout regimen includes getting up at 4 a.m. to
run seven miles and lift weights. He also rides a stationary bike
and runs another 12-13 miles in the afternoon. Clark surprised even
Williams when he was able to run for more than four hours straight
last weekend. The pair covered approximately 18 miles as they ran
from the mission to Beverly Hills and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited,'' Clark said. ``I've never done anything
like this before.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought I was crazy, the people that first
heard about it and saw how big I was. I may finish walking, but I'm
going to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   His goal is to complete the course in 4{-5 hours but admits time
isn't his top priority. Those who know him believe Clark is ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you really know how tough it is until you
actually get there,'' Williams said. ``When you get to the halfway
point, the three-quarter mark, that's when your body starts giving
up on you and it becomes mental. You have to tell yourself, `If I
have to crawl across the line, I'll finish.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He has that mental toughness. He will definitely make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
