<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBIL-EXXON-REFINERIE     03-10 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBIL-EXXON-REFINERIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC TO EXAMINE EXXON, MOBIL REFINERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission will take a close look
at refinery operations of Mobil and Exxon on the Texas Gulf Coast
as it considers whether to approve an $80 billion merger of the two
oil giants, a top agency official told Congress on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   William Baer, director of the FTC Bureau of Competition, also
said that the agency will look at the effect.MDNM/ of the merger _
the largest ever _ on competition at the pump in the Gulf Coast
area, California and the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``vitally important for nearly all of this country east of
the Mississippi to maintain a competitive Gulf Coast refining
market,'' Baer told a House panel that is examining the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This nation's principal refining market, the Gulf Coast, not
only supplies that immediate area, but also sends substantial
amounts of gasoline by pipeline to the Southeast, the Northeast and
the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Baer made his comments during the first of two days of hearings
conducted by the House Commerce Committee's energy and power
subcommittee, headed by Rep. Joe Barton, R-Ennis.
</P>
<P>
   The merger requires .MDBR/the .MDNM/approval of the Federal
Trade Commission, the Securities and Exchange Commission and
regulators in Europe, where there are also concerns about the two
companies' share of refining capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon agreed in December to acquire Mobil, combining the two
biggest U.S. oil companies and reuniting two of the largest pieces
left from the 1911 government breakup of John D. Rockefeller's
Standard Oil empire.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that the combined company would have
to sell .MDBU/service .MDNM/stations and divest refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil's refinery at Beaumont, with 1,200 employees, is its
biggest domestic refiner, processing 315,000 barrels .MDBR/of oil
.MDNM/a day. At .MDNM/Baytown, Exxon's refinery, with 4,200
employees, processes 427,000 barrels a.MDNM/ day.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the companies would have about 18 percent of Gulf
Coast refining capacity. Antitrust experts say that market share
may not be high enough to require the FTC to order Mobil or Exxon
to sell a refinery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two companies that combined to have 18 percent of the market
is not enough to worry about,'' said Tyler Baker, an antitrust
expert at the Dallas law firm Carrington, Coleman, Sloman &AMP;
Blumenthal. ``The FTC would have to come up with some other
explanation. They may be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Hakes, an administrator at the Energy Information
Administration, told the panel that Mobil-Exxon's Gulf Coast
capacity would be comparable to that of BP-Amoco in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the combined production capacity would be
dwarfed by that of state-owned oil companies abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1997, state-owned oil companies represented the world's top
six producers,'' Barton said. ``Exxon ranked No. 7 and Mobil was
down to No. 18.''
</P>
<P>
   But prices at the pump are at the heart of consumer concerns,
and the FTC will also examine its effect.MDNM/ there, Baer said. He
said that the commission forced the sale of gasoline stations in
past oil industry mergers.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
