<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORRE-PROSTATE-CANCER     03-10 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORRE-PROSTATE-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING AND TREATING PROSTATE CANCER
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBA-YANK-TORRE; also moving in `a' category) 
(rk) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Torre joins more than 179,000 men in the United
States who will be found to have prostate cancer this year,
according to estimates by the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   New cases of prostate cancer have risen dramatically in recent
years with the widespread use of a test to detect prostate-specific
antigen. The test, first introduced in 1985, is recommended
annually for men over 50 and measures the level of this substance
in the blood and may indicate the presence of a cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy has swirled around the use of the prostate-specific
antigen test because in some men prostate cancer is not an
aggressive disease and would never become a clinical problem before
they die. But in many others the test has proved to be a lifesaver
that picked up potentially deadly cancers before they caused
symptoms and while they could still be cured.
</P>
<P>
   Death rates from prostate cancer have been declining
significantly, at a rate of 1.6 percent a year in the early 1990s.
This year an estimated 37,000 men will die from the disease, making
it the second-leading cause of cancer death in men.
</P>
<P>
   The leading cause, lung cancer, will claim about 90,000 lives
among American men this year.
</P>
<P>
   More than three-fourths of men who have prostate cancer are over
65. The risk is highest among American blacks and those with a
family history of the disease. Suspected risk factors include
cigarette smoking and a diet high in fat. Recent studies have
singled out lycopene, a substance in cooked tomatoes, as a possible
protector against this disease.
</P>
<P>
   The most effective treatment for prostate cancer depends on the
stage of the disease and how aggressive the cancer is believed to
be. The three leading treatments are radical surgery to remove the
prostate and surrounding tissue (which can cause impotence and
incontinence), external radiation therapy and implantation of
radioactive seeds. Men are also often treated with hormone therapy
in conjunction with other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   A study of 1,872 men with localized prostate cancer published
last September in the Journal of the American Medical Association
showed that those with cancers rated a high risk for spreading
beyond the prostate did best if treated with radical surgery. Their
survival rate exceeded that of those who got radioactive implants,
even if the implant group also got hormone therapy.
</P>
<P>
   For those at intermediate risk, radioactive implants plus
hormone therapy proved as effective as radical surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A second study published in the same journal suggested that a
conservative approach to treatment may be appropriate in some
cases. Of 767 men with localized prostate cancer, those with
cancers considered a low risk faced only a 4 percent to 7 percent
chance of dying from their disease within the next 15 years when
either no treatment was given or only hormonal therapy was used.
However, those with high-risk disease faced as much as a 60 percent
to 87 percent chance of dying when similarly treated.
</P>
<P>
   But experts warn against acting on these findings since
definitive results of studies that are weighing radical surgery
against such ``watchful waiting'' are still years off.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
