<SLUG> BC-OUT-SALMON-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON HERE; ARE SALMON?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Predicting the fishing success of the opening day
of salmon season in Southern California is a difficult prospect,
and this year is no different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' said Bruce Williams, proprietor of Port Hueneme
Sportfishing, ``we'll know by Saturday whether or not they're
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for anglers trying to get an edge on the
competition, that's not much help; Saturday IS opening day.
</P>
<P>
   At least the water temperatures are more favorable than last
year for catching the cold-water-loving denizens. The Santa Barbara
Channel is registering 58 degrees; salmon prefer temperatures in
the low to middle 50s. During last year's salmon opener, the same
waters were as high as 61 or 62 _ 3 to 4 degrees higher than normal
for late winter due to residual effects of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   Since salmon are swimming from the north, it's advantageous to
fish upcoast. And if you don't already have a reservation on a
charter out of Avila Beach or Morro Bay, a landing in Santa Barbara
and Ventura county might be your next best bet.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of landings with charters targeting salmon on
Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   __ Port Hueneme Sportfishing, Port Hueneme, two }-day boats, $30
per angler, (805) 488-2212.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gold Coast Sportfishing, Oxnard, two }-day boats,$33 and $40,
(805) 382-0402.
</P>
<P>
   __ Capt. Hook's Sportfishing, Ventura, one }-day boat, $29,
(805) 644-2500.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sea Landing, Santa Barbara, one half-day boat, $25, (805)
963-3564.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
