<SLUG> BC-POLK-KCAWARD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC STAR SERIES ABOUT FEDERAL JUDGES WINS POLK AWARD FOR LEGAL
REPORTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Joe Stephens of The Kansas City Star has won
the 1998 George Polk award for legal reporting for ``On their
honor,'' a series of stories about conflicts of interest among
federal judges.
</P>
<P>
   The series, which ran in April 1998, showed that some federal
judges _ two-thirds of the judges in Kansas City courthouses alone
_ had presided over cases in which they owned an interest in one of
the litigants. The series led to congressional hearings and broad
reform by the federal judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens, 39, will accept the award in April in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second Polk for Stephens, who won the 1994 political
reporting award for stories about riverboat casinos, political
connections and the role played by then-Missouri Speaker of the
House Bob Griffin in obtaining state gaming licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The judges series also recently won the Burton W. Marvin Kansas
News Enterprise Award, named for the first dean of the William
Allen White School of Journalism and Mass Communications at the
University of Kansas. Stephens accepted the award last month at KU.
</P>
<P>
   The Polk awards were established in 1949 to honor a CBS reporter
who was killed while covering the Greek civil war. They are
conferred by Long Island University and are considered among the
most prestigious honors in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Other 1998 Polk winners:
</P>
<P>
   Economic reporting _ Mary Jordan, Keith Richburg and Kevin
Sullivan of The Washington Post for ``Shattered Lives,'' a series
about the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental reporting _ Gardiner Harris and R.G. Dunlop of the
Louisville Courier-Journal for stories about the deaths of 1,500
coal miners each year from black lung disease.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign reporting _ Tracy Wilkinson, Los Angeles Times, for
dispatches about ethnic Albanians' armed struggle for independence
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   International reporting _ Alix M. Freedman, The Wall Street
Journal, for ``Population Bomb,'' which led to the ban of a
carcinogenic sterility drug manufactured in the United States and
distributed in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   Local reporting _ Clifford J. Levy, The New York Times, for
documenting instances of unethical political contributions in
stories that sparked federal criminal investigations of state
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Medical reporting _ Robert Whitaker and Dolores Kong, The Boston
Globe, for ``Doing Harm: Research on the Mentally Ill,'' which
exposed harmful experiments conducted on mental patients.
</P>
<P>
   National reporting _ Donald L. Barlett and James B. Steele, Time
magazine, for reports showing that taxpayer incentives to
corporations rarely pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Book award _ Philip Gourevitch for ``We Wish to Inform You that
Tomorrow We Will be Killed with Our Families: Stories from
Rwanda,'' an account of genocide in Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Career award _ Russell Baker, author and retired New York Times
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Commentary _ Juan Gonzalez, New York Daily News, for columns
challenging myths about people of color and describing the effects
of unequal distribution of wealth in urban America.
</P>
<P>
   Radio reporting _ Amy Goodman and Jeremy Scahill, Democracy
Now//Pacifica Radio, for ``Drilling and Killing: Chevron and
Nigeria's Oil Dictatorship,'' which reported that the company's use
of the military to protect its interests led to the death of two
environmental activists.
</P>
<P>
   Television reporting _ Brian Ross and Rhonda Schwartz, ABC
News-20//20, for ``Made in America?'' which revealed a loophole
allowing firms to put ``Made in the U.S.A.'' labels on garments
manufactured in sweatshops on Saipan.
</P>
</TEXT>
