u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAECIS-PROSTATE-BOS &LR;      03-10 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAECIS-PROSTATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAECIS GETS AMGEN FUNDS FOR WORK ON PROSTATE DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Praecis Pharmaceuticals Inc. has received a $100 million
commitment to complete development of a drug to treat prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The funding for the Cambridge, Mass. company will come from
Amgen Inc., the world's biggest biotechnology firm, which is
anxious to develop the drug, called Abarelix, and bring it to
market in the next several years. The injectable medication is now
being tested nationwide in a pivotal 500-patient Phase III clinical
trial, according to Malcolm Gefter, president and founder of
Praecis.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is the largest development deal for a
Massachusetts biotech company with a single drug in more than 15
months. It comes amid growing concerns that some young biotech
companies are running out of cash at a time when venture capital
and Wall Street are investing in more lucrative areas such as
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, biotech funding comes at the early stages of a drug's
development. The Abarelix deal stands out because Amgen is
providing extensive financial backing in the final stage of the
testing required for US Food and Drug Administration approval.
Gefter said he expects Amgen, based in Thousand Oaks, Calif., and
Praecis will seek FDA permission to market the drug in about 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Amgen will market Abarelix in North America
and Asia. More than two years ago, Praecis sold many of the foreign
rights to Abarelix for $80 million to Synthelabo SA, France's
third-largest pharmaceutical company, which will market it in
Europe, South America, and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listened to a group of companies who were interested in
Abarelix, but it became clear to us very quickly that Amgen was
culturally the best fit because of their aggressive pursuit and
commitment to develop meaningful drugs,'' said Gefter, a former
professor of immunology at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. Gefter left MIT to form ImmunoGen before starting
Praecis nearly five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, Abarelix would compete with Zeneca PLC's Zoladex
and Lupron, a treatment marketed by TAP Pharmaceuticals Inc. _ a
joint venture of Abbott Laboratories and Takeda Chemical
Industries. Those two products had 1998 US sales of $950 million,
according to Hambrecht &AMP; Quist analyst Alex Zisson.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer affects nearly 180,000 men annually and is
expected to cause 37,000 deaths this year. A major portion of the
diagnosed cases are in late stages, which often require surgery and
result in sterility. The slow-growing cancer is stimulated by
testosterone, and Abarelix is designed to reduce testosterone
levels without requiring surgery, Gefter said.
</P>
<P>
   Praecis, a 90-person company that has raised $90 million in
venture capital and private investment, has recently begun testing
Abarelix on women with endometriosis, a painful condition resulting
from abnormal growth of the lining of the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abarelix represents an exciting opportunity for Amgen to
leverage our success with Neupogen (which stimulates white blood
cell growth) in the oncology area and to establish a strong
presence in urology and gynecology,'' Gordon Binder, Amgen chairman
and chief executive, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's deal follows a failed partnership between Praecis
and New Jersey-based Hoffman-LaRoche that ended last year over
Abarelix, said Gefter.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which has climbed steadily since the
completion of a stock split last month, closed Wednesday at 70 1/2,
up 3 1/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
