A5669 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEATER-DEFECT-KAN &LR;      03-10 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATER-DEFECT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY BEGINS INQUIRY INTO DEFECTIVE PARTS FOR WATER HEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perfection Corp., the company that produced defective ``dip
tube'' plastic pipes for water heaters, has launched an in-house
investigation into how widespread the problem may be and whether
more should be done to publicize it.
</P>
<P>
   Perfection said it was reviewing its earlier estimate that only
about 15,000 water heaters made from 1993 to 1996 were affected by
dip tubes that failed prematurely _ a problem that can make the
heaters ineffective and clog other plumbing with plastic chips from
the deteriorated tubes.
</P>
<P>
   During those years, 24 million water heaters were sold, and more
than 90 percent had Perfection's dip tubes, which are designed to
funnel cold water to the bottom of the water heater's tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're intensely investigating the situation,'' said William
Mertens, an attorney for a Washington law firm that is representing
Perfection.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company is looking at whether more should be
done to publicize the defect. Critics have said the lack of a
recall or notification program has played down the extent of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it took several months for Randy Nicola of Olathe,
Kan., to get his water heater problem fixed. He was told by the
water heater manufacturer that his problem was sediment in the
heater's tank. He paid for four visits by a plumber trying to fix
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Then Nicola read a story in January in The Kansas City Star
about the dip-tube problem. He called the maker of his heater and
eventually got a new dip tube, and the manufacturer agreed to pay
for some of the installation costs and for flushing the plumbing to
get rid of plastic chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of a waiting game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perfection's in-house inquiry comes as legal maneuvers continue
to unfold against Perfection and the water-heater companies. Two
class-action suits in Missouri and Kansas, filed in January and
naming Perfection and two water-heater companies, have been
expanded to include all the leading water-heater companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Phalen, an attorney for the Independence, Mo., law firm
that filed the lawsuits, said another class-action suit would be
filed this week in Michigan, and another was planned to be filed in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is progressing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate move, a Birmingham, Mich., law firm filed a
class-action lawsuit last week in a Michigan state court naming
Perfection and several water-heater companies as defendants, said
Tim Arnold, an attorney for the law firm Ishbia &AMP; Gagleard.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Michigan attorney general's office is looking
into whether it should launch a formal investigation. Among the
issues is whether state consumer protection laws might have been
broken because those responsible for fixing the problem reduced
their exposure by doing little to publicize it, said John
Szczubelek, a Michigan assistant attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at it,'' he said. ``There are a lot of people
out there having a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Missouri attorney general's office said no
investigation was being contemplated at this time. At least one
Missouri resident, Steve Miller of Belton, said he had tried to
file a state complaint but was told it was a national problem.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Kansas attorney general's office said the
state would look into the issue but was waiting on paperwork from
one consumer who allegedly had a defective water heater.
</P>
<P>
   Perfection and the water-heater companies said they were intent
on fixing the problem. Perfection has been reimbursing the
water-heater companies for repairs. Its analysis of the magnitude
of the problem has been based in part on the number of repairs that
have been reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem, say critics, is that more consumers would have
complained had they known about the defect. Joe Gagnon, the host of
a weekend radio program in Detroit about appliances and their
repair, said the low-key approach had hidden the dip-tube problem.
</P>
<P>
   Since publicizing the problem in January, Gagnon said, he has
received more than 700 calls and letters from people who say they
have water heaters with defective dip tubes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, plumbers reported receiving hundreds of
calls after The Star's story appeared. Nationally, manufacturers
such as Bradford White said they were seeing increases in calls
from consumers who believe they have the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
