<HEADER>
A5670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NISSAN-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      03-10 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: WITH DAIMLER TALKS OFF, NISSAN HAS TO LOOK ELSEWHERE
FOR RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Germany, France, Japan)  (See also DAIMLER-NISSAN) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Once again, the future of Japan's second-largest car
maker, Nissan Motor Co., is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Wednesday by DaimlerChrysler AG that it was
walking away from negotiations about acquiring a controlling stake
in Nissan and in its equally troubled truck-making affiliate,
Nissan Diesel, ended one topic of speculation and debate only to
renew another: What will happen to Nissan?
</P>
<P>
   With known debts of more than $20 billion, declining sales in
two of its three main markets, a cost structure that is high even
by Japanese standards and uncertain plans for fixing its problems,
the outlook is grim.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan had little comment Wednesday night. ``It's true, our
negotiations about a tie-up with DaimlerChrysler have ended,'' said
Masataka Saito, a spokesman. ``Other negotiations about potential
tie-ups are continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   Renault SA, the French car company, has said it was talking with
Nissan, but those discussions were believed to be far less advanced
than the ones with DaimlerChrysler had been. Analysts consider a
deal between Nissan and Renault a long shot because of Renault's
relatively small size and its balance sheet, which, while much
improved, still bears a high level of debt.
</P>
<P>
   At the Geneva Motor Show, Renault's chairman, Louis Schweitzer,
said the company was proceeding with an in-depth study of its
options related to Nissan, although he cautioned that the hurdles
were high.
</P>
<P>
   Those hurdles _ Nissan's debts and its very traditional Japanese
management _ are what are believed to have stymied a deal with
DaimlerChrysler. ``I'm telling my clients that this deal broke down
because it could not get over the hurdles posed by the debt and by
the issue of control,'' said Peter Boardman, an auto analyst at
Warburg Dillon Read in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Boardman said, however, that DaimlerChrysler's exit did not
throw Nissan into any more of a crisis than it already faced.
``Nissan has many good qualities _ its engineering, its assets _
and it has positive cash flow, so it's not facing a crunch,'' he
said. Nissan already has established a $4.1 billion standby line of
credit with a group of 10 banks to help survive hard times.
</P>
<P>
   But many, including two former company executives, say that
Nissan is in a financial squeeze. Its banks, led by the Industrial
Bank of Japan and Fuji Bank, are not sound enough themselves to
lend it more money, and so it has kept itself alive by issuing
large sums of short-term commercial paper, which is bought by the
Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effectively,'' one analyst at an investment company said,
``it's moot to talk about a government bailout of Nissan because
the government is already bailing it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The government also has provided about $7 billion in credit to
Nissan through the Japan Development Bank, whose traditional role
has been lending for capital investment. That generosity has been
compared to the United States government's 1979 bailout of the
Chrysler Corp., which consisted of loan guarantees that gave the
company access to the money it needed to turn itself around.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan does have a revamping plan in place that pledges it to
slice 1 trillion yen of its 4.3 trillion yen in debt, including
liabilities related to auto financing, by next year. The company
has been selling assets, including its Ginza headquarters, a piece
of its textile machinery business and stakes in an advertising
agency and a printing company, but that is bringing in money at a
very slow pace.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently hired J.P. Morgan to advise it on
revamping, and the pace seems to be picking up. The Japanese press
reported Wednesday that Nissan was likely to sell its stakes in
nine cellular telephone companies, which could bring in several
billion yen, and it wrote off a small portion of its investment in
Nissan Diesel Sales Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Asset sales are necessary, analysts say, but Nissan has not
really tackled its cost structure. ``The end of the discussions
with DaimlerChrysler means they have got to get serious about
restructuring and that means cutting their costs,'' said
Christopher Redl, an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting costs, however, inevitably will involve cutting jobs,
which is more of a taboo at Nissan, perhaps, than at other Japanese
companies these days. Yoshikazu Hanawa, Nissan's president, and
many members of his board came up the ranks through the personnel
and human resources departments and are likely to be less disposed
to reducing the work force than their counterparts at other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The government, too, is concerned about Nissan's headcount, but
for other reasons than the investment community is. Including its
suppliers and affiliates and other related entities, most of which
are beholden to the parent company, Nissan employs nearly 200,000
people. Were the company to go under, some economists estimate that
Japan's unemployment rate, already at record levels, would jump by
one-tenth of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   One subtle prop the government might consider is encouraging
Nissan's banks, which are trying to clean up their balance sheets
at the government's behest, to forgo some portion of the car
company's debts in exchange for promises that they would be made
whole later or that such an action would not impede their own
revampings.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the government is constrained in what it can do.
Nissan's woes have received more coverage than the problems of
other corporate giants here, but there are Nissans in just about
every capital-intensive, labor-laden industry _ shipbuilding,
steel, chemicals _ in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Were the government to ``save'' Nissan, it might set a precedent
it would regret.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
