r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWYERS-FRAUD-KAN &LR;      03-10 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYERS-FRAUD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES OF MEDICARE FRAUD DISMISSED AGAINST TWO LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN T. DAUNER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ Eliciting cheers and tears from relatives
and associates, a federal judge on Tuesday acquitted two lawyers of
charges in a major Medicare fraud case.
</P>
<P>
   The case is of particular interest to the legal and health-care
community because Ruth Lehr and Mark R. Thompson, both specialists
in health-care law, were the first lawyers in the country to have
been charged in a Medicare fraud case as a result of their legal
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Construing the evidence in the light most favorable to the
government...no reasonable jury could find beyond a reasonable
doubt that defendants Lehr and Thompson willfully committed any of
the criminal acts charged,'' U.S. District Judge John W. Lungstrum
ruled at the close of the government's evidence.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge discharged the lawyers, Thompson grasped Lehr's
hand and exclaimed, ``Ruth, we got what we deserved _ finally!''
</P>
<P>
   That triggered a round of hugging, involving the defendants,
their attorneys, and friends and relatives. The jury was not in the
room.
</P>
<P>
   Lungstrum said that during a period of changing federal law and
regulations, Lehr and Thompson attempted to properly advise
executives of Baptist Medical Center in Kansas City, Mo., on the
do's and don'ts of legal relationships with physician brothers
Robert LaHue and Ronald LaHue.
</P>
<P>
   Along with three former Baptist executives and the two lawyers,
the LaHues were charged with conspiring between 1984 and 1995 to
solicit and receive more than $2 million in kickbacks in return for
the LaHues' referral of Medicare patients. The government contends
that the defendants attempted to disguise the payments as
consulting fees, and that Thompson and Lehr knowingly drew up sham
consulting agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The case also has generated national attention because it is
among the earliest trials brought about by the federal government's
attempts to attack medical fraud. Because of that crackdown, legal
experts say, the defense of doctors and administrators in fraud
cases nationwide has become one of the fastest-growing aspects of
the legal profession.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Lungstrum stripped away some counts against the
hospital executives _ Dan Anderson, former Baptist president;
Ronald Keel, former Baptist vice president; and Dennis McClatchey,
a senior vice president on paid leave from Health Midwest,
Baptist's parent. The dismissed counts alleged that the three
executives had conspired to solicit payments from other hospitals
besides Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Charges involving other hospitals stand only against the LaHues.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the trial, Lungstrum severed two other counts from
the current trial, which began Jan. 25. One count alleged that the
LaHues had filed Medicare reimbursement claims for services not
provided. The other charged Robert LaHue with witness-tampering.
The LaHues are to be tried later on those charges.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr and Thompson and their attorneys said Tuesday that they
would not have any public comment until the jury returned its
verdicts at the close of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. attorney Tanya Treadway, the lead prosecutor,
also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the jubilant observers were Thompson's parents, Clyde and
Nan Thompson of Denver, who have attended the trial regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Thompson, an oil and gas lawyer, said it had come as a
``shock'' when his son was indicted. The elder Thompson said his
son ``never should have been in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The start of the defendants' case was delayed until this morning
because a juror had a family emergency Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. German, who represents McClatchey, said the acquittal
of Lehr and Thompson could bolster the hospital executives'
defense. The executives contend they were following their
attorneys' advice when they signed consulting and other agreements
with the LaHues.
</P>
<P>
   Robert LaHue owned Blue Valley Medical Group and operated it
with Ronald LaHue, a former Leawood, Kan., councilman. Blue Valley
provided medical services to about 7,000 patients in 200 nursing
homes in Kansas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The government alleges that $150,000 a year that Baptist paid
the LaHues in consulting fees amounted to nothing more than illegal
payments for the LaHues' referral of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively little of the government's case related to Lehr, a
solo practitioner, and Thompson, a partner in the Kansas City, Mo.,
firm of Seigfreid, Bingham, Levy, Selzer &AMP; Gee.
</P>
<P>
   The defense contended that the lawyers' advice was based on the
information they were given and that they were not responsible for
monitoring how that advice was used.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence generally indicated that the lawyers repeatedly
warned Baptist that it must receive fair market value in any
dealings with the LaHues and Blue Valley; otherwise, the hospital
would leave itself open to charges of Medicare fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also warned that any consulting services that the
LaHues provided needed to be documented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
