</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-BREAKUP-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NABISCO NOW SEEN AS A HOT TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also RJR-NABISCO-JAPAN) 
(mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The breakup of RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. that was announced on
Tuesday may have satisfied a good many shareholders who had lobbied
for such a change for years. But more fireworks may be in store for
the separate companies that will be created by RJR's decision to
abandon its 14-year effort to run food and tobacco operations under
the same corporate roof.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts and industry experts think a contest could
erupt over Nabisco, the cookie-and-cracker giant that is mostly
held by RJR and is now renamed Nabisco Group Holdings. Many expect
Philip Morris Cos. to make a run at Nabisco, and some also mention
Pepsico, which made its first foray outside the soft-drink and
snack aisles in July when it spent $3.3 billion to acquire
Tropicana.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think that Philip Morris, which bought General
Foods in 1985 _ the same year that R.J. Reynolds Industries bought
Nabisco Brands Inc. _ and Kraft Foods in 1988, needs to expand its
portfolio of food products. Those now range from Jell-O to frozen
pizza to shredded wheat, a product that was acquired from Nabisco a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In both tobacco and food, Philip Morris has enjoyed more success
than RJR, dominating the domestic and international cigarette
markets. Though both RJR and Philip Morris face expensive
settlements stemming from lawsuits filed by smokers and state
attorneys general, Philip Morris has continued a healthy cash flow
and enjoyed a more manageable debt load than RJR, which labored
mightily to reduce the $30 billion in debt it inherited after a
hotly contested leveraged buyout in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Morris has gaps in food. Although its Kraft unit
sells chocolate and other confectionery products abroad, for
example, it does not have a niche in the United States in snack
food, cookies or crackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kraft is very large, but it is conspicuously absent from that
very important biscuit category,'' said Jaine Mehring, an analyst
for Salomon Smith Barney. Kraft's sales are about $27 billion,
compared with $8 billion for Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco recently won new affection from Wall Street as sales
rose for the first time in many months. And the spinoff of RJR's
domestic tobacco business, combined with the sale of its
international tobacco operations, leaves Nabisco essentially alone
and, some say, an attractive target.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't speculate on what will happen in the future, but
clearly, this new structure makes a sale a possibility,'' said Nomi
Ghez, a food analyst for Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   The president and chief executive of Nabisco, James Kilts, who
joined the company a little more than a year ago, used to run
Kraft. ``I'm sure his dream transaction would be to see a union
between his old love and his current love,'' Ms. Mehring said.
``And by the way, maybe he'd get to run the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Where such a deal becomes complicated, Ms. Mehring added, is in
the way it would be handled. An all-cash deal is possible, she
said. Nabisco's valuation is thought to be $17 billion. But if
Philip Morris did a stock swap, some might object because Nabisco
would then be back inside a tobacco company. One way around that
might be to spin off Kraft and then use shares of Kraft instead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``If you ask Jim Kilts why he left Kraft, it's not that he
didn't like the organization,'' Ms. Mehring said. ``He said he
wanted to be the CEO of a publicly traded company. If you believe
that, then in going to Nabisco he must have thought, in his heart
of hearts, that there was a chance that Nabisco offered some bigger
potential for him ultimately.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Philip Morris said the company would not comment
on speculation about any takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico, the other possible suitor for Nabisco, might also
benefit from expanding its snack-food line to include the brands in
Nabisco's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a perfect marriage of sweet and salty snacks,''
Ms. Mehring said. And the two parties might be compatible in terms
of their business systems, too, she added. ``The only company with
a bigger direct-store delivery system than Nabisco's is Pepsi,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico's rationale for the Tropicana purchase might apply to
Nabisco, too, although a spokesman for Pepsico refused to comment
Wednesday. Pepsico's chairman, Roger Enrico, said at the time that
Tropicana was a great brand that Pepsi could put to good use.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fits in with what we want to be, a company of big brands
staying within the beverage and snack business,'' Enrico said at
the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
