<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS FOR 20 GREAT YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ On the eve of the 20th anniversary of my
column's debut in this corner of the newspaper, today's effort is
offered as an expression of gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   It was March 11, 1979, when the first column appeared. This one
is the 3,425th.
</P>
<P>
   Its origins were in the mid-1970s at a newspaper in Dayton,
Ohio, but this is where the column evolved into a career calling.
Kansas City became home not only because the welcome was warm, but
also because The Kansas City Star was the culmination of a nearly
20-year quest to make it to the big leagues of newspaper
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of newsies are lucky enough to make the bigs early in
their careers. Not me. It took 18-plus years of seasoning in the
minors before the big break finally came. For a guy who never
wanted to be anything other than a newspaperman, the wait was worth
every single day of it. The Star was hallowed newspaper ground, and
this was a town so rich in history that songs celebrated its very
being.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, 1979 was the worst and best of times to start
a new job as a business journalist in a storied city. If you're old
enough to remember, you may recall '79 as the final year of a
dreadful decade.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't know it then, but the worst was yet to come. Events
were converging that would result in a three-year national
nightmare of hyperinflation, stratospheric interest rates and the
most wretched economy since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   The critical development of 1979 was both the source of most of
the country's subsequent pain and its ultimate economic salvation.
Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker dropped a bombshell in early
October by announcing a radical monetary policy change. Instead of
trying to keep interest rates stable, the Fed would henceforth
concentrate on controlling money supply growth while allowing
interest rates to go wherever the market took them.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it was one of the most momentous policy decisions
in U.S. history. The medicine was akin to giving a cancer patient a
near-fatal dose of chemotherapy because risking death to destroy
the malignancy offered the best chance to save the patient. Before
this struggle to wring hyperinflation out of the system ended, the
interest banks charged their most creditworthy borrowers topped 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   There were occasions, though, when quoted rates were meaningless
because loans were unavailable at any price. The misery began to
subside in late 1982, about the time many Americans had despaired
of things ever getting better.
</P>
<P>
   An economic miracle then sprang from the wreckage. Since 1983
only one shallow recession in 1990-91 has marred an unprecedented
expansion. Tens of millions of new jobs have been created,
inflation appears tamed, and rising incomes and technological
progress have combined to boost the U.S. standard of living to
unprecedented heights. Meanwhile, the Kansas City area has shared
fully in this era of national prosperity and appears positioned to
reap the bounty of more good times to come.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't part of my plan to make Kansas City home back in '79,
but this has since become the longest stop in this life's journey.
So, thanks again for the good times, Kansas City. You're the
greatest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
