A5678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES11-COX     03-10 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmakers: Bad service by airlines doesn't fly
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like angry passengers crowded around the ticket
counter during a delay, politicians are giving airlines a piece of
their minds.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration on Wednesday unveiled a plan to
ensure fair customer treatment and raise penalties for bad service,
adding to ``passenger rights'' bills in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The industry says the measures are driven by sensational but
rare anecdotes that obscure its good overall record.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-Texas) called the White
House plan a ``one-way ticket to higher airfares.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal doubles the cap on required compensation for lost
baggage to $2,500. It also doubles maximum compensation for
involuntary ``bumping'' to $800.
</P>
<P>
   The plan subjects airlines to fines if they fail to notify
passengers of flight delays as soon as possible. It requires them
to provide food and restroom facilities during lengthy delays and
disclose more detailed service policies.
</P>
<P>
   It's intended to ``put passengers first and make airline travel
a much more pleasurable experience for everyone consistently,''
Vice President Al Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore announced the measure on the same day the House
Transportation Committee opened hearings on a bill by Chairman Bud
Shuster (R-Pa.). It requires compensation for runway delays of more
than two hours _ a byproduct of the much-publicized snowstorm
fiasco in which packed Northwest Airlines planes sat for hours on
runways in Detroit, with no food or working toilets.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a Senate committee begins hearings on a bill by John
McCain (R-Ariz.) and Ron Wyden (D-Ore.) to make all tickets
refundable for 48 hours after purchase. It also stops airlines from
penalizing fliers who use ticketing loopholes to save money, and it
requires more disclosure about frequent flier award redeemability.
</P>
<P>
   The bills come after years of rising passenger loads and crowded
airports, which have restored airline profits but strained the
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been building for a few years,'' said travel expert
Ed Perkins, a consultant to the American Society of Travel Agents.
``A few recent incidents have pushed it over the top and now we're
hearing the 'I'm mad as hell and not going to take it any more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins predicted that not all changes will be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines, among other carriers, has
wrestled with service problems but contends most have been solved.
A spokesman declined to comment Wednesday, referring questions to
the Air Transport Association.
</P>
<P>
   An ATA spokesman noted U.S. airlines carried 611 million
passengers last year and only 7,994 filed complaints with the
government, although that doesn't include complaints made directly
to airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Travel Coalition, which includes some corporations,
said government action should be aimed at boosting competition
rather than policing service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
