</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLAWOM-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA POINT GUARD ALMOST ALL BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When UCLA's Erica Gomez signs autographs, she
never looks at the seeker.
</P>
<P>
   When she's inbounding the ball and young girls shout her name,
she doesn't look at them, causing her to be labeled arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   She often leaves Pauley Pavilion via a back door.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Arizona game (last week), I came out,'' she said.
``People said, `I've been waiting for you since your first home
game.' I feel kind of bad, but at the moment, I want to go home and
take a shower and be by myself. All that attention can be
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Even teammates say when one first meets her, her body language
says to stay away. They say Gomez's face is expressionless, like
she's ``numb to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``During the game, I'd rather be more focused on the game than
what's going on around me,'' she said. ``You have to be an athlete
to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez has led the Bruins to their second straight NCAA
Tournament berth _ they host Wisconsin-Green Bay Saturday at 9 p.m.
_ and their first Pac-10 women's basketball title.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez had to deal with attention early. In high school in New
Jersey, young girls wrote her letters seeking autographs and
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``She found it fun,'' said her father Larry. ``She would answer
every single one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   She found it difficult, though, when crowds stuck papers in her
face for her to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Her public, basketball life is well chronicled. Gomez was a high
school preseason Parade All-American, and one scouting service
listed her among the country's top 35 players. She led three St.
John Vianney High teams to New Jersey state titles.
</P>
<P>
   At UCLA, Gomez was Pac-10 Freshman of the Year and a Basketball
Times freshman All-American. After redshirting her second year
because of a knee injury, she returned last season and led the
Bruins to second place in the Pac-10, which earned her Women's
Basketball News Service's Comeback Player of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Gomez broke Ann Meyers' 20-year-old career assist
record. She has 555, 11 more than Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the key to our success,'' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier
said. ``For her to break the assist record in three years tells you
how important she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gomez is rarely seen at campus events. Most of her teammates
live in apartments that are walking distance from school. She lives
alone near the marina and prefers to stay at home, relaxing,
studying, spending time with her boyfriend or cooking Puerto Rican
food.
</P>
<P>
   When she makes an appearance, as she did for the men's game
against Syracuse, it's big news.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said, `Oh my God, you're here. We never see you
around,' '' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Her teammates know of a different side to her, however. Once
Gomez warms up _ and she says it doesn't take long _ ``Once I start
talking, I'll talk forever'' _ she becomes the team's big
instigator.
</P>
<P>
   Example: During the Bruins' trip to Washington in late February,
Gomez set up team wrestling matches, pitting the 6-foot-4 Janae
Hubbard against the 5-9 Michelle Greco.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the Don King,'' teammate Marie Philman said. ``Erica was
the first one to say, `In my room, 7 o'clock!' She wants to make
sure we're all wrestling. She'll push you into someone to start
something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was chanting. I was ranting, `Fight! Fight! Fight!' '' Gomez
said. ``I even did the part when the guy goes, `Ladies and
gentlemen! In this corner . . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez says she strives for balance in her life, which explains
the tattoo on her ankle _ the Chinese dualistic symbols yin and
yang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
