<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TORRE-ART-2     03-10 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TORRE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE DIAGNOSED WITH PROSTATE CANCER  
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TORRE-PROSTATE-CANCER) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Joe Girardi sat silently at the front of a
New York Yankees' team bus this morning, an island among teammates
who cheerfully anticipated the return of Darryl Strawberry in a
spring training game Wednesday afternoon against the Red Sox. This
was supposed to be a good day.
</P>
<P>
   But Girardi wondered how he would tell teammates the words Joe
Torre had just asked him to relay _ that Torre, who managed the
Yankees to World Series championships twice in his first three
seasons with the team, has been given a diagnosis of prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Torre told others in the organization Wednesday that his doctors
believed they had detected the cancer in its early stages, and he
underwent further diagnostic tests Wednesday that will help
determine the course of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees announced that Torre will leave the team for an
unspecified period _ perhaps only a week or two if moderate
treatment is required, perhaps three to four weeks or more if
surgery is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine,'' the 58-year-old Torre said in a statement
released by the Yankees Wednesday, ``and am looking forward to
taking care of this problem and getting back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, told
reporters this afternoon that Wednesday's test results were
encouraging. ``We might see Joe in the next two to three weeks,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Torre will come out of this like a champion,'' he said as
he waited at the team's complex in Tampa for Yankees players to
return from their two out-of-town exhibition games Wednesday so he
could speak to them about their manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have not named a temporary replacement for Torre,
and officials within the organization are hopeful he can continue
as manager this season. His coaching staff will collaborate on the
day-to-day workings of spring training. But if Torre is forced to
miss days or weeks of the regular season, Don Zimmer, the Yankees'
bench coach, now in his 51st year in the game, is expected to take
over.
</P>
<P>
   So as Strawberry went 1 for 4 in his first game since the
discovery last October that he has colon cancer, the mortality of
mankind once again was apparent in the Yankees' family.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's brother, Frank, required a heart transplant during the
1996 World Series. A week ago, Hall of Fame pitcher Jim (Catfish)
Hunter, stricken with the terminal illness named after former
Yankees star Lou Gehrig, arrived here to be with old friends.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, the legendary Joe DiMaggio passed away at age 84
after a fight against lung cancer and pneumonia. And Torre learned
late Tuesday night that a biopsy confirmed he has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer is second only to skin cancer as the most common
type of cancer found in American men, according to the American
Cancer Society. Cancer of the prostate, a male sex gland located
just below the bladder and in front of the rectum, is found most
often in men older than 50, and 8 out of its 10 cancer patients are
older than 65. The three leading treatments are surgery, external
radiation therapy and implantation of radioactive seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Torre was tested for prostate abnormalities during spring
training in 1998 and apparently was given a clean bill of health;
Torre did not require follow-up tests through last season. He had
another prostate-specific antigen test last month, as part of the
club's annual spring training physical examination, and the results
alarmed doctors. At some point, Torre had a biopsy, and for about a
week he waited for word from the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The father of four children, including 3-year-old Andrea Rae,
Torre left exhibition games in the middle innings on Monday and
Tuesday. He told reporters he felt sick and was suffering from
flu-like symptoms, and suggested that maybe he had caught a bug
from his mother-in-law. In fact, he was distracted, worried about
the impending biopsy results, others in the organization say.
</P>
<P>
   After learning of the cancer Tuesday night, Torre told
Steinbrenner, and at some point called Bob Watson, the team's
former general manager. Watson had surgery for prostate cancer in
1994, before joining the Yankees and sharing in the 1996 title. Now
we have something else in common, Torre said to Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Players had noticed a change in Torre's demeanor in recent days:
Usually upbeat, Torre had become quiet and reserved, and they all
learned why this morning. Torre informed his coaches of the
diagnosis at the Yankees' complex before two squads of players
departed for exhibitions here and in Bradenton against the Pirates.
He asked Girardi and the outfielder Paul O'Neill into his office
separately, and requested they tell the players of his condition
once they reached their respective destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi said he told Torre, ``Joe, our prayers are going to be
with you and we're going to do everything we can to be right
alongside you, and you tell me what you need and we're here for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he had no indication of it whatsoever,'' O'Neill said,
expressing hope that that meant the cancer had been caught at an
early stage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Girardi told the players once they arrived here; O'Neill told
the other players when they reached Bradenton. His teammates were
quiet, sad, Girardi said, almost too accustomed to these sort of
meetings now. ``After what happened to Straw,'' said Tino Martinez,
``you're ready for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chambliss, who managed the Yankees' squad here Wednesday,
spoke to reporters after Girardi did and mentioned that although
any form of cancer is bad for the body, prostate cancer is one of
the more treatable forms. The players seemed to hang on these
words. ``From what I understand, he's going to be all right,''
Derek Jeter said, three times.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee players are so intense and dedicated that for a few
days or weeks, they could probably manage themselves. But it was
clear Wednesday how much they would miss Torre if he couldn't
manage for a substantial period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a tremendous leader for us,'' said Girardi. ``He's
just really in tune with what this club needs and when it needs it
and why it needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just as big as any player on this team,'' said Martinez.
``We need him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre became manager of the Yankees prior to the 1996 season,
and as Steinbrenner is fond of pointing out to reporters, he was
not, at first, a popular choice in the media or among fans. But the
Yankees responded to Torre's leadership _ in tense situations, he
seems to become more calm, and his team played this way _ and they
won the American League East and then came back from two games down
to beat Atlanta in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, a native of Brooklyn, was New York's favorite son, and he
somehow managed to forge a strong relationship with Steinbrenner,
calling the owner whenever he sensed Steinbrenner was angry about
something. The Yankees suffered a disappointing loss to Cleveland
in the 1997 playoffs, but set an all-time record with 125 victories
in 1998, with a team known for its togetherness. They all came
together like family after Strawberry was diagnosed with colon
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Torre did not expect Strawberry to play until the final days of
spring training, and the manager's speculation to that effect
seemed to spur Strawberry: His personal trainer flew in from
California to join Strawberry, and the slugger accelerated his
workouts. On Monday, Strawberry met with Torre and suggested he
felt good enough to serve as designated hitter, and Torre _ masking
fears of his own at the time _ said yes.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry batted four times Wednesday, striking out on a
breaking ball from Boston's Pedro Martinez in his first at-bat,
grounding to first in his second at-bat, blooping a single over
third base and then popping up in the eighth inning. He swung
ferociously, and did not move well; he needs to strengthen his
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Playing again was fun, Strawberry said afterward. ``I feel like
I'm a part of it again,'' he said. ``I can't tell exactly where my
swing is yet, until I start playing a few games.''
</P>
<P>
   But Strawberry's joy was sapped by the words Girardi relayed to
the roomful of Yankees here this morning. ``It's a very sad day,''
said Strawberry. ``I really knew I couldn't be as motivated as I
wanted to, knowing Joe's situation. It touches your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   As it touched others. ``He's a guy who played the game,'' said
Jeter. ``He knows what it's like to succeed, what it's like to
fail. He's a players' manager and everybody loves him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves Joe,'' said Girardi, ``because Joe treats us
the way we want to be treated.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
