<HEADER>
A5686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUPONT-MARKETPLACE-50     03-10 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPONT-MARKETPLACE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A HALF-STEP FOR DUPONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paving the way for possible future acquisitions,
DuPont Corp. is taking a half-step to separate its giant chemical
business from its pharmaceutical, agricultural chemicals and other
so-called life sciences products.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than spin off life sciences as a stand-alone company,
DuPont said Wednesday that it planned to issue a new stock that
would track the performance of that fast-growing business, which
accounted for $4.3 billion of DuPont's $24.8 billion in total sales
last year. The company also confirmed reports that it is seeking an
alliance with a drug concern, but did not identify which one.
</P>
<P>
   A tracking stock _ also called lettered stock or targeted stock
_ allows investors to bet on the performance of one part of a
company. But ownership of a tracking stock does not represent
ownership of the underlying assets, as common stock does.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont will continue to run the life sciences company, own all
its assets, be responsible for its debt _ and, of course, share in
its growth. It is simply creating a company with two income
statements and one balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Since the tracking stock will trade separately from that of
DuPont, shareholders _ and potential merger partners _ will be able
to tie their futures more directly to the ups and downs of the
turbulent but fast-growing life sciences market. And they will
benefit from DuPont's deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lets life sciences benefit from the exceptional credit
strength of one strong company,'' said Peter Vermylen, an
investment banker at Salomon Smith Barney, which along with Credit
Suisse First Boston advised DuPont on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but is it good for shareholders? Or does it lull them into
thinking that they are investing in life sciences when, in fact, a
big, bureaucratic chemical company is still making the decisions?
Do they realize they have little recourse _ since they don't own
the assets _ if the company falls into financial trouble?
</P>
<P>
   And if tracking stocks are such a great idea, why don't more
companies do them? General Motors, US West, USX,
Tele-Communications Inc. and a few other big companies have tried
them, to mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   A tracking stock did not help USX realize much value out of its
Delphi pipeline. AT&AMP;T backed off a plan to create a tracking stock
for its consumer business in January after determining that its
businesses were too closely entwined.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tracking stock is simply a way to rip off future
investors,'' said Bruce Greenwald, a finance professor at Columbia
University. ``DuPont knows this market is putting crazy valuations
on tech stocks, and this tracking stock is just a way for it to get
dumb investors to overpay for part of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, which has long expressed interest in expanding in life
sciences, is not rushing matters. The company said it would
register the new stock offering late this year, and seek
shareholder approval after that to issue the new shares as a
dividend.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By then, many potential merger partners that it intends to court
with its new ``life sciences stock'' may have already found mates.
``The band is playing, everyone's on the dance floor, they'd better
hurry up if they don't want to be left out of deals,'' said Jeffrey
Cianci, a portfolio manager at Jesup Capital, which owns DuPont
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Clinton administration's proposed budget for 2000
includes a provision to tax the issuance of tracking stock as
though it were a sale of assets. It is by no means guaranteed to
pass, but if it did, the tax implications could be horrendous. In
fact, tax liabilities that would be caused by a spinoff are often
cited by companies opting to create a tracking stock instead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, DuPont's announcement garnered more kudos than pans. Its
shares soared $3.8125 Wednesday, closing at $57.375.
</P>
<P>
   ``DuPont is a textbook case of how tracking stocks can be used
in a positive way,'' said Robert Willens, a tax analyst at Lehman
Brothers who helped design USX's tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Ravitz, an analyst with Morgan Stanley, noted that if
DuPont shareholders did not like the tracking stock, ``they can
sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   DuPont's move may at least ease some shareholder pressure for
the company to split in two. DuPont has long insisted that its
chemical and life sciences business feed off each other's
technology and that the life sciences business needs access to the
cash and credit rating of the less exciting but more stable
chemical operations.
</P>
<P>
   But DuPont was a chemical company long before it was a life
sciences company, and old images die hard on Wall Street. Its stock
generally trades at about 18 times earnings; life sciences
companies, many of which have been growing 30 percent a year, trade
at 30 to 50 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   That has made it hard for DuPont, which has been on the
acquisition trail, to persuade life sciences companies to hook
their stock up with its own. ``The tracking stock makes it a lot
easier for them to use their equity as currency in deals,'' said
Frank Mitsch, an analyst at Deutsche Bank Securities.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, DuPont is said to be deep in talks with Monsanto Co.
about a possible merger, and DuPont reiterated Wednesday that it
seeks an alliance with a pharmaceuticals company. Many European
drug analysts say that Zeneca Inc. of Britain is looking to spin
off its agricultural business and that DuPont would be a logical
buyer.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, the alliances that DuPont chooses are the real
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracking stocks merely track the underlying business,'' said
Jeffrey Sechrest, a principal at Evercore Partners, a merchant
banking firm. ``They can't make it better or worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
