u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GUERRILLAS-AR     03-10 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUERRILLAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RECEIVES CORDIAL OVATION BY EX-SALVADOR FOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-SALVADOR) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador _ Sitting in the front row directly
across from President Clinton as he addressed the National Assembly
of El Salvador on Wednesday was Nidia Diaz, a former guerrilla
commander who is still barred from the United States for her role
in an attack that killed four American Marines here in 1985, during
the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   In the same row, a few seats to her right, sat Schafik Handal,
who led the El Salvadoran Communist Party and one of the five
factions of the former guerrilla movement. Interspersed in the
audience of legislators were scores of other former leftist rebels
whom the United States tried to crush in the 1980s through its
support of the El Salvadoran armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, they stood in business suits to give an American
president a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, reacting after Clinton's address with remarks devoid of
rancor, the legislative leadership of the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, now the largest opposition party, seemed to hold
just one grudge, that the United States has not invested in the
peace the billions of dollars that it put into the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States gave $400 million one year, an average of
more than $1 million a day, to crush the guerrillas,'' said Gerson
Martinez, a former guerrilla leader who is now first vice president
of the Assembly and on Wednesday shook Clinton's hand. ``If today's
investment were equivalent to that of the war, El Salvador would be
the most developed country in Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   El Salvador, a poor country of 5.8 million people that became a
Cold War battleground where 70,000 people died, was an American
foreign policy obsession until 1992, when peace accords ended the
12-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, on the third stop of a four-day trip to survey the
damage to the region caused by Hurricane Mitch in October, Clinton
noted that the ideological battlefield had been transformed into
``a marketplace of ideas'' and acknowledged the election Sunday of
Francisco Flores of the Nationalist Republican Alliance, or Arena,
as president. Flores was at the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   But side by side with the right-wing Arena deputies were 27
legislators from the leftist FMNL, which controls the second
largest bloc in the 84-member unicameral legislature and a large
number of mayoral posts, including the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to both sides, Clinton recognized that the American
role in the Salvadoran war had caused ``deep divisions'' in the
United States, too, and said the past should be remembered so that
it is not repeated. ``I hope the people of Central America see the
United States in a new way, as a partner, a friend,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who were targets of American intervention and who
fault the United States for helping prolong the war, the friendship
was welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we, as a legal political party, say, `I'm
resentful`?'' asked Dr. Violeta Menjivar, 47, a physician who said
she had joined the guerrillas after the National Guard had killed
an older brother and who lost six nephews in the war. ``It hurts me
to think of my dead, and I'll never forget them, but that doesn't
paralyze me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Diaz, the former rebel commander who still goes by her nom
de guerre, said Clinton represented ``a new administration that is
part of the historic justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some leaders of the front said they regarded the United States
as much a part of the problem as of the solution, for eventually
seeing the need for a negotiated settlement and supporting the
peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ms. Diaz, 46, vice-presidential candidate of the front, can
enter the United States only with special permits for specific
events. She said she was blamed for having ``psychologically
motivated'' the attack, but insisted that she had nothing to do
with it, noting that she had been imprisoned before the attack
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't harbor any hate,'' she said. ``Many Americans
supported me when I was wounded.''
</P>
<P>
   The cordiality is understandable, said Martinez, whose
decorations in his office include what he said were framed
scribbles from President John F. Kennedy given to him as a gift.
The 42-year-old legislator, who had joined the rebellion at 14,
said there were always mixed feelings about Americans in the
revolutionary ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could go to Chalatenango and see FMLN combatants listening
to rock or blues on the radio,'' Martinez said. ``There was never
xenophobia or chauvinism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be indifferent if a third part of the country lives
in the United States, if Central America needs help after the war
and Hurricane Mitch, if we're all interested in a new age of
commercial relations.''
</P>
<P>
   The single most widespread preoccupation for Salvadorans today
is the precarious status of Salvadorans who live illegally in the
United States and send money back to their families here. As
American aid dropped, now at $34 million a year, so-called
remittances grew, to $1.2 billion a year, becoming the largest
source of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed to do ``anything I can possibly can'' to end
inequalities in deporting Central Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
