<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIERS'-RIGHTS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Gore unveils plan to help airline passengers 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to complaints from air travelers, Vice
President Al Gore unveiled a passengers' bill of rights Wednesday
that would require airlines to be more responsive to customers on
everything from ticketing to lost baggage and flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater announced new
rules and proposed legislation designed to give passengers more
timely flight information even as a House panel heard testimony
about airline ``horror stories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are launching a brand new initiative to put passengers
first and make airline traveling a much more pleasant experience
for everyone consistently,'' Gore said at the White House event.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the front-runner for the Democratic presidential
nomination in 2000, is seizing on a popular issue of making
carriers accountable, just as legislation pushed by GOP lawmakers
gains momentum.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, criticized the Gore
plan as costly and ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new regulations represent a one-way ticket to higher air
fares,'' Armey said. ``Low air fares are giving more people than
ever access to affordable travel. ... The last time I checked,
federal bureaucrats aren't experts at finding lost bags or speeding
up flight delays.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Clinton administration's proposed legislation,
airlines would have to disclose their flight cancellation policies,
return lost baggage within 24 hours and give passengers 48 hours
after making a reservation to purchase a ticket, rather than
requiring instant payment.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would also double to $800 the amount of
compensation offered to ``bumped'' passengers and double to $2,500
the payment for mishandled baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Under a Transportation Department regulation that took effect
Wednesday, airlines must tell travelers what carrier they will be
flying under ``code-sharing'' arrangements that enable an airline
to sell a ticket on one of its partner carriers. The innovative
arrangements expanded travel options but also confused travelers,
federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department also required carriers Wednesday
to tell passengers if they will have to change planes on a trip.
</P>
<P>
   The administration package follows on the heels of efforts in
the House and Senate to respond with legislation that grew out of
outrage over the treatment of passengers in Detroit during an early
January snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, members of the House Transportation and
Infrastructure Committee's aviation subcommittee heard from some of
those passengers, many of whom were trapped on runways for eight
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have struck a raw nerve here,'' said Rep. Bud Shuster,
R-Pa., chairman of the House committee who introduced his own
passenger bill of rights legislation Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate Commerce and
Transportation Committee, has also introduced similar legislation
and will hold a hearing Thursday about the rights of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The embattled airline industry responded through its trade
association, the Air Transport Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the frustrations passengers experience from time
to time with weather and other factors,'' ATA President Carol
Hallett said in testimony she is to give before the Senate panel
Thursday. ``The airlines share some of those same frustrations.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallett said carriers would voluntarily provide more information
to the public and emphasized that ``satisfied customers are the
heart of our industry.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
