<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Column: Boom in Online Media Stocks Raises All Kinds of
Ethical  Questions  By Dan Fost  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
When the media mixes with money, funny things can happen.
</P>
<P>
   That's why most news organizations prohibit reporters and
editors from owning stock in companies they cover.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when journalists own stock in the company they
work for? And that stock represents a huge part of their current or
future fortune? And their stock's performance depends not so much
on earnings, but on market hype?
</P>
<P>
   The boom in online media stocks, which has turned many underpaid
journalists into paper millionaires, has raised all kinds of
ethical questions.
</P>
<P>
   Those questions were debated at a conference on online
journalism at the University of California at Berkeley Graduate
School of Journalism yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a roomful of millionaire reporters whose stake
is linked to the stock market, how can they cover the stock market?
How can they cover Internet stocks?'' asked Kara Swisher, who
covers the Internet for the Wall Street Journal. ``Newsrooms are
getting giddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Swisher said online writers are ``not the best journalists'' but
instead are ``linkalists,'' whose stories are basically links to
other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lewis, who writes for the New York Times Magazine and
the New Republic, noted his own blown opportunity to get in on the
ground floor of TheStreet.com. In 1996, founders Martin Peretz and
James Cramer offered him a 2.5 percent stake in TheStreet.com, with
an option to buy another 2.5 percent, in exchange for a weekly
column. He turned it down, choosing the Times instead.
</P>
<P>
   When the Times paid $15 million for a 7.5 percent stake in
TheStreet.com, Lewis said ``that implied a $5 (million) to $10
million value'' for the stock he turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of earning a ``modest sum'' from the Times, a
publication with 4 million readers, Lewis said he could be worth
millions of dollars working for a publication with 30,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   A few people in the crowd stood up to defend TheStreet.com,
including one reporter for the site. He said TheStreet does not
allow its reporters to own stocks. However, co-founder and star
columnist Cramer runs an investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MEDIA11 (90036 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The reporter said the New York Times business coverage is not as
good as the rest of its coverage and that TheStreet could give it a
leg up.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter, who didn't give his name, then said he shouldn't
even be talking because TheStreet is in a ``quiet period'' before
an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' response: ``I'm trying to get my mind around the idea of
a journalist in a quiet period.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MULTIMEDIA: &LR;  CBS MarketWatch doesn't have a print version, but
the financial news service exists in just about every other medium.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the San Francisco company, which already has a Web
site and reports for CBS television news, inked a deal to broadcast
short daily radio spots in 27 markets. Most of them are in smaller
cities, except for one big fish: 1010 WINS, the New York City
all-news station.
</P>
<P>
   ``WINS is the one we really wanted,'' MarketWatch chief
executive Larry Kramer said. Three WINS financial reporters at the
New York Stock Exchange will now report for all of MarketWatch's
various outlets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer still hasn't wiped the smile off his face since
MarketWatch.com raised $47.5 million in an initial public offering
in January. And why should he?
</P>
<P>
   That money has not only bought him a glass-top desk for his
corner office in the KPIX-TV building at Battery Street and
Broadway. It's also allowed him to expand his staff from 60 to 80
this year and expand bureaus in Los Angeles, Washington, New York
and London. Plans are in the works for a Tokyo bureau.
</P>
<P>
   With $800 million in market value, the company's stock is
valuable currency to make acquisitions. He's already in
negotiations with smaller content providers.
</P>
<P>
   How does he view his East Coast rival TheStreet.com? They've got
``half our revenue, and (almost) twice our losses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POURNELLE BYTES BACK: &LR;  After more than 20 years writing reviews
in Byte magazine, Jerry Pournelle was left without much of a
platform when Byte folded last year.
</P>
<P>
   CMP Media, &UR;  &LR; which bought the venerable computer trade
publication from McGraw-Hill, kept it going as a Web site only.
Pournelle kept writing his columns for foreign-language Byte sites
in Turkey, Bulgaria and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MEDIA11 (90036 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  This week, Byte rehired its legendary writer to put his column _
in English _ on its site.
</P>
<P>
   Pournelle, who lives in Studio City (Los Angeles County), is in
his late 60s. He refers to himself as ``Doctor'' after earning _
but never using _ a Ph.D in psychology.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was the first person to write a book using a
computer. He said the computer now resides in the Smithsonian, but
he can't recall the name of the sci-fi novel.
</P>
<P>
   Pournelle explained his writing: &UR;  &LR; ``You could subtitle my
column, `I do all these stupid things so my readers don't have to.'
I have probably run more bad software and more bad hardware than
any other human being on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRESSING DEADLINES: &LR;  Get ready for the stealth Web site.
</P>
<P>
   New York high tech PR man Don Middleberg, in town this week for
the Alley to the Valley conference, said many companies still
haven't realized how important the Web is in communicating with the
press, particularly in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Middleberg has helped one Midwestern pharmaceutical firm set up
a ``stealth'' Web site. ``It's not launched, but it can be ... if
and when there's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The company already has a Web site, but if a disaster strikes,
the company would activate the second site, which would have more
detailed information about the company, its products, photos and
media contacts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``When big news breaks, consumers go to CNN; journalists go to
Web sites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The San Francisco Chronicle.
Send buzz, dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com, call (415)
777-6004 or fax (415) 543-2482. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
