<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Citigroup Fans the Flames of Credit Card War  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A marketing war heated up in the credit card industry yesterday
when MasterCard named a Citigroup official to its board _ a month
after two representatives of the largest U.S. bank quit the board
of Visa.
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard International said it had nominated Citigroup
consumer lending chief Robert Willumstad as a director. Citigroup
hadn't been represented on MasterCard's governing body.
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard said it is also shrinking its board from 31 to 17
members to make it easier to govern.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination follows a dispute between Citigroup and Visa over
the credit card association's far-reaching marketing activities.
Citigroup has complained that Visa's aggressive advertising
competes with the bank's efforts to forge a separate brand
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Early in February, Citigroup co-Chairman John Reed and a second
executive of the bank left the boards of Visa USA and its
international parent after talks on the branding issue broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Association officials later said they were willing to accept the
bank's demand to move the Visa name from the front to the back of
the card but balked at the bank's insistance that it be exempted
from paying for some of Visa's marketing activities.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, currently the second-largest issuer of Visa credit
cards, confirmed yesterday that Willumstad's nomination to the
MasterCard board was part of the bank's broader switch of
allegiance from Visa to its rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe they are more aligned with our strategic
thinking,'' said Citigroup spokeswoman Susan Weeks. ``Over time, we
expect to increase the proportion of business we do with
MasterCard.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  While no longer represented on Visa's boards, the bank will
remain an association member and continue issuing Visa cards, Weeks
said.
</P>
<P>
   Visa, based in Foster City, and MasterCard are associations
comprised of thousands of members which actually issue credit
cards. The associations handle advertising, process transactions
and manage relations with merchants who accept cards.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of CITI11 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Neither Citigroup nor MasterCard would comment on the nature of
any agreement between them.
</P>
<P>
   Visa officials have said they expect Citigroup will pressure
MasterCard to soft-pedal brand promotion, letting its members take
the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, MasterCard insisted that it would continue to
market aggressively. ``Our relationship with Citigroup does nothing
to undermine the strong MasterCard brand,'' spokeswoman Sharon
Gamsin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gamsin hinted that MasterCard is relaxing its rules in
ways that might let members choose how much they want to take
advantage of the association's marketing activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which services members buy from us and how they want to use
the brand will vary widely,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Visa International spokesman David Brancoli declined to comment
on Citigroup's move to join the MasterCard board. He said Visa is
also considering proposals to let members choose from a menu of
services, though he said he didn't know whether paying for
marketing would be optional.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card specialists said the growth of giant financial
institutions with widely recognized brand names makes banks less
dependent on the associations, fundamentally shifting the
industry's balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially hard on Visa, which has a stronger brand name
than MasterCard. ``It's got to be very unsettling to Visa,'' said
Robert McKinley, chief executive of CardWeb.com, which monitors the
credit card industry.
</P>
<P>
   An executive appointment announced yesterday underscored Visa's
anxiety about keeping its biggest members happy.
</P>
<P>
   Visa USA said it hired IBM executive Bond Isaacson for a newly
created position overseeing relations with members and merchants
nationwide. Instead of working at headquarters, Isaacson will be
based in Charlotte, N.C. That's the home of BankAmerica, the
fifth-largest Visa issuer and one of the most vocal advocates of
change in Visa's marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of CITI11 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  A Visa spokesman described the location as a coincidence, noting
that Isaacson already lives in Charlotte and that most of the
bank's members are in the East.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of CITI11 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
