<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-Trade Moves Ad Account to S.F.'s Goodby  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-Trade of Palo Alto has tapped San Francisco ad agency Goodby,
Silverstein &AMP; Partners, creator of the ``Got Milk'' campaign and
Budweiser frogs, to come up with strong branding advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Goodby &LR;   &LR; succeeds New York's Gotham Inc. on the account, which
is worth $33 million to $42 million and represents one-third of
E-Trade's $100 million to $125 million annual advertising and
marketing budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole message of our advertising until now has been trying
to get the public to come to the Web site,'' said E-Trade
spokeswoman Lisa Nash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that the market is becoming increasingly competitive and
very fast-paced, it made sense for us now to focus on extending our
brand leadership,'' Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   The account is also a milestone for Goodby. ``This is our first
toe in the water of e-business,'' said Rich Silverstein,
co-chairman and co-creative director of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein said the tide of e-commerce advertising is heading
toward ``creative'' agencies like his that are known for building a
strong brand image for their clients. The agency is currently in
discussions with other potential e-commerce accounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade is one of many Web companies that are shifting their
focus to brand-building, said Drew Ianni, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications in New York. ``When you're in customer-acquisition
mode, you have to go to the media that give you most bang for
buck,'' often online advertising, said Ianni.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you're really just trying to build mass awareness, you
need to get out there in the mass media,'' said Ianni. ``I think
it's a great move to go after Goodby.''
</P>
<P>
   Ianni believes the focus will shift back to the Web in a few
years as Web businesses begin to concentrate on customer retention.
``Then you'll see more relationship-building through customized
programs (on the sites) and through online advertising,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Modem Media-Poppe Tyson is E-Trade's interactive agency of
record and Pickholz Tweedy &AMP; Co. handles its direct marketing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
