<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEPCS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-10 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEPCS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 The Great Computer Giveaway  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The personal computer, once a big-ticket item costing thousands of
dollars, has become just another home appliance, with prices
starting at under $500.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think that's cheap, just wait. It's only a matter of
time, industry observers say, until cable and telephone companies,
other Internet service providers and even computer-makers
themselves start providing PCs, or PC-like devices, for little or
no money.
</P>
<P>
   To get them, however, customers may have to sign long-term
Internet service contracts, agree to purchase thousands of dollars
in merchandise online or suffer a constant barrage of advertising
on their computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   Already, several companies have taken the first steps toward
turning the PC into a come-on. Connect Plus, a Massachusetts
supplier of cellular phones and other telecommunications equipment,
has started giving away eMachines PCs to anyone willing to sign up
for three years of Internet access at $29.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Free-PC.com of Pasadena plans to give away 10,000 Compaq PCs to
folks who agree to being bombarded with nonstop onscreen
advertising for two years.
</P>
<P>
   And a New York company, One Stop Communications, will give you
an Apple iMac if you agree to buy at least $100 of products each
month from affiliated retailers off its Web site for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The real push for free PCs, however, probably won't begin until
cable modems and/or DSL bring high-speed access within reach of
millions of potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   With such ``broadband'' access in place, consumers will have
access to a wealth of new content and services, including movies on
demand and live concerts that rival home theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Cable and phone companies looking to entice new customers for
high-speed services could subsidize much or all of a new PC in
return for a multiyear commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Other, even less-expensive devices such as Internet-only
appliances and set-top boxes a la WebTV also could wind up being
given away. Those now sell for about $200.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet-only device could take a  &LR; many forms, from a set-top
box to an Internet phone companion, said Michael Feibus, an analyst
for Mercury Research. Such devices would cost less than a PC and
therefore be easier to subsidize.
</P>
<P>
   Many free-PC programs probably will mimic the successful
approach taken by cellular telephone companies, which give away
phones or sell them cheaply in return for a customer's commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get a computer and we get a customer,'' said Tom Johnson,
a vice president of Connect Plus, which has patterned its PC
giveaway on the cell-phone model. He admitted that ``It's not a
very profitable deal for us,'' but said it has been invaluable in
attracting new customers who either had very old PCs or weren't on
the Internet. ``So far, the response has exceeded our
expectations,'' said Johnson, whose company has set a target of
10,000 free PCs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of FREEPCS1 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Far less promising than the cell-phone strategy, say analysts,
are the approaches being taken by Free-PC.com and One Stop
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Free-PC.com is counting on advertising revenue to offset the
cost of the PC giveaway, but that's an uncertain prospect because,
while the amount of Internet advertising is going up, the cost per
ad is going down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to sustain a model based only on Internet
ad revenues,'' said David Stremba, a PC analyst with Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   One Stop's strategy provides more ways for the company giving
away the PC to make money. Each month the company requires you to
spend at least $25 per shop in four of the stores in its online
mall &LR;  (www.shopss.com).  &LR; And each purchase includes a sizable
shipping charge.
</P>
<P>
   The One Stop approach, however, has a couple of big drawbacks
for the consumer. First, the customer has to be willing to cough up
$3,600 in online purchases just to get a computer that sells for
one-third that amount. And second, the company's online stores must
have items people want and offer prices that are competitive with
other online shopping sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it very difficult to see how that can happen at this
stage of Internet commerce,'' said Stremba. ``The average Joe isn't
spending $100 a month online.''
</P>
<P>
   If free PCs take off, it could mean bad news for PC retailers,
who might find it hard to sell computers when there are ads in the
newspaper giving them away.
</P>
<P>
   PC-makers, however, could wind up with a whole new channel of
distribution. Eckhard Pfeiffer, the chief executive of Compaq
Computer Corp., hinted last week that the world's No.1 PC-maker
could start giving away low-end computers as part of its effort to
become an Internet powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq could recoup the cost of the PCs through onscreen
advertising over the AltaVista Web site, which it is developing
into a major Internet portal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
