<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES SAG AS OTHER DEBT MARKETS SWELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities fell in price under the sheer
weight of corporate and municipal supply Wednesday, as big
companies including Lucent Technologies and Freddie Mac sold debt
to the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond fell 11/32 to a price of 95 20/32; the yield,
which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 5.55 percent, from
5.53 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Mac sold $3 billion of 10-year notes, and Lucent sold
about $1.4 billion of 30-year global bonds. Often, securities firms
handling such offerings sell Treasury securities as a hedge against
losses should interest rates increase before the corporate sales
find their way into the public's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Mac, which is second only to Fannie Mae in mortgage
financing, priced the 10-year notes to yield 5.81 percent, or about
five-eighths of a percentage point more than Treasury notes with a
similar maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae also said it planned to exchange 71 outstanding debt
issues with a reopened 5.125 percent five-year benchmark note due
in February 2004. It is the largest exchange offer Fannie Mae has
ever made to holders of its debt securities.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, the telephone equipment maker, increased the size of its
30-year bond offering through joint lead managers Bear, Stearns &AMP;
Co. and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. by 36 percent, to $1.36 billion,
selling the issue at a price to yield 6.49 percent. That is about
89 basis points, or hundredths of a percentage point, more than a
similar Treasury issue.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects of more corporate debt offerings in the next few weeks
are rising as higher-quality issuers line up to take advantage of a
strong economy, little inflation and low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. plans to sell $5 billion to $6 billion of bonds in
three parts as early as next week to help pay for recent
acquisitions. It would be the second- largest corporate sale ever
after the $6.1 billion MCI WorldCom sale last year.
</P>
<P>
   Market perceptions have changed, according to Robert Pugliese,
senior vice president and director of the fixed income department
at J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca Raton, Fla. Expectations
that the Federal Reserve would tighten interest rates havce
dissipated following recent data indicating that inflation is still
benign, so the market has now shifted from fundamentals to
technicals, and is trading on prices. ``This market remains in
decent shape,'' Pugliese said.
</P>
<P>
   The market for municipal bonds trailed Treasuries Wednesday, as
borrowers sold almost half the $5.4 billion of debt expected this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leading issues was a $700 million general obligation
bond deal by the City of New York through underwriters led by
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. That issue was initially priced to yield a
maximum 5.26 percent for a bond due in 2029.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Turnpike Authority sold $801.8 million of
metropolitan highway system revenue bonds through underwriters led
by Paine Webber, initially priced to yield a maximum of 5.27
percent for a 40-year bond due in 2039.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
