<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-POLITICS-1     03-10 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-POLITICS-1,025(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. DOLE, THE CANDIDATE, NOW MUST ANSWER SOME TOUGH QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related DOLE-2000)  
(nk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During her husband's 1996 presidential campaign,
Elizabeth Hanford Dole showed up, right on time, to tape a
commercial for him. She read the spot through once, off the
prompter. Then she thanked everybody and got up to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Even professional actors can go through a dozen takes at such a
taping, just getting warmed up. But when Mrs. Dole was called back
and asked to try once more, she seemed at first not to understand
the request, then took umbrage at the implication that her
presentation had been other than perfect the first time. Before a
third try, according to a sympathetic witness, she cleared the room
and proclaimed herself thoroughly humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   A long career in Washington has produced many such anecdotes
about Mrs. Dole: Ever professional and widely admired for what one
friend calls her ``superhuman discipline,'' she prepares so
thoroughly for public appearances that she even requires aides to
count the number of steps she must take to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Though roughly as fragile as Margaret Thatcher, she is also
famously thin-skinned, and has been known to burst into tears over
unflattering press. Even friends who think Americans might
appreciate a president with an extra measure of self-control after
the Clinton years wonder why she would subject herself to the
ordeal of running for the office.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview this evening, Mrs. Dole said, ``I've long
ago learned to deal with the slings and arrows of politics.'' And
if she does run, she said, ``It will be to make a positive
contribution to people's lives (and) to bring civility back to
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, when Mrs. Dole announced her intention to formally
consider a presidential run, in what would be her first bid for
public office, she appeared ready to become the country's first
serious female presidential candidate and a serious contender,
period. As a two-time Cabinet secretary, a former head of the
American Red Cross and an immensely popular campaigner for her
husband, former Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas (Remember all the talk
about how the wrong Dole was running?), she has stirred enormous
interest among Republicans, and has consistently done well in early
polls, usually placing just behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But now she will also have to answer two major questions: What
does she stand for? And can she stand the messy, uncontrolled,
often out-of-control political process that will decide who becomes
the next president? After decades in the public eye, she is hardly
an unknown quantity. But some in her party continue to wonder about
her politics _ and whether she is suited to the political life.
</P>
<P>
   Is she a centrist in the style of, say, her husband? Or do her
beliefs as a committed Christian put her politics more in line with
the religious right? Now 62, she became a Republican just before
she became Mrs. Dole, at age 39. And although she has repeatedly
thrown herself into her husband's campaigns, her politics have
remained ambiguous, if only because she has never run for office
herself.
</P>
<P>
   She said she defines herself politically as a mainstream
conservative and laughs at the suggestion that she is too much of a
perfectionist to handle a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been so overplayed,'' she said. ``I said in a speech
in 1987 that I considered myself a perfectionist, but I've really
tempered that extensively and there's no way I could have taken on
the issues I have if I had not tempered that.''
</P>
<P>
   And thin-skinned? Another laugh. ``I have to disagree with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends say she is running out of a real sense of calling, an
almost missionary zeal, and the theory of her campaign is this:
``Elizabeth has an opportunity to put together a new version of the
Reagan coalition,'' appealing to conservative Democrats and
independents, said Mari Maseng Will, another old friend and
longtime adviser. ``She's not forbidding in the way many
Republicans are, not seen as a threat to others' views and not
intolerant. A lot of women would be drawn to her in a way they
haven't been drawn to the Republicans in a long time _ and young
professionals, and eventually, the social conservatives.'`
</P>
<P>
   But the challenge will be filling in the blanks in that general
portrait of her: ``She's a tough lady; she's as hard as her
hairdo,'' said Alex Castellanos, a Republican consultant who has
worked for Bob Dole. ``And she'll be one of the serious contenders.
But until America learns where she would lead, she won't pass the
threshold test. There's always a place at the table for a female
candidate. But for it to become more than that, she has to have a
message beyond `I am woman, hear me roar.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Dole is an active Christian who schedules time for
daily prayer and who, friends say, is largely motivated by the
dictates of her faith, she has never been a particular favorite
among her party's base. Her husband was never eager to join the
abortion debate and seemed to put his foot in his mouth whenever he
did broach the issue, and Mrs. Dole's stated position that she is
pro-life but respects other viewpoints seems similarly wishy-washy
to some conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   She says her position is wholly unambiguous: `It's pretty clear.
I'm pro-life, with exceptions for the rape, incest and the life of
the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   But even her pollster, Linda DiVall, suggests that her position
is a little more complex, saying, ``I don't know that she wants to
overturn the law of the land,'' referring to the Roe vs. Wade
decision legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   And one religious conservative leader, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, recalls that every time Mrs. Dole has
spoken to his group, she has routinely excised references to
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd put the line in, it would come back taken out. I'd put it
back in, it would come back taken out. I'd say `Hey, this is not
the Chamber of Commerce.' But she never came through with the
applause lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some Republican consultants say they worry even more
about Mrs. Dole's flexibility than her politics, whatever they may
be, and wonder whether she's gaited for the free-for-all of a
national campaign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In ``Unlimited Partners,'' the book the Doles wrote together in
1988, Mrs. Dole described herself as a perfectionist from the
earliest age: ``I was a serious child, and eager to please. When my
second-grade teacher sent me home to fetch a forgotten book, I
considered myself such a total failure that I cried all the way
down South Fulton Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Idle moments were frowned on by her family, particularly her
father, John Hanford, a flower wholesaler in the small town of
Salisbury, N.C., who ``liked work and plenty of it'' and did not
much appreciate leisure.
</P>
<P>
   While writing with great respect for her father and her mother,
Mary Hanford, who at age 98 is still her daughter's best friend,
Mrs. Dole nonetheless drops a hint or two about where her
unforgiving standards come from. In her family, she wrote,
``Self-improvement was a measure of personal growth. It was also a
way to satisfy my goal-oriented parents. Piano lessons stretched
into 10 years ... My dance career was comparatively short-lived. As
the curtain fell on one performance, Dad turned to Mother and said,
`Mary, why in the world did you encourage her to take ballet? She
doesn't have a single curve!' ''
</P>
<P>
   At Duke University, she was so organized that some classmates
referred to her as ``Miss 3-by-5 Index Card.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, where she was among a tiny minority of women law
students, former Democratic congresswoman Patricia Schroeder said
Mrs. Dole was even more concerned than other women with the
question, ``Can you be a lady and a lawyer?'' Apparently, she
answered yes.
</P>
<P>
   Working for President Nixon's Office of Consumer Affairs under
Virginia Knauer, her boss found her trying to memorize reference
books to cram for her first press interview. Mrs. Knauer remembers:
``I told her, `You can't know everything, but the important thing
is, never try to fake it. Just smile and say, ``Great question.
I'll get back to you.'' ' And that's what she's always done.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Mrs. Knauer, who at 83 is perfectly sharp until the
questions turn personal, most of Mrs. Dole's close friends are
protective, careful and a little bit worshipful. One compares her
to Princess Diana, another says the country has never seen the
likes of Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But how to define her politics?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an excellent question,'' says her friend and adviser,
Bob Davis. `I want to defer on that.''
</P>
<P>
   If her political record is a blank slate, her record of public
service is ample, but mixed. As transportation secretary under
President Reagan, she was given credit for improving highway safety
with the ``Dole light,'' the brake light mounted in a car's rear
window. But she was strongly criticized for agreeing that there was
no need to re-hire the air traffic controllers fired by Reagan
after a 1981 strike.
</P>
<P>
   As labor secretary for 22 months under President George Bush,
she made friends with labor leaders but was also seen by some as
more interested in image than substance.
</P>
<P>
   At the Red Cross, where she served for nearly eight years, she
got high marks for raising money and vastly improving quality
control and oversight for their blood collection system _ after the
Food and Drug Administration pushed her into compliance by filing a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she has critics who see her tenure as a
disaster in the fight against the spread of HIV, because, as they
see it, she pandered to the religious right by taking the power to
make decisions about prevention policy away from Red Cross staff
and turning it over to the charity's board, with the result that
educational materials put more emphasis on abstinence than on safe
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Along with her own religious faith, friends mention another
major motivator in Mrs. Dole's life. They say that Mrs. Dole, who
married at 39 and usually says she would have welcomed children but
was not unhappy that she never had any, was in fact quite
disappointed, and resolved to channel the energy that might have
gone into child-rearing into public service instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``She resolved that, OK, that isn't going to happen, so she
substituted from the personal to the macro,'' said one friend.
``The children in Africa have become a meaningful substitute for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that she has ever been accused of failing
to give her work her all; but she seems never to have learned to
suffer imperfections in others, either. Those who have worked for
her say no one would dare fail to prepare for a meeting. Show up
twice without full command of the facts, and you don't get a third
opportunity to waste her time.
</P>
<P>
   A recent rebroadcast of a 1996 interview with Leslie Stahl on
the CBS News program ``60 Minutes'' showed Mrs. Dole shooting her
interviewer a downright scary look after Ms. Stahl slipped and
called her by her childhood nickname, Liddy.
</P>
<P>
   Why does she hate that name so much? Another question to be
answered in the weeks ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
