<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CONTEMPLATING NEW YORK'S TRASH IN A QUIET CORNER OF VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
 VA-NY-TRASH-ART-2TAKES-NYT  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUSSEX, Va. _ In this quiet corner of southeastern Virginia,
sturdy farmhouses command vast fields of peanuts, soybeans and
cotton. Slender loblolly pines poke through the flat, wet terrain,
like celery stalks wedged into a marshy bog. It seems like a Robert
Penn Warren poem sprung to life.
</P>
<P>
   But if this county is rich in beauty, it is also poor in
opportunities. For years, the courthouse had no indoor plumbing,
and so little space that defendants occasionally had to wait
outside before their arraignment. No new schools have been built in
30 years, and teachers had to make do with antiquated equipment.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Sussex County discovered garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the county embarked on a risky, controversial
path that many people believed would improve their struggling
economy, even though it would jeopardize their beloved environs: a
private, state-of-the-art landfill that would import thousands of
tons of garbage a day, much of it from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   A result, so far, is that the landfill, while still far from
beloved, now generates one-third of all annual local revenues,
enabling the county to hold taxes steady, build a new courthouse
and waste water plant, and break ground on a $600 million high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Sussex has found itself in the middle of a
multistate battle over trash that has once again prompted many
people here to try to reconcile their economic needs and
environmental concerns, pragmatism and principles.
</P>
<P>
   Trash has become a hot topic in an election year, with
politicians deploring Virginia's status as the second-biggest
importer of out-of-state trash. Egged on by Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's insouciant suggestion that Virginia should accept New
York's trash in return for the city's cultural and financial
contributions, the Virginia General Assembly approved legislation
last month limiting garbage imports. And last week, Sens. Charles
Robb, a Democrat, and John Warner, a Republican, reached across
party lines to co-sponsor a bill that would also restrict the flow
of garbage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most Virginians have applauded such antitrash, anti-New York
reflexes. But here in Sussex, one of several places in Virginia,
Pennsylvania and Ohio that import garbage, the reaction has been
more ambivalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather not have it, but we're caught between a rock and a
hard place, because the county is in bad shape and we need the
money,'' said Bill Jenkins, 40, a peanut farmer who was eating
breakfast at the Virginia Diner in Wakefield. He initially opposed
the landfill; now he tolerates it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else can we do?'' Jenkins continued, as the diner's
owners, Bill and Mary Ann Galloway, nodded. ``If we don't have this
dump, the next thing they're going to do is raise taxes on the
land. I don't see another solution.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, several of Virginia's rural landfills _ including the
Atlantic Waste Disposal landfill in Sussex _ faced no limits on
importing garbage.
</P>
<P>
   But under the State Senate proposals, Virginia would be able to
limit a landfill's intake, ban garbage barges on major rivers and
regulate waste more rigorously. That bill would become law on July
1 if signed by Gov. James Gilmore, who is squarely in the
anti-trash camp. The Robb-Warner bill, meanwhile, would restrict
the interstate commerce of garbage as well, and allow states to
collect fees on imported trash.
</P>
<P>
   Sussex officials worry that any reduction in trash revenues may
hamper an economy already sapped by declines in agriculture and
manufacturing, said Mary E. Jones, the county administrator.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5716 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  VA-NY-TRASH-ART-2NDTAKE-     03-10 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 VA-NY-TRASH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 SUSSEX, Va.: county administrator. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Situated 45 miles southeast of Richmond, this county of 10,000
has long struggled to get by. One-fifth of the county's residents
live in poverty, almost double the state average. The school system
perennially ranks near the bottom. The teen-age pregnancy rate is
triple the state average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The workforce is not that great, and you have a small working
pool to grow from,'' said Thomas Rose, 57, a lawyer who was having
lunch at the Thornton General Store in the village of Sussex.
``We're not going to get anything high-tech.''
</P>
<P>
   To compensate, Sussex has absorbed industries that more
prosperous areas would avoid: two state prisons, hog farms and, in
1994, the landfill in the county's northwest corner.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether to build the landfill sharply divided
the community, and in no discernible pattern; certainly not along
traditional lines of race (Sussex is 60 percent black) or politics
(Sussex usually votes Democratic). The final vote by the Board of
Supervisors was 4 to 3.
</P>
<P>
   Some are still smarting from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sussex counts on the money, but sometimes you've got to think
above money,'' said Rhonda Powell, postmistress of the tiny post
office in the village of Yale. ``People are tired of getting all
these things to get money, instead of getting something more
acceptable. You don't want to be thought as, `All we can get is the
dregs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Others, meanwhile, have grumbled that the county has received
less money than originally promised. But Ms. Jones said that
without the landfill, which has generated more than $12.3 million
total so far in taxes and fees, the county might have had to double
or triple the tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   Now owned by Waste Management Inc., the landfill covers 1,315
acres, or roughly the size of Central and Prospect Parks combined.
Up to 50 percent of its 4,200 daily tons of trash comes from New
York City; the rest is from Maryland, northern Virginia and
Washington. About three-fourths of the trash comes by truck; the
rest by rail, said Jerry Johnson, the site's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the dump itself, New York garbage is easy to spot: an ``I
Love New York'' bag here, a mustard-colored bag from a Chinatown
noodle shop there, New York newspapers all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the dump, it is easy to find Sussex residents who feel
queasy about the landfill's odors, the trucks lumbering down Route
460 or just the idea of the highest hill in Sussex (450 feet)
rising in their backyard.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was only a couple of weeks ago that a Sussex-bound
truck carrying New York City garbage overturned on Interstate 295.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stinking up the place,'' said Floyd Edward Hardy 3rd, a
Bronx native who moved to the town of Waverly almost a decade ago
and now works at a Hardee's restaurant. ``I think that every state
should take care of their own trash.''
</P>
<P>
   To gain perspective, New Yorkers should put themselves in
Sussex's shoes, said Tom Raines, the county registrar and a farmer
whose family can trace its Virginia roots to the 1600's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell New Yorkers that we like this landfill as much as they
would if it sat in the middle of Central Park,'' said Raines, who
was among the lunchgoers at the Thornton General Store.
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable to see why some Sussex residents are
prickly about New York. A couple of years ago, the New York Post
annoyed many people here when it described the county as a
``dirt-poor, dirt-filled'' place with a ``warren of tar-paper
shacks'' and potbellied residents who couldn't get enough of New
York's refuse.
</P>
<P>
   That is a bit unfair. Most people work hard to scrape by,
occupying small but well-groomed bungalows or mobile homes. They
take pride in their surroundings. They pray at the county's 60
some-odd churches, most of them Baptist. They also make this the
kind of friendly, leisurely place where a cup of coffee with a
stranger turns into a few cups, then some biscuits, then maybe a
full meal.
</P>
<P>
   But whenever the conversation veers from hometown pride, to
local affairs, to environmental fears, the same nagging conundrum
remains: Has the landfill been worth it?
</P>
<P>
   According to interviews with more than three dozen people over a
few days, the answer is a resounding ``Not Sure.'' On the streets
of Waverly, for instance, Thelma W. Wyatt, a former English teacher
who now teaches at one of the state prisons, initially voiced solid
opposition, then paused to consider the other factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand the smell; we're supposed to have clean fresh
air in the rural area here,'' said Mrs. Wyatt, 54, who supports the
proposed curbs on garbage intake. ``But I think people have
accepted it, because they definitely needed a school, and they felt
that they didn't have much of a choice but to go with this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the peanut fields of Stony Creek, Marvin Wachsman, a farmer
who harvests timber, peanuts and soybeans, straddled the issue as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got enough sense to know that we've got no other choice,
but we're a little afraid about what's going to happen to the
environment in the future,'' said Wachsman, 55, who was nuzzling
twin newborn calves under threatening skies. ``There are no easy
answers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
