<HEADER>
A5718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CORRUPTION-ART-     03-10 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CORRUPTION-ART-970&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 COMPLAINT OF CHINESE: ALL THIS CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEPU, China _ In a typical Chinese town like this one, the local
Communist Party chief rules with the authority of an old-time
mobster.
</P>
<P>
   Using the local police as enforcers, a party chief often cruises
around his territory in a black limousine, demanding a cut from the
most prosperous local businesses. When a day's business is done, a
chief may hold court at the town's best hotel, where a restaurant
and a massage parlor serve the town's top officials free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   He Jianlin, until recently the party chief of Hepu in Guangxi
Province in southern China, acted that way. And like his
counterparts in thousands of similar towns all over the country, He
organized a system of selling appointments to official jobs in his
government so openly that his prices were common knowledge all over
town: $10,000 to become a deputy party chief, $2,750 to be a bureau
chief, $2,500 to run a small neighboring town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying and selling official positions,'' as the practice is
known, is now a common phrase in the Chinese lexicon. In a town
where a family earning $100 a month is considered affluent, several
thousand dollars is a small fortune to pay for an official job, and
the prices roughly correspond with how much an official can make in
bribes in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   China's authorities like to portray corruption as the fault of a
few immoral individuals, rather than a symptom of deeper trouble
within the nation's stubbornly old-fashioned one-party system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet corruption is now virtually built into the middle levels of
China's vast authoritarian apparatus, under an ideology that has
become a hollow shell while the new market economy swells around
it.
</P>
<P>
   Westerners often decry human rights conditions in China, citing
political restrictions on writers and intellectuals in the large
cities. But for hundreds of millions of ordinary Chinese who live
in towns and villages, it is the unrestrained authority of a local
party chief that is usually most oppressive.
</P>
<P>
   Without institutional checks or balances to hinder improper
behavior, a local party chief can essentially rule the way he _
leading officials are overwhelmingly men _ sees fit. The growing
prevalence of buying and selling official positions points to how
extensively corruption has spread across rural China.
</P>
<P>
   ``An official job is like a piece of fruit,'' said a local
businessman in Hepu. ``You pay the money and it's yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Many ordinary Chinese are nostalgic for the days, only a
generation ago, when Communist ideology and enforced poverty
prevented anyone from getting rich. Public opinion surveys
regularly find that corruption is overwhelmingly the No. 1 concern.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese people disagree over the degree to which corruption
exists at the very top of the Communist Party. President Jiang
Zemin and Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, for instance, appear to be
personally upright officials who are alarmed by the extent of
corruption, though they are unwilling to change the system that
perpetuates it.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, buying and selling official positions has become so
rampant, and such a cause of public discontent, that even Beijing's
top leaders are publicly denouncing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it possible that official positions are openly labeled with
a price?'' Prime Minister Zhu asked at a meeting addressing the
issue in January. ``This problem must be given serious attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Zhu visited this region along China's southern
coast, long known for uncontrolled smuggling of cars, oil and
cigarettes, often undertaken by local leaders like He with
cooperation from the police or the military.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Zhu could do little more than exhort officials to more
honesty and integrity, since genuine political reform is still
unacceptable to Communist Party leaders, who fear that it would
inevitably threaten their own rule.
</P>
<P>
   He, 45, amassed hundreds of thousands of dollars by selling more
than 60 positions, businessmen in Hepu say. A short, taciturn man
with a plodding, cautious nature, He tried to hide his growing
fortune in real estate and in a number of separate bank accounts,
many of them in the names of his mistresses.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the illicit money taken by He and his cronies is
evident on a street at the edge of town that is lined by opulent
townhouses with ornate doorways and fancy patios, all homes of
local officials. Townspeople call it ``corruption street.''
</P>
<P>
   An official report on He, whose downfall came only after leaders
in Beijing decided to make an example of him, cataloged a few of
the cases in which officials paid him cash in exchange for job
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the report said, an official named Xu Lifa from a
village near Hepu called on He and left a shopping bag with two
cartons of imported cigarettes and several bricks of cash, totaling
30,000 yuan, worth about $2,750, beside He's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Xu was soon appointed to head Hepu's finance bureau, even though
he had no experience in finance and the incumbent had no plans to
move. When the incumbent official opposed the appointment, he was
transferred to a lesser position in a nearby county.
</P>
<P>
   In February, He was found guilty of selling official positions
and taking other bribes worth more than $50,000. He was sentenced
to eight years in prison. Three other officials were also convicted
of bribery.
</P>
<P>
   What He said in his own defense, if anything, remains secret. He
is now in jail in the provincial capital, Nanning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years is a pretty light sentence for his crimes, so his
connections must still be pretty good,'' another local businessman
said. ``They did not confiscate his property, or go after his
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   He often deputized his wife, Zhang Siyi, to collect his bribes,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called her `cash bag Siyi', '' the businessman said. ``She
was very unpleasant.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An obvious question is whether He shared his illicit earnings
with any of his superiors in Nanning, where he moved in 1997 when
he was promoted to a new position. Another question is how He got
away with his antics for so long, so openly, and why he finally
came under suspicion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The official report said complaints ``from the masses'' had led
to an investigation. But local businessmen said his actions were
pretty typical for a county chief, up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   Only when He hired an attractive 18-year-old prostitute as his
``secretary,'' frequently taking her on trips out of town, did
townspeople start to think he had gone too far. Someone, perhaps a
rival, reported his actions to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   When an investigation team from the central government's
discipline inspection committee arrived in Hepu last year, it was
clear to many people here that his days were numbered.
</P>
<P>
   But his case was hardly unique. Dozens of other cases of buying
and selling official positions have been reported in China's
official media in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Exasperated that his young escort was apparently his undoing, He
complained to friends that he had spent more than $40,000 on her to
keep her happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
