<SLUG> BC-DOCKERS-AD-COLUMN-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MAKING KHAKIS SEXY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a khakis counterattack, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. is responding to
inroads made by competitors by portraying its Dockers line of
casual pants for men in a far more sensual and youthful manner.
</P>
<P>
   The retailoring of the image for Dockers, which have been
rebranded as Dockers Khakis to capitalize on the craze for cotton
slacks, intensifies this week with a campaign by the San Francisco
office of Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding. The budget for mass media
advertising is being increased 12 percent from the estimated $20
million to $30 million spent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the makeover is a pair of television
commercials that focus on romance between beefy boys and tasty
ladies in the offbeat locales of a seedy carnival and a funky
nightclub. The sex-drenched spots suggest that Dockers Khakis are
the millennial version of Brylcreem in that just as ``a little
dab'' of hair dressing once attracted hordes of willing women, now
it takes the right pants.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is indicative of the Herculean efforts that Levi
Strauss is taking to alter perceptions of its products and imbue
them with qualities that would appeal to teen-agers and men in
their 20s and 30s. Those consumers have been bypassing Levi Strauss
brands for labels like Gap, Fubu, Banana Republic, Tommy Hilfiger
and JNCO.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul includes new advertising for the flagship Levi's
denim jeans; new offerings like Dockers K-1 Khakis, with retro-chic
styling billed as ``cut from the original cloth''; sponsorship of
concerts and musicians; product placement in movies and television
series, and promotions aimed at niche markets like women, blacks,
fans of independent films and gay men and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The new Dockers Khakis campaign ``reflects the challenge at
hand,'' said Vince Tarani, marketing director for Dockers Khakis
USA at Levi Strauss in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great franchise with men 35-plus, who we must
keep,'' he added, ``and at the same time be more relevant to the
25- to 34-year-old'' as well as ``a secondary market of 18 to 24.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still the leader in the khakis category,'' he added,
``but of course ever since it got hot, a lot of people are coming
into it, and that increases the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are purposely different from previous Dockers
pitches that carried pleasant themes, like ``Nice pants,'' that
were intended to appeal to men by presenting average-looking models
_ the buff need not apply _ in identifiable situations, like
playing golf or traveling for business. The goal now, though, is to
make the spots slick and provocative enough to have viewers believe
they may be eavesdropping on the exploits of the older brothers of
the Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch catalog crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to do it right,'' said Chris Shipman, senior vice
president and group creative director at Foote, Cone San Francisco,
which is part of True North Communications. ``A brand trying to be
cool and failing is worse than an uncool brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Dockers Khakis were being perceived as ``your father's
pants,'' he added, ``we needed to push the sexiness a little
overboard'' in the commercials to ``open the doors to a lot of guys
who never thought Dockers would be appropriate for them.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in the carnival spot, when a model strips to his khakis to
try the dunk tank, there are lingering shots of the clinging wet
pants and his chiseled torso; one could, it seems, bounce a quarter
off his abdominal muscles and get a dime back in change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've left the golf course on this one,'' Tarani said, adding
that though the model ``is not a regular guy in the street, he's
quite credible for the brand.'' (The women in the spot are no
slouches in the hubba-hubba department, either, in displaying their
sultry charms.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The sensuality is even more pronounced in the nightclub spot, in
which a hip-hop hunk is so besieged by beautiful women that he has
to spend the night dancing with all his fans. Come the dawn, he
emerges from the club and steps into a taxicab, only to hear the
same song he has danced to all night and see a gorgeous driver with
a come-hither look in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Shipman said, the nightclub spot will run only after 9
p.m. because of a shot of one dancer's leg wrapped around
another's.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign represents an abrupt shift from a more traditional
approach in one that the agency created last year. One commercial
from that campaign, for instance, was centered on a man rescuing
his girlfriend from a mouse. The 1998 campaign was suddenly cut
short and replaced with a playfully sexy spot created by another
Levi Strauss agency, Bartle Bogle Hegarty in London. That spot
showed buff swimmers who doffed their Dockers to surf and then used
their surfboards to iron their pants.
</P>
<P>
   Shipman, who will soon leave Foote, Cone San Francisco to work
on freelance projects in advertising and perhaps entertainment,
described the new campaign as ``the end of a couple years' work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've positioned Dockers to be ready for this,'' he added.
``The spots have a fantasy appeal, but also a universal aspect you
can relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarani agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get it right, and we will, we'll have the brand set up
for the next three to five years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All that is predicated, however, on the success of the makeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to the brand that the image shifts,'' Shipman
said.
</P>
<P>
   One way to accomplish that would be to rename the brand Dockers
Khakis San Francisco. Imagine how alluring the ``DKSF'' label would
be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
