<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW JONES AND S&AMP;P 500 ESTABLISH RECORD HIGHS
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index set new highs as oil prices soared, but concerns
about technology-company earnings crimped gains in the Nasdaq
composite index. The Dow climbed 79.08 points, to 9,772.84,
surpassing its previous high of 9,736.08, set last Friday. The Dow
is up 6.44 percent for the year. The S&AMP;P 500 set its second record
of the week, adding 7 points, to 1,286.84. Nasdaq added 13.06
points, to 2,406.00.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell under the sheer weight of corporate and
municipal supply. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to
5.55 percent, from 5.53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH BANKS CRITICAL OF RIVAL'S BID
</P>
<P>
   Two of France's biggest banks, Paribas and Societe Generale,
said in a statement that a $37 billion takeover offer by their big
French rival, Banque Nationale de Paris, was a ``hazardous
venture.'' They vowed to study the bid and then convene their
boards.
</P>
<P>
   SEARS SETTLES CREDIT CARD SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck said that it would settle a class-action suit
from plaintiffs who contended that the retailer had fraudulently
raised the annual interest rates on their credit cards after it had
promised not to. The company agreed to pay $36 million in cash and
issue store coupons worth $118 million.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup joined the board of Mastercard, a month after leaving
Visa's board as competition between the groups intensifies.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT LAWYER ASSESSES TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders may think that Microsoft is faring badly in its
antitrust trial. But the case is actually going Microsoft's way,
according to an internal assessment sent by a senior lawyer to
company executives last week.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and 3Com intend to announce an alliance today to
jointly develop products to connect personal computers and computer
peripherals within homes.
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM ITALIA WEIGHS ITS DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Honing its weapons in the fight to fend off a $60 billion
hostile bid, the board of Telecom Italia met to discuss strategies
intended to make the cost of a takeover too costly for its pursuer,
Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILIAN BANKER OPTIMISTIC
</P>
<P>
   Arminio Fraga, the new president of Brazil's central bank,
promised to reduce the growing public debt brought on by the
financial crisis. He also said Brazil would return to the capital
markets in a matter of weeks as the worst of the ``recent
turbulence'' had passed. He spoke hours before he and other top
Brazilian officials embarked on a trip to financial capitals to
explain Brazil's latest austerity measures and seek a reopening of
credit lines.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE FOR RJR UNIT SEEN AS HIGH
</P>
<P>
   The $8 billion that Japan Tobacco agreed to pay for the
international tobacco business of RJR Nabisco was about $1.5
billion more than RJR had expected to get, leaving many grumbling
that Japanese companies had failed to learn any lessons from their
last spending spree, when they were notorious for overpaying for
overseas assets.
</P>
<P>
   MEASURE ON ATM FEES ADVANCES
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into consumer anger, the House Banking Committee
approved a bill that would require clear disclosure of any
surcharges for using automated teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN SEES NO DELAY FOR IVILLAGE
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs, the lead underwriter, said iVillage's planned
initial public offering would not be delayed by a lawsuit filed by
a former employee against the company, which operates an Internet
site for women.
</P>
</TEXT>
