<HEADLINE>
RCA DOME IS HOUSE OF DREAMS FOR DAVIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The RCA Dome, as the sight of its 1996
first-round loss to Princeton, holds horrific memories for UCLA.
But for sophomore guard Baron Davis, it's the most treasured
building in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was an unknown 5-foot-8 high school junior-to-be when he
arrived at the Nike Camp here in the summer of 1995. He left a week
later as one of the most coveted players in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most defining point in my career,'' Davis said.
``It was the first opportunity I had to show the nation and the
college coaches that I could play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until then, no one had ever seen me play. Nobody was
recruiting me. I was at Crossroads (a small school in Santa
Monica), and I was small. But when I got out of there, everyone was
sending me letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis wasn't considered good enough for the West team _ which
included Kenny Brunner, Mike Bibby and Chris Burgess, Jason and
Jarron Collins and Eric Chenowith _ so he played for the Southeast.
Despite nerves, he performed well enough in his first game (against
Brunner and Bibby) to attract attention from recruiters. At week's
end, he was selected for the prestigious underclass game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That week is still my most vivid memory,'' he said. ``I walked
in and saw the lights and it was everything I dreamed about Nike
Camp. The lights, the huge dome, the college coaches and all the
players you read about. I was hungry. I wanted to prove I could
play, that I belonged in at least the top 200 players.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Health report: Davis will wear a metal plate in his right
shoe to protect his sprained middle toe. Otherwise, he's ready to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine,'' he said. ``It's tournament time. It's no time for
excuses or being babies. Even though it's aching, I've got to be a
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve guard Ray Young will play despite lingering soreness
from a hip pointer suffered last week at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I'm not playing is if somebody tries to
assassinate me,'' said Young, whose presence is critical to UCLA's
pressure defense. ``The most painful thing is the first step when I
cut. But it's nothing that will affect my game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Late night: The Bruins practiced at home Tuesday morning and
did not arrive in Indianapolis until 11:30 p.m. It was one of the
smartest moves UCLA has made all season.
</P>
<P>
   By flying late, they avoided the delays, cancellations and
airport closures caused by a massive winter storm that dumped a
foot of snow in some parts of the Midwest. They connected in Denver
and landed here on time.
</P>
<P>
   But the late arrival, combined with the time change, meant
several players were awake until 5 or 6 a.m. Matt Barnes and Baron
Davis played video games, while JaRon Rush watched two movies _
``American History X'' and ``Face Off,'' which he now has seen five
times.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ready for action: Reserve shooting guard Brandon Loyd has
sufficiently recovered from the bruised right (shooting) hand that
kept him out of the Arizona game. He and reserve Ryan Bailey are
preparing for extended minutes tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bailey because of his experience and Brandon because he's hit
big shots for us,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said. ``Those two could
end up being critical. I may start Bailey because he played in the
Big Ten (for Penn State in 1996-97), and he could help us deal with
the pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
