<SLUG> BC-LAND-CONSERVATION-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS OF ALL PERSUASIONS RALLY ROUND RIVAL BILLS TO PROTECT
LANDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Mich., Calif., La., Ala.)   (rk) 
 By   JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sensing widespread support for programs to preserve
open spaces, lawmakers from both parties have offered competing
proposals that exceed even the Clinton administration's record $1.1
billion request to protect open land from development.
</P>
<P>
   But while many liberal Democrats and conservative Republicans
alike say they want to conserve land, their proposals are starkly
different, complicating negotiations on what may become the biggest
environmental spending program to emerge this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers favor spending most of the money in coastal
states, where offshore drilling for oil and gas produce the federal
revenue to pay for land conservation. Some would put large sums
into fish and wildlife programs that benefit hunters, or in
habitats for endangered species. Some would emphasize buying lands
in the eastern states, where the federal government owns relatively
little land.
</P>
<P>
   And the proposals differ in how much power they delegate to the
states, even allowing some of the money to be spent on development
rather than conservation.
</P>
<P>
   But the differences serve mainly to underscore the political
popularity of spending more on conservation, demonstrated by the
success across the country of ballot measures to buy open space and
preserve it for the public good.
</P>
<P>
   However the pending proposals are designed, they all would
commit the federal government to spending billions of dollars on
land purchases for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few lonely dissenters, mostly advocates for the rights of
property owners, are complaining that there is already too much
land in public hands. Environmental groups are generally
enthusiastic as long as the programs are not designed to encourage
more offshore drilling, which they oppose.
</P>
<P>
   And at hearings that began on Tuesday, Rep. Don Young, the House
Resources Committee chairman, who usually sides against
environmentalists and with property owners, said bluntly, ``We do
not need a quid pro quo from these groups to validate our
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the committee plunged into the wheeling and dealing
over how much to spend, and how to spend it.
</P>
<P>
   Federal land conservation programs are paid for by royalties
collected by the government from offshore leases for oil and gas
drilling. For years, the government has collected far more from
these leases than it has spent on conservation, using the rest of
the revenue to reduce the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the deficit is gone, the Clinton administration and
Congress both seem ready to spend more of the oil revenue on
conservation.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed to more than double conservation
spending next year. The $1.1 billion he would spend is a record
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Mary L. Landrieu, D-La., and Frank H. Murkowski, R-Ala.,
have introduced a bill in the Senate to spend $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Young, R-Alaska, and Representative John D.
Dingell, D-Mich, want to spend $1.7 billion. And two California
Democrats, Rep. George Miller and Sen. Barbara Boxer, have proposed
spending $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At the House hearing, Young, the committee chairman, and Miller,
the ranking minority member _ who have fought many battles over
their environmental views _ committed themselves to working
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not allow this debate to descend into sniping at each
other's bills or motives,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech last week, Clinton also promised to work with
Congress to create a guaranteed fund for protecting land.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The main conduit for the proposals is the Land and Water
Conservation Fund, a trust fund that pays for public purchases of
land. In the past, it has spent little more than $300 million a
year, far less than what is collected in royalties from drilling.
And it shared almost nothing with state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed spending $642 million from the conservation
fund in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, two-thirds of it in
direct federal purchases and one-third in federal contributions to
states that would buy land themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Young's bill would spend $540 million, half of it by the federal
government and the rest by the states. His bill would require that
one-third of the direct federal land purchases be in Eastern
states; Young believes that too much of the West, especially his
home state of Alaska, is already in federal hands.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's bill would spend $900 million, half in direct federal
land purchases and half in money to the states.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other significant differences, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Young's bill, like the Senate bill, would provide huge amounts
to coastal states for a wide variety of programs that he says they
need to compensate for the effects of offshore drilling. That might
include projects for water quality, fish and wildlife habitat or
other natural resources. But it might also help pay for public
works projects that assist the drilling industry or the communities
that support it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
