Barbour, a physicist and theologian, at the United Nations Church
Center on Wednesday. The world's largest monetary prize, the
Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion, will be awarded to
Barbour who has devoted four decades to fostering a dialogue
between science and religion. His selection as recipient of the
prize, valued at 750,000 British pounds, or about $1.24 million,
was announced at a news conference Wednesday at the Church Center.
(G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SUSSEX, Virg. -- March 10, 1999 -- VA-NY-TRANSIT, 3-10
-- Trash from New York City fills a land fill in rural Virginia.
Five years ago, Sussex County embarked on a controversial path that
many people believed would improve their struggling economy while
jeopardizing their beloved environs: accepting a private,
state-of-the-art landfill that would import thousands of tons of
garbage a day, much of it from New York City. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
