hybrid billboard in SoHo. As New York's construction boom spreads,
advertisements for carriage rentals and patent medicines painted on
brick walls previously hidden by buildings appear suddenly, flashes
of the past, when a building is razed. ``People are noticing them
more and more,'' says Linda Cooper Bowen, who wrote an article on
signs in the current issue of Print magazine. (Marilynn K. Yee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- March 10, 1999 -- FOOD-REICHL-B&AMP;W, 3-10 -- A
wig and glasses used as disguises by New York Times food critic
Ruth Reichl to ward off special attention while sampling a
restaurant's attributes. Reichl surprised colleagues in January
with the announcement that she would leave the Times after 5 1/2
years to revamp sleepy Gourmet magazine. Considered one of the most
influential voices in the food world, Reichl writes reviews that
are read as much for lively cultural commentary as for her
dissection of restaurant pretentions. (Janet Knott/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRINCE WILLIAM SOUND, Alaska -- March 10, 1999 --
EXXON-SPILL, 3-10 -- Biologist Bruce Wright holds a piece of
contaminated soil commonly found along the area known by locals as
the ``Death Marsh.'' The Exxon Valdez dumped 10.8 million gallons
of thick, crude oil into the water near here 10 years ago after
running aground. Only two of the 23 most damaged species have fully
recovered and an estimated 40 percent of the fishermen suffer
depression over their decimated livelihoods. (Mark Wilson/Boston
Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) KOTLINA, Yugoslavia -- March 10, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 3-10 --
A doctor working for a humanitarian aid group checks a baby on
Wednesday who was born the previous day at a school turned into a
refugee shelter in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province. The baby's mother,
Minadije Loki, an ethnic Albanian who fled from a nearby village
which was being shelled, looks on at right. Despite pressure from
senior U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and the threat of NATO
airstrikes, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic rejected NATO
forces to police a Kosovo peace agreement. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 10, 1999 -- CIR-BIBLE, 3-10 -- Whatever
the edition and whatever the language, the Bible is considered by
many as the the very word of God. Electronic versions of the Bible
offer readers commentaries, maps and dictionaries to help decipher
and explain the text. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- March 10, 1999 -- CIR-KIDS-INTERNET, 3-10 --
Alan Rothenberg, with son Joel. Tired of spending money for
children's software and fearful of his kids surfing the web,
Rothenberg formed his own company offering the first safe on-line
service just for preteen-agers. (Rick Friedman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 10, 1999 -- CIR-ARCHITECTURE, 3-10 --
Designers from left, James Stewart Polshek, V. Guy Maxwell and Todd
Schliemann in their office at the Polshek Partnership where they
are working on the design of the dome for the Rose Center For Earth
and Space which will be part of the Hayden Planetarium at the
American Museum of Natural History. No engineering degree is needed
to appreciate how useful a computer is in designing an 87-foot
steel sphere capable of holding 585 people which will apparently
float in the air with no apparent support at top or bottom. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
