   (NYT28) HEPU, China -- March 10, 1999 -- CHINA-CORRUPTION, 3-10
-- A street scene in Hepu, in southern China. In towns like this
one, the local Communist Party chief rules with the authority of an
old-time mobster, and the new market economy has increased
opportunities for corruption. (Seth Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- March 10, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REPUBS, 3-10 --
Henry Kissinger, former national security adviser to President
Richard Nixon during the Vietnam War, addresses the House Committee
on International Relations as Sen. Bob Dole, and former US
Ambassador to the UN Jeanne Kirkpatrick look on, Wednesday, on
Capitol Hill. Kissinger questioned the wisdom of forcing the
sovereign nation of Yugoslavia, under the threat of bombing, to
sign an agreement to allow foreign troops to intervene in a civil
war. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 10, 1999 --RELIGION-PRIZE, 3-10 -- Ian
Barbour, a physicist and theologian, at the United Nations Church
Center on Wednesday. The world's largest monetary prize, the
Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion, will be awarded to
Barbour who has devoted four decades to fostering a dialogue
between science and religion. His selection as recipient of the
prize, valued at 750,000 British pounds, or about $1.24 million,
was announced at a news conference Wednesday at the Church Center.
(G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SUSSEX, Virg. -- March 10, 1999 -- VA-NY-TRANSIT, 3-10
-- Trash from New York City fills a land fill in rural Virginia.
Five years ago, Sussex County embarked on a controversial path that
many people believed would improve their struggling economy while
jeopardizing their beloved environs: accepting a private,
state-of-the-art landfill that would import thousands of tons of
garbage a day, much of it from New York City. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 10, 1999 -- BBA-YANK-TORRE, 3-10 --
Joe Torre, manager of the New York Yankees, at batting practice
earlier this week. Torre announced on Wednesday that he had
prostate cancer and left for treatment. (Barton Silverman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
