<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-BANKS-600&AMP;ADD-     03-10 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-BANKS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 FRENCH BANKS REBUFF $37 BILLION TAKEOVER OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Michel Pebereau thought he would crash the wedding, but
the happy couple told him three was a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, two of France's biggest banks, Paribas SA
and Societe Generale SA, said that an offer on Tuesday by their big
French rival, Pebereau's Banque Nationale de Paris, was a
``hazardous venture'' and that the offer ``cannot therefore be
considered as a friendly takeover bid.''
</P>
<P>
   The takeover effort was announced on Tuesday night as Pebereau,
Banque Nationale's chairman, offered $37 billion for the two
rivals, which had agreed to merge last month.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Paris Wednesday morning, Pebereau argued
that the new European single currency had accelerated consolidation
of banking and that the proposed alliance ``will allow us to
confront the competition on a European level.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the alliance would yield a bank whose assets, totaling
$1 trillion, would push it past UBS of Switzerland as the world's
largest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country is capable of dominating this sector on a global
scale,'' said Pebereau, 57, playing the nationalist card. He called
banking ``a sector in which France has historically excelled.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the hostile bid, Paribas and Societe Generale promised
to study the proposal and then convene their boards. Paribas hired
the investment bank Rothschild &AMP; Co. to study ways to repel the
bid, and Societe Generale said it, too, would hire advisers.
Trading in the shares of all three banks was suspended in Paris but
was expected to resume on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For the two target banks, the bid threatens the well-laid plans
for Societe Generale to acquire Paribas for $18 billion in stock.
Investors have been skeptical of the plan, arguing that there was
little overlap at the two banks and that there was scant room for
cost-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   For Banque Nationale de Paris, the bid holds great potential. It
has been cut out of most French banking deals, and Pebereau is
desperate for a partner. Societe Generale is a well-run bank with a
good profit record, and Paribas is a respected name with a strong
consumer banking unit, Cetelem.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the move poses great risks. The bid effectively puts all
three banks into play, and if Banque Nationale fails, it could fall
prey to a takeover. Moreover, it could face resistance from labor
unions and the French government. The bank employees union
denounced the plan Wednesday as ``adventurous and very serious for
jobs.'' For the French government _ which is preparing a sale of
Credit Lyonnais, the state-owned bank that has returned to profit
after losing billions _ the proposed combination would create a
retail banking giant that would alter the terms of any
privatization.
</P>
<P>
   And the bid could face resistance from Jewish organizations. In
New York, Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish
Congress, said that if the banks applied for a merger in the United
States, a ``great deal of sentiment'' existed in the leadership of
Congress to oppose it until French banks showed a more conciliatory
attitude in talks to settle issues related to the accounts of
Holocaust victims or their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The banking alliance that Pebereau proposed involves keeping all
three banks' brand names and includes no sweeping layoffs. Banque
Nationale de Paris intends to retain the investment banking
activities of Paribas while combining its own banking units with
those of Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
   The merger would create a bank with 4,700 branches in France,
giving it 18 percent of the retail market and making it the No. 2
retail bank behind Credit Agricole. The bank said it expected
annual savings, before taxes, of $1.3 billion, or 8 percent of
combined costs, by 2002.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Elie Cohen, an economist at the National Center for Scientific
Research, said: ``It's crazy, but Pebereau had no other choice. For
him it was a matter of survival.'' If the bid fails, Cohen said,
Banque Nationale de Paris could find itself the target of a bid
from a Dutch or German bank. ``If he succeeds, he will be No. 1,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Banque Nationale's bid is the latest in a series of giant-scale
transactions that are reshaping European banks as they struggle for
position in a market gaining cohesion with the euro. And there is
no sign of the pace slackening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bold, aggressive step,'' said John Leonard, banking
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in London. He said Banque Nationale
wanted to ally itself with Societe Generale, a goal it set last
year but failed to achieve when Societe Generale refused an
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said the real winner, if the deal succeeds, would
be Claude Bebear, chairman of the AXA insurance group. AXA is the
largest shareholder in both Paribas and Banque Nationale de Paris
and would emerge as a controlling shareholder in a combined bank.
And Bebear, 63, a kingmaker in French finance, is said to want the
deal done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
