<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/10/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) LONDON -- March 10, 1999 -- SUB-BRITISH-AUTHOR'S-MUSE,
3-10 -- Alex Garland knows literary success ``could slip away
easily.'' The author of two well-received novels, ``The Beach'' and
``The Tesseract,'' Garland, 28, builds his plots, he says, with
comic-strip storyboards in mind. ``I leave a lot of gaps, and in
order for the book to work, the reader needs to fill in those
gaps,'' he says. ``The reader needs to engage.'' (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador -- March 10, 1999 --
CLINTON-GUERRILLAS, 3-10 -- Former leaders of the rebel Farabundo
Marti Liberation Front who are members of the Assembly in El
Salvador. From left, Gerson Martinez, Dr. Violeta Menjivar. Schafik
Handal and Nidia Diaz. (Cindy Karp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) HEPU, China -- March 10, 1999 -- CHINA-CORRUPTION, 3-10
-- A street scene in Hepu, in southern China. In towns like this
one, the local Communist Party chief rules with the authority of an
old-time mobster, and the new market economy has increased
opportunities for corruption. (Seth Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- March 10, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REPUBS, 3-10 --
Henry Kissinger, former national security adviser to President
Richard Nixon during the Vietnam War, addresses the House Committee
on International Relations as Sen. Bob Dole, and former US
Ambassador to the UN Jeanne Kirkpatrick look on, Wednesday, on
Capitol Hill. Kissinger questioned the wisdom of forcing the
sovereign nation of Yugoslavia, under the threat of bombing, to
sign an agreement to allow foreign troops to intervene in a civil
war. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 10, 1999 --RELIGION-PRIZE, 3-10 -- Ian
Barbour, a physicist and theologian, at the United Nations Church
Center on Wednesday. The world's largest monetary prize, the
Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion, will be awarded to
Barbour who has devoted four decades to fostering a dialogue
between science and religion. His selection as recipient of the
prize, valued at 750,000 British pounds, or about $1.24 million,
was announced at a news conference Wednesday at the Church Center.
(G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SUSSEX, Virg. -- March 10, 1999 -- VA-NY-TRANSIT, 3-10
-- Trash from New York City fills a land fill in rural Virginia.
Five years ago, Sussex County embarked on a controversial path that
many people believed would improve their struggling economy while
jeopardizing their beloved environs: accepting a private,
state-of-the-art landfill that would import thousands of tons of
garbage a day, much of it from New York City. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 10, 1999 -- BBA-YANK-TORRE, 3-10 --
Joe Torre, manager of the New York Yankees, at batting practice
earlier this week. Torre announced on Wednesday that he had
prostate cancer and left for treatment. (Barton Silverman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NAKANOJOMACHI, Japan -- March 10, 1999 -- JAPAN-ECONOMY,
3-10 -- Construction workers for the Takahashi Komuten Co.
implement a road widening project in Nakanojomachi. Japanese
leaders have traditionally funneled money into such
brick-and-mortar projects to stimulate the economy, so the signs of
life these days are interpreted by most experts as just a temporary
comeback, not a self-sustaining recovery. (Stuart Isett/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PARIS -- March 10, 1999 -- PARIS-FASHION-2, 3-10 -- From
left, Marc Jacobs fur anorak and bootleg pants for Louis Vuitton;
Jacobs' knit sweater and asymmetric skirt for Vuitton; Ocimar
Versolato's leather strapless dress over sheer turtleneck.
(Jean-Luce Hure/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) PARIS -- March 10, 1999 -- PARIS-FASHION-1, 3-10 -- From
left, a leather thong-tied dress from Alber Elbaz's first
collection for Yves Saint Laurent; from Christian Dior, reversible
Prince of Wales jacket and knit skirt by John Galliano; fur chubby
vest and tweed trousers by Elbaz for Saint Laurent. (Jean-Luce
Hure/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) FAIRFIELD, Calif. -- March 10, 1999 --
MILITARY-VACCINES, 3-10 -- Jeffrey Betendorf talks about his
reasons for refusing the Air Force's orders to receive an anthrax
vaccine in the backyard of his home on Wednesday. After threatening
him with court martial, the Air Force discharged him under ``other
than honorable conditions.'' Sixteen months after the Pentagon
announced that all 2.4 million military personnel, whether on
active duty or in the reserves or national guard, would be
vaccinated, the military is facing a rebellion from a small, but
growing legion of those who have refused. (Thor Swift/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- March 10, 1999 -- SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-2,
3-10 -- Patients waiting for organ transplants walk across the
floor of their ward at Mt. Sinai Hospital during an exercise
session last December. The patients, from left, are Leroy Simeon,
Fullord Modefte, Shelley Clarke, Charlie Schultz, and Doris Napoli.
A battle over the nation's scarcest medical resource, human organs,
has moved from Washington to the states, where a number of
legislatures have begun passing laws that would bar donated organs
from being shipped beyond their borders to sick people elsewhere in
the country. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- March 10, 1999 -- SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS, 3-10
-- Dr. Anil Apeydan, left, and Dr. Alan Gass, fly back to New York
from Maryland after harvesting a heart from a donor in November,
1998. A battle over the nation's scarcest medical resource, human
organs, has moved from Washington to the states, where a number of
legislatures have begun passing laws that would bar donated organs
from being shipped beyond their borders to sick people elsewhere in
the country. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LONDON -- March 10, 1999 -- CHER-HIT, 3-10 -- From left,
Mark Taylor, Paul Barry and Brian Rawling at their studio near
London, where Cher recorded ``Believe.'' This week, her song went
to the top of the pop charts, resurrecting a mutating career that
refuses to be buried. Cher may be the only singer who had No. 1
hits in the 1960s and '70s to return this decade with a new No. 1
single. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 10, 1999 -- EMERGING-ARCHITECTS-2,
3-10 -- Hani Rashid, 40, and Lise Anne Couture (with Tynan, 2), 39,
of Asymptote designed a research center in Kyoto to be more fluid
than geometric. Rashid and Ms. Couture are ``set on running all our
credit cards into the ground'' in order to realize their design
objectives. They utilize the most advanced computer technologies to
create a space that exists simultaneously in the real world -
``first-reality architecture,'' Rashid calls it - and in virtual
reality. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BERKELEY, Calif. -- March 10, 1999 --
EMERGING-ARCHITECTS-1, 3-10 -- Ralph Nelson and Raveevarn
Choksombatchal, both 37, who were married in 1989, have shared an
architectural practice called Loom for six years. ``We've spent 10
years becoming an overnight success,'' Mr. Nelson says. Loom was
among eight architecture firms selected as ``Emerging Voices'' of
1999 by the Architectural League of New York, a nonprofit
organization that has sponsored public programs in architecture
since 1881. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LONDON -- March 10, 1999 -- HOPPEN-DESIGN-3, 3-10 -- A
designer who is to English residential design what John Pawson is
to the country's architecture scene, Kelly Hoppen creates interiors
that are sleek, minimalist, obsessively finished and deceptively
simple. Ms. Hoppen created a Stanley Kubrick air in the entry of
her London home, with doors lacquered taupe, and light from wall
niches. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LONDON -- March 10, 1999 -- HOPPEN-DESIGN-2, 3-10 --
Kelly Hoppen has seen the future, and it is beige, accented with
sorbet-sweet shots of aubergine, blackberry and lilac. ``I'm always
trying to convince people to spend money on lighting and buy a sofa
later,'' says Ms. Hoppen, 39, whose recently remodeled home in
London has a glass-walled bathroom with a tub on limed oak blocks;
the basin is carved from stone. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LONDON -- March 10, 1999 -- HOPPEN-DESIGN-1, 3-10 --
Lionized in Britain but largely unknown here, Kelly Hoppen has seen
the future, and it is beige, accented with sorbet-sweet shots of
aubergine, blackberry and lilac. Ms. Hoppen (with a fossilized
shell) uses carefully calibrated light and Asian allusions to warm
rooms. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) URUSEVAC, Yugoslavia -- March 10, 1999 -- KOSOVO-2, 3-10
-- Kadri Bulica tends to the bodies of Mustaf Lika, 22, and Qani
Luma, 21, foreground, both ethnic Albanians, on Wednesday. The two
men were killed on Tuesday in a nearby village during shelling of
the region by Serb forces. Despite pressure from senior U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke and the threat of NATO airstrikes, Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic on Wednesday rejected a proposal
allowing NATO forces to police a Kosovo peace agreement. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LINCOLN, Neb. -- March 10, 1999 -- PIPHER-PROFILE, 3-10
-- Dr. Mary Pipher sees age as a landscape that deserves to be
explored. Landscape is the metaphor she uses to explore aging in
her new book, ``Another Country: The Emotional Terrain of Our
Elders,'' which will be published next week. As in ``Reviving
Ophelia,'' which is as much a social critique as it is a
psychological treatise, Dr. Pipher, 51, views aging through the
lens of the anthropologist she set out to be in college. (Kent
Sievers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- March 10, 1999 -- FRANKEL-BOOK-REVIEW, 3-10 --
Max Frankel, author of ``The Times of My Life and My Life with The
Times,'' to published this month by Random House. For 40 years
Frankel was the quintessential Times reporter with had a front-row
seat at the great political and diplomatic events of the age and
backstage access to many of its leading players. (Jon
Frankel/Random House)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- March 10, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 3-10
-- Various methods of bonding wood to concrete. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 10, 1999 -- NY-OLD-SIGNS, 3-10 -- A
hybrid billboard in SoHo. As New York's construction boom spreads,
advertisements for carriage rentals and patent medicines painted on
brick walls previously hidden by buildings appear suddenly, flashes
of the past, when a building is razed. ``People are noticing them
more and more,'' says Linda Cooper Bowen, who wrote an article on
signs in the current issue of Print magazine. (Marilynn K. Yee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- March 10, 1999 -- FOOD-REICHL-B&AMP;W, 3-10 -- A
wig and glasses used as disguises by New York Times food critic
Ruth Reichl to ward off special attention while sampling a
restaurant's attributes. Reichl surprised colleagues in January
with the announcement that she would leave the Times after 5 1/2
years to revamp sleepy Gourmet magazine. Considered one of the most
influential voices in the food world, Reichl writes reviews that
are read as much for lively cultural commentary as for her
dissection of restaurant pretentions. (Janet Knott/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRINCE WILLIAM SOUND, Alaska -- March 10, 1999 --
EXXON-SPILL, 3-10 -- Biologist Bruce Wright holds a piece of
contaminated soil commonly found along the area known by locals as
the ``Death Marsh.'' The Exxon Valdez dumped 10.8 million gallons
of thick, crude oil into the water near here 10 years ago after
running aground. Only two of the 23 most damaged species have fully
recovered and an estimated 40 percent of the fishermen suffer
depression over their decimated livelihoods. (Mark Wilson/Boston
Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) KOTLINA, Yugoslavia -- March 10, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 3-10 --
A doctor working for a humanitarian aid group checks a baby on
Wednesday who was born the previous day at a school turned into a
refugee shelter in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province. The baby's mother,
Minadije Loki, an ethnic Albanian who fled from a nearby village
which was being shelled, looks on at right. Despite pressure from
senior U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and the threat of NATO
airstrikes, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic rejected NATO
forces to police a Kosovo peace agreement. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 10, 1999 -- CIR-BIBLE, 3-10 -- Whatever
the edition and whatever the language, the Bible is considered by
many as the the very word of God. Electronic versions of the Bible
offer readers commentaries, maps and dictionaries to help decipher
and explain the text. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- March 10, 1999 -- CIR-KIDS-INTERNET, 3-10 --
Alan Rothenberg, with son Joel. Tired of spending money for
children's software and fearful of his kids surfing the web,
Rothenberg formed his own company offering the first safe on-line
service just for preteen-agers. (Rick Friedman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 10, 1999 -- CIR-ARCHITECTURE, 3-10 --
Designers from left, James Stewart Polshek, V. Guy Maxwell and Todd
Schliemann in their office at the Polshek Partnership where they
are working on the design of the dome for the Rose Center For Earth
and Space which will be part of the Hayden Planetarium at the
American Museum of Natural History. No engineering degree is needed
to appreciate how useful a computer is in designing an 87-foot
steel sphere capable of holding 585 people which will apparently
float in the air with no apparent support at top or bottom. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
