<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DWI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DWI MEASURE PASSES PANEL AFTER HEARTFELT PLEAS FROM PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Doug McWhorter, a plain-speaking father from
Parker County, offered four reasons Wednesday for Texas lawmakers
to crack down on drunken driving:
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Mandi McWhorter, 15, and her friends Staci Lee,
16, Whitney Welch, 16, and Lacey Osina, 17.
</P>
<P>
   The four inseparable friends, who were athletes and cheerleaders
at Brock High School in tiny Brock, Texas, died of injuries
suffered in a Dec. 19 head-on collision with a pickup. They had
gone out for dinner and to rent Christmas videos on what had seemed
a carefree Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup driver, Rickey Carter of Fort Worth, survived.
Officials said Carter's blood-alcohol level measured .16, and he is
awaiting trial on charges of intoxicated manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Doug McWhorter said the deaths of his daughter and her friends
should make it clear to the Legislature that the blood-alcohol
level to define intoxication should be lowered from .10 to .08
percent and that penalties for drunken driving should be increased.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Criminal Justice Committee took the first step
Wednesday toward obliging the request by unanimously approving
legislation by Sen. Mario Gallegos, D-Houston, that would lower the
blood alcohol limit. The action on Senate Bill 114 came after
nearly two hours of sometimes tearful testimony from the girls'
families and friends in a packed committee room.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the room wore buttons with photos of the girls who were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the needless deaths of our daughters could have
been avoided if the laws governing drinking and driving were
tougher.'' McWhorter said in a solemn but steady voice. ``A person
must know that their actions have consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission today is to ask the lawmakers of Texas to pass
strict DWI laws so families like ours may not have to endure the
grief that we feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Pax Welch, the mother of Whitney Welch, told the committee
members, ``If this law passes, and it saves one life _ and it saves
one parent, one brother, one sister, one grandparent from what
we've been through _ then it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also heard testimony from officials of Mothers Against
Drunk Driving and the Department of Public Safety, who said that
Texas routinely leads the nation in the number of fatal traffic
accidents in which alcohol is a factor. In 1997, the most recent
year for which figures are available, 1,748 people died in
alcohol-related wrecks in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, legislation to establish .08 as the limit for DWI
was killed in a parliamentary maneuver by Sen. Eddie Lucio,
D-Brownsville. Lucio said Wednesday that he ``will probably vote
for .08'' this year. The bill has the strong support of Gov. George
W. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which could reach the Senate floor for a vote as
early as next week, drew opposition from the American Beverage
Institute and some defense lawyers. The groups expressed concern
that social drinking could be criminalized and that
breath-measuring devices that detect alcohol might be inaccurate
when measuring amounts as small as .08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos said Texas stands to receive as much as $26 million in
extra federal highway funds under recent legislation that
encourages states to set the blood-alcohol limit for DWI at .08.
</P>
<P>
   But most of those who addressed the committee said stricter
drunken-driving laws are needed to save lives.
</P>
<P>
   The girls killed in the wreck were remembered as athletes and
cheerleaders in the community about 35 miles west of Fort Worth.
Two of their friends told the criminal justice panel that the
accident devastated Brock and left an irreplaceable void in the
lives of many of its young residents.
</P>
<P>
   Candice Sanders, 18, who was McWhorter's best friend, said she
was in another car only a few hundred yards from the four girls'
vehicle when the accident occurred. She said she remains haunted by
the vision of the swerving pickup and the fatal crash, which she
said might have been prevented if Texas laws were tougher on
drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to wake up every morning, and all I have are pictures
and memories,'' Sanders said, ``because that's all that's left.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
