u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-LABEL-MEDICINE-52     03-10 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LABEL-MEDICINE-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA ORDERS CLEARER LABELS ON OVER-THE-COUNTER MEDICATION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Food and Drug Administration is about to order
the drug industry to revamp the labeling on over-the-counter
medications, a move that will do away with dense fine print on
medicines from aspirin to cough syrup, replacing it with simple,
and bigger, text that is similar to the nutrition labels on food
packages.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, which are outlined in a new regulation, are
scheduled to be announced by Vice President Al Gore at a White
House ceremony on Thursday, an administration official said. The
official said the new ``Drug Facts'' labels would start appearing
early next year and would be phased in over two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate that this will occur very rapidly, with the
backing of both the pharmacists and the manufacturers,'' the
official said, citing experience with the ``Nutrition Facts''
labels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once this gets out into the marketplace, many of the producers
will start doing this for all their products because consumers
become very comfortable with it and, in some cases, will think that
if it doesn't have a new label the product will be old.''
</P>
<P>
   Current labeling varies considerably from product to product, is
often laced with legalistic prose and is difficult to read,
particularly for the elderly. And while over-the-counter drugs are
generally safe, their misuse causes more than 170,000
hospitalizations each year, costing the health care system an
estimated $750,000, the administration says.
</P>
<P>
   The new labels will take a standard format. They will list the
active ingredient in each drug, what the medicine is used for and
explain which ingredients are used to treat which symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The labels will tell consumers with questions to ``ask your
doctor or pharmacist,'' _ a nod to the growing role pharmacists
play in health care _ as opposed to the less specific advice,
common on current labels, to consult a ``health professional.''
</P>
<P>
   The warnings are to be written in plain, clear English. The
familiar phrase ``may cause drowsiness'' will be replaced with the
more direct ``you may get drowsy.'' And the common warning to
``avoid alcoholic beverages'' will now read ``avoid alcoholic
drinks.'' Gore, a stickler for eliminating bureaucratic language in
government business, plans to give the food and drug agency one of
his ``plain language'' awards.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Nonprescription Drug Manufacturers of America,
which represents over-the-counter drug makers, were unavailable for
comment on the new rule. But pharmacist groups praised the
administration's action, saying it is an important step toward
improving drug safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think a standardized label is very important,'' said Susan
Winckler, director of policy and legislation at the American
Pharmaceutical Association, which represents more than 53,000
individual pharmacists. ``Over-the-counter drugs are safe when they
are used correctly, but there was a good amount of confusion among
consumers and health care professionals about over-the-counter
medications. Part of that confusion came from the fact that the
labels weren't clear.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The agency's next step may be to tackle labeling on prescription
drugs, a far thornier issue that has already attracted the
attention of Congress. In 1995, lawmakers passed legislation
barring the food and drug agency from overhauling prescription drug
labels until at least the year 2000, and even then it is required
to conduct a study before taking action.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is, however, free to order labeling changes for
prescription drugs with serious side effects, and it recently
proposed a regulation addressing that problem. Even so, at least
one critic, Sidney Wolfe of Public Citizen's Health Research Group,
said the changes are not coming quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very dangerous double standard between what they
are doing on information for patients on over-the-counter drugs and
what they are not doing on prescription drugs,'' Wolfe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
