<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOOPCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE AGAINST 63 POOR DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In their search for hope, in their desperate
attempt to beat Duke, teams across the nation have turned to the
Blue Devils themselves, 1991 version.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Nevada-Las Vegas was the mightiest team in the land,
the unbeaten, defending national champion with a Hall of Fame coach
and a slew of future pros. Considered invincible, the Rebels lost
to Duke 79-77 in the national semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, that game stands as the beacon for those who
cross the Blue Devils' path. If Duke beat UNLV in 1991, they
reason, then Duke can be beaten today.
</P>
<P>
   They are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   After facing enormous pressure and expectations all season _
would UNLV be the first unbeaten team since Indiana in 1976? _ the
Runnin' Rebels were exhausted when they reached the 1991 Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   They were weeks removed from their best game, a dominating
victory at No. 2 Arkansas, and had encountered unexpected
resistance from Georgetown and Seton Hall in the second round and
Elite Eight, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   And although it wasn't apparent at the time, it is now: The
Rebels were a better team in 1990, when they thrashed Duke by 30
points for the title. In '91, they were without their frontcourt
enforcer, Moses Scurry; they were overly dependent on point guard
Greg Anthony, whose phantom fourth foul early in the second half
changed the game; and they did not have the hunger they possessed
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the small matter of opposition. The Duke team that
stunned UNLV had Christian Laettner, the nation's best player in
1992, Grant Hill, the nation's best player in 1994, and Bobby
Hurley, the nation's best point guard in 1993-94. All three were
NBA lottery picks.
</P>
<P>
   No team playing today has that type of talent. In other words,
there is no Duke '91 to beat Duke '99.
</P>
<P>
   So, are the Blue Devils invincible? ``Remember Tonya Harding?''
Stanford coach Mike Montgomery quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Short of clubbing, it'll take an unlikely combination of factors
to beat them. Duke has a Hall of Fame coach, seven McDonald's
All-Americans and two more who should have been, point guard
William Avery and versatile forward Chris Carrawell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are head and shoulders right now above anybody I've
seen,'' Arizona coach Lute Olson said. ``When you have that many
talented kids and an outstanding coach like Mike (Krzyzewski), for
them to go down, it'll take a huge upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Trajan Langdon is hurting, if they aren't hitting from
outside, if somebody's hurt or sick or has an off game, they
replace him with another All-American. To put it in perspective, in
my 16 years, we've had seven McDonald's All-Americans, and they
have (seven) on one team.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does it take? Which teams possess the ingredients to
conquer the Devils? The equation seems tougher to solve than
Fermat's Last Theorem, but here's a basic blueprint:
</P>
<P>
   __ Offense, offense, offense: Sure, defense wins in the NCAA
Tournament, except when the opponent is Duke. No one's going to
stop the Blue Devils from scoring. No one's going to beat them
65-60. Won't happen. They have too many weapons and too many ways
to score, which explains their 93 points per game, tops in the
nation. If not center Elton Brand inside or Langdon and Avery from
3-point range, then it's Shane Battier and Corey Maggette slashing
to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   That means someone must score 85 or 90 points against the
Devils' stifling pressure defense, match their relentless attack
basket for basket for 40 minutes. That eliminates a
defensive-minded team like Miami, which is seeded No. 2 in the East
but cannot score at Duke's level.
</P>
<P>
   __ A proven point: The Blue Devils play fabulous halfcourt
defense. They deny passing lanes to the perimeter. They rotate to
snuff penetration. They're quick enough to double-team in the post
and recover on 3-point shooters. The rules that govern standard
halfcourt offense will not work; there are no seams to puncture.
Stanford's precision attack, for instance, would have no chance.
</P>
<P>
   Although it seems incongruous, the way to beat Duke's defense is
with chaos _ and that starts with a point guard who can dominate
with the dribble and create shots when all else fails. Duke thrives
on the surges spawned by its defense. Limit turnovers and you limit
the surges.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to control the ball offensively, because
they're so good on defense,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a task for excellent point guards, like Michigan
State's Mateen Cleaves, Kentucky's Wayne Turner or Connecticut's
Khalid El-Amin. Duke would tear them up. No, this is a job for the
best of the best: Utah's Andre Miller, Arizona's Jason Terry and
UCLA's Baron Davis.
</P>
<P>
   __ Size at center: Containing Duke's attack starts with
containing Brand (18 ppg). Why? There's a better chance Langdon and
Avery will miss from 20 feet than Brand will miss from two feet.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not easy. Brand is 6-foot-8 and very strong. He creates
contact in the post and uses his strength to pin, seal and
overpower defenders. If he has a weakness, it's his face-up game.
He's not a great shooter from 8-10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's 7-foot center, Brendan Haywood, provided a
blueprint in the first of three losses to Duke. Haywood bodied
Brand until Brand caught the ball in the post. Then Haywood backed
off a step and played sound defense, moving his feet to keep Brand
from penetrating. When Brand readied for a short jumper, Haywood
extended his arms and forced Brand to shoot over him. The ploy
worked, although Duke pulled away in the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, there aren't many Haywoods around. (He's a future
lottery pick.) A few centers who would stand a chance are Arizona's
A.J. Bramlett, Washington's Todd MacCulloch and perhaps Utah's Nate
Althoff.
</P>
<P>
   __ A master tactician: Talent is not enough; there must be s
special plan, an unexpected wrinkle, that disrupts Duke's rhythm
ever so slightly _ like the triangle-and-two Utah used to
discombobulate Arizona last year.
</P>
<P>
   Just as you need an elite point guard, so you need an elite
coach. Michigan State's Tom Izzo, Auburn's Cliff Ellis, Maryland's
Gary Williams, Connecticut's Jim Calhoun and Miami's Leonard
Hamilton won't cut it. This is a job for Rick Majerus, Lute Olson
or Tubby Smith.
</P>
<P>
   __ And finally: Luck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
