u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STABBING-NEIGHBORH     03-10 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STABBING-NEIGHBORHOOD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STABBING VICTIM'S NEIGHBORHOOD CONSIDERED SAFE BY NEW YORK
STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan.)  (rk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ To understand the yin and yang of gentrification in
the Prospect Heights section of Brooklyn, consider two very
different types of recent visitors to the Park Place brownstone of
William Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   About eight months ago, Bullock said, two men pushed him inside
his home, taped his hands behind his back and robbed him. Then
there are his other frequent visitors _ the young, affluent-looking
people who pull up in cars almost every week and ask him whether
any houses on the block are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   In the 27 years that he has lived in Prospect Heights, Bullock,
72, said he has watched his neighborhood rise and fall and now rise
again, each trend dictated by the prosperity of the city and the
ebb and flow of crime. Today, Prospect Heights is one of the many
neighborhoods in New York that real estate agents often describe as
``up and coming,'' attracting middle-class professionals from
Manhattan or nearby Park Slope who are in search of affordable
homes and apartments in a safe, convenient area.
</P>
<P>
   But the slaying Monday night on Park Place of Amy Watkins, a
26-year-old graduate student from Kansas who had come to New York
to become a social worker, has shaken the sense of security held by
many residents, particularly newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   People interviewed in Prospect Heights were both saddened by the
killing and stunned that the apparently random attack happened on a
block considered among the neighborhood's safest.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, the slaying illuminated the odd paradox of
living in a neighborhood like Prospect Heights: even as rents rise
dramatically and apartments and brownstones sell for record prices,
residents also described boundaries separating nice blocks from
those that are considered less safe.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the police precinct that includes Prospect Heights
has reported dramatic two-year reductions in robberies and
homicides, Bullock said he was robbed four times last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, citing the improved crime statistics,
said Wednesday that ``people in that community are safer than in
just about any urban area in America.'' But the mayor, referring to
Ms. Watkins' slaying, conceded that ``until they locate the person
who did it, no matter what I say, people will be afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins was walking home from the subway at 9:45 p.m. Monday
when she was stabbed in the back with a kitchen knife in an
apparent robbery. The police said there were no witnesses, and
investigators had no suspects Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The attack horrified residents. ``I just pray they find him,''
said Catherine Jackson, 36, who lives across the street from Ms.
Watkins' apartment on the 400 block of Park Place. ``I want them to
find whoever did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins moved to Prospect Heights last September, joining
other newcomers, many of them young and white, who have arrived in
recent years in what had been a mostly minority neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheaper rent, bigger apartment, quieter neighborhood,'' said
Josh Feierman, 31, explaining why he moved to Prospect Heights from
the Upper West Side of Manhattan eight months ago. ``It feels
mostly like a safe and comfortable neighborhood. There are not a
lot of people out at night, so it can feel deserted.''
</P>
<P>
   The influx of newcomers, many of them more affluent than
longtime residents, has happened without hostility, according to
many residents. Anthony Katchuba, 34, said he and his wife moved
about a year ago from Brooklyn Heights to Prospect lace, a block
north of where Ms. Watkins was killed.
</P>
<P>
   He said he always meets his wife at the subway when she returns
late at night from acting classes, but he also described the
neighborhood as mostly safe. ``There are a lot of nice blocks, and
then one block away there are blocks that aren't too nice,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Inside Muddy Waters, a coffee shop on Vanderbilt Avenue that
opened about three years ago, the owner, Ntozake Lundy, 27, said
Ms. Watkins often stopped by for coffee. Unlike most people
interviewed, Ms. Lundy said the slaying did not surprise her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not safe,'' she said, noting that a close
friend who lives nearby was stabbed nine times last year by a man
who attacked her in her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lundy said that the recent gentrification has improved
Prospect Heights, and that it has also helped her business, but she
said that newcomers are oblivious to what she called obvious
warning signs of trouble. She said that as prime blocks of Sterling
Place and Park Place have become fully occupied, the boundaries of
the neighborhood have expanded into more marginal blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're young, and they don't intend to have roots here, so
that makes a difference,'' Ms. Lundy said of the new arrivals.
``They just don't want to know. They just want to get in their
apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   George Benson, 65, who lives on Park Place a half block from the
site of the attack, said the neighborhood was violent when he
purchased his brownstone in 1982. Once, he said, he was held up at
gunpoint outside his home.
</P>
<P>
   Benson said neighbors created a watch system in which at least
one resident would sit outside at night to keep an eye on people
coming from and going to the subway.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Benson said the neighborhood is far more tranquil but not
without problems. The watch system has been abandoned, he said,
because people feel safer, or because newcomers have not shown
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Garstein, president of Warren Lewis Realty, a Park Slope
real estate agency with listings in Prospect Heights, estimated
that home values have appreciated 30 percent in the past two years.
He said he recently sold two brownstones, each for more than
$635,000, a hefty price but far less than the $900,000 that he said
such homes could bring in Park Slope.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as relative safety, it's New York City,'' Garstein said
of Prospect Heights. ``If you are walking down a dark street in New
York City and even if you are very cautious, something can happen
to you.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, many people in Prospect Heights are simply grieving.
James Caldwell, president of the area's citizens liaison group to
the police, said residents will hold a candlelight vigil Friday
night, marching from the Seventh Avenue subway stop where Ms.
Watkins got off the D train, down Park Place past the spot where
she was killed, then to her apartment about another block away.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, Brigitta Krueger, 54, who has lived in
an apartment building on Park Place at Vanderbilt Avenue since
1985, walked by the site of the slaying. Flowers and two candles
had been placed on a nearby stoop.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was shocked and deeply saddened by the killing. But
she also said Prospect Heights had improved so much in recent years
because people like Ms. Watkins had moved there. ``I've noticed a
lot of young people moving here,'' Ms. Krueger said. ``It's nice. I
hope they are not scared off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
