<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS UCLA DESTINED FOR EARLY EXIT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The most popular upset pick in the NCAA
Tournament involves the team in blue and gold. The Bruins know it,
they've heard it and they don't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just hate us, basically, because we're UCLA,'' guard
Baron Davis said, grinning. ``We're young and we're all good
looking. For some reason, people don't like us.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the oddsmakers, who have installed No. 5-seed UCLA
as a 2{-point favorite tonight against No. 12 Detroit _ a small
school (enrollment: 7,000) from a small conference (Midwestern
Collegiate) with a tiny tournament history and a one-eyed ex-coach
(Dick Vitale).
</P>
<P>
   On closer inspection, however, there are plenty of reasons to
believe the Bruins won't survive the night. At least, that's what
their coach claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have your head in the sand not to know Detroit's
the most dangerous team in the tournament,'' Steve Lavin said. ``We
feel like the underdog this year even though we are the No. 5 seed.
This is an unusual feeling for us, but we are a very young team,
youngest in the field of 64, and Detroit on the the other hand is
very experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Why even bother?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Bruins have no chance. They have nothing in their
favor except speed, size, depth and talent. They've faced tougher
opposition than Detroit and beaten better teams. They have the best
player on the court (Davis), the best big man (Jerome Moiso) and
the deeper bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate the reverse psychology,'' Titans forward Bacari
Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   But eliminate the posturing and postulating, and what remains is
a contrast in philosophy and a test of style. UCLA has the superior
athletes and wants to run. It wants to play a frantic, ragged pace.
Detroit has the toughness and discipline. It wants to play at a
crawl and make each possession essential.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever team imposes its plan on the other will have an
enormous advantage. And history says the Bruins are in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   After a 17-point season-ending loss at Arizona, they have more
questions than they did two months ago _ about their health and
their heads, their halfcourt offense, their defense, their
rebounding, their free-throw shooting and their experience.
</P>
<P>
   They rarely play well in this position, as a mid-level seed.
Since the field expanded to 64 teams, the Bruins have been lower
than a No. 2 seed eight times, and they've survived the first
weekend twice.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they often struggle against tempo teams in the
tournament. Detroit doesn't run Princeton's hypnotic weave, but its
approach will be similar: work the clock, limit possessions,
smother the Bruins with defense and don't give them any easy
baskets. Make UCLA's halfcourt offense win the game.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same plan Miami used against the Bruins last year in a
65-62 first-round loss, and Detroit is better than Miami. The
Titans have four of their top five scorers back from a team that
upset St. John's in the first round last year. They beat Gonzaga
and they almost won at Iowa. They won't be intimidated and they
won't get flustered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to play smart and show some maturity,'' UCLA
freshman Ray Young said. ``We have to be crisper with our passes
and cuts against their defense, but we're not afraid of how they
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a little fear would help. Against Princeton and Miami,
the Bruins were guilty of lethargy, of not taking their opponent
seriously. A repeat effort tonight and they'll be home for lunch
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
