<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM ITALIA BOARD MEETS ON STRATEGY TO THWART OLIVETTI BID 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Honing its weapons in the fight to fend off a $60 billion
hostile bid, the board of Telecom Italia, Italy's biggest phone
company, met Wednesday night to discuss strategies intended to push
the cost of a takeover beyond the reach of its pursuer, Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would release a statement on its
deliberations Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia's proposed moves _ which included a swap of its
common stock for shares in its mobile phone ally, Telecom Italia
Mobile, the conversion of nonvoting shares into common stock with
voting rights, a share buyback, and a sale of noncore assets _ were
laid out before company directors in Rome by its chief executive,
Franco Bernabe.
</P>
<P>
   To finance the measures, Telecom Italia was proposing to raise
at least 10 billion euros, or almost $11 billion, on the capital
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The moves were intended to increase the cost of a takeover to
beyond the price that Olivetti, Italy's No. 2 phone company, is
willing or able to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The measures must be put to a vote at a shareholders' meeting,
which could be called as early as April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti, the computer maker-turned-phone provider that began
its attempt last month, has argued that under new government
takeover rules, Telecom Italia is blocked from adopting
conventional defensive measures _ including a poison pill _ against
the hostile bid. But Bernabe was expected to propose the measures
to the board as part of the company's normal course of business, to
increase profitability and augment the return on equity to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's stock market regulator, Consob, would have to rule on
Olivetti's objections and the legality of any steps that Telecom
Italia might vote to undertake.
</P>
<P>
   Investors anticipating the company's moves drove the share price
up almost 2 percent Wednesday, to 9.915 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's bid, the largest hostile bid ever in Europe, remains
in its early stages, as investment bankers and advisers for both
sides work to assemble the necessary financing. Olivetti plans
shareholder meetings early in April to discuss capital increases
and bond issues. In addition to raising $25 billion in syndicated
loans, Olivetti must find as much as $15 billion by selling bonds
and more than $8 billion by selling its phone business to its phone
partner, Mannesmann of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of Bernabe's proposed measures, people close to the
process said, are plans for Telecom Italia to acquire all of the
mobile phone company's outstanding shares and a buyback of up to 10
percent of its own equity at a maximum price of 15 euros a share.
Telecom Italia owns just over 60 percent of the mobile phone
provider, and a combination of the companies would add to the
pressure on Olivetti to lift its bid of 10 euros a share. Moreover,
Telecom Italia's proposal is to pay shareholders cash, while
Olivetti's bid is 60 percent cash, and the remainder in stock and
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe was expected to propose that his company, within a year,
divest itself of most of its real estate holdings and sell several
noncore manufacturing units and an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, major American and British investment funds have
thrown their weight behind Telecom Italia's efforts to repulse the
Olivetti bid, arguing that the price is too low, and that the shape
of the bid relies on objectionable practices, including burdening
the takeover target with immense debt, the continuance of nonvoting
shares and the use of cascading holding companies as a means of
corporate control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
