<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COMMENTARY: JOE DiMAGGIO'S RINGS, BATS AND TEE SHOTS 
 (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ Before he was to throw out the first ball at
Old-Timers' Day at Yankee Stadium last July, the silver-haired Joe
DiMaggio suddenly arrived in the shadowy corridor behind the Yankee
dugout. He was wearing what he often wore: a blue blazer over a
white shirt with a burgundy tie, sharply creased gray slacks and
shiny black shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look great,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't see how I feel,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   He was 83 and he had pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   He soon recovered. When I visited him in Florida a few weeks
later for a five-hour interview, I noticed the gold
diamond-encrusted ring glistening on the third finger of his left
hand _ his 1936 World Series ring, his rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My other World Series rings were stolen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While on a business trip in the early '60s, he explained, his
eight other World Series rings, along with some cuff links and tie
clasps, were stolen from his Lexington Hotel suite. But when he was
honored on ``Joe DiMaggio Day'' late last season, he was presented
with replicas of those stolen World Series rings, a gift from
George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``George read what you wrote about Joe's rings,'' DiMaggio's
lawyer, Morris Engelberg, told me that day. ``Joe was really
surprised, really thrilled.'' After the ceremony at what would be
the Yankee Clipper's last appearance at Yankee Stadium, he returned
to that shadowy corridor behind the dugout, sat down, opened the
box with the World Series rings and stared at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't they beautiful?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Oct. 12, weak from the return of pneumonia, he entered
Memorial Hospital in Hollywood, Fla. Two days later, he underwent
lung-cancer surgery. He never recovered. Early Monday morning, he
died at his Hollywood home. Thursday, he will be buried in San
Francisco, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw him play baseball remembers his swing with that
long, flowing follow-through and how he moved across center field
so gracefully. As a teen-ager, I saw him play for the Yankees every
so often, and in 1981 I saw him play the way his Yankee teammates
did. As his teammate, in a golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   He was 66 years old then, strong and solid. We were in the same
fivesome at the Super Bowl XV golf tournament at the Chateau
Country Club outside New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   We were playing well in the scramble format, but on the 17th
hole, a par 4 of 310 yards with a pond to the left of the fairway,
I splashed my tee shot. So did our three other teammates. We now
needed the great DiMaggio, as Ernest Hemingway wrote of him in
``The Old Man and the Sea'' to be great.
</P>
<P>
   He was, drilling his tee shot long and straight into the
fairway. Then he spun a wedge to within 10 feet. Birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to that birdie, we finished second in the tournament. His
Yankee teammates will always remember his hits in his 56-game
streak, or in his 1949 comeback at Fenway Park, or in the World
Series, but I'll always remember that tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   I also remember how, before we teed off that day, several
youngsters surrounded him for his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   With each one, he asked, ``What's your name?'' One of the boys
was named Bobby. More than two hours later, we were near the
clubhouse on our way to the 10th tee when that same youngster
suddenly appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Bobby,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Super Bowl XXII golf tournament outside San Diego, the
great DiMaggio, then 72, signed autographs after hitting his tee
shot at each of the first dozen holes. Now, as we moved down the
14th fairway, a middle-aged man holding a white-ash Louisville
Slugger bat emerged from the trees.
</P>
<P>
   `` DiMaggio,'' the man asked, ``will you please sign this bat?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' he said, turning toward the man. ``I don't sign
bats.''
</P>
<P>
   He did sign bats, of course, but only at memorabilia shows,
which by then were his primary source of income. He commanded as
much as $250,000 a show to sign bats and other baseball items.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's your bat,'' the man said. ``It's got your name on it.
It's your model.'' He asked to see the bat and when the man handed
it to him, he glanced at the ``Joe DiMaggio'' signature burned into
the barrel, then he gripped the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got my name on it,'' he said. ``It's not my model.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned the bat. As we moved on, I mentioned that as a
youngster, I had a ``Joe DiMaggio'' bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right,'' I said. ``That man's bat had a thick handle.
The bat I had, the handle was very thin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And whenever I got a shipment of new bats,'' he said, ``I
sand-papered the handles even thinner.''
</P>
<P>
   But now my favorite memory of Joe DiMaggio is my last memory:
his sitting in that shadowy corridor behind the Yankee dugout on
the last day of last season, wearing his 1936 World Series ring and
staring at the shiny replicas of his eight World Series rings that
had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't they beautiful?'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
