<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-SNOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON MAYOR WINS POLITICAL POINTS FOR SNOW REMOVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ill., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the biggest winter storm of the year dropped
as much as 10 inches of snow in some parts of the District of
Columbia, local residents woke up Wednesday morning to find _ could
it be? _ that streets were plowed.
</P>
<P>
   In stark contrast to the last big storm in the capital, a 1996
blizzard that dumped almost two feet of snow, major streets this
time were virtually clear by the morning rush hour, and work crews
were swarming neighborhoods to open up side streets.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal? Here, it is huge.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the district was so broke that only 50 trucks
were available to salt and plow, and many of them broke down,
leaving some streets covered for days. Private contractors refused
to work because the city still owed them money from earlier storms.
The mayor at the time, Marion Barry Jr., toured the city by
helicopter and pronounced streets passable, prompting many
residents to wonder what city he had been inspecting.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has changed since then. Washington has a new mayor,
Anthony Williams, and its fortunes have turned around. When snow
began falling Tuesday morning, city officials had as many as 130
trucks and crews worked continuously.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no comparison,'' Williams said of the efforts then and
now, speaking to reporters after giving a speech about the district
at the National Press Club. ``Back then, there was no real
mobilization, no real plans, and even if there were real plans,
there was nothing to mobilize. I think we have come a long way, but
we still have far to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some critics said snow trucks could have reached
neighborhoods earlier, the big sweep was a major political victory
for Williams. This is a city, after all, that has long grown
accustomed to poor services and whose day-to-day operations
Congress turned over to a financial control board in 1995. Williams
ran for election last fall vowing to improve city services, so to
many district workers and residents, snow clearing was an early
measure of accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least having the main thoroughfares open is progress.
That's a step up,'' said Stanley Sloan, a senior specialist in
international security policy for the Congressional Research
Service, offering an assessment echoed around the city Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is not the first city in which snow removal has had a
political impact on the mayor. In Detroit, Mayor Dennis Archer
faces a recall effort, in part because of the city's lax efforts in
clearing streets this year. Mayor Michael Bilandic lost a
re-election in Chicago in 1979 after the city was slow to remove
snow from a blizzard. And Mayor John Lindsay of New York had
trouble winning re-election in 1969 after streets in Queens were
not plowed quickly following a snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the city's former chief financial officer, has made
``restoring faith and confidence in the government,'' as he said in
his speech, a major thrust of his administration. In addition to
focusing on the big-ticket problems that mayors confront, like
substandard schools, inadequate housing and health-care for the
poor, he has also vowed to fix the kinds of annoyances _ like
irregular garbage pickups and uninterested city employees _ that
reduce the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Wednesday, Williams offered his grand image of the
district government as a well-oiled corporation in which workers
are held accountable for their production.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people really want to hear is how this government is
performing,'' he said. ``But if our government is fundamentally
broken, this vision will not become a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also said improvements would make district residents
less likely to view issues through a prism of race.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a white city administrator resigned after complaints
that he used the word ``niggardly'' in a conversation with a black
colleague who said he heard a racial epithet that sounds similar.
After Williams accepted the resignation, he learned that the
administrator had not used the epithet.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that incidents like that deflect public attention
from the district's larger mission, to improve services and hasten
the day when local residents might win true representation in
Congress. Now, they have only a delegate to the House, who has no
vote. The district is suing to attain full voting representation in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The city's success with snow removal may help in some small way,
and Williams offered it as a solid example of a city on the mend.
And he said the snow was good news for another reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps with rats,'' he said. ``A good snow and a good freeze
kills them because they don't have a house to live in. The only bad
news is, we'll probably have more potholes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
