<HEADER>
A5799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-10 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TWO MEN WITH MUCH IN COMMON
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ Bob Watson was home in Houston early Wednesday
morning, when his phone rang. Joe Torre was on the line. Watson was
pleased and surprised to hear from his old friend, his good friend.
He had hired Torre to manage the Yankees in 1995 when Watson was
the team's general manager and Torre was looking for a job.
</P>
<P>
   They were friends as players and when Torre was a manager in
Atlanta and Watson was a player, Torre encouraged him to become a
manager and to move into the front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was my idol as a player,'' Watson said. ``When George
Steinbrenner asked me who to consider for the job, I had a short
list, and Joe was at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   But this call wasn't a baseball call. Torre, not one for
chitchat, cut to the chafe. ``He said, `Hey, looks like we've got
more in common than you know,''' Watson recalled. ``He said, `I got
my biopsy back; I have prostate cancer.' There was a moment of
silence on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson's reaction was repeated throughout the baseball world
Wednesday. Even though Joe DiMaggio had died early Monday, the team
was primed for Darryl Strawberry's debut on Wednesday. After a
six-month bout with colon cancer, Strawberry's appearance was
expected to be an inspirational symbol of the Yankees new
imprimatur: tough, resilient, enduring.
</P>
<P>
   But Strawberry's moment was upstaged and dwarfed by Wednesday's
jarring news that Torre, the only manager with the temperament,
tolerance and perspective to manage the Yankees this well, was
suffering from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a team regarded as invincible. Now, in the span of a
few days, with DiMaggio's death and Catfish Hunter's illness, young
and old players were reminded that life outside the lines is
fragile in an unpredictable way that neither uniform nor legacy can
protect.
</P>
<P>
   `` I'm not surprised by anything anymore,'' Watson said. ``I
guess I was surprised by this. Joe's on top of the world now. He
manages the best team in the history of the game. He just signed a
new contract. He has a new wife, they have a new baby.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Torre called Watson; he knew that he'd been there.
Watson was on top of the world in 1993 when he was named general
manager of the Houston Astros, the first African-American to be
appointed GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the top of my game,'' Watson said. In the spring of
1994, it was determined that Watson had prostate cancer and his
world was turned around. ``I got in touch with my spiritual side, I
looked at the way I spent time with my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months after his surgery, Watson returned to work two times
per week. Torre's diagnosis is too new to even discuss the various
treatments or the prognosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depends on what it is and where it is,'' Watson said. ``Right
now there's still too many questions. What you want to hear is that
it's still in a gland and hasn't spread. He was going to get a bone
scan Thursday to find out how aggressive it is, or if it's
aggressive. The biggest thing now is to try to cope mentally more
than physically, knowing he has this thing growing in his body.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be easier said that done. Even Watson admitted there
wasn't a time that he didn't think about his condition. ``I always
think about it,'' Watson said. ``You got that scar, you know it's
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the great Yankee triumphs and great Yankee lore, the
franchise has always walked a pathos-tinged hero's path. No
franchise better exemplifies the mortality of the sports hero than
the Yankees. Babe Ruth frail with cancer, hoarse saying farewell at
Yankee Stadium; Lou Gehrig cut down in his 30s by a disease that is
commonly known by his name, saying farewell at Yankee Stadium;
Billy Martin's drinking and death in an auto accident; Thurman
Munson, killed in an airplane crash, and Strawberry receiving a
diagnosis of cancer last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, former Yankees star pitcher Catfish Hunter appeared
at the Yankees camp, too weak to shake hands because of Lou
Gehrig's Disease. Thursday in San Francisco, the world pays final
tribute to DiMaggio _ the defining Yankee. Now Torre is faced with
the challenge of survival.
</P>
<P>
   If Torre feels as Watson felt in 1994, batting orders, lineups
and world championships are the last thing on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you this,'' Watson said. ``Baseball will be way
down on the totem pole while he goes through this. ``I just want to
be very supportive. This will be a difficult time.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he hung up Wednesday and got on with his day, Watson said
he told Torre that was determined to see him become a living
legend. ``I told him that we can beat this thing,'' Watson said.
``I'm living proof.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
