<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MOISO-LADN     03-10 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MOISO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIND FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ UCLA freshman forward Jerome Moiso and assistant
coach Jim Saia discussed many things during Moiso's long
recruitment last season, but the subject invariably returned to
Moiso. To his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Saia,'' Moiso would say, ``I can be good, but there's
something I'm missing, and that's the mental stuff. That's what I'm
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Saia knew it. He knew the 6-foot-10 Moiso, with his long arms
and soft touch, had NBA talent and high school insecurity. He knew
the Bruins would have to counsel Moiso more than coach him. He knew
that if the Bruins could combine American confidence with Moiso's
sharp European skills, they'd have an All-American.
</P>
<P>
   He knew it would be an enormous challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Jerome had a lackadaisical attitude and somewhat of a
European (ie: finesse) game,'' Saia said. ``All his people told me
he needed to be more aggressive. I've thought about taking him to a
sports psychologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Bruins prepare for tonight's NCAA Tournament
first-round game against Detroit, the difference between success
and failure sits atop Moiso's shoulders. With center Dan Gadzuric
on crutches, Moiso is their only big man, their best shot blocker
and their best interior scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Davis cannot carry them through March Madness alone. He
needs help. He needs Moiso.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's extremely important to what we do,'' Davis said. ``He has
to be a force inside, be our defensive stopper. I have a feeling
the tournament will bring out the best in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso isn't so sure. Then again, he never is. When he plays his
best _ Kentucky, Arizona (first game), USC and Louisville _ the
Bruins usually follow. But when February arrived, his body broke
down. He developed tendinitis in his right foot, near the arch, and
it spread to his left. He played in pain and lost all confidence,
bottoming with a 1-of-12 performance at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   He missed the Cal and USC games, then discovered the wonders of
a sports cream. The heat soothed his tender arches, and his timing
and conditioning returned. Last week, at Arizona State, Moiso
scored eight points, grabbed 10 rebounds and dominated the lane in
the second half. He was back to his pre-injury form _ or so
everyone thought. Two days later, at Arizona, Moiso was
ineffective, struggling with confidence and foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Which Moiso appears tonight?
</P>
<P>
   Prepare for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm struggling right now,'' he said. ``I don't feel the same
way I did at the beginning. I'm looking for that. We need me
(tonight), and for the rest of the way. I need to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``it'' is, no one knows for sure. Perhaps it's
aggressiveness. Perhaps it's confidence. Most likely, it's a
combination of the two. But this much is certain: Moiso, born on
the Caribbean island of Guadeloupe and educated in France, is not
the first European player to lack these qualities. No one has ever
accused Toni Kukoc or Vlade Divac of playing rough.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Moiso is a product of his culture. European
teen-agers don't view basketball as a means to the good life. They
lack the determination of their American counterparts. Where soccer
is king, basketball is considered back burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system creates that mentality because the sport is not a
social issue in Europe,'' said Christophe Douchand, a French
television journalist who interviewed Moiso two weeks ago at UCLA
for a documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fine line between confidence and arrogance.
American athletes go as far as you can without crossing the line.
That is not the case in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, the kids say, `I'm good.' In Europe, they say,
`I'm good, but maybe I'm not.' Jerome is as confident as an average
European player. But put him next to JaRon Rush or Baron Davis, and
his attitude is not as aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Saia and Moiso have developed what they call an
aggression scale. At various times during practices and games, Saia
will ask, ``Jerome, where are you?'' If Moiso is feeling confident,
he'll say six or seven. If not, he'll say two or three. Then Saia
proffers his evaluation and it usually includes the line: ``We
can't win with that _ we need you at a seven or eight.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about the best the Bruins can hope for.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll never be a nine,'' Saia said. ``That's just not him. But
that's all we talk about. We don't talk about moves or shots. All
we talk about is him being aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   If Moiso is going to regain his lost confidence, the time is
now. Detroit's center, 6-11 sophomore Walter Craft, is no match for
Moiso's skills. No doubt, the Bruins will try to establish Moiso
early _ something they did not do at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I cannot say that I'm ready to be the man,'' Moiso
said. ``I'm struggling for it. But I know I need to be that
person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
