<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-VIRTUAL-WALKOUT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT staff stage virtual walkout over pay
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Jennifer Gill wore black, chanted loudly and
hoisted a sign that said ``Show Us the Money'' at a University of
Texas rally Wednesday to keep a spotlight on low staff pay.
</P>
<P>
   In her 11 years at UT, Gill, 46, has climbed the do-it-yourself
career ladder that many staff members follow: moving from one
department to the next to gain bit-by-bit improvements in pay.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gill has reached an all-time high of $25,428 a year as an
administrative associate in the School of Music where she processes
applications, coordinates auditions and serves as the information
contact for undergraduate admissions. But a history of low wages
has left her struggling financially in a city where the cost of
living has risen dramatically this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just me,'' Gill said. ``It's many, many people. . .
.There are plenty of people at UT with master's degrees making less
than $20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   She was among the non-teaching staff members at UT taking part
in a ``virtual walkout'' Wednesday to protest below-market pay.
Recent pay surveys showed that the vast majority of UT staff,
including custodians, secretaries, library aides and student
advisers are paid below average for the Austin market.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual walkout participants stayed on their jobs but posted
signs in their work areas stating what they contribute to the
university. Several hundred _ most of them clad in black _ also
joined a noon rally despite a steady drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look around you and look at the collective power we have,''
said Peg Kramer, president of the University Staff Association,
which organized the group's fifth demonstration this year.
</P>
<P>
   Staff are not alone in their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Several at the rally noted they came with the blessings of their
supervisors and support from faculty, administrators and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``This potentially great university would be lost without the
staff,'' said Mia Carter, an associate professor of English who
spoke at the rally. ``Every single degree granted by this
university has the imprint of many hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Smith, a graduate student in social work, said an increase
in staff salaries would mean ``boosting the quality of education on
this campus.''
</P>
<P>
   UT President Larry Faulkner has raised the lowest salaries from
$11,220 to $14,004 a year. He has said that increasing pay remains
one of his highest priorities, even if it means sharply limiting
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders have said UT should not expect a big boost
in state aid. Several local delegates, however, sent statements of
support that were read at the rally, including Austin Democratic
Reps. Sherri Greenberg, Glen Maxey and Elliott Naishtat. Dawnna
Dukes, another Austin Democrat, sent an aide.
</P>
<P>
   Several staff speakers said they enjoy their jobs but wonder how
long they can hang on.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Mallory, 23, a library assistant who makes $16,400 a year
and has a bachelor's degree in psychology, said she wonders why she
earns so little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay because I love my job,'' she said later.
</P>
<P>
   Gill, a pianist, said she stays because she likes the academic
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to be out in the cut-throat business world,'' she
said. ``I could probably make more money, but I wouldn't enjoy it
so much. Here, I'm surrounded by art and music.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a price.
</P>
<P>
   Gill has a child at UT and another at Austin Community College
but she can't afford to help pay their tuition. She also is trying
to dig herself out of credit card and medical debt. She copes by
working a second job at at a bookstore, sharing rent with a
housemate and avoiding purchases that are not essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have pared my life down,'' she said. ``I make my own skirts,
I shop for bargains and I buy the cheapest gas I can. I don't buy
things. I don't rent videos, I don't buy CDs, even though I love
music, and I don't buy books or newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill's take home pay from UT is $1,659 a month; she takes home
another $425 a month from the bookstore, for a total of $2,084. But
her expenses each month average $1,904, including rent of $575, a
car payment of $222, a $300 minimum credit card payment and a $165
payment to her dentist for a bill that exceeds $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   She has almost no cushion for emergencies and no savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of sad,'' she said, ``that we run up these
bills just to get by because we work at the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
