<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUNGLED-SMUGGLING11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why did she leave Haiti?
 &HT;    By Mary Lou Pickel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Edner Doirin sat expressionless at the
Palm Beach County Medical Examiner's Office Wednesday, looking at a
Polaroid of a woman's face.
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes were closed, her hair disheveled.
</P>
<P>
   He looked again and again, comparing the dead image before him
with a passport-style photo he carried of his carefully coiffed
young bride, Michaelle Dieujuste.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was one of 40 Haitian refugees feared dead in the
worst immigrant smuggling catastrophe in Florida since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   She carried a card with a name and phone number that led
authorities to Doirin, who said he was expecting Dieujuste to
arrive by boat last weekend. They asked him to come to the Medical
Examiner's Office to identify her Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two boats with 43 people sank 26 miles off the coast of West
Palm Beach before dawn Saturday. Three men survived. The U.S. Coast
Guard pulled two bodies from the sea _ Dieujuste, 25, of
Port-au-Prince, and a woman they believe is Immacula Fleurantin, 33
of Jacmel.
</P>
<P>
   Doirin, a tobacco and sweet-potato picker, left Rocky Mount,
N.C., Saturday to meet his wife. Someone in Haiti had told him she
was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 7 p.m., while driving past Fort Pierce, he
received a page.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said two boats sank in the water,'' Doirin said. His wife
didn't swim.
</P>
<P>
   Doirin began searching the emergency rooms of West Palm Beach
that night.
</P>
<P>
   Why did she leave Haiti, he asked himself.
</P>
<P>
   Dieujuste earned a living by buying clothes, soap and lotions in
the Bahamas and selling them in Haiti, Doirin said.
</P>
<P>
   In Port-au-Prince, he said, ``she's got a home, she's got a car,
she's got no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she left their 18-month-old twins in her mother's care and
took her chances on a smuggler's boat.
</P>
<P>
   The lanky Doirin came to the United States in 1986 and has a
green card. He visited Dieujuste every five months of their
six-year relationship. They married two years ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials told him it could take 10 years for his
wife to emigrate legally, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She come because I'm here,'' he sighed.
</P>
<P>
   The woman in the photo, her features muted by a watery death,
resembled the woman in Doirin's wallet picture.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to see her body, but that's not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to see a necklace she wore, to make sure it was the
one he had given her, but the Border Patrol had collected it for
safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   At last, he saw a photocopy of a business card found on her
body. It was of the North Carolina garage where he fixes his car.
</P>
<P>
   He had given it to her so she could call the number if she ever
needed to get in touch with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's her,'' Doirin finally said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to make it official, he signed the back of the photo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
