<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5942 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARKANSAS-HNS &LR;      03-10 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARKANSAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ His team lost 10 games along the way, double the total of
his first-round opponent here. The characteristic full-court
pressure went by the wayside early in the season because his young
team couldn't run it, and he benched a couple of seniors late
because he was worried they were trying too hard.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday, though, Nolan Richardson, college basketball's angry
man, was all smiles. However today's NCAA West Regional opener
against Siena turns out, the Arkansas coach already is feeling like
a winner this week.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger battle at long last has been won, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, talking to John Thompson and John Chaney and those
guys, all that effort for a while we didn't think it was going to
work out,'' Richardson said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it did. Earlier this week, a United States district
judge struck down Proposition 16, ruling that the NCAA cannot
impose Scholastic Assessment Test scores as a method to establish
qualifying standards for athletes because the standardized tests
tend to discriminate disproportionately against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The battle isn't over, as the NCAA will seek to have the
decision muted or reversed. For the moment, though, the
Richardsons, Thompsons and Chaneys have found at least one ally in
a high place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love standards,'' Richardson said. ``You've got to have
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the standards have got to be fair. Education has to be for
the poor also.''
</P>
<P>
   That stance, simple and logical as it might have seemed to
Richardson and those of similar mind, hadn't always been the stuff
to win friends and influence people. Richardson even conceded
Wednesday that his decision to seize the pulpit and speak out took
some of the joy out of Arkansas' 1994 national championship.
</P>
<P>
   His angry countenance didn't always play well with fans or
media. Certainly, it didn't make life any more pleasant for the
fellow who unfailingly took up residence at the heart of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look back now and see what has happened with one judge's
ruling,'' he said, ``it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Richardson would like to have a little more fun. With an
odd mix _ three seniors and six freshmen, three of whom have played
prominent roles _ the Hogs have been up-and-down for most of the
season and are tough to handicap as the big show gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   They started 5-1, employing their customary full-court pressure,
before a 30-point defeat at Oklahoma convinced Richardson they were
not quite ready to use the whole ``40 minutes of hell'' package.
</P>
<P>
   Reverting to a half-court game, Arkansas won six in a row before
a defeat at Auburn. After subsequent losses to Mississippi and
Alabama, Richardson went back to the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on the bubble for a Tournament spot, the Hogs sealed
the deal by defeating Auburn and Kentucky at home within a five-day
stretch. A loss at Alabama let some of the air out of the balloon,
but the Hogs beat Florida and Mississippi State in the Southeastern
Conference tournament before losing to Kentucky in the final game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they hit the NCAAs as a No. 4 seed in the West. At 22-10,
they meet 25-5 Siena today 30 minutes after Iowa (18-9) and
Alabama-Birmingham (20-11) get the day started with an 11:40 a.m.
tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri (20-8) and New Mexico (24-8) lead off the evening
session at 6:50 p.m., with top-seed Connecticut (28-2) taking on
No. 16 Texas-San Antonio (18-10) in the last game of the day.
</P>
<P>
   In Arkansas, Siena finds one of the Tournament's enigmas, a team
with potential but one not burdened by great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The seniors _ guard Pat Bradley, forward Derek Hood and guard
Kareem Reid _ are the leading scorers, averaging 14.4, 12.5 and
10.2 points respectively. Hood, just 6-8, has been the main force
inside, averaging 10.5 rebounds, while Reid manages five assists
per game.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, from the Bronx, N.Y., generally is the best indication of
which way the wind is blowing. When he is on, the Razorbacks can
play with anyone, but he is given to be less than his best at
inopportune moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't so much good hype at the beginning,'' he said.
``But I think it's been a smooth ride lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid will be at the heart of the matter again today, if Siena
coach Paul Hewitt is to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we run up against great guards who have great games, we
have problems,'' Hewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's freshmen hope to cause problems, too. Forwards
Chris Jefferies and Sergerio Gipson and guard Brandon Dean have
played in 95 of a possible 96 games combined, with Jefferies making
19 starts. Each averages more than 7.1 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   What next, then? Will March Madness bring out the team that beat
Auburn and Kentucky or the one that was blown out by an OU club
that barely made the field of 64?
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Richardson doesn't know, but he appreciates the irony in
what this postseason brings. When times should have been happier,
they weren't. Now, a fellow atop a Tournament dark horse is able to
enjoy the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time in '94, I was an angry person,'' he said. ``But I
had a reason to be angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm walking around on Cloud Nine, and I ain't played a
game yet.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, with practice about to begin, he stepped down from
the soapbox unhurried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, write about that,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan's happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
