<HEADLINE>
JAIL INSTEAD OF PSYCHIATRISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It did not take long after the vaunted reforms of the 1970s,
when warehouses for the mentally ill were shut down, for reformers
to notice that the mental-health millennium had not arrived.
Inmates were freed from appalling conditions behind institution
walls only to reappear on city streets, wandering at risk to
themselves and sometimes to others as well as to civic propriety.
The community health alternatives that were supposed to replace the
oversize state hospitals remained wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven years ago, Geraldo Rivera was one of those who
contributed to deinstitutionalism when he exposed Willowbrook, a
New York home for the mentally retarded that came to stand for
warehousing at its most excruciating. Friday night he delivers case
histories of what he says represents the latest fashion in
society's noncare: confining the mentally ill in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rivera is in a relatively sober mode, his program's
production effects are as frenetic as ever, loading on the most
sensational images available of violence and commotion. That is
particularly unfortunate, not only for their slow-motion,
fast-motion triteness and their reminder of Rivera's reputation
before reform gripped him, but also because this time his material
is worth attention.
</P>
<P>
   From Louisiana to California to Tennessee to Colorado, he finds
people with schizophrenia and other psychiatric illnesses consigned
to the company of criminals rather than sick people. The
consequence for perhaps a million inmates, who Rivera says are
``caught between good intentions and broken promises,'' seems to be
at best inadequate care and too often abuse by guards trained to
subdue their charges rather than assist them.
</P>
<P>
   Especially painful are the accounts of parents who find that the
only way they can get some sort of medical attention for their
children is to have them convicted of a felony. Yet the examples
featured here of what goes on in the generally jammed prisons _
fights among prisoners, isolation cells and tough nonlove _ are not
reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   At best, Rivera reports, the ill may receive drugs but not much
else that passes for treatment. A prison official laments that
there is nowhere else to send the afflicted youths. One despairing
mother calls the practice ``imprisonment for mental health.''
</P>
<P>
   A few concluding minutes are given to a model halfway house in
Washington and a plug for Tipper Gore, who is organizing a White
House meeting on mental health in May. These days reformers appear
to be focusing on luring or coercing the mentally ill into
treatment, pressure once resisted by civil liberties advocates. But
then, as evidenced by Rivera's work, exposes have a way of changing
with the times.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`BACK TO BEDLAM'  &QL; 
 &QL; 
9 p.m. ET Friday on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Susan Farkas, executive producer; Bob Abeshouse and Carl
Ginsburg, producers; Subrata De and Melanie Neilson Junceau, field
producers; Bob Brandel, editor.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
