<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-EVERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBIN, THE PRACTICE PARTNER, STUNS HINGIS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIAN WELLS, Calif. _ On Wednesday morning Martina Hingis, the
Evert Cup's defending champion, selected Chanda Rubin as her
practice partner for this afternoon's quarterfinal even though it
was none other than Rubin whom she was scheduled to face in that
round.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for complication was easy for the top-ranked
Hingis to overlook because, in her opinion, Rubin is the perfect
practice partner. And Hingis takes perfection wherever she finds
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practice, she could be a real champion, but in matches, she
just wasn't really able to put her game together and beat great
players,'' said Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   But to the great surprise of Hingis, the 26th-ranked Rubin
didn't leave her championship game on the practice court. Instead,
she took them out to the sunlit stadium court and used them to
inflict a 6-3, 7-6 (7-2) thrashing on Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis was fallible on her backhand side, sluggish with her
footwork, and feeble with her ever-suspect second serve, which
Rubin demolished 15 of the 20 times she took a swat at it.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hingis twice served for the second set, she couldn't
convert either attempt, and the ensuing tie breaker was just an
encore to what had unfolded before: Rubin, renowned as a comeback
artist rather than a front-runner, led the whole way. An unfocused
forehand return from Hingis at match point clinched an upset Rubin
readily described as the best victory of her injury-interrupted
career.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since she underwent wrist surgery in August of 1996, Rubin
has been in comeback limbo, unable to restore her game to its
former stability: she went to a career-best sixth in the world, and
was touted as a serious Slam contender before her wrist intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin will face seventh-seeded Steffi Graf, who improved her
record against Jana Novotna to 29-4 with a perfunctory 6-2, 6-0
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week I've felt like I'm hitting the ball well enough to
play with anybody and to beat anybody,'' said Rubin, who has won 13
of her last 15 matches, including upsets of 14th-seeded Conchita
Martinez and seventh-seeded Amanda Coetzer here before Wednesday's
dismantling of Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hingis: ``I was always one step late and too defensive
today; on the rallies with the backhand, I usually am better than
most of the players, usually I win these rallies, but she just
wouldn't miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin broke Hingis' serve on 7 of 13 opportunities. ``I wanted
to take advantage on her second serve, start the point off
aggressively, and overall I felt I did the things I wanted to do
out there,'' said Rubin, whose down-the-line drives and cross-court
passes continually flummoxed Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, who knocked second-seeded Lindsay Davenport
from contention in the second round, continued to rid the draw's
bottom half of its seeds: Wednesday's victim was sixth-seeded Mary
Pierce, 7-5, 7-6 (7-1). ``She's a powerful, powerful player,'' said
Pierce, who has often heard that comment about her own game.
</P>
<P>
   The men's event, the Newsweek Champions Cup, operated in upset
mode as well: Third-seeded Alex Corretja of Spain, one of four
players who had a chance of overtaking Pete Sampras at No. 1 this
week, was dismissed by Australia's Mark Philippoussis, 4-6, 7-5,
6-2. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
