<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEARS-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARS SETTLES SUIT ON RAISING OF ITS CREDIT CARD RATES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ariz.)  (nk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. announced Wednesday that it would settle a
class-action suit from plaintiffs who contended that the retailer
had fraudulently raised the annual interest rates on their credit
cards after it had promised not to. Sears agreed to pay $36 million
in cash and issue store coupons worth $118 million to card holders.
</P>
<P>
   The company's large credit-card operations _ about 63 million
U.S. households own a Sears card _ have a troubled history. Just
last month, Sears pleaded guilty to federal changes that it had
illegally forced card holders who had filed for personal bankruptcy
to pay their Sears debt anyway. Sears paid $475 million in fines
and penalties to settle all suits related to those charges.
</P>
<P>
   This credit-card settlement was unrelated to the bankruptcy
issue. From 1994 to 1996, Sears, based in Hoffman Estates, Ill.,
moved many of its credit-card accounts to a credit-card bank it had
acquired in Arizona. When Sears transferred the accounts, it
changed the annual finance charge to 21 percent for all accounts
but said that balances accrued before the transfer would continue
to be billed at their old rates.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, Sears sent a notice that it was changing credit
terms. Under the new terms, unpaid balances accrued before the
consolidation would be subject to the same annual interest rate
that Sears charged on all its other accounts. In some cases, that
amounted to a rate increase. Defendants in the class action
contended that the first letter amounted to a promise not to change
rates and that Sears was breaching the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In settling the case, Sears admitted no wrongdoing. The action
was taken ``to avoid the litigation,'' said Jan Drummond, a company
spokeswoman. She also said, ``It is an acknowledgment that the
communication we sent may have been misconstrued by customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Raising credit-card rates without customer approval has become a
national issue as the credit-card business consolidates into fewer
and larger hands and banks sell accounts to other banks, which are
free to impose whatever interest rate the traffic will bear. But
the Sears ruling is not likely have significant effect on the
industry. ``The issue here is specific to them and their
literature,'' said Anita Boomstein, a partner at Hughes Hubbard &AMP;
Reed L.L.P. who specializes in credit-card law.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was brought on behalf of a nationwide class who were
transferred to the Arizona bank and who had not fully paid off
their balances when credit terms changed in 1997. All 11 million of
these customers will get a coupon worth $7.50 _ even though not all
of them had their interest rates changed. Three million customers
who had their rates increased will receive a combination of cash
and coupons totaling $23.80.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sears agreed to spend $3 million for consumer
counseling, protection and education. The settlement is subject to
court approval.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, Sears said Wednesday that it would
buy back up to $1.5 billion of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   The buyback, which will take place over an unspecified time,
represents about 9 percent of outstanding Sears shares. Shares of
Sears rose $1.3125, to $45, on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
