<HEADLINE>
MURDERS IN NEW YORK UP 5% SO FAR IN '99
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The number of murders reported in New York City has
risen slightly this year compared with the same period last year,
the police said Wednesday, adding that there was no way to know
whether the increase represented a temporary jump or a leveling off
in the city's historic drop in crime of the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   There were 115 murders reported in the city this year through
March 7, an increase of 5.5 percent over the same period last year,
when 109 murders were reported, according to preliminary Police
Department statistics. Reported crime continued to drop in all
other major categories, though, and overall reported crime was down
14 percent, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said at a news conference that
it was too early to say what the figures presage. ``Homicides, like
all crimes, have peaks and valleys,'' he said. He noted that even
if the city ended the year with 700 murders _ there were 629
reported last year _ it would still represent the second-lowest
total since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary analysis of the year's homicides indicated that
the biggest jump was in those stemming from domestic violence or
family disputes, Safir said. Marilyn Mode, a police spokeswoman,
said that of the murders with known motives, 21 stemmed from
domestic violence or family disputes, up from 11 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic violence murders are among the most difficult to curb
with policing tactics. Though the police have found that increasing
patrols in high-crime areas and starting antidrug initiatives can
bring down the number of murders related to robberies and drug
deals, they have a much harder time keeping a husband from killing
his wife at home.
</P>
<P>
   Not all areas of the city saw the number of murders go up.
</P>
<P>
   The largest increases were in southern Queens, which had 8
reported killings compared with 4 last year, and northern
Manhattan, which jumped to 16 from 9. But there were fewer reported
killings this year in the Bronx, which had 26, and northern
Brooklyn, which had 19.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Queens remained steady with 11, as did Staten Island,
which had none. There were 8 killings reported in Manhattan south
of 59th Street, and 27 in southern Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The increase was most striking in the last four weeks, when 52
killings were reported, compared with 45 over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Safir has credited aggressive police tactics with
driving down crime. He noted Wednesday that some people had
suggested that after the Feb. 4 shooting of Amadou Diallo and the
increased scrutiny it has brought on the Police Department, some
officers might fear taking aggressive action.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is unclear whether the police are holding back, in
the four weeks after the Diallo shooting, officers made 186 arrests
for firearms possession, down 17 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have expressed concerns with me about police officers
not wanting to take chances because of the possibility they will be
viewed in the wrong light, or as overly aggressive,'' Safir said.
``All of that is just speculation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-10-99 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990310.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-10 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
