<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STRAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. PHILIP STRAX, 90, IS DEAD; AN ADVOCATE OF MAMMOGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Fla., Texas)  (nk) 
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Philip Strax, a radiologist whose early and passionate
advocacy of the mammogram helped revolutionize breast-cancer
detection, died on Tuesday at a daughter's home in Bethesda, Md. He
was 90.
</P>
<P>
   A general practitioner with a small family practice in
Manhattan, Strax was spurred into a single-minded battle against
breast cancer in 1947, when his first wife died of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   About 16 years later, he helped conduct a milestone study
involving almost 62,000 women in New York that established
conclusively that early detection of breast cancer significantly
reduced its mortality rate. Strax went on to open several
pioneering clinics devoted to breast-cancer detection, often at no
charge, and inaugurated the city's first mobile mammography units.
</P>
<P>
   Bertha Goldberg Strax, the doctor's wife, was 39 when she died.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very much in love with her,'' said Dr. Albert Messina,
director of Park Avenue Radiology, where Strax practiced until
about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they discovered it, he was shocked,'' Messina said of the
breast cancer. ``It was a major blow to him. And he decided at the
time that he was going to spend his lifework preventing that kind
of shock from happening to anyone else, especially the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Bertha Strax's death, few doctors realized that
X-rays could be useful in detecting breast cancer, in part because
the technology of the time was best-suited for giving doctors a
picture of bones. When it came to detecting problems in soft tissue
like that making up the breast, the pictures were so blurry as to
be of little value. Many doctors, moreover, attributed the
mortality of any given case to the strength of the individual
cancer, not to the time when it was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the technology was refined, allowing doctors to get a
clearer picture of the breast.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Strax collaborated in the first large-scale
controlled study of women to determine the effectiveness of
mammograms in reducing mortality. The study was conducted from 1963
to 1966 by the Health Insurance Plan of Greater New York and
involved tens of thousands of women 40 to 64 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Half the women were given mammograms and manual breast cancer
examinations; the other half were not. When the first results of
the study were published some years later, doctors announced that
the use of mammography had reduced breast-cancer deaths by a third.
Even now, since patients from the HIP study are still alive, new
analyses of the data are being published, Dr. Michael A . Cohen,
medical director of Memorial Sloan-Kettering's Guttman Diagnostic
Center, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Strax, then affiliated with the University of Miami
School of Medicine, and a colleague, Prof. Sam Shapiro of Johns
Hopkins University, were honored for their work by the General
Motors Cancer Research Foundation. The HIP study, the foundation
said in awarding the $100,000 prize, ``almost unilaterally changed
medical thinking about early detection.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the results of the studies were fully known, Strax
had opened two clinics in New York where women could have
mammograms at low cost or no charge. He also opened a third clinic,
the Strax Institute, in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he started his breast center and he started to use
mammography,'' Cohen said, ``it had not been statistically proven
that mammography was an effective means of cancer detection and
mortality reduction in women. He had that vision. He thought it was
the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Cohen noted, ``it is today really our only effective way of
screening for breast cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Strax also emphasized the importance of manual examinations. ``A
good exam has three components,'' he said in an interview in 1966,
``the mammogram, a clinical examination by a physician or trained
nurse, and a lesson in breast self-examination.''
</P>
<P>
   Some debate persists, however, about the reliability and
effectiveness of mammograms for women under 50. The often denser
nature of breast tissue in younger women can make it harder to spot
problems. At the same time, a higher number of false alarms have
been reported in mammograms of women below 50.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Strax was born on Jan. 1, 1909, the son of Jacob and
Molly Strax, and grew up in Brooklyn. His parents had emigrated
from Eastern Europe, and his father worked in the garment industry
sewing pockets. Philip Strax was one of five children, three of
whom became doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Strax graduated from New York University Medical School in 1931,
at the age of 22, and went into private practice.
</P>
<P>
   After the death of his first wife, Strax married Gertrude
Jacobson. She died in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Strax was the author of several books about breast cancer and
three volumes of poetry, his other lifelong passion. In the poetry,
as in his life, ``his most important theme is, always do more for
others than is done for you,'' said a daughter, Rita Weil, of
Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Strax retired about a decade ago and lived in Hollywood, Fla.,
but he was taken to Mrs. Weil's home about a week before he died
there.
</P>
<P>
   Strax is survived by a sister, Dr. Anne Robbins of Ossining,
N.Y.; three daughters: Polly Hammer of Huntington, N.Y., Gayle
Martin of Plantation, Fla., and Mrs. Weil; three sons: Norman, of
New York, Marshall, of Nanuet, N.Y., and Dr. Richard, of Houston;
eight grandchildren and one great-grandson.
</P>
<P>
   At the Guttman Institute, Cohen said, some of Strax's patients
still talk about him decades after their encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could live in the heart of one of my patients for the
next 30 years,'' Cohen said, ``that would be an accomplishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
