<HEADER>
A5971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-SENATORS-     03-10 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-SENATORS-230&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO DEBATE: THESE SENATORS ARE GOOD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In losing by 3-0 to the Ottawa Senators Wednesday
night at Madison Square Garden, the Rangers saw their undefeated
streak end at six games and their winning streak end at three. They
missed a chance to move back into a tie with Boston for the eighth
and final playoff berth in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defeat, the Rangers performed well against the team
with the best record in the conference, battling hard until the
end. Even without three regular defensemen and three regular
forwards, even after being outplayed for the first two-thirds of
the game, they came on strong in the third period, pressuring
Ottawa goalie Damian Rhodes, who stopped 29 shots, 11 of them in
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Ottawa's goals were scored by Aleksei Yashin, one in the
first period on the power play, the other in the third period into
the empty net after the Rangers pulled goalie Mike Richter for an
extra attacker. Lance Pitlick scored at even strength in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers hope to get at least one or two of their injured
players back Thursday night when they play host to the Bruins. This
was the sixth time the Rangers have been shut out this season, five
of them defeats, one of them a 0-0 tie. It was the first time they
have been shut out by the senators since 1933, when the first
version of the Ottawa team played in the National Hockey League.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Senators, in their seventh season, are proof that expansion
teams can build contenders with draft choices and that Canadian
teams can compete with American teams despite differences in
currency values and market size. Should the Senators maintain their
position while the Rangers qualify for the last playoff berth,
these two teams could meet in the first round of the Stanley Cup
playoffs in late April.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators scored once in the first period and once in the
second, and the Rangers were fortunate to be trailing by only 2-0
at the second intermission. Ottawa dominated the first 40 minutes,
keeping the puck at the Ranger end of the ice for long stretches of
time. Occasionally, Ranger fans cheered sarcastically when the Blue
Shirts were able to clear the puck out of their zone. Ottawa's
26-18 shot advantage was misleading. In good scoring chances, the
Senators might have been ahead by 15-5.
</P>
<P>
   Yashin, a candidate for the Hart trophy as the NHL's most
valuable player, gave the Senators a 1-0 lead at 6 minutes 18
seconds of the first period when he scooped up a pass next to
Richter's net on the power play and flipped the puck over the
sprawling goalie. It was Yashin's 36th goal of the season and came
during the first part of a double minor against Rich Brennan, the
defenseman, who was sent off for high-sticking Vaclav Prospal, an
incident that left Prospal with a broken tooth and a cut mouth.
Yashin, the captain, is a 25-year-old star from Russia who leads a
roster that is heavily stocked with European players.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators made the score 2-0 at 9:18 of the second period on
the goal by Pitlick, a defenseman who finished a transition rush by
moving up uncovered into the slot and beating Richter. The goal was
typical of the way the Senators play. Young, strong and fast, they
take advantage of turnovers in their defensive end or in the
neutral zone, and use them to trigger speedy counter rushes.
Although Ottawa plays a variation of the neutral-zone trap, it is
not a passive and boring version. The Senators rarely fight and are
lightly penalized. Their average of 11.4 penalty minutes per game
is the lowest in the 27-team league. So it is difficult for a team
like the Rangers _ which counts on its power play _ to get manpower
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers killed off three power plays in the second period,
one of them for high-sticking against Stan Neckar, a former
Senator. Because the Rangers have so many injuries to their
defense, players such as Neckar, Brennan and Rumun Ndur are getting
more exposure. But, following his penalty, Neckar began to spend
longer minutes on the bench. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
