<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-GREEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' GREEN HAS STREAK APPROACHING 1,000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A.C. Green is trying his best to treat Saturday's home
game against the Vancouver Grizzlies as just another basketball
game.
</P>
<P>
   But deep down, the Mavericks forward knows this game is very
special to him and to the NBA. That's because it will be the
1,000th consecutive game Green has played in _ assuming, of course,
he plays in his 999th game in a row when the Mavericks (6-14) face
the Orlando Magic (14-5) at 7:30 tonight at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Green, 35, has been besieged with interview requests this week
leading up to his milestone. He now knows this is an event that he
can't push off to the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really pay attention to it,'' Green said, trying to
convince his listener. ``I'm just preparing for another game _ and
a home game _ and one that you're trying to get the momentum going
into it so we can try to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know people are coming in, and I need some more
tickets. That's been in the forefront more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Green has played more NBA games in a row than teammates Michael
Finley, Gary Trent, Steve Nash, Chris Anstey, Erick Strickland,
Dirk Nowitzki and Samaki Walker have played combined. Total.
</P>
<P>
   Those seven players _ more than half of Green's teammates _ have
played in a total of 934 NBA games. And none of them, except
Finley, has a streak of playing at least 200 games consecutively.
</P>
<P>
   Green's teammates use adjectives like unbelievable, amazing and
incredible to describe his iron man status.
</P>
<P>
   Nash said: ``For a guy to have played that many games, let alone
that many consecutive games, is a real tribute to the character of
that person and their ability to prepare themselves physically and
mentally to play and to remain healthy through thick and thin. It's
a real tribute to A.C., and I commend him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks center Shawn Bradley said he doesn't think Green's
teammates can comprehend what he has achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes out with broken noses, broken teeth, and other
injuries _ things that he just fights through,'' Bradley said.
``He's one of the workhorses, and you can see by looking at him and
having been on the team with him, that his work ethic and how he
takes care of his body is second to none.''
</P>
<P>
   Green became the NBA's all-time iron man when he played in his
907th consecutive game on Nov. 20, 1997, breaking the record set by
Randy Smith. But the 6-foot-9 forward almost didn't reach the
elusive record.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 25, 1996, then-New York Knicks forward J.R. Reid
clobbered Green in the mouth, dislodging two teeth, while Green was
playing for the Phoenix Suns. However, instead of taking a game or
two off, Green played the next 12 games with a face mask.
</P>
<P>
   More than three years later, Mavericks center/forward and former
Suns player John ``Hot Rod'' Williams says that the punch was meant
for him. Williams said Suns coach Cotton Fitzsimmons removed him
from the game and replaced him with Green when he noticed Williams
and Reid were involved in a heated trash-talking exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``When J.R. came downcourt he told me, `I'm going to kick your
butt,' '' Williams said. ``I said, `Well, I'm here. If you want to
do it, come on.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach heard all of that, so he took me out the game for a
minute to cool down, and when A.C. went into the game J.R. hit him.
I'm glad to have a guy like A.C. on my team, because he takes your
licks for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Green is to the NBA what Cal Ripken is to major-league baseball.
But when Ripken decided to remove his name from the starting lineup
and end his iron man streak, Green was confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he did that, and I don't understand why he
did it,'' Green said. ``But I won't be doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach Don Nelson marvels at how Green answers the bell
time after time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to even talk about it, because it's just such an
incredible feat that I don't know how to describe it,'' Nelson
said. ``We've seen him play when he probably shouldn't have _ even
here when his back sometimes is hurting pretty bad. But he still
gets out there and straps them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who is a free agent after this season, hopes to retire as
a Mavericks player _ but not after this season. He said he still
has a lot of basketball left in him, and plans to stretch his
streak as far as he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect positive things to happen because it's just all part
of God's promise,'' Green said. ``So I'm not surprised, and I don't
know where this streak will end up. I think I'll retire before it
ends.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
