A5976 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ANALYSIS-LADN-(SL     03-10 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ANALYSIS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE RAISES MORE QUESTIONS THAN ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A blockbuster trade for a team in the midst
of a nine-game winning streak? Even though four of those victories
are against the Clippers, it sounds like the type of move reserved
for the one of the NBA's knee-jerk franchises, like the Pistons,
Raptors or, yes, Hornets. Certainly not the Lakers, whose every
move seems to be thoughtfully calibrated. Or at least used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's trade that sent Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell to
Charlotte for Glen Rice, J.R. Reid and B.J. Armstrong was only the
latest example that the franchise is becoming the NBA's version of
the Fox-run Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency to win a title, combined with the on-again,
off-again tension between owner Jerry Buss and executive vice
president Jerry West, is creating transactions that seem better
suited for teams in need of a major overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is considered heresy to criticize any decision West
makes, and the acquisition of Dennis Rodman has been brilliant, the
five-player trade with Charlotte raises plenty of questions. Rice,
one of the best pure shooters around, isn't completely healthy and
has yet to play a game this season. He's been sidelined with an
injury in his shooting elbow, and those injuries are tricky to deal
with.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Rice is 100 percent, he has to jell with the rest of
the lineup, not exactly ideal circumstances for a team trying to
ready itself for a title run with 30-odd games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Reid is essentially a throw-in to make the deal work under the
salary cap. Armstrong seemed like a valuable addition, a veteran
with championship experience to spell Derek Harper. So what did the
Lakers do? They waived him a few hours after the trade.
</P>
<P>
   From West's perspective, the trade made sense because the Lakers
add an outside shooter (if healthy) and become instantly older.
That's right, older. Neither Buss nor West wanted to wait until
Shaquille O'Neal or Kobe Bryant reached 30 to win another title.
</P>
<P>
   In order to compete against Utah or Indiana, the Lakers needed
to add some veterans, according to the conventional wisdom. But
didn't Rodman already take care of that void?
</P>
<P>
   This trade not only alters the roster, it demolishes team
chemistry. If Rice plays small forward, what happens to Rick Fox?
He's demonstrated loyalty by signing one-year deals the past two
seasons, and is now about to be buried on the bench. That's too
bad, since Fox is one of the few good influences in the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Robert Horry, who will never see minutes at his
natural position of small forward and continue to play out of
position at power forward. He'll now split time with Travis Knight
and Reid. Oh yeah, and Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Lakers are making moves, one wonders if Rice will be
back if they don't win the title this year. He's a free agent after
the season, and even though the NBA now has a salary scale, Rice is
represented by mega-agent David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   There's another reason to dislike the trade. Falk is generally
detested by most NBA teams, and even though he's been diminished by
the current labor agreement, don't think he won't pester West about
trading for or signing some of his other clients, and use Rice as a
bargaining chip to do it.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of nuisance Washington and Miami have dealt
with, but not the Lakers. But the way the revolving door keeps
spinning, the Lakers are resembling those teams more every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
