<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-BULL-RIDING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BULL: HEDEMAN &AMP; CO. PLAYERS IN LAST REAL SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not just Worm Rodman or Albert Belle or Roger Clemens. It's
even an above-it-all icon such as Jack Nicklaus screwing up this
thing of ours. This thing called sports.
</P>
<P>
   Way to be a hypocritical old legend, Jack. Or at least you came
across as one this week.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Nicklaus raised his right hand and solemnly swore to
tell the truth on that kid, Casey Martin.
</P>
<P>
   It was too bad, Jack testified, about Casey's withered leg and
his degenerative, crippling disease. But carts had no place out
there on the manly PGA Tour. Unfair advantage, you see.
</P>
<P>
   As of this week, Nicklaus is considering a cart ride for Senior
Tour events. Hip replacement surgery has hampered Jack.
</P>
<P>
   To Nicklaus, and everybody else, I say bull.
</P>
<P>
   And thank goodness, there will be plenty of that in the
neighborhood this weekend. The way I've got it figured, the last
real sport known to mankind makes its annual visit to Will Rogers
Memorial Coliseum starting tomorrow night. The bull stops here, you
might say.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the PGA, there are no guaranteed contracts. You have
to earn your paycheck week to week. One difference, however, is the
rules don't allow boulder removal for any Tigers. Instead,
contestants are required to stay atop a ton of fast-moving,
four-legged, man-eating boulders.
</P>
<P>
   And if your given name is Richard Neale ``Tuff'' Hedeman, you
don't even count broken arms or separated shoulders as serious
occupational hazards. And when every bone between your upper lip
and your forehead is crushed, you shrug off the total
reconstructive face surgery with, ``it didn't matter _ I was ugly
to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, you saw your best friend, Lane Frost, killed
during a competition in 1989, with you no more than 20 feet away
that awful day in Cheyenne, Wyo. Now, your 4-year-old son is named
Lane, and when he's old enough, he can rent the Hollywood version
of the Frost story, called ``Eight Seconds.'' Luke Perry plays
young Lane's namesake. Stephen Baldwin plays young Lane's dad.
</P>
<P>
   Then a year ago, here in Fort Worth, ``the next Hedeman'' or
``the next Frost,'' crashed to the Will Rogers dirt, and in another
split-second of tragedy, Jerome Davis was paralyzed, probably for
life.
</P>
<P>
   These are tough people, and to most of us, crazy people. But as
it turned out, also enterprising and business-smart individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Just six years ago, a small group of bull riders led by Hedeman,
a four-time world champion, removed its event from the traditional
rodeo format, and took it on the road as a separate sport.
Originally, there were a handful of stops on the Professional Bull
Riders tour.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 28 PBR events, coast-to-coast, leading up to a
national finals. TNN purchased the television rights for every
show, and because of strong attendance and the TV focus, tour prize
money is up to $5.5 million, plus individual commercial
sponsorships for contestants has skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of sports, that kind of money isn't much,'' Hedeman
said yesterday. ``But for rodeo, it's huge. And it's growing every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   For me, however, it's all about sheer entertainment. The ``Tuff
Hedeman Championship Challenge,'' makes a Fort Worth stop each
March. I attended my first one three years ago. Now, I arrange
Florida trips to baseball spring training around bull riding. I get
funny looks when I tell people. My answer: ``see just one,'' and
then tell me I'd rather be in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the PBR can guarantee goes far beyond what even the
biggest of the traditional rodeos can provide,'' said Hedeman.
``The best bull riders in the world and the best bulls will be
here. The governing body of rodeo (the Professional Rodeo Cowboys
Association) viewed us as outlaws to start with, but we thought we
had something that would sell nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   It did, and the danger element is obviously part of the appeal.
``Just like with NASCAR,'' said Hedeman, 36, who will miss
competing in his own event this weekend because of a re-injured
neck, which is a potential career-ending injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to popular opinion, I have always listened to the
doctors,'' said Hedeman, smiling. ``I will have another checkup in
about a month. If it's time for me to retire, I can accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuff also serves as president of the PBR, and along with Ron
Pack of Stephenville, co-produces the Fort Worth tour stop, voted
by contestants as the PBR's best event three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, it's OK to bring on the bull. But that also
doesn't mean you, Jack, or you, Worm, or you, Roger, or ...
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
